<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-RECEIVER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS STILL ON LOOKOUT AS SAINTS OBTAIN KENNISON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys' search for a receiver continues
after their attempt to trade for the St. Louis Rams' Eddie Kennison
fell through yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams traded Kennison to the New Orleans Saints for a
second-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cowboys officials, who are in Indianapolis for the
NFL's scouting combine, are looking for another receiver to
complement starter Michael Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones was unavailable for comment yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the early talk centered on unrestricted free-agent
receivers Carl Pickens of the Cincinnati Bengals and Raghib Ismail
of the Carolina Panthers. Both, however, would cost more than the
Cowboys are willing to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Pickens turned down a deal for $3.5 million a year from the
Bengals because he wanted $5 million a year. He is also the
Bengals' franchise player, and would cost the Cowboys two high
draft picks as well as the high salary.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys had also shied away from Ismail for similar reasons.
market, ]Ismail is coveted by several teams and is sure to get a
deal for at least $4 million per season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have also evaluated Green Bay Packers restricted
free agent Derrick Mayes. Other possibilities are restricted free
agents Bobby Engram of the Chicago Bears and Reggie Barlow of the
Jacksonville Jaguars. After that the free-agent pool is thin. The
original team of a restricted free agent has the right to match any
offer.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys could be viewing their options this weekend at the
scouting combine, as they may have to land a receiver in the draft.
Among the players who could be available when the Cowboys pick 22nd
are Troy Edwards from Louisiana Tech and Peerless Price from
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   What is certain is that the Cowboys are not trying to a find a
receiver to replace Irvin as the team's primary option. Jones said
earlier in the week that the team's evaluation found that Irvin is
not declining, even though he caught only one touchdown pass last
season. Jones said the Cowboys believe Irvin is still a weapon and
blamed his poor production on Irvin's being doubled-teamed ``90
percent'' of the time last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to find someone to make teams pay for so much
concentration on Michael, somebody who can win the one-on-one
battle when Michael is double- teamed,'' Jones said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
