A1149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-NH-1STLD-WRIT     02-19 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5,6&AMP;7. ) 
A SYMBOLIC VISIT TO THE STATE THAT RE-LAUNCHED THE `COMEBACK KID' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs with updates on evening speech by adding new grafs 8-12;
deletes last line from graf 13; editorial refinements in grafs(js) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Seven years ago, the voters of New Hampshire
threw Bill Clinton a lifeline when it looked as if he were sinking
for the third time under the weight of disclosures about his draft
record and his private life.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, President Clinton returned to thank the people of
New Hampshire for their indulgence, spending a day here discussing
health care, greeting old friends and raising money for the state
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit Thursday to Dover, Merrimack and Manchester was
his first domestic trip out of Washington since his acquittal by
the Senate last Friday on two articles of impeachment charging him
with perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the Gennifer Flowers affair that almost doomed
his candidacy in 1992 was just a tantalizing preview of the vastly
more damaging Monica Lewinsky scandal that consumed the sixth year
of Clinton's presidency and has permanently altered his place in
history.
</P>
<P>
   The president was not gloating Thursday over his escape from the
impeachment ordeal, not exactly. But the symbolism of the trip was
unmistakable. It was here in the early days of the 1992 campaign
that Clinton earned the nickname the Comeback Kid, a bold bit of
spin by his handlers after he survived the sex and draft
disclosures to finish a strong second in the New Hampshire primary
seven years ago Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said then that his second-place finish, to former Sen.
Paul E. Tsongas of Massachusetts, ``proved I can take a punch.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was nothing, Clinton's appearance here Thursday said.
In the past year, he has taken everything the Supreme Court, a
relentless independent counsel and bitterly partisan Congress could
throw at him.
</P>
<P>
   His popularity mocks his enemies, and he exults in talking about
how he intends to spend his remaining two years in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   In a rambling, sentimental speech Thursday night to state
Democrats at the National Guard Armory in Manchester, Clinton
recalled the dark days of the 1992 New Hampshire primary, when many
pundits had written him off. But he recalled the line he delivered
at an Elks Club meeting in Dover on Feb. 12, 1992, promising,
``I'll never forget who gave me a second chance and I'll be there
for you until the last dog dies.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Clinton said, ``if you had listened to the
experts, the dog would have died.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, the people of New Hampshire gave his faltering
campaign a boost that propelled him to the White House. ``We've
seen a lot of dogs killed,'' the president said, ``but at least the
last one is still living.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also used the occasion to plug the presidential
candidacy of Vice President Al Gore. At the mention of Gore's name,
the crowd rose with a roar and waved ``Gore 2000'' placards.
</P>
<P>
   In Dover on Thursday morning, Clinton presided over a discussion
of his proposals to expand health-care programs to cover part of
the cost of nursing home care, extend health benefits to more
children and expand the rights of subscribers to health maintenance
organizations. He lingered after the event, shaking hands and
embracing nearly all of the 250 people who sat through the
discussion at the Dover town hall. It was a friendly crowd, a
handpicked group of loyalists who remembered Clinton's words seven
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Peter B. Schmidt, 60, a retired professor of German at the
University of New Hampshire, said he was eager to see the president
return to matters of substance after a year in which he, as Schmidt
delicately phrased it, ``suffered some distractions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has paid a price, damn right he has,'' Schmidt continued.
``The idea that he `got away with it' is rubbish. Clearly he has
been harmed and his legacy has been tarnished.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schmidt echoed the findings of many polls that the public
can separate Clinton's private behavior from his performance in
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people decided wisely that they were not electing
a pope, a minister or a moral icon. They have elected a man who has
a good handle on the problems of the country,'' Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   Others were not as forgiving. The Union Leader newspaper of
Manchester carried a banner headline reading, `` Mr. President,
you're a disgrace!'' and published a front-page editorial telling
Clinton he was not welcome in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The editorial, signed by the paper's publisher, Nackey Loeb, was
titled, ``Don't come back, kid'' and said that once upon a time a
presidential visit to New Hampshire was a special occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when it was purely political, it was something special
just to have the president of our country in our midst,'' the
editorial said. ``Not anymore. Not today. Not with this man.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the president's spokesman, shrugged it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the First Amendment is great,'' Lockhart said, ``and
should be protected at all costs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
