<HEADER>
A1153 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-TOMJANOVICH-OLYMP     02-19 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-TOMJANOVICH-OLYMPICS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich on Thursday officially was named
head coach of the USA Basketball men's senior national team that
will participate in the 1999 Americas Olympic Qualifying
Tournament.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Should the team qualify, Tomjanovich, who coached Team USA to a
bronze medal in the World Championships of Basketball, also will
coach the next edition of the Dream Team that will play in the 2000
Summer Olympics at Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very honored to have been selected to coach the USA
team,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I feel that it's an opportunity that
doesn't come often, and I'm blessed to have a second opportunity.
My experience with USA Basketball has been nothing but wonderful. I
love the people I've worked with; we've developed a very good
relationship. Last year's experience was one that I will always
remember. It wasn't what I expected, but we took what we had and
did the best that we could.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich, 50, was selected because of the job he did in
leading the U.S. team to a bronze-medal finish in the 13th FIBA
Men's World Championship at Athens, Greece, last summer.
Tomjanovich accepted the job with the idea that he was supposed to
coach a team of NBA players, but the lockout resulted in NBA
players honoring a union request to not participate in the World
Championships until a new collective-bargaining agreement was
reached.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich took a team composed of free agents, college and
Continental Basketball Association players, one many thought would
be quickly eliminated but instead worked its way through the field,
finishing 7-2 and defeating Greece 84-61 to capture the bronze
medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were obviously a number of qualified candidates,'' said
Russ Granik, president of USA Basketball, ``but based on Rudy's
contributions to last summer's World Championship team, the
committee felt he was most deserving to coach this team in its
pursuit of an Olympic gold medal.''
</P>
<P>
   The qualifying tournament will be held July 14-25 at San Juan,
Puerto Rico. The USA men, gold medalists at the last two Olympic
Games, will play against 10 teams from North, South and Central
America. The top two finishers will earn a qualification spot for
the 2000 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   The committee that selected Tomjanovich consisted of Rod Thorn,
a non-voting chairman, and 10 voting members _ seven NBA
appointees, one NCAA appointee and two former athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The seven NBA appointees are Wally Walker of the Seattle
SuperSonics, Wes Unseld of the Washington Wizards, Kevin McHale of
the Minnesota Timberwolves, Ernie Grunfeld of the New York Knicks,
John Gabriel of the Orlando Magic, Wayne Embry of the Cleveland
Cavaliers and C.M. Newton, athletic director at the University of
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Newton replaced Mike Dunleavy of the Portland Trail Blazers. The
NCAA appointee is Mike Krzyzewski of Duke. The two former athletes
are Billy King, now the general manager of the Philadelphia 76ers,
and former Rockets player Clyde Drexler, now the men's basketball
coach at the University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also has arrived at a list of players it would
like on the Team USA roster and will formally contact those players
in the upcoming days. The team is expected to be composed primarily
of NBA players.
</P>
<P>
   Some players aren't waiting to be asked. New Jersey's Jayson
Williams suggested that NBA players will go out of their way to
play even harder against the Rockets, hoping to impress
Tomjanovich.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like an audition,'' Williams said before Thursday
night's game against the Rockets. ``Man, I'd love to play in the
Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich stressed that he does not pick the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no, I never thought of that,'' said Tomjanovich, laughing.
``Please tell Jayson that I don't pick the team. Tell everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very experienced and talented committee makes those
selections. And I'm confident that they're not only going to have a
talented team but a team that will have chemistry. With strong
inside players, guys who can make outside shots and some
penetrating slashers.''
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity to coach in the Olympics would help make up for
when Tomjanovich, then playing college ball at Michigan, was
overlooked for the 1968 Olympic Trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in '68, I wasn't asked to try out for the Olympic Trials,
and it was something that hurt me,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I felt
that I was of the caliber to at least try out at that time, and
this has given me a second chance to get into that situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ranks right up there with anything that I've done. The
opportunity to represent our country in international play is
something very special. I don't think Americans really get the feel
for how important these tournaments are internationally. They
really get a lot of interest and a lot of coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year's World Championship, in many countries, that was
bigger than the Olympics. But here's a situation where I feel a
great deal of responsibility in preparing this team and getting us
to qualify. So it's not only an honor but a tremendous
responsibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
