<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARNHAM GETS JUST DESSERTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sean Farnham was calm and collected as he strolled
to the pregame meal Wednesday afternoon. Three hours later, as his
second starting assignment of the season approached, Farnham was
more excited than a makeup salesperson at the Rodman household.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `It's USC and UCLA, and I'm about to start,'
'' Farnham said. ``Man, I was excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Farnham, a walk-on junior, channeled that energy into the most
effective game of his career: six points, two rebounds, two
assists, a blocked shot and a steal in a career-high 18 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Watching him, it was difficult to envision the gangly freshman
who joined the Bruins in 1996. He played with smarts and controlled
energy _ the energy that UCLA lacked in its 18-point loss at Cal
last weekend, the energy Farnham displays in practice each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays like that all the time, and he was finally
rewarded,'' freshman forward Matt Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Farnham played for five minutes, rested, then returned with
10:15 left in the half to battle USC center Brian Scalabrine. It
wasn't a tolken start _ Farnham played throughout the game _ and
that meant as much as anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know how much I'd play,'' he said. ``My dad was
asking me if I was going to play for four minutes and come out, or
stay in. I played well enough that I ended up getting back in. It
was great.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeding stuff: If the NCAA Tournament began today, the Bruins
probably would be a No.5 seed based on their power rating (19) and
three losses in their last six games.
</P>
<P>
   There's little difference between a No. 4 and 5 seed, since both
would have to play the top seed in the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd guess we're a 4 or 5 seed,'' UCLA coach Steve Lavin said.
``We could sink as low as 7 or 8, or climb back to 3 or 4. That's
another reason there has to be a sense of urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   Stat of the week: UCLA outrebounded USC 40-35, the first time in
seven games the Bruins outrebounded their opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Pine time to fine time: Barnes played his best game in months
Wednesday, with three rebounds in 11 minutes and smothering
second-half defense on Scalabrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Matt's best game in terms of energy and toughness,''
Lavin said. ``He brought the effort we've been asking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes and reserve forward Travis Reed have the smallest margin
for error among UCLA's regulars. If they do not produce quickly _
sometimes within 60 or 90 seconds _ they are abruptly replaced.
Fleeting appearances have a way of squashing confidence, especially
when freshmen and sophomores are involved.
</P>
<P>
   But Lavin let Barnes play through a mistake or two Wednesday,
and the result was Barnes' first impact performance since the Dec.
19 Cal State Northridge game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past few games, I've been hesitating,'' Barnes said.
``Coach told me to look for my offense, and that helped. I tried to
be aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go in the games, I have to produce. I don't have a
chance to get warm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
