<HEADER>
A1156 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-19 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ When Roger Clemens said he wanted to move closer
to home, he meant it.
</P>
<P>
   New York and Toronto might be about the same distance from
Clemens' Memorial-area house, as the former Blue Jay flies. But at
least Clemens won't have to worry about packing his passport and
fussing with Customs on the commute.
</P>
<P>
   He is closer to home, indeed. He is in Yankees pinstripes. Home,
at last.
</P>
<P>
   All this time, we thought Clemens meant Houston when he talked
about coming home. We thought he meant plans for 20-minute drives
to the new Ballpark at Union Station, not four-hour flights from
LaGuardia. We thought he was talking about the city so nice it
names highways after favorite sons _ like the Nolan Ryan Expressway
_ not the city so nice they named it twice.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Clemens is a devoted father who cherishes the time he
spends with his four K-kids. To see Clemens shooting baskets with
his kids, or roughhousing with them, it's clear Clemens wanted to
be close to his family year-round.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, home for this fierce pitcher had to be in
Yankees pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   His ferocious baseball personality, his huge talent and hunger
for a championship ring ultimately had to lead him to the Bronx, to
the jungle that is the most celebrated team in baseball. He had to
stand in the center of the Yankees' swirl, under the critical gaze
of owner George Steinbrenner, the demanding microscope of Yankees
fans and the focus of the media capital of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ruth and Reggie, Wade and Darryl, the Rocket's game and
demeanor were too big to ride out with middle-market teams and all
their nice media, comfortable suburbs and strict payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   But what you also should know about the trade that sent Clemens
to the Yankees on Thursday: The Astros demanded it, too. As
recently as two days ago, it was all but a done deal in the Blue
Jays' eyes. Clemens was going to be an Astro.
</P>
<P>
   He was going to play with his kids by day, toy with National
League batters by night. He was going to be the Final Ingredient to
an Astros pennant.
</P>
<P>
   After the long, bizarre trade negotiations _ the wild contract
demands, the miscommunication, the bad words _ emotions finally
settled. Astros GM Gerry Hunsicker dealt long and hard with the
Jays, and two offers that the Blue Jays liked were on the table.
</P>
<P>
   One of the offers involved outfielder Derek Bell, pitcher Scott
Elarton and a minor-leaguer. The other centered on Elarton and
three top minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   But inevitably, Hunsicker and manager Larry Dierker hesitated.
They questioned the deal and talked about what they would lose by
trading Elarton.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker loves the command and control the 6-7, 240-pound kid
possesses. Only Thursday, as Elarton was breezing through the first
day of spring workouts, Dierker stood behind the 22-year-old and
heard Astros catchers kiddingly call Elarton ``Michelangelo,'' for
the way he paints corners of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker indicated throughout the trade talks that the two
players he did not want to lose were outfielder Richard Hidalgo and
Elarton _ the cornerstone of the club's future. Hunsicker meant it,
and Dierker could not agree more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle wanted him in the Randy Johnson deal, and we didn't do
it,'' Dierker said. ``We didn't do it for Clemens. It tells him
something about what we think of him and the expectations we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton's name was pulled out of the deal, all but sealing it
for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's trade certainly clinched another World Series run for
the Yanks and finally gave Steinbrenner the player he has coveted
for years. For the Astros, a team without a bona fide ace, their
1999 fate is much less secure as they try to defend their NL
Central Division title and move deeper into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But there were several reasons the Astros were not emotionally
broken about not getting Clemens. The biggest was keeping Elarton,
but if this is going to be a hitting team like few others in
baseball, the Astros also wondered why they should get rid of a
proven slugger like Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Why tinker with the depth and explosiveness of Astros bats and
further slash the minor-league pool when that is what has carried
the team this far?
</P>
<P>
   Passing on the deal also gives the Astros a few months to see
how their staff works out with Elarton in the rotation, time to see
if Shane Reynolds will fit in as the ace, if Jose Lima will
continue his rise, if Chris Holt will come back strong from his
injury and if Sean Bergman will continue to improve.
</P>
<P>
   If the staff does not respond by midseason, there still will be
time before the trade deadline to acquire someone such as
Philadelphia's Curt Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday, Elarton was called to the clubhouse. When he
walked into the meeting, he saw Hunsicker, Dierker and pitching
coach Vern Ruhle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was anxious,'' Elarton said. ``They looked kind of happy.
But I didn't know if they were happy because I was leaving or
because I was staying.''
</P>
<P>
   They were happy because as Clemens finally found his home,
Elarton did, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
