<SLUG> BC-SMITH-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIVE SON SAYS HE'S RUNNING, AND FEW ARE HAPPY ABOUT IT 
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS to add new 8th graf in 2nd take to add background on other
presidential hopefuls and to note that Smith is the first to make a
formal declaration. )  (af)  
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOLFEBORO, N.H. _ Casting himself as a bedrock conservative
determined to ``keep America strong and free for millions yet
unborn,'' Sen. Robert Smith returned Thursday to the high school
where he taught history three decades ago and stepped forward as
the first candidate to make a formal announcement of his campaign
for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But the candidacy of Smith, New Hampshire's senior senator, was
not widely welcomed by Republican leaders in the state. Although
his campaign gets under way with just the barest of public support,
they fear that if he begins running unexpectedly well here, other
contenders will be inclined to concede him a home-state advantage
in New Hampshire's first-in-the-nation primary, do little stumping
here and so make the primary all but irrelevant to a nomination
that, they believe, he is unlikely to win.
</P>
<P>
   Smith acknowledged that his national ambitions had been
ridiculed by Republicans in his own state. But he predicted that he
would emerge from the pack, because, he said, he is the most
genuine, unabashed conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a leap-year conservative jumping out of the grass
every four years to say, `Here I am, I want to be president,'''
Smith declared to a cheering audience at Kingswood Regional High
School in this summer resort town in central New Hampshire. ``I've
been fighting day after day for the past 15 years in the United
States House and the Senate for the conservative values I believe
best represent New Hampshire. I might be a new face in this
presidential campaign, but I'm an old warrior.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith invoked God and the Bible, and spoke most passionately of
three unswerving stands that have marked his tenure in Congress:
his support for a national anti-missile defense, his demand for a
full accounting of Americans missing in Vietnam (the senator, who
served with the Navy in Vietnam, heaped praise in his speech on
Eugene McDaniel, a former prisoner of war there who introduced him)
and his opposition to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life's goal is to protect all unborn children,'' Smith
asserted, drawing applause from an audience in which students far
outnumbered his adult supporters. ``As president, I will nominate
only pro-life justices to the Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Likening his intentions to Lincoln's freeing of the slaves, he
said, ``Abortion is the moral outrage of the 20th century, and I
will end it.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator dismissed Republicans who say the party should drop
President Clinton's impeachment as an issue, He condemned the
president for ``criminal behavior,'' offered himself as an official
of upstanding character and later said he viewed Clinton's ``in
your face'' visit to this state Thursday, less than a week after
his acquittal by the Senate, as inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans perplexed by Smith's designs on the White House, and
their implications for the state's primary, recall that when, for
example, Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa sought the Democratic presidential
nomination in 1992, most other democratic contenders stayed away
from the Iowa caucuses, which as a result carried little weight
that year.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, Smith's quest has done little to discourage
prospective Republican opponents, perhaps because he barely
registers single digits in New Hampshire polls, in which he is
overwhelmed by George W. Bush and Elizabeth Dole. Smith referred to
both, and to Steve Forbes, only obliquely Thursday, saying, ``I
don't have a big name or a huge family trust fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith performed so weakly in winning re-election to the Senate
two years ago that network exit polls at one point declared him the
loser to his democratic opponent, former Rep. Dick Swett. Smith
ultimately won, with only 49 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Now his presidential candidacy carries substantial risks to his
support at home. A humiliating showing in his own state would leave
him particularly vulnerable should he seek re-election to the
Senate in 2002: He could suffer a humiliating showing. Already, he
has irked some constituents who thinks he should be tending to the
state's business rather than seeking higher office.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Carney, a veteran Republican strategist in New Hampshire,
``noted that since 1960, every statewide elected official around
the country who had run for president, lost and then ran for
re-election to the lower post has done worse.''
</P>
<P>
   In seeking a presidential nomination, Carney noted, candidates
have to move further to the left or right and thus lose some of the
broader appeal that helped them get elected back home.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in an interview Thursday before his announcement why early
polls showed him badly lagging, Smith said: ``It's because I've
never run for president in my own state. What it says is I have not
run for president. These candidates are in here all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But both Bush and Mrs. Dole ahver barely set foot in the state's
snow-covered hamlets. And Smith could not explain why he was
scoring so low in plls here, when native sons customarily score
high.
</P>
<P>
   Although he plans a low-budget campaign, Smith has traveled the
country extensively in the last year (he tallies 42 days in Iowa).
He disputes speculation that he is running simply to advance his
views or to position himself for a cabinet job in a Republican
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be in this race if I wasn't intending to win New
Hampshire and Iowa and North Dakota,'' he said. ``There's no other
reason to get into this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   A few presidential prospects have already formed exploratory
committees or, as in the case of Vice President Al Gore and former
Sen. Bill Bradley, taken the further step of creating official
campaign committees. But with his appearance here Thursday, Smith
became the first to make the formal declaration.
</P>
<P>
   He thus set off what will be a succession of official candidate
announcement tours in the next few months, and will take his
fledgling tour to Iowa on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   While his speech dwelled on social issues, Smith also called for
an across-the-board 10 percent tax cut for all Americans, curbing
the federal government's involvement in education and supporting
the rights of gun owners. Presenting himself as a populist with
grassroots appeal, Smith said, ``You've heard of the country club
Republicans. Well, I'm a country music Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   The sentiment that Smith may be trying to do the impossible came
across even in his rally. The trappings were there: the admiring
wife and children. The school band (playing ``Rocky'' at the
beginning and ``God Bless America'' at the end.) The American
Legion color guard.
</P>
<P>
   But in introducing Smith, Phil Decelle, who hired him to teach
and coach baseball here a quarter-century ago, mentioned the
naysayers. ``Maybe familiarity breeds a little bit of contempt,''
he said. ``Maybe, because he is so close to us, we can't see Smith
as president. I'd like to say I can see Smith as president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
