<HEADLINE>
TRENT INSISTS MAVS MUST BE AGGRESSIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Mavericks forward Gary Trent, frustrated with
the club's losing streak that reached six games with a 101-88 loss
to the Los Angeles Lakers on Wednesday, challenged his teammates to
become more aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Mavericks display some aggression, they will be
battered on the boards, the referees won't give them a break and
victories will be difficult to come by, Trent said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are known to be soft, and that's why \Rthe referees\S let
us get done like we do,'' Trent said. ``If we control the interior
of our defense and get physical and bump everybody that comes
through the lane ... and make everybody know that when you come
through the lane somebody is going to lay a forearm or bump you,
good things will happen for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Trent cited the New York Knicks as a team with a long-standing
reputation of being physical. That's the image he wants the
Mavericks to portray.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Knicks, even though they don't have that same physical
team that they used to have, they still get away with a lot of
bruising,'' Trent said. ``That's because that's what they're known
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Trent said he hopes his teammates heed his words, starting with
tonight's 9:30 game against Golden State (3-5) in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Trent, who signed a one-year, $1 million contract with the
Mavericks on Jan. 23, has worked into shape and given the Mavericks
(1-7) a physical inside presence in the past two games. He scored
14 points, on 6-of-10 shooting, and grabbed five rebounds in 23
minutes during Monday's 99-84 loss at Portland. He scored a
team-high 15 points, on 7-of-14 shooting, and grabbed seven
rebounds in 23 minutes against the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually he's better than I thought he was,'' Mavericks
coach/general manager Don Nelson said. ``He is definitely a
pleasant surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to find ways to use him, because he's everything
that this team needs. He's a pretty darn intelligent player also,
and we need intelligent players out there, because we're making too
many bonehead errors.'' Mavericks reduce roster
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks placed guard Erick Strickland on the
injured-reserve list and waived guard Khalid Reeves, trimming their
active roster to 12 players.
</P>
<P>
   All NBA teams have until today to reduce their active rosters
from 14 to 12 players.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland strained his right groin when the Mavericks practiced
yesterday morning in Los Angeles. He is expected to be sidelined
two to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland played in six of the Mavericks' eight games this
season, and averaged 4.2 points, 1.8 rebounds and 0.8 assists in
8.7 minutes. He made nine of 24 field-goal attempts (37.5 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he tried to trade Reeves but could find no takers.
Back in Oakland Just because the Mavericks' victory was against
Golden State doesn't mean win No. 2 will also be against the
Warriors. At least that's what the Mavericks are saying.
</P>
<P>
   The two clubs play tonight, and the fortunes of both teams have
changed since they last met. The Mavericks have lost six
consecutive games since the 102-99 double overtime victory over
Golden State, and the Warriors have won their past three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to play a whole lot better than we've played the
last couple of games if we expect to beat anybody on the road,''
Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks guard Michael Finley added that the Warriors might be
seeking a little payback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a little revenge factor on their part, and
they're going to come up with some top-notch intensity,'' Finley
said. ``We just have to match their intensity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
