A1164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-FRATERNITIES-1ST     02-19 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FRATERNITIES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RETHINKING FRATERNITIES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 5th graf to rephrase 3rd sentence.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Feb. 19:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the trustees of Dartmouth College to improve
campus life by making fraternities and sororities substantially
coed and reining in alcohol abuse is perhaps surprising from an
institution where fraternities have been a tradition since the
1840s and whose frat parties inspired the movie ``Animal House.''
</P>
<P>
   Piggish behavior has been tamped down in recent decades, but the
Dartmouth trustees are steering in the right direction when they
question the role of fraternities as a means of social
organization. Their move ought to inspire leaders at other colleges
to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   The very selectiveness of the Greek houses is what makes them
desirable to students who naturally crave a sense of belonging. But
that exclusivity often works against efforts by college
administrators to create an inclusive atmosphere for all students.
</P>
<P>
   At their worst, fraternities and sororities perpetuate social
cliques. Their unsupervised parties can encourage excessive
drinking. They may intensify fragmentation of the student body into
ethnic and income groups. On smaller campuses, they can dominate
social life so completely that there are limited options for
socializing outside of the frat-sponsored mixer.
</P>
<P>
   The Dartmouth faculty recommended in 1978 that fraternities and
sororities be abolished, believing that they fostered
anti-intellectualism and sexism. A more recent report from the
college's committee on diversity and community leveled similar
criticisms. There has been continuing concern that the system
creates a climate at odds with the college's academic mission. But
the trustees are also aware that they cannot simply abandon the
Greek system without replacing it with new types of housing and
student gathering spots. They say they are prepared to make the
necessary investments.
</P>
<P>
   Many colleges, including Dartmouth, have long relied on
fraternities and sororities, despite their flaws, to provide
students with social activities and opportunities for friendship
and emotional support. Many Dartmouth students support the Greek
system because there is little else available. Reducing the role of
Greek houses means college administrators will have to shoulder
more responsibility for meeting the social needs of their students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
