<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WOMEN-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSES FROM FUTURISTIC TO FOLK
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By   ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Designers find inspiration in the darnedest places.
Movies watched on an airplane. Ski slopes. Art books. Children
playing. Any place or anything that sparks an image that lends
itself to translation into clothing.
</P>
<P>
   The fall collection Anna Sui showed on Wednesday evening had its
genesis in flea markets, where she saw Danish modern furniture and
Marimekko dresses. That led her, she said, to think about the early
1960s, the period between Beatnik and Hippie when young people were
flocking to folk festivals to hear singers like Bob Dylan and Judy
Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started listening to early Dylan for an element of cool,''
she said before the show, ``and I invented this girl going to folk
festivals.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Sprouse, on the other hand, found his muse on Mars,
specifically the pictures sent back from the Pathfinder landing in
July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Italy that summer,'' he recalled Thursday, ``when
they were sending back the images from Mars and I stayed up all
night to see them on television. I've been into the rover and Mars
thing ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Then last August, National Geographic printed stereoscopic
pictures from the landing and supplied 3-D glasses for viewing
them. Sprouse said he was looking for an idea to follow up his Andy
Warhol theme of last year's show, and decided that that was it.
</P>
<P>
   He obtained images from NASA and permission to reproduce them.
Working on a computer, he developed prints for fabric and had them
produced in nylon, wool and silk.
</P>
<P>
   He then tried looking at the patterns through 3-D glasses and
got the same effect as looking at the magazine pages. So he
supplied the glasses to the audience on Wednesday night, and they
were able to see three-dimensional versions of the dusty,
rock-strewn landscape of Mars, complete with multiples of the
six-wheel rover, on dresses, coats and pants.
</P>
<P>
   To heighten the space age effect, he outfitted models with body
computers, complete with headphones holding miniature monitors
hooked up by wires to keypads worn on the wrist. ``So you can walk
down the street surfing the Internet,'' Sprouse said.
</P>
<P>
   But unless the world is equipped with 3-D glasses by fall, the
clothes will have to stand on their own when worn off the runway.
The patterns are certainly bold enough in the reds, greens, russets
and black tones of the NASA photographs. And Sprouse has always
been adept at cut, so his fans will be able to add new tailored
coats with Velcro closings, short shift dresses, hip-slung pants
and sexy evening dresses that shimmer with the blues and pinks of a
Martian sky.
</P>
<P>
   Sprouse has been on and off the runways sporadically in recent
years, so it was good to have his strong vision back to inject some
vitality into what has been a rather calm season so far.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing futuristic about Ms. Sui's folkies, who took
to the runway in black and white grid and chain prints, giant
Marimekko circles, ombre mohairs in blues and reds, afghan knits,
ribbon-trimmed suedes, and intarsias of turquoise and blue or
orange and pink suggested by Scandinavian fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   They wore long skirts and dangling earrings, had triangular
peasant scarves tied in back under long straight hair, and carried
guitars or guitar-shaped bags. On the backdrop, Murray Lerner's
documentary ``Festival,'' about the Newport Folk Festival, was
screened, recreating for a modern audience the seemingly innocent,
pre-Woodstock days, yet setting the scene for the next phase in
music by capturing the moment when Bob Dylan went electric.
</P>
<P>
   This was one of Ms. Sui's most wearable collections, but it
lacked the spark of sex and even danger that her best shows have
had.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Sui's sensibility reflects pop culture, designers like
Linda Allard of Ellen Tracy, Jill Stuart and Susan Lazar look to
the women who wear their clothes. Reality, not fantasy or
role-playing, defines their approach.
</P>
<P>
   With Ellen Tracy celebrating its 50th anniversary this year, Ms.
Allard said she looked to the company's past and then stripped away
the details to come up with pure, pared-down designs. But she upped
the luxury by using double-faced flannel, shearling, leather,
Shetland wool, alpaca, hand-knit cashmeres and satin.
</P>
<P>
   Unstructured jackets and coats had collarless necklines that
closed with snaps or not at all. Many tops were cropped to bare a
sliver of skin over hip-slung pants or long evening skirts. For
day, skirts hovered safely in the area of the knee. Colors were
soft and pretty in shades of pumpkin, sage, lemon, sky blue, mauve,
rose and green.
</P>
<P>
   The sportswear attitude continued into evening, with pants or
long skirts of satin or feather-light alpaca topped by camisoles,
tanks and cardigans enlivened with discreet beading.
</P>
<P>
   With seeming effortlessness, Ms. Allard captured the way the
average woman with a healthy interest in fashion would like to
dress.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Stuart concentrated on a youthful style epitomized by
smocking on nearly sheer mohair or silk, bib-front dresses that
bared the back, skinny pants in glittery materials, and coats with
thonglike ties placed high under the bosom.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Lazar also focused on a high waistline, sometimes
accenting it with obi wrapping. She also showed long skirts wrapped
to the back or the side, hand-knit sweater coats, and unexpected
touches of beading, on one shoulder, say, or under one arm. Like
Ms. Stuart, she showed perfectly nice clothes but nothing to shake
up the status quo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 0026EST &QL; 
