<SLUG> BC-HKN-MODANO-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODANO'S OFF-NIGHT NOTHING MORE, COACH SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Ken Hitchcock cringes when he hears even the
slightest hint of an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Stars coach said yesterday that Mike Modano's excuse of
being tired in a poor performance against the Florida Panthers on
Wednesday night was acceptable, as far as he was concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one guy that you have to cut a little slack,''
Hitchcock said. ``He comes in and works hard every game. For him to
be off one night is going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In 19 minutes, 20 seconds of ice time, Modano had no shots and
four giveaways and was on the ice for the only goal-against in a
2-1 victory against the Panthers. Afterward, he said he felt
horrible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a bad overall game for our whole line,'' Modano
said. ``That's as worse as I've felt in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Modano said he doesn't expect any lingering effects when the
Stars play host to the Chicago Blackhawks tonight, beginning
another stretch of four games in six nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``You usually bounce back from a night like that,'' Modano said.
``Sometimes, it takes a night like that to really refocus you on
what made you successful before.''
</P>
<P>
   And Hitchcock said Modano has been successful.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' leading scorer with 55 points in 52 games, Modano is
second on the team in plus-minus at plus 19, and ranks third in the
NHL in game-winning points at 13. For the past three seasons, he
has been the team's go-to guy on offense and its top checking
center, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ask a lot of him, but that's because he can do it,''
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Craig Ludwig said the expectations can be suffocating
at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys think he can play 82 games the way he does. There
ain't nobody who can play 82 games like that,'' Ludwig said.
``There's pressure, but he handles it as well as anybody, that's
why they're paying him $45 million. Look, he's going to get tired
just like everyone else, and I'd rather have him tired now than in
May. He's one guy we're not worried about.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano said he expects the pressure, but he adds the pressure
for his line increases in home games. For one, Hitchcock can wait
until the visiting coach puts his players on the ice, so he can
better match Modano and linemates Brett Hull and Jere Lehtinen
against the opposing team's top scorers. On the road, opposing
coaches look to keep their top scorers away from Modano. As a
result, Modano has scored 32 points on the road and 23 at home.
He's also a plus 11 on the road and a plus 8 at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some pressure there to perform. Our line is depended
upon to check and defend and score,'' Modano said. ``First and
foremost, we've got to go out against their best lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``At home, there's a lot of pressure to check them and then turn
around and score at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, the top line has done just that. Before
Wednesday's meltdown, Modano, Hull and Lehtinen had scored goals in
10 of the previous 11 games. Over that stretch, Hull had nine goals
and five assists, Modano had three goals and 11 assists and
Lehtinen had three goals and six assists.
</P>
<P>
   But with five of the next six games at Reunion Arena over a span
of 10 days, is there any worry Modano could burn out?
</P>
<P>
   ``He usually responds as well as anyone after he has a bad game.
I don't think it will be a problem.'' Hitchcock said. ``The thing
about the last game is that for whatever problems he had
offensively, he still was out there at the end of the game making
big plays on defense. His offense might go at times, but he has
become the type of player that his defense is there every night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
