<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1173 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BIG-12-REPORT-TEX     02-19 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIG-12-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS CONSIDERS DRUMMING UP MONEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Old-timers, though I don't necessarily like that term, still
refer it as the Super Drum. Or just the Drum.
</P>
<P>
   And after 22 years as the home to men's and women's basketball
teams at the University of Texas, the Frank Erwin Center has yet to
show its age like some of us have who were around for the first
game in 1977. Once the crown jewel of Southwest Conference arenas,
it yet ranks among the upper echelon in the Big 12 and, for its
size (16,175), holds up well nationally.
</P>
<P>
   But from an athletic-department point of view, things might be
better. And that's why Texas athletic director DeLoss Dodds has
initiated discussions within the university system that could lead
to the multipurpose arena becoming an athletic-department entity.
</P>
<P>
   The Erwin Center operates as an ``auxiliary enterprise'' under
the university umbrella, with its own staff, and reports to the UT
office of business affairs. The UT athletic department pay
approximately $100,000 yearly in rent for games, practices and
other functions.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast and consider, for instance, that Texas Tech's income
from 22 luxury suites in its new United Spirit Arena figures to be
in excess of $500,000 annually. You get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   What Dodds pictures is at least a closer association between the
athletic department and the Erwin Center _ which could in turn lead
to things like marketing consolidation, income-generating luxury
suites and other niceties in keeping with the recent and ongoing
$90 million worth of athletic facility improvements.
</P>
<P>
   As I understand it, there are a number of things to be resolved
before such a thing could take place. Dodds indicates a decision
regarding even the feasibility of the idea could be a month _ or
more _ away.
</P>
<P>
   But athletic-department officials have already visited Ohio
State's new Schottenstein Center _ a 19,500-seat facility that has
52 luxury suites that go for between $45,000 and $65,000 with
commitments for five, seven and nine years. They also will look at
Nevada-Las Vegas' plans to renovate the Thomas &AMP; Mack Center and
explore how other facilities around the country are operated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call them fact-finding expeditions,'' said Chris Plonsky,
associate athletic director for external services and one of three
department staffers who are involved. ``We did the same thing when
we were talking about redoing \RRoyal Memorial\S stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all on an information-exchange level right now,
nothing more. And there is no chance that this would happen unless
it were mutually beneficial for the Erwin Center, the university
and the athletic department.''
</P>
<P>
   An interesting idea. And one whose time may have come.
QUICK HITS WATCHING WAGNER
</P>
<P>
   Hopes of winning the Big 12 title and a postseason push for
Texas men might ride on the tenuous condition of point guard Ivan
Wagner's left knee.
</P>
<P>
   The knee, from which about 50 pieces of floating cartilage were
removed during the off-season, locked up during Saturday's practice
at Oklahoma State. Yet, Wagner continues to play on and well _ as
evidenced by his defensive performance Wednesday in holding Texas
Tech's Rayford Young to 10 points four days after he scored 41
against Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bothering me, but I want to try and play through it,''
Wagner said. ``We've got some goals we're so close to
accomplishing; I want to be a part of it. I just try to ignore the
pain that shoots through it sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Rick Barnes says, ``There's no one on our team any
tougher.''
SHOOTING STARS
</P>
<P>
   Figure this. Oklahoma is the league's most prolific 3-point
shooting team _ even thoughthis is Kelvin Sampson's worst-shooting
(.430) and lowest-scoring squad (71.5) at OU and the player who
figured to be the best long-range shooter (guard Kelley Newton) is
a medical redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   OU has made 209 3-pointers in conference games. Colorado is next
at 175.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we recruited these guys, they couldn't shoot a lick,''
Sampson said.
</P>
<P>
   But seriously, folks, the Sooners do a great job getting shots
off screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it has to do with the system, but give the kids
credit,'' Sampson said. ``They work at it. ... and some of them
have some been good shooters for long time.''
ARE THEY BACK?
</P>
<P>
   With a strong second half of the Big 12 season, the Texas women
just might have played themselves into contention for an NCAA
berth.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has won six of eight, including three in a row, over Texas
Tech, Oklahoma State and Missouri. At 8-5, the Longhorns have
remaining home games against Texas A&AMP;M and Baylor before finishing
at Tech. Winning two of three puts them at 10-6 and 16-10. A win in
the Big 12 tournament and Texas could be back in the NCAA
Tournament after missing last season for only the second time in 16
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' UT coach Jody Conradt hedged. ``I hate to look
ahead with this team, but we have played pretty well lately. We've
still got a long way to go in this conference race, which is not
showing any signs of loosening up any.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest RPI from ``College Basketball News'' ranks Texas
53rd.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA Tournament selectors use the Rating Percentage Index _
derived from a team's Division I winning percentage, its schedule
strength and its opponent's schedule strength _ to supplement the
selection of at-large teams.
</P>
<P>
   Other Big 12 teams in the top 64 include Texas Tech (No. 6),
Iowa State (No. 11), Nebraska (No. 40) and surprising Oklahoma (No.
57). At this stage, OU coach Sherri Coale gets my vote for women's
coach of the year.
NEBRASKA CENTER IN ELITE COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   Forgive Nebraska coach Danny Nee if he has just about run out of
razzle-dazzle adjectives to describe senior center Venson Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just really, really good,'' Nee said most recently.
</P>
<P>
   Don't take Nee's word for it, even though Hamilton had led the
Cornhuskers from an 0-2 Big 12 start into the thick of the
conference race. Look at numbers, if that's your game.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Hamilton became the first Cornhusker and only
the fourth player among players from Big 12 schools to score 1,000
points, pull down 1,000 rebounds and block 200 shots in a career.
Hamilton has 1,296 points, 1,017 rebounds and 224 blocked shots..
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches started talking to me about it last year,''
Hamilton said. ``But I wasn't really thinking about it until I
started getting close. Then, I really started striving for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton has also thrust himself into contention for player of
the year. His 14 double-doubles lead all Big 12 players this season
and he has 11 of those in his past 14 games. Interestingly, he also
ranks fourth in Nebraska career steals and had a career-high six
assists in Nebraska's victory at Missouri two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   In conference games, Hamilton averages 17.5 points, 11.0
rebounds and a league-high 2.7 blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that amazes me is his consistency,'' Nee said.
``He's a natural rebounder and the most consistent player we have.
He's played himself into a special group of players. If those
figures aren't MVP stats, I don't know what is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
