<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROGAN-PLANS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROGAN BACK HOME TO FIGHT IMPEACHMENT BACKLASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LEE CONDON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, Calif. _ Transformed overnight from a freshman
congressman into a national political star, Rep. James E. Rogan
came home Thursday for the political fight of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Crisscrossing his Los Angeles-area district, Rogan _ targeted
for political extinction by Democrats and hailed as a hero by
Republicans _ was in a feisty mood, ready to confront questions
about his role as House prosecutor in the impeachment trial of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In his first full day back home after the trial, Rogan preached
against drugs to schoolchildren, reassured South Pasadena residents
about a proposed freeway, kibbitzed with high-tech business and
academic leaders, and glad-handed with the Republican Party
faithful.
</P>
<P>
   He received a standing ovation Thursday night from a gathering
of about 150 Republicans celebrating Lincoln's birthday at the
Oakmont Country Club in Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never walk away from a fight,'' Rogan said earlier in the
day, noting that he's the only one of the 13 House managers from a
swing district and that Democrats have made him a prime target.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll wear that bull's eye proudly. If standing up for what I
think is right, standing up to protect sexual harassment laws,
makes me a bull's eye to the Democrats, then I think they've got a
lot of explaining to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogan, 41, who barely won a second term in November with 50.7
percent of the vote, started the day at Mark Keppel Elementary
School in Glendale by warning fifth-graders about the dangers of
drugs. Police security was heavy because of an anonymous threat.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke later to the Technolink Association of business,
academic and high-tech industry leaders at the California Institute
of Technology and then went to South Pasadena where he visited a
historic area slated to be demolished for the Long Beach Freeway
extension.
</P>
<P>
   He greeted residents warmly, recalling names, kissing and
hugging the elderly ladies who led the battle and inviting
neighborhood kids to come visit him in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my home. These folks know me,'' Rogan said.
</P>
<P>
   Lorna Moore, a 40-year-old Democrat from Pasadena who attended
the chat, admitted she and many others in her city disagreed with
Rogan on impeachment. But she'll support him anyhow because he's
helping locals fight against the freeway extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to do what he believes in,'' Moore said. ``We support
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogan will need voters like Moore come Election Day in November
2000. While other house managers come from safe Republican
districts, Democrats seeking revenge for impeachment have made
Rogan a top target for the 2000 elections in part because his
district is moderate, has more Democrats than Republicans and
supported Clinton in both 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic political action committees have been formed to start
raising money now and Hollywood heavyweights like television
producer Norman Lear and entertainment mogul David Geffen have
pledged their support to bounce Rogan from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually look forward finding the Democrat who wants to run
for my seat who says the values of those (Hollywood) people are the
values of our constituents because they are not,'' Rogan said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan knows impeachment wasn't popular but those who are writing
his political obituary aren't aware of the strong bond with his
constituents, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel like Mark Twain when he said, Reports of my death
have been greatly exaggerated. A lot of people who are licking
their chops now about me don't understand the political dynamics of
this district,'' said Rogan, a former Glendale Municipal Court
judge and assemblyman.
</P>
<P>
   ``In polls voters always say they want politicians who follow
their conscience. That will be the big test in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogan said Hollywood has targeted him before and that in
November he beat ``one of their own,'' former Screen Actors Guild
President Barry Gordon. While many high-profile actors and
producers may be at the ``left end of the political spectrum,''
Rogan insisted that most of the studios are actually run by
Republicans and said Hollywood has no better friend in Congress
than him.
</P>
<P>
   But Karen Wingard, a regional director of the California
Democratic Party, said Rogan's conduct on impeachment brought him
``out of the closet as an ultraconservative.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden he's going to focus on the district, which is
something he hasn't done. Now that he's got some national
recognition he's back to mend fences in the district,'' Wingard
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wingard said local Democrats already are gearing up for the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally we wouldn't have started this soon. We feel it's
within our grasp to take the seat,'' Wingard said. ``There are
people all over the county who want to get Jim Rogan.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogan said his new visibility takes getting used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not aware of it as much as my wife is,'' he said. ``We'll
be at a restaurant and she'll say, Did you see how many people were
looking at you?''
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment was a grueling experience for him with frequent late
nights, many lasting until 5 a.m., he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it's over. I'm not far away from it enough yet where
I can sort out my philosophical and historical perspective on it,''
Rogan said. ``Everyone is still trying to take a step or two back
from it.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
