<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICH AND THE RUTHLESS: YANKEES PULL A FAST ONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thirty-six hours ago, the Rangers were privately celebrating in
the executive wing of Arlington ballyard offices.
</P>
<P>
   They had him. They had Roger Clemens. The trade with Toronto
appeared signed, sealed, and . . .
</P>
<P>
   The delivery, of course, never happened.
</P>
<P>
   The long New York arm of Boss George suddenly reached out and
snatched away Clemens at the last second.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, after the bombshell deal of Clemens to the Yankees
was announced, disappointment flowed freely from the lips of
general manager Doug Melvin and owner Tom Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been led to believe Roger really wanted to play for the
Rangers,'' Hicks said. ``We bent over backward to make a deal, and
frankly, as of Wednesday afternoon, thought we were there.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Melvin was told by Toronto GM Gord Ash that the deal
with the Rangers was 90 percent certain. Ash advised Melvin he had
one more phone call to make _ to the Yankees on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks ago, I phoned \RYankees GM\S Brian Cashman and asked
if he was involved in the Clemens thing,'' Melvin said. ``Brian
told me there was no involvement, and wouldn't be. But he did add
all this could change if his owner \RGeorge Steinbrenner\S began to
worry about us or the Indians getting Clemens.''
</P>
<P>
   One very small consolation is involved for the local baseball
club.
</P>
<P>
   The mighty Yankees, or at least George Steinbrenner, feared the
Rangers if they had Clemens. Ain't that a hoot? Wednesday night,
Steinbrenner ordered his postseason pitching hero, David Wells,
included in the Toronto package. He did so to keep Clemens away
from Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin: ``I do know this much _ when Toronto started talking
with the Yankees \RWednesday night\S there was no way David Wells
was included in anything the Yankees offered. Gord Ash made that
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the debate rage locally _ why didn't the Rangers not include
enough to counter the Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   The trade Toronto was set to make with the Rangers centered on a
package headed by super prospect Ruben Mateo, the outfielder slated
for Triple-A duty in Oklahoma City this season.
</P>
<P>
   While neither Melvin nor Hicks discussed the players the Rangers
were offering, other voices confirmed Mateo as the main attraction
for the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not giving up any of our starters to make the trade,''
Hicks said. ``But what we had offered, Toronto really liked.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Steinbrenner roared into the picture. In young Homer Bush,
the Blue Jays think they have solved their second-base vacancy.
Left-hander Graeme Lloyd also filled a glaring bullpen need. But
the deal with New York totally centered on what starting pitcher
the Yankees would part with. Wells, frankly, was a shocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``My disappointment at the moment would be a lot worse if they
had gotten Clemens for something like El Duque \ROrlando
Hernandez\S,'' Melvin said. ``Put in Wells, however, and that's
hard for any team to counter.''
</P>
<P>
   From Hicks: ``The Yankees were the only team in baseball that
could give up that much and still have Roger approve the deal.
Roger was only going where he thinks he can win a ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on Wells, the Rangers would have had to include pitcher
Rick Helling, along with Mateo and something else, to approach the
New York offer.
</P>
<P>
   This closes the debate on how far should the Rangers have gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the newspapers, Rusty's \RGreer\S name had come up for
Clemens, so even did Pudge \RRodriguez\S and Helling,'' Hicks said.
``But like we were told early on by Clemens' people, if we had to
trade Pudge, Rusty or Helling, then Clemens wouldn't want to be
here. Lose any of them, and even with Roger, could we win? I doubt
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly without Helling, winning would have been very
doubtful. He had to be the No. 2 starter behind Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   After Steinbrenner ordered Wells inserted in the deal, Clemens
had the right to veto his trade to New York. Another disappointment
for the Rangers was he immediately OK'd it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simple. Clemens thought he had a better chance to win
with the Yankees,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, who wouldn't?
</P>
<P>
   But it's also interesting that Steinbrenner traded a very good
pitcher for a great pitcher in a defensive move to shut off the
Rangers. The Yankees' rotation is now better, but by how much?
</P>
<P>
   And Hicks, a businessman who doesn't exactly warm to finishing
second, did so again, as with Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``So let's just keep working hard,'' Hicks noted, ``to build the
kind of team depth the Yankees have. Then we can answer these kind
of moves.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin, a longtime friend of Ash's, added: ``Two years from now
I think Gord will wish he had taken our deal. But for now, he got
what he wanted in Wells.''
</P>
<P>
   All because Boss George provided what the Rangers couldn't. The
rich and ruthless win again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
