<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELS WINS MATCH-PLAY PREVIEW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ernie Els defeated Paul Azinger 3 and 1 Thursday
to advance to the second round of the World Golf Championship. Wait
a minute, that was Riviera Country Club the twosome was playing,
not La Costa, and Brandel Chamblee was their playing partner, not a
member of the ESPN on-course reporting crew.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. Coincidental?
</P>
<P>
   Oh well, it was an honest mistake. Els, No.7 in the official
world golf rankings, will go against No.58 Azinger on Wednesday on
the first day of the inaugural match-play event that will award $1
million to the sole survivor in the field of 64.
</P>
<P>
   Els is among 35 players who qualified for the La Costa event who
are using the Nissan Open to spit-and-polish their games. Even
though, truth to tell, using stroke play to get ready for match
play is like reading comic books to prepare for the SAT.
</P>
<P>
   Azinger had to be glad this was but a practice test. Els trumped
Azinger's birdie on the par-5 opening hole with an eagle and
finished par-birdie-birdie to Azinger's bogey-par-bogey to card a
3-under-par 68 to Azinger's 72.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of making an early exit, Azinger is afforded an early
(7:27) rematch, if you will, today with Els (and let us not forget
Chamblee, who carded a 74).
</P>
<P>
   Before teeing off, Els and Azinger poked fun at their pairing.
``We kind of made a joke about it,'' Els said. ``He said he's going
to check my game out and I said I'm going to check his game out.''
</P>
<P>
   The pleasantries ended as soon as their first round began. On
the back nine especially, smiles and small talk between Els and
Azinger were as rare as birdies. While Els could be heard
acknowledging a good putt by Azinger here and a nice drive by
Azinger there, his praise was not roundly reciprocated.
</P>
<P>
   As Els retrieved his ball from the 17th hole to warm applause
after draining a 10-foot putt, Azinger seemed inordinately
interested in a speck of dirt or a wrinkle or something on the
crease of his black pants.
</P>
<P>
   He did shake Els' hand before bolting past the outstretched arms
of autograph seekers and disappearing up the hill. If gamesmanship
got the best of Azinger's graciousness, Els professed not to notice
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul's a great guy,'' Els said after signing some two dozen
caps, programs and pieces of paper that were thrust in front of
him.
</P>
<P>
   So is Els, though Angelenos can be forgiven for not knowing it.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Penn shows his face in L.A. more often than the affable
South African, who has graced the PGA Tour stop here only once
before in his six years as a PGA Tour semi-regular.
</P>
<P>
   He typically has joined the U.S. circuit during its Florida
swing in March. The California gold rush of 1999, though, turned
him into yet another prospector, heading west.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, I haven't ever started (on the PGA Tour) early,''
Els said. ``The tournament next week changed my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   A million-dollar pot of gold might have altered Els' schedule,
but it hasn't changed his priorities. He continues to gear his game
toward the four majors, starting with the Masters the first week of
April.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're playing a major,'' Els said, when asked if
he is aiming to peak next week. ``It's a big-money event, but the
majors matter more (to him), absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   If Thursday's scores were any indication, the games of many of
the match-play participants are in as good shape as Riviera's
greens. David Duval and Bob Estes shared the first-round lead at
66, and two other players headed to La Costa, Loren Roberts and
Nick Price, were among the top seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd prefer to have a good week going into it,'' Duval said
in his typically understated way.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Swede Robert Karlsson, who's simply trying to
salvage something from an exhausting journey that took him from
Dubai to L.A. via Singapore. Karlsson, a European Tour regular, is
making his first appearance here and his sixth on the PGA Tour. He
gained entree to the field because his No.66 world ranking at the
start of last week boded well for his securing the final qualifying
spot for the Match Play World Championship.
</P>
<P>
   That was before he missed the cut at the Dubai Classic and David
Toms didn't finish high enough at the concurrent PGA event in San
Diego and all the other dominoes fell wrong for him.
</P>
<P>
   Karlsson isn't exactly an unknown quantity - he finished 11th on
the European Tour money list last year. But he has a ways to go to
build a name for himself here. The back of his caddy's bib read
``Karisson.''
</P>
<P>
   That was par for the course, as was his first-round score of 71.
Who knows? By the end of next week, more than a few strange names
might become familiar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
