<HEADER>
A1184 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-CLEMENS-TRADE-TEX     02-19 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLEMENS-TRADE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKED AWAY: RANGERS OUTBID FOR CLEMENS BY NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ The Rangers had their hands on pitcher Roger
Clemens, only to be blindsided by the New York Yankees and owner
George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees stepped in yesterday and acquired Clemens from the
Toronto Blue Jays for pitchers David Wells and Graeme Lloyd and
second baseman Homer Bush. The Rangers had all but closed a deal
with the Blue Jays on Wednesday that would have brought Clemens to
Arlington for a package of minor-league prospects headed by
outfielder Ruben Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   But Blue Jays general manager Gord Ash made one more phone call
and got a better offer from the Yankees. The deal came two weeks
after Yankees general manager Brian Cashman told the Rangers he
wouldn't pursue Clemens unless pushed by Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great day for New York as it is for the Yankees,''
Steinbrenner said at the team's spring training complex. ``Two
years ago we tried to get Clemens \Ras a free agent\S, and we
didn't get it done. I don't like to lose out, especially on a guy
like Clemens.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner admitted the Yankees were motivated by the fear
Clemens would end up pitching for the Rangers or the Cleveland
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always concerned where Roger is going to show up,''
Steinbrenner said. ``I was. I gave thought to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who demanded Toronto trade him after last season, could
have vetoed the deal according to his agreement with the Blue Jays
and instead gone to the Rangers. He lives outside Houston and has
long expressed a desire to pitch in Texas, either with the Rangers
or the Houston Astros. But he accepted this trade immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was elated to get a second chance to go to the Yankees,''
Clemens said. ``I'm still catching my breath. I'm happy to be in
the American League. I know all the players and the umpires and I
hope this is where \Rmy career\S winds up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said he was disappointed the
deal wasn't done, especially because he was led to believe Clemens'
first choice was to pitch in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm most disappointed in that,'' Melvin said. ``You hear from
players and agents that a guy wants to go to a certain place, like
Roger wanting to stay here in Texas. Then you work hard to make it
happen, and it doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said he was told Wednesday the deal was 90 percent done.
Ash told the Yankees he had another deal for Clemens and asked them
if they wanted one more chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard what the Blue Jays wanted, my knees buckled,''
Cashman said. ``It was a tough call but when you have a
Clemens-caliber pitcher staring you in the face, you have to make
the trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, 36, was 20-6 with a 2.65 earned-run average for the
Blue Jays last year, earning his second consecutive Cy Young Award
and the fifth of his career. He joins a team that won an American
League-record 114 games last season and its second World Series
title in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Clemens brings to the table is pretty impressive,''
Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``Not that \RWells\S doesn't, but
what Clemens has accomplished in his career is long and
considerable. He gives you the kind of guy who can dominate a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we better? I don't know. But I still like the idea of
putting him down there and having him pitch for my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Yankees took the news with mixed emotions. Wells was a big
factor in the Yankees' success last year, going 18-4 with a 3.49
ERA. He pitched a perfect game during the regular season, started
the All-Star Game and won three games in the playoffs. He was also
one of the Yankees' emotional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It floored me,'' Yankees pitcher David Cone said. ``It stunned
me. Boomer was a cult figure in New York. This is the only trade
you could have made to send Wells away. I'm sure there will be some
mixed emotions. He was amazingly popular. But once Rocket throws
his first 15-strikeout game at Yankee Stadium, people will be
oohing and aahing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells, whose career began with the Blue Jays, left the Yankees'
clubhouse without speaking to the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be extremely despondent,'' said Cone, who was planning
to join Wells for a few beers last night. ``He loved being a
Yankee. He was proud of what we did last year. This was probably
the toughest day of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has two years left on the four-year contract he signed
with the Blue Jays before the 1997 season. He will be paid $8
million this year and $8.1 million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Because Clemens was traded while under a multiyear contract, he
could demand to be traded at the end of the season. But Clemens
said he doesn't foresee that. Steinbrenner said the Yankees will
likely talk to agents Alan and Randy Hendricks about a contract
extension, but it wasn't a prerequisite for him agreeing to the
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect we'll be talking over the next year,'' Steinbrenner
said. ``I think Roger will pitch four or five more years of top
baseball. He's a great competitor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
