<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INVITATION LIST IS NOT A GUEST LIST 
NO. 1 RUN OR NONE 
OFF THE MARKET 
CREME DE LA CREME
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   with C.J. SATTERWHITE   and JOE BRESCIA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What if they gave an awards benefit and none of the
A-list award-winners came?
</P>
<P>
   If not for the singer known as Jewel, it would have happened at
the Time for Peace Award dinner Thursday night. Steven Spielberg,
Robin Williams, Tracy Chapman, Joan Baez and Mary J. Blige were all
no-shows, even though their names had been listed prominently on
the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the winners plan their lives so far in advance that they
already had other engagements for Thursday night on the calendar
when they were notified months ago that the Time for Peace
committee had chosen them. Even Jewel was a question mark: She
rushed to the $1,000-a-person dinner, at the Manhattan Center on
West 34th St. near Eighth Ave., after taping ``Late Show With David
Letterman.''
</P>
<P>
   Time for Peace was following a time-honored strategy of trying
to draw a large paying crowd by inviting a handful of well-known
people. And Time for Peace was hardly the first benefit to have to
cope with celebrities' jam-packed schedules.
</P>
<P>
   At the opening-night party for the Winter Antiques Show last
month, &UR;  &LR; Carolyn Bessette Kennedy was nowhere to be seen, though her
name had been at the top of the invitation, in larger letters than
anyone else's. (Her husband, John F. Kennedy Jr., dropped by for a
little while.)
</P>
<P>
   Anne Fuchs, a senior vice president and publishing director at
Hearst magazines, may have solved the celebrity no-show problem.
She is one of the heads of Bright Nights at the Whitney Museum next
month. It will honor no one at all.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 Run or None &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If nothing else, Steve Forbes is focused. He spent _
appropriately enough _ Presidents Day weekend closeted with his
family, discussing the pros and cons of running for president
again.
</P>
<P>
   Word that Sen. Frank R. Lautenberg will not run for a fifth term
in 2000 did not prompt Forbes _ the millionaire publisher and
flat-tax fan of the 1996 presidential campaign _ to schedule
another get-together to discuss the pros and cons of running for
Lautenberg's seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he chooses to run, he will run for the presidency,'' Bill
Dal Col, Forbes' top strategist, said. ``That's a decision he has
yet to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Off the Market &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Here is a postscript to all the talk that Hillary
Rodham Clinton was buying an apartment on the Upper West Side of
Manhattan: A contract for the $1.295 million apartment that the
real estate grapevine had her purchasing is in the hands of a
would-be buyer. Would that be Mrs. Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's not,'' said the broker who listed the apartment, Jeff
Rothstein. ``I wish it was. That would be great. I'm sure the
building would love them.''
</P>
<P>
   Creme de la Creme &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Eric Clapton plans to auction several guitars at
Christie's in June to raise money for his drug and alcohol
rehabilitation clinic in Antigua. But his most famous guitar will
apparently not be on the block.
</P>
<P>
   That instrument is in the hands of musician Todd Rundgren, who
performed with Ringo Starr at the Beacon Theater this week.
</P>
<P>
   This raises two questions: How did Rundgren come to have
Clapton's guitar, and why is it so special?
</P>
<P>
   To answer the second question first, it was originally George
Harrison's guitar when the Beatles were still appearing together.
Eventually, Harrison gave it to Clapton, who played it when he was
with Cream, the blues-jazz-rock fusion group that was inducted into
the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   When Cream disbanded, Clapton lent the guitar to the singer and
songwriter Jackie Lomax. Rundgren bought the guitar from him in
1972.
</P>
<P>
   Rundgren said that Clapton had contacted him about including the
instrument in the auction. Rundgren said he had told him that it
was spoken for.
</P>
<P>
   But if that deal falls through, Rundgren said he might give it
to Clapton ``out of a sense of karma.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember,'' he added, ``I've owned it longer than Eric Clapton
did and I've played it longer than he did.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
