<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLEMENS-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JILTED RANGERS ASK, `WHAT'S THE DEAL?'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Right-hander Roger Clemens drew the ire
of Rangers general manager Doug Melvin, whose attempts to acquire
the five-time Cy Young Award winner nearly reached fruition.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who requested Dec. 2 that the Toronto Blue Jays trade
him to a contender or an organization closer to his Houston-area
home, witnessed the realization of his wish.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Jays general manager Gord Ash, who despite a proposal from
the Rangers involving minor-league center fielder Ruben Mateo as
the centerpiece, traded Clemens to the New York Yankees yesterday
for left-handers David Wells and Graeme Lloyd and second baseman
Homer Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays required Clemens' consent to consummate any trade,
and the 36-year-old right-hander would have been traded to the
Rangers had he vetoed yesterday's trade to the Yankees, Melvin
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm most disappointed in the fact that I hear from the player
and his agents that he wants to stay at home and in the American
League to pitch,'' Melvin said. ``So, you work ... thinking it's
going to happen _ and then it doesn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to call his agents and ask, `Hey, what the heck is
happening here? I thought he wanted to play in Texas?' This was a
case here where he thought he had a better chance to win with the
Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Clemens nor his representatives, Alan and Randy
Hendricks, could be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo, the Rangers' No. 1 prospect, served as the centerpiece of
Melvin's proposal, which also included left-hander Eric Gunderson,
major-league officials said. Melvin only confirmed that the
Rangers' proposal included three players and an undisclosed amount
of cash.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' proposal, though, did not include left fielder
Rusty Greer or catcher Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our package, we keep all of our starters and add Roger,''
Rangers owner Tom Hicks said. ``I was looking forward to what was
going to happen in September and October.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of parting with Mateo did not sit well with some
members of the organization, and the Rangers' proposal put a ``knot
in my stomach,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough deal for us to do,'' Melvin said. ``We were not
all in agreement on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Melvin and Ash reached a tentative agreement
Wednesday, but the latter promised to listen to the Yankees' final
offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas really wanted this,'' Ash said. ``They tried, and they
tried very hard. They came up with a lot of creative proposals, and
they came up with what I thought was a very good offer this week.
It was more for the future, and given the state of our team now, we
needed to bridge the gap from the present to the future right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's trade signaled the Rangers' second failure in as
many attempts this winter to acquire a dominant No. 1 starter.
Left-hander Randy Johnson spurned the Rangers' four-year contract
offer worth $50 million and signed with the Arizona Diamondbacks on
Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like 90 percent of our off-season was spent on trying
to acquire a No. 1 starting pitcher,'' Melvin said. ``We're very
fortunate that we were able to improve our club and get done what
we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Ash placed a 10 p.m. phone call to Melvin's Southlake residence
Wednesday to inform him that the Yankees' offer appeared more
attractive. Melvin, though, was en route to Port Charlotte and did
not arrive here until 2 a.m. yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Ash spoke to Melvin's wife, who relayed the message to her
husband early yesterday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ellen put one other player in the deal,'' Melvin said, ``but
she couldn't get it done, either.''
RANGERS NOTES
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers do not expect catcher Ivan Rodriguez in camp for
today's first scheduled workout for pitchers and catchers. The
recent American Airlines pilots' sickout likely will delay
Rodriguez's arrival from Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin spoke yesterday with minor-league outfielder Ricky
Williams, who might not report to camp. The former University of
Texas running back and Heisman Trophy winner remains interested in
reporting, but the two parties did not reach a resolution. Melvin
expects to discuss the matter with Williams again within the next
few days.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers signed left-hander Matt Perisho and Rob Sasser to
one-year contracts worth the major-league minimum $200,000. Perisho
and Sasser will earn $1,098.90 per day while on the 25-man roster.
Right-handers Danny Patterson, Al Levine and Dan Kolb, catcher
Cesar King and Mateo remain the Rangers' only unsigned players.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo, who injured his right hamstring in November while playing
winter ball for Escogido of the Dominican Republic, participated in
yesterday's first minor-league workout along with 41 others. Mateo
will continue to do so until the Rangers' first full-squad
major-league workout Feb. 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
