<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1199 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYNDICATE-AD-COLUMN-A     02-19 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYNDICATE-AD-COLUMN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: OGILVY &AMP; MATHER FORMS CONSORTIUM WITH SEVEN SMALLER
COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATT: Calif., Minn., Mo., Texas, Va., Wash.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's a Madison Avenue version of a fairy tale:
Snogilvy White and the Seven Dwarfs. But will there be the
requisite happy ending or a Grimm one?
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual experiment, a giant agency, Ogilvy &AMP; Mather North
America, will affiliate with seven independent shops that are small
in size _ their combined billings are not even 5 percent of Ogilvy
North America's _ but loom large in creative abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Ogilvy North America in New York, part of the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather
Worldwide unit of WPP Group PLC, is forming a consortium with the
seven so-called hot shops to collaborate on campaigns for present
clients as well as seek new business.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership, called the Syndicate, is to function as a
secondary network for Ogilvy North America, meant to complement its
work with Ogilvy &AMP; Mather sibling agencies. The collaborators, to
be compensated with retainers and other nonequity investments, are:
Core in St. Louis; Grant, Scott &AMP; Hurley in San Francisco; Hunt
Adkins in Minneapolis; Pyro in Dallas; Vitro Robertson in San
Diego; Wong Doody in Seattle and Los Angeles, and Work in Richmond,
Va.
</P>
<P>
   The innovative aspects of the fledgling venture were underscored
by Rick Boyko, president and chief creative officer at Ogilvy &AMP;
Mather, who, when asked questions about procedural matters, replied
with a smile, ``We're making it up sort of as we go along.''
</P>
<P>
   And the consortium is fraught with risk. Will small shops
accustomed to avid competition against big ones _ and each other _
be able to cooperate effectively? Will clients of the small
agencies be miffed as they pronounce themselves ready for prime
time? Will the copywriters and art directors on the Ogilvy North
America payroll perceive the Syndicate as a sinister slight?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there's talk among the junior and midlevel
employees,'' said Tro Piliguian, president at Ogilvy North America.
``There will be angst.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the North American Creative Council has known about,
discussed and embraced this,'' he added, referring to a group of
senior executives, ``which should make it a lot more palatable and
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   The formation of the Syndicate is emblematic of efforts by
industry stalwarts like Ogilvy &AMP; Mather to confront the challenges
posed by the growing propensity of blue-chip corporations to shun
the formidable infrastructures and bureaucracies of traditional
agencies when they seek solutions to marketing problems.
</P>
<P>
   Competition from smaller, nimbler, more entrepreneurial shops,
as well as from alternative sources of advice like management
consultants, has taken its toll on conventional big agencies as
free-spending advertisers like Anheuser-Busch, Coca-Cola and
Unilever search outside that realm for answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ogilvy has a heritage and legacy of innovation and a belief in
the creative product,'' said Rick Boyko, president and chief
creative officer at Ogilvy &AMP; Mather. ``We're always looking for
ways to find and work with the best talent we can.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us access to talent we've never had the opportunity
to tap into before, and gives them access to a large, multinational
agency with services like media and interactive they would not
normally be able to get to.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Wong, the outspoken chairman at Wong Doody who once worked
for Ogilvy North America, echoed that sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This affords us the opportunity to use Ogilvy as much as they
use us,'' he said, ``to squeeze every red drop of blood out of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   That jocular remark was indicative of the tone of a boisterous
breakfast Thursday at the midtown Manhattan headquarters of Ogilvy
&AMP; Mather, where reporters learned details of the consortium.
Attendees included Piliguian, Boyko, Wong and principals of the
other six small shops.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been, to paraphrase a remark made by President John
F. Kennedy to a group of Nobel laureates visiting the White House,
the most extraordinary collection of creative talent that has ever
been gathered together at Ogilvy &AMP; Mather with the possible
exception of when David Ogilvy dined alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have great respect for all the agencies involved,'' said
Scott Aal, principal and co-creative director at Grant, Scott.
</P>
<P>
   And Wong said: ``If we don't know each other, we do know of each
other. You're always watching agencies of similar size if what
they're doing is interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   The seven small shops have agreed to approach Ogilvy &AMP; Mather
first if they ever decide to sell. But the principals emphasized
their belief that the partnership would not mean surrendering their
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ogilvy's made it very clear they're buying into this because
of what we are: independent, fiercely independent,'' said Patrick
Hunt, president at Hunt Adkins.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Wong said, if ``Sorrell writes us a check for $100
million, we're acquired.''
</P>
<P>
   His reference was to Martin Sorrell, chief executive at WPP,
which has been much less active than its primary competitors like
the Interpublic Group of Companies and Omnicom Group in acquiring
shops like the Syndicate seven.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the biggest Omnicom agencies _ BBDO Worldwide, DDB
Needham Worldwide and TBWA Worldwide _ can cooperate with creative
shops that are also owned by Omnicom like GSD&AMP;M in Austin, Tex.;
Martin/Williams in Minneapolis, and Merkley Newman Harty in New
York. WPP once owned some creative hot shops, including the Martin
Agency in Richmond, Va., but sold those interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been in the works for 15 months,'' Piliguian said,
``since Rick Boyko seeded the idea in my head. I thought he was
crazy, but after reflecting a day I realized it was a good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The idea is not unlike what Katharine Hepburn once said about
the benefits of pairing Fred Astaire and Ginger Rogers: he gave her
class and she gave him sex. Here, Ogilvy North America is Astaire
and the small agencies are Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   As they dance together, the question is whether they are dancing
in the dark (though Astaire danced to that tune with Cyd Charisse).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for the small agencies since it's a regular source
of income,'' said Paul Cappelli, president and creative director at
the Ad Store in New York, a small creative shop that is a peer of
the seven Syndicate members. ``And it's good for Ogilvy because
it's the way big agencies should structure themselves in the
future, with satellites supplying creative work.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's better if you own the satellites,'' he added,
``because what's to keep an Ogilvy client from going directly to
one of the creative shops? And this doesn't address the problem of
the bureaucracy inside the big agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as a behemoth agency, Ogilvy North America deserves
points for a willingness to try something unconventional. There are
several cooperative associations of small and midsized independent
agencies like the Advertising Marketing International Network, but
a dedicated teaming of small shops with a single mammoth one
appears innovative.
</P>
<P>
   And the Syndicate could develop into a promising attempt at
formalizing and solidifying relationships that have become
increasingly common between agencies large and small, as the big
shops hire the small ones on a freelance or project basis for
short-term assignments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how it's going to work,'' Wong said. ``That's
part of the fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
