<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON AND HER ADVISER TEST THE WATERS ON SENATE RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton stepped up her efforts Thursday toward a
run for the U.S. Senate from New York as her political adviser
contacted a wide range of union leaders and campaign consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is to discuss her possible race at the White House
Friday with Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., who is retiring
from the seat in 2000. Next week, Mrs. Clinton is expected to meet
with John Sweeney, the president of the AFL-CIO, and other labor
leaders. She is planning several trips to New York over the next
few months.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Ickes, Mrs. Clinton's political adviser and a veteran of
New York politics, said he has discussed Mrs. Clinton's potential
race with the campaign consultant David Doak, of Doak, Carrier &AMP;
O'Donnell, who is an old friend of Mrs. Clinton's and was the media
adviser in David Dinkins' two New York City mayoral campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Ickes said he also talked this week to the campaign consultant
Bill Carrick of Morris, Carrick &AMP; Guma. Carrick has worked for Sen.
Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., and is a partner of Hank Morris, who
was the media consultant last year in Charles Schumer's successful
U.S. Senate campaign in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ickes also spoke this week about Mrs. Clinton's potential
campaign to Sandra Feldman, the president of the American
Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd certainly be delighted to see her run for the Senate in
New York,'' Ms. Feldman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the teachers would be very happy,'' she said. ``She
knows education. She has been a good friend for many years. I think
there would be a lot of enthusiasm for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Ickes is to return to Washington late Friday and expects to
begin calling county leaders in the state on Mrs. Clinton's behalf
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said on Tuesday that she was giving ``careful
thought'' to a Senate race and would make up her mind ``later this
year'' _ a timetable that irked many New York Democrats because it
makes it difficult for other candidates to raise the $10 million to
$20 million needed for the race.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Clinton's advisers said she needed the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't want to drag this out, and she wants to come to a
decision as quickly as possible,'' said one adviser. ``But she
doesn't want to be stampeded.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
