<SLUG> BC-NY-LOTTERY-COSTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK LOTTERY TO GET MORE EXPENSIVE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   RAYMOND HERNANDEZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ With revenues stagnating, New York state
officials are adopting the biggest changes in the lottery in years,
increasing the number of prizes but making it even more difficult
to win the Lotto jackpot and effectively raising the price of a
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Under the changes, a customer with a dollar will soon be able to
buy only one Lotto number instead of two, as is now the case. The
changes also mean that a person's chance of hitting the Lotto
jackpot will decrease from 1 in 13 million, to 1 in 18 million,
odds that lottery experts say are among the most difficult in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, officials said, the number and size of the
smaller cash prizes in the Lotto game will increase.
</P>
<P>
   The changes come as the New York State Lottery faces increased
competition from a growing number of casinos and the multistate
Powerball lottery that provides bigger payoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, New York lottery sales were $3.8 billion last year,
down 4 percent from the year before. The state's profit, after
administrative costs and prize payoffs, was $1.3 billion, down $63
million, or 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffery Perlee, the director of the New York State Lottery, said
the changes had been largely prompted by concerns from Lotto
customers, who complained that the game's nonjackpot prizes were
too small and too few.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been made loud and clear to us that people are willing
to have a longer shot at the jackpot if we can deliver them a
better chance at winning second, third and fourth prizes,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   New York's lottery was started in the early 1970s. The state
keeps 45 percent of the sales from the lottery as revenue, which
state officials say is earmarked for education. Forty percent is
paid out in prizes, and the remainder is used to pay for
administration.
</P>
<P>
   New York's lottery has a number of different games, including
instant-win scratch-off games and daily numbers with relatively
small payoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the high-stakes Lotto games that have become the
biggest revenue producers because the payoffs can grow into the
millions with increased numbers of players. For Lotto, sales were
$745 million last year, down 14.4 percent. The profit on that was
$335 million.
</P>
<P>
   Under the changes to Lotto, which will take effect next month,
the total weekly payoff will not change _ starting at $3 million
for the Wednesday drawing and $4 million for the Saturday drawing,
and increasing if no one wins the jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   But the changes mean that winning the jackpot will be harder
than ever. The odds were already longer than in neighboring states
like New Jersey, where the odds of hitting the state's Pick 6
jackpot are one in 9 million.
</P>
<P>
   But to sweeten the Lotto pot, New York officials are increasing
the number of secondary prizes that are handed out, as well as
decreasing the odds of winning those prizes. They are also planning
to hand out bigger payments for those prizes. In effect, they say
they are revamping the weekly payoffs so that more money goes to
the lesser prizes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, second prize could total as much as $25,000 under
the new rules, compared with the $3,000 that Lotto now pays out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 0057EST &QL; 
