</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-LEWINSKY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: IF SENATE RACE SIZZLE FIZZLES: LEWINSKY FOR CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The political buzz of the week, of course, was all
about Hillary Rodham Clinton and whether she will move to New York
to take on big, bad Rudolph W. Giuliani in next year's race for
U.S. senator.
</P>
<P>
   You can already see the drool on the collective media lip. Don't
be surprised if you read tabloid headlines blaring ``Beauty and the
Beast'' in World War III type, with The Daily News and The New York
Post arguing editorially over which is which.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the most exciting local battle since the 1971
Ali-Frazier fight at Madison Square Garden never takes place? New
York politics in 2000 would have all the fizz of a college lecture
on urban planning in Greenland.
</P>
<P>
   So here's an alternative to keep the political fires crackling:
</P>
<P>
   Monica S. Lewinsky for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead and laugh, but some political scientists and
strategists are saying, Why not? They think she could put up a good
fight running in, say, the district of Rep. Carolyn B. Maloney,
which lies mostly on the East Side of Manhattan, or in the
Westchester-Queens district of Nita M. Lowey. Both congresswomen
have been mentioned as possible Senate candidates if Mrs. Clinton
sits out the race.
</P>
<P>
   Should either give up her seat, Ms. Lewinsky, 25 and thus
constitutionally eligible for the House, could slide right in. What
has she looked for since leaving the White House if not a good New
York job?
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a job where I feel challenged, engaged and
interested,'' she wrote to President Clinton in 1997. Congresswoman
would surely fill the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. Ms. Lewinsky already spends a lot of time in the
city, and she would start out way ahead of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``You usually have to spend half your money to build name
recognition,'' said Norman Adler, a New York political consultant.
``She wouldn't have to spend a penny. She's photogenic. And what
can you say to attack her that everybody doesn't already know?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who watched Ms. Lewinsky's videotaped testimony at the
Senate impeachment trial this month could see that she had been
unfairly typecast throughout 1998. She was no Valley Girl ditz. She
came across instead as mature, well-spoken, savvy about the law and
more than a match for the House prosecutor who was questioning her.
(Not that that was necessarily an Olympian feat, some would say.)
</P>
<P>
   ``She knows how to handle herself, and she's connected to the
three kinds of people you have to know: politicians, the media and
the legal community,'' said Mitchell Moss, a political scientist at
New York University. ``If you can master those three, you can be
elected in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   In an age when people are famous simply for being famous, who
can top Monica Lewinsky? That can be a strong political asset.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all celebrity,'' said George Arzt, a public relations
consultant to New York politicians. ``Geraldine Ferraro ran as a
celebrity. She didn't run with any record on anything. She was a TV
star.''
</P>
<P>
   True, Ms. Ferraro went down in flames in the Senate race last
year, but there is no reason to assume Ms. Lewinsky would, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll get a break,'' Adler said. Moss, citing the violent
offenders and recovering drug addicts who dot the lineups of local
sports teams, added, ``New York is a city of second chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents, he said, might find her a sympathetic figure, a young
woman treated badly by both the president and his Republican
pursuers. For fellow Generation X-ers, who thus far have shown
meager interest in politics, she could be a role model for getting
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Ms. Lewinsky may have more to offer than celebrity
status. Remember the Starr report's revelation that she had sent
the president her thoughts on education reform? Wouldn't you want
to hear what she has to say about charter schools in New York? None
of the consultants suggested that a congressional race would be a
cakewalk.
</P>
<P>
   There are obvious pitfalls. Ms. Lewinsky would be well-advised,
given the associations that could be made, to avoid campaign stops
near pizza parlors or Gap stores. She shouldn't even think about
Lucianne Goldberg as her communications director.
</P>
<P>
   But victory is within reach, and it could be a great thing for a
woman who must have had it up to here with the limelight. In New
York, if you want to stay out of the newspapers and off television,
you can't do much better than to be in Congress. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 0059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
