<HEADLINE>
SPANIARDS HOLDING FIRM ON SIZABLE INVESTMENTS IN BRAZIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By AL GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ Spanish companies that invested heavily last
year in Brazil insist they are not having second thoughts because
of its financial crisis, and several have turned it to their
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The state-run telecommunications giant Telefonica, for example,
gained $1 billion on Brazil's currency devaluation in January. And
Banco Bilbao Vizcaya, Spain's second-largest bank as measured by
assets, acquired the troubled Banco Excel-Economico in August for
one Brazilian real while agreeing to invest $820 million to bring
it back to health with the aid of government concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bet we made on Brazil is a long-term bet,'' said Francisco
Blanco, Telefonica's director of investor relations, echoing a
policy heard in other Spanish board rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica agreed to pay $6 billion last July for the largest
piece of Telecomunicacoes Brasileiras SA, known as Telebras,
Brazil's telephone system, when the government auctioned it off.
But after the real was devalued in January, Telefonica saved $1
billion on the deal through the early redemption of bonds
denominated in dollars that it had encouraged the Brazilian
government to issue last autumn.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, potential investors think twice about investing in
Brazil,'' Blanco said. ``So we are gaining position.''
</P>
<P>
   But not without some pain. Telefonica's share price has declined
8 percent since last July, and Standard &AMP; Poor's slightly lowered
the company's long-term rating in November because of increased
exposure in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   After the devaluation of the real last month, share prices also
dipped for Banco Bilbao and Banco Santander, Spain's largest bank,
which bought Brazil's Banco Noroeste for $756 million last year.
Standard &AMP; Poor's placed Banco Bilbao on credit watch last month
because of its exposure in emerging markets, including Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   But the buying spree by Telefonica and the two big Spanish banks
in Brazil came after they spent several years investing heavily in
banks and telecommunications in Argentina, Chile and Peru. The
companies say Brazil's growth potential is too important to ignore
despite the current financial instability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil accounts for about half of Latin America's gross
domestic product,'' said Jose Sevilla, Banco Bilbao's financial
director for Latin America. ``We have a project to build franchises
in Latin America to combine the advantages of global and local
banking. Brazil is part of our overall strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Spanish companies are following. Endesa, Spain's largest
electric utility, paid about $400 million last year for key stakes
in Coelce, an electricity distributor serving the area around the
northeast port of Fortaleza, and in the Cien consortium, which will
supply Brazil with electricity from Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Endesa's director of affiliated companies, Alberto Lopez, said
the company made the relatively small investments to better
position itself for the privatization of Brazil's electricity
generation network, which is expected within 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Iberdrola, Spain's second-largest utility, invested about $1
billion in electricity and gas distributors in Brazil in 1997,
mainly in Bahia state, but last year it focused on
telecommunications there, part of the company's diversification
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Iberdrola bid $769 million in the privatization of Telebras,
following Telefonica's lead but buying smaller stakes in several of
the same Brazilian phone companies, like the fixed-line provider
Telesp, which serves the Sao Paulo region.
</P>
<P>
   Blanco of Telefonica said the backlog of 5.5 million clients who
want phone lines in Sao Paulo was so large that ``even in a
recession scenario, it's not enough to rethink the capital
expenditure program.''
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica plans to install two million lines in Sao Paulo this
year, though Blanco said that the poor economy in Brazil could
prompt some people on the waiting list to delay their requests.
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica and other Spanish companies in Brazil ``are seeing
that the capacity of the market outweighs the risks. Even in the
most pessimistic scenario, they would keep earning money,'' said
Jose Luis Perez, a managing partner of KPMG Peat Marwick in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latin America is where Spain considers it has a competitive
advantage,'' said Fernando Fernandez, head of research for Banco
Central Hispano, Spain's third-largest bank, which agreed last
month to a stock swap sale to Banco Santander.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategic position in Brazil will be maintained,''
Fernandez said. ``There's no way they'll pull out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
