<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSE-RACING-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DERBY OFFERING NEW BETTING TWIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The terms ``future book'' and ``winter book'' have long been
part of horse racing's lexicon. But now the concept has a new look.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill Downs kicked off its Kentucky Derby Future Wager
yesterday at simulcast sites nationwide, including Lone Star Park
at Grand Prairie. Similar to early betting that has been offered by
Nevada casino racebooks for years, the Future Wager gives fans an
opportunity to lock in a win bet at higher odds on Derby
contenders, while assuming the risk that the 3-year-old might
suffer an injury or attack of slowfootedness that keeps him out of
the Derby starting gate altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The new twist is that Churchill Downs is offering the Future
Wager as a pari-mutuel pool, in which odds are set based on the
money wagered on each horse.
</P>
<P>
   Future Wager betting on 23 designated Triple Crown nominees will
continue through 3:30 p.m. (CST) on Sunday, at which time official
odds will be calculated for each horse. For the uninitiated, it
works like this: if a Future Wager is made on filly Excellent
Meeting and her final odds for this weekend's pool are announced
Sunday at 12-to-1, the ticket holder will get those odds even if
Excellent Meeting beats the boys in the May 1 Kentucky Derby at
3-to-1 odds. If she doesn't run in the Derby at all, or loses, the
ticket holder is out the amount of his bet.
</P>
<P>
   Those who don't like the 23 entrees on the Future Wager menu can
order ala carte by selecting a popular option: No. 24 for ``all
other 3-year-olds.''
</P>
<P>
   The Future Wager will return March 11-14 (Pool Two) and April
8-11 (Pool Three) with an updated list of contenders and odds. In
other words, it is possible that bettors favoring Excellent Meeting
could buy separate tickets on her at 12-to-1 odds in Pool One,
8-to-1 in Pool Two and 5-to-1 in Pool Three.
</P>
<P>
   The Future Wager is providing greater access to early Derby
bets, but for those planning a trip to Las Vegas or who have
contacts there, futures odds at racebooks can be more profitable.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a late-developing 3-year-old at Oaklawn Park might
be listed at 100-to-1 or more at some racebooks. But if he isn't on
the 23-horse Future Wager list, he will grouped in the ``all
others` category at single-digit odds, hardly a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   The ``all others'' was established as the early-program
favorite, and for good reason. If this wager had been offered in
previous years, Derby winners such as Grindstone (1996), Lil E. Tee
(1992), Strike The Gold (1991) _ and possibly Winning Colors (1988)
and last year's Real Quiet _ likely wouldn't have made future-book
radar screens in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   KRONE REGAINS WINNING FORM
</P>
<P>
   According to press clippings, jockey Julie Krone entered the
Fair Grounds season suffering from a confidence crisis.
</P>
<P>
   You would never know it now.
</P>
<P>
   The country's all-time leading female jockey won five races
Tuesday, including the 3,500th winner of her career. In her first
season at the New Orleans track, she is riding in such
extraordinary form the past two weeks that she even appears to be
improving the performance levels of her mounts. She has regularly
been bringing home long shots as well as favorites.
</P>
<P>
   The popular Krone endured a career's worth of injuries the past
five years, including a knee fracture before this Fair Grounds
season. The repeated misfortunes affected her performance in the
saddle, and at one point, she says she even saw a psychiatrist in
an attempt to regain her bearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``But anybody that's been watching her ride would agree that her
confidence is 100 percent,'' said her agent, Joey DiAngelo.
</P>
<P>
   Krone said, ``I've lost it before, and now it's back.''
</P>
<P>
   DiAngelo said some Fair Grounds trainers were skeptical of Krone
when she arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had never rode this circuit before, and a lot of people had
never seen Julie first-hand,'' he said. ``Now, people that said
they would never ride girls are giving us \Rmounts\S. They have a
different outlook about her now.''
</P>
<P>
   Krone is third-leading jockey at Fair Grounds with 46 wins,
trailing Robby Albarado (76) and Eddie Martin (68). She probably
can't catch the top two New Orleans veterans, but if she were on
the Billboard chart, she would be No. 3 with a bullet. In the past
10 days, she has been riding winners at a 31 percent clip.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS
</P>
<P>
   Last year's champion juveniles are scheduled to race this
weekend at Fair Grounds. Answer Lively attempts to make amends in
Sunday's Risen Star Stakes for a recent poor showing, and filly
Silverbulletday makes her first 1999 start tomorrow in the Davona
Dale Stakes. Ten 3-year-olds were entered for tomorrow's Fountain
of Youth Stakes at Gulfstream Park, the first major Triple Crown
prep of the year. Leading contenders in a wide-open field are Cat
Thief, Aly's Ally, Doneraile Court, Certain, Vicar, Grits'n Hard
Toast and The Groom is Red. The 1 1/16-mile race will be televised
on WFAA/Channel 8 with a 2:14 p.m. CST post. Deadline for stall
applications for Lone Star's upcoming thoroughbred meet is March 3.
The 72-day meet runs April 15 through July 25. Santa Anita has been
selected as host for the 2000 Breeders' Cup. The Arcadia, Calif.,
track previously had the races in 1986 and 1993. This year's
Breeders' Cup will be at Gulfstream Park in November. Arch, last
year's Super Derby winner, has been retired due to chronic ankle
problems. Plans are for him to stand at stud this year at Claiborne
Farm, which owns the 4-year-old in partnership with Adele
Dilschneider. Because of compatibility problems, Churchill Downs'
Kentucky Derby Future Wager won't attract as much betting action as
it might have. Santa Anita, Gulfstream Park and Aqueduct are not
accepting bets on the wager this weekend because their computer
systems cannot process races with 24 separate betting interests.
/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
