r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     02-19 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S HAVE MORE THAN MURMURS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What the world needs is another golf tournament.
</P>
<P>
   I hear you shrieking at the very thought of one more Touchstone
Energy Tucson Open, Par-Three Challenge, Bruno's Memorial Classic,
Shark Shootout or Sprint International. Well, save your voice, you
might need it.
</P>
<P>
   You will need it if my tournament concept gets off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere on the year-long schedule of pro events ... for men,
women and old men ... and every possible combination of the three
... competing in stroke-play, match-play and pairs formats ... is a
tournament that caters to the fans.
</P>
<P>
   By which I don't mean the fans who limo up to the local PGA stop
in tweeds, jewelry and ``member'' badges, the ones who are too
refined to utter a sound or step on a twig within earshot of the
oh-so-sensitive golfers.
</P>
<P>
   I mean the fans in Hooters sweatshirts, painters' hats and dingy
sneakers, the ones who picked up their etiquette from Al Bundy and
just happen to be the sport's growing public.
</P>
<P>
   Why not reward those guys with a tournament where the customary
rules of gallery behavior are suspended and it's all right to
cheer, jeer, heckle and _ if this isn't going too far _ trip a
camera shutter?
</P>
<P>
   Not every tournament. One.
</P>
<P>
   Try it, they might like it. Even Tiger Woods, whose gripes about
midswing camera clicks at the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am two
weeks ago resurrected the issue of photographers', cell phones' and
pagers' intrusions.
</P>
<P>
   One PGA Tour pro endorses the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like one tournament where everybody can scream and yell
anything they want _ `Miss it! Miss it!' '' said Jerry Kelly, tied
for eighth at 3-under-par after Thursday's first round of the
Nissan Open at Riviera Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee we'd play just as well. If it's one guy (making
noise), it bothers us. If everybody's doing it, it doesn't bother
us.''
</P>
<P>
   By accident, the PGA Tour has something approaching our
high-decibel proposal already, a January tournament called the
Phoenix Open. It's the best-attended stop on the tour and a few of
the week's 500,000 fans might not have attended finishing school.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, a lot of them might show up chip-faced.
</P>
<P>
   The par-3 16th hole in Phoenix has grown so notorious for its
bleacher bums that nearby beer sales were halted this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only place I've got booed for hitting it in a
bunker,'' Kelly said. ``I'm lucky I hit the green a little bit
first, or they would've been yelling, `Air ball!'''
</P>
<P>
   David Duval mis-hit a chip into a far-side bunker and heard a
woman behind him grouse loudly, ``Well, I could have done that!''
</P>
<P>
   Duval admitted coming unglued because of the comment as much as
the shot.
</P>
<P>
   There was a taste of Phoenix in Pacific Palisades Thursday when
a fan near the 14th green, three empty beer cans on the bench
beside him at 10 in the morning, rattled Kelly's group with his
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some players hear it more than others,'' Phil
Mickelson said after his 68. ``I don't really mind it that much.''
</P>
<P>
   The heck he doesn't, said a writer who watched Mickelson go
face-to-face with a camera-wielding fan at Spyglass Hill during the
Pebble Beach tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``How come you can have a camera and no one else can?''
Mickelson said. The fan tucked the camera under his coat.
</P>
<P>
   Other athletes tolerate such abuse, if that's what it is.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, when baseball's Ken Griffey Jr. played in the
Pebble Beach pro-am, he was unnerved by the silence as he bent over
a putt. He's used to the occasional crowd murmur during his
backswing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody, please make some noise,'' he told the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that baseball players expect a din. Golfers
expect a morgue.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Quiet Please'' signs are such an institution, they bear a
sponsor's logo this week.
</P>
<P>
   But golfers don't complain about constant noise like the drone
of a blimp or the whine of a buzz saw at the house overlooking
Riviera's seventh tee Thursday. So why would it be a problem if
they showed up at our tournament _ don't you know we'll hold it in
the Bronx _ expecting sound and fury from behind the ropes?
</P>
<P>
   Where'd you learn that swing, Furyk _ in a granite quarry?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Michelson, I thought left-handers could hit the low pitch!
</P>
<P>
   Time for a grip change, Hoch: Take your hands off your throat!
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there'd be a ``Rah, Tiger!'' mixed in.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the catharsis would unburden the 20th century American
male of the obligation to whisper a comment on every golf stroke he
sees.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine: No ``You da man!'' No ``It's in the hole!''
</P>
<P>
   None of the little cliches fans have picked up from TV: ``He
pulled that little 5-iron a little bit. He's left with a tricky
little flop shot over a little bit of a hump....''
</P>
<P>
   We might even discover that given a tournament where they could
say anything, fans would have nothing to say.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, that's the idea. Once a year, a loud break from
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA can reach me at Riviera. (My pager will be set on
``vibrate.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
