<SLUG> BC-NABISCO-MINI-TENDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 INVESTOR MAKES UNDERPRICED BID FOR 2% OF RJR NABISCO SHARES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the latest example of a practice known as a ``mini-tender,''
a tiny investment company offered Thursday to buy 2 percent of the
outstanding stock of RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp. for $24 a share, or
8 percent lower than its recent closing price.
</P>
<P>
   While those seeking to buy more than 5 percent of a company's
outstanding stock must make regulatory filings with the Securities
and Exchange Commission, a company making a mini-tender can skirt
that requirement by offering to buy less. In recent months, such
offers have been made to holders of Greyhound Lines Inc. and United
States Office Products Co. at prices up to 20 percent lower than
the market value of those stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Although mini-tenders are not governed by any regulations, such
offers are transmitted to a company's investors once they are
received by the Depository Trust Company, the national central
securities depository.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, some regulators are growing concerned that some
investors, particularly the elderly, might perceive that such
tender offers have to be acted on promptly in order for them not to
lose money. But in doing so, they relinquish their stock for a
price often far lower than they could get if they sold it in the
open market.
</P>
<P>
   The offer Thursday for stock of RJR Nabisco, the tobacco and
food giant, came from Schultze Asset Management, a tiny company in
New Jersey. It could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Nabisco urged holders to reject the offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``RJR Nabisco strongly recommends that its shareholders reject
this tender offer,'' the company said, adding that the price
``based on current market prices is below the amount shareholders
could receive from a sale of their RJR Nabisco shares in the public
markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of RJR rose 31.25 cents Thursday, to $26.125.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
