<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEEDED TO WIN SENATE SEAT IN NEW JERSEY: LOTS OF CASH 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JENNIFER PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ There is already a long list of potential
candidates for the U.S. Senate seat that will be vacated next year
by Sen. Frank R. Lautenberg, but there is one qualification that
will quickly separate who is viable and who is not: the campaign
bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Because running for statewide office in New Jersey requires
candidates to reach voters through two expensive media markets, New
York and Philadelphia, political analysts say most Senate
candidates will need to raise and spend $10 million to $12 million
in the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money has become the first primary in elections these days,''
said Paul Hendrie, communications director of the Center for
Responsive Politics, a nonprofit research organization that tracks
the role of money in federal politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the first test for whether a candidate is credible or
not. It is not the candidate's resume or a candidate's track record
or positions on issues or even base of support. The first thing
that people look at is how much money can they raise.''
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg, 75, a multimillionaire, cited the pressures of
raising such a gigantic sum as a primary reason behind his decision
to retire after three terms. He said that he realized, as he sat
through the impeachment proceedings that ended last week, that the
five-week trial was costing him $750,000 that he could have been
raising for his campaign. With only $500,000 in the bank, he
estimated that he would need to raise $25,000 to $30,000 a day for
the next 18 months to help make up the difference. ``I decided
that's not what I wanted to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While money in the bank can turn a candidate into an early
front-runner and scare off potential opponents, the ability to
raise money can be even more important.
</P>
<P>
   Take Gov. Christine Todd Whitman. She said that she would
consider making a bid for the Senate in 2000. She does not have a
dime in the bank for a Senate race, but neither her top aides nor
Republican Party leaders are concerned because they say there is
little doubt about her fund-raising abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Mrs. Whitman raised millions of dollars in the past
for her campaigns and the state party organization, but she has
also raised millions for fellow Republican candidates around the
country in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Several other Republicans who are considering entering the race
already have hundreds of thousands in the bank, but they lack Mrs.
Whitman's star power and statewide appeal. According to federal
campaign finance records, Rep. Frank A. LoBiondo of Vineland, who
said he was talking to supporters about seeking the Republican
nomination, raised $846,000 for his re-election to Congress last
year. But he spent only $146,000, leaving him more than $700,000 to
start a Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican, James W. Treffinger, the Essex County
executive, who said he was also thinking about the Senate seat,
expressed confidence in his ability to find donors. At his
inaugural, he raised $550,000. ``The fund-raising does not seem to
be a problem,'' he said, acknowledging that not all of the $550,000
could be used for a Senate bid because it was raised under state
campaign finance rules, not federal rules.
</P>
<P>
   For Democrats, a review of recent campaign finance filings shows
that Rep. Robert Menendez of Union City is ahead of the pack with
$1.2 million. Menendez, the fourth-ranking Democrat in the House
and already a favorite of party regulars, is expected to announce
early next week whether he will seek the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Another Senate hopeful, Susan Bass Levin, a Democrat who is the
mayor of Cherry Hill, created an exploratory committee last year to
test the waters and held a fund-raiser that she said had raised
several hundred thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Jim Florio, who has also expressed interest in the
seat, has shown in the past that he can raise money with a network
of wealthy donors. But party leaders point out that he has not run
for office since he lost to Mrs. Whitman in 1993, and they are
hoping that party leaders and donors will rally behind a new face
in the state Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   According to the most recent federal campaign finance records,
some of the others who said they were considering running for
Lautenberg's seat would be starting with next to nothing. Rep.
Marge Roukema, a Republican from Ridgewood, has about $33,500; Rep.
Steven R. Rothman, a Democrat from Fair Lawn, $31,470, and Rep.
Frank Pallone Jr., 23,678.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
