<SLUG> BC-SOUND-SOURCE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUND SOURCE SOARS, RETREATS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Shares of Sound Source Interactive soared 30
percent in early trading Thursday after the CD-ROM publisher
announced a distribution deal with Macmillan Computer Publishing,
but then Wall Street took back most of the gain by the end of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Sound Source shares closed the session up 9.375 cents to 93.75
cents, or 11 percent, in a performance reflecting the volatility
among tech stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Calabasas-based company, recently ranked as the seventh
largest publisher of educational software, said the Macmillan deal
would expand its existing sales channels and develop new sales
possibilities for its library.
</P>
<P>
   Macmillan, which will handle the entire line of Sound Source
CD-ROMs in North America, is the world's largest computer book
publisher.
</P>
<P>
   But even with Thursday's gain, Sound Source remains down 40
percent from its 1999 high, reached just two weeks ago during a
session when its value more than doubled even though there was no
news to drive that increase. By contrast, the Feb. 9 announcement
that Sound Source had hired investment bankers to explore strategic
alternatives -- a sign that the company could be sold and usually
an upward spur to a stock -- led to a 30 percent decline during the
session.
</P>
<P>
   Sound Source's wide swings may be related to the intense
interest in the high-tech sector among day traders and investors
who participate in Internet chat rooms, a company spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's gain came on the heels of a 33 percent loss during
the previous session following three negative disclosures:
</P>
<P>
   __The company reported a loss of $760,503, or 13 cents a share,
for its second quarter ended Dec. 31, compared with profits of
$1.27 million in the year-earlier period. Sales plunged to $1.67
million from $3 million due to slow sales of ``The Abbys: Incident
at Europa'' and three ``Babe: Pig in the City'' titles.
</P>
<P>
   __Nasdaq recently notified the company that the stock may be
delisted since it had failed to keep the closing price of the stock
above $1 for 30 consecutive sessions. To avoid delisting, the stock
must close above $1 for 10 consecutive sessions prior to April 29.
</P>
<P>
   __The company has decided to abandon the nonfamily oriented
software business to focus on its ``core competence'' of family
titles.
</P>
<P>
   Sound Source, which has 42 employees, went public with a $10
million offering in 1996. The stock traded at over $6 on its first
day but fell under $3 in early 1997 and has never regained that
level.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
