</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DEMS-TOBIAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFILE: `BEST LITTLE BOY' IS NOW A CHIEF FUND-RAISER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are three essential things to know at this
moment about the financial writer Andrew Tobias.
</P>
<P>
   The first is that he went to Camp Wigwam in Maine with Steve
Grossman, who recently resigned as national chairman of the
Democratic National Committee. The second is that Hillary Rodham
Clinton squeezed his hand at the stroke of midnight on New Year's
Eve 1992. ``I will never forget it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The third is that he has become a crucial fund-raiser among gay
men and lesbians for the president and other Democrats, and has
himself given the party $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   So next month, Tobias is to become the new treasurer of the
Democratic National Committee _ the first openly gay person to have
such a leadership position in the national party. His job is to
help raise $250 million for the Democrats in 2000, and get money
from an increasingly important interest group that the party still
considers untapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing very sexy or cool about the DNC,'' Tobias said
this week in his Manhattan apartment, adding that his new job is,
partly, to make the party relevant to people who focus most of
their philanthropy on AIDS and gay civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows how much gay men and lesbians give to the party,
although the Democratic National Committee estimates that it was $3
million in 1996. ``I'm going to try to give the gay and lesbian
community a way to give money so that it's identifiable,'' Tobias
said. ``When tobacco gives money to the Republican National
Committee, they don't do it anonymously.''
</P>
<P>
   Since December 1997, the Clintons have attended three Democratic
National Committee gay and lesbian fund-raising events _ two at the
Mayflower Hotel in Washington, one last summer in the Hamptons at
the home of Dr. Christopher Barley, an internist, and Jonathan
Sheffer, the artistic director of the Eos Orchestra. They raised
$1.2 million, and Tobias was at all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party is still wondering, `Should we take money
from these awful people?''' Tobias said.
</P>
<P>
   Tobias became a Clinton partisan some 15 years ago, when he met
the couple at a Renaissance Weekend. ``I don't know them very well,
but they have totally changed my life,'' he said. ``I think what
the government does is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials say it was President Clinton and
Grossman's idea to offer Tobias, 51, the job. ``He was sort of a
natural for this,'' said Richard Socarides, a presidential adviser
who oversees issues of gay rights. ``Andy checks a lot of boxes for
the White House and the Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobias is the kind of generous and self-deprecating person who
is fun to sit next to at dinner but hides a lot of life behind an
amusing persona.
</P>
<P>
   The amusing part first: ``This Teletubby thing is so
wonderful,'' said Tobias, referring to the Rev. Jerry Falwell's
criticism of the television Teletubby character, Tinky Winky, as
gay. ``And incidentally, Tinky Winky is gay. And part two, so what?
And part three, he's not molesting any of the others. Mainly,
though, he carries what the Reverend Falwell calls a purse, and
what the producer calls his `magic bag.''' Tobias smiled. ``Come
on,'' he said, ``it's a purse.''
</P>
<P>
   The not-so-amusing part, from Tobias' memoir, ``The Best Little
Boy in the World Grows Up'': ``I think my own loneliest moment may
have been on a winter evening senior year in college with my two
roommates up at Killington, in Vermont. . . . What got me was
trying to negotiate the `apres-ski' that night, scoping out chicks
at the dance bar, and having to pretend I was loving it, man _
loving it! In fact, I was hating it. I was inadequate, I didn't fit
in, my life was a complete deception . . . As I crunched back
through the cold crisp air, under the stars, feeling so left out, I
realized that my life was absolutely, completely hopeless. I sat
down in the snow, alone, and cried.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobias remembers himself as a profoundly ``out of it'' child who
grew up on Fifth Avenue and spent weekends at the family's country
house in Bedford in Westchester County. His father was an
advertising executive; his mother adored him. Tobias went to Horace
Mann in Riverdale and then Harvard, where he was better at making
money than going to class. By the time he graduated in 1968, he had
put ``Let's Go,'' then a slender Harvard Student Agencies guide to
Europe, into the black.
</P>
<P>
   He became a writer for New York magazine, then a financial
columnist for Esquire and in 1973 published ``The Best Little Boy
in the World,'' his first memoir about growing up gay, under a pen
name. The book became a classic among gay men, and 25 years later
was re-issued by the Modern Library, this time with Tobias' name
and picture on the front cover. ``The Best Little Boy in the World
Grows Up'' was published simultaneously by Random House.
</P>
<P>
   Tobias told his parents and friends about his homosexuality in
the 1970s, but did not come out publicly until the early 1990s. His
partner is Charles Nolan, who designs the Ellen Tracy clothing line
with Linda Allard.
</P>
<P>
   Tobias became rich _ a ``tongue in cheek'' vast fortune he hints
is around $10 million _ with a line of personal-finance software,
now obsolete. His salary at the Democratic National Committee will
be $1 a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
