u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-SENATORS-B     02-19 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SENATORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFELESS BRUINS LEFT SPINNING WHEELS AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANATA, Ontario _ They're consistent, but that's the pain and
not the pleasure. In a season fast unraveling, a playoff spot
growing more elusive by the shot, the pass, the shift, the Bruins
suffered their third straight loss Thursday night, a 2-0 blanking
at the hands of the playoff-charged-and-ready Ottawa Senators.
</P>
<P>
   Behind by two goals in less than seven minutes of the first
period, the Bruins watched the Senators rev up their skating game,
sharpen their penalty-killing knives, and proficiently put away
what amounted to a ho-hum victory (No. 31 vs. Boston's 22).
</P>
<P>
   ``We won the battle of the special teams,'' said Senators coach
Jacques Martin, who watched netminder Ron Tugnutt chalk up the
sixth shutout against the Bruins this season, the third in the last
month. ``And we won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss also dropped the Bruins another rung in their quest for
a playoff berth in the Eastern Conference. The Canadiens, with a
3-1 win in Philadelphia, slipped past Boston into the No. 9 spot in
the conference, still a spot short of the playoff picture. The
Bruins slipped to 10th and now have the Panthers (No. 8) and
dreaded Habs to upend if they're going anywhere come mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how disturbingly consistent the Bruins have become: they
have won only three times in their last 17 games (3-11-3). Thursday
night, they had key contributor Kyle McLaren back on their blue
line, and that made for a tighter picture in their back end. But in
the attacking zone, where they are unable to generate any sustained
pressure or mount good shots, they skate without authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now our confidence is just not where it should be,''
said netminder Byron Dafoe, who absorbed the loss despite stopping
26 of 28 shots. ``We have to hurry up and get on a roll, but
unfortunately that's not as easy as it sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Pat Burns started to alter the offensive approach
early in the second period when he finally moved Dmitri Khristich
off the No. 1 line, where his effectiveness has been next to
nothing for most of the season's second half. Burns bumped
Khristich off the right wing of the No. 1 line and moved Anson
Carter in there, with Sergei Samsonov and Jason Allison, Carter's
old linemate in Washington. What followed wasn't exactly magic _
the trio managed a total of six shots in the second and third
periods _ but at least it was a move that showed some
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to try something,'' said Burns, a noticeable shrug in
his voice. ``We still had no goals to show for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns added that his Bruins could have been ``a little meaner
with their shots.'' Translation: no one showed much of a fight or
snarl to follow up on rebounds or fight through traffic for initial
shots. It was a cordial, spiritless loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators cracked Dafoe only 77 seconds into the game on a
Daniel Alfredsson goal that was meant as nothing more than a
centering pass off the right wing board. His back to the net,
wanting only to keep the puck deep, the talented Swede swept in a
backhander that first eluded Carter on the way in and then
ricocheted in off one of McLaren's gloves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost it on the way in,'' said Dafoe. ``In fact, I lost it
twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexei Yashin scored the second _ and last _ for the Senators on
a power play at 6:21 (Dave Ellett off for roughing). The big,
mobile slot man slid into the middle and nailed a one-time slapper
off a pretty feed from Andreas Johansson.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators are young, fast, and deep. They play an aggressive
trap, always ready to spring two forecheckers, preying off mid-ice
transitions. The Bruins try to play the same way, but lack the legs
and talent to be as forceful with the forecheck. When they do
trigger good scoring opportunities, they lack the polish to
convert.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, they've clearly been exposed as understaffed
and undertalented, and the lack of passion in their game says they
know it. They might not admit it, but they know it. They work, but
it's more going through the motions than it is going with the
gusto. The follow-through that so many expected from last season _
the particular hope of the front office _ instead has fallen flat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
