<HEADLINE>
EX-UNIVERSAL STUDIOS BOSS SIGNS DEAL WITH KING WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Frank Biondi, who left the top slot at Universal
Studios three months ago, has agreed to a consulting deal with
syndicated TV producer King World Productions Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Biondi, who resigned after ``Meet Joe Black'' opened to
disappointing grosses, will work in strategic planning and
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The naming of Biondi, who also has headed Home Box Office and
Viacom, likely signals that cash-rich King World is looking for
deals. ``With a billion dollars in cash reserves, long-term
contract renewals for `Wheel of Fortune,' `Jeopardy!' and `The
Oprah Winfrey Show' and the recent success of `Hollywood Squares,'
King World has never been stronger,'' Biondi said in a written
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Biondi's departure from Universal, where he had been chairman
and chief executive officer, came after a long string of dismal
performances at the box office and a decision by Edgar Bronfman
Jr., chief executive of Seagram Co., to take more direct control of
Universal. Biondi left Viacom in 1996 when Chairman Sumner Redstone
took a similar course.
</P>
<P>
   Biondi will receive more than $25 million from Seagram to settle
his contract, which was to expire in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Biondi has been criticized by some analysts for not exerting
enough hands-on control over costly projects, but others regard him
as an astute player in the complex world of entertainment
financing. Before joining HBO in 1978, he was an investment banker.
</P>
<P>
   Recent speculation about Biondi was that he might form a
partnership with Wall Street investor Richard Reiss to back media
companies. Biondi and Reiss reportedly were seeking to raise $150
million to $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
