<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-OILERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUCK BOUNCES KINGS' WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Kings' 3-2 victory over the
Edmonton Oilers before 11,287 at the Forum on Thursday night might,
or might not, merely prolong the agony that has accompanied Los
Angeles' disappointing 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   But the agony of losing to the Oilers just hours after being
lectured by an angry Dave Taylor wasn't a very appealing option.
</P>
<P>
   A defeat would have left the Kings 10 points out of a playoff
spot and certainly out of the good graces of their general manager.
</P>
<P>
   But the bounces were going the Kings' way on Thursday and they
pulled within six points of the eighth-place Oilers as they prepare
for a six-game road trip that begins Saturday in Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the hockey gods were showing their kindness early when
defenseman Philippe Boucher used his hockey stick like a pool cue
and bounced a shot off the boards for his first goal of the season
two minutes into the game. Strangely enough, Boucher, who has spent
much of the season in the press box, was the offensive catalyst,
recording a career-high three points.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game of follow the bouncing puck in the first period
and Mikhail Shtalenkov wasn't good at it. The Edmonton goalie was
pulled after allowing three goals on 12 shots in the first 18
minutes of play.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' 26th-ranked power play opened the scoring when
Boucher's dump-in bounced off the left-wing boards and went into an
empty Edmonton net after Shtalenkov had left the crease to play the
anticipated bounce.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings took a 2-0 lead at 5:15 when Luc Robitaille, while
falling down, got his stick on Boucher's shot from the right point.
The goal was Robitaille's 30th of the season and 900th point as a
King. Robitaille has scored 30-plus goals nine times in a season,
all with the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Selivanov, who scored three third-period goals at
Anaheim on Wednesday, scored on a deflection at 12:38 of the first
period to pull the Oilers within a goal. He then tied game on a
breakaway goal at 14:50. But good fortune continued to go the Kings
way when Steve Duchesne's 60-footer hit the stick of an Oilers
defenseman and fooled Shtalenkov at 17:52.
</P>
<P>
   The puck and the game settled down in the second period. Neither
team scored and they combined for just nine shots on goal. The
Kings, however, missed two great chances to take a two-goal lead.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes into the period Olli Jokinen took a nice pass from
Vladimir Tsyplakov in the right circle and hit the right post with
half of the net open.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the period Marty McSorley fanned on his shot
attempt from the point and Robitaille started off on a clear
breakaway. The Kings winger went for lower left corner of the net,
but Essensa knocked it wide.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton's best chance came on a power play when one of the Los
Angeles penalty killers flipped an ill-advised pass into the slot
and Stephane Fiset was forced to make a scrambling save.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 0155EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
