<SLUG> BC-BKN-RODMAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN INSISTS IT'S A GO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dennis Rodman is ready to sign with the Los
Angeles Lakers. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with knowing for certain is that the source of the
information this time is Rodman himself, and that means nothing can
be taken at face value.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's editions of the Chicago Sun-Times, Rodman said he
planned to sign a one-year contract either Thursday or today. But
Thursday passed without a signing, and the Lakers have indicated
they do not expect anything to happen today either.
</P>
<P>
   But Rodman insists he's coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's do it,'' he told the Sun-Times, in his first public
comments on the matter. ``The media has been saying, `Dennis Rodman
is broke, over the hill, not happy and can't play anymore.' But
what else is new? People have always been counting Dennis Rodman
out and telling lies. So that's not going to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good (and) I feel like playing again.''
</P>
<P>
   The team confirmed that Rodman and Lakers owner Jerry Buss met
after Wednesday night's game between the Lakers and Dallas
Mavericks, but the result of that meeting is unclear. It was the
first face-to-face meeting Rodman has had with any team official in
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rodman is scheduled to appear today on ESPN's
``UpClose'' at 3 p.m. perhaps to explain the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Buss himself extended the invitation to the eccentric former
Chicago Bull _ over the strong objections of Lakers management _
about three weeks ago. But Rodman has been slow to accept the deal
for the veterans minimum salary, $12,195 per game, because it's far
below his market value.
</P>
<P>
   Yet no one else wants the seven-time rebounding champion or can
pay him the millions he once commanded, so it's a mystery why he
has dragged out the process, unless one simply assumes he's pumping
it for the publicity.
</P>
<P>
   His explanation: ``I had to take my time and do what's best for
Dennis Rodman. (There is) no rush. I'm a free agent. They can't pay
me what I'm worth anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   His sister and business adviser, Debra Rodman, said she had
spoken with the Lakers and also indicated he would sign the deal
Thursday or today.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't know if he'll suit up to play Friday night or
Sunday, because he's probably got to go through at least a couple
of practices with them,'' Debra Rodman said. ``Personally, I'm
happy to see him getting back out on the court, because this is
something he really loves doing and is something he's really good
at.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just had to take some extra time to rest, because he has
been so busy going nonstop for three years playing ball, shooting
movies, doing TV shows and making personal appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he recently got married (to actress Carmen Electra). And
he never felt the need to hurry because, let's face it, the league
will be making a hell of a lot more money off of Dennis than he
will be making off of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 0200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0052 </DOCNO>
