<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1259 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-NETS-HNS &LR;      02-19 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-NETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Rockets were running on fumes and
adrenalin. Scottie Pippen, who had made just about every play he
could have, was barely moving as he backpedaled.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The final seconds of a game that could have been sacrificed to
the realities of the lockout-season schedule were slipping away,
and Pippen, who understandably could have collapsed, fell down.
</P>
<P>
   Had Scott Burrell squeezed into a size 13, the Rockets and New
Jersey Nets might still be playing. Instead, Burrell was called for
tripping Pippen, who got up to sink a free throw with 3.3 seconds
left in overtime and give the Rockets a 93-92 victory Thursday
night at Continental Airlines Arena, completing their third game in
as many nights with a stunning comeback win.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is big, big, big, big, big,'' said Rockets forward
Othella Harrington, who finished with 12 points and 12 rebounds.
``Things weren't right for us in the first half, but we hung tough
and kept closing, closing, closing, until we got a great win for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an impressive victory because of the schedule problems
and just how poorly the Rockets had started the game, trailing by
as many as 13 in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   It also was remarkable because, after getting whipped on the
boards in Minnesota the night before and playing their third game
without Charles Barkley, the Rockets outrebounded the Nets and
rebound machine Jayson Williams 57-39.
</P>
<P>
   And it was most inexplicable because as worn as the Rockets
clearly were by the road, they grew stronger defensively as the
game went on, limiting the Nets to two field goals in the final two
minutes of regulation and overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said of his
team's last-legs defense. ``I love that stuff. That's how we used
to win in the old days. It wasn't always pretty. But when we got in
the huddle, we're talking about defensive assignments, instead of,
`You missed me.' We're heading in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets turned back that way when, after a late-first-half
rally, they found themselves back in a game they could win and,
with back-to-back games at Miami and Orlando over the weekend, one
they might have needed.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, after a horrid first-half performance, took over in the
third quarter, scoring six points and getting four assists. He
finished with a season-high 26 points.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes into the fourth quarter, Michael Dickerson (14
points, five rebounds) drove the baseline for a 75-74 lead, the
Rockets' first of the night. But with 2:35 left in regulation, the
Nets led 84-83 and the Rockets needed a stop.
</P>
<P>
   From then on, the Rockets got every defensive stop they could
want. Pippen switched defensive assignments to battle Keith Van
Horn in the low post, and the Nets forward missed his three
remaining shots in regulation. With an 84-81 lead, the Nets then
missed five consecutive shots, including a Pippen block of a Van
Horn jumper at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets pushed their lead to 85-83 with 12.8 seconds left in
regulation on an Eric Murdock free throw. But with 4.4 seconds
remaining, Hakeem Olajuwon took a quick dribble to his left and hit
a 17-footer to force overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets led for most of the overtime, but with 1:14 left,
Pippen knocked the ball loose from Van Horn only to have it bounce
off Brent Price's shoulder and back to Van Horn, forcing Price to
foul. Van Horn hit both free throws to tie it at 90.
</P>
<P>
   Williams appeared to poke the ball loose from Olajuwon on the
next possession, but Murdock was called for a foul and Olajuwon hit
both free throws for a 92-90 lead with 53.4 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn then scored immediately for another tie, and the Nets
had their chance to grab the victory when Harrington came up short
inside, finding himself open too late to get off a good shot over
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Kittles then drove for what could have been the
game-winner, but as the ball ricocheted off the rim and appeared to
be headed back in, Williams went up to give the ball a tap and was
called for offensive basket interference, giving the Rockets their
chance.
</P>
<P>
   With Olajuwon (21 points, 15 rebounds) looking to get rid of the
ball, he turned to Pippen, only to have Pippen fall and the ball
sail out of bounds. Burrell, however, was called for tripping
Pippen, the Nets screamed and Pippen took the line to give the
Rockets the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a foul,'' Pippen said. ``I was tripped. It was obvious.
He tried to overplay me, and he tripped me, the same as he did in
practice all last year (with the Bulls).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
