<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOURCE: MARTINEZ MAY DEPART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ In the back corner of the Los Angeles Dodgers
clubhouse, amid the names of prospects and stars, is a locker for
Ramon Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Strange thing is, Martinez isn't a Dodger. And it's looking more
and more like he won't be unless something changes.
</P>
<P>
   A source said a deal with another organization could come
quickly, but that Martinez's camp is weighing the option of waiting
for a more lucrative deal. A source also said, as of events of the
past few weeks, he didn't anticipate Martinez returning to the
Dodgers organization.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander, who's been in the Dodgers system since 1985,
remains in the Dominican Republic rehabilitating his surgically
repaired right shoulder. And he's there without a contract.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez last pitched June 14. Two weeks later he had surgery to
repair a tear in his rotator cuff. The prognosis was he wouldn't be
ready to pitch at the major-league level until late May.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got an invitation to come in and work out here as a free
agent,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said. ``We'll
continue to rehabilitate him and continue to do everything we can
to get him ready to pitch. It's my understanding that when he gets
closer to being game ready, he'll make a decision on where he wants
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez isn't scheduled to arrive in the United States until
the second week of March.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers physical therapist Pat Screnar saw Martinez three weeks
ago at a workout at Dodger Stadium and said the veteran was on
schedule. Martinez, who went 7-3 with a 2.83 ERA before injuring
his arm last season, is 123-77 with a 3.45 ERA since joining the
Dodgers in 1988 but has missed parts of the past two seasons with
shoulder injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``His progress to this point has gone well,'' Screnar said.
``He's been on a throwing program for the last couple of months and
he continues to improve his strength. His throwing to this point is
just on flat ground. He hasn't been off the mound yet. Everything
we've seen, to this date, has been positive to his return.''
</P>
<P>
   Granting Clemency: Malone was curious to see where Roger Clemens
wound up, and had a grin when he learned that the five-time Cy
Young Award winner had gone to the American League instead of to
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   And before the Dodgers signed Kevin Brown to the $105 million
free-agent contract in December, Malone said he was intrigued about
the opportunity of acquiring Clemens from the Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to someone about it, but after we got Kevin Brown
(the talk ended),'' Malone said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 0204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1262 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     02-19 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRAN BLINEBURY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ When the third game in three nights goes
into overtime and you tiptoe off to the bus with a one-point win,
there is usually talk of the little things.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Munchkin Brent Price shows that he's part kangaroo and leaps to
grab hold of two critical offensive rebounds coming down the
stretch. The perpetual-motion machine Othella Harrington sprints
out of the paint to get a fingertip on Keith Van Horn's last,
desperate 25-foot shot. There is a tripping call by a rookie
referee, a reach-in call by a veteran whistle-blower.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Scottie Pippen. Nothing little there.
</P>
<P>
   This is why the Rockets were contortionists and nearly bent
themselves out of shape trying to get him.
</P>
<P>
   This is exactly what they have been expecting all along.
</P>
<P>
   Learning to fit in is fine for a start. Easing into a comfort
zone is all right for a while.
</P>
<P>
   But taking control is what the Rockets need.
</P>
<P>
   And taking over is what Pippen did in the second half of the
wacky, wild, scrappy, hustling 93-92 win over the Nets on Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   With injuries to Charles Barkley, Antoine Carr, Rodrick Rhodes
and Stanley Roberts already crippling them, this most grueling
stretch of the compressed schedule was threatening to bury the
Rockets beneath a blizzard of fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Until Pippen rose up and howled like the storm of the century.
Give me what I want, and I'll go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to have a lot more control of what was happening in
this game after what happened in Minnesota,'' Pippen said. ``I
thought that we let the fatigue get to us in that one. I thought
that a game that we had some control over got away from us. I
thought that we had a breakdown in our composure and our
concentration, and I didn't want it to happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``So at halftime (of the Nets game), I kind of told myself that
it was time to step up and take on a lot more of a leadership role.
I haven't tried to take over since I've been here with this team. I
haven't tried to force myself into any situations. But I did
believe that this situation called for me to do something
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Something bigger. Something better. Something special. Something
quite reminiscent of his days with the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen scored 18 of his game-high 26 points in the second half
and grabbed five of his six rebounds then. It was after the
intermission when he picked up five of his six assists and all four
of his steals.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Scottie Pippen of all those years and all those
playoff games, using those long arms to get into the passing lanes
and knock balls loose to start fast breaks in the other direction.
This was a charging, slashing Pippen lowering his head and going to
the basket.
</P>
<P>
   This was a sure, confident Pippen running the offense from the
point-forward position, the blender who mixed all of the
ingredients in the Rockets' grittiest effort of the young season
and turned it into victory.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the Astros might have had with Roger Clemens on the
mound, a proven winner who knows what has to be done and just does
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't necessarily want me or need me to score all the
points or take all of the shots,'' Pippen said. ``But they do want
me to make plays and get things going.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Pippen running the show in the second half, taking the
quarterback burden off Price and allowing the point guard to roam
free and get those big offensive rebounds. It was Pippen directing
traffic, allowing Harrington _ Charles Lite _ to bang away on the
inside for his 12 points and 12 boards. It was Pippen who, from the
midway point in the fourth quarter, teamed with Hakeem Olajuwon's
21 points and 15 rebounds to carry the load.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt comfortable,'' Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely enough, that may have been in part due to Barkley's
absence. Pippen has more room to operate. He has less concern with
trying to stay out of the path of another charging bull.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're darn right it's easier,'' Pippen said, smiling. ``We're
not calling `4-hold' for Charles all the time, which means I stand
around spotting up for a shot. That's not my game. I like motion. I
like the movement to create my opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen found enough of those opportunities to score nine points
in the fourth quarter, and he and Olajuwon combined for 17 of the
Rockets' final 23 in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a lot of fun for me,'' he said. ``This is the kind of
role I envisioned, and when Charles and the other guys get back, I
think we're going to be able to raise our game. This was a good
step in the right direction for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is straight ahead, not looking back. Pippen is now the
only member of the defending champions not to have received his
1998 championship ring. A couple of weeks ago, that bothered him.
Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them to keep it up there in Chicago,'' he said. ``Why
do I need to wear a Bulls ring in Houston? Maybe I'll get myself
another here.''
</P>
<P>
   A night like this could be a start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
