<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NISSAN-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRATTON MAKES MOST OF STROKES OF GOOD FORTUNE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Alan Bratton, who needed to win a playoff in
gathering darknesss to earn the final qualifying berth for this
week's Nissan Open, sits one stroke off the tournament lead today.
</P>
<P>
   Bratton's first-round 67, a 4-under-par effort including six
birdies, left him tied with Loren Roberts, Nick Price, Kirk
Triplett and Kevin Sutherland, a stroke back of tournament
co-leaders David Duval and Bob Estes.
</P>
<P>
   Bratton earned his Nissan berth by shooting 6-under-par 66 in a
qualifying event Monday at Los Serranos North, then defeating
reigning U.S. Junior Amateur champion James Oh in a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   So close: Valencia's Jason Gore, who finished 26th in last
week's Buick Invitational as a qualifier, just missed Monday's
playoff at Los Serranos, shooting a 67.
</P>
<P>
   Price check: Nick Price, playing the Nissan in an attempt to get
ready for next week's World Match Play Championships, shot 67 to
trail the leaders by one stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Price's 4-under par, four-birdie, no-bogey showing was his first
since playing two weeks ago in South Africa. Price said he finished
eighth in that tournament and ``didn't play well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to take time off,'' said Price. ``I was able to
sleep in the same bed for 30 straight nights and I haven't done
that for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucky shot: Kazuhiko Hosokawa, a pro from the Japanese Tour
playing on a sponsor's exemption, recorded the day's luckiest shot.
</P>
<P>
   On the famed bunker-on-the-green No.6, Hosokawa hit his tee shot
over the hole. The ball bounced off a sprinkler cover, appeared to
hit a sitting fan, then rolled to within two feet of the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Hosokawa, who shot 73, made the birdie putt and tossed the ball
to the fan in the gallery. Baseball angle: Former Dodgers general
manager Fred Claire is not at spring training in Vero Beach, Fla.,
for the first time since 1968. Instead, he attended the Nissan
Open.
</P>
<P>
   Claire was telling baseball stories in the press tent Thursday
morning when his wife, Cheryl, tugged on his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard these stories before, Fred,'' she said. ``I want to
see some golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to school: Corey Pavin spent the night before the
tournament attending the USC-UCLA basketball game. Pavin played
golf at UCLA. He didn't fare quite as well as the Bruins did,
however, shooting a 1-over par 72, which placed him six strokes off
the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Chip of the day: Phil Mickelson might have had the prettiest
chip of the day Thursday. On the par-3 16th hole, Mickelson hit his
tee shot near the edge of a bunker adjacent to the green. With his
feet planted just on the edge of the bunker, Mickelson calmly
pitched the ball about 20 feet and straight into the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't overpower the course here, you have to be patient,''
Mickelson said. ``The course tempts you, but you have to be
patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowd control: Thursday's opening round was ideal for
spectators. There was plenty of room in the galleries for fans to
find a place to watch, even on the 18th green when co-leader David
Duval concluded his round. The announced attendance Thursday was
13,652. Last year's opening round at Valencia drew 11,480 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Golf weather: The cloudy skies didn't bother the golfers, and
they should be able to get used to them. Today's forecast is for
mostly cloudy skies with some peaks of sunshine in the afternoon
and a high of 59. Saturday's forecast is cloudiness in the morning,
with partly cloudy skies in the afternoon and a high of 68.
</P>
<P>
   No one is complaining about the cool weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was going to be sunny today, but it never
happened,'' Duval said. ``It worked out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
