<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KURD-EUROPE (Berlin) _ Political divisions have long undermined
the scattered Kurds in their battle for a homeland. But for the
overwhelming majority of the estimated 850,000 Kurds now living in
Europe, it is clear that Abdullah Ocalan's arrest has constituted a
moment when differences are swept away, however fleetingly, by a
shared sense of outrage. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KURD-TURKEY (Istanbul, Turkey) _ All eyes turned Thursday toward
a small island in the Sea of Marmara where the Turks' most hated
enemy is being held prisoner. The principal Kurdish guerrilla
leader, Abdullah Ocalan, is now the sole prisoner on the island of
Imrali. Naval boats have been deployed around Imrali, which lies 35
miles southwest of Istanbul, and military helicopters patrol
overhead. By Stephen Kinzer. With map.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-CHRISTIANS (Gandhinagar, India) _ Despite the hostility to
Christians in Gujarat, where Hindu militants have attacked dozens
of Christian prayer halls and schools over the last year, several
Hindu nationalist leaders have chosen to have their offspring
educated by those same reviled Roman Catholic missionaries, who
happen to have a reputation for running some of the finest schools
in the state. By Celia W. Dugger. With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-FINANCES (Jerusalem) _ A strong and somewhat unexpected
show of support from Jordan's neighbors is helping King Abdullah's
new regime gain its financial footing. By William A. Orme. Jr. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DRUGS-MUSIC (San Luis Potosi, Mexico) _ The Tucanes are
one of the most successful of hundreds of Mexican country bands
whose lyrics chronicle drug traffickers' daily lives and violent
routines. The extraordinary popularity of their music here and in
the United States underscores the profound roots the drug industry
has sunk into North American popular culture, suggesting that
millions of fans quietly admire the smugglers' fabled wealth,
anti-establishment bravura and bold entrepreneurial skills. By Sam
Dillon. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-IMMIGRANT-VOICES (New York) _ Blacks' fear of the police, and
whites' struggle to understand it, is not a new story. But with
crime lower than it has been in a generation in New York City, the
shooting of Amadou Diallo, a West African immigrant, has become a
new lens through which people view their relationships with the
police, and the stark contrasts that mark life in the city's
disparate but connected communities. By Ginger Thompson and Jodi
Wilgoren. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   CRUISE-LOOPHOLES (Miami) _ Doing business under a decades-old
loophole in the tax code, the growing cruise ship industry pays no
income taxes in the United States even though its companies are
based here and 90 percent of its passengers are Americans. The
industry also does not observe the nation's labor laws, minimum
wage law and many environmental and safety regulations. By Douglas
Frantz. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ELEPHANTS-VIRUS (Undated) _ The death of a much-loved baby
elephant at the National Zoo in 1995 of a previously unknown virus
that researchers think is a major cause of death worldwide among
young elephants in captivity, and a serious threat to their
conservation in zoos. Discovery of the virus has also led to the
identification of a drug that can cure the illness, but it is not
an ideal solution. Part of the problem apparently stems from mixing
African and Asian elephants, which are separate species, in
captivity. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   SMITH-POLITICS (Wolfeboro, N.H.) _ Sen. Bob Smith on Thursday
became the first candidate to formally announce his candidacy for
president. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BIAS (Novato, Calif.) _ People have painted Novato, a
Marin County town, as a county aberration, a place where hate
crimes happen. But Cynthia Murray, a Marin County supervisor from
Novato, said that perception was not reality. ``One of the things
that is happening is that we take hate crimes very seriously,'' Ms.
Murray said. ``It has given us a reputation for having bias
incidents. We sort of get punished for reporting every incident
that other towns wouldn't.'' By Evelyn Nieves. With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JUSTICE-STARR (Washington) _ The Justice Department is
considering whether to appoint a special investigative prosecutor
to conduct its inquiry into charges of possible misconduct by
Kenneth Starr, government officials said Thursday. By David
Johnston and Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   EMBASSY-SECURITY (Washington) _ The retired chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff who led a State Department investigation of
bombings of two U.S. embassies in Africa last summer said on
Thursday that the department is so frightened of seeking money from
Congress that other embassies could be left vulnerable to terrorist
attacks. Adm. William J. Crowe Jr. said the embassy security budget
that the State Department requested this month was clearly
inadequate and would leave American diplomats abroad vulnerable. By
Philip Shenon and James Risen. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ACCOUNTANT-SHORTAGE (New York) _ From Georgetown University to
the University of Colorado, the number of students graduating with
accounting degrees this spring will be only half of what it was a
few years ago. The profession's largest and most powerful group has
proposed a plan aimed at making the job more attractive by, in
part, reducing the requirements. But some accountants, regulators
and investors adamantly oppose that plan, saying it makes about as
much sense as lowering the standards for emergency-room nurses or
police officers. By Melody Petersen. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Using internal company
documents and sworn depositions in the Microsoft trial, a
government lawyer was able Thursday to depict Compaq Computer Corp.
as ever fearful of Microsoft _ so much so that Compaq repeatedly
abandoned the software products it preferred in favor of
Microsoft's offerings. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   BANKBOSTON-BRAZIL (Boston) _ BankBoston, the oldest bank in the
nation, is being buffeted by fears that Brazil's economic crisis
may overwhelm it. The bank has also been embarrassed by financial
scandal, trading losses and an untimely and expensive acquisition.
Its stock has plunged from its 52-week high at a time when mergers
are sweeping the banking industry, and as a result, the bank is now
seen by many analysts as takeover bait. By Timothy L. O'Brien. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BONDS (Tokyo) _ National bonds have become the center of a
policy debate between politicians and economic policy-makers over
how to pull Japan out of a deflationary spiral and its prolonged
recession, the worst since the end of World War II. By Sheryl
WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   SYNDICATE-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ In an unusual experiment, a
giant agency, Ogilvy &AMP; Mather North America, will affiliate with
seven independent shops that are small in size but loom large in
creative abilities. The partnership, called the Syndicate, will
operate as a secondary agency network for Ogilvy North America. By
Stuart Elliott. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SARGENT-ART-REVIEW (Washington) _ The big Sargent retrospective
opening Sunday at the National Gallery and a smaller companion show
of a few dozen of his drawings at the Corcoran Gallery. By Michel
Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   APPLES-PHOENIX (Phoenix, Ariz.) _ This is a city well named. It
may not have arisen, like the fabulous bird of Egyptian mythology,
from its own ashes, but, like the original phoenix, this one sprang
to life in a desert. It owes its existence to modern technology.
Without large-scale irrigation and without air-conditioning,
Phoenix as it now exists _ the sprawling, verdant, dynamic center
of a metropolitan area of more than 2.8 million people _ would have
been utterly unthinkable. By R.W. Apple Jr. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   CONTINUUM-SACHS (New York) _ A look at Continuum, a new music
ensemble, and its co-director, Joel Sachs. By Allan Kozinn. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-WOMEN-FASHION (New York) _ A review of women's fashion
collections by Ellen Tracy, Anna Sui, Xuly Bet, Jill Stuart and
Zang Toi. By Anne-Marie Schiro. With photos. (Moved in `l'
category)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROSENTHAL-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Western democracies, sometimes
separately, sometimes together, are working out a historic policy:
Reward selected terrorist nations for their crimes. Commentary by
A.M. Rosenthal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ March 1, 2000 _ For the second time
in the past century, the United States today occupied Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. landing force was led by the newly designated secretary
of defense, Robert Rubin, and the newly designated chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Lawrence Summers. The U.S. force
immediately seized control of the Bank of Japan and the Ministry of
Finance. Commentary by Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-CLEMENS (Tampa, Fla.) _ In a startling trade, the New
York Yankees acquired Roger Clemens, a five-time winner of the Cy
Young award, in exchange for David Wells, a colorful and very
valuable member of the 1998 championship team. In obtaining
Clemens, the Yankees now have one of the best pitchers of the 20th
century on their roster and conceivably could be even more
dominating in 1999 than they were in 1998. But in losing Wells, the
Yankees will now be without a pitcher who had one of the best
postseason records in baseball history. By Buster Olney. With
photos and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on
David Wells, perhaps the most colorful of all the Yankees of the
great 1998 team and a perfect-game pitcher to boot, and now off to
Toronto in exchange for Roger Clemens. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-REACT (Tampa) _ Yankee players react to the big trade,
which gives them a future Hall of Fame pitcher but leaves them
without a very dependable and very colorful player who was so
instrumental in the overwhelming success of the 1998 team. By Jack
Curry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
