<HEADLINE>
SALUTE TO WHITTINGHAM IS NO RETIREMENT PARTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Men like Charlie Whittingham never get
retirement dinners, and it's not because they don't deserve the
toasts and testimonials.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't retire,'' said Jack Mandato, a thoroughbred owner
who's been a friend of Whittingham for nearly 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   So Mandato, co-owner of Charlie G's Prime Steak House, is giving
the Hall of Fame trainer something just as good, a dinner Monday
night to mark the dedication of a room in his name at the recently
opened restaurant in Tarzana.
</P>
<P>
   The room is decorated with plaques and winner's circle photos
from some of the 600 stakes victories recorded by Whittingham, who
has ruled the sport for decades like a racetrack Bear Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Given his accomplishments _ three Eclipse Awards for training,
11 national champions, two Kentucky Derby winners, eight Santa
Anita Handicap winners, etc. _ you could fill a shopping-mall food
court with Whittingham memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is Charlie one of a kind and probably one of the best
there ever was or will be in his profession, but he's also one hell
of a man,'' said Mandato, of Westlake Village. ``He's the most
unassuming legend I've ever met.''
</P>
<P>
   And no, he's not retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Whittingham, who will be 86 on April 13, has been battered in
recent months by the loss of sight in one eye, by a bout with
pneumonia, and by a fall last week that left him with a fractured
right elbow and two black eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You oughta see the other guy,'' he jokes when he pulls off his
dark glasses to reveal the bruises to a visitor.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the pneumonia, which forced his longest absence from
the track since his days as a World War II Marine, the maladies
haven't kept him away from his Santa Anita barn.
</P>
<P>
   He's still out of bed at 3:30 a.m. The difference is that he
doesn't get to the track until after dawn now _ wife Peggy drives _
to avoid the cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything else (but racing),'' Whittingham said
wryly. ``Staying in bed's not very enjoyable after a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Whittingham doesn't do the hands-on horsemanship anymore. But he
doesn't have to. Son Michael moved his own horses into Charlie's
barn last spring and acts as assistant trainer. Pony rider Jeanie
Lockett doubles as a steadying hand for the boss.
</P>
<P>
   Between Charlie's and Michael's horses, the barn is alive with
19 runners, plus a well-fed Australian Shepherd named Ferdinand
after Whittingham's 1986 Kentucky Derby winner.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie's horses won only 10 races in 1998. But just when you
thought he was fading away, he sent an 8-1 shot to the Gulfstream
Park Breeders' Cup Sprint Championship in Florida last Saturday and
the horse came within an unlucky neck of winning the $200,000 race.
</P>
<P>
   The horse, a son of Ferdinand, is co-owned by Mandato, who named
him Young at Heart in a nod to Whittingham and an octogenarian
uncle. Young at Heart's mother is Bannockburn, a freakishly fast
sprinter who happened to be the first horse Whittingham trained for
Mandato.
</P>
<P>
   They met in 1980 when Mandato was running his fleet-management
consulting firm in Maryland and Whittingham was visiting Laurel
Race Course to run Perrault in the Washington D.C. International.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy who, I think, has trained for the Queen and
people like that, but he always made sure I was taken care of at
the track, always made sure I was invited to dinner because he knew
I didn't know anybody (in California),'' Mandato said, explaining
his affection.
</P>
<P>
   Others relate tales of Whittingham's harder edge with equal
affection.
</P>
<P>
   Like when Charlie was due to get out of the hospital after 12
days in December, and Michael was late arriving to pick him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike, is that you?'' said Charlie, who'd been dozing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What the (bleep), did you take the bus?''
</P>
<P>
   Michael, who made his own mark on the sport by training 1986
Breeders' Cup Classic winner Skywalker, had resisted the idea of
working with his father, preferring to establish his own identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have done it years ago,'' said Michael, 52. ``I never
realized how great it is to be around him all the time. I'm
savoring every moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael isn't sure if his dad has come to grips with the
possibility he has trained his last champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he knows he's winding down,'' the son said. ``Of
course, he might get some (good) horses and that could change. He's
been up and down many times in his life. He's always been an
optimist. That's what's kept him strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandato hopes 150 people _ including jockeys, trainers and other
racetrack stars _ will attend Monday's dinner. Tickets are $125, to
be donated to the Don MacBeth Memorial Jockey Fund for injured and
ill riders. Information: (818) 654-0387.
</P>
<P>
   71 days to the Derby: The week's fork in the road for Kentucky
Derby candidates is the Fountain of Youth Stakes at Gulfstream. At
midweek, the probables included Aly's Alley, Casanova Star, Cat
Thief, Certain, Doneraile Court, Grits'n Hard Toast, Legal Street,
The Groom is Red and Vicar.
</P>
<P>
   News of other 3-year-olds:
</P>
<P>
   _Unbeaten colt Cape Canaveral, trained by D. Wayne Lukas,
suffered a stress fracture to his right front shin and will miss
the Kentucky Derby, Bloomberg News reported. He could return to
racing by late summer.
</P>
<P>
   _Epic Honor became this year's Northern California hope by
adding the Golden State Mile at Bay Meadows on Monday to his Golden
Gate Derby win last month. The colt and jockey Lonnie Meche had a
rough trip to a three-length victory.
</P>
<P>
   _Bob and Beverly Lewis' Straight Man debuted with a four-length
victory in 1:08.82 for 6 furlongs Sunday at Santa Anita. That eased
the sting for trainer Bob Baffert of Finder's Gold's last-place
finish in his first try against winners earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   _Baffert's champion filly Silverbulletday makes her '99 debut at
the New Orleans Fair Grounds in Saturday's Davona Dale. Gary
Stevens rides.
</P>
<P>
   _Bobby Frankel-trained Honest Lady will face colts _ including
Baffert's Prime Timber _ in the Feb. 28 San Rafael at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A WEEK AT THE RACES
</P>
<P>
   Santa Anita leaders: Jockeys (going into Thursday): Alex Solis,
39 winners; David Flores, 32; Chris McCarron and Laffit Pincay, 29;
Gary Stevens, 26. Trainers: Bob Baffert, 21; Bobby Frankel, 12; Ron
McAnally, 11; Vladimir Cerin and Richard Mandella,
10.!tvspt2!Handicapper helper:!off! Front-running horses held on to
win a perfectly normal 7 of 28 races at Santa Anita over the
three-day weekend. But look closer: Pacesetters in 6-furlong races
won 5 of 6; pacesetters at other distances on dirt and turf won 2
of 22.
</P>
<P>
   On the stakes schedule: At Santa Anita: Saturday, $100,000 Boo
La Boo Stakes, 3-year-old fillies bred in California, 6 furlongs,
and $75,000 San Marino Handicap, 4-year-olds and up, 1\ miles on
turf; Sunday, $125,000 Las Flores Handicap, fillies and mares 4 and
up, 6 furlongs. At Gulfstream Park: Saturday, $200,000 Fountain of
Youth, 3-year-olds, 1 1/16 miles. At the Fair Grounds: Saturday,
$125,000 Davona Dale, 3-year-old fillies, 1 mile 70 yards; Sunday,
$125,000 Risen Star, 3-year-olds, 1 1/16 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Mileposts: Official word is expected in March that the 2000
Breeders' Cup will be held at Santa Anita.... The 1998 Eclipse
Awards for horses and humans were evenly spread geographically _
seven winners were based in Southern California, seven in the 49
other states and Canada. The bad local news: Skip Away was the
fifth straight Horse of the Year from outside SoCal, which had
dominated.... The U.S. team was named for the March 21
international jockey competition at Santa Anita: Kent Desormeaux,
Julie Krone, Chris McCarron and Mike Smith.... Whitney Tower, the
former Sports Illustrated racing writer who became president and
chairman of the racing Hall of Fame, died last week at 75.... Santa
Anita said it will offer its only ``guaranteed'' pick-six of the
season March 6, the day of the Santa Anita Handicap. If the pool
doesn't reach $1 million, the track will make up the difference. In
a new wrinkle, there would be a carryover instead of a mandatory
payout if nobody has six winners.... John Shirreffs won with seven
straight starters before Weather's eighth-place finish on Saturday
stopped the trainer one short of matching Laz Barrera's Santa
Anita-record streak.... Jockey Isaias Enriquez was happy to end his
streak _ he was 0 for 72 at Santa Anita before Luckyisforever's
victory Friday.... Two wins Monday put Laffit Pincay within 131 of
Bill Shoemaker's career record.... Chris Antley, making a comeback,
rode Winning Crusader on Sunday to the jockey's first Santa Anita
victory since 1997.... Former Hollywood Park exec Rick Baedeker has
another new position. He has gone from VP of marketing for the
National Thoroughbred Racing Association to a similar job with the
Television Games Network. TVG is the yet-to-be-seen 24-hour racing
channel.... Gulfstream Park near Miami plans to review videotape to
correct the clockings of 20 to 30 races whose official times have
been found to be slow by as much as four-fifths of a second (or
about four lengths) because of a system operator's error....
Gulfstream leader Jorge Chavez rode six winners Saturday, one short
of Jerry Bailey's track record.... Blue-collar Hawthorne Race
Course near Chicago opens today for 203 days of racing, the first
95 run by neighboring Sportsman's Park, which is being redone as a
horse and auto racetrack.
</P>
