<SLUG> BC-GLF-NISSANSIDE2-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE BIRDIES SALVAGE PAR FOR SANDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeff Sanday's previous appearance in a PGA Tour event was last
year's Buick Invitational, in which he shot a 9-under-par 63 and
was tied for second after the first round. But a lot has changed
since then.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference is Sanday isn't playing the North Course
at Torrey Pines, where he shot his memorable 63. He is at storied
Riviera Country Club, site of this week's Nissan Open.
</P>
<P>
   Sanday, a resident of South Pasadena and a graduate of Cal State
Northridge, got a first-hand look at Riviera's challenges Thursday
and shot an even-par 71. It could have been worse, but he birdied
two of his last three holes to salvage a good score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel content with even par, because it was starting to get
away from me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He started his round with a birdie from three feet on the par-4,
315-yard 10th hole, but he bogeyed the 11th after driving into the
rough and finished his first nine holes in 1-over 37. He then
birdied the par-5, 503-yard first hole but followed that with
back-to-back bogeys and felt frustration creeping into his game.
</P>
<P>
   Sanday recovered but not before another test of his patience. He
hit what he called ``a perfect 2-iron'' through the green on the
par-3, 236-yard fourth hole, but he got up and down for par after a
difficult chip.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I hit the 2-iron, I thought, `How do you make a par out
here?''' Sanday said. ``It was getting frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   He proceeded to play some of his best golf. He birdied the par-4
seventh hole from three feet and the par-4 eighth hole from eight
feet, and lipped out a 15-footer for birdie on the par-4, 420-yard
ninth hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I started to feel good after I made the par on
(number) four and hit the fairway on five,'' he said. ``I changed
something in my alignment and I hit the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   ``From there, I pretty much didn't miss any shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanday and his caddy, Alhambra's Joe Citro, said hitting the
fairways made all the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he did that, he got it close to the hole,'' Citro said.
``That was the key. Late in the round, he hit the fairways ... on
those two (late) birdies, he had wedges into the green. It made it
a lot easier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf course, I don't think, is that hard,'' said Sanday,
who pointed out he has played only two rounds at Riviera _ one in
practice and one Thursday. ``If you hit the fairway, it's not that
hard. If you miss the fairway, you're dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rough is clumpy and the ball will sit down. You can't even
get to the green from 150 yards. You just don't have enough power
to get it there. You hit the fairway, it's not like you'll hit a
4-iron into every hole. You'll hit a lot of wedges and 9-irons,
even 7-irons. You can shoot low.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 0228EST &QL; 
