<HEADLINE>
STANFORD STOMPS WASHINGTON, 89-57 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ There were airballs and errant passes, too many
mistakes and not enough field goals. For the first time this
season, Washington lost a game at Hec Edmundson Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's defeat was not that surprising, coming as it
did to Stanford, the seventh-ranked team in the country. But the
disparity was: Stanford 89, Washington 57. If the game is any
indication, there are many miles between first place and fourth
place in the Pac-10 Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford, posting its biggest win ever over the Huskies in
Seattle, improved to 11-2 and maintained a one-game lead over
Arizona. The Huskies dropped to 8-6 and are now in precarious
territory. They fell one game behind the third-place Bruins and are
still in the NCAA Tournament picture.
</P>
<P>
   But Cal arrives tomorrow afternoon for what is suddenly a
crucial game. It is one of four remaining, and the Huskies (15-9)
probably will need to go 3-1, perhaps 2-2 to secure a tournament
bid. They play at USC and UCLA next week followed by a home finale
against Washington State on March 6.
</P>
<P>
   If the selection committee members were watching Thursday night,
they would have seen an overmatched team that lacked the firepower
to contend with Stanford. Supposedly vulnerable in light of their
recent play, the Cardinal looked ready for the tournament to begin.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in some time, the Huskies looked sloppy. They
weren't crisp, they didn't rebound, they fumbled the ball and
basically were humbled by a superior team.
</P>
<P>
   In one sequence that captured the evening, Todd MacCulloch lost
control of the ball, flopped to the floor in an attempt to retrieve
it, and watched as Kris Weems picked it up and went the distance
for a layin. A few minutes later, MacCulloch threw a bounce pass to
Grant Leep, hitting him right in the chest. The problem was that
Leep was seated on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd get the ball and I'd just throw it to the other team,''
said MacCulloch.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring 13 points in the first 20 minutes, MacCulloch did
not even take a shot in the second half. All he took was abuse. The
foursome of Mark Seaton, Jarron Collins, Tim Young and Mark Madsen
unsettled the Husky center.
</P>
<P>
   Madsen was productive at the other end as well, converting
putbacks and leading Stanford with 15 points. He shot an air ball
from the line but otherwise offered positive contributions. When
there were nudges on the floor, Madsen was usually the deliverer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just pushed me off the block and got me farther away
where it's harder for me to make moves,'' MacCulloch said.
</P>
<P>
   When the Huskies made moves Thursday night, they were
ill-advised or off-balance. Stanford caused the disjointed effort
with its conference-leading defense, but Washington was expected to
counter with its own weapons. Aside from Donald Watts, who had 18
points, the Huskies did not have a perimeter game. Deon Luton and
Senque Carey both went 2-for-8.
</P>
<P>
   Neither took good shots because none was to be found, not with
the Huskies hastily running their offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got impatient and tried to create a lot of 1-on-1 stuff,''
coach Bob Bender said. ``We've never been effective doing that.
Everybody was trying to get us out of the hole and then it
escalated from there.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared ominous at halftime when Stanford led 45-31. The
Cardinal had trailed at halftime in their previous seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Then when Washington opened the second half in a zone, Weems
busted a 3-pointer that continued the onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   The key development was evident early when Stanford began to
overwhelm Washington on the glass. The Cardinal finished with a
48-25 advantage. No one assisted MacCulloch, who collected 10.
Collins came off the bench to provide nine of his 10 rebounds in
the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Carey was ordinary for the first time since he took over the
starting job 12 games ago. Stanford senior Arthur Lee outdueled the
Husky freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like he had control of his team a little more than I
had control of mine,'' Carey said.
</P>
<P>
   With its relentless rebounding and defense, Stanford dominated.
In the first half, the Huskies went through two scoreless stretches
lasting almost five minutes each. Most of their field-goal attempts
were wild ones. A couple drew gasps instead of iron, like Luton's
misguided 3-point attempt and Carey's shot from the lane.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal contested every cutter and pass. Perhaps the
Huskies weren't out of their league, but they were certainly out of
sync, bobbing and weaving and rarely connecting. Washington hit 4
of its first 18 shots, falling behind 24-13 as a result.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal weren't exactly finding the cylinder either for
awhile, missing nine straight at one point. But they often found
Madsen inside, finally discovering the team that went all the way
to the Final Four last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the road this is as good as you can ask for,'' said
Stanford forward Peter Sauer. ``Not many people beat Washington
here by 30.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the end when Watts went to the bench and watched the
reserves play it out, he wondered: ``How did we let this happen.
Why didn't we perform better.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to the Huskies' lack of intensity, particularly on
the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rebounding is not really a skill thing,'' he said. ``It's
something that involves heart. We didn't play with heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Or much direction. Washington will be back at practice today,
preparing for Cal, hoping to rebound in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to figure out the answers, and we've got to figure
them out fast,'' Watts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
