<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1303 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      02-19 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANFORD PROVES WASHINGTON IS OUT OF ITS LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Fans of local hoops are having a bad week.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the Sonics wobble through two games of hideous
offense, the University of Washington men's team Thursday night
under-did their pro counterparts so dramatically that the thought
of a Vin Baker free throw actually lightened the mood.
</P>
<P>
   Is it too early to entertain water-cooler discussion about the
Mariners' No. 5 spot in the rotation?
</P>
<P>
   OK, one bad week doesn't end a season (even if the NBA season is
only three weeks long). But Thursday night at Hec Ed, the Huskies
had a game that stunk so badly it might have bent light rays, never
mind postseason prospects.
</P>
<P>
   These sorts of things happen with college kids. But with the
expectations created by eight wins in the past 10 games, including
triumphs over ranked Pac-10 Conference foes UCLA and Arizona, the
Huskies figured to at least cause Stanford a fair degree of
annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Cardinal barely had to dampen its garments with
sweat in order to dispatch Washington, 89-57. Fortunately for the
Huskies, a single horrific loss won't cause irreparable damage to
their NCAA tourney hopes. But the outcome left no doubt as to who
was championship material on the West Coast and who was tourney
filler.
</P>
<P>
   And if Washington doesn't snap back abruptly for Saturday's game
here against Cal, it will be NIT filler.
</P>
<P>
   With a packed house anticipating upset and a regional TV
audience figuring entertainment, the Huskies instead emitted a
night-long dial tone. The 32-point loss where they had been
undefeated this season probably was the worst emotional whipping
the Huskies have endured during Bob Bender's six-year tenure as
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very disappointing and frustrating evening,'' said
Bender, his description failing as badly to grasp the enormity of
the evening as the team failed to grasp anything in red.
</P>
<P>
   As much as the Cardinal had its way on offense, the defense was
a jaw-dropper. Or perhaps a jaw-breaker. Against a team that had
found an offensive rhythm in recent weeks, Stanford so completely
denied the interior to Washington that Todd MacCulloch, the nearest
thing to money in baggy pants hereabouts, went scoreless the final
22 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was by far the best defense I've seen in six years,''
said Bender, whose club shot 36 percent for the game and never
mustered so much as a whisper of a run in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   A remarkable collection of bones and brains, these Stanford
guys. They came into the game allowing opponents an average of 37.8
percent from the field, so it wasn't exactly a surprise that the
defense was formidable. But the ferocity with which they ripped the
game from the players and the crowd by challenging every UW
thought, much less dribbles or passes, was startling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so big, and they played so much harder than we did,''
marveled Senque Carey, who had his freshman comeuppance against
senior star guards Arthur Lee and Kris Weems. In 32 minutes, Carey
had seven meaningless points and two assists. Without Carey
organizing the drill, MacCulloch might as well have been the
Washington Monument for all his scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was trouble when I looked up (at the clock) with
11:36 remaining in the first half, and Todd hadn't touched the
ball,'' said Bender. But it wasn't just the big guy. Every Husky
starter shot at least one airball. It's one thing to chip paint off
the rim with bad shotmaking; it's another to leave the rims shiny
and buffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to move our feet,'' said Stanford coach Mike
Montgomery, himself mastering the understatement. ``We knew
Washington likes to use a motion offense so we wanted to stay in
front of them and keep hands off so they had to shoot over us.''
</P>
<P>
   The resultant airball festival was breathtaking in its
ineptitude. The Huskies quickly broke down into one-on-one contests
for which they have little aptitude or skill. During the 12-minute
stretch in the first half when the element of contest was
eliminated, the Huskies scored two field goals.
</P>
<P>
   And they were the hottest team in the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   Who ordered the ice?
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's dominance was so pronounced that it warped time back
to last year when the Huskies were perceived as too soft to prevail
against college basketball's big boys. But the UW success in last
year's NCAAs, coupled with the 3-3 mark against ranked teams this
season, offered evidence that passivity was passe.
</P>
<P>
   The way Mark Madsen, Tim Young and a seemingly endless supply of
reserve big men knocked around the Huskies, the suspicion returned
in locomotive fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it could also be argued that since the Huskies were
similarly roughhoused by second-ranked Connecticut earlier this
season, the seventh-ranked Cardinal demonstrated that the gap
between the top of the NCAA field and the bottom of the bracket is
far broader than anyone knew starting the week.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
