<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1306 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHAT-PRICE-HOLOCAUST?     02-19 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHAT-PRICE-HOLOCAUST?-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAZI GUILT MONEY TRIVIALIZES UNSPEAKABLE CRIMES  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 650-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 20 Feb. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can justice be counted in money? Yes, comes the answer every
day, from parliaments and congresses, and from the courts that
enforce their laws: a small fine for a parking offense, a bigger
one for theft; damages for negligence; compensation for injury.
</P>
<P>
   So how much for the Holocaust?
</P>
<P>
   Germany has never answered that question directly, but from its
early post-war days it has accepted that only by offering material
restitution as well as expressions of remorse could it prove that
it had broken completely with its Nazi past.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years it has paid out fully $60 billion in reparations.
But the demands for more have not stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, indeed, they have grown more insistent, especially in
America, where the collective actions of lawyers, Jewish groups,
politicians and regulators now beset German companies as never
before, and threaten to hold up the takeover of Bankers Trust by
Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to put an end to the lawsuits, a dozen prominent
German banks and businesses, backed by Chancellor Gerhard Schroder,
announced this week that they would set up a fund _ it could be
worth more than $2 billion _ to compensate former slave laborers
and others who suffered under the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   This will not put an end to the pursuit, however, if only
because it is not only Germans who are being pursued. Several
American companies, for instance, now face claims because their
former German subsidiaries are accused of helping the Nazi war
machine; Ford, General Motors, Chase Manhattan and J.P. Morgan are
among the well-known names.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's largest insurer, Generali, is beset by claims. Eight
French banks are said still to owe money to Jewish depositors.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Barclays, whose French subsidiary has likewise been
accused, is setting up a $3.6 million fund in response.
</P>
<P>
   Two Austrian banks are likely to pay out much more in
compensation, though nothing like as much as the $1.25 billion that
Switzerland's banks last year agreed to put into a fund for the
heirs of Jewish depositors who died in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The list could go on. Britain has created a small fund to
compensate Jewish refugees interned during the war. France is
producing an inventory of Jewish assets seized during the German
occupation, with a view to compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Some 44 countries met in Washington in December to try to settle
disputes about assets, notably works of art, stolen by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   And many lawsuits are still outstanding: the French state rail
company is being sued by a man whose parents were sent to
Auschwitz, he says, in one of its trains.
</P>
<P>
   Better late _ even 54 years late _ than never? Certainly, that
is the right response where banks or insurance companies have
simply refused to come clean about deposits or policies, and
thereby robbed Holocaust victims or their heirs of what they were
owed.
</P>
<P>
   And, equally certainly, many of the belated payments of
compensation would not have been forthcoming but for legal action.
Nor indeed would much of the information that is needed for the
historical record, without which no accounting, financial or
otherwise, can ever be done.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, there is something distasteful about the quest for
``compensation.''
</P>
<P>
   The relentlessness of some Jewish groups, the ambitions of
American politicians seeking ethnic votes, the class-action suits,
the lawyers' contingency fees: do these really bring justice to
those who survived the Nazi terror, or honor the memory of the 6
million who did not?
</P>
<P>
   Or do they, by seeming to put a price on the Holocaust, reduce
this most terrible of episodes to something more like an everyday
crime?
</P>
<P>
   Several American lawyers say that, despite the new German fund,
they will fight on. They should think again. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 650-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax us at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
