<HEADER>
A1309 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMOSEXUAL-CONTENT-SF     02-19 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMOSEXUAL-CONTENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GROUP SEEKS WARNINGS FOR `GAY' PROGRAMS  &HT;     By ELAINE HERSCHER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Christian lobbying group is calling on the federal government
to add a new warning label to television programs _ HC for
``homosexual content.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar to warnings on programs containing violence, sex and
adult language, the HC rating would alert parents to shows that
have ``homosexual situations,'' said Phillip Vaught of the
Christian Action Network in Forest, Va.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent Tuesday, Martin Mawyer, the organization's
president, requested a meeting with Federal Communications
Commission Chairman William Kennard to discuss the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Vaught said Thursday that any show with a lesbian or gay
character would need to be slapped with an HC warning.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if that would include the Teletubbies _ whose Tinky Winky
was fingered as gay last week by the Rev. Jerry Falwell because
he's purple, has a triangle antenna and carries a purse _ Vaught
replied: ``I don't think that would be necessary because (Tinky's)
not a gay character. At least not the way I look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mawyer released a statement this week complaining of 25
``homosexual characters'' on prime-time television, 12 on NBC
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are parents across the country that are sick and tired
of having their living rooms invaded by homosexual characters and
activities on their television,'' Mawyer said. He said he was
shocked to learn that Fox's ``That '70s Show'' recently portrayed
two teenage boys kissing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it doesn't end with just the networks,'' he said. ``HBO is
planning to air in June a program called `The Sissy Duckling,'
which they describe as a `fuzzy little yellow bird who learns he's
gay.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mawyer said he is taking his 250,000-member organization's issue
to Congress, every network and to situation comedy producers across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless these producers are trying to promote a secret
agenda,'' he said, ``they should have no problems alerting parents
that their programs contain homosexual content.''
</P>
<P>
   FCC spokesman David Fiske said Thursday that the commission had
not seen Mawyer's letter. He noted that the current television
rating system is based on voluntary industry standards under the
federal Telecommunications Act.
</P>
<P>
   To San Francisco Supervisor Tom Ammiano, who is gay, the
Christian Action Network's proposal is ``again a case of twisted
values. The message is: What's coming up is evil, what's coming up
is less than human.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has feelings about something, but you can't subject
the public to feelings every time you have one,'' Ammiano said.
``Maybe we should have a warning about people like this,'' Ammiano
said, referring to Mawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The liberal policy group People for the American Way said
Thursday that it strongly opposes gay warning labels.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're proposing goes far beyond current warning labels
that alert viewers to explicit adult content,'' the group's
president, Carole Shields, said in a statement. ``This is an
obvious attempt to stigmatize an entire group of Americans,''
Shields said. ``The Christian Action Network seeks to put a
slanderous smear on gay and lesbian Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Action Network describes itself as a grassroots,
pro-family organization. The group has lobbied hard for the demise
of the National Endowment for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Mawyer said homosexual content is creeping not only into
programming but into commercials as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``These commercials are called `gay vague' because homosexuals
understand the advertisements are directed toward them,'' he said.
``But the so-called straight community just can't figure it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
