A1313 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-OILERS-WRIT     02-19 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-OILERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUCK GOES KINGS' WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Kings' 3-2 victory over the
Edmonton Oilers before 11,287 at the Forum on Thursday night might,
or might not, merely be a case of prolonging the agony that has
become Los Angeles' 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   But the agony of losing to the Oilers just hours after being
lectured by an angry Dave Taylor wasn't a very appealing option.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the type of guy to get angry, so we got the
message,'' said Philippe Boucher, the Kings' unlikely offensive
hero with a career high three points (a goal and two assists).
``Dave told us he believes in us, but it's time to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we all knew, but it had to be said.''
</P>
<P>
   A defeat would have left the Kings 10 points out of a playoff
spot and certainly out of the good graces of their general manager.
</P>
<P>
   But the bounces were going the Kings' way and they pulled within
six points of the eighth-place Oilers before starting a six-game
road trip in Calgary on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher used his hockey stick like a pool cue two minutes into
the game and bounced a shot off the boards for his first goal of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there is a God,'' joked Kings coach Larry Robinson of
the good bounces. ``It was nice to see.''
</P>
<P>
   It truly was a game of follow the bouncing puck in the first
period and Mikhail Shtalenkov wasn't good at it. The Edmonton
goalie was pulled after allowing three goals on 12 shots in the
first 18 minutes of play.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' 26th-ranked power play opened the scoring when
Boucher's dump-in bounced off the left wing boards and went into
the empty Edmonton net after Shtalenkov had left the crease to play
the anticipated bounce.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings took a 2-0 lead at 5:15 when Luc Robitaille, while
falling down, got his stick on Boucher's shot from the right point.
The goal was Robitaille's 30th of the season and 900th point as a
King.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Selivanov, who scored three third-period goals at
Anaheim on Wednesday, scored on a deflection at 12:38 of the first
period. He then tied the game, 2-2, on a breakaway at 14:50.
</P>
<P>
   But good fortune continued to go the Kings' way when Steve
Duchesne's 60-footer hit the stick of an Oilers defenseman and got
past Shtalenkov at 17:52.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher, who has spent much of the season in the press box, was
the first to admit both he and the Kings got the majority of the
good bounces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got some lucky breaks, but you've got to take advantage of
them,'' said Boucher, referring to the Kings' ability to maintain
their lead after Duchesne scored his fourth goal of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The puck and the game settled down in the second period. Neither
team scored and they combined for just nine shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things were laid out pretty plainly for us,'' said center Ray
Ferraro. ``Tonight everybody came focused and ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   One win, however, doesn't even come close to pulling the Kings
out of the hole they've dug for themselves, especially when they
have games coming up in St. Louis, Detroit and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Necessary, crucial, do-or-die, all of the cliches,'' said
Robinson of the trip. ``You have to be realistic and not think you
are going to win all five (before the Kings return to Southern
California for a game No.6 against the Ducks), but we can't do
worse than .500.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
