<HEADLINE>
CLINTON-KOSOVO: `HARE-BRAINED CHATTER OF IRRESPONSIBLE FRIVOLITY'  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent, provocative 1,075-word ``separate buy'' article is
from the current (week beginning 20 Feb. 1999) Economist
magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: THE QUOTE IN HEADLINE IS BY BENJAMIN DISRAELI)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last Saturday, the day after his acquittal in the Senate, it was
glibness-as-usual for Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``This week,'' he said in his weekly radio address, ``the
warring parties in Kosovo have been meeting at a 14th-century
castle in France in search of 21st-century peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Savoring the rich sweep of the past, the president proceeded to
enunciate two lessons from history. First, ``World War II taught us
that America could never be secure if Europe's future was in
doubt.'' Second, ``Bosnia taught us...(that) violence we fail to
oppose leads to even greater violence we will have to oppose later
at greater cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of these two lessons, the president explained, America
should intervene in Kosovo, though there should of course be ``a
clear and realistic strategy to allow us to bring our forces home
when their work is done.''
</P>
<P>
   These standard phrases constitute pretty much all Clinton has to
