<HEADER>
A1324 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEPATITISA-VACCINATIO     02-19 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEPATITISA-VACCINATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL EXPERTS RECOMMEND EXTENSIVE HEPATITIS A VACCINE
PROGRAM  FOR 11 STATES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal health officials called Thursday for routine vaccination
programs for children in California and 10 other states to stop the
spread of hepatitis A.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of medical experts advising the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention urged that public-health programs use
statewide vaccination programs in escalating efforts to control the
virus, but left details up to each state. In most states,
vaccination programs are targeted now only at certain high-risk
communities.
</P>
<P>
   California and the other 10 states singled out by the CDC panel
accounted for about half of all the hepatitis A infections from
1987 to 1997, although they contained only about 22 percent of the
population.
</P>
<P>
   The new recommendations are part of a long-term strategy that
ultimately aims at nationwide vaccination efforts, even in states
that do not have particularly high incidence of hepatitis A
infections.
</P>
<P>
   California state health officials said they planned to study the
recommendations but would wait for financing issues to clear up and
for two independent organizations of pediatricians and family
practitioners to weigh in on the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC panel report was formally approved Thursday and now goes
to the CDC director for final adoption, considered a formality.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey-based Hepatitis Foundation International
applauded the recommendations, noting that the Hepatitis A virus is
one of the most common infectious agents in the country and results
in annual costs of $450 million.
</P>
<P>
   Well-designed vaccination programs, the organization said, have
proved to be safe and cost-effective. One shot, followed after at
least a few months by a booster, is sufficient for lifetime
protection.
</P>
<P>
   Hepatitis A, which affects the liver, is generally spread by
oral-fecal contact or by consuming contaminated food or water.
About 125,000 to 200,000 people are infected annually in the United
States. It is a different virus than blood-borne hepatitis B and C.
</P>
<P>
   Infections with hepatitis A often cause no serious symptoms in
young children, but they can easily spread the infection to older
children and adults who may suffer severe flu-like symptoms, weeks
of fatigue, jaundice and liver damage.
</P>
<P>
   Children entering school or group child-care programs may be
particularly prone to spreading the virus, the experts noted,
suggesting that may also be the most practical setting in which to
administer vaccines. Children between the ages of 5 and 14 are most
likely to catch the virus; 30 percent of reported cases occur in
people under age 15.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC panel's recommendations cover anyone between the ages of
2 and 19 but focus mainly on preventing infections in the younger
kids, said Dr. William Schaffner, a panel member who serves as
chair of preventive medicine at Vanderbilt School of Medicine in
Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the vehicle for bringing the virus home to Mom, Dad,
Suzie and Grandpa,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Studies are under way as to the safety and benefits of
vaccinating infants. For now, though, the experts recommend parents
and caregivers rely mainly on good hygiene, not vaccination, to
protect children below age 2.
</P>
<P>
   Hepatitis A has not reached epidemic levels even in the states
with the most cases. Nor is it often linked to chronic infections
and life-threatening liver disease as is hepatitis C, for which
there is no vaccine. Hepatitis B also can cause chronic infections,
but there is a vaccine against that pathogen. Being vaccinated
against hepatitis B does not protect you from acquiring hepatitis
A.
</P>
<P>
   Control initiatives already have been begun in four of the
states _ Oklahoma, Texas, Arizona and Alaska _ with particularly
high disease rates. The highest incidence was in Arizona, with 48
cases per 100,000 population during the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   California had 21 cases per 100,000, about double the national
average.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
