<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suspect competent to represent himself, but many paradoxes in
case border insanity
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ You keep wishing somebody would pull the plug.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to do this,'' defendant James R. Taylor Sr.,
representing himself in a double-murder case, told Greene County
Common Pleas Court Judge Thomas Rose Wednesday during the testimony
of his estranged wife, Patricia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for everybody, I think,'' Rose said. ``Carry on.
We'll get through this somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who spent the day in court couldn't help but come away
feeling Rose's pain. In one of the most unusual trials in recent
memory _ and most likely the first time in modern Ohio history that
a defendant has served as his own counsel in a death-penalty case _
the judge and prosecutors find themselves between a judicial rock
and a hard place.
</P>
<P>
   Greene County Prosecutor Bill Schenck knows what everybody is
thinking: How could the courts allow this to go on? The answer lies
in that one pesky word that seems to be wreaking so much havoc in
the world lately: The Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he was ruled competent to stand trial, we had no choice,
under the Constitution, but to grant his request to represent
himself,'' Schenck said. Before and during the trial, Rose has
pleaded with Taylor to allow his two stand-by attorneys to step up
to represent him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Constitution says you're entitled to counsel,'' concurred
University of Dayton law Professor Dennis Turner, ``and that means
it's your constitutional right that you can pick yourself. Once it
is determined you are competent to stand trial, that also means you
are competent to make choices about your case, including who should
represent you.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has pleaded not guilty and not guilty by reason of
insanity to two counts of aggravated murder in the Valentine's Day
1998 shootings of Ron and Carolyn Rihm, two of his wife's closest
friends.
</P>
<P>
   In a trial that has many ``Alice in Wonderland'' qualities, you
have the paradox of a defendant claiming he is competent to
represent himself, and on the other hand claiming insanity as part
of his defense. And there's the additional paradox that, despite
the extraordinary circumstances, the trial can best be described by
one word: Tedious.
</P>
<P>
   True, it made for a dramatic half hour when the 68-year-old
Taylor cross-examined his estranged wife, Patricia, Wednesday.
Taylor peppered his wife of 46 years with questions about alleged
infidelities, but she hung tough, answering ``No sir,'' and ``No,
Mr. Taylor,'' with vehemence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some good times together, didn't we?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few, sir, very few,'' she responded.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Wednesday's proceedings were, at best, dull. Taylor
stopped questioning his wife because ``I hurt too much,'' he told
the judge. He grilled Fairborn police Officer Lee Cyr at least
three times that long, asking endless variations of the same, often
irrelevant question, until everyone in the courtroom wished he had
a dollar for every time the judge admonished, ``That question has
been asked and answered. Move on to the next question, Mr.
Taylor.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner said Rose is in a tough spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the circumstances, he has to give the defendant the
benefit of the doubt and certain advantages,'' he said. ``He can
get away with things a trial lawyer never could.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, after Taylor asked Cyr the same question for what seemed
like the tenth time, Rose could barely contain his exasperation:
``I'm allowing some flexibility as to the rules of evidence. But
I'm not going to let you entirely dismantle it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Taylor is convicted, would an attorney be able to file an
appeal based on inadequate representation?
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say no. ``That would be like the kid who kills his
parents and argues he should be found not guilty because 'I'm an
orphan,''' UD's Turner said. ``He could find an attorney to appeal
on other grounds, but not because he insisted on exercising his
constitutional right to represent himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Are state competency standards the culprit? Is it too hard to
find a defendant incompetent? ``Here is your dilemma: If you
conclude he's not competent, that also means you can't try him,''
Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Why does Taylor insist on representing himself, bruskly brushing
away his court-appointed attorneys, despite the obvious discomfort
it brings him and the court?
</P>
<P>
   Schenck said he has never seen a trial quite like it. ``It's all
about control,'' he speculated. ``At this moment in court we are
living out the marriage of Jim and Patricia Taylor. You see it in
the way he tries to control the court, the witnesses, in the way he
refuses to accept the court's rulings. You see it in the way he
tried to control his wife on the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether we like it or not, we are prisoners of this process,
just as Patricia Taylor was a prisoner during 46 years of
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor may not be doing himself any favors by serving as his own
counsel _ ``The old saying goes that a man who represents himself
has a fool for a client,'' Turner noted _ but he has every legal
right to do so. And the court has a legal obligation to allow him
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   As Taylor fumbles through his questions, as the trial drones on,
you can imagine Judge Rose steeling himself in the same words with
which he admonished Taylor: ``Carry on. We'll get through this
somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
