<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1503 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN20-COX     02-19 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A stray act of kindness
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ One of the items my wife brings home from
the grocery store along with a selection of fat-free foods is a
little magazine with all sorts of health news. I read it in
self-defense, and sometimes find useful information.
</P>
<P>
   For example, I can lengthen my lifespan by 10 to 20 years
without paying ridiculous prices for chemically manufactured drugs.
Something as simple as eating a cup of nonfat yogurt and a cup of
cubed cantaloupe every day will keep me from having a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   I've discovered 23 home remedies hiding in our spice rack.
</P>
<P>
   Spices, being generally fat-free, have been approved by the Food
Police. You'd never guess all the simple ways to stay healthy
merely by swallowing potions of ground-up leaves and roots.
</P>
<P>
   I'd always known hot pepper sauce did a lot for collards and
turnip greens. What I didn't know was that a single pod of hot red
pepper can cure cluster headaches, arthritis pain, sore throats,
toothaches, cold feet and various digestive disorders.
</P>
<P>
   If you have cold feet, grind some dried red peppers, mix with
talcum powder or cornstarch, and sprinkle into your socks. This
will cause the small blood vessels under your skin to dilate,
providing extra blood flow and warmth.
</P>
<P>
   Red pepper can be a solution to an age-old problem that has
plagued sleeping partners of the opposite sex since Adam and Eve,
one that has cause considerable discord in my own marriage. If she
has enough cover I'm drenched with sweat. If I'm not sweating she's
shivering. Now I can simply sprinkle her side of the bed with red
pepper and we can both sleep happily ever after.
</P>
<P>
   These are only samplings of the various nuggets you can pick up
from the pages of magazines dedicated to better living without
chemistry. There are many others, including the first known
practical use for parsley. Tea made from parsley cures urinary
tract problems.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't surprised to learn that a spoonful of horseradish will
blast sinuses open. What I didn't know was that cats lower blood
pressure and prevent heart attacks. Dogs maybe, but not cats.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that people who own cats have significantly lower
blood pressure than people who don't. I would have guessed, from
personal experience, that it's the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   A University of Texas at El Paso study claims cat ownership can
help even more if you have already had a heart attack. Cat owners
are far more likely to complete a course of cardiac rehabilitation
than those who don't have a cat, 96 percent to 77 percent.
</P>
<P>
   I'm hopeful the UTEP findings will solve the long-standing cat
problem at our house. It began four years ago when my wife heard a
mewing at the back door. Upon investigating she found a small
kitten. She served the little visitor a saucer of milk and
instructed me to prepare sleeping quarters on the carport.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion that we carry the kitten to the county pound for
adoption fell on deaf ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know what they do with pets that don't get adopted?''
she asked.
</P>
<P>
   As months and years went by, what began as ``my kitty'' turned
into ``our kitty'' and eventually into ``your cat.'' My cat began
to fall further out of favor when it began making paw tracks on her
car, scratching the paint with clawing leaps onto the hood.
</P>
<P>
   The cat also perfected a ruse of lurking in the shrubbery when
we drive into the carport, then dashing inside and hiding under the
car. I keep a broom to sweep it out, which necessitates getting
down on my knees on the concrete, which is hard on breeches.
</P>
<P>
   We managed to cope fairly well with one cat. Then last summer a
full-grown calico stray decided to accept our hospitality. The two
fought a lot. We had hopes one or the other would give up and move
on to one of our neighbors. That didn't happen. The calico stayed,
and began ``marking'' territory, which included the carport.
</P>
<P>
   Marking is next to having a polecat in residence. It will get a
human arrested for indecent exposure. In a less compassionate
household than ours, it would trigger a quick trip to the pound, or
down to the Flint River in a croaker sack. Being a humanitarian
soul, soft of heart, slow to anger, my solution so far has been to
scrub the carport with Lysol and Pine-Sol almost daily.
</P>
<P>
   Even my wife has finally admitted we have a serious cat problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't we find them a good home and give them away?'' she
asked.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a happy solution. Except for one thing. I have
never known anyone who has successfully given away a full-grown
cat. Certainly not two. Research shows chances of giving away a
grown cat are roughly 1 in 1,000. Odds on giving away a marker are
worse.
</P>
<P>
   The UT El Paso findings offer a glint of hope. There must be
people reading this who are at high risk for a heart attack. Surely
there is somebody out there who has suffered a heart attack and
doesn't want to have another. I would be willing to give up both my
cats to prevent heart attacks. Furthermore, I'll do home delivery
anywhere in Georgia, or in contiguous states, plus furnishing free
cat food for six months.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
