<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1504 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN20-COX     02-19 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Ritz with a bang
 &HT;    By Roland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you haven't seen a uniformed doorman in white
gloves chase a speeding wine bottle, you haven't been traveling
with my mother and me.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted our stay at San Francisco's five-star Ritz-Carlton to
be memorable. Darn if I didn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   After a post-breakfast goodbye to family members in Monterey, my
mother and I took a leisurely back-road drive north to San
Francisco where I had a club-level suite reserved for the last day
of our weeklong vacation and family reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year my mother's eyesight has deteriorated rapidly
due to age-related macular degeneration. The loss of her vision
took away a lifetime of artistic pursuits, among other
taken-for-granted pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   That was partly why I wanted to splurge on a world-class luxury
hotel before we returned to our respective homes in Colorado and
Texas. I wanted to do something nice for my mother.
</P>
<P>
   Irving Berlin's ``Puttin' On The Ritz'' kept running through my
head as we drove north past irrigated fields of artichokes,
attractive horse farms and pocket vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   I called ahead to confirm our reservations. All was in order.
The entire staff of the Ritz-Carlton was prepared to make my our
stay comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, boy. Can't wait.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the rural roads ran out. We were forced onto the
ever-clogged Highway 101. I tried to follow directions to the hotel
that I had printed out from the hotel's Internet page.
</P>
<P>
   It was tough navigating unfamiliar freeways, turnoffs and
streets while keeping up with the breakneck pace of the surrounding
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   After climbing a hill that caused everything in the car to roll
to the rear, I made two sharp right-hand turns and pulled under the
front portico of the Ritz-Carlton where a small army of uniformed
doormen, bellmen and who-knows-what surrounded our rental car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' was all I got to mumble before our doors were opened,
we were welcomed warmly and runners were dispatched to notify
who-knows-who of our arrival. Things were moving fast. White-gloved
hands removed luggage from the trunk, hanging clothes from the back
seat and various scattered sacks and bags.
</P>
<P>
   Small clumps of well-dressed guests watched our arrival while
they waited for their cars or limousines.
</P>
<P>
   The white gloves were quickly loading a brass luggage cart with
our belongings when the tune in my head changed from ``Puttin' On
The Ritz'' to ``The Ballad of Jed Clampett.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom of a paper shopping bag broke and an amazing variety
of California food specialties splatted onto the elegant
entranceway of the Ritz-Carlton. A bottle of excellent California
merlot thunked down in the middle of spiced shrimp, scallops,
calamari, grapes and other eatables.
</P>
<P>
   Since we were in hilly San Francisco _ on Nob Hill, to be exact
_ the merlot took off like a chain-gang escapee in a downhill dash
toward California Street and, presumably, Chinatown. A uniformed,
white-gloved doorman was in close pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom of the paper bag had become wet with the juices from
doggie bags my mother brought back to our room refrigerator when
she couldn't eat all of a meal. She thought most servings too large
and refused to waste good food.
</P>
<P>
   I made matters worse by trying to help clean up the mess before
being coaxed away and told everything would be taken care of.
</P>
<P>
   I signed the guest register smelling like Cajun shrimp, a fact
politely ignored by one and all.
</P>
<P>
   In the suite, Mother and I toasted our trip with the trophy
merlot. Then we got ready to put on the Ritz.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor for the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears on Wednesday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
