<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1506 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-URBAN-HEATISLAND20-CO     02-19 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URBAN-HEATISLAND20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The pruning of Atlanta
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Metro Atlanta is losing an average of 50 acres per day
of tree cover to make way for new housing, roads, shopping malls
and office parks, according to a new analysis of satellite images.
</P>
<P>
   And as its urban forest disappears, metro Atlanta's misery level
is going up - more heat, more flooding, more air pollution, higher
electric bills.
</P>
<P>
   The new analysis of Landsat Satellite data by NASA climate
scientists, University of Georgia researchers and others shows that
from 1988 to 1998, the13-county metro Atlanta lost about 190,000
acres of tree cover - about five times the size of Lake Lanier.
Between 1973 and 1988, the loss was about 151,000 acres, or about
27 acres per day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Metro Atlanta is certainly losing its tree cover at a rapid
rate,'' says Dale Quattrochi, a scientist with NASA's Global
</P>
<P>
   Hydrology and Climate Center in Huntsville, Ala., which has been
studying the metro area's changing landcover since 1996. ``The
biggest reason for the tree loss (in the past 10 years) is new
residential subdivisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Other studies by the Washington-based American Forests, NASA and
other groups show the metro area is paying a heavy toll for the
decline of its urban forest:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Since 1973, average summer temperatures in downtown Atlanta
and at Hartsfield International Airport have increased by 6 to 9
degrees more than those of the surrounding countryside, creating
urban ``heat islands.'' In 1973, temperatures in the hottest part
of downtown were more than 6 degrees hotter than surrounding areas,
and at Hartsfield 3 to 6 degrees hotter. Now, downtown and airport
temperatures can soar up to 12 degrees higher than the surrounding
treed areas. At the same time, average temperatures in the suburbs
also have increased by a few degrees, and, with fewer cooling
breezes blowing Atlanta's way, that may be a reason downtown has
gotten even hotter. In addition, the urban heat islands have
increased in size, changing weather patterns in the metro area. One
NASA study shows that the heat from downtown Atlanta helps trigger
summertime thunderstorms in Fayette and Clayton counties south of
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hotter temperatures not only increase air-conditioning bills
and make life more unpleasant outdoors, they also cause more air
pollution. For instance, smog, Atlanta's biggest air pollution
problem, forms on hot sunny days. While no one has linked air
pollution levels to the metro area's tree loss, some studies show
that a 1 degree rise in summertime temperatures boosts the risk of
smog formation by as much as 3 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  With fewer trees to help rainwater soak into the ground,
stormwater runoff - from roads, parking lots and other developed
sites - since 1986 in metro Atlanta has increased. For each major
storm that drops more than 3.5 inches of rain within a 24-hour
period, an additional 7.4 billion gallons of stormwater flow into
are creeks and the Chattahoochee River than was the case 13 years
ago. The excess water would fill more than 7,000 Olympic-size
swimming pools. Previous research has shown that trees and other
vegetation slow the movement of stormwater, lower the total runoff
volume and reduce flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Trees also help remove or trap lung-damaging dust, ash, pollen
and smoke - particulate matter - from the air. They absorb carbon
dioxide and other dangerous gases and, in turn, replenish the
atmosphere with oxygen. One acre of trees can produce as much oxgen
as 18 people breathe annually, and absorb enough carbon dioxide to
equal the amount produced by a car that is driven 26,000 miles in a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental factors aside, trees beautify the landscape - they
provide us with pleasing-to-the-eye shapes and forms, add natural
character to cities and towns and soften the outline of concrete,
metal and glass.
</P>
<P>
   The American Forests environmental organization says a city
should have an overall tree cover of at least 40 percent to ensure
its environmental, economic and social health. However, the city of
Atlanta and a 3-mile buffer area around it have only 27 percent
tree cover, says a study by the group.
</P>
<P>
   The study estimates that the existing tree cover represents a
value of about $883 million for stormwater control in the city of
Atlanta and the 3-mile-wide buffer area. By increasing the tree
canopy to 40 percent in the area, stormwater benefits would
increase by an estimated $358 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to see decision-makers incorporate this natural
capital into their decision-making process,'' says American Forests
researcher Gary Moll, who led the study.
</P>
<P>
   There are several intense efforts underway in metro Atlanta to
mitigate heat island effects and tree loss. Most notable are the
efforts of Trees Atlanta and Cool Communities, a program of
American Forests. Marcia Bansley, the director of Trees Atlanta,
says one of the organization's goal is to encourage parking lot
owners to plant trees around their lots. Gas fumes escaping from
parked in unshaded parking lots in the summertime heat can be a
major contributor to air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Another major goal, says Lucie Griggs, who is coordinator of the
Cool Communities program in Georgia, is to encourage builders to
use material that reflect sunlight. ``We are talking with several
roofers in metro Atlanta about using such material,'' she says. The
roofs of large structures, such as shopping malls, large warehouses
and office buildings, can get as hot as 150 degree in the summer,
enough to affect whole neighborhoods. The reflective materials
would bounce heat back up into the atmosphere, and buildings and
surrounding areas would stay cooler.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Seabrook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
