<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ SAN FRANCISCO _ If you haven't seen a
uniformed doorman in white gloves chase a speeding wine bottle, you
haven't been traveling with my mother and me. (Rowland Nethaway is
senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ One of the items my wife
brings home from the grocery store along with a selection of
fat-free foods is a little magazine with all sorts of health news.
I read it in self-defense, and sometimes find useful information.
What wonders exist. (Jim Minter is a former editor of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ You keep wishing somebody would
pull the plug.``It's hard to do this,'' defendant James R. Taylor
Sr., representing himself in a double-murder case, told Greene
County Common Pleas Court Judge Thomas Rose on Wednesday during the
testimony of his estranged wife, Patricia. Anyone who spent the day
in court couldn't help but come away feeling Rose's pain. In one of
the most unusual trials in recent memory _ and most likely the
first time in modern Ohio history that a defendant has served as
his own counsel in a death-penalty case _ the judge and prosecutors
find themselves between a judicial rock and a hard place. (McCarty,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
