<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   AUS-JOHN-KELSO-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   A message for GRUMP cardholders
</P>
<P>
   By John Kelso
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ I'm a little bit miffed with you people who have been
given free membership cards to Good Riddance to Unrelentingly
Morose People, or GRUMP.
</P>
<P>
   You may remember that I formed this political action group with
the intent of eliminating the humorless from the planet by the year
2000. At the rate we're going, we'll still have a bunch of
soreheads around these parts until about 3009.
</P>
<P>
   You GRUMP members aren't doing your jobs.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 membership cards to GRUMP have been distributed to
readers. Some came to the newspaper and picked them up. I mailed
others. By the way, if you didn't get a GRUMP card, they're still
available in the main lobby of the newspaper. All you have to do is
show up during normal work hours and ask the security guard at the
desk.
</P>
<P>
   What are you doing with these membership cards, people? Putting
them in your wallet and sitting on them? Taking them out
occasionally and showing them off to your friends for a couple of
quick, cheap chuckles?
</P>
<P>
   You're certainly not using them for the purpose for which they
were intended _ to give me something to write about.
</P>
<P>
   On your GRUMP membership card, it clearly states that the holder
is a GRUMP Ranger, and that when you spot an incident of grumpy
behavior, you're supposed to report it to me by e-mail or phone.
</P>
<P>
   To date, I think I've received one e-mail from someone pointing
out that on Saturday afternoons, the produce shoppers at Central
Market on North Lamar run into each other with their shopping
carts, and another e-mail from a guy who turned himself in for
getting in a fight with a co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   I know there's more grouchiness than that going on in that you
aren't reporting. I can tell so from reading my mail.
</P>
<P>
   Take this letter from Blake Batte, of Odessa, the Indian word
meaning drive-up window. Seriously, Batte was chapped when I
mentioned a fictitious perfume, Evening in Odessa, in my
Valentine's Day column.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evening in Odessa?'' he wrote. ``I'm from Odessa and I take a
little offense to your using Odessa in a derogatory fashion. I know
that Odessa is not Utopia, but it is home for me and about 100,000
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It follows the thought of . . . I can cuss my sister, but
nobody else better cuss her! Might I suggest using a town or city
outside the state of Texas. Or, how about Bryan-College Station?''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it's Eau de Aggie from now on.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an e-mail from someone who got fire ants in his drawers
over my Wednesday column about developer Gary Bradley and his
Circle C Ranch development in Southwest Austin. The writer was put
out when I suggested the Circle C Ranch children should gather up
the endangered salamanders at Barton Springs Pool, take them home,
and give them homes in aquariums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your comments about the salamanders border on the illicit; it
is a violation ofFfederal law to remove any salamanders from Barton
Springs Pool, yet you encourage it,'' the writer tells us.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently this writer is unaware that if you are a resident of
South Austin, you are entitled to a bag limit of 12 salamanders per
day, as long as each salamander is at least two inches long _ or a
hawg-o-mander.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy your salamander license at the same place you get
duck stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-02-18-99 2016E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
