<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Saturday, February
20 and Sunday, February 21, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Religion, science &AMP; health, and home &AMP; garden
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available
for purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-NYSHOWS _ NEW YORK _ Fall fashion week '99 concludes.
Designers showing: Patrick Robinson, Vera Wang, Donna Karan and
Calvin Klein. (Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-FALLNOTES20 _ NEW YORK _ Runway notes and scene sidebar.
(Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-POSTCARD20 _ NEW YORK _ Greetings from New York
postcard-like story for Living cover with photo. (Walton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   CIVILRIGHTS-MURDERS _ Unsolved civil rights murders from the 60s
being reinvestigated. In light of the guilty verdicts in the trials
of Byron de la Beckwith and this summer, of Sam Bowers, both for
killing black civil rights workers in the 60s, several more cases
are being reopened and investigated. One is in Jackson, the case of
a student protester shot in the back ''by accident'' by the jackson
police. There are others in Miss, Alabama, and Louisiana - we will
check on Georgia as well, of course. Is this a good effort or
should folks let the past be the past and move on? (Konigsmark,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE-WASHINGTON _ MOUNT VERNON, Va. _ Nearly two centuries
have passed since George Washington _ after being bled by would-be
healers and prophetically reviewing his will _ whispered `` 'tis
well'' and died in an upstairs bedroom of his beloved mansion
beside the Potomac River. Now in the bicentennial year of
Washington's death on Dec. 14, 1799, the keepers of his historic
homestead and his legacy are fearful that the Father of His Country
is being forgotten. So, seeking to restore Washington to his
traditional place of ``first in war, first in peace, and first in
the hearts of his countrymen,'' the directors of Mount Vernon have
begun a $3 million campaign to spread his story far and wide during
the bicentennial year of his death. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE-BOX _ Information on visiting Mount Vernon.
</P>
<P>
   MOVED Wednesday, Feb. 10 and repeated Monday in (w) Washington,
(l) lifestyle and (t) travel categories.
</P>
<P>
   HOME &AMP; GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-SURVEY _ A survey of gardening habits _ how much time and
money gardeners spend, why gardening is so important to them, their
favorite plants. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   BIRDWATCHING _ Birdwatching isn't really just for the birds _
humans get a lot out of it, too. All over metro Atlanta this
weekend, families are participating in the National Backyard Bird
Count, but other weekends of the year, many pursue it as a hobby.
What you need to get started as a family; what your kids can learn.
(Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BIRD-FEEDERS _ A guide to common bird feeders. Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   BIRDGUIDE _ A page on the National Backyard Bird Count that
starts Saturday and runs through Feb. 22, including: a 5-inch
intro, 2 Websites where folks can report sightings, photos of 25-30
bird and text providing the name of the bird, it's length, a brief
description and a cool fact. Birds will be in three categories:
Birds common to backyards and feeders in Central Texas (about 15 of
them); birds common at places like Town Lake (about 10 of them);
and birds that are rare but it would be cool to spot one (about 3
of them). Will also have a short tips box on birding and books
(free ones, too) to get. (Austin American-Statesman). FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-LOUGANIS _ Former Olympic diving champion Greg Louganis has
become the poster boy for a new program aimed at getting people on
HIV drugs to take those drugs regularly and correctly - to avoid
developing drug resistance. The fact is, most people don't take
their drugs exactly when and how they should. But with AIDS drugs,
such cavalier attitudes can have tragic outcomes. A look at new
efforts to help patients adhere to dosing schedules, through the
eyes of Louganis, one of America's first healthy faces of AIDS.
(Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, FEB.
21.
</P>
<P>
   URBAN-HEATISLANDS _ ATLANTA _ In Atlanta, summertime in the city
is hotter, by more than five degrees, than summertime in the
suburbs. The problem is something called an urban heat island - the
pocket of hot, rank air that settles over a city. Heat islands can
exacerbate air pollution levels and make life miserable for city
inhabitants. In the countryside, trees provide cooling shade, and
water evaporating from leaves cool the air. A new NASA study is
helping Atlanta and four other cities pinpoint heat island problems
so that steps can be made - such as planting more trees _ to
mitigate the heat island effects. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 22. MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   CPR-SATURDAY _ The annual CPR Saturday, where ordinary people
can learn or brush up on this life-saving technique, will be March
6. What might you learn if you last took the class five or 10 years
ago? (AHusted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   LADIES-SUNDAYSCHOOL _ It outlasted the church. It outlasted the
town. The Ladies' Sunday School Class at Mountain View Baptist
Church still meets every month at Butch's Chicken House in
Jonesboro, but there is no more Mountain View. The women are all
members of other churches now. But eighteen years after the airport
ate their town and their church, about 50 of them and their
husbands gather for food and fellowship. We look at the Sunday
School class that goes on and on and on and on. (GWhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   IMPRESSIONISM _ Q&AMP;A with Impressionism shows' curators about
shows opening Tuesday. Talking with Atlanta High Museum of Art's
Michael Shapiro about the logistics of borrowing 39 works from all
over Europe to bring to Atlanta. (Fox, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 28 WITH PHOTOS and LLUSTRATION. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IMPRESSIONISM-FACTS _ It's difficult to fathom that
impressionism, so beloved in our time, was once considered radical
and appallling. (Fox, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   IMPRESSIONISM-MONET-BAZILLE _ A preview of the Monet and Bazille
exhibit at the High Museum of Art in Atlanta. WITH PHOTOS. FOR
SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
