<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1533 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     02-19 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, Feb. 19, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Saturday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONKEY-VIRUS (Houston) _ Health officials at the Baylor College
of Medicine say there is no need for alarm about new research
showing a monkey virus is now being detected in human tumors. But
there is mounting evidence that the virus infects humans and is
associated with certain types of human tumors. By JO ANN ZUNIGA.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE-AMERICANS (San Francisco) _ Fifty-seven years after
President Franklin D. Roosevelt authorized the mass internment of
120,000 people of Japanese ancestry in World War II, a national
campaign gets under way to build a memorial to the patriotism they
displayed during some of America's darkest days. By ANNIE NAKAO.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-ADMISSIONS (San Francisco) _ A plan to make 4 percent of
the students in each high school graduating class eligible to
attend the University of California is getting support from the
state's top politicians, but is denounced by student advocacy
groups as ``a farce.'' By KATHERINE SELIGMAN.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-FORCE (San Antonio) _ The Army's Delta Force
anti-terrorist team struck the old Brooke Army Medical Center
building here in a mock attack the other night. As the roar of
helicopters and the crackle of small arms fire echoed into nearby
neighborhoods, many residents said they loved it. By SIG
CHRISTENSON and JENNIFER WALSH.
</P>
<P>
   REDWOOD-FOREST (Sacramento) _ The federal government is offering
the Pacific Lumber Co. one last compromise to end a marathon
dispute over the Headwaters redwood forest in northern California.
By ROBERT SALLADAY and ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYOR (San Francisco) _ Millionaire Clint Reilly, a retired
political strategist who has long harbored a desire to run for
office himself, plunged into the mayor's race here with a pledge to
restore an ``ethic of service'' to government and a strong attack
on the incumbent, Willie Brown. By CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SONNY&AMP;CHER (Albany, N.Y.) _ Sonny Bono always made a great
punch line to a lot of jokes. So the fact the Sonny and Cher story
was being turned into a movie for ABC was initially greeted with a
yawn and a smirk. We underestimated Sonny yet again. ``And the Beat
Goes On: The Sonny &AMP; Cher Story'' is pretty good. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-OFFICESPACE (Albany, N.Y.) _ It's hard to sum up the
philosophy behind ``Office Space,'' a harmless proletarian revenge
fantasy, without resorting to a certain well-worn vulgarism. But we
can try: Work is a pain in the patoot. The printer is always down,
the nerd at the next desk is always muttering, and the boss is an
oily creep. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-TAKEOVERS (San Francisco) _ One by one, some of San
Francisco's most powerful corporations have been acquired by
out-of-state and foreign companies in a recent global frenzy of
mergers. Many local people worry that the city may be losing its
reputation as a ``Wall Street West.'' By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Houston) _ Veronica Wallace said her working
life took a definite downward slide during her annual job
evaluation, at a time when she was pregnant with her second child.
The Houston nurse said her boss told her she had to decide what is
more important: her career or her family. Employers want workers to
have a single focus, says Joe Ahmad, an employment lawyer. By L.M.
SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-QUAKE3 (Mesquite, Texas) _ In the new Quake III Arena
from id Software, there will be no slavering monsters to kill, no
endangered worlds for individual players to save. Instead, id is
creating a game that focuses on what is known as death-match play,
in which the only fiend a player stalks is another player, usually
connected via the Internet. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   With: COMPUTER-QUAKER3-SIDER
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ We offer tips on how to turn off
background applications. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ Tips on how to clean a computer
mouse that is sticking a lot. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HOTLIST (Undated) _ A look at amusement parks, from
Disneyland to a Web site on small, unusual theme parks. By DWIGHT
SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-ONLINE (Undated) _ A look at GameSpyder, one of a new
breed of computer search engines. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DOG-SLEDS (Undated) _ Hundreds of dogs will be taking part this
weekend in sled races outside Warrensburg, N.Y. Some 100 teams and
mushers from throughout the Northeast and Canada will be on hand
for the event. By BUZZ GRAY.
</P>
<P>
   SKI-SAFETY (Albany, N.Y.) _ The recent death of a 9-year-old
girl on a New York ski slope is tragic, but ski deaths _ especially
among young children _ are rare. And despite such catastrophes,
statistics show that skiing is predominantly safe _ much safer than
bicycling, skateboarding or recreational boating. By ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   CLEMENS-YANKEES (Albany, N.Y.) _ They were the best baseball
team of the past half century, maybe the best team ever, and that
wasn't good enough. So the New York Yankees had almost no choice
but to add a pitcher who is on his way to the Hall of Fame. Before
Roger Clemens gets to Cooperstown, he'd like a detour to the World
Series. By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
</TEXT>
