<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-LIVES-$ADV21-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY DID SO MANY IGNORE THE CLINTON TRIAL? THEY HAD LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've been thinking this heretical thought: King Hussein's recent
death was well timed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean I wished him dead. Or that the world is better off
without him. Or that I have no sympathy for his family or his
fellow Jordanians. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What I mean is that his death came at just the right time to
remind our elected officials why so many of us put President
Clinton's impeachment trial fairly far down our list of things to
fret over. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Look at what happened when Hussein died. Bill Clinton
immediately led a large American delegation to Amman. He and others
simply dropped what they were doing and went to do something they
considered more important. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton went. Gerald Ford went and Jimmy Carter
and George Bush. So did Sen. Ted Stevens and Sen. Patrick Leahy,
who at that very moment were jurors in the impeachment trial. And
23 other people went with the president, too, from two members of
the House to the executive secretary of the National Security
Council to the parents of Jordan's Queen Noor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If all those people put the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal in a
secondary position, why is anyone surprised that many of the rest
of us often found compelling reasons to do the same? Pollsters
regularly reflected Americans' discontent with the impeachment
process _ and disinterest, too. The reasons, no doubt, were many.
But at least one cause was that those of us who live outside the
Beltway actually have lives that require our daily attention. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm not suggesting the Clinton affair wasn't worthy of notice
and analysis. Indeed, the president's behavior sickened nearly
everyone I know _ especially people who believe in the policies he
has represented. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But King Hussein's death was a painful reminder that some things
take precedence over others. That's something most of us out here
in the country instinctively knew as we took care of private
matters that were, quite simply, more crucial to us than what Ken
Starr or Henry Hyde or Charles Ruf or Tom Daschle or even Chief
Justice William Rehnquist were saying or doing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the Senate trial went on, for instance, both a current and
a former member of my church died. For me, this sad news quickly
became more important than whatever was happening in Washington.
Oh, like Bill Clinton I can ``compartmentalize'' pretty well. I
could, thus, devote time to both matters. But there was no doubt
which was more important, which explains why I was at a funeral
when the acquittal vote came. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I had a similar _ though joyful _ experience as I watched the
teen-ager who lives in my house prepare for a big role in a school
musical while the impeachment trial raged. His hard work _ and his
brief illness just before the play's opening _ were, in the end,
more important to me than whether senators would call Monica
Lewinsky to their chamber for live testimony. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And no doubt all across the land parents of young actors and
actresses (and basketball players and debaters and oboe players and
on and on) were more engaged in the lives of their children than in
the personally pathetic life of the president or in the distended
rhetoric that demanded his ouster. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Washington seethed, one of my sisters experienced a career
crisis 500 miles from where I live. At the same time _ and at more
than twice that distance from me _ an old friend was undergoing
surgery. Beyond worrying about all that, I was working with my wife
on important projects in our house. I was planning speeches I have
to give and classes I'm committed to teaching. And along with
working on a book of my own, I was writing a dedication to a
soon-to-be-published book containing a friend's sermons and hymns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All over the country, in fact, decent citizens lived their
decent lives and took care of business that they had every right to
feel was more important than what had entangled Washington. And
Washington would do a lot better by all of us if it would remember
that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column is for use Sunday, Feb. 21, and thereafter.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
