<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPANESE-AMERICANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIAL TO RECALL WORLD WAR II INTERNMENT OF JAPANESE AMERICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: SPELLING of Davis Buckley in 9th graf and Melvin Chiogioji in
next to last graf is correct.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANNIE NAKAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Fifty-seven years after President Franklin D.
Roosevelt authorized the mass incarceration of 120,000 people of
Japanese ancestry in World War II, a national campaign is under way
to build a memorial to the patriotism they displayed in those dark
days.
</P>
<P>
   A major fund-raising drive for the memorial _ to be built just a
few blocks from the U.S. Capitol _ began Friday, the National Day
of Remembrance, marking Roosevelt's signing of Executive Order
9066, which set the internment in motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the memorial puts a proper focus on the Day of
Remembrance,'' said Cressey Nakagawa, a San Francisco attorney and
board member of the National Japanese American Memorial Foundation,
which is raising private money for the project.
</P>
<P>
   National Day of Remembrance activities were held across the
country. On Saturday in San Francisco the National Japanese
American Historical Society will honor a team of researchers and
lawyers who successfully challenged the constitutionality of the
internment camps in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   For many Japanese Americans, a national memorial commemorating
their experience resonates deeply.
</P>
<P>
   Many camp survivors, whose families lost everything in the
forced evacuation of their homes and businesses, were so
traumatized that they only began talking about their experiences in
the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important that we tell the story,'' said World War
II veteran Harry Fukuhara, 79, of San Jose. ``It's so hard to
explain it in words, though. So you have to have a monument you can
see.''
</P>
<P>
   In a city famous for its memorials, the tribute to Japanese
Americans might be regarded as unique because it focuses on a
particular ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   But the memorial's architect, Davis Buckley, who also designed
the National Law Enforcement Officers Memorial in Washington, said
it has a broader message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Memorials become focal points,'' said Buckley. ``They are part
of the texture of our memory. And it's that memory that's so
essential and extraordinarily important here. Because the memorial
speaks to a despicable event in our history, it goes beyond
Japanese Americans. It speaks to every American.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress and President George Bush approved the project in 1992,
setting aside a sloping triangle of federal land in the shadow of
the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The design by Buckley, who consulted with Japanese-American
architects, envisions a park-like setting of cherry trees and a
plaza whose central feature is a Nina Akamu sculpture _ two
Japanese cranes entwined in barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   On a curved wall will be the names of Japanese Americans killed
in action during the war, along with the names of the 10 internment
camps where families were imprisoned and other inscriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the memorial was to be a tribute to Japanese
American fighting men of World War II. About 33,000 Japanese
Americans from Hawaii and the mainland volunteered for military
service. Most served in the legendary 442nd Regimental Combat Team
and the 100th Battalion, which combined to become the most highly
decorated military unit of its size.
</P>
<P>
   About 6,000 Japanese Americans also served with the Military
Intelligence Service in the Pacific, shortening the war by serving
as translators and breaking enemy codes.
</P>
<P>
   But with ethnic-specific military memorials seeming to draw
disfavor, organizers of the memorial broadened its theme to capture
the entire experience of Japanese Americans during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, the foundation has quietly raised $5 million of the
$8.6 million needed for construction. It has until Oct. 15 of this
year to raise the rest _ or the legislation authorizing the
memorial will lapse. ``We plan to run a full-blown campaign,'' said
Nakagawa.
</P>
<P>
   Once built, the memorial will be maintained by the National Park
Service. The foundation, on whose honorary board sit some of the
nation's most prominent Japanese Americans _ including former Rep.
Norman Mineta, D-Calif.; Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii; and Rep.
Robert Matsui, D-Calif. _ will dissolve after construction is
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta sponsored the bill to authorize the memorial. He also
wrote House legislation in 1988 that provided $1.2 billion in
reparations and apologies to Japanese Americans who were interned.
</P>
<P>
   For Mineta, who was 10 when he and his family were interned, the
memorial is a ``monument to the faith and patriotism of the
Japanese Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   It also speaks to something else, said retired Rear Adm. Melvin
Chiogioji of Washington, D.C., who chairs the foundation board.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country was big enough to apologize _ I don't think any
other country in the world would do that,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
