<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-SLEDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE HIGHLY TRAINED ATHLETES HAVE GONE TO THE DOGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUZZ GRAY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sassy, Pepper and their 15 fellow highly-conditioned athletes do
nothing but run, chow down, take a nap and then run some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're at their happiest when they are out dashing through
the snow,'' said Bev Donovan, matriarch of this family that has
totally gone to the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband Mike and twin daughters Andrea and Angela are all
actively involved in racing sled dogs. They buy, breed, train,
feed, shelter and love their assortment of canines to the point of
obsession. Yet the rewards are endless.
</P>
<P>
   ``You grow extremely close,'' said Scott Gille, the husband of
Angela who became an enthusiast himself after marrying into the
clan. ``I have 10 dogs of my own now.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the animals will be participating in the races this
weekend outside the town of Warrensburg in upstate New York.
Approximately 100 teams and mushers from throughout the Northeast
and Canada will be at the event Saturday and Sunday. The races,
staged at Pack Forest just north of Warrensburg, are sponsored by
the Pennsylvania Sled Dog Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a room left in town,'' said Barbara Fredericks
of the Warrensburg Chamber of Commerce. ``I've been fielding calls
for two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the second year that the event is being held at Pack
Forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see some of the finest dog sled races in the country,''
Bev Donovan said. ``They'll be races staged in many classes.''
</P>
<P>
   The most popular is the four-dog sportsman division. The
unlimited class will see anywhere from 10 to 20 dogs pulling a sled
around a 13-mile circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite a sight,'' Donovan said. ``The dogs are all barking
and pulling on their harnesses. Then, once the race starts, you
could hear a pin drop. All you can hear is the patter of their paws
on the snow. They're all business then.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams are sent off at one and two-minute intervals. Some are
light and fast. Others are stronger and slower. Depending upon the
snow conditions of that day, one type will have an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The devotion between human and dog exceeds the normal bond
usually found between the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outright, unconditional love,'' Donovan said. ``A musher
would do anything for his dogs and vice versa.''
</P>
<P>
   One may not look any further than the Donovan family. They go
through 500 pounds of high energy dog food each month. The animals
get the best medical treatment that can be provided. Their
veterinarian, Dr. John O'Connor of the Glens Falls, makes a house
call to the Donovans since it usually takes several hours attending
to all the team members' shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Donovans work two jobs each and go without much sleep in
order to attend to their 17 athletes. They arise at 2:30 a.m. to
deliver newspapers. Then Mike Donovan goes to work at the post
office and Bev Donovan as a nurse at a rest home. They're home by
3:30 p.m. to begin running the dogs on their training routines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the temperatures climb above 50 degrees, we can't run
them anymore,'' Bev Donovan said. ``They are exercised twice or
three times a day but would get too hot if they ran hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means the dogs only have about two more months of their
season. Sassy seems to sense it. She addresses everyone personally
who comes within earshot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't pay too much attention to her,'' Gille said. ``She
just likes to hear herself talk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 1244EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1609 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-EASTTIMOR-0     02-19 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-EASTTIMOR-0220-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PROSPECT OF EAST TIMOR INDEPENDENCE CARRIES FEARS OF CHAOS,
BLOODSHED
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 800 words.
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIQUICA, Indonesia _ Ragged coffee farmers are battling with
bows and arrows, while teachers and doctors are packing their bags
to flee chaos they fear will descend if the disputed territory
called East Timor goes independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us are in danger,'' said Timorese separatist Gregory
Dos Santos, who this week gave harbor in his home to five skinny,
glassy-eyed warriors who had run from fighting 10 miles away. Two
of them were 12 years old.
</P>
<P>
   They share his sentiment that East Timor must seize the chance
for full freedom from Indonesia, and this is the issue that has
sparked a month-long escalation of violence.
</P>
<P>
   The 800,000 people of this jungle-covered half-island, a
colonial remnant still afflicted with rampant poverty and feudal
polarization, suddenly in the past month were told they will have a
choice: accept broad self-rule as part of Indonesia, or become
independent.
</P>
<P>
   They are almost certain to opt for independence if they get the
chance. But a determined minority of islanders who see benefits in
Indonesian rule already are fiercely resisting the split.
</P>
<P>
   And charges are growing that Indonesia's military is acting to
thwart its own government's stated policy by arming
anti-independence paramilitary groups. Army officers admit they are
supplying guns, but say their aim is maintaining order.
</P>
<P>
   ``One side talks about the solution, the other side provides
weapons,'' said David Ximenes, a one-time guerrilla fighter and now
a leader of a pro-independence coalition here. ``It is Indonesia's
scheme to build a civil war. Their goal is to legitimatize their
army here.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether pro or con, many East Timorese acknowledge that
independence is a status for which they are not ready, one that
risks throwing them back to a fruitless and anarchic past.
</P>
<P>
   The international community, which did nothing to restrain the
often brutal colonial handling of East Timor by Indonesia, now is
scrambling to prevent the slide backward. A United Nations
peacekeeping force or transitional authority may be needed to head
off total societal collapse.
</P>
<P>
   This past week alone, thousands trod through sultry heat in
funeral processions mourning two young men killed in separate
clashes.
</P>
<P>
   One victim buried in the provincial capital Dili was an
independence supporter. The funeral here was for a pro-integration
youth, whom the five frightened young fugitives admit was killed by
their group -- they said in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   It was only late last month that Indonesia first suggested East
Timor might be set free if its people turn down a limited autonomy
plan still being constructed under UN auspices. Then on Feb. 11
President B.J. Habibie stunned his countrymen and the world by
saying this Connecticut-sized territory could be independent as
early as next Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie engineered a reversal of his country's 23-year policy
that began when Indonesia invaded East Timor in late 1975. Its
troops smothered a civil war that broke out as soon as the previous
colonial occupier, Portugal, abruptly withdrew earlier in the year.
In 1976 Indonesia formally annexed East Timor as its 27th province.
</P>
<P>
   The annexation was not recognized internationally -- except by
Australia -- and guerrilla fighters of the East Timor independence
movement, Fretilin, have clashed with Indonesian armed forces
stationed here ever since.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 200,000 East Timorese died as a result of
Indonesia's presence, through fighting, executions or starvation
and disease attributed to draconian resettlement policies. Now,
those Timorese who cooperated with Indonesian authorities fear
retribution in an independent East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The visiting Swiss president of the International Red Cross,
Cornelio Sommaruga, appealed for permission to expand the Red Cross
presence in East Timor for an urgently needed ``humanitarian
mobilization.'' He cited the departure of frightened essential
service providers and a growing wave of thousands of internal
refugees from local hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have started packing up stuff. Our worry is that we will
have to leave very quickly,'' said August Sugiarto, 32, who has
taught chemistry for 10 years at General High School No. 2 in Dili,
the East Timor capital about 15 miles east of Liquica (pronounced
``Li-KEE-sa'').
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is conflict, we may be caught in the middle,'' said
Sugiarto, who is from Indonesia's main island of Java.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 90 percent of junior and senior high school
teachers on East Timor, like Sugiarto, are not Timorese. They are
employees of the central government from other parts of the
Indonesian archipelago who were assigned to work here, as are
thousands of others running everything from hospitals to power and
water plants.
</P>
<P>
   If Indonesia cuts ties to East Timor, these civil servants
expect to be removed to other jobs. And many of them want to go,
fearing they are obvious targets if hostilities flare.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, employees at the central hospital in Dili
went on strike for a week, after an Indonesian doctor was attacked
by distraught relatives of a Timorese patient who died. In the
understaffed facility, the doctor had had to choose one of two
emergency patients he would treat, and the untreated patient did
not survive.
</P>
<P>
   Violence here, as elsewhere in Indonesia, has escalated since
economic and political crises led to the ouster of former President
Suharto last May. Confusion and conflict are exacerbated here by
the independence issue.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the young warriors hiding out at the Liquica
bungalow of Gregory Dos Santos, a local leader of the armed branch
of Fretilin, is an example of the murky disputes already raging.
</P>
<P>
   Dos Santos and the fugitives said the pro-independence group was
attacked by a band of anti-independence fighters in their village
Vatoboro. Both sides battled with spears, machetes, bows and arrows
-- the traditional weapons found in every East Timor home.
</P>
<P>
   One attacker was killed, and he turned out to be the son of an
East Timorese serving with the Indonesian army. The next day the
soldiers came.
</P>
<P>
   Troops beat up the pro-independence group with sticks and the
butts of their rifles, they said, and those who could flee, did.
About 60 families all escaped into the forest, though some emerged
to find shelter with sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   However, local military authorities put the blame 100 percent on
pro-independence forces, saying they grabbed a man who was
innocently working in the fields. The man's friends in the
anti-independence civilian militia decided to retrieve him, and a
battle ensued in which one of their fighters was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened, the result is the same. One 18-year-old who
was pro-Indonesia died. Four young men who are pro-independence
were viciously battered, one ending up in the military hospital in
Dili and three others on the spare wooden pallets of what passes
for a hospital in Liquica.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
