<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-OFFICESPACE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OFFICE SPACE' OFFERS A FEW LAUGHS BUT NO HURRAHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to sum up the philosophy (or the advertising) behind
``Office Space,'' a harmless proletarian revenge fantasy from the
creator of ``Beavis and Butthead,'' without resorting to a certain
well-worn vulgarism. But we can try.
</P>
<P>
   Work is a pain in the patoot. The printer is always down, the
nerd at the next desk is always muttering, and the boss is an oily
creep. Work bites the big tomato. Work is a drag. Work stinks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, whether it actually does is an individual matter. But for
the disgruntled occupants of ``Office Space,'' gainful employ is a
cause for much comic whining. Some of it gets a laugh and some of
it doesn't, but all of it speaks to the deep, dark frustrations of
the average cubicle dweller.
</P>
<P>
   Peter (Ron Livingston, ``Swingers'') is about as average as they
get. Armed with crippling ennui and the waggish eyebrows to express
it, Peter trundles daily into his job as a software programmer at
Initech _ a sterile corporate workplace where eight bosses oversee
his every move, or lack thereof. The worst, a slithery jerk named
Lumbergh (Gary Cole, repulsive par excellence), makes Peter's life
purgatory with incessant demands on his time and patience. Peter is
one unhappy fella.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single day of my life has been worse than the day before
it,'' he explains to a hypnotherapist in one of the movie's funnier
sequences. ``So, every day you see me _ that's the worst day of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The hypnotherapist mesmerizes Peter into a state of profound
relaxation, then croaks of a heart attack before he can wake him
up. Thus Peter becomes a blissed-out deadbeat. Thus he assumes a
who-the-hey-cares attitude about work, where he shows up on
occasion to trash his cubicle and gut fish at his desk.
</P>
<P>
   Thus he engages two beleaguered colleagues (Ajay Naidu and David
Herman, both convincing nebbishes) in an embezzlement scheme that
could crash the company. And thus the movie becomes a ``Nine to
Five'' for malcontent Gen X drones.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the plot might have whirled off into a bunch of
directions _ into a high-concept fantasy (the hypnosis thing), into
a comic romance (with Jennifer Aniston, playing Peter's waitress
girlfriend), into a farcical crime caper (the embezzlement). But
writer-director Mike Judge (who made his feature debut with
``Beavis and Butt-head Do America'') has more modest ambitions,
wanting only to spin some humor from the hum-drum angst of everyday
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's transformation from working stiff to enlightened
slacker is amiable enough, and if the movie is too flat to be
hilarious _ if Judge's direction never quite breaks out of his
animated background _ it has some memorable moments. Watch for the
gangsta-rap attack on an obnoxious laser printer _ it's a killer.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Aniston's presence here is a puzzler, since the part
amounts to a few measly scenes, most of them spent discussing the
details of her restaurant uniform. She has one great moment: When
Peter first invites her over to his place to watch ``Kung Fu,'' the
camera zooms into her face and tinkly music materializes on the
soundtrack. ``I ... LOVE ... KUNG ... FU,'' she says, staring at
Peter with dazed-kitten eyes. Piinn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
