<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1650 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-KURDS-BOS &LR;      02-19 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-KURDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KURDISH PROTESTS ATTRACT ATTENTION, LITTLE SYMPATHY IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The image of 15-year-old Nejla Kanteper running down a
London street, her head on fire, horrified Britons this week.
</P>
<P>
   But it also spoke a bitter truth about Kurdish exiles like
Kanteper. Here, as in the rest of Europe, the Kurds are only
noticed when they light themselves on fire, as she did, or engage
in violent protests like the ones launched by the arrest on Monday
of the fugitive Kurdish separatist leader Abdullah Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, about 75 Kurdish protesters ended their three-day
takeover of the Greek embassy in London. A Greek caretaker who had
been held hostage was released unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   British police refused the protesters' demands that they not be
arrested and be allowed to make a statement to the news media in
exchange for leaving the premises. Before the standoff ended,
frustrated officers said they were receiving muddled demands and
messages from inside the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know what they want,'' one senior officer
complained.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the standoff in London underscores the lack of
organization and political sophistication, not to mention bitter
infighting, that have all hurt the Kurds' pursuit of their own
country.
</P>
<P>
   Hostility has replaced indifference among many British people
toward the Kurds. The violent demonstrations that flared across
Europe this week, and are likely to erupt again when Ocalan stands
trial in Turkey, appear to have have eroded what little sympathy
there was here for the Kurdish cause.
</P>
<P>
   A middle-aged Englishwoman who paused on Wednesday afternoon to
observe the demonstrators outside the embassy expressed little
empathy for the teenage girl who set herself on fire to make a
political statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's you and I paying for her in the National Health,'' the
woman complained, referring to the long hospitalization Nejla
Kanteper is expected to undergo while recovering from severe burns.
</P>
<P>
   Kurdish outrage, and reaction to it, continued to reverberate
across Europe, even as the occupations of Greek diplomatic missions
and a brief takeover of a UN office in Vienna ended.
</P>
<P>
   German authorities fear that the estimated 500,000 Kurds in
Germany, the biggest Kurdish exile community in Europe, will cause
widespread havoc if protests continue.
</P>
<P>
   After riots flared throughout Germany, and Israeli security
guards shot dead three Kurdish protesters when they stormed the
Israeli embassy in Berlin, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder spoke for
most in his country when he warned that Kurds who break the law to
make political statements would be deported.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates on the number of Kurds living throughout Europe are
notoriously inaccurate, largely because most countries don't
recognize Kurds as a separate nationality. Instead, they are listed
as Turks, Iraqis, or Syrians _ after the nations in which the bulk
of the estimated 25 million Kurds live.
</P>
<P>
   Kurdish activists claim that upwards of 60,000 Kurds live in
Britain, most of them in London. But an official at Britain's
Foreign Office Thursday said the accurate figure is much lower.
``If there were 60,000 Kurds living here, you'd see more than a few
hundred people outside the (Greek) embassy,'' said the official.
</P>
<P>
   At Britain's Home Office, which is responsible for immigration
and criminal justice, officials admitted they knew little about the
Kurdish exile community. But they said it has not mounted an
organized political movement. Andy Cole, a Home Office spokesman,
said the storming of the Greek embassy was the first ``controlled
reaction'' by Kurds in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   But as frustrated police officers trying to resolve the standoff
explained, the storming of the embassy appeared to be the only
coordinated aspect of the protest. They added that the protesters
entered the building with no obvious plan or leader and gave police
conflicting demands.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the embassy, Zinar Hogir, a spokesman for the Kurdistan
Information Center, said the protesters want British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook to intervene with Turkish authorities to
ensure a fair trial for Ocalan. By that, Hogir and other Kurdish
separatists explained, they want a trial in which Ocalan would not
be charged for any killings. Over 30,000 people have died in the
ugly, 14-year war between the Kurdish Workers' Party, known as the
PKK, and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Because Ocalan is engaged in ``a national liberation struggle,''
he cannot legally be charged with murder, argued Hogir. Besides, he
added, Turkey has killed more people than have ``Kurdish freedom
fighters.''
</P>
<P>
   A Foreign Office spokesman said those demands underscore the
political naivete of the protesters. First, he said, the government
will not intervene in what it regards as the internal affairs of
Turkey. And Britain has no intention to allow the protesters to
leave the embassy without facing criminal charges, ``We don't
reward people who take over embassies,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kurds have long complained that history, national boundaries
and political alliances have worked against them. Hogir and other
Kurds here complain that Turkey's membership in NATO mutes western
criticism of it. They contrast the determination of the western
allies to stop Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's operations
against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo with the muted reaction toward
Turkey's ruthless crushing of Kurdish separatists. They also
acknowledge that rivalry among different Kurdish factions hurts
their causes.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy seizure, and especially the holding of a hostage,
have done little to endear Kurds to a British government that
already regards Kurdish claims of persecution in Turkey with
considerable skepticism. British tourists have been killed in
Turkey by Ocalan's group in a campaign to hurt the country's
thriving tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1,085 heads of Kurdish households who applied for
political asylum in Britain last year claiming persecution in
Turkey, only 40 were granted refugee status. Another 30 were not
recognized as refugees but allowed to stay. In 1997, of the 1,585
applications for asylum, only 110 were allowed to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Liberals and leftists here tend to be isolated in their sympathy
for the Kurds. Tony Benn, the dean of the Labor Party's old
socialist wing, mingled with demonstrators on Wednesday. Benn said
the Kurds' demand for a homeland is as legitimate as that of the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the playwright Harold Pinter said that British people
should regard the acts they've seen this week not as evidence of
irrational malcontents but of a people so desperate that they were
willing to kill themselves to draw attention to their cause.
</P>
<P>
   But most Britons, like taxi driver Steven King, have tired of
them. King, who said he lost half a day's wages on Tuesday when the
demonstrators blocked a main road in the Holland Park section of
London, said: ``If they had their own country, they wouldn't act
like this there. And if they did, the police wouldn't tolerate it
like ours do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 1333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1651 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-LENNON-BOS &LR;      02-19 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LENNON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JULIAN LENNON: BACK WITH A `SMILE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did you intend to come back with another album?
</P>
<P>
   An emphatic no is the quick answer by Julian Lennon, the
once-shy son of Beatles icon John. The new album, ``Photograph
Smile,'' will appear Tuesday, a triumph of grit and perseverance
for a Lennon who was considered finished in the eyes of the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Although Julian popped up in 1984 as a teen favorite with the
album ``Valotte,'' he ended up ``beyond disillusionment'' with the
music business for most of the past decade. He felt shafted by his
managers and his record label, before walking away after 1991's
ironically entitled ``Help Yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, today, Julian (about whom Paul McCartney wrote the
classic ``Hey Jude'') is not afraid to lash out at the biz, nor
afraid to criticize his dad's widow, Yoko Ono, for what he
perceives as diminishing his role in the Lennon legacy. More on
that later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got so frustrated after the last album,'' says Julian.
``I'd had too many broken promises, lack of support, things not
going the way I had hoped, and people just not coming up with the
goods. After living 100 percent in this wonderful industry, it was
time to cut my losses and get the hell out of there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't happy anymore. I wasn't doing what I wanted to do and
I didn't have any control,'' adds Lennon, now a worldly-wise 35.
``It took me five years to be released from the contract I was tied
into, with the record company and management. In that time, if I
had worked, they would have owned it. So I chose not to work. But
it was a blessing in disguise, because I actually lived life for a
change.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of John Lennon by his first wife, Cynthia, Julian
started painting and sculpting. He drove across Europe visiting
friends. He did a lot of sailing, bicycling, and cooking. He tried
photography. eventually, he started composing music again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started writing naturally again,'' he says. ``No time
clocks, nobody knocking at the door. Nobody telling me that it's
not commercial enough or it's not uptempo enough, or this or that.
And once I started writing naturally again, it flowed. I was just
writing for the sake of writing.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Photograph Smile,'' which starts out slowly in a
style very derivative of his dad, but shows a maturing talent as
the 14 songs unfold. There's the chiming, 12-string pop of ``I
Don't Wanna Know,'' the Middle East touches of ``Crucified''
(``we're all freaks in this sideshow,'' he sings), the Paul
Simon-like bounce of ``Kiss Beyond the Catcher,'' the environmental
anthem ``How Many Times'' (about deforestation), the tautly
interesting ``Walls'' (``you feel you have to scream and shout to
let the demons out''), and the idealistic ``Believe,'' which
reaffirms Julian's innate optimism.
</P>
<P>
   The overall sound is Beatlesque (much more so than half-brother
Sean Lennon's album last year), but with better melodies and more
insightful lyrics than Julian has previously shown. It's not a
hard-rock album by any means (he hasn't inherited that side of his
dad's genes), but it's a very decent pop record that he hopes to
back with a tour later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Lyrically, the album appears to be chiefly concerned with the
pros and cons of romance, but the hidden agenda is a discussion of
the music industry, Lennon admits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The album is written with the theme of love in mind, but a lot
of songs are actually written about the business, about the
relationships I was in with record companies and with managers. But
at the end of the day, the last things I want to write about are
record companies and business managers. And I certainly think the
public would agree with that. So, rather than droning on about the
business side of life, it's turned around into the theme of love to
make it more relatable.''
</P>
<P>
   Happily, he comes out the other side with a still positive
outlook. As the last song, ``Way to Your Heart'' (a ballad with a
pretty string arrangement) states: ``I want to love you but not to
mold you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been an optimist in that respect,'' he says.
``I've felt that there's always an answer. That's why I've felt
that I would find a level of peace in life. . . . I think what
keeps you going is that love inside you and the hope and the faith
that things are going to bloody work out in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lennon is thrilled to release another record, he's not as
thrilled with his relationship with Yoko Ono. He has always gotten
along with Sean, but feels Ono has never given him his due as
John's other son. In fact, he had to fight hard, he says, just to
negotiate a settlement to get some of the money from his dad's
copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I've gotten a piece of something that I can pass down
to my kids and to the rest of the Lennon family which does exist in
Europe, which has been shut out from the rest of the world by
Yoko,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He's also been buying some of his dad's stuff back from auctions
_ ``some of the Beatles stuff, because none of that was handed to
me at all. The most ironic thing is how do you think I'm paying for
these things of dad's from the auctions? I'm buying back his stuff
for myself and my kids and the Lennon family in Europe with his
money, which is slightly insane, to say the least.''
</P>
<P>
   Julian, who has no children as yet, says that Yoko ``wants the
history books to show that she and Sean are the Lennon family, and
that we do not exist. If you look at the (recent boxed set) the
`John Lennon Anthology,' if you look at anything that she has part
and parcel to do with, that she's had any control over, if it had
anything to do with dad or the Beatles or before the Beatles or
after, it's a rarity that you'll see my mom and myself as part of
that. It's always Yoko and Sean.''
</P>
<P>
   Lennon can go on about this subject, but he'd clearly rather
talk about the happier life he leads today. He has lived in England
and the United States (in New York and Los Angeles), but now lives
in the lake country of northern Italy, which he loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live on a lake and it's very quiet, very peaceful,'' he
says. ``The people are sweet, the food is phenomenal, the scenery
is phenomenal. Within an hour, you're skiing. Within a couple of
hours, you're on the beach. It's absolutely beautiful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
