<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1652 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-OCTOBER-BOS &LR;      02-19 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-OCTOBER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OCTOBER SKY' MAKES THE MOST OF ITS TIME AND PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
OCTOBER SKY 
Directed by: Joe Johnston 
Screenplay by: Lewis Colick (based on Homer Hickam Jr.'s memoir) 
Starring: Jake Gyllenhaal, Chris Cooper, William Lee Scott, Chris
Owen, Chad Lindberg, Natalie Canerday, Laura Dern 
Running time: 108 minutes 
Rated: PG (language, brief teen sensuality and alcohol use, and for
some thematic elements) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't have to be a rocket scientist to love ``October Sky.''
Based on the memoir of retired NASA scientist Homer Hickam, it
traces his struggle as a teenager in Coalwood, W. Va., inspired by
Sputnik when everyone else was afraid of it and the Soviets who
launched it. Their gaze is downward-directed, into the coal mine
whose owners call the shots in the town. The gaze of Jake
Gyllenhaal's young Homer, however, is resolutely upward. Inspired
by his hero, Wernher von Braun, he and three buddies experiment
with homemade rockets in a far from encouraging climate.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that we know Homer went on to a career with NASA never
undercuts the suspense. So solidly are he and his pals
characterized, so persuasively is the texture of the community laid
in, that the film not only is convincing, it's affecting in a
moment-to-moment way. We want to know how he did it, how he
overcame skepticism and initial failure. ``October Sky'' isn't
afraid to be unabashedly inspirational. But its message wisely
takes a back seat to its storytelling skills, which are as
compelling as they are considerable, starting with our amusement at
the seriousness with which the inhabitants of Coalwood take the
Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   But quickly we realize that fearfulness is bred into communal
life there, including the fear of economic devastation. That's one
reason Homer's father, played by the underappreciated Chris Cooper
in one of his finest performances, automatically thinks in terms of
sending his sons down into the mine, unless an athletic scholarship
should enter the picture. Not that Homer and his family are poor.
They belong to Coalwood's version of an aristocracy, since the
senior Hickam is the mine supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   It's momentarily startling to hear Cooper, so unforgettable as
the union organizer in John Sayles's ``Matewan,'' intensely voice
the management's anti-union line. But it's a measure of the
strength of ``October Sky'' that Cooper's John Hickman is no mere
cardboard heavy. Never do we doubt that he loves his family, or
that he is, in his own skewed way, conscientious, a hard-working
and honest man whose intrinsic pride and self-reliance have been
used against him, turning him away from a communal ethos. It's out
of misplaced love that he wants to literally give his sons the
shaft. So urgently does Cooper project his conflicted character
that it would be criminal if he didn't nail down one of next year's
Oscar nominations.
</P>
<P>
   But while Cooper's John Hickam is the film's most complex
character, there's nothing lacking in Gyllenhaal and the other
young actors playing his buddies. He's rightly unpolished but
characterful and doesn't give up when his first experiments fail.
Prospects improve when he enlists the aid of his three friends
believably played by Chris Owen, William Lee Scott, and Chad
Lindberg. The biggest boost comes from Owen's geeky math whiz,
Quentin, who lives at the low end of the Coalwood scale, in a
rickety shack. One of the strands in the film's huge emotional pull
involves us wishing Quentin can escape Coalwood along with Homer.
</P>
<P>
   Although the high school principal is discouraging, and
represents the Coalwood majority strongly enough to make you ask
why they're so invested in the boys' failure, Homer and the others
do get some backing, most notably from Laura Dern's teacher, who
points them toward a science fair. Dern's low-key naturalism sits
perfectly in the film's unerring evocation of time and place and
community texture. It may sound corny in the telling, but you'll be
caught up in the boys' attempts to end their long string of
misfires, launch one of their homemade rockets according to plan,
and, in doing so, launch their lives as well, blasting them beyond
the soul-crushing life that awaits them in the pits. As a movie,
the biggest obstacle ``October Sky'' faces is a pall of uplift. But
with the old-fashioned resoluteness of its era, it soars beyond
that, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
