<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC SPONSORS REEVALUATING THEIR ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (s and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What for 15 years has been indisputably a golden calf among
sports marketing opportunities for major corporations like
Coca-Cola, Xerox and Samsung, now is suddenly open to question.
</P>
<P>
   After two months of horrific publicity about corruption in the
International Olympic Committee and the Winter Games scheduled for
Salt Lake City in 2002, companies are begining to reevaluate
whether the Olympics continue to be the ultimate advertising
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   While there remains a stubborn reluctance on the part of
executives of the companies to publicly challenge the IOC _ leaving
David D'Alessandro, the president and chief operating officer of
Boston's John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. as the most
prominent public critic _ observers say that a meeting in New York
City last week among the major sponsors and the IOC was a
watershed.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the sponsors strongly challenged IOC officals at the
meeting to move more aggressively to clean up the scandal.
Moreover, the companies are starting to field queries from their
boards of directors and stockholders about how they are handling
the Olympic mess.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if this was a normal Olympic cycle, the only talk
about the games at Coca-Cola's headquarters in Atlanta Thursday
would have been about strategies to maximize the company's $50
million sponsorship of the bi-annual events.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the board of directors of Coke, a sponsor of the
Olympics for 70 years, was slated to discuss far more rudimentary
issues: the relative value of the sponsorship, and whether the
company's brand could be tarnished by associating with the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, as a sponsor we're concerned when events of this
seriousness _ and they are quite serious _ impact any activity of
the company, whether they be sponsorships or what have you,'' said
board member Susan B. King, a former senior vice-president of the
company, who is a trustee of Duke University. ``I think everybody
would like to see this weathered.''
</P>
<P>
   While Coke has not gone public with strong criticism of the IOC,
sports marketing sources say that the company and Visa
International have been outspoken in private dealings with the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several sponsors who share D'Alessandro's concerns,
but for whatever reasons they don't want to be as public about
it,'' said Bob Heussner, the senior vice-president for strategic
planning at Advantage International, the worldwide sports and
marketing agency, based in McLean, Va. ``There was a lot of concern
expressed at that meeting, and a lot of questions asked for which
the IOC had no answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think how all of this sorts out depends on what happens in
the next 60 to 90 days,'' Heussner said. ``If, by then, all of the
skeletons are out of the closet and dealt with effectively, I would
predict that most of the sponsors stay involved, and at the current
level. If the IOC doesn't do that, it's a roll of the dice.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four members of IOC have been linked to ethical
misconduct involving Salt Lake City's bid for the 2002 Winter
Games. The IOC has said it will expel at least eight of those
members. Meanwhile, the IOC, the Attorney General of Utah, the
United States Justice Department, and the US Olympic Committee are
all conducting investigations.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, according to industry observers and some
company officials, the sponsors are expected to use the negative
publicity as leverage to try and drive down sponsorship fees, and
to loosen the IOC's control of the use of the Olympic rings as a
marketing symbol. The IOC's rigid approach to how the symbol of the
Olympics may be used in marketing is a source of continued
frustration for the companies.
</P>
<P>
   Some firms are starting to be more proactive, albeit behind the
scenes. Sources, including industry observers, say that Visa is
telling the IOC that it wants the leader of the Olympic movement,
President Juan Antonio Samaranch, to step down, if Visa is to
continue to support the Olympics at its current level of about $40
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would never make any of our private communications with the
IOC or anyone else public,'' said Michael Sherman, director of
international corporate communications for Visa. ``Visa has had
discussions on the role of the IOC leadership in the future, as
have other sponsors. But Visa has sent no letter discussing Mr.
Samaranch's position.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11 major Olympic sponsors would appear to have considerable
leverage. With the exception of Coca-Cola and TIME/Sports
Illustrated, all must renew their sponsorships with the IOC later
this year. The scandal is forcing the companies to consider whether
their cherished international showcases are yielding diminishing
returns.
</P>
<P>
   At stake, industry sources say, is nearly $1 billion that the
IOC derives from sponsorships and, indirectly, from television
advertisers that the IOC uses to finance both the games and the
development of sports around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   What the companies are hoping for, and advocating strongly
behind closed doors, is swift and certain action by the IOC at its
March meetings in Switzerland to make clear that the way it has
conducted business since the Olympics became big money in 1984 is
no longer viable. At the meeting in New York last week, they
demanded, and received, assurances that there will be a conference
telephone call with IOC officials in early March, before the
crucial meetings, to make sure that certain reform is on track.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro is specifically seeking: an admission from the IOC
that it is incapable of investigating itself; a new IOC membership
appointed by every member nation of the United Nations, as opposed
to the current membership appointed by Samaranch himself; a new
site-selection process that eliminates the IOC members' role of
visiting cities and then voting; full-disclosure of all gifts
received by members; and an immediate start of a search for a
successor to Samaranch, who is scheduled to retire in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the companies are about the difficult business of
weighing what impact the scandal is having on their brands. That is
difficult to assess, and the efforts so far have produced mixed
results.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner &AMP; Associates, a public research firm in Baltimore,
conducted a survey in early February that showed 70 percent of
American adults either had not heard about the scandal, or felt no
differently about the sponsors after having heard about it. Only 18
percent of those surveyed felt negatively about the companies. But
according to a USA Today/CNN/Gallup poll conducted on February 9,
51 percent of 711 adults examined said their respect for the games
has declined, with 23 percent saying they are less likely to watch
the 2002 games on television.
</P>
<P>
   Amid that confusing context, one of the sponsors making a
decision about involvement beyond 2000 is UPS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we are about the business of measuring constituent
impact,'' said Susan Rosenberg, an Olympic marketing official with
the company. ``We're using our customers and our employees and
surveying them to measure their reaction to what's been happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most of the sponsors, I would think, we're in a
wait-and-see mode, seeing what actions the IOC is going to take and
what the impact is,'' Rosenberg said. ``We feel we've had such
success with the Olympics, so far, why would we make a snap
decision now, when the process involving the allegations is still
ongoing?''
</P>
<P>
   The same wait-and-see approach, with caveats, prevails at Visa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expressed our concerns at the New York meeting,'' Sherman
said, ``and we expect decisive action across the board on a number
of issues both with the IOC and other areas. There is a lot of
communication involved with this at Visa International, and we are
very much on top of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, many officials involved with the Olympics say that
the athletes and the long tradition of spectator interest in the
games themselves are likely to win out. But the sponsors will push
publicly or privately for reform and use their leverage to try and
rein in the escalation of fees _ which have jumped to the current
average of $40 million per sponsor from as little as $150,000 to
$250,000 for the 1980 Winter Games at Lake Placid.
</P>
<P>
   An example of the continued popularity of the games themselves
is the bright portrait painted by Dick Ebersol, the chairman of NBC
Sports, which owns the US broadcast rights to the Olympics through
2008, at an estimated cost of $3.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one at the IOC can take any confidence that what they have
done to date is enough,'' Ebersol said. ``They must continue to
move to deal with new members under suspicion, to have new voting
procedures and to show, when it comes time to select the site of
the 2006 games, that this is a whole new way of doing things.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, the fact of the matter is, we have not heard a single
word from any of our advertisers signed up for the (2000) Sydney
games in terms of them being concerned about what they have bought.
And we are half sold, already.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
