<SLUG> BC-CALIF-VIETNAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CALIFORNIA, A DIVISIVE ECHO OF VIETNAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTMINSTER, Calif. _ As painful proof that he values freedom in
all its forms, Lap Nguyen offered the bullet hole just inches from
his heart, the dent behind one ear, the jagged pink scars on both
ankles.
</P>
<P>
   ``See,'' he said in English that was strong but still broken
after five years in the United States, ``I fight for what I
believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Nguyen, along with hundreds of other Vietnamese refugees who
have settled in Orange County, has taken the fight against
communism to an unlikely setting: a nondescript shopping center
along one of Westminster's main boulevards.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every day for more than a month, they have marched,
shouted anti-communist slogans and waved banners outside a store
whose owner insists on displaying a poster of communist leader Ho
Chi Minh and a communist Vietnamese flag in a part of town known as
Little Saigon. Fights have broken out. When 150 police officers in
helmets and body shields tried to disperse a crowd of 500 on
Monday, demonstrators laid down in their path.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters say they are exercising the freedom of speech
guaranteed in their adopted homeland. The store owner, Truong Van
Tran, says he is doing the same. With both sides unwilling to
budge, the standoff has highlighted the difficulties that can arise
when old wounds come up against new freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   No one _ not the police, not the protesters, not even Tran's
lawyers _ can quite explain why Tran dared the Vietnamese community
to make him take down the flag and photo, which he had displayed
quietly for some time. Little is known about his personal story or
beliefs. All anyone knows for certain is that the 37-year-old Tran
returned to Vietnam last year for the first time in two decades and
that he came away convinced that the current government is a
legitimate one that deserves normalized relations with the United
States. He does not call himself a communist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to provoke our community, the same as if he hang
Hitler's picture in Jewish community,'' said Nguyen, 48, who fought
against Ho Chi Minh's army and later spent 10 years in jail. ``The
law is not everything. There is a moral obligation to his
neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   An Orange County Superior Court judge, however, ruled that Tran
has a constitutional right to display the communist symbols at his
HiTek TV and VCR store. The American Civil Liberties Union, which
is representing Tran, said police must now enforce his right to do
so. Tran, who was hospitalized briefly after he was hit in the head
outside his store in mid-January and again last week when he fell
to the ground after a melee erupted, has vowed on Vietnamese radio
to rehang his display.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are your rights as guaranteed by the court and then your
rights as exist practically,'' said Peter Eliasberg, one of the
ACLU attorneys handling Tran's case. ``Right now he's being denied
his rights practically. . . . All I can say is if he's willing to
put his principles before the profit motive, more power to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tran's business has been closed for a month now, and Vietnamese
community leaders say they cannot imagine anyone shopping there
ever again. The landlord wants him out and has issued an eviction
notice, claiming that Tran owes thousands of dollars in back rent
and other fees. The landlord also says that Tran has hurt other
mall tenants by creating a public nuisance. Tran has said he
intends to fight the eviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very appropriate time to evict a guy who's in arrears
on rent and then invites all these people down for a
confrontation,'' said attorney Jonathan Slipp, who represents
landlord Danh Quach. ``At that time, you start saying, `Maybe this
guy isn't the best tenant.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks a one-note song is coming out of the Vietnamese
community in Orange County,'' Eliasberg explained. ``He thinks it's
important to have a dialogue and that issues should be discussed.
He's a stubborn guy and he thinks he has a right to speak and, as
an American, he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Vietnamese-Americans in Orange County, where a third or more of
the 300,000 Vietnamese refugees in southern California live, say
they are horrified by how Tran has gone about making his point. In
one letter addressed to Vietnamese community leaders, and
translated into English by them, he boasted of the portrait of ``my
beloved Uncle Ho Chi Minh.'' In another, he added, ``If you all
think you are great, then go ahead, come over to clear me out.'' It
was signed, ``Good bye all of you in a state of anger.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, a core group of a dozen or more protesters has been
spending the night outside HiTek. Days, hundreds of Vietnamese
immigrants show up regularly, some to gawk, most to express the
anger and hurt that the symbols still evoke in them. Vietnam and
Korean war veterans have turned out to show their support for the
demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing this in this community, it's just uncalled for,'' said
Alfred Garcia, 65, who wore his dog tags from the Korean War over
his shirt. ``Sure he has his First Amendment rights, but these
people were hurt really deeply by the war. What he's doing is like
shouting fire in a theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Bui Binh Ban, president of the Federation of Overseas Free
Vietnamese Communities in nearby Garden Grove, said, ``We lost
everything to survive. . . . We cannot accept to see the communist
flag fly here. He can do anything he wants, but he cannot provoke
the people.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Orange County Human Relations Commission has been
unable to negotiate an armistice between the demonstrators and
Tran. Rusty Kennedy, the commission's executive director, doesn't
think there can or will be one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not even on our list of expectations,'' Kennedy said.
``The spokespersons for the protesters will not negotiate with him.
Period. And he wants publicity for his cause.''
</P>
<P>
   The intransigence on both sides has put Westminster police in
the position of having to guarantee everyone's safety and their
right to air differing opinions. At one point, when Tran refused to
cooperate with their plans to safeguard him, police threatened to
arrest him if he returned to the video store. Police also declared
an unlawful assembly, and temporarily ordered the protesters to
leave. Both orders have since been rescinded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems intent on trying to inflame the community; at one
point he was talking about having a helicopter drop fliers with a
picture of the Hanoi flag,'' said Lieutenant Bill Lewis, spokesman
for the Westminster Police Department. ``What was that about? . . .
So we're ready for the long haul. Ending this would take I don't
know how many police officers and putting them in harm's way.''
</P>
<P>
   Thang Tran, president of the Vietnamese Community of Southern
California and no relation to the store owner, said his group has
repeatedly urged peace among the protesters. Violence is what they
left behind in Vietnam, he said. It would do no good to bring it to
their streets now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the right to free speech and we know that,'' said Ky
Ngo, one of the protest organizers. ``We have the right, too, to
raise our voice and show we're against him. You can do that in
America and we're in America now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
