u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV21     02-19 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV21-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE SENSIBLE CORE POSITON SHOULD BE IN INDEX FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, February 21, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have a sizable five-figure amount of savings in an IRA. I
am 41 and am fairly risk-tolerant. Until March 1998 it did fairly
well in Columbia Growth. My financial adviser guaranteed me that we
could do better with other funds. Following this advice, we moved
it to the following investments: 50 percent in Oakmark, 30 percent
in Brandes Institutional International Equity, and 20 percent in
Acorn USA. Had I left the funds in their original location, I would
have garnered a 19 percent gain in the past 10 months. However,
presently the group as a whole has lost 3 percent. I realize this
is a small time period to judge the performance, but I really don't
want to head down this path if the past is any indication of the
future. Not to mention that I am paying a 1 percent annual fee for
this advice. What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   P.S., Tigard, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   A. To a degree I wouldn't be too hard on this adviser _ the
suggestions went largely along the lines of advice that I
frequently give, which is to diversify beyond a large-cap growth
portfolio domination. With the benefit of hindsight, it seems to me
that the big error here was to move the core position from
large-cap growth (Columbia Growth) to the large-cap value
(Oakmark).
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the past 52 weeks have not treated Oakmark kindly,
with its loss of 4.20 percent ranking it number 909 of 991 growth
funds tracked during that period by Lipper Analytical Services. The
average growth fund tracked by Lipper in that period returned 17.98
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps your adviser relied on your assessment that you are
fairly risk-tolerant when choosing this fund. Oakmark's portfolio
manager Robert J. Sanborn is given to take big positions in what
Morningstar Mutual Funds calls deep value plays.
</P>
<P>
   This has led to a 9 percent-plus position in Phillip Morris and
a little more than 6 percent in downtrodden Nike. But Morningstar
also notes that over the long run Sanborn's plays have frequently
rewarded his gutsy shareholders well _ evidenced by its five-year
record of 17.29 percent returns, only slightly trailing the
large-cap value average of 17.88 percent in that period.
</P>
<P>
   The report on the two diversifications is better. Acorn USA, a
small-cap fund, lost 2.55 percent over the 52 weeks ended Feb. 11,
according to Lipper _ the average loss for its peers was 7.89
percent. It's a keeper.
</P>
<P>
   Brandes Institutional International Equity is your only fund
that was in the black for the 52-week period, returning 8.20
percent. Another keeper.
</P>
<P>
   So what to do? You're perhaps right that ten months isn't a
sufficiently long period to let the investment adviser show his or
her stuff. And as I said before, I agree with the idea of
diversifying beyond the large-caps. But I also think Oakmark is a
sufficiently contrarian fund that it's not a good choice for a core
position. Thus you might consider moving the lion's share of that
position back to Columbia Growth, or to a fund tracking the
Standard and Poor's 500. That last suggestion probably would make
your adviser scowl _ after all, who wants to pay somebody a 1
percent fee to suggest an index fund?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My son is 32 and has his IRA with T. Rowe Price, entirely
invested in its Equity Income. The current balance is approximately
$9,000. Because of his age, both he and I felt the IRA should be
invested in equities. Do you agree? We also wondered whether it
would be better to have his IRA invested in Price's Equity Index,
which gained 27.9 percent in 1998, compared to 8.4 percent for
Equity Income.
</P>
<P>
   J.Z., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, I think you're both right that this IRA should be
invested entirely in stocks at this point. And I also agree that
Price's Equity Index would be better than Equity Income over the
long haul. That's not to say that Price's Equity Income isn't a
good offering, but its objective requires that its portfolio be
concentrated in issues with strong yields _ and this steers it to
the value-oriented old workhorses which indeed deliver solid
dividends, but also offer little in the way of growth prospects. If
you go with the index fund, you'll get these same stocks, but
they'll also be mixed with the growth stocks, thus providing a good
deal of spark to the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   I agree that you should make the switch. But you should also be
prepared for the inevitable second-guessing that you will do when
the markets turn sour.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My problems and questions concern holdings in Mutual
Financial Services Z, Mutual European Z, and Mutual Shares Z funds,
all of which have performed very poorly over the past year. I have
had money in the Mutual fund family for a long time, going back to
the time when Mr. Price directed them, and I was satisfied with the
results up to the time they were absorbed by the Templeton fund
family. What is the reason for the lackluster performance of these
funds? Would you advise an exit? I am 68, retired, and living on a
pension and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   E.B., Easton, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, I can't argue with your discontent. In 1998 all three
of these funds trailed their peer averages, and two of them _
Mutual Shares Z and Mutual European Z _ were way behind, with the
.45 percent total return of Mutual Shares comparing to a 12.34
percent average return for large-cap value funds, and the 4.74
percent return of Mutual European comparing to an 18.97 percent
peer average, according to Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Price, who was viewed as the key manager behind the
splendid long-term record of the Mutual fund group, is now gone. I
can't see any particularly good reason not to follow.
</P>
<P>
   If I were you I'd transfer to another fund family. I'll suggest
a few Vanguard funds, although you could build a similar portfolio
with a number of other families. I would treat Vanguard Index Value
as the equivalent of Mutual Shares, Vanguard European Stock Index
as a swap for Mutual European, and I would quit the financial
services arena entirely. You might decide that at your age you
don't want any sector fund, given the higher risks that go with
investing in single market sectors. If that's the case, you might
want to consider Vanguard Wellesley Income fund, which would
provide you with a tidy income stream. But if you are comfortable
with sector risk, I'd go with Vanguard Specialized Heath Care.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address, and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
