<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NENGLAND-CASINOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING LUCK HUNTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLOUCESTER, Mass. _ Mike Paolucci first put out of the harbor
here on a lobster boat at 12 years old. Twenty years later, he's
still going out, and as the fishing vessel Christina-Eleni bobs on
the waves, he talks about the dangers of heading to sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger used to be out there,'' he says, his hand sweeping
the salty horizon.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not on the Christina-Eleni. He's standing on the Vegas
Express, the state's first gambling cruise boat. ``These days,'' he
says, ``the danger's in here.''
</P>
<P>
   He's got $140 in his pocket _ and a stash left ashore _ and
that's the way the 32-year-old disc jockey and Renaissance singer
limits the danger aboard what is virtually a floating casino.
</P>
<P>
   The Vegas Express, which leaves the harbor for afternoon and
evening cruises Wednesday through Saturday and on Sunday
afternoons, heads quickly out beyond the three-mile limit of
Massachusetts waters and beyond the reach of state gambling laws.
</P>
<P>
   As it crosses the line into federal waters, 175 electronic slot
machines come to life with what sounds like a communal gulp. The
craps tables and poker and blackjack tables and the roulette wheel
are bathed in bright light. Gamblers, full of expectation, flock to
the tables and machines, ignoring the bob of the vessel in 5-foot
swells.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts, with House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran apparently
in the forefront, is considering whether to continue to lose
gambling revenue to video gambling in Rhode Island and casinos in
Connecticut. New Hampshire may yet consider allowing video gambling
at its racetracks.
</P>
<P>
   Aboard the Vegas Express or inside the video casino at the
Lincoln Park dog track in Lincoln, R.I., there is a glimpse of the
future of gambling here. If gambling is indeed on the menu in
Massachusetts, these places are today's surf and turf offering.
</P>
<P>
   It costs $39 for a cruise of about five hours on the 204-foot
Vegas Express. For that, as many as 400 passengers get a hot meal
in the dining room and about four hours of gambling time _ or time
to walk exterior decks and take in the sea. Many customers view the
trip as a sightseeing cruise, as well as a gambling junket.
</P>
<P>
   The video games are set up in rows on all three levels. The
second level, which has no windows, most resembles a Las Vegas
casino. Video games line the outer walls, while craps, roulette,
and poker and blackjack tables fill the center of the deck. The
video games take bills as high as $100, and the gambling tables
have $200 limits.
</P>
<P>
   The cheaper, 25-cent video games are on the third deck, where
windows give a sweeping view of the sea. The machine's names are
full of promise: Diamond Roses, Red Hot 7, Blazing 7s, Fame and
Fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty minutes after the cruise begins, Mike Paolucci is up on
the third deck, looking for a comeback. He's already down $100 from
the craps table.
</P>
<P>
   Paolucci, a big man with hands to match, works two machines at
once, his fingers hitting the buttons, and he more than makes up
for his earlier losses. The speed with which the games are played _
and money lost and won _ is remarkable. Wheels whir in slot games;
in electronic card games, hands are dealt almost instantly.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd is almost all white. There are young couples, older
women, young singles. When somebody wins _ the loud tink, tink,
tink of coins being disgorged announces a win all through the
second deck _ others gather to watch and smile.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Delphia, 31, of Charlton wins on a slot machine but does
not know why: She doesn't understand the mix of bars and fruit and
7s that adds up to money. ``No, no, I didn't know I'd won at all.
Everybody else told me I did, and then the money started pouring
out.''
</P>
<P>
   She came aboard with $200 she had saved for the trip. Her plan
is to put all she wins into her pocketbook to take home with her
and gamble only the $200 base. By the time her machine quits
spitting coins, she's got $400 to tuck away. She'll hit another
machine for $100 later.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Barry is 21 and a business major from Salisbury. He's here
on an outing with his father, Neil, a Seabrook, N.H., businessman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both had the day off, and he took me here,'' Brian says.
``It's a nice way to spend the day together, gamble a little, enjoy
the cruise.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, they sit on the exposed upper deck, protected from
Febrary weather by clear plastic sheets draped on poles. As the
song, ``Come Break My Heart,'' blares from loudspeakers and the sun
begins to set, Neil says, ``Hey, this is great. You pay $40 for a
whale watch, and you don't even get a meal.''
</P>
<P>
   When the cruises began last July, there was some concern about
easy access to gambling and about paychecks being lost. Lenny Ross,
a Gloucester native and a heavy-equipment mechanic, saw it happen
among friends.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing a beer at Old Timers' bar on the waterfront, Ross, who
does not gamble, said, ``When it first started, you had locals
going out on the boat, but they learned pretty fast you can lose a
paycheck out there, so they've backed off now.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Cheryl Delphia, the lucky novice gambler, says she has seen
much the same thing ashore and in a far more pervasive way, at
lottery outlets where people gamble as an afterthought while doing
something as simple as picking up a quart of milk at the corner
store.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take the lottery, and you can just go down to the store
and scratch your pay away on those things,'' she says. Coming to a
gambling vessel or deciding to go to a track to wager at video
machines is a conscious, planned decision, she says.
</P>
<P>
   That's evident in the parking lot at Rowe Square, from which the
Vegas Express embarks. It is filled with the cars of travelers who
have made a conscious effort to get here to gamble, not only from
Massachusetts, but also Maine and New Hampshire. The scene is
repeated at the dog track in Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   There on a Tuesday night, the oval itself was cold and unlit.
But the lot held a hefty supply of cars, and an orange neon glow
beckoned through glass doors.
</P>
<P>
   While the Vegas Express has a cruise ship feel, with songs,
trivia games and other nongambling entertainment, the two large
video gaming rooms at Lincoln have a distinct Vegas air. There are
about 1,200 machines here, the state's answer to 1992, when
Foxwoods opened in nearby Connecticut and hurt the dog track's
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Markarian, an East Providence jeweler, scoffs at the
notion that places like this take money from the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You segregate gambling; it helps to eliminate the casual
gambler,'' he says. ``Widespread gambling is too much temptation.
Here, you have to come with a goal and a plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what Mike Paolucci did. He boarded with his
$140, lost most of it fast, but then made it back up at the video
games.
</P>
<P>
   After the Vegas Express docks, the big man ambles up the gangway
and crosses the parking lot to ease himself into the seat of his
black Cadillac for the drive home to Beverly. He's been on a sunny
winter cruise, he's had a meal, and he's $40 richer than when he
left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
