<HEADLINE>
GARBAGE CLIMBS TO THE TOP OF THE GRAMMY HEAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Garbage at the Grammys. That's right. The pride of alt-rock
nation is not just going to the Grammys next Wednesday, but is
among the elite five acts whose recordings have been nominated for
album of the year, joining Lauryn Hill, Sheryl Crow, Madonna, and
Shania Twain in that category.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be up there with all those women artists is unbelievable,''
says Garbage drummer Butch Vig. ``And it's really five women if you
include our singer, Shirley (Manson). I think it's cool.''
</P>
<P>
   What's also cool is that Vig doesn't even think Garbage should
win. ``I hope Lauryn Hill wins. I think her record is the most
challenging,'' says Vig, whose group performs at the FleetCenter
Monday (opening up for Alanis Morissette) before flying to Los
Angeles for the Grammys.
</P>
<P>
   Garbage is also up for best rock album for ``Version 2.0,'' its
provocative, rock-techno pastiche CD that uses drum loops and
samplers, but also raw, retro-rock guitars and a few
well-publicized lyrics and riffs from the likes of Chrissie Hynde,
Brian Wilson, and Romeo Void.
</P>
<P>
   In short, this band has a history (it consists of a 20-something
Scottish singer and three older males from the Midwest) and it
doesn't take its Grammy nominations for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're younger, you feel you can go on forever,'' says
Vig. ``But we're now well aware that pop bands can be very
fleeting.''
</P>
<P>
   So, win or lose, Vig intends to have fun in LA. ``I'm staying in
a room next to Snoop Dogg!'' he says with a laugh. ``The way I look
at it is that the ceremony should be fun, but the whole schmooze
thing will be fascinating.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, it's right back on the road for Vig, who is also
widely known as the producer of Nirvana's breakthrough album,
``Nevermind.'' (Of which he says: ``That was a difficult record to
make, because I had to push Kurt Cobain a lot to go beyond what he
thought he was capable of.'')
</P>
<P>
   Garbage, which has reeled off such hits as ``Stupid Girl,''
``Queer,'' ``Only Happy When It Rains,'' ``Push It,'' and the
latest, ``Special,'' is looking forward to touring with Morissette,
though it will be hard to be an opening act again after just
completing its own headline run in Europe. Over there, Garbage
played to 12,000 people at London's Wembley Arena and in Dublin,
there was the added thrill that ``we partied with U2 until the sun
came up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to jokingly say that we wanted to be an international
pop band,'' adds Vig. ``It's very gratifying to see that coming
true.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SFX goes Vegas: Concert giant SFX never rests. The latest move
is signing a three-year deal with the Las Vegas Convention and
Visitors Authority to mark Las Vegas as ``the official resort
destination'' of SFX, according to a Pollstar report. The
partnership means that Las Vegas will have a ``highly visible
on-site promotional presence at SFX-produced shows in 10 major US
markets this year.'' No word on whether Great Woods, now an SFX
venue, will be one of them, but don't bet against it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
