<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLULM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORLD OF GRIEVANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know what they say: It's OK to eat sausages, but you don't
ever want to see how they are made.
</P>
<P>
   The same might apply to Microsoft's ballyhooed CD-ROM
encyclopedia, Encarta Africana. Now being aggressively promoted by
Harvard professors Henry Louis (``Skip'') Gates Jr. and Kwame
Anthony Appiah as the culmination of W. E. B. Du Bois's lifetime
dream, the colorful encyclopedia boasts over 400 contributors,
including United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan, Quincy
Jones, and Whoopi Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   But the vast majority of Encarta's 2.5 million words were
written by a group of about 15 writers hunkered down in the Vanserg
Building on the fringe of the Harvard campus _ and a fractious
group at that. During the year and a half of intense work that went
into creating Africana, the project suffered an embarrassing
plagiarism incident, and a near-revolt on the part of the
piece-work writers who complained about low salaries, the lack of
benefits, and the paucity of African-Americans working on the
project.
</P>
<P>
   The plagiarism occurred when Gates and Appiah's newly formed
corporation, Afropaedia LLC, submitted a batch of text to Microsoft
in 1997. Student temporary employees turned out to have copied, or
flimsily rewritten, many articles from the Encyclopedia of
African-American Culture &AMP; History, co-edited by Gates's Harvard
colleague, Cornel West. Depending on who's telling the story,
either Microsoft editors or Gates and Appiah spotted the copying
and called a halt to it. When the full-time staff was hired, the
Afropaedia managers laid down strict guidelines about sourcing new
articles.
</P>
<P>
   Once work ramped up in the summer of 1997, the writers learned
that working on Africana would be no bowl of cherries. Deadline
pressure was intense, and some staffers sardonically observed that
they were working ``for the wrong Gates,'' meaning that their
working conditions more closely resembled those of benefit-deprived
``temps'' at Bill Gates's Microsoft than those of the Harvard
staffers surrounding Professor Gates at his W. E. B. Du Bois
Institute. Pay was writerly, i.e. low. Furthermore, each man or
woman had to meet a daily writing quota, and there were no formal
provisions for paid vacation, medical benefits, or sick leave.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions came to a head in October of 1997, when 12 of the
writers signed a letter to Gates and Appiah, asking to discuss
their grievances. Gates said the Encarta budget didn't allow for
benefits or higher salary, but he did make some concessions.
Thereafter, the writers received some paid vacation, productivity
bonuses, and an extra month's pay if they stayed until the
project's end.
</P>
<P>
   After that meeting, Africana staffer Stephen Bicknell asked the
Harvard Union of Clerical and Technical Workers if the 14 Africana
writers could unionize. Bicknell recalls: ``(Organizer) Kris
Rondeau told me: `Let me get this straight. You want me to help you
unionize, you'll be leaving here in 10 months, and you want to go
up against Skip Gates?' '' Says Rondeau: ``I agreed that it was a
highly imperfect labor situation,'' but nothing came of it.
</P>
<P>
   Gates says he has been roundly attacked by Afrocentrist
historians for not employing enough African-American staffers on
Encarta Africana, and is chary about discussing the working
conditions of his mostly white labor force. ``I've never had a
project that generated as much friction,'' he says of Africana.
``It was a learning experience for me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ich bin Monika!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the more outre book proposals yet seen on our fair shores
landed at 11 US literary agencies this week. The would-be writer:
Monika Lewinsky, a Viennese pharmacology student with a tentative
grasp of the English language, but a rock-solid sense of American
book-publishing priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a synopsis of the proposed 50-page humor book:
</P>
<P>
   ``A. Monika's reaction to the breaking news in the media and how
her life changed due to the notoriety of her name.
</P>
<P>
   B. Family name's history. Coat of arms of the Lewinskys.''
</P>
<P>
   And so on. Reached at home, Lewinsky proved to be as press-shy
as her American namesake. During the height of the scandal, she
complained, ``Everyone wanted to interview me. It was getting on my
nerves.'' Then she hung up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 1348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
