<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1672 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-STONES-BOS &LR;      02-19 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-STONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STONES' AN EERIE, ENGROSSING NOVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN CLEGG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE STONES CRY OUT 
By Hikaru Okuizumi; translated, from the Japanese, by James N.
Westerhoven 
Harcourt Brace, 138 pp, $20 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine the history of the universe encased in a single stone.
The clash of tectonic plates and the burble of red-hot magma, the
emergence of vertebrates from the ooze, all calcified, stratified,
and frozen forever as granite or schist. It's an image that appeals
to anyone with a yearning for order, because one needs only to pick
up a geologist's hammer and chisel to make sense of mystery, to
illumine the dark cave where candlelight and reason get snuffed
out.
</P>
<P>
   Tsuyoshi Manase, the protagonist of this eerie and engrossing
novel, must emerge from just such a cave. It's literal and
figurative, that cave, and it dominates his dreams and his wakeful
malarial ravings. Ultimately, it undoes him. ``The Stones Cry
Out,'' by Japanese writer Hikaru Okuizumi, is the story of an
amateur geologist and bookseller slowly collapsing under the burden
of his own history. The book, which received the Akutagawa Prize
recognizing new Japanese writers, was published in 1993. This
English translation, by James N. Westerhoven, is as polished as any
pebble in Manase's sample case.
</P>
<P>
   Manase learns his first, and most enduring, geology lesson from
a dying soldier in a cave on the Philippine island of Leyte, where
a remnant of the Japanese army has taken refuge at the end of World
War II. The soldier, a corporal, is skeletal, his eyes swarming
with maggots, but his voice is low and steady. ``What I'm trying to
say is, the tiny pebble that you might happen to pick up during a
walk is a cross-section of a drama that began some five billion
years ago, in a place that would later come to be called the solar
system _ a cloud of gas drifting idly through space, growing denser
and denser until after countless eons it finally gave birth to this
planet. That little pebble is a condensed history of the universe
that keeps the eternal cycle of matter locked in its ephemeral
form.''
</P>
<P>
   As circumstances within the cave grow more desperate, the
captain, convinced that the Japanese army will make one final
stand, organizes the starving, wounded men who have crawled in from
the jungle. The search for food becomes primary, and soldiers who
are strong raid abandoned villages and hack through the tangle of
vines to bring back snakes, lizards, a gaunt chicken. The captain
eats first, and leftovers are divided among those who have a few
days of life left. In order to amass the strongest fighting force,
the captain issues an order: Men who can no longer get up must end
their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, not one of the sick soldiers had enough physical or
moral strength left to do it,'' Okuizumi writes. ``The captain
issued orders to kill them. You were going to die soon yourself _
so you grabbed your bayonet and prepared to end their suffering wih
one well-aimed thrust. At the last moment your courage melted away.
You began to tremble. Boiling with rage, the captain struggled to
his feet and limped toward the invalids, trailing his wounded leg,
naked sword in hand, and one by one slit their throats.''
</P>
<P>
   The image of the captain's sword, flashing red with blood and
firelight, stays with Manase as he reconstructs his peacetime life.
So does the dying lance corporal's geology lecture. Manase marries,
opens a bookstore, and fathers two sons. But he retreats for hours,
then days, to his storehouse of stones _ polishing, cutting,
categorizing, viewing samples under the white light of a polarizing
microscope. Although the events of the cave have marked him, he
hopes to achieve mastery through careful study, as if he is taking
cross-sections of his life and mounting them on slides. It seems
inevitable that he will draw his sons into his passion _ and in
doing so, destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   His older son, Hiroaki, begins his own rock collection, and
father and son spend an idyllic summer gathering specimens. On an
outing in an old quarry, they discover a cave. The dank walls are
shot through with green chert, a rock that Hiroaki covets. Here,
the plot becomes riveting. The menace of the father's obsession and
the fever dreams of wartime atrocities make the book hard to put
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Manase's study of the hard, glinting edges of rock has not
completely blotted out his past, nor his collusion with the mass
slaughter in Leyte. His own failure to apprehend where the edges of
memory begin and end has tragic consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Okuizumi seems intrigued by the theme of expiation, although it
comes at a cost. Manase must return to the cave for a final test.
This time, the geology lesson is different. At dawn, the jungle
comes alives with the trill of birdsong and chatter of monkeys and
Manase receives a gift: an ordinary gray stone, perhaps from a
riverbed. But bathed in the golden morning light, it looks radiant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 1349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
