<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-OFFICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OFFICE SPACE' IS WORKMANLIKE SATIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
OFFICE SPACE 
Written and directed by: Mike Judge 
Starring: Ron Livingston, Jennifer Aniston, David Herman, Ajay
Naidu, Diedrich Bader, Stephen Root, Gary Cole, Richard Riehle,
John C. McGinley, Paul Willson, Greg Pitts 
Running time: 90 minutes 
Rated: R (language and brief sexuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Office Space'' is a cheerful little screenful of payback from
cubicle hell. It's pretty clueless when it leaves the office and
clanks through some tired boy-girl and computer-theft plot
mechanics. But Mike Judge must have worked some godawful jobs
before he became the ``Beavis and Butt-head'' mastermind. His
feature filmmaking debut really digs in and takes some swings at
the soul-corroding corrida known as the corporate world. At its
best, ``Office Space'' is ``Dilbert'' with sharp teeth, at its
funniest in its matter-of-fact assumption of corporate viciousness
as a given.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens with a trio of software programmers (Ron
Livingston, David Herman, and Ajay Naidu) sweating their way
through meaningless jobs in a bland building in a nondescript
office park, only occasionally daring to raise their heads above
their partitions like prairie dogs popping out of their holes. The
only thing that keeps them from numbing out entirely is fear of
losing the jobs they hate, an edge the company exploits ruthlessly.
When the guys learn that two consultants have been brought in to
start the downsizing process, they freak. But Livingston's hapless
drudge named Peter is dragged to a therapist, where he catches a
lucky break.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner does the therapist hypnotize him into laid-back
blissfulness than the doc drops dead of a heart attack. Blissed to
the gills, Livingston's nerd prospers. By coming to work whenever
he pleases, exuding easy confidence, and describing the company's
operations with brutal frankness, he's tabbed as upper management
material. But when he sees his buddies about to be canned, he
realizes this isn't enough, and figures out how to scam the company
with what looks like, but of course isn't, a foolproof computer
larceny scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston is funny simply because his eyebrows don't line up.
They look like false brows slapped on in a hurry. His pals are more
sympathetic than funny. Most of the laughs come from the guys Judge
is satirizing. Gary Cole is best as their power-tripping piranha of
a boss who makes a point of coming on cool and casual, beginning
every sentence with a slowly drawled, ``Yeahhhhh,'' as if he's
going to agree with his subordinate, then ending it by barking an
order and saying, ``Great!'' Stephen Root is hugely funny, too, as
the company scapegoat, a maladroit loser who's either going to go
nuts or explode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Office Space'' is mostly populated by live cartoons. I'm
thinking of the maniacally gleeful hatchet men played by John
McGinley and Paul Willson. Richard Riehle has his moments, too, as
a character who has spent 30 years worrying about being kicked out
of job purgatory, and Diedrich Bader is a plus as Peter's
down-market neighbor. As a waitress who also despises her job, and
addresses the specter of corporate fascism more directly than any
of the others, Jennifer Aniston is nice to have around, although
Judge is only going through the motions in her romantic sequences.
``Office Space'' is scattershot, but 9-to-5ers will find stuff to
like in its satire of the so-called work environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
