<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAYOR TAKES THE HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's add up the damage from Boston Mayor Thomas Menino's week
from hell:
</P>
<P>
   His city has to pay $900,000 to the undercover cop who was
savagely beaten by fellow officers too craven to own up; its
oft-lauded Fire Department is undressed as a poorly-managed bloated
feather bed; Boston loses the MacWorld convention this year and the
Democratic National Convention next; and HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo
lobs a grenade at the Boston Housing Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Did I leave anything out? Only the upside. Menino's six-year
record as a hands-on urban mechanic should help him withstand the
blustery winds of his bad hair week. Taking the convention losses
first: Everything that could reasonably have been done to land
those lucrative conclaves, Menino did. In spades.
</P>
<P>
   Boston was always fated to finish never higher than No. 2 on the
Democratic National Committee's national convention scorecard. But
Menino pounded his city's bid down to the two-yard line. He just
couldn't nudge it across the goal line for the simple reason of
California's 54 electoral votes, 4 1/2 times as many as
Massachusetts's 12. But there's no shame in coming close to a prize
of that scale.
</P>
<P>
   And with the new Boston convention center and hotels sprouting
like fiddlehead ferns after a rainy spring, Boston will get its
share of the lucrative tourist-convention trade. MacWorld needed it
all under one roof, and we are still maybe three years away from
that here.
</P>
<P>
   The other three hits the mayor took are less amenable to
aggressive mayoral action because they involve strands of America's
greatest domestic dilemma: race. Twisted, gnarled threads of racial
conflict weave through three of Menino's challenges: the police
beating, the Fire Department's record on hiring and promoting
minorities, and the BHA's shoddy record of protecting tenants from
racial assault.
</P>
<P>
   The $900,000 settlement for the undercover cop brutalized by
fellow officers too timid to come forward is a blot on the Police
Department's reputation. Police work is inherently confrontational
and controversial. After New York officers fired 41 bullets at an
unarmed man, Mayor Rudy Giuliani's job approval rating cratered
from 60-33 favorable-unfavorable to 44-47 in a matter of a few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Mayors of big cities, with big-time problems of
police-versus-suspects, are vulnerable to the shifting winds of
public opinion. It's how they handle the inevitable buffeting that
determines their ultimate level of political support.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Fire Department, whose soft managerial
underbelly was exposed by Globe reporter David Armstrong's recent
series, there is clearly need for the mayor to demand swift
insertion of civilian management skills in a department used to its
own cozy internal arrangements. You can be a brave and skillful
firefighter, but not the person to manage things. Taking all
managers from the firefighting ranks makes no sense in this
complicated world.
</P>
<P>
   They have the slimmest management training and no experience in
the world outside the insular ways of this admittedly successful
department. The featherbedding is ludicrous. Having round-the-clock
drivers to walk the commissioner's dog or drive him to coach his
high school hockey team is indefensible.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing all superior officers to remain members of the
politically robust union is just asking for trouble. Political
favors are stored up by creating expensive and inefficient cul de
sacs like the marine unit or the alarm box system. But the mayor's
greatest hurdle is to reestablish control over the out-of-control
abuse of injury pay. Taxpayer dollars are being funneled into this
bottomless pit at an astonishing rate.
</P>
<P>
   Now we come to the BHA. One-10th of Boston's population lives in
public housing projects. For most of the 15,000 families housed at
much-cheaper-than-market rents, this is a great deal; some families
are fourth-generation project people. Secretary Cuomo's 50-page
report documents a grisly record of harassment against minorities
in South Boston's Old Colony and Charlestown's Bunker Hill
projects.
</P>
<P>
   There were ``KKK'' graffiti, cross-burnings, beatings, verbal
threats, barricading of apartments, a whole litany of vicious,
racist conduct. The Boston police dragged feet on furnishing HUD
with responses to federal inquiries. And the BHA was remiss at
several junctures. But things are better now.
</P>
<P>
   The episodes Cuomo documented took place between three and six
years ago. Menino has a beef: The feds are beating on the BHA with
old news. Menino took the lead in fashioning a combined strike
force of Boston police, the municipal cops and the Housing
Authority cops back when he was a city councilor.
</P>
<P>
   Nine tenants have been ejected from Old Colony and Bunker Hill,
after hundreds of hours of police work and court time, using
regulations that allow trouble-makers to be tossed out. ``I think
we have stabilized the problem,'' said one city official.
``Anything can happen, there'll always be incidents, but as far as
systemic problems, particularly in South Boston, I believe that has
ended, though you can have an incident anytime.'' Some minority
tenants were viciously harassed, and the city was slow to get a
handle on the persistent racial tension.
</P>
<P>
   Said Deputy Superintendent Phil Vitti, who is in charge of of
project policing, his 40-officer force, which melds three police
agencies with BHA input and five unions: ``I think it's an
effective partnership, and I think it's working. Public housing
today is a different place to live in.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 1353EST &QL; 
