<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-BUILDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADAPTATION, DIRECTION OF IBSEN'S `BUILDER' SHINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE MASTER BUILDER 
Play in three acts by Henrik Ibsen. Adapted by Robert Brustein. 
Directed by Kate Whoriskey. Set, Christine Jones. Lighting, Michael
Chybowski. Costumes, Catherine Zuber. Sound, Christopher Walker.
Produced by American Repertory Theatre. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Much is made in Henrik Ibsen's ``The Master
Builder'' about the artist's fear of ``the younger generation.''
The builder of the title, Halvard Solness, is terrified that
younger architects will pass him by. Ibsen himself may have been
jealous of the younger August Strindberg's growing influence, as
Robert Brustein points out in his program notes. Brustein, the
American Repertory Theatre's artistic director, was obviously
pleased with the symbolism of choosing a recent graduate of the ART
Institute to direct his adaptation of ``Master Builder.''
</P>
<P>
   And directors of the world beware. Kate Whoriskey is a major new
talent, to judge from the stunning psychological-aesthetic
landscape she and set designer Christine Jones have fashioned on
the Loeb stage. It, along with Brustein's adaptation, may not sit
well with traditionalists looking for the more representational
home-and-office setting, but if one is at all open to the ART's way
of doing the classics, ``The Master Builder'' blends beautifully
into the company's overall concept.
</P>
<P>
   There are certainly echoes of avant-garde director Robert Wilson
in the look of the piece. As it opens, everyone in Solness's
household and office, except for him, is enclosed in a rectangular
form that's physically and psychologically confining: the secretary
in a big green glassed-in cubicle, counting into a microphone; the
father-and-son associates behind a horizontal control panel; the
wife appearing from time to time at a cutout in the wall.
</P>
<P>
   The language and movements aren't as radically transformed as in
a Wilson piece. Brustein's adaptation is similar to his ``Wild
Duck'' of a couple of years ago, which is less deconstruction than
reconstruction with contemporary idiomatic English _ a ``goddamn''
here, a ``that's a hot one'' there. Solness isn't any more of a
happy camper than the people who work and live with him, only one
of whom, the secretary, he's able to stand. He wonders if the homes
he has become renowned for are anything more than glorified
anthills for the bourgeoisie bugs who inhabit them. Into this
desiccated world enters Hilde Wangel, a saucy and irreverent young
woman who aims to cash in on Solness's pledge to build her a castle
by urging him to go for the gold, personally and professionally.
</P>
<P>
   Brustein's adaptation is solid, particularly in the
characterization. This isn't a ``Fatal Attraction'' seductress and
her victim. It's never clear who's seducing whom or even whether
Solness should resist her imprecations. Of course he overreaches,
but the tragedy lies with the inevitability of that overreaching.
</P>
<P>
   One unfortunate Ibsenism that remains is Wangel's constant
references to him directly as ``Master Builder,'' which carries
echoes of the ``Master Thespian'' skit on ``Saturday Night Live,''
particularly because Christopher McCann delivers his lines with a
formality bordering on pretentiousness. The ART regulars, though,
are very much at home with Brustein's language. Kristen Flanders is
particularly adept in the difficult role of the perky Hilde.
</P>
<P>
   As good as it is, the production doesn't make a case that this
is one of Ibsen's better plays, which may have something to do with
the company's tinkering with time and space. By taking ``The Master
Builder'' out of strict historical time, Solness's wrestling with
God seems too fevered and less impressive than it might have been
in a production that underlined how far ahead of his time Ibsen was
in responding to the silence of God.
</P>
<P>
   It's an interesting trade-off, though. One walks away from ``The
Master Builder'' with an appreciation of an old master's power to
live beyond the confines of theatrical history. And of a young
artist's dazzling potential to make theatrical history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
