<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-JAWBREAKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW REDEEMING QUALITIES IN `JAWBREAKER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
JAWBREAKER 
Written and directed by: Darren Stein 
Starring: Rose McGowan, Rebecca Gayheart, Julie Benz, Judy Evans
Greer, Carol Kane, Pam Grier 
At: Copley Place, suburbs
<TEXT>
<P>
   Running time: 90 minutes &QL; 
Rated: R (violence, salty language, sexual situations) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was announced this week that Rose McGowan, perhaps best known
for almost wearing a dress to an MTV awards show a few years back,
is engaged to become the future Mrs. Marilyn Manson.
</P>
<P>
   If you think that's frightening, you should see McGowan in
``Jawbreaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Let us not mince words: ``Jawbreaker'' is a terrible movie, and
McGowan is terrible in it. This is supposed to be McGowan's
breakthrough film, but it's the kind of swill that has derailed far
more established careers. Obstensibly an offbeat comedy in the
style of ``Heathers,'' it's the dull-as-dishwater story of a high
school prank that goes fatally wrong. But really, the most lethal
mistake here is the pathetic, humor-starved script by Darren Stein,
who also directed, and some of the worst acting anyone is likely to
see this year.
</P>
<P>
   The setting for all this is Reagan High School. Three teen
queens _ Courtney (McGowan), Julie (Rebecca Gayheart), and Marcie
(Julie Benz) kidnap their galpal Liz (Charlotte Roldan) as a joke
on her birthday. They tie her up, and to stifle her screams, they
jam a cueball-size jawbreaker _ those nasty dreadful things we used
to eat as kids _ into her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Bad move. The jawbreaker lodges in Liz's throat, and she
suffocates. Instead of reporting the accident to the cops,
Courtney, the relentlessly amoral ringleader, concocts a scheme to
make it look as through Liz was whoring it up with the local trade,
and was raped and murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Are you, like poor Liz, gagging yet?
</P>
<P>
   ``Heathers,'' the devastatingly dark 1989 comedy that launched
the careers of Winona Ryder and Christian Slater, was wicked and
funny, while making some pithy observations about teen suicide. But
Stein isn't interested in doing anything except carting out the
same old dusty jokes about cliques, clueless teachers _ heavens,
what is Carol Kane doing in this movie?! _ and every other cliche
of high school movies.
</P>
<P>
   In her slathered makeup and too-tight clothes, McGowan plays
Courtney as a vixen without a single redeeming quality. It's a
tiring, one-note performance. (Marilyn Manson, sans makeup, has a
brief, don't-blink-or-you'll-miss-it appearance.) And not to be
overlooked is that McGowan simply looks too old to play a high
school senior _ not that Gayheart or Benz are any more convincing.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Grier turns up as a detective named Vera Cruz investigating
Liz's death, and her participation here is proof that ``Jackie
Brown'' didn't provide the same career resurrection John Travolta
has enjoyed since ``Pulp Fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best bit in the film is the brief appearance of
William Katt and P. J. Soles as Liz's parents. In 1976, Katt and
Soles costarred in the ultimate high school horror film,
``Carrie.'' Stein certainly knows his movies _ even the name of
Grier's character comes from the title of a 1954 Gary Cooper
western. But it would really be saying something if he learned how
to make one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 1357EST &QL; 
