<HEADER>
A1694 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-19 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY'S HUMILIATION IS HER BIGGEST FOE IN SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is impossible to overstate the humiliation Hillary Rodham
Clinton has endured this past year. No one in her position has ever
experienced anything quite like it. There were days when simply
maintaining her composure seemed to require every ounce of her
will. And it never ends. Friday, her husband was credibly accused
of rape in The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   So it should come as no surprise that when Mrs. Clinton looks
north toward New York, she sees greener pastures. What began as a
daydream has become a serious consideration, holding out the
promise of a new and perhaps better life. And on a number of
levels, it makes sense. New York is the place you go when there's
no place else called home.
</P>
<P>
   She would be a formidable candidate for the United States
Senate. She is intelligent, disciplined, hard-working, and tough.
She's also a bit of a crackpot, but New York is nondiscriminatory
in this regard. It frequently nominates crackpots for high office
and occasionally elects them. It is understood that you have to be
a little crazy to live there.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has other assets. They include 100 percent name
recognition and the ability to raise all the money she could ever
need in a matter of months.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she would have the executive branch of the federal
government at her beck and call. In addition to that, the
Democratic nomination would be hers the day she announced, which
may be the most important asset of all.
</P>
<P>
   It is a thousand times easier to wage a coherent general
election campaign if one's march to the nomination is unimpeded.
Chat-show experts say that this moment is as high as her kite can
fly; that the process, the press and the pressure of the campaign
would gradually diminish her. Not necessarily. The fact is that any
Democrat with no primary opposition and $25 million in the bank
would be a 50-50 bet to win the Moynihan Senate seat. In a two-way
general election race, Hillary Clinton would always be in the hunt,
never out of it. In a three-way race, she would be even more
formidable. New York's demographics have shifted since the 1980s,
as any GOP pollster will attest. It is again a Democratic state.
</P>
<P>
   She would, however, face competent and compelling opposition in
the general election. New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has done
what many thought was impossible; by sheer doggedness and
determination he has reversed the city's civic fortunes. New York
is livable again. It is clean again. It is safe again. Walking down
the city's streets, one can actually feel Giuliani's
accomplishment, and it is considerable.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, Democrats win statewide elections in New York by
racking up huge margins in the city, splitting the suburbs, and
holding on for dear life upstate. Giuliani changes that formula; he
would at least break even in the city. As a result, Mrs. Clinton
would have to spend most of her time outside of Manhattan _ on Long
Island, in Westchester, and in the counties bisected by the New
York State Thruway. The campaign would be what professional golfers
call a ``grind.'' And she would be competing with an opponent at
the top of his game.
</P>
<P>
   But her real opponent would be her apparently ceaseless
humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's story in The Wall Street Journal alleges that in 1978,
her husband raped a woman named Juanita Broaddrick in a Little Rock
hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources at NBC News, where I used to work, four
contemporaneous witnesses and reams of supporting detail support
Mrs. Broaddrick's story. Lawyers for President Clinton have, to
date, refused all comment on these new allegations.
</P>
<P>
   How much more of this can Mrs. Clinton endure? What does she say
when some hostile reporter from the New York Post asks her to
explain her position on tougher sentencing laws for rapists? How
does she explain her complicity in all the cover-ups of her
husband's extramarital activities? How can she champion women's
rights when her husband is widely believed (based on substantial
and credible evidence) to be a sexual predator? Hypocrisy is part
and parcel of politics. But hypocrisy on this scale is untenable.
And unlike normal hypocrisy (``so good to see you!''), this kind of
hypocrisy sears the soul.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton will find solace in New York if she goes there.
After the initial flurry of interest, no one will bother her, just
as no one bothered Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis. But she won't find
solace there if she runs for the Senate. Her humiliation will
continue unabated. Which is why people who know her believe that,
in the end, she will forego the race. One hopes, for her sake, that
they're right.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
