<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN LASSIE IS A LIABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, you go out and buy a big, aggressive dog to protect your
property. But something funny happens. Those number-crunching
actuarial types at your insurance company think Bowser is more of a
liability than an asset.
</P>
<P>
   Are they crazy?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. We are experiencing an epidemic of dog bites in
this country. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in
Atlanta estimates that as many as 4.7 million people are bitten
each year, 1 million of them require medical treatment, and 334,000
end up in the emergency room. About a dozen people a year die from
dog attacks. The Journal of the American Medical Association
estimates that almost half of all children will be bitten before
reaching age 12. It is the No. 1 health problem among children.
</P>
<P>
   According to Loretta Worters, spokeswoman for the Insurance
Information Institute, all that adds up to a whopping price tag of
$1 billion a year, $250 million of that shelled out in medical and
liability payments by insurance companies. Dog attacks now account
for one third of all homeowners' insurance liability claims. And
the insurers are not wagging their tails over it.
</P>
<P>
   What are they doing about it? ``Insurance companies are all over
the block on this issue,'' says Frank O'Brien, regional manager of
the Alliance of American Insurers. Some companies deny coverage in
certain cases. Some may add a higher premium. Some don't treat dog
owners any differently than others. And many try to sort it out by
sizing up risk according to statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Bottiano, of Liberty Mutual Group, says her company does
have a list of certain breeds they would call ``unbindable.'' Cases
presenting these dogs _ pit bulls and American Staffordshire
terriers; Doberman pinschers; Rottweilers; German shepherds; chows;
wolves and wolf hybrids _ would have to be reviewed by an
underwriter. (Though the American Kennel Club may differentiate
between pit bulls and American Staffordshire terriers, most
insurance companies do not.) Siberian huskies, Alaskan malamutes,
Great Danes, Saint Bernards, and Akitas appear on other companies'
lists, too.
</P>
<P>
   If someone owns a breed from the red-flag list, Liberty Mutual
would ask more extensive questions concerning the dog's history,
training, gender, sexual status (neutered or spayed?), intent of
ownership, presence of children, and precautions (is the yard
fenced, for example).
</P>
<P>
   What's interesting here is that many of these factors are
exactly the ones that animal welfare organizations have warned
owners about for years. Aggressive dogs tend to be young,
unneutered males who have been poorly socialized. Also, the most
likely victim of an aggressive dog is not a burglar, but the owner,
the owner's children or the neighbors. As Worters and many dog
trainers say, having a big, aggressive dog around without proper
training (of the owner as well as the dog) can be as risky as
``having a loaded shotgun'' in the house.
</P>
<P>
   What dog experts have cautioned is exactly what insurance data
confirms. And as more and more owners ignore warnings and purchase
fierce creatures instead of companions, the bite statistics soar.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: While dog attacks have grown by 37 percent in a
decade (1986-1996), the actual dog population has only grown by 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   We all know lovely German shepherds or sweet Doberman pinschers.
Breed banning is no solution, though most insurance companies
simply raise a flag with certain breeds and look into the matter.
Here, again, the insurance world is in agreement with dog experts:
Worters says, ``Insurance companies believe that the ownership,
rather than the breed, per se, is the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This should serve as a wake-up call,'' says nationally known
dog trainer Brian Kilcommons, ``because the few are going to ruin
things for the many. The bigger the dog, the greater the
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilcommons says people too often rationalize aggression,
particularly in the early stages. ``What is deceiving about
aggression,'' he says, ``is that the frequency and intensity take
time to develop. People miss these signals: Your pet growls to
protect a bone? Psychologically, the dog is pulling a knife on you.
And you better listen up, because we know the insurance companies
are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
