<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1699 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-19 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE BAD NEWS FOR AMERICA'S MEAN STREETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As cities sue gun makers for flooding the streets with handguns,
the gun makers are making their arms more deadly than ever. One
needs no skills of investigative journalism to see this. All one
has to do is wander by a newsstand.
</P>
<P>
   An ad for Beretta handguns neatly sums up the current mentality
of the industry: ``Easy to Conceal. Easy to Fire. Easy to Acquire.
Hard to Beat. Beretta Cougar pistols set a tough new standard,
making heavy firepower easy to handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget the 1980s and early '90s, symbolized by Schwarzenegger
and Stallone spraying the screen with massive assault rifles.
Beretta, Smith &AMP; Wesson, Colt and a host of imitators are up to
something new. In the American Handgunner, an article said, ``A
peculiar reverse arms race is underway among the gunmakers to see
who can make the smallest, lightest handgun.''
</P>
<P>
   Handguns magazine's ``Giant Buyer's Guide To Pocket Guns,''
said, ``At one time not so very long ago, you could cover the
subject of pocketable magnum or big-bore revolvers and 9mm
Parabellum and more powerful autos in a single sentence: `There
aren't any.' . . . None of these firms came near to creating
anything like the mini-powerhouses we have today. Today's guns show
a size/power ratio undreamed of 25 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazines, of course, say their market is confined to
law-abiding gun owners who are concerned only with competitions,
hunting, collecting, and self-defense. But the illegal market, in
which several gun makers were found guilty of feeding by a federal
jury last week in New York, is certainly not oblivious to ads like
the one for a palm-sized .32 caliber Beretta Tomcat that ``might
surprise you'' with ``the punch of a .380.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor will the illegal market long be ignorant of Smith &AMP; Wesson's
small guns. In referring to S&AMP;W's AirLite, The Complete Book of
Handguns said, ``A year ago, a .38 Special this light would have
been unbelievable. It can change the nature of concealed carry . .
. the first reaction on picking it up is `Unbelievable!' It's
almost as if there's nothing there.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine reviewer said such a gun ``has the potential to
save lives that may not be saved otherwise,'' particularly for
people who found that guns that were ``reasonably capable of
stopping a fight to the death'' were previously too heavy.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the medical studies that show that owning a gun
significantly increases one's chance of dying by gunfire. Gun
makers prey on paranoia over street crime, which has declined. Not
only did the magazine say the gun was light enough for joggers and
women, it even said the gun would be great for ``the doctor in the
ER'' who could hide it ``under his scrubs.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not explained why doctors need guns in the ER. Perhaps
every surgeon should be prepared for the day that his heavily
sedated patient leaps off the table to go on a suture rampage.
</P>
<P>
   In the same magazine, an article on Colt says the gun maker
``has been through a lot of positive changes lately. New CEO. New
consultants. New guns. Most important, a new attitude . . . The new
administration understands that one of their strongest potential
assets is the burgeoning concealed carry market . . . Colt has
never had a fuller, better set of choices for the decent person who
carries a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colt lineup of small handguns is so powerful that the author
said, ``Maybe Colt agrees with me: `Friends don't let friends carry
mouse guns.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In The American Handgunner, a reviewer said Kimber's Ultra Carry
compact pistol was more powerful than a comparable Smith &AMP; Wesson
and ``just took the lead in the race for smaller and lighter.
Shooters want little guns with big bullets.'' A piece in Guns and
Ammo said that a Sigarms ultra-compact auto pistol ``offers the
ballistic potential of potent .357 Magnum loadings in a package
appreciably more compact than any police service revolver chambered
for that powerful handgun cartridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Para-Ordnance advertises a line of compact guns ``with the
increased magazine capacity and firepower potential that was once
the exclusive domain of the modern 9mm.''
</P>
<P>
   The buyer's guide in Handguns says, ``Thanks to the popularity
of `pocket pistols' in the marketplace nowadays, new models are
constantly forthcoming.'' That makes the lawsuits by the cities all
the more important. No matter what these companies say, these guns
will wind up in the hands of criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The Beretta ad says, ``Easy to Conceal. Easy to Fire. Easy to
Acquire.'' Just when Boston and other cities are exhaling in relief
from declining gun violence, here come the gun companies, with
instruments that could very easily come back to terrorize us. Their
heavy firepower may be easy to handle for gun owners. Such power
will be hard to handle on the streets of America.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In my last column, I mistakenly credited Charles Bronson instead
of Clint Eastwood with the phrase ``Make My Day.'' Sorry, whether
it's Bronson, Eastwood, Schwarzenegger or Stallone, with a gun in
front of their faces, I cannot tell them apart.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
