<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BOTTOM LINE MAY NOT BE AS BAD AS IT SEEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roger Clemens is a New York Yankee. That means Mr. Roger's new
neighborhood is the Bronx. It means Clemens will not be the first
Roger to come to mind when people start talking about great,
history-making Rogers in team history. It also means it's time to
send out some memos . . .
</P>
<P>
   To Red Sox fans: Please do not be confused. Clemens being traded
from the Blue Jays to the Yankees Thursday is not a postscript to
the Curse of the Bambino. You don't have to worry about that. The
surreal Babe Ruth was a 25-year-old pitcher/slugger when he was
sold away from Fenway Park to New York. He forever haunted the Sox
with his titles and his lore. Clemens is 36. He will only haunt the
Sox because they will forever remember the World Series game he
didn't finish in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. to Sox fans: Don't get excited by that last message. You
know your team is still going to be terrible this season, right? If
they pay attention to their diets and eat all their Minnesotas,
Kansas Citys, and Tampa Bays like they are supposed to, the Sox
could reach 80 wins. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   To Dan Duquette: Come on, man. Real quick. Let's play the Truth
segment of Truth or Dare. When all the cameras are not focused on
your mug, do you admit to yourself that the Sox are not a good
team? I know you do. You have to. I know you're a Bruce ``The
Boss'' Springsteen fan. Do you put on your copy of ``Born To Run''
to calm you? Or do you make like David Wells, crank up the
Metallica, and bash your noggin against the wall until you're
red-faced, sweaty, and screaming, ``I hate my team''? And when
someone mentions The Boss these days, do you think of Springsteen
or Steinbrenner?
</P>
<P>
   P.S. to Duquette: Been meaning to talk to you about this. You
mentioned that fans predicting doom after the loss of Mo Vaughn
were a ``bunch of Chicken Littles.'' Very dated reference. The term
you're looking for these days is ``player-haters.'' Use it in
interviews this way: ``Jose Offerman is a player. A big-time
player. Those who can appreciate the fact that he doesn't have a
position on this team are player-lovers. The rest of y'all?
Player-haters.''
</P>
<P>
   To fans who think other fans and media are too negative: When
Sox pitcher Tim Wakefield heard that Clemens was an official
Yankee, he unleashed an expletive.
</P>
<P>
   To Steinbrenner: What's up, man? You crazy? If ``Seinfeld''
wasn't in rerun status, Frank Costanza, George's father, would not
only be screaming about Hideki Irabu, he'd be upset about Clemens,
too. Your team won 114 regular-season games in 1998, the most in
American League history. So I thought you knew history. You don't.
You believe Clemens, 36, has four or five great years left. You
don't know history. More on that in a second.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. to Steinbrenner (I brought my historical Cliff's Notes this
time): All right, Boss. Name any great pitcher from 1960 to the
present. Bob Gibson, you say? Great choice. Gibson was the original
Rocket. He had a 1.12 ERA when he was 33. He was 23-7 with a
ridiculous 23 complete games when he was 35. After 35, his wins
went 16, 19, 12, and 3. Catfish Hunter once had a two-season win
total of 48 and had his best years in his 20s. He was out of
baseball by 35. Tom Seaver had five seasons of 20 wins or more,
none after 35. The great Jim Palmer was 43-30 after 35.
</P>
<P>
   Overkill to Steinbrenner: Look, Clemens already has proven that
he can pitch well in his mid-30s. But what makes you think he can
be a historical exception and do what the Gibsons, Palmers, and
Seavers could not? By the way, they all won World Series titles,
which Clemens has not.
</P>
<P>
   Random Shout-Out to the Dodgers: You guys are nuts. A seven-year
contract for 34-year-old Kevin Brown? How many 20-win seasons in
that contract?
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. to Duquette: I feel like Statman after writing that stuff
to Steinbrenner. Now I know what you must have been thinking two
years ago when you said Clemens was in the twilight of his career.
That's accurate, historically. And, Dan, maybe Toronto general
manager Gord Ash felt the same way. But the difference is that he
got three major leaguers for Clemens while you . . . well, you
know. And while we're at it, everybody not named Duquette and
Harrington knew Mo was leaving after last season. Why didn't you
trade him before . . . never mind.
</P>
<P>
   To sports fans in cyberspace: One of the best Clemens lines of
the day was posted on an on-line message board. We all know that
Clemens has given his children ``K'' names, after the symbol for
the strikeout. Well, one cyber type wrote that the Rocket only
wanted to play in New York because he needed a city with a ``K'' in
it.
</P>
<P>
   To Yankees GM Brian Cashman: Ever hear of chemistry, man? Your
team was one of the rare ones in sports that contained players that
actually liked each other. So you traded a 35-year-old pitcher for
a 36-year-old one? You traded a lefty setup man who didn't give up
a run at Yankee Stadium, you traded a gifted young second baseman.
Yes, your team will win more than 100 games again. But it would
have done that with or without Clemens. Was it worth it?
</P>
<P>
   To those who believe in Babe Ruth conspiracies: You know
Steinbrenner and Clemens are going to taunt the Sox and give Roger
No. 3 to wear, just for one season. If that doesn't happen, look at
it another way. Clemens usually wears No. 21. Two plus one is
three. Babe wore No. 3. Clemens may wear No. 12. One plus two is
three. Babe wore No. 3. Clemens is playing for his third team. Babe
wore No. 3. If the Yankees win the Series this year, it will be
their third title in the last four years. Babe wore No. 3. And like
Mo and Roger, Babe was also a Fenway visitor who shouldn't have
been.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
