<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO. 1 IN THE EAST A TOUGH CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ongoing debate in college basketball right now is not who's
No. 1, but who's going to be No. 1 in the NCAA East region next
month.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates: Duke and Connecticut. Unless one goes into a
total tailspin and loses a bunch of games _ and that doesn't seem
likely _ both deserve to stay at home. Obviously both can't.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the arguments for and against each. Duke has not lost
since being beaten in Alaska by Cincinnati in November on a
last-second basket.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils are blowing people away and everyone concedes
they are the No. 1 team in college basketball right now.
</P>
<P>
   Since the natural region of the Atlantic Coast Conference is the
East, sending the Devils to Charlotte for its first- and
second-round games makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   That's clearly where Duke wants to go. And it also wants to go
to the East Regionals in the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. But what about UConn? The Huskies are hearing criticism
for the way they have played of late.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me. The last time I looked, they had lost one game _ with
two starters missing _ to a decent Syracuse team. Other than that,
they haven't lost _ period.
</P>
<P>
   But the argument goes that they aren't playing the way they did
a month ago. They are banged up and struggling against some bad
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Please. College basketball is a long season. Teams have slumps.
And the Huskies have still won. And if anyone doubts their ability
when they are focused, check out the way they took care of Stanford
in Palo Alto two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Duke is a fine team. Maybe a great team. But having seen both
the Blue Devils and Huskies play in person on more than a couple of
occasions, I found no evidence that jumps out and says if both
teams play their absolute best game, Duke will win.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tossup, which is why the call of keeping UConn in the
East, where the Huskies can play in Boston for the first two
rounds, is so tough.
</P>
<P>
   What's the tie-breaker? Maybe history. Maybe it's time to give
UConn a break.
</P>
<P>
   Lest anyone forget, the Huskies played North Carolina for a
regional title in Greensboro last year. They have also played
Florida for a regional title in Miami and UCLA for a regional title
in California. Of those three, only the game against North Carolina
was a clear-cut case of home-court advantage, but that's not the
point. Maybe it's time to keep UConn home _ if the Huskies finish
the season with only one loss.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody on the NCAA selection committee owes the Huskies if all
things are equal _ and in this case they seem to be.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a travesty if the Huskies wind up heading west and
facing a team like Arizona in the regional final in Phoenix, which
would provide another home-court edge.
</P>
<P>
   Or head south and face a team like Kentucky in the regional
final at Knoxville _ an easy car trip from Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are this will work itself out. Someone will lose and the
choices will be easier.
</P>
<P>
   But the feeling here is that if UConn wins out, it should stay
in Boston. Duke can be switched to the South to play in Orlando and
Knoxville, and a team like Auburn, which has had a great season but
is still a relative new kid on the block in terms of NCAA
tournament play, can take the trip west.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Homecoming unlikely
</P>
<P>
   All of you former Boston College fans who are visualizing a
return by Ohio State coach Jim O'Brien to Boston for an NCAA
tournament appearance in the FleetCenter can probably forget about
it. Although it could happen, the most likely scenario is to keep
the Buckeyes, who have won 20 games and made a remarkable
turnaround from last year's cellar-dweller campaign, will stay in
the Midwest or South . . . By the way, O'Brien should be a lock for
Big Ten coach of the year, and were it not for what Cliff Ellis has
done at Auburn, would be the favorite for national coach of the
year. Under O'Brien, Ohio State has five conference road wins this
season. The last two seasons the Buckeyes had four road wins total.
They also have 10 conference wins this season. Over the previous
four seasons, they had a total of 10 conference wins. And they have
season sweeps over Indiana and Purdue. All of this because of one
coach _ and one special player in guard Scoonie Penn. The BC
transfer is the only change from last year's team, which went 1-15
in the Big Ten. ``Scoonie has just stepped it up big time,'' said
O'Brien. ``He just keeps making plays.'' . . . If UConn does get
shipped elsewhere, don't expect to see Kentucky in Boston either.
Here's why. The NCAA likes to avoid rematches. Having Duke and
Kentucky as the top two seeds in the East would set up a possible
rematch of a regular-season game and of last year's South Regional
final. It's more likely that the Wildcats will get shipped to the
Midwest as a No. 2 seed to Michigan State . . . Keep an eye on what
San Diego State does in its search to replace Fred Trenkle.
Athletic director Rick Bey wants to upgrade the profile of the
program and reportedly is focused on a big name. Supposedly he has
Utah's Rick Majerus on his short list. Lots of luck on that one.
The other name that keeps coming up is Rhode Island's Jim Harrick.
Harrick's return to the West Coast is a foregone conclusion; it's a
matter of when, not if.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Double crossed
</P>
<P>
   Bill Raynor deserved better than getting dumped at Holy Cross.
Granted the W's weren't there and college basketball is still a
bottom-line, win-loss business. But anyone who has watched the
self-destruction of the Holy Cross program with its decision first
to go nonscholarship, and then bring back scholarships on a limited
basis this season knows that Raynor was working with constraints
that were out of his control. Supposedly he had a decent recruiting
class coming in with a real chance to compete in the Patriot
League. Now someone else will benefit from that work. And that
person could be lame duck Pittsburgh coach Ralph Willard . . .
Xavier could be searching for a new coach if Pittsburgh lures Skip
Prosser. Speaking of Pitt, consider this: A loss to BC Saturday
could make the Panthers the No. 13 seed in the Big East tournament
next month. When has the Big East or any other league had a
last-place seed with a regular-season win over Kentucky on its
resume, as the Panthers do . . . The Atlantic 10 could wind up with
only two NCAA tournament bids, which isn't all that surprising. The
A-10 has had a bad year. Only four teams are above .500, and Rhode
Island and George Washington both must be considered bubble teams .
. . Want a couple of early tournament sleepers? Try Ohio State and
Texas. Rick Barnes has quietly turned the Longhorns into a Big 12
power (that's not saying much this season), but the Longhorns have
become a decent team under Barnes's guidance . . . Things just get
worse and worse for UMass and Boston University with the lack of
senior leadership being as big a problem as anything. Both Bruiser
Flint and Dennis Wolff had reasonable expectations of playing in
the postseason this year. Now it looks like both will be done by
the first week of March . . . North Carolina has won at least 20
games for an NCAA-record 29 seasons . . . Rutgers has received
permission to talk to former UMass forward Ajmal Basit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
