<SLUG> BC-FALL-FASHION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPRACTICAL IDEAS BLANKET THE RUNWAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some designer creations die early. One trip down a
runway and they're history.
</P>
<P>
   As fashion designers previewed their fall '99 collections to
media and retailers this week, there were several candidates for
death from lack of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Take hoop skirts from the Barbara Bui collection, for example.
Hoops are rarely used, even in ballgowns, because they don't move
about easily. But Bui's short hoop skirts are accidents waiting to
happen. Imagine walking around with a hula hoop in your hemline and
envision sitting in a car. Overexposure would be just one hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Body muffs are another puzzlement. A model walked down a runway
with her chest and upper arms encased in a wide velvet band.
Shoulders and belly were bare, but she wore a long evening skirt.
It was obvious she'd never get a coat over the costume. And could
she eat? And if she lifted her arms for a close dance, wouldn't she
expose her breasts?
</P>
<P>
   Not all these semi-shrouds are alike. Sometimes they're a knit
band worn over a sweater. They can also resemble a very short
pullover without sleeves _ a capelike garment that confines and
covers upper arms and chest before ending just below the bustline.
</P>
<P>
   Vivienne Westwood delivered plenty of runway throwaways:
oversized ``buttoms'' in strategic places on a black bustier, a
fringed shawl over a red bustier and fringed blanket wraps.
</P>
<P>
   Hers aren't the only blankets. They're everywhere, cleverly
described as serapes, stoles, ponchos and riding capes, but looking
like blankets. Designers clearly adore them.
</P>
<P>
   Blanketlike wraps are made of fleece, wool, felt or combinations
of fibers. They're plain, striped and patterned. Some are short
(twin size?). Others are more voluminous (double or queen?).
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes models simply clutch them about their bodies.
Occasionally these wraps are stuck together with some invisible
closure. A few have an opening for the head. But fastened or
handheld, it's a sure bet they won't replace parkas for trips to
the grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   Aprons are another peculiarity on the runways. John Bartlett
showed wool ``utility aprons'' over trousers. They looked more like
chaps.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no mistaking Betsey Johnson's aprons. Most
memorable was a hand-crocheted number tied around the waist of a
baby-doll dress.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's fashion shows are always theatrical and this one was
no exception. It was staged in the service bays of the Manhattan
Mercedes-Benz dealer, a site in a West Side neighborhood where
buildings have barred windows and doors and are triple locked,
covered with metal gates and further protected behind chain-link
fences with rolls of barbed wire on top.
</P>
<P>
   The dealership, however, was spotless. Guests slid out of cabs
and limos and walked up a ramp into a vast and very clean service
area. A long runway with bleacher seating had been installed
between service stalls.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to aprons, Johnson showed boned bustiers, laced
corsets, jackets with peplums, nightgowns as daytime apparel and
feather-trimmed coats and sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was plain and simple _ that's not Johnson's style. Every
costume was an eclectic mix of fabrics, trims and textures: a
yellow floral print, a red plaid ribbon, a bit of muslin, all
joyously combined. The collection appeared to have been created
from dozens of scrap bags, odds and ends of ribbons and yarns.
</P>
<P>
   Guests were treated to little rag dolls labeled ``Betsey.''
Hundreds of them peeked out of tiny black shopping bags, one placed
on each assigned seat. The dolls had stuffed heads and bodies,
button eyes, cotton rope arms, silk cord fringe for bangs and black
ribbon legs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
