<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SHOWS WHY THE REPUBLICANS HATE HIM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, February 21, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seven years after his ringing ``I'll be with you till the last
dog dies'' speech that mesmerized the Democrats inside the Dover
Elks Club in New Hampshire, a still-promising politician nicknamed
The Comeback Kid came back.
</P>
<P>
   Still promising. In 1992, he promised a 69-cent per day tax cut
that was ridiculed by Paul Tsongas, who whomped Bill Clinton in the
New Hampshire primary, and shortly thereafter held the eventual
two-term president to a rock-bottom 16 percent of the vote in the
Massachusetts primary.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton had something; still does. His enemies were holding
nasty signs and shouting ribald insults along his route in the
Granite State Thursday. The Union Leader editorial was, to put it
charitably, venomous(surprise!). But the persuasiveness and
sincerity that the nation's First Razorback exercises on the clear
majority of American voters was evident in spades.
</P>
<P>
   This trip, Clinton was promising to save not his own skin, but
Social Security. He vowed to repair not his own personal
reputation, but the public schools. He didn't have to go into great
detail about his day job, as the world's most prominent _ and
powerful _ peacekeeper. The satchems and sages of Europe are doing
that for him, round-the-clock, as he calibrates the threat of US
firepower against the latest tinpot despot to bait Uncle Sam, the
repulsive Butcher of the Balkans, Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's is the fast-forward presidency. Has it really been
seven years since he roamed New Hampshire, seizing every
un-mittened hand, staring intently into every unwary gaze,
collaring every doubtful voter with the grip of the drowning man?
He has won New Hampshire twice in national elections, yet all the
Granite State's federal officials _ two senators, two congress _
voted to toss him out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there he was, in a Dover health care roundtable, a
Manchester party dinner, pumping hands, rallying Democrats, busting
through the media chaff with his patented sales pitch. Thanks to
C-SPAN, you could catch Clinton's triumphant return _ ``This dog is
limping, but still going'' _ then an hour of one of his bitterest
critics, Sen. Bob Smith, who wants to replace him. I am not making
this up. Bob Smith, who was lucky to win re-election last time out
with 49 percent of the vote, is running for president. As they say,
folks, it's a free country. You just have to be older than 34 and
native-born.
</P>
<P>
   So Bob Smith, in the Wolfeboro high school gym where he used to
teach, aims for Clinton's job, vowing he's not one of those hated
``deal-makers,'' but a real sincere fella. His announcement was a
nice, homespun small-town-America playlet.
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned growing up without a father in a rural community
(just like Clinton), dedicating himself to bettering the lot of
humanity (just like Clinton), focusing on doing the right thing
never mind the politics (just like you-know-who), and prevailing
time after time solely because he is in tune with just-plain-folks
(just like, etc.). Of course, it goes without saying, Smith
promises to be the anti-Clinton, and we'll see how he makes out.
Clinton proved small-town is not necessarily small-time; Smith has
yet to demonstrate those same skills.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob, drawing barely four percent of New Hampshire
Republicans in early polls, mentioned Jimmy Stewart, the actor, and
the movie ``Mr. Smith goes to Washington,'' and another actor named
Reagan. He also referenced Alice in Wonderland, and during his
peroration waved a large starfish at the loyal listeners. The
parable of the hopeful soul who throws starfish from the beach back
into the ocean is the metaphor for this Mr. Smith's
one-man-can-make-a-difference campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Mr. Smith idolizes Jesse Helms, opposes making Dr.
Martin Luther King's holiday into a state holiday, and would
require every pregnant woman to have a baby whether the mother
wishes it or not _ all these stands may affect his political
future. But that's for another day. His grand announcement featured
a stirring acapella rendition of the national anthem by Rose
Remitter, whose brave smile and sweet notes would have melted the
most skeptical heart. The Star Spangled Banner is a hard song to
sing, and running for president is a hard row to hoe, but
determined folk manage to do both, against great odds.
</P>
<P>
   While Smith and his fellow Republicans hold Clinton in the
lowest regard, and disparage the President in most-insulting terms,
I chose to look on the bright side. I listened intently to Smith
deride the dovish tilt of American foreign policy over Vietnam, and
heard him exalt a more muscular US policy, stoutly vowing new
weaponry and a take-no-prisoners attitude toward the rest of the
world. The thought naturally occurred: what if a guy like Bob Smith
replaces Clinton? Smith begged his audience to relish the prospect.
</P>
<P>
   I will not ask you to decide whether Clinton showed elemental
political courage, or base political calculation, when he ordered
US warplanes to bomb Iraqi installations just as the US House voted
to impeach him. Take instead my question from the roiling debate of
Clinton's trial in the Senate. Do you recall that Clinton clung to
about a 60-40 polling majority on the crucial keep-him-or-croak-him
question of impeachment?
</P>
<P>
   Yet he still kept US aircraft patrolling the no-fly zones,
correct? And any day, or any night, Saddam Hussein's anti-aircraft
missiles could have knocked down a US aircraft? And killed or
captured an American aircrew? You remember the propaganda value of
the pilots Saddam captured in the Gulf War? When George Bush
enjoyed remarkable political and media support?
</P>
<P>
   Now ask yourself: if you were a president just a handful of
votes away from impeachment, and your survival depended upon a
handful of senators in each party, and you had a shooting gallery
going every day over Iraq's no-fly zones, would you have the nerve
to tell your commanders to keep firing at those Iraqi missile
batteries? When every ring of the red phone might mean a terse call
from the Situation Room that an Air Force captain had been shot
down, captured, and shoved before a CNN camera, to instantly become
the planet's most famous pilot-hostage?
</P>
<P>
   Do you think your poll rating might take a dip? Like, 10 points?
15? Maybe 20? Do you think having one of your pilots shot down, or
two of them, or ten, would make it easier for your political
enemies to impeach you? My hunch is that Clinton's enemies, already
at his throat, would have been vastly emboldened if his measured
efforts to restrain Saddam had gone astray. I'd argue that Sen.
Trent Lott and his Merry Men have largely forfeited our faith that
they would rise above partisan passions to do the right thing when
the country's basic policies are in peril. They haven't yet proven
me wrong.
</P>
<P>
   So I think I can legitimately argue that Clinton showed guts in
holding to a tough, we'll-shoot-if-we-have-to policy in the no-fly
zones. I understand why the Republicans hate him. He keeps winning,
and they can't stand it. Or him. But I've been around enough
presidents to understand the most important thing is that they hang
tough when basic national interests are at stake. And I don't think
Lott, or Bob Smith, for that matter, get it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
