u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-19 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPN NOT BOTHERED BY UP-AND-COMING FOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As so called wars go, the competition between ESPN and Fox
Sports Net has received its share of media attention, most bringing
a little exposure to Fox and no serious damage to ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN holds an almost 8-1 advantage in viewers over Fox. Those
numbers allow ABC Sports and ESPN Chairman Steve Bornstein to talk
boldly about his competition. ``The less I acknowledge that, you
know, that I put them in the same breath with me, the better I feel
about it,'' Bornstein told HBO's Real Sports with Bryant Gumbel.
``I look at Fox as a bit of a mosquito. But again, my real interest
is not what my competitors are doing. My real interest is what
we're doing. Are we still the leader in sports television?''
</P>
<P>
   That's true now, but Fox has made inroads by acquiring former
ESPN anchors Keith Olbermann and Chris Myers to headline a regional
approach to covering sports across the country. Fox has 22 regional
stations and owns the broadcast rights to 70 professional teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``What ESPN is doing, I think it's complementary,'' Fox's David
Hill said. ``They're a national service. We're a local service,
we're a regional service. Our mantra is `Sports is tribal.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Armen Keteyian reported the segment scheduled to air Monday at
10:30 p.m. on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CNN/SI has a interesting story about trying out for a high
school basketball team. CNN/SI reporter Tom Rinaldi spent five days
at U.S. Grant high school in Portland, Ore., and focused on three
young men competing for spots. The 30-minute show airs Sunday at 10
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With no more impeachment to cover, CNBC dives head-first into
sports with its first live broadcast. The PGA Tour's Tucson Open
airs Feb. 25-28 . . . Fox Sports Net jumps on March Madness by
airing a documentary on the 1979 NCAA title game between Michigan
State and Indiana State on March 28 at 9 p.m. ``Magic vs. Bird: The
Game that Changed the Game'' will be presented on the eve of this
year's championship game. John Thompson has also jumped on the
bandwagon. The former Georgetown basketball coach will host a
one-hour show on WTEM, a suburban Washington all-sports-talk
station . . . Members of the 1969 Miracle Mets appear March 1 on
the CBS series ``Everybody loves Raymond.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HBO airs the Oscar De La Hoya-Ike Quartley fight 9:30 Sataurday
night. By all accounts, De La Hoya's 12-round split decision was
one of the best fights in recent memory.
</P>
