<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOSE LIPS SINK FISH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. has a new board member.
</P>
<P>
   He is Ed Linde, chief executive of Boston Properties Inc., the
big real estate development company. He replaces Larry Fish,
chairman of Citizens Financial Group Inc., who resigned from the
board of the state's largest insurer this month after nearly six
years.
</P>
<P>
   This is usually the stuff of briefs in the back of the Business
section. But bear with me, please.
</P>
<P>
   Both Fish and Hancock chairman Stephen Brown offer the same
explanation for the parting of the ways: The growing convergence of
banking and insurance made it dicey to have a banker sitting on the
insurer's board with Hancock preparing for an initial public
offering of stock. Both banks and insurance companies sell products
like mutual funds and annuities and are increasingly pitching to
the same customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to eliminate any appearance of a conflict of
interest,'' Fish said in a brief telephone interview Thursday. He
called the decision ``very much mutual.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he ``hated'' to lose Fish. ``He has been a great
director,'' Brown said, particularly as part of the board's finance
committee, where his lending experience was so useful.
</P>
<P>
   The finance committee is charged with reviewing all of Hancock's
investments. And here's where things get interesting.
</P>
<P>
   According to two sources familiar with the situation, Hancock
directors became concerned about loose lips, specifically Larry
Fish's. Several directors heard back that Fish had been talking to
friends and business associates about the investments Hancock was
considering. That didn't fly at the top of the Hancock Tower. It
didn't help, either, that Fish was known for being
less-than-courteous to the staff of the finance committee.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to ask Fish about the issue, but couldn't. From the
moment I raised the finance committee, he told me he ``didn't want
to hear about it.'' I tried again: ``I don't care what else you
have!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I resigned. . . . I am telling you the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said Fish's role on the finance committee had no bearing
on his resignation. ``I don't know anything about that,'' Brown
said. ``The only thing I know about is the issue of convergency''
of banking and insurance and the timing of the public offering,
which could come in 18 months to two years.
</P>
<P>
   Other local banks and insurers don't seem to be nearly as
concerned about such potential conflict of interest as Brown and
Fish say they are.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston Corp. chairman Charles K. Gifford, for instance, sits
on the board of Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Co., and Thomas
B. Wheeler, chairman of Mass. Mutual, is on the bank's board. Gary
L. Countryman, chairman of Liberty Mutual Group, is also on the
BankBoston board. Terrence Murray, chairman of Fleet Financial
Group Inc., sits on the board of Allmerica Financial Corp., the
Worcester insurer; Allmerica went public 3 1/2 years ago, just as
Hancock is now planning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can email Steve Bailey at sbailey(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
