<SLUG> BC-MERGER-FRENZY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGERS PUT A DENT IN `WALL STREET WEST' 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Stands for FOREIGN-TAKEOVERS.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ One by one, some of San Francisco's most
renowned hometown companies have been swooped up in a recent frenzy
of mergers.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisitions, including BankAmerica and Pacific Telesis,
have raised the specter that San Francisco may be losing its
reputation as ``Wall Street West.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest deal, announced Thursday, the Dutch insurance
company Aegon NV plans to acquire Transamerica Corp. and its famed
pyramid tower for $9.7 billion. The headquarters, with only 120
employees, will remain in the city.
</P>
<P>
   While public officials put a positive spin on the mergers,
others fear that the city's reputation is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you have a high-profile merger with a large
established company, the issue of prestige comes into play,'' said
Sean Randolph, president of the Bay Area Economic Forum, a
public/private organization that studies the regional economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a loss of image when you lose a corporate
headquarters,'' Randolph said. ``It's not a trend that any city
wants to see.''
</P>
<P>
   That trend has been well established here recently:
</P>
<P>
   _ Britain's Vodafone Group PLC has offered $56 billion for
AirTouch Communications.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two years ago, SBC Communications Inc. of San Antonio acquired
Pacific Telesis, the parent of Pacific Bell.
</P>
<P>
   _ NationsBank of Charlotte, N.C., acquired BankAmerica Corp.
last year. Most headquarters operations were moved to Charlotte,
but the merged bank was renamed BankAmerica.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also last year, Norwest of Minneapolis grabbed another local
financial institution, Wells Fargo. Norwest retained the Wells
Fargo name and relocated to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   _ BankBoston Corp. took over the financial services company
Robertson Stephens, while NationsBank bought Montgomery Securities.
</P>
<P>
   More deals may be coming down the pike. The Pacific Exchange and
the high-tech investment bank of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist are viewed as
likely takeover targets.
</P>
<P>
   The merger activity is by no means unique to San Francisco.
Mergers nationwide hit an all-time high last year, with 7,700 deals
worth $1.2 trillion, according to Houlihan Lokey Howard &AMP; Zukin, an
investment bank in Los Angeles. Consumer-rich California led the
way, with 13 percent of all companies sold based in California.
</P>
<P>
   Given a robust economy, boosters pooh-pooh the idea that San
Francisco has lost its attraction as a big-time business center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be losing headquarters,'' said Rhea Serpan, president
of the San Francisco Chamber of Commerce, ``but on the upside,
people continue to invest in our companies. There are so many
growth opportunities and good markets here.''
</P>
<P>
   Finance and banking are two of the city's strongest sectors,
Serpan said, and there has been strong job growth in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the new economy,'' Serpan said. ``It's global, it's
high-tech-related and we're well-positioned to take advantage of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Mayor Willie Brown echoed the chamber
president's views about the merger activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we're concerned, San Francisco continues to be the
headquarters capital for Northern California,'' said Ron Vinson,
the mayor's deputy press secretary. ``We don't seem to be adversely
affected by them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Business experts say that mergers are economic Darwinism at
play, with solid companies and industries surviving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a healthy development, especially for those institutions
that are strong players,'' said Lenny Mendonca, a director at
management consulting firm McKinsey &AMP; Co. in San Francisco. ``The
net effect on San Francisco and the Bay area is actually positive,
not negative.''
</P>
<P>
   In the corridors of City Hall, policy makers continue to debate
the impact of the mergers. So far, the economy here appears
unharmed. Building permits continue to rise. The downtown real
estate market is hotter than ever. And small businesses and
startups are thriving.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco remains home to several conglomerates and Fortune
500 companies, including Chevron Corp., The Gap Inc., McKesson
Corp., Charles Schwab Corp. and Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric. And some of
the world's largest privately-held companies, among them Bechtel
Group Inc. and Levi Strauss &AMP; Co., are based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, San Francisco is on an incredible economic roll,''
said Hector Chinchilla, president of the city's planning
commission. ``We're spending money, people are getting jobs, we're
putting up buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, there is always the threat of
mergers, mass layoffs and recession. He said San Francisco's
diverse economy would cushion the blows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some argue that the mergers are giving us a black eye, while
others say it's the natural evolution of the economy,'' Chinchilla
said. ``I'm somewhere in between. It's too early to tell how all of
this will shake out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
