<SLUG> BC-POP-COPELAND-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAD'S MUSIC LIVES THROUGH SHEMEKIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shemekia Copeland, 19, knows she can count on the ``true blues
lovers'' to come to her shows. It's a mature, knowledgeable and
supportive audience.
</P>
<P>
   If only she could convince people her own age to embrace the
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``If young people just knew more about it, they would like it,''
Copeland said by phone from a San Francisco hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have friends a little older than me, in their early 20s. And
when they come out to my shows, they're like, `Wow, this is so
cool.' They've never seen anything like it. There's a drummer
making those funky beats ... and a singer actually up there
singing. They're amazed at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Copeland thinks many young people have based their opinions of
the blues on a misperception.
</P>
<P>
   ``When young kids think of the blues, they think of songs about
pickin' cotton and things like that. And it's not like that,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be singing about pickin' cotton, because what
the hell do I know about that?''
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the blues fret about its demographics. Those who love
the music are often middle-aged, while the most celebrated blues
performers _ B.B. King, Bobby Bland and John Lee Hooker _ are in
their 70s and 80s.
</P>
<P>
   Other greats, including Albert Collins, Junior Wells and Albert
King, have passed away. Copeland's own father, singer and guitarist
Johnny Clyde Copeland, died last year.
</P>
<P>
   So when a 19-year-old singer with a full-throated voice like Big
Mama Thornton comes along, blues aficionados have reason to
rejoice. Some have even dubbed her a savior.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can't hang anything on you that you don't want, but the
fact that people say I could help the future of the blues, I think
that's great,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Copeland, who grew up in Harlem and now lives in Teaneck, N.J.,
made her singing debut at 8 at the Cotton Club. But she didn't get
serious about singing professionally until she was 15, just a few
years before her dad died. She grew very close to him during his
final days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved my dad. I'm so glad I spent that time with him when I
did,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While growing up, Copeland absorbed the music of Otis Redding,
Aretha Franklin, Koko Taylor and Etta James. But her father was
always her biggest inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father's music will live through me for as long as I
live,'' Copeland said. ``I wanna make my daddy proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Copeland's ground-pounding debut album, ``Turn the Heat Up,''
was released late last year on Alligator Records. Jimmy Vivino and
Michael Merritt of Conan O'Brien's Late Night Band played on the
album and also backed her during a December performance on the
show.
</P>
<P>
   Since her album was released, Copeland's elders in the blues
community have offered plenty of advice for the young belter, who
turns 20 on April 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the blues community. They're so supportive and helpful.
They look after me and they warn me about stuff,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Copeland's current tour includes songs from the album, among
them ``Ghetto Child,'' ``Married to the Blues'' and ``Big Lovin'
Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   During the tour, Copeland will get a boost from her role in the
upcoming Neve Campbell/Matthew Perry movie, ``Three to Tango.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big stretch for me, but I play a blues singer in a
nightclub,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
