<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DDJ HOPING TO HIT PAYDIRT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in their swashbuckling Fidelity days, the ``vulture''
investors who now run DDJ Capital Management were famous for buying
risky distressed assets at dirt-cheap prices.
</P>
<P>
   Now DDJ is about to buy gardening supply company Smith &AMP; Hawken
for $75 million, as the winner of a bankruptcy court auction
conducted in Worcester, Mass. last week.
</P>
<P>
   The lingering question: Did DDJ get the drop on other potential
bidders thanks to an unusually fast auction timetable, or did it
overpay to protect a lackluster investment? You could hear either
point of view among people familiar with the process.
</P>
<P>
   Court testimony indicated that Smith &AMP; Hawken, a healthy
division of bankrupt CML Group Inc. of Acton, Mass., had suffered
through a poor Christmas season and cut its cash-flow forecasts for
the current fiscal year to just under $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   That means the DDJ bid, which includes about $25 million of
assumed debt, would amount to 15 times cash flow, roughly double
the going price for a healthy company in the same business. But
others seemed to be interested at those prices, or at least talked
a good game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret we didn't have more time to look at the business
because we were interested,'' said George Majoros, chief operating
officer of Wasserstein Perella Merchant Banking in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Unsecured creditors, mostly investors who owned $40 million of
convertible debt, also beefed about the fast-track auction. But
they dropped their objection after a settlement improved their odds
of getting at least a little money back.
</P>
<P>
   Wasserstein Perella did not make a bid deemed acceptable, but
Majoros wrote to CML lawyers that his firm was prepared to pay $85
million or perhaps more for Smith &AMP; Hawken, pending further review.
The Majoros letter was dated Feb. 4, the deadline for Smith &AMP;
Hawken bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you sell your company based on that letter?'' Judy
Mencher of DDJ fired back. She said the Wellesley firm, which
manages about $1 billion, paid up in a fair auction for a company
it liked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smith &AMP; Hawken is a good little growth company that just needs
to be properly nurtured,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   DDJ was created in 1996 when original principals David
Breazzano, Daniel Harmetz, and Mencher left Fidelity Investments,
which decided the high profile of hard-nosed vulture investing
didn't fit with the Boston mutual fund giant's corporate image.
Smith &AMP; Hawken will be DDJ's largest retail gamble since it bought
hundreds of millions of dollars of debt owed by the bankrupt R.H.
Macy &AMP; Co. for Fidelity (Harmetz is no longer at DDJ).
</P>
<P>
   Everyone seems to like Smith &AMP; Hawken's business, which is based
in California. Unfortunately, it has been owned by CML, which
sucked up cash like a Hoover.
</P>
<P>
   DDJ already had $70 million of loans outstanding to CML when it
teamed up with the Wisconsin Investment Board, which had loaned the
company another $20 million, to make a joint bankruptcy bid for
Smith &AMP; Hawken.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, DDJ money didn't come cheap when it became a lender to
CML last summer. CML was losing millions and its Nordic Track unit
was starting to look like a money pit.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston Corp. and a partner, Rothschild Inc., had loaned $50
million to CML in the first step of what could be a two-stage
lending agreement, with more money expected. On the other hand, the
original loan actually matured in midsummer. Instead of advancing
more cash, BankBoston and Rothschild could demand their $50 million
back, and perhaps they would have.
</P>
<P>
   The solution: DDJ took over the entire loan and advanced another
$15 million to CML. The price: interest at 4 percent over the prime
rate, plus points like you might pay for a home mortgage and a 19
percent equity stake in CML, not to mention every piece of
collatoral the company could muster.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they turned Nordic Track around, we were going to make
money because the stock would be worth something,'' said Mencher.
``If it was unsuccessful, then our backup position was that we were
protected by the value of Smith &AMP; Hawken.''
</P>
<P>
   By the fall, investment bankers at BancBoston Robertson Stephens
had been hired to find ways of raising capital for Smith &AMP; Hawken.
At least 20 to 25 of the most likely big investors were contacted
but all were scared off by the debt levels of CML, according to
Joseph Pelligrini, the investment banker working on Smith &AMP; Hawken.
</P>
<P>
   The Nordic Track turnaround never happened and that subsidiary
filed for bankruptcy protection in November. CML followed suit a
month later.
</P>
<P>
   CML executives said they wanted to sell Smith &AMP; Hawken quickly
because it was already being hurt by the financial drag of its
parent company. Smith &AMP; Hawken also needed access to new credit by
the end of February to build inventory for its crucial May-July
selling season.
</P>
<P>
   The auction process opened by the end of December with a
deadline six weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if Smith &AMP; Hawken had been kept under wraps and
then suddenly and unexpectedly been put through a process in a
short period of time,'' said John Pound, the chief executive of
CML. ``It was set up from the get-go to facilitate quick due
diligence from serious parties.''
</P>
<P>
   He said 70 potential bidders reviewed initial due diligence
material and 10 of them went to California for an on-site look.
</P>
<P>
   One of the conditions: CML was only accepting ``no-out'' bids,
meaning a potential buyer couldn't back out because it discovered
problems later or failed to get financing at prices it expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fear was that in the event things were not as advertised,
you wouldn't have any recourse,'' said Majoros of Wasserstein
Perella. ``It's at least conceivable we could have paid more. Had
they opened up the process for one more month, I think Smith &AMP;
Hawken would have been just as valuable and its customer
relationships preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasserstein Perella had been one of the prospects that received
initial information but did not go to California to visit Smith &AMP;
Hawken, according to Pound.
</P>
<P>
   The company's sale to DDJ is expected to close within weeks, and
Mencher said her firm was reviewing whether Smith &AMP; Hawken required
more money to stock up for its prime gardening season. She said DDJ
might seek an additional Smith &AMP; Hawken investor to put up new
capital.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
