<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KOSOVO _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is meeting
Friday with French President Jacques Chirac and expected to discuss
the tense ongoing negotiations between Serbs and Albanians over the
Yugoslavian province of Kosovo. The United States, which already
has committed some 2,000 troops to the region, has issued a warning
to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic that unless a deal is done
by noon (Paris time), 6 a.m. EST, on Saturday, U.S.-led NATO
airstrikes on Serb targets could begin within 24 hours. Developing.
(Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Clinton and Chirac will have a news conference at 3:30 p.m.
EST.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton holds his first news
conference since winning acquittal in his impeachment trial, a
joint session Friday with President Jacques Chirac of France.
(Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-EASTTIMOR _ LIQUICA, Indonesia _ Ragged coffee farmers
in this disputed territory of East Timor are battling with bows and
arrows, while teachers and doctors are packing to flee out of fear
of chaos. ``All of us are in danger,'' said Gregory N.M. Dos
Santos, who this week gave harbor in his home to five skinny,
glassy-eyed warriors who had escaped nearby fighting. Two of them
were 12 years old. They share his sentiment that East Timor must
gain independence from Indonesia, and this is the issue that has
sparked the escalation of violence. The 800,000 people of this
jungle-covered half-island, a colonial remnant still suffering deep
poverty and feudal polarization, suddenly have been offered the
choice to remain a part of Indonesia or to become independent. They
are almost certain to opt for independence, a status for which East
Timor is unprepared and which risks throwing them back to a
fruitless and anarchic past. (Kunstel-Albright, Cox News Service).
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving by 2 p.m. EST Fri., Feb. 19 for use Sat., Feb. 20.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BERRY-EXECUTION _ At 9 p.m. EST, Ohio will join the college of
executioners when it gives a lethal injection to Wilford Berry _
abused as a child, suicidal as a child, diagnosed schizophrenic and
stone cold murderer. Last minute appeals are filed but are not
likely to spare the man who says he wants to die. (Beyerlein,
Dayton Daily News). 25-30.
</P>
<P>
   FLIPPER _ WASHINGTON _ Nearly 60 years after Henry O. Flipper's
death, President Clinton is to pardon the Army's first commissioned
black officer at a ceremony in Washington tonight. Retired Gen.
Colin Powell, who kept a photo of Flipper on his wall while serving
as chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, is expected to attend
along with other black officers and Flipper's descendants. Ceremony
scheduled for 6:30 p.m. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LYONS _ LARGO, Fla. _ Continuing coverage of racketeering trial
of Rev. Henry Lyons, president of the National Baptist Convention
USA. (Williams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-DEATHJURY _ JASPER, Texas _ They have sat, poker-faced,
through hours of graphic testimony, but jurors in the dragging
death trial have already divulged to the court their horror at the
crime. ``Horrible,'' said one. ``I was sickened by it,'' said
another. The 12 men and women chosen to hear the case reacted much
like the nation. And in many respects, they are like your next-door
neighbors. They watch Wheel of Fortune and Walker, Texas Ranger,
they believe honesty is the most important value to impart to
children and their personal heroes are their spouses and others
close to them. A portrait of a jury, based on testimony and their
responses to questionnaires. (Gamino, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
