A1754 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS     02-19 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOUR MOUSE IS GETTING DRAGGY, TRY WINDEX AND COMPRESSED AIR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have looked in all of our manuals that came with the
computer and cannot find info about how to clean the mouse. It
seems to be dragging a bit and is one year old. Could it possibly
need to be replaced?
</P>
<P>
   A: You probably just need to clean it, which is a fairly simple
task.
</P>
<P>
   A mouse uses a small rubber ball that sticks out of the bottom
of the case; this ball is in contact with a series of rollers
inside the case. As a mouse rolls around, the rollers sense the
ball's motion and communicate that to your computer.
</P>
<P>
   As it moves, a mouse picks up dust, crumbs, cat hair, etc., even
if it's on a mouse pad. You need to clean this out from time to
time.
</P>
<P>
   Turn your mouse over and look at the bottom of its case. You'll
see where the mouse ball sticks out, and it's surrounded on most
mice by a plastic ring. Turn the ring counterclockwise and it
should come off.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the mouse ball. Take an ordinary household cleaner _ I
like to use Windex _ and spray the mouse ball. Dry it well with a
lint-free cloth and set it aside.
</P>
<P>
   Now, take a can of compressed air and blow out the inside of the
mouse case. (If you don't have a can of compressed air, get one at
any office supply or computer store. You'll also need it to blow
out the dust that gathers inside your computer's case, something
you should do every six months or so.)
</P>
<P>
   Put the mouse ball back in place and secure it with the plastic
ring. Your mouse should work fine now.
</P>
<P>
   However, there's a chance it might not. If it's still sluggish,
try replacing the mouse pad. The surface of a mouse pad can wear
smooth, which provides less friction.
</P>
<P>
   If it's still sluggish, check the connection to the computer. If
you have a cordless mouse, check the battery. If it remains
unresponsive, it may be time for a new one.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I had tried Disk Defragmenter on my computer a couple months
ago without any problem, but when I tried it yesterday, my computer
froze at 10 percent complete. I reset my computer, turned off the
screen saver and tried it again, but it did the same thing. There
were no virus scanners in the background and no other program
running. What can I do next to accomplish the task? My computer is
a Compaq, Pentium II, 333-megahertz and using Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   A: The answer to this can be found at the Microsoft Knowledge
Base at support.microsoft.com, in article
support.microsoft.com/support/kb/articles/q186/9/78.asp. But here's
the summary:
</P>
<P>
   Basically, you weren't patient enough. Windows 98 has a
different way of defragmenting a hard drive than Windows 95, and
part of the process slows the computer down to the point that it
appears not to be responding.
</P>
<P>
   With a traditional disk-defragmentation process, the files on
the computer are placed sequentially, one after the other, so there
are no gaps in between. But with Windows 98, the operating system
arranges your files so that the most-used items are placed on the
fastest part of the hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   To do this, Windows keeps a series of logs showing which
programs you use most. It then reads these logs and rearranges the
files accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   This takes some time, causing the process to appear to ``hang''
at 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Your best fix _ go get a cup of coffee, take a jog around the
block or call an old friend.
</P>
<P>
   The more you use the computer, the more extensive these log
files become. That's why your first defrag effort went quickly, and
the next one seemed to hang up.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is to use the Norton Utilities' Speed Disk, which
does the same thing but much faster.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
