<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1755 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-19 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO GET KINDER, SIMPLER OPERATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A recent column on the hazards and frustrations of using
programs that run in the background in Windows 95/98 struck a
nerve. I was flooded with e-mail from readers who either had
experienced problems firsthand, or who now had suspects to blame
for some of their woes.
</P>
<P>
   The column looked at the tradeoffs of using utility programs
that work in the background in Windows, including virus scanners,
crash protectors and installation monitors. I ran Symantec's System
Works _ which includes all these things _ for about a month, then
turned off the background components for another month. The result
was a faster, more stable system without all the bells and
whistles.
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma, of course, is that if you shut down these
components, you don't get their benefits. If you sacrifice the use
of a background virus scanner for the sake of improved performance
and fewer software conflicts, you must be willing to manually scan
all programs and some documents that are introduced on your
computer.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not confined to the Symantec products. Every
virus checker comes with an in-the-background component. And most
personal computers sold at retail are loaded down with background
components that do everything from controlling special keyboard
buttons to looking for patches and updates via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SACRIFICE BACKGROUND PROGRAMS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many readers appreciated my comments, but had an additional
question: ``So, um ... how exactly do I identify and disable these
things?''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there's no easy answer here. Each program handles
it differently. But there are some general places you can look and
strategies you can employ.
</P>
<P>
   You can get a feel for how much is running in the background by
doing a ``three-fingered salute'' _ hold down the Control, Alt and
Delete keys at the same time. This will bring up a box that will
show you just what's running on your system. The identity of some
entries, such as Explorer, will be obvious. Others, such as systray
(or system tray, the area on the taskbar that contains the clock),
will not be so obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Clicking on the End Task button here will abruptly shut down the
program you've highlighted. However, the program will come right
back the next time you start your computer. What you need to do is
figure out which programs you don't want to run at start-up and
configure them so they do not.
</P>
<P>
   And now it's time for a very important caveat: If you don't know
what something is, don't mess with it. Every time you turn off a
background application, you are losing some functions, and shutting
down the wrong thing could be irritating at best and disastrous at
worst.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CAN'T GO WRONG WITH RESEARCH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First, read any manuals or help files you may have for the kind
of programs that might have background components. The manuals will
discuss the software's different components and how to configure
them. Usually this will be through some kind of configuration
utility or control panel you can access through a program's primary
component. Find these main components under Start/Programs.
</P>
<P>
   Next, look in the Windows 95/98 system tray. The tray is the
area to the far right of the taskbar _ it typically includes the
clock and some icons, such as a speaker. Many background programs
place an icon in the tray. First, try right-clicking on it. You're
likely to get a menu, or a control panel might launch.
Double-clicking it also may bring up a control panel.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Norton AntiVirus 5.0, right-clicking on its tray
icon brings up a menu that includes the items ``Disable
Auto-Protect'' and ``Configure Norton AntiVirus.'' Clicking on the
former will disable its background activities, but it will remain
loaded and in system memory. If you choose the latter, you will get
a control panel that lets you completely unload Auto-Protect, and
it won't launch the next time you start your computer.
</P>
<P>
   If you use McAfee VirusScan 4.0, right-clicking on its tray icon
also will bring up either a menu that lets you disable or enable
different components, or a full control panel that lets you unload
the module altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Some programs are even easier to prevent from loading when a PC
boots up. They launch by putting an icon in the Startup folder, and
preventing this is as simple as moving the icon out of the folder.
</P>
<P>
   To see what's in Startup, right-click on the Start button and
choose Explore from the menu that appears. Open the Programs
folder, then go to the Startup folder and look inside. Some
examples: if you have Microsoft Office, you'll find some icons
there that speed up its launch time; if you've got Norton
Utilities, the System Doctor places an icon here.
</P>
<P>
   Create a new folder on your desktop (right-click on the desktop,
choose New, the Folder) and name it ``From Startup.'' Drag the
icons of the programs you don't want to launch from the Startup
folder and onto this new folder. Restart your computer, and the
programs won't be running. If you want to run them manually, launch
them from the new folder on your desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Some older programs may launch background components using a
line in the WIN.INI file, a legacy from the old MS-DOS/Windows 3.1
days. You can check here by using Sysedit, a configuration file
editing utility. Click Start, then enter sysedit and click OK.
</P>
<P>
   Find the WIN.INI file and look for a line that starts either
LOAD or RUN. If there is a program here you don't want to run at
start- &QL; 
up, place your cursor in front of the filename, hit the Enter key,
then place a semicolon in front of the filename on its own line.
</P>
<P>
   Some programs are harder to track down. They launch via the
Windows Registry, the big database of settings in Windows 95/98. If
you have Windows 98, you're in luck _ it has a nifty feature called
the System Configuration Utility that lets you turn on and off
anything that runs at start-up.
</P>
<P>
   Click Start, Programs, Accessories, System Tools, then System
Information. Go to the Tools menu item and click on System
Configuration Utility, then click the Startup tab.
</P>
<P>
   From here, turning components on and off is a matter of clicking
a check box. You also can use the System Configuration Utility to
edit WIN.INI, AUTOEXEC.BAT and other configuration files. To me,
this application alone is worth the price of upgrading to Windows
98.
</P>
<P>
   Again, let me emphasize that if you are unsure about making any
of these changes, then don't make them. There's no sense killing or
maiming your computer in a neurotic hunt for any and all background
applications.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
