<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HOTLIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER HOTLIST: AMUSEMENT PARKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ The American Midway: www.americanmidway.com/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Looking for information about small, unusual theme parks off the
beaten path, as well as some of the majors? Jim Westland offers his
unabashed opinions about them for vacationers, with a separate
section for hard-core roller coaster enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Six Flags: www.sixflags.com/
</P>
<P>
   Keep your eyes peeled on the Web site for the Six Flags theme
parks, including Six Flags Astroworld in Houston. Many of the pages
here are undergoing renovations _ including Astroworld's _ but the
completed pages for other parks give you an idea of what's to come.
</P>
<P>
   _ Walt Disney World and Disneyland: www.disneyworld.com and
www.disneyland.com
</P>
<P>
   Disney's theme parks are the most elaborate _ and commercialized
_ in the country, and the Web sites reflect that. You can use these
sites to plan a trip to either park, including arranging and paying
for transportation, lodging and tickets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Disney Trip Planning Resource:
members.aol.com/DVClubber/dvchome.htm
</P>
<P>
   Looking for independent help in planning a journey to a Disney
park? The highlight of this site is reviews of off-site hotels
posted by everyday folks who've stayed there.
</P>
<P>
   _ Amusement Park Physics: www.learner.org/exhibits/parkphysics/
</P>
<P>
   As this site points out, amusement park rides may feel
dangerous, but they really are not. Learn about how roller coasters
and other wild rides work, and then build your very own online
coaster.
</P>
<P>
   _ Haunted America: www.hauntedamerica.com/
</P>
<P>
   File this one away for next October. Haunted America specializes
in finding haunted houses across the United States, typically those
that are operated around Halloween. But there are other features
here the rest of the year, including games and an online horror
shop.
</P>
<P>
   _ Roller Coaster Database: roller.coaster.net/
</P>
<P>
   Roller coaster fans can be incredibly rabid, and this site shows
the extent to which they'll go. It contains detailed statistics on
more than 475 roller coasters, including some that are being built
this year. Search by location and type of coaster, then view the
list sorted by height, speed or other factors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yesterland: www.yesterland.com/
</P>
<P>
   Remember the House of Tomorrow at Disneyland, an all-plastic
home built in the '50s to show how people would live in The Future?
Well, it's been history for years, but you can learn about it _ and
other discontinued Disney attractions _ at this clever and
fascinating Web site.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Schlitterbahn: www.schlitterbahn.com/
</P>
<P>
   The Schlitterbahn in New Braunfels celebrates its 20th
anniversary this year. While the park can get incredibly and
uncomfortably crowded in the peak of its season, it's still a fun
place to cool off in the middle of a hot Texas summer. Get
schedules and download a ``test drive'' video.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sea World: www.seaworld.com
</P>
<P>
   Part amusement park, part aquarium, the Sea World parks are a
unique combination of simple fun and animal education. Learn about
the different attractions at each park, including the one in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
