</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-QUAKER3-SIDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE-RAUCOUS GAME MAKER TONES DOWN CORPORATE CULTURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESQUITE, Texas _ In 1994, id Software's office in this suburb
northeast of Dallas was not a place for the faint of heart.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoons, the game company's employees and owners would
fire up the latest version of Doom for a game of death-match,
supposedly to test the latest round of code. In the heat of virtual
battle, they'd scream epithets that would make a sailor blush.
</P>
<P>
   A large open space had room for pool and ping-pong tables. Level
designers' stereos blared heavy metal music. And co-founder John
Romero's door had a hole hacked in it, the result of an encounter
with a medieval battle-ax.
</P>
<P>
   It was, in short, a work space only twenty-something computer
game developers could love.
</P>
<P>
   Today, id Software still occupies the same offices _ though
they've expanded to take up more of the sixth floor in the Town
East Tower office building _ but it's a different environment.
</P>
<P>
   The offices where its employees work are almost hushed. Gone are
the pool and ping-pong tables, replaced by a set of free weights
and a boxer's punching bag.
</P>
<P>
   A visitor can still hear music, but it's muted.
</P>
<P>
   And when it's time for a round of death-match to test the
upcoming Quake III Arena, there's a lot less profanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone's just grown up,'' said Katherine Anna Kang,
id's director of business development and an ace death-match
player.
</P>
<P>
   The company's corporate culture now mirrors the personality of
John Carmack, the genius 3-D programmer who co-founded id and who
remains the soul of its creative efforts.
</P>
<P>
   After Quake I was completed in 1996, id saw an exodus of some of
its original team, including co-founders Romero and Jay Wilbur, the
company's original ``Biz Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Romero, known as much for his waist-length hair and rock-star
style as for his ability to design killer game levels, left the
company after Quake was released. He now co-owns Ion Storm, a
Dallas game company that aggressively seeks publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1994, Romero had the most powerful personality in the
company, and id was viewed by the public through Romero's
persona,'' said Todd Hollenshead, id's chief executive and Wilbur's
replacement. ``But John Carmack is not that sort of a person. When
the people changed, the dominating personalities changed. As a
result, id became more reserved, and that took over the apparent
culture of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, where the old id sought publicity, the company now
avoids it. In-person interviews are rarely granted, photographers
are seldom allowed in id's offices and Carmack doesn't release his
photo for publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one here is interested is being the poster boy for the
company,'' said Carmack, adding that he intensely dislikes what's
necessary to promote a game. He concedes that getting out in front
of the public is going to be more important with Quake III Arena,
because it represents a departure from id's past titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish this was the kind of a world where I just do my
work, we'd put out the game and everyone would just get it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
