<HEADER>
A1761 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENTURA-SATIRE-KEILLO     02-19 2668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURA-SATIRE-KEILLOR-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 HOW I WON THE MINNESOTA STATEHOUSE, By JIMMY (BIG BOY) VALENTE As
Told To GARRISON KEILLOR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By GARRISON KEILLOR &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; For release: Feb. 14 to Aug. 14, 1999, only &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; FROM: The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 by Garrison Keillor.
 &UR; World rights excluding Minnesota and the UK (England, Australia,
South Africa, New Zealand, Ireland) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   __  &UR; (This is a satire chronicling the rise of a certain wrestler
cum pol, and imagining a future that might give Al Gore the
willies.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   __  &UR; (Garrison Keillor is the author most recently of ``Wobegon
Boy'' and the host of ``A Prairie Home Companion'' on public radio.
This article is adapted from his coming book, ``Me, by Jimmy (Big
Boy) Valente as Told to Garrison Keillor,'' to be published by
Viking.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (It was inspired by the election in November of Jesse (the
Body) Ventura as governor of Minnesota, one of whose first acts was
to propose cutting aid to public broadcasting. Of his state's new
governor, Keillor says: ``He's Jesse Helms with pectorals and a
stronger chin. And he makes it fun to read the newspaper.'') &LR;  __
</P>
<P>
   .......................
</P>
<P>
   At International World Wrestling, I, Jimmy (Big Boy) Valente,
was the headliner, Mr. Magnificent, the Boss Man.
</P>
<P>
   I brought wrestling into the modern age.
</P>
<P>
   I was the one who introduced rock 'n' roll. I was the first to
use loops of accordion wire in place of ropes. I was the one who
introduced pyrotechnics. A flaming genius!
</P>
<P>
   Every night it was a Ring of Fire!
</P>
<P>
   I was the first to employ sweat-seeking cruise missiles in the
ring. The first to use explosives: We liked to have one wrestler
throw another in a Dumpster and blow it up. Our slogan was ``Come
See Extreme Wrestling _ No Children Under 6 _ Not for the Squeamish
_ Don't Wear Your Good Clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   The blood flowed, the monster truck roared, the ring burst into
flames and the fans went away happy. I was sitting on top of the
world, earning millions, getting a million hits a day at
jimmybigboy.com.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling gets hard when you pass 40, though. Your back hurts
from lifting 300-pound guys and heaving them into the seats.
</P>
<P>
   One night in the Boston Garden, Hump Hooley and I fought a
marathon tag-team match against the Messenger of Death and Mr.
Disaster, a real shorts-scorcher involving quarts of blood,
thousands of vampire bats, a pack of rabid wolves, six suicide
bombers from Hamas and 12 Tomahawk missiles, and in the finale I
hoisted the Messenger over my head and heaved him into the
turnbuckle, only to have him ignite a moat of gasoline around the
ring, and I passed out from the fumes and lay unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   The flames were licking at my feet, death seemed near at hand _
and then pain awakened me!
</P>
<P>
   I leapt up and called in an air strike on myself! The cruise
missiles came straight at me! Smoke and flames! Utter confusion!
And when the smoke cleared, there was a heap of ashes in the middle
of the burning ring where I had been!
</P>
<P>
   The crowd screamed: ``No! No! Not Big Boy!'' And then I jumped
up and brushed the ashes away and Old Glory descended from the
rafters and I took hold of a corner and was lifted to safety as the
ring exploded and burned.
</P>
<P>
   When the match was done, I lay on the dressing-room floor, too
tired to shower. The Messenger of Death brought me a beer and Hump
helped me into a chair.
</P>
<P>
   I glanced at myself in a mirror and was shocked at the grayness
and blankness of me, the fatuous look in the eyes, as if I were on
powerful medications. Or else, as if I wasn't and should be. I
looked like a snake that had swallowed a dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Loved the flag bit,'' Hump said. ``Write that into the act
from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   I said, ``Boys, I believe I need a vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   In the morning I went to a doctor who diagnosed a nasty case of
testosterone poisoning. The pills I took to keep my energy up were
causing a metabolic vasodilatation of the nerve endings. I was
getting numb above the neck.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One night in Dallas, a man waiting for me in the dressing room
stood as I entered and extended his hand: ``Jimmy, I am Earl
Woofner, the chairman of the Ethical Party of Minnesota. And I've
come a thousand miles to say that our state needs a man like you.''
</P>
<P>
   My skull glittered with sweat, my pink tights were spattered
with blood and I was wearing a peacock-feather headdress, cobalt
blue shades and a cape with 600 flashing light bulbs. Plus, a
python named Virg draped around my neck. Earl did not flinch.
</P>
<P>
   He set down his briefcase and sat on a bench and looked up at me
with utter sincerity and said: ``The people of Minnesota are crying
out for a champion to break the liberal choke hold and open up
politics to common sense and honesty. And I am looking at him.''
</P>
<P>
   I took off the glasses and set down the snake.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about it, Jimmy?'' he said. ``The troops are ready. When
do we get the order to march?''
</P>
<P>
   By rights I should be a Democrat, because I am for the little
guy, but the Democrats are run by yuppie liberals trying to remake
American society into a day-care center for adults. Making folks
stand outdoors to smoke a cigarette. Making a teacher fill out a
14-page questionnaire if she says boo to a kid. Labels on beer cans
warning that alcohol is not good for your health and may cause you
to fall down on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats started out with the New Deal, a good idea for its
time, and then delusions of grandeur led them to keep adding on to
it, like a guy who sets out to make carbonara sauce and starts
throwing sausage and peppers and onions in, and pretty soon you've
got peas and anchovies and pineapple swimming around in it and the
thyme and oregano are at toxic levels and nobody is hungry anymore.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Democratic platform. Programs for everything _
programs to combat grumpiness, stupidity, discrimination,
covetousness, improper lane changes, low math scores, flat beer,
poor taste and too much air in the Cracker Jack box, and all of the
programs require battalions of social workers and reams of paper.
</P>
<P>
   So I look to the Republicans, and what do I see? The Me First
Party: Squeeze the maximum profit out of everything, strip it
clean, gouge what you can, clear-cut the forest, to hell with
everybody else _ lay off the 20-year guys and hire cheap
replacements, cut costs, inflate the stock, sell out, make your
pile, leave town, head for your compound in Palm Springs, buy an
electronic security system and a team of Rottweilers, sit around
the swimming pool, enjoy your brains out and feel no more remorse
than a fruit fly.
</P>
<P>
   So I thought, What the heck, why not the Ethical Party, a grab
bag of bikers and bird-watchers and disgruntled dishwashers and
surly seniors and people who call in to talk shows to gripe about
the mailman.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was May 1998. I took a week off from the I.W.W. tour and got
in my Porsche with the ``Mess With the Best, Die With the Rest''
bumper sticker and took a run around Minnesota to think about the
governorship.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer the gravel roads, where you can make time, roads that
would shake your fillings out at 30, but at 140 you fly over the
bumps like melted butter. From Moorhead to Worthington, on some of
those straight stretches, I held it at 200 for a while. I think
better when I'm moving fast.
</P>
<P>
   I cruised the state and I pondered the future.
</P>
<P>
   Out in the country, farmers were in hock and going broke, having
bought fancy combines at 20 percent interest, and now the price of
corn was bottoming out and the loans were coming due. In the
cities, the factories had gone south and the old factory buildings
were turned into restaurants serving lamb chops the size of
chickadees, plus an artichoke and a small red potato, for $30.
</P>
<P>
   I saw a picture of a candidate for the Democratic nomination for
governor, eating tofu at a fund-raiser and wearing a T-shirt that
said ``I Really Could Use a Hug Right Now.'' And a picture of a
Republican hopeful dedicating a milk-producing plant where 40,000
genetically engineered Holsteins, heavily sedated and lying on
canvas slings and fed with stomach tubes, could produce 2 million
gallons per day.
</P>
<P>
   I called Earl Woofner. ``I can't do it,'' I said. ``I am not a
politician. I don't have the stomach for it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is your strong suit, your honest independent nature,'' he
said. ``Sleep on it. Call me tomorrow. The brochure is at the
printer's, ready to go. The 'Jimmy for Governor' beer is bottled,
all we have to do is slap on the labels.''
</P>
<P>
   That morning, as I often do when I'm on the road and have an
extra minute, I dropped by the local hospital to visit children,
and as it happened, there was one, a 12-year-old boy named Tommy,
who had lost his left hand in a corn picker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Boy,'' he said, ``how can I grow up to become a wrestler
without a left hand?''
</P>
<P>
   I told him: ``You can be anybody you want to be. Don't ever give
up. And it would be a great gimmick. Tommy (the Talon) Anderson.
Jump in the ring with your eagle-feather headdress and clack your
prosthetic device and get the audience to chant, 'He fought the
claw and the claw won.'''
</P>
<P>
   He was a chipper little guy, and he looked up at me and said,
``How did you become what you wanted to be, Big Boy?''
</P>
<P>
   And I was about to say, ``By sheer determination and
imagination,'' and then I thought: ``Hey, I'm not there yet. I want
to be governor. For once in my life, I want to be taken
seriously.'' And I looked down at his freckled face on the pillow
and said, ``Tommy, I came here to help you out, and instead you
helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   I called my wife, Lacy, and told her I had decided to run for
governor.
</P>
<P>
   There was a long breath of a pause, and she said: ``Fine, but I
don't campaign. I don't do the candidate's wife thing at all. No
fund-raisers, so don't even ask.'' I understood, I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are you doing this?'' she asked. I said I was tired of
people making fun of me for wearing pink-feather boas.
</P>
<P>
   Felix, my promoter, offered to manage my campaign. Felix is a
hatchet-faced little guy with a toupee that looks like a raccoon
that got crushed by a semi. He favors livid green-plaid sport coats
and is very sallow and liverish looking, all splotches and rheum
and exploded capillaries, a stub of a cigarette smoldering on his
lower lip.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, thanks,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   I put on my Australian bush hat, my running shoes and my
``Gopher It'' T-shirt, and for five months I rode around Minnesota
in a motor home, green, the interior a soft beige that reminded me
of the inner thighs of a woman I met once in Miami, and lived on
Cheez Doodles, Ho Hos and root beer, which gave me so much gas I
could hardly keep my socks up. I addressed every Kiwanis Club,
Elks, Moose, Jaycees, Sons of Norway, Knights of Columbus, V.F.W.
and Eastern Star that cared to hear me and roamed the coffee shops
and Kmarts, handing out literature, pressing the flesh, chewing the
fat.
</P>
<P>
   I told the people: ``I am not a joke, I am a decent clean person
you could bring home and not be embarrassed by. Yes, I wore a pink
boa and gave flying mules and nipple lifts and atomic handshakes,
and will employ them against the Special Interests. I am no smarter
than anybody else and I don't claim to have all the answers, but it
ain't nuclear physics and I will work hard and accept no special
privileges.
</P>
<P>
   And what I don't know about state government, I'll know a month
after I take office.''
</P>
<P>
   My platform was exactly as follows:
</P>
<P>
   1. I will not tell a lie.
</P>
<P>
   2. I make no promise except to do my best.
</P>
<P>
   3. Any tax surplus goes straight back to you, the folks.
</P>
<P>
   4. I will scorn Big Business and Special Interests in favor of
you, the taxpayer and voter. The trough is closed.
</P>
<P>
   5. There will be action, not just a lot of yik-yakking.
</P>
<P>
   6. No weenies need apply.
</P>
<P>
   7. Let's party.
</P>
<P>
   I destroyed my opponents in the televised debates. I hung them
out to dry.
</P>
<P>
   The weaselly Democrat talked about government needing to create
jobs. I said: ``There used to be a country for people like you, but
it doesn't exist anymore. Its capital was Moscow.''
</P>
<P>
   He whimpered and looked toward the corner of the studio, where
his advisers and pollsters were standing, holding his cue cards.
They were helpless to save him.
</P>
<P>
   The Wepublican was a scrawny runt with one wet finger in the
wind who used the word ``family'' in every sentence, as if this
might win him an Amana gas range, and said he favored social
welfare programs if they ``strengthened the family.''
</P>
<P>
   I said, ``If a person is smart enough to live in Minnesota, then
he is smart enough to take care of his own self and not look around
for a handout.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody else dared to say it plain like that.
</P>
<P>
   And in gratitude, the people of Minnesota put me in the
governor's office.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I was sworn in on Mon., Jan. 4, and the national press was
fawning all over me. Newsweek, Time, you name it.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore phoned that morning and wished me luck. ``Thanks, Al,''
I said. ``See you in Iowa.'' He had a coughing fit.
</P>
<P>
   I look forward to whipping the pants off Gore, that Cigar Store
Indian, in New Hampshire and Iowa. Al will be the 10-to-1 favorite,
and when he falls he will crumble. When he garners 18 percent of
the vote in New Hampshire, compared with 52 percent for the
300-pound candidate with the big pink noggin, I am going to enjoy
watching him go on TV to explain what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Al will wind up running the Ford Foundation and I will be a
president you can be proud of and land in Air Force One and inspect
honor guards and do my duty, and none of that groping in the West
Wing _ I will do mine upstairs in the First Bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   The thought of Inauguration Day 2001 keeps me toasty warm on
these cold winter nights.
</P>
<P>
   I'll be sitting ramrod-straight in my seat on the flag-draped
platform before the U.S. Capitol in Washington, D.C., dressed in my
black suit and Led Zeppelin T-shirt, a big wad of Copenhagen in my
cheek. On the back of my big bare head I'll feel, like dancing
snowflakes, the cold glares from all the big bonzos in the seats
behind me and I'll smile my Big Boy smile to the cameras on the
platform.
</P>
<P>
   I'll stand and raise my right hand and place my left hand with
the World Tag-Team Champion gold ring on the third finger upon the
Holy Bible held by my foxy wife, Lacy, and look Chief Justice Billy
(the Robe) Rehnquist straight in his black cobra eyes and vow to
preserve, protect and defend the Constitution of the United States
and then turn to give Lacy a smooch and hug my daughter, Tiffany,
and my son, Adrian, and shake hands with Bill and Hillary and
squeeze Al Gore's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'll bear down a little until his eyes water and he looks
queasy, and say, ``Tough luck, buddy boy,'' and hold my arms up so
that my supporters out in the cheap seats can see me.
</P>
<P>
   I'll cock my ear to that distant cry of ``Jimm-ee, Jimm-ee,
Jimm-ee!'' _ and turn to go to the limo and look up and see every
senator and congressman and justice and ex-president and ambassador
standing, mouth open, in shock and confusion, as if they had just
witnessed the explosion of the Hindenberg, wondering: ``How did
this happen?''
</P>
<P>
   It's called democracy, boys.
</P>
<P>
   __________ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 1445EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1762 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISCIPLINE-KIDS-ROSEM     02-19 2875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCIPLINE-KIDS-ROSEMOND-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE YOU SPANKED YOUR KID TODAY? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By SUSAN BOLOTIN  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    We all know them, if only by caricature. The parents who devote
hours each night to the ritual of their children's bedtimes. The
children with roomfuls of toys who complain of nothing to do. The
parents whose phone conversations are really interruptions
interrupted by conversation. The children who won't do their
homework unless their parents are nearby. The parents who intervene
on their children's behalf whenever a teacher delivers a bad grade,
a rebuke, a punishment. The children so incapable of dealing with
frustration they explode in rage whenever something goes any way
other than theirs. The children who think of no one but themselves.
The parents who think of no one but their children.
 &HT;    These are the parents, and these are the children, whom John
Rosemond would expunge from the national fabric.
 &HT;    Among an ever-growing group of usually conservative, often
Christian givers of authoritarian child-rearing advice, he is the
expert of the moment, largely because of a recent public dispute
with T. Berry Brazelton over the timing of toilet training.
 &HT;    But Middle America saw his day coming long before the potty wars
hit the papers. Twenty years ago, Rosemond (``Train them by 2!'')
was a family therapist in Gastonia, N.C., with an occasional
article in the local paper. Today, his weekly column appears in
about 150 newspapers.
 &HT;    His practice boarded up, the 51-year-old Rosemond wanders the
country eight months of the year, the Johnny Appleseed of
discipline, putting on nearly 250 shows annually. He publishes a
bimonthly magazine, Affirmative Parenting. He operates a Web site.
And his eight books, which have sold a total of more than a million
copies, have experienced a 30 percent increase in sales over each
of the last two years.
 &HT;    There's more in the works: an infomercial to market a ``take it
home'' effective-discipline kit; a series of nine hourlong programs
being developed for possible placement on PBS; a series of ``news''
segments to be marketed to television stations.
 &HT;    In the fall of '99 you'll even be able to take a cruise with
Rosemond. And when you return home, if he has done his job, you
will, in his words, ``fling open the door and say, 'Hey, kids,
things will never be the same!' ``
 &HT;    It wasn't a cruise, but they came mostly two by two, as hopeful
of salvation as the animals to Noah _ young married couples, women
walking with the shared gait of friends. They came by the hundreds,
up the steps to Wichita's Century II Convention Center.
 &HT;    They came with the purposefulness of disciples, ready to receive
the wisdom being handed out that day. And they were not
disappointed.
 &HT;    Though Rosemond's posture is stooped _ think John Lithgow on a
bad-back day _ his manner is straightforward, unambivalent. Part of
that authority must come from familiarity with his material. Not
only does he repeat three basic talks hundreds of times a year, but
he also uses the same anecdotes in his shows that he uses in book
after book.
 &HT;    ``Are you the kind of parents who tell your kids to pick up
their toys and then leave the room?'' Rosemond asked. ``Or are you
the sort who wants to have a warm and fuzzy relationship going with
the kid?'' His disdain turned to parodic soprano: ``I know, let's
make a game of picking up the toys. The person who gets the most
will get a bowl of ice cream after supper.'''
 &HT;    Rosemond moved on. ``If you punish your child,'' he advised,
``he will hate you. He won't talk to you for three days.'' Beat.
``It's a blessing. Take a vacation.''
 &HT;    The crowd laughed and clapped. They felt ``empowered'' _ a word
I heard to this side of nausea _ by Rosemond. He may have been
telling them they were jerks, but he was also telling them that
they could change. They could realize that rearing kids is ``a
no-brainer.'' They could learn to ignore the ``mental-health
professionals who have convinced us, with the assistance of the
media, that we were all raised in pathological, dysfunctional
families.''
 &HT;    They could forget everything they've ever heard about building
self-esteem in children. They could see their children as ``direct
descendants of Adam and Eve'' and, as such, ``inclined to
mischief.'' They could start confronting their children every time
they misbehaved, and then they could punish them. They could put
their marriage at the center of the family. They could stop
worrying about their relationships with their children and accept
the challenge of leadership. They could make their children happy
by making them well behaved.
 &HT;    Rosemond has not always thought such thoughts; indeed, the story
of his transformation is proof that there really is no conservative
like an ex-drug-taking, rock 'n' roll-playing liberal.
 &HT;    This is how he tells it: His parents divorced when he was 3;
when he was 7, his mother remarried, to an older man who moved the
family from Charleston, S.C., to Chicago. The marriage was marked
by violence, first verbal, then physical. (``I wasn't traumatized
by it, just scared to death.'') His stepfather believed all
emotions should be kept under wraps.
 &HT;    When Rosemond was 15, he went to live in Georgia with his
father, a golf pro, who gave him his own apartment. (``This was not
good for me.'') He finished his high-school years in Chicago. (``My
mother moved into her own room with a bolt lock and her own
refrigerator.'') He then went to Western Illinois University, where
he eventually received his master's degree in psychology.
 &HT;    While there, he played in a rock band. He did a lot of drugs. He
sported red hair down to his shoulders and a fatigue jacket with a
flag sewn upside-down on the back. But after he was married _ he
was 20; his bride, Willie Herman, was 19 _ it was time to get a
job, at a community-health center in the mountains of North
Carolina.
 &HT;    Their son, Eric, was born in 1969. At first, John and Willie
followed the advice of the ``nouveau parenting experts'' they
despise these days. But their son's rambunctiousness and Willie's
second pregnancy (Amy, their second child, is now 26) combined to
make them reconsider. ``Eric's behaviors were going to destroy our
relationship,'' Willie recalls.
 &HT;    The Rosemonds came to understand that Eric needed discipline of
the old-fashioned kind, and the conversion began.
 &HT;    (``This is Eric,'' Rosemond says, introducing me to his son.
``His career,'' Eric adds, laughing.)
 &HT;    As Rosemond's attitudes toward child rearing solidified, his
politics turned toward the right. These days he cannot abide
no-fault divorce; homosexual parenting; Selma Fraiberg's ``The
Magic Years''; sex-education programs; Thomas Gordon's Parent
Effectiveness Training program; homework planners (``a source of
codependency'' between the overinvolved parent and the
irresponsible child); single parenthood by choice; the inclusion of
spanking in definitions of child abuse; TV; and Hillary Clinton and
Marian Wright Edelman (``ultraliberals, leftists, socialists'').
 &HT;    The Rosemonds' home in Gastonia is Country Living perfect _
sampler pillows, stenciled walls, racks and racks of pipes, George
Washington hanging over the fireplace. But when Eric and his wife,
Nancy, walk in with their two little boys, ready for a lovefest
with Grandpa, it takes on the aura of a stage set. The afternoon
feels rehearsed, and everyone in the cast _ including me _ knows
his or her part.
 &HT;    Eric (``I don't read the books, I don't read the articles'') is
there to scoff at Dad. ``So, do you think he seems harsh, like not
a fun person?'' he asks me right off, laughing. ``Well, I tell
people he can dole out punishment with a smile on his face.''
 &HT;    Nancy casually but firmly minds the children, while Willie
soothes any queasiness Rosemond's beliefs about women might
engender. Rosemond is the well-rehearsed pro.
 &HT;    Here he is, in nutshell version.
 &HT;    _ Parents should stop worrying about developing self-esteem in
their children. If held accountable for their behavior and allowed
to experience hardship and frustration, children will develop
self-esteem on their own. Mothers, in particular, he says, are
guilty of rushing in the minute the child begins feeling unhappy or
distressed.
 &HT;    ``If there are two words that underlie self-esteem,'' Rosemond
says, ``they are 'I can.' Well, I was in a school recently. I
walked into the boys' bathroom. Above the mirror, there was this
sign that said, 'You are now looking at the most special person in
the whole world.' This isn't self-esteem. This is narcissism.
Today's child justifies anything. Bill Clinton is a prime example.
He grew up with a single mother who told him his excrement didn't
stink.''
 &HT;    _ Spanking is fine, if done swiftly, occasionally, privately, in
anger but not in rage, with the hand, on the rear.
 &HT;    _ Attention Deficit Disorder is not genetic _ as much as parents
(who don't want to think it's their fault) and professionals (who
want to continue treatment forever) want it to be.
 &HT;    ``Every 2-year-old has ADD, because the left temporal lobe is
not sufficiently developed,'' Rosemond claims. Parents who pay
attention to their children's proper brain development _ by
shielding them from electronic media, making them focus on adult
authority figures and expecting them to finish tasks _ cause this
innate ADD to disappear.
 &HT;    _ Toilet training should occur by the age of 2; otherwise, a
child will become a spoiled brat. Here's how it's done, on the
now-famous three-to-five-day plan: ``You take their clothes off.
You put the potty where they can see it. When they have an accident
they scream, because they hate it running down their legs. Every
time you hear them screaming you put them on the potty.'' Carpet
cleaning is the final step.
 &HT;    _ Chores are essential. By their teens, children should be doing
all kitchen cleanup, most of the housework and the lion's share of
the laundry.
 &HT;    _ All disobedience, no matter how small the infraction and even
if followed by an apology, must be punished. The punishment should
be unpleasant, memorable and inflicted at a time that is convenient
for the parent.
 &HT;    Rosemond talks like this until dusk, indefatigable, cool, even
when I ask if it might be easier to get his point of view across if
he separated it from his religion (``nondenominational
Jewish-Christian,'' by his description) and his politics: ``People
need to understand that conservatives did not politicize parenting
in America, that the people who did are people like Hillary Clinton
and Marian Wright Edelman.''
 &HT;    I didn't know then that Rosemond has his eye on a possible run
for the House of Representatives, but the information wouldn't have
mattered; my role in our stage play does not include a debate about
who politicized the family, how Clinton and Edelman came to be
linked at the hip or why he's polarizing the debate.
 &HT;    It is very easy to find people willing to take on Rosemond.
According to the executive director of the North Carolina
Psychology Board, Martha N. Storie, the board investigated a
complaint brought against Rosemond in November 1987. After an
informal hearing early the next year, a reprimand was issued.
 &HT;    In September 1995, after the board received another complaint,
Rosemond voluntarily entered into a consent order, which stipulated
that a state supervisor review his columns prior to publication.
 &HT;    (Rosemond, who first told me of these incidents, says the first
complaint referred to a column in which he said there was no
evidence that putting a very young child into therapy was efficient
either in time or money; the second complaint was a response to his
advice to the family of an 18-month-old who had been sexually
abused. He told them to forgo therapy for her, since she would
never remember the incident anyway. His descriptions of the
columns, which he stands by to this day, are generally accurate.
They have been excised from the archives on his Web site.)
 &HT;    Much more recently, Grace Reef, director of intergovernmental
relations for the Children's Defense Fund, told me that Edelman has
never worked on any legislation to make spanking illegal, as
Rosemond claims, and that the CDF knows nothing about any program
that would mandate a visit to every new mother to assess her
ability to mother, as Rosemond inveighs against.
 &HT;    I'm sure I also could have found sociologists more than willing
to label his thinking on women sexist. (``Women don't want men to
be more involved, they just want them to be more at their beck and
call.'') But it seemed too easy.
 &HT;    Besides, writing Rosemond off might suggest I don't recognize
anything of my family in the ones he criticizes. I do, and have to
admit that my husband and I have recently made subtle
Rosemond-inspired shifts in our child rearing. Now when we say,
``This is our car, and we are listening to 'All Things
Considered''' _ that ultimate line in the sand _ we mean it. Our
kids, age 10 and 13, look at each other, roll their eyes and
mutter, ``Brainwashed in Kansas.''
 &HT;    The people who adhere to Rosemond's philosophy would laugh at
that _ for more than the obvious reason of our general wussiness.
Their families had once been out of control, their children more
headache than pleasure, but that's history.
 &HT;    As Amanda Riley, a mother of two from Danbury, Conn., tells me,
hearing Rosemond speak three years ago ``rocked'' her world, though
the change in parenting style was not easy at first. ``My daughter
did not get that there were consequences for bad behavior,'' Riley
recalls. ``Since then, I haven't tried anything from Rosemond that
hasn't worked. He's kind of like a religion to me. What he says is
gospel.''
 &HT;    Rosemond often asserts that all parenting advice can be broken
down into a series of aphorisms. ``I'm going to give you enough
rope to hang yourself.'' ``You paddle your own canoe.'' ``You can't
get something for nothing.''
 &HT;    But what, I wonder, about that other maxim: ``Don't hold a
grudge''?
 &HT;    And that's what troubles me most about Rosemond. I respond to
some of what he says, but not to how he says it. ``Gotcha!'' he
seems to bellow, delighting in every punishment doled out. And
while research has shown that children turn out best in families in
which parental demands are enforced, that is true only if the
punishment is not punitive. Loosey-goosey parenting may not work,
but neither does ``seeing and not hearing'' children.
 &HT;    Besides, where does the fun in rearing children get factored in?
Where is the acknowledgment that complexity is not necessarily bad?
Where is the intellectual adventure that comes from helping kids
learn to discriminate between legitimate and bogus authority?
 &HT;    My time with Rosemond has helped me develop a theory. I call it,
in homage to the sociologist Arlie Russell Hochschild's ``second
shift'' (the work a woman does after returning home from her paid
job), ``the third shift.'' But unlike Hochschild's work of
scholarship, my theory is based on that grand journalistic
standard: myself and a couple of friends.
 &HT;    Somewhere along the line, my female friends and I took on,
unasked, a ``third shift'' _ the job of family-happiness manager,
juggling not only lessons and games and school events and nights
out with adult friends, but everyone's emotional well-being,
articulated or not. This is a thankless and exhausting task,
particularly if it includes eradicating frustration and boredom
from children's lives while simultaneously making sure they feel
good about themselves.
 &HT;    I accepted this work, without thinking much about its
consequences, until I met Rosemond. And then it came to me like a
nightmare. He might worry I was turning my children into the Bill
Clintons of tomorrow. But I had another concern: What if I was
rearing them to be Monica Lewinskys _ young adults who don't want
jobs where hard work is expected, who turn petulant when they don't
get what they want, even when what they're looking for is their own
happiness.
 &HT;    That realization _ that your kids can't grow up unless you let
them do it for themselves _ is what I'll take away from this
Rosemondian adventure. Or, as the man says, ``You can't get
something for nothing.''
 &HT;    .......................................................
 &HT;     c.1999 Susan Bolotin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Susan Bolotin is a New York-based journalist.) &LR;
</P>
