was 20; his bride, Willie Herman, was 19 _ it was time to get a
job, at a community-health center in the mountains of North
Carolina.
 &HT;    Their son, Eric, was born in 1969. At first, John and Willie
followed the advice of the ``nouveau parenting experts'' they
despise these days. But their son's rambunctiousness and Willie's
second pregnancy (Amy, their second child, is now 26) combined to
make them reconsider. ``Eric's behaviors were going to destroy our
relationship,'' Willie recalls.
 &HT;    The Rosemonds came to understand that Eric needed discipline of
the old-fashioned kind, and the conversion began.
 &HT;    (``This is Eric,'' Rosemond says, introducing me to his son.
``His career,'' Eric adds, laughing.)
 &HT;    As Rosemond's attitudes toward child rearing solidified, his
politics turned toward the right. These days he cannot abide
no-fault divorce; homosexual parenting; Selma Fraiberg's ``The
Magic Years''; sex-education programs; Thomas Gordon's Parent
Effectiveness Training program; homework planners (``a source of
codependency'' between the overinvolved parent and the
irresponsible child); single parenthood by choice; the inclusion of
spanking in definitions of child abuse; TV; and Hillary Clinton and
Marian Wright Edelman (``ultraliberals, leftists, socialists'').
 &HT;    The Rosemonds' home in Gastonia is Country Living perfect _
sampler pillows, stenciled walls, racks and racks of pipes, George
Washington hanging over the fireplace. But when Eric and his wife,
Nancy, walk in with their two little boys, ready for a lovefest
with Grandpa, it takes on the aura of a stage set. The afternoon
feels rehearsed, and everyone in the cast _ including me _ knows
his or her part.
 &HT;    Eric (``I don't read the books, I don't read the articles'') is
there to scoff at Dad. ``So, do you think he seems harsh, like not
a fun person?'' he asks me right off, laughing. ``Well, I tell
people he can dole out punishment with a smile on his face.''
 &HT;    Nancy casually but firmly minds the children, while Willie
soothes any queasiness Rosemond's beliefs about women might
engender. Rosemond is the well-rehearsed pro.
 &HT;    Here he is, in nutshell version.
 &HT;    _ Parents should stop worrying about developing self-esteem in
their children. If held accountable for their behavior and allowed
to experience hardship and frustration, children will develop
self-esteem on their own. Mothers, in particular, he says, are
guilty of rushing in the minute the child begins feeling unhappy or
distressed.
 &HT;    ``If there are two words that underlie self-esteem,'' Rosemond
says, ``they are 'I can.' Well, I was in a school recently. I
walked into the boys' bathroom. Above the mirror, there was this
sign that said, 'You are now looking at the most special person in
the whole world.' This isn't self-esteem. This is narcissism.
Today's child justifies anything. Bill Clinton is a prime example.
He grew up with a single mother who told him his excrement didn't
stink.''
 &HT;    _ Spanking is fine, if done swiftly, occasionally, privately, in
anger but not in rage, with the hand, on the rear.
 &HT;    _ Attention Deficit Disorder is not genetic _ as much as parents
(who don't want to think it's their fault) and professionals (who
want to continue treatment forever) want it to be.
 &HT;    ``Every 2-year-old has ADD, because the left temporal lobe is
not sufficiently developed,'' Rosemond claims. Parents who pay
attention to their children's proper brain development _ by
shielding them from electronic media, making them focus on adult
authority figures and expecting them to finish tasks _ cause this
innate ADD to disappear.
 &HT;    _ Toilet training should occur by the age of 2; otherwise, a
child will become a spoiled brat. Here's how it's done, on the
now-famous three-to-five-day plan: ``You take their clothes off.
You put the potty where they can see it. When they have an accident
they scream, because they hate it running down their legs. Every
time you hear them screaming you put them on the potty.'' Carpet
cleaning is the final step.
 &HT;    _ Chores are essential. By their teens, children should be doing
all kitchen cleanup, most of the housework and the lion's share of
the laundry.
 &HT;    _ All disobedience, no matter how small the infraction and even
if followed by an apology, must be punished. The punishment should
be unpleasant, memorable and inflicted at a time that is convenient
for the parent.
 &HT;    Rosemond talks like this until dusk, indefatigable, cool, even
when I ask if it might be easier to get his point of view across if
he separated it from his religion (``nondenominational
Jewish-Christian,'' by his description) and his politics: ``People
need to understand that conservatives did not politicize parenting
in America, that the people who did are people like Hillary Clinton
and Marian Wright Edelman.''
 &HT;    I didn't know then that Rosemond has his eye on a possible run
for the House of Representatives, but the information wouldn't have
mattered; my role in our stage play does not include a debate about
who politicized the family, how Clinton and Edelman came to be
linked at the hip or why he's polarizing the debate.
 &HT;    It is very easy to find people willing to take on Rosemond.
According to the executive director of the North Carolina
Psychology Board, Martha N. Storie, the board investigated a
complaint brought against Rosemond in November 1987. After an
informal hearing early the next year, a reprimand was issued.
 &HT;    In September 1995, after the board received another complaint,
Rosemond voluntarily entered into a consent order, which stipulated
that a state supervisor review his columns prior to publication.
 &HT;    (Rosemond, who first told me of these incidents, says the first
complaint referred to a column in which he said there was no
evidence that putting a very young child into therapy was efficient
either in time or money; the second complaint was a response to his
advice to the family of an 18-month-old who had been sexually
abused. He told them to forgo therapy for her, since she would
never remember the incident anyway. His descriptions of the
columns, which he stands by to this day, are generally accurate.
They have been excised from the archives on his Web site.)
 &HT;    Much more recently, Grace Reef, director of intergovernmental
relations for the Children's Defense Fund, told me that Edelman has
never worked on any legislation to make spanking illegal, as
Rosemond claims, and that the CDF knows nothing about any program
that would mandate a visit to every new mother to assess her
ability to mother, as Rosemond inveighs against.
 &HT;    I'm sure I also could have found sociologists more than willing
to label his thinking on women sexist. (``Women don't want men to
be more involved, they just want them to be more at their beck and
call.'') But it seemed too easy.
 &HT;    Besides, writing Rosemond off might suggest I don't recognize
anything of my family in the ones he criticizes. I do, and have to
admit that my husband and I have recently made subtle
Rosemond-inspired shifts in our child rearing. Now when we say,
``This is our car, and we are listening to 'All Things
Considered''' _ that ultimate line in the sand _ we mean it. Our
kids, age 10 and 13, look at each other, roll their eyes and
mutter, ``Brainwashed in Kansas.''
 &HT;    The people who adhere to Rosemond's philosophy would laugh at
that _ for more than the obvious reason of our general wussiness.
Their families had once been out of control, their children more
headache than pleasure, but that's history.
 &HT;    As Amanda Riley, a mother of two from Danbury, Conn., tells me,
hearing Rosemond speak three years ago ``rocked'' her world, though
the change in parenting style was not easy at first. ``My daughter
did not get that there were consequences for bad behavior,'' Riley
recalls. ``Since then, I haven't tried anything from Rosemond that
hasn't worked. He's kind of like a religion to me. What he says is
gospel.''
 &HT;    Rosemond often asserts that all parenting advice can be broken
down into a series of aphorisms. ``I'm going to give you enough
rope to hang yourself.'' ``You paddle your own canoe.'' ``You can't
get something for nothing.''
 &HT;    But what, I wonder, about that other maxim: ``Don't hold a
grudge''?
 &HT;    And that's what troubles me most about Rosemond. I respond to
some of what he says, but not to how he says it. ``Gotcha!'' he
seems to bellow, delighting in every punishment doled out. And
while research has shown that children turn out best in families in
which parental demands are enforced, that is true only if the
punishment is not punitive. Loosey-goosey parenting may not work,
but neither does ``seeing and not hearing'' children.
 &HT;    Besides, where does the fun in rearing children get factored in?
Where is the acknowledgment that complexity is not necessarily bad?
Where is the intellectual adventure that comes from helping kids
learn to discriminate between legitimate and bogus authority?
 &HT;    My time with Rosemond has helped me develop a theory. I call it,
in homage to the sociologist Arlie Russell Hochschild's ``second
shift'' (the work a woman does after returning home from her paid
job), ``the third shift.'' But unlike Hochschild's work of
scholarship, my theory is based on that grand journalistic
standard: myself and a couple of friends.
 &HT;    Somewhere along the line, my female friends and I took on,
unasked, a ``third shift'' _ the job of family-happiness manager,
juggling not only lessons and games and school events and nights
out with adult friends, but everyone's emotional well-being,
articulated or not. This is a thankless and exhausting task,
particularly if it includes eradicating frustration and boredom
from children's lives while simultaneously making sure they feel
good about themselves.
 &HT;    I accepted this work, without thinking much about its
consequences, until I met Rosemond. And then it came to me like a
nightmare. He might worry I was turning my children into the Bill
Clintons of tomorrow. But I had another concern: What if I was
rearing them to be Monica Lewinskys _ young adults who don't want
jobs where hard work is expected, who turn petulant when they don't
get what they want, even when what they're looking for is their own
happiness.
 &HT;    That realization _ that your kids can't grow up unless you let
them do it for themselves _ is what I'll take away from this
Rosemondian adventure. Or, as the man says, ``You can't get
something for nothing.''
 &HT;    .......................................................
 &HT;     c.1999 Susan Bolotin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Susan Bolotin is a New York-based journalist.) &LR;
</P>
