<HEADER>
A1770 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SF-MAYOR-HNS &LR;      02-19 0319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLIONAIRE SEEKS TO UNSEAT SAN FRANCISCO MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHUCK FINNIE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Clint Reilly, the retired political strategist
who has long harbored a desire to run for office himself, has
plunged into the race for mayor of San Francisco with a pledge to
restore an ``ethic of service'' to government.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly launched his campaign Thursday with a scathing indictment
of Mayor Willie Brown's handling of the city's Municipal Railway
transit system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sincere in my concern for the future of this city, and I
am sincere in my commitment to restoring an ethic of service to
city government,'' Reilly told about 60 supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie Brown, who promised us leadership, has given us only
showmanship, and nowhere does that failure show more than with
Muni,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly offered a 10-point plank that included promises to fire
Muni managers who don't meet performance goals, an end to rules
that allow drivers not to show up for work without consequences and
a city charter amendment to remove a requirement that drivers be
paid salaries that are at least the second highest of any transit
agency in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was in no rush to engage the Reilly, a millionaire real
estate investor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to do the job of the city,'' he said. ``I'll get around
to running in September or October.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene, with Reilly standing in the shadow of a subway train
entrance, was meant to focus attention on the chief issue he hopes
to exploit: public dissatisfaction with city transit.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, 52, faces a tough challenger even as he attacks one of
the mayor's weakest issues. Brown is a longtime officeholder who is
endorsed by the city's dominant Democratic Party and traditionally
has enjoyed the support of minority groups in this ethnically
diverse city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
