<HEADLINE>
UC REGENTS SEEK TO EXPAND POOL OF ELIGIBLE STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHERINE SELIGMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ University of California regents are considering
a plan to make 4 percent of the students in each high school
graduating class eligible to attend the system.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis said the proposal would ``reward excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   University of California President Richard Atkinson called the
plan historic in its attempt to extend opportunity and improve high
schools, but acknowledged that it would do little to increase the
numbers of minorities attending campuses in the University of
California system. The proposal would have no effect on black
enrollment and would mean about a 1 percent increase in Hispanic
enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not enough in terms of providing diversity,'' Atkinson
said after Thursday's regents meeting, ``but we must abide by the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of student groups protested the proposal, saying it
was ``inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This goes to show how hesitant UC officials are to stop
discriminating,'' said Heather Bergman, a student at Berkeley and a
member of the Coalition to Defend Affirmative Action By Any Means
Necessary. ``No one is going to fall for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Regent Ward Connerly, the architect of the plan that ended
affirmative action in the university system, said he was concerned
that the 4 percent proposal was a ``back-door'' approach to
re-instituting racial preferences. But Connerly did not indicate he
would oppose the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson defended the plan, which is part of a series of
proposed changes to alter admissions policy, as a ``front-door
path'' and ``a loud and clear message that we will reward
excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal calls for extending eligibility for admissions to
the top 4 percent of high school students in each graduating class.
In order to do that, the University of California will identify
high-achieving students in their junior year, giving the university
more time to recruit them.
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson said that no eligible students admitted under previous
admission criteria would be displaced by the new proposal, which is
expected to add about 3,600 students.
</P>
<P>
   Regents generally praised the 4 percent proposal, but some were
skeptical about other proposed changes in the admissions policy
that would give less credit for advanced placement classes and
alter the emphasis given to SAT scores.
</P>
<P>
   One change calls for giving students who complete advanced
placement classes half a point boost in their grade instead of a
full point. That would mean that an ``A'' in AP English would be
counted as a 4.5 instead of a 5 in calculating grade point
averages.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the change said it would help curb grade inflation
and even the playing field for students who have limited access to
AP courses.
</P>
<P>
   Regent John Davies said he worried that giving less credit for
AP classes would ``lower the bar'' for admission. He asked that the
changes be considered separately.
</P>
<P>
   Another change would give more consideration to SAT achievement
tests in specific academic areas as opposed to basic SAT skills
tests.
</P>
<P>
   All the changes are necessary in order to make 12.5 percent of
state's top students eligible to attend the University of
California system, a goal that is part of the system's master plan,
said Keith Widaman, a professor of psychology at Riverside. Widaman
is head of the statewide faculty governing body's Board of
Admissions and Relations with Schools, which generated the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Only 11.1 percent are now eligible, he said. Newly eligible
students would still meet high standards under the proposals, he
said. Two-thirds of those who would be covered by the 4 percent
plan are already eligible.
</P>
<P>
   But many students don't attend even if they're eligible, one
school counselor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't see themselves as having the opportunity to go to
UC,'' said Patricia Bunyard, a counselor at Arvin High School in
Kern County. ``Their parents don't expect them to go. They
certainly have the motivation, but they are missing something to
get there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
