<HEADLINE>
MERCEDES SUV IS TOUGH AND POSH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Mercedes-Benz decided to get into the sport-utility market,
the German luxury automaker took the task seriously.
</P>
<P>
   While some other designers of high-end SUVs decided to put a lot
of luxury in their vehicles but leave true off-road capability to
the Jeeps of the world, Mercedes chose to build a vehicle that
isn't the most luxurious in the class, but has a unique combination
of excellent on- and off-road performance.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced last year, the V-6 powered ML320 is a smooth and
comfortable passenger car on the highway, similar to driving a
Mercedes E-class sedan.
</P>
<P>
   But off the road, the M-class is a tough machine, thanks to its
rugged body-on-frame construction. Unlike some of its luxury
competitors, including the Lexus RX 300, Mercury Mountaineer and
Oldsmobile Bravada, Mercedes equipped the M-class with a low-range
transmission mode that puts the vehicle in the same class with the
market's best off-road explorers, including the Toyota Land
Cruiser, Jeep Grand Cherokee and Isuzu Trooper.
</P>
<P>
   With a base price of just $34,950, the ML320 has already proved
to be serious competition for the premium sport-utilities in the
same price range, such as the Ford Explorer Limited, Grand Cherokee
Limited, RX 300, Acura SLX and Mitsubishi Montero.
</P>
<P>
   Sales have been so good that Mercedes has announced an expansion
to its Alabama M-class factory that will increase annual output
from the current 65,000 units to at least 80,000, and a European
factory is being set up to provide M-class vehicles for that
market.
</P>
<P>
   For 1999, the company has rolled out a V-8 version called the
ML430, our test vehicle for the week. It lists for $43,750 and
comes with a list of extra items that aren't included on the base
ML320, including leather seats, power/heated front seats,
leather-wrapped steering wheel and shift knob, privacy glass,
auto-dimming rearview mirror, wood interior trim, trip computer and
a safe box under the front passenger seat. (Those items are
available as a single package in an upgrade for the ML320.)
</P>
<P>
   The ML430's numeric designation refers to the 4.3-liter
displacement of the engine (the ML320 has a 3.2-liter six), which
is rated at 268 horsepower and 288 foot-pounds of torque, compared
with 215 horsepower and 233 foot-pounds of torque for the V-6
model.
</P>
<P>
   Off-the-line performance isn't spectacularly different, however.
The ML320 goes from zero to 60 mph in nine seconds, while the ML430
improves on that by only a second. Still, with the extra power, the
ML430 is a more capable tow vehicle for boats, campers and/or horse
trailers. Top speed on both models is electronically limited to 112
mph.
</P>
<P>
   Either one has plenty of power for normal driving, including
freeway merges and passing. Both engines are connected to a
smooth-shifting, electronically controlled five-speed automatic
transmission. The transmission's fuzzy-logic computer control
varies the shifting points to match the driving habits of the
operator, or to keep the vehicle from shifting unnecessarily while
going up or down hills.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things people say when they see the M-class is
that it seems to be rather small. But its exterior appearance is
deceiving. The interior is roomy enough for five adults _ two in
the front buckets and three seated comfortably on the second seat _
and the cargo area is larger than that of the segment-leading Ford
Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Explorer and most other midsize SUVs, the M-class has
a third seat available. It seats an additional two people, although
it's best left to children or smaller adults.
</P>
<P>
   Because Mercedes decided to build a sport-utility to compete in
the high-volume mid-$30,000s to low-$40,000s range, the M-class
doesn't have all of the luxury and convenience trappings of luxury
cars in this class, such as automatic climate control. In fact, the
base ML320 has cloth seats and manual seat adjusters _ almost
unheard of in a vehicle priced higher than $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Included on the base M-class are manual air-conditioning with
dust and pollen filtering, power windows and door locks, 80-watt
AM/FM/cassette stereo, cruise control, tilt steering, rear
defroster and wiper, dual heated/power side mirrors, alloy wheels,
six-way manual front seats and retractable cargo cover.
</P>
<P>
   Other standard features on all M-class vehicles include
four-wheel antilock brakes, electronic stability control,
four-wheel independent suspension, front and side air bags for the
driver and front passenger, and the patented ``Baby-Smart'' front
passenger-seat system that detects the presence of a Mercedes
infant or child safety seat and turns off the passenger air bag.
</P>
<P>
   A new option for '99 is the ``power skyview top'' ($2,395), a
4-by-3-foot sliding sun roof that opens over the front and rear
passengers. A smaller glass sun roof is available for $1,095.
</P>
<P>
   If you want more luxury for the money, try the high-end
Explorer, GMC Jimmy Envoy, Grand Cherokee, Lexus RX 300 or Toyota
4Runner. But for those of you who want a Mercedes, as well as a
vehicle that is as capable off road as it is on the highway, the
M-class is worth your consideration, even in base form.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's worth paying $9,000 more to get the V-8 engine, and
other extras that come with the ML430, is for you to decide.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel economy for the V-8 model is 15 miles per gallon in the
city and 18 on the highway; for the V-6, it's 17 mpg city/21
highway. The tank holds 19 gallons of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   At A Glance:
</P>
<P>
   1999 Mercedes-Benz ML430 sport-utility wagon
</P>
<P>
   THE PACKAGE: Midsize, four-door, five- or seven-passenger, V-8
powered, four-wheel-drive sport-utility wagon, a new version of the
M-class that debuted last year with a V-6 engine.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS: More power for towing is available from the new V-8;
excellent on- and off-road capabilities; smooth, quiet ride,
well-constructed; priced to compete against the popular
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVES: Not as luxurious as some of its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR COMPETITORS: Lexus RX 300, Ford Explorer Limited, Jeep
Grand Cherokee Limited, Toyota 4Runner Limited, Infiniti QX4,
Oldsmobile Bravada, Mercury Mountaineer, Mitsubishi Montero, Isuzu
Trooper/Acura SLX.
</P>
<P>
   EPA FUEL ECONOMY: 13 miles per gallon city, 18 highway.
</P>
<P>
   BASE PRICE: $43,750 plus $595 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD rating: A.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III writes on transportation issues for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His mailing address is
Star-Telegram/Northeast, 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford,
TX 76021; his E-mail address is chambers(at)star-telegram.com. Fax:
(817) 685-3883. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)  &QL;
</P>
