<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANNING ISN'T UP TO THE JOB OF RESUMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Is there a program that will allow me to scan a
resume and then store it in a database where it can be reached at a
later time by typing in keywords?
</P>
<P>
   _ Big-Time TV Guy
</P>
<P>
   DEAR BIG: As a matter of fact, I once wrote just such a program,
but there was a lot of resistance to its use, merely because it
pulled up my own resume no matter which keyword you typed in.
People can be so petty.
</P>
<P>
   True, scanners can ``read'' text, but you'd probably be better
off hiring a temp to punch the resumes into a database program like
Access or FoxPro. A scanner simply takes a picture of a page.
Text-recognition software then tries to figure out what all the
letters are, then jams them into a text file. If you have enough
patience, you can teach the software to recognize different
portions of the resume as different fields for a database, but that
only works if every resume you get looks exactly alike. One frilly
font, and the whole thing blows up.
</P>
<P>
   One thing you might try is a database program that can store
images as well as text. Then you could scan the resume and stash
the image file along with keywords you type into other fields. Of
course, if you do it right, mine's still the only resume that
should pop up. Did I mention that I could use a job?
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Is there more than one version of Win98 now
available? I would like to buy the latest with the most patches
installed. Can I tell by the package info?
</P>
<P>
   _ Up to Date
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DATE: The only thing you can tell from the package is that
you're about to spend 90 bucks. Don't worry, though. No matter when
you buy Windows 98, it will upgrade itself to the latest and
greatest.
</P>
<P>
   If you have some way to get on the Internet _ and any
self-respecting geek does _ Win98 will go out and check the
Microsoft Web site for updates. Just click on the cleverly named
``Windows Update'' shortcut at the top of the start menu.
</P>
<P>
   If it's your first time there, you'll automatically download a
couple of helper programs, then Microsoft can reach out and poke
around your computer. I know, it's not a pleasant feeling having
Bill Gates groping your gear and pawing your peripherals. It gives
me a new appreciation for what my prom date went through.
Nevertheless, they do a pretty good job of figuring out what you
ought to download. And you won't have to call up your pal Werner
von Foureyes for help, since most stuff installs automatically.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a deal you can download that checks the site for
updates whenever you're on the Net, in case you're too lazy to do
it yourself. Just don't get all paranoid and think that it's some
way for Microsoft to keep track of you. It's merely a way for
Microsoft to keep track of you. Hey! Wait a minute ...
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I only buy the paper to get your comments. The
rest of the paper is trash.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wise Beyond His Years
</P>
<P>
   DEAR WISE: That's exactly what I keep telling the editors, but
they never listen. They seem really hung up on all that news stuff.
The ad people are no better, except they occasionally print pizza
coupons and lingerie pictures, which pretty much makes my life
complete.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay is checking out the
Victoria's Secret ad on Page 9 right now. His real name is Michael
Gerst, editorial systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
If you need to contact him, try drbombay(at)star-telegram.com,
especially if you're Tyra Banks. Snail-mail: Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Fax: (817)
390-7257.)
</P>
</TEXT>
