<HEADER>
A1837 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONKEY-VIRUS-HNS &LR;      02-19 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONKEY-VIRUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINK DOWNPLAYED BETWEEN POLIO VACCINE, TUMOR RISKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Tilde needed over n in Zuniga) 
 
By JO ANN ZUNIGA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ There is no cause for public alarmover new research
that shows a monkey virus that contaminated early batches of the
Salk polio vaccine now is being detected in human tumors, a Houston
doctor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can be considered a very important clue, but no need for
alarm,'' said Dr. Janet Butel, head of molecular biology at Baylor
College of Medicine in Houston. ``There is no elevated risk for
those who had the vaccine.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are uncertain whether the simian virus 40 (SV40)
caused the tumors. Many of those who have the tumors did not have
the Salk polio vaccine, so another method of how the virus was
transmitted needs to be discovered.
</P>
<P>
   But evidence is mounting that SV40 is associated with certain
types of human brain, bone and lung tumors, Butel said.
</P>
<P>
   However, she said a London newspaper misinterpreted her study of
the monkey virus in early polio vaccines when the paper reported
the virus had been proved to be ``cancer-causing'' and could be
responsible for hundreds of cancer deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going one step further than I am prepared to go,'' said
Butel of the London Telegraph report. ``There is no evidence'' that
the virus found in some human tumors came from the polio vaccine,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The monkey virus has been found in the tumors of people who were
not alive in the 1950s and 1960s, when the contaminated polio
vaccine was used, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper based its report on Butel's study, published last
month in the Journal of the National Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Butel and Dr. John Lednicky, also a Baylor molecular virologist,
presented an overview of SV40 in the Jan. 20 issue of the journal.
</P>
<P>
   SV40, which originated in the rhesus monkey, was discovered in
1960 as a contaminant of polio vaccines given to millions of people
from 1955 through early 1963. Monkey kidney cells that were used to
grow the polio vaccine unknowingly were contaminated with SV40.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the polio vaccine has been purified and no
contamination exists. Butel also stressed that the SV40
contamination occurred mostly in the injected Salk vaccination or
polio shot, and not as much in the popular Sabin vaccine sugar
cube.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nothing negative against the polio vaccine which saved
so many lives and so much suffering,'' Butel said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, this link between the virus and tumors ``provides
insight for possible causes of certain types of human cancers,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   This would be another step toward a new vaccine to attack SV40
and prevent these cancers, Butel said.
</P>
<P>
   She estimated roughly one-third of bone tumors and up to half of
pediatric brain tumors could be caused by SV40.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
