<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, Feb. 21, and thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYBOY-MANSION (Los Angeles) _ The return of Hugh Hefner's
Playboy Mansion as a nightlife destination for young Hollywood. By
Rick Marin.
</P>
<P>
   SEARS-FASHION (Undated) _ Top fashion editors shop at Sears to
help women leaving welfare for the workforce to chose a wardrobe.
By Bob Morris.
</P>
<P>
   SUGARRAY-BAND-NITEOUT (Undated) _ Sugar Ray, the very
fashionable band with hunky lead singer, Marc McGrath (cover of
Cosmo last year). Performing before Tommy Hilfiger's show on
Thursday and walking down the runway, then doing Letterman and
having a private dinner and party with Tommy. By Bill Powers.
</P>
<P>
   LILY-FASHION (Beverly Hills, Calif.) _ Over the last few years,
certain stars _ Demi Moore, Wynona Ryder, Nicole Kidman _ have been
wearing to the Oscars the most delicious gowns, drop-dead elegant
and fitted like a dream. When asked where they came from, they say,
``Rita, from Lily.'' Lily is shorthand for Lily et Cie, possibly
the most opulent collection of vintage haute couture and top-end
manufacturers from the 1920s to the 1970s assembled in the country.
By Alex Witchel. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ With the exception of a few stray
flamingos and a handful of gnomes, gardening has never been a
terribly funny affair in this country. Mired in compost, knee-deep
in axial symmetry and preoccupied by integrated pest management,
gardeners have tended to be a sober bunch. By Tovah Martin.
</P>
