<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE TO FIND THE BOOK THAT LOCATES GHOSTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Eakin Press was scheduled to release a book by Richard
Stewart and Allan Turner called ``Transparent Tales: An Attic Full
of Texas Ghosts'' around Halloween. Where can I find this book?
</P>
<P>
   _ V.E.F., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: You can order the $24.95 book directly from Eakin Press by
calling (800) 880-8642.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transparent Tales,'' written by two Houston Chronicle
reporters, contains two ghost stories about downtown Fort Worth
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   One describes a ghost haunting the third floor of the building
that used to house Barber's Books, which was once a
turn-of-the-century hotel in the city's red-light district.
</P>
<P>
   The other takes place in the Jett Building at 400 Main St. in
Sundance Square.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'd like to send Sophia Loren snapshots of an old charcoal
drawing of hers. Where can I write to her?
</P>
<P>
   _ E.M., Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Loren in care of the William Morris Agency, 151 El
Camino Dr., Beverly Hills, CA 90212.
</P>
<P>
   Loren, 64, has recently been doing interviews to promote a new
cookbook, ``Sophia Loren's Recipes and Memories.''
</P>
<P>
   She was hospitalized briefly in August for cardiac arrhythmia.
``They did all the checkups here in New York and everything was
fine,'' she told a USA Today reporter earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Loren's next project is ``Destinazione Verna,'' a science
fiction film directed by Michelangelo Antonioni. Loren's
26-year-old son, director Edoardo Ponti, also is working on the
project.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was Red Skelton's first name?
</P>
<P>
   _ F.O., Hardwick, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: The comedian and painter was born Richard Bernard Skelton on
July 18, 1913, in Vincennes, Ind. His father, a former circus
clown, died two months before his birth.
</P>
<P>
   Skelton left home at age 10 to join a traveling medicine show
and became a vaudeville performer at age 15. Debuting on radio and
Broadway in 1937, he went on to appear in 43 films.
</P>
<P>
   After TV's ``The Red Skelton Show'' ended a 20-year run in 1971,
Skelton made up to $2.5 million a year from his paintings of clowns
and other subjects, and they sell for $120,000 or more today. He
died in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
