<SLUG> BC-TV-GLORY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PASSING GLORY': AN INSPIRATIONAL SPORTS MOVIE THAT WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By WILLIAM McDONALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports stories about underdogs defeating expectations have been
a staple of American culture for generations, whether in a dimly
remembered 1950s book for boys called ``Five Against the Odds'' or
in the crowd-pleasing '80s movie ``Hoosiers,'' both of them about
basketball heroics.
</P>
<P>
   The newest tale to join the fold, and a true one, is ``Passing
Glory,'' a television movie on TNT Sunday night. But this story
does its brethren one better. It finds its drama not just in the
inevitable Big Game between the lowly and the lordly but in the
even more momentous conflict between blacks and whites.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, though the executive producer is Earvin ``Magic''
Johnson and the director is Steve James of ``Hoop Dreams'' fame,
``Passing Glory'' is less about basketball than about bigotry. Or
to put it another way, it's about a group of Southern blacks for
whom the only court promising justice in 1965 is one with painted
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Much of ``Passing Glory'' feels familiar, no doubt because it
draws deeply from two often-visited wells: the inspirational sports
movie and the Jim Crow race movie, the latter with its moss-draped
evocations of Deep South languor and menace. These might be reasons
to dismiss the film as warmed-over fare. But in many ways the
merging of the genres gives the movie a surprising freshness; if it
serves up the same old conventions, at least it has made a new dish
out of them.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the story is a powerful one, even if it's easily
recognizable. And it's told well here. Apart from a smattering of
speechifying, the script is taut (written by the actor Harold
Sylvester, who based it on his own experience as a young
ballplayer). The mood, of muffled tension, is faithful to the time
and place, a segregated New Orleans yet to feel the brunt of the
Civil Rights movement. And the acting is uniformly good,
particularly by Andre Braugher, an Emmy Award winner on
``Homicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Braugher offers a complex portrait of contained righteous anger
as the Rev. Joseph Verrett, a native son who returns to New Orleans
to join the faculty of an all-black Roman Catholic high school run
by his former white mentor, the gruff but dedicated Father Grant
(Rip Torn). Verrett, who had been banished as a rebel from the
Baltimore diocese, remains defiant, brooding and impatient with the
pace of racial progress, but in Braugher's layered rendering he's
also capable of quiet moments of humility and humor.
</P>
<P>
   His story dovetails with that of the school's unbeaten
basketball team (unbeaten in a black league, that is) when its
weaselly white coach quits and Verrett, who barely knows the sport,
is forced to take over. Soon he's confronting an echo of his own
rebellious self in the shape of the team's confident but smoldering
star, a role handled with striking subtlety by Sean Squire. The
young man's own story, in fact _ peopled by dropouts from the
projects on the one hand and go-along, get-along elders on the
other (Ruby Dee plays a wise grandmother here) _ is as finely drawn
as Father Verrett's.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Verrett is driving his team toward a barrier-breaking
showdown with the undefeated white league champions from across
town. The outcome may be easily guessed, but what makes its stock
ending bittersweet is what ultimately makes this sports movie more
than one: a kind of unstated truth that lingers in the air after
the final buzzer, reminding us that in 1965, so much was still left
to be won.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PASSING GLORY'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. (repeated 10 p.m. and midnight) Sunday on TNT
</P>
<P>
   Quincy Jones, David Salzman, Earvin ``Magic'' Johnson, executive
producer; David A. Rosemont, co-executive producer; produced by
Gordon Wolf; Tamara Gregory, Joel Simon and Jill Tanner,
co-producers; Steve James, director; written by Harold Sylvester.
Produced by Magic Johnson Entertainment and Quincy Jones/David
Salzman Entertainment in association with David Rosemont
Productions.
</P>
<P>
   With: Andre Braugher (Father Verrett), Rip Torn (Father Grant),
Ruby Dee (Mommit Porter), Sean Squire (Travis Porter), Bill Nunn
(Howard Porter), Daniel Hugh Kelly (Mike Malone, Sr.), Tony Colitti
(Chick Viola) and Khalil Kain (Heatwave Hundley).
</P>
</TEXT>
