<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN GARDENERS CAN TOO GIGGLE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Conn., Calif., N.H.)   (af)  
 By TOVAH MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the exception of a few stray flamingos and a handful of
gnomes, gardening has never been a terribly funny affair in this
country. Mired in compost, knee-deep in axial symmetry and
preoccupied by integrated pest management, gardeners have tended to
be a sober bunch.
</P>
<P>
   The British, of course, have a tradition of incorporating whimsy
into their grounds. In the 18th century, they began littering their
landscapes with follies, false ruins, temples dedicated to mythical
creatures, mirrors that made paths seem to continue indefinitely,
trick water jets that sprayed visitors, and topiary peacocks and
chess pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, after all, was the birthplace of the ubiquitous
pointy-capped, potbellied garden gnome.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow all the merriment didn't translate over here. Initially,
of course, the colonists had the wilderness to tame _ undeniably
serious business. Then there was suburbia to render homogeneous.
American gardens have been called gorgeous, serene and fantastic.
But they couldn't be described as fun, except perhaps in a few
eccentric pockets of California or the Ozarks.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, American gardeners seem willing to crack a grin. As
Bill Thomas, the research horticulturist at the famed Longwood
Gardens in Kennett Square, Pa., observed, ``It takes a measure of
confidence to throw caution to the wind, and Americans just didn't
have that assuredness until now.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kent, Conn., there's a two-story silver gazing globe, for
example, and in Berkeley, Calif., a five-foot-tall steel spider web
anchors a front-yard garden. Longwood Gardens has added a
young-at-heart children's garden with topiary bunnies brandishing
real carrots.
</P>
<P>
   And to the north, a four-piece orchestra of five-foot-tall frog
sculptures swing into a jazz piece when they sense motion on a
garden path in La Malbaie, Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   Although flippant, the humor that increasingly hedges the garden
is more iconoclasm than outdoor sitcom. Gates are positioned where
no one of normal dimensions could possibly enter or leave, paths
are knee-deep in flowering plants that can't be walked on, boots
are planted with thorny succulents, suggestion boxes are placed
safely out of reach at the tip of 20-foot poles, garishly colored
rakes and shovels are stuck business end up where flowers have
failed to sprout.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Bishop, who tracks trends for Smith &AMP; Hawken, the
upscale gardening catalogue giant, has noticed a definite incline
toward playfulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally, everyone thought they had to emulate Sissinghurst
or some other grand estate in their backyard,'' she said. ``Now
it's O.K. to have fun. Creativity is now seen as part of gardening.
Even irreverence is allowed.''
</P>
<P>
   My first inkling that a more jovial juncture had arrived
occurred last winter when I encountered the newly positioned Four
Seasons sculptures in Hanover, N.H., of Alice Moir, truly a
tongue-in-cheek gardener. The sculptures, four waifs with wistful
Elizabethan expressions, carried sheaves of wheat or something
equally symbolic of spring, summer, fall or winter.
</P>
<P>
   They were capped in snow and wrapped in Dartmouth mufflers, with
Dartmouth beanies on their heads and varsity sweaters draped over
their shoulders. I couldn't help but smile.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Moir's fence pickets are capped with hole-riddled gardening
gloves, she stations seatless footstools in the beds to keep her
iris from flopping and she sticks wooden tulips around the
playhouse ``because they're the only flowers my grandchildren are
willing to tend.''
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly, the trend to comedy began with gazing balls and
bizarre color combinations. When gardeners found they weren't
tarred and feathered for mixing orange with magenta, they took
additional courageous steps.
</P>
<P>
   A few summers ago Peter Wooster, an interior designer and avid
gardener in Roxbury, Conn., surrounded his severely invasive plume
poppies in a spiked cupola resembling the guard tower at Alcatraz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plume poppies are wonderful tall plants with flowers
attracting so many bees that it sounds like La Guardia Airport, but
they are best when controlled,'' he said. He topped the posts of
his Belgian fence with weird metal shapes and supported a vine on a
horse-head hitching post.
</P>
<P>
   Other vines climb up dead tree trunks and recycled street signs,
while chimney pots serve as pedestals. Wooster selects items that
are beautiful, like the nine-foot-tall rusted weather vane that
serves as plant support, and uses each piece inventively.
Everything has a punch line.
</P>
<P>
   After all, when you think about it, levity in the landscape
isn't such a stretch. A theological friend points out that
gardening has been steeped in fantasy since the Garden of Eden and
says it's about time gardeners started poking fun at something that
was formerly drenched in sweat of the brow.
</P>
<P>
   It's true. The sharpest garden whimsy spins off from the
drudgery of gardening. In a slightly overgrown garden in
Bridgewater, Conn., I encountered a post bearing directional signs.
The arrow pointing to the east said, ``Nettles,'' the arrow facing
west said ``Bindweed'' and south was marked ``Something Very Nasty
Indeed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
