<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIUM WEAR OUT OF THIS WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Is your wardrobe ready for the new millennium? Maybe
you'd better check with John Glenn or some of the other high flyers
from NASA.
</P>
<P>
   At the fall 1999/winter 2000 fashion shows here this week, more
than 80 design houses presented their visions of fashions for 2000.
And some of them were out of this world.
</P>
<P>
   Helmut Lang's astronaut-like outfits looked like they were ready
for the space shuttle. Yet the silver rubber clothes, with ribbed
elbow- and knee-pads, were street chic. Malibu's futuristic
accessories _ a computer and a vanity mirror attached separately on
the wrist and designed to match one's outfit _ had bestseller
possibilities. (Alas, the wrist computer is still only a concept.)
And Barbara Bui's knee-length hoop skirts and pointy shoulder
shapes were downright Judy Jetson-esque.
</P>
<P>
   Just what is Seventh Avenue trying to tell us? The cultural
statement reflected in the collections is clear: Today's women are
ready for the new millennium. They are confident risk takers (think
potential candidates Elizabeth Dole and Hillary Clinton) and strong
leaders (think Madeleine Albright). In the new era, the designers
suggest, women will dress for themselves in comfortable,
utilitarian clothing. While they may not wear astronaut suits, they
will have fun _ with sartorial touches of luxury and fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   Since women have suggested they want no-fuss, comfortable
wardrobes, it makes sense that the skirt and sweater continued to
replace the structured pantsuit or skirted suit. Designers such as
Carolina Herrera paired A-line skirts with knee-high boots.
Hemlines remained firmly at the knee or below. And embellished tops
were replaced with decorated skirts. Oscar de la Renta, for
example, showed long wool skirts with large embroidered patterns at
the hem.
</P>
<P>
   The '50s A-line skirts were often matched this week with that
era's three-quarter-length sleeves; bunched, three-quarter-length
gloves; ballet slippers; and fur collars and stoles. While
certainly the look is feminine, ultimately it may be too
costumelike to sell in numbers anywhere but Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   As a contrast to the innocent '50s look, glam rock also had a
strong presence on the runway. Many designers showed funky leather
pants, skirts, and three-quarter-length jackets that were hip and
modern.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Hilfiger, who had one of the most exciting shows of the
week, said in his program notes that he has always drawn
inspiration from rock stars. This season, he was influenced by old
punk-rock groups the Sex Pistols, Iggy Pop, and the Clash. His
show, which opened with an unexpected live performance by rock
group Sugar Ray at the head of the runway, was attended by
celebrities such as actress Andie MacDowell, guitarist Kirk
Hammett, and singers Lenny Kravitz, Maxwell, and Mya. The
collection included pants, jackets, and boots made of colorful
snakeskin-patchwork prints, along with waxed-leather motorcyle
pants and a cool black leather hooded poncho.
</P>
<P>
   But Hilfiger, whose customers range from rappers to corporate
executives, showed some classic looks as well, though with a twist.
His male and female models paraded the floor in unusual
combinations, like red nylon ski pants paired with a charcoal
cashmere sports coat, and a pink cotton dress shirt with French
cuffs worn with black leather pants, their seams stitched in white.
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger, in his program notes, said, ``This collection is about
contrast, which I find sexy, young and intelligent. . . . It brings
sportswear to a new level and it brings luxury into reality. . . .
I constantly have to ask myself, `What makes us different?' And the
answer is that we're mixing high and low as we have always done. A
cashmere sweater from the collection with a pair of nylon pants
from the Tommy Jeans line. That is what I consider modern.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's the hottest color for the new millennium?
Interestingly, it's white (after so many years of black).
Considering Princess Leia's futuristic all-white wardrobe in ``Star
Wars,'' maybe it was inevitable. For retailers such as Filene's, it
could be a tough sell, said Robert Rutkauskas, Filene's fashion
director, since ``there's the old adage of don't wear white after
Labor Day.'' He concedes, ``It looks so new, it adds newness to
one's wardrobe.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan's DKNY line had plenty of white jackets, pants,
dresses, and boots, as did Max Azria's BCBG collection. Indeed, in
an early embrace of the trend, a number of magazine editors already
had on white leather jackets as they watched the shows.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no show this week was as innovative and futuristic as
Helmut Lang's. Virtually every one of his outfits _ presented on
male and female models _ had an interesting detail that made it
unique and utilitarian.
</P>
<P>
   A number of jackets, for example, had straps sewn inside,
enabling a jacket to be worn on the back like a backpack (the end
of coat check). A man's tuxedo pants had chaps placed over one leg
(with pockets) in which the wearer could stash keys, cigarettes, or
other items. And several outfits featured silk organza neck rests (
the kind people use on an airplane). The purpose? Maybe busy people
in the new millennium will want to take naps more often.
</P>
<P>
   Lang's clothes _ presented mostly in black, white, silver, and
orange _ weren't for everyone, especially the rubber astronaut-like
ensembles. But Lang's design ideas are still an exciting and
welcome change from the norm. Out-of-the-box dressing (like John
Glenn) is the only way to embrace a new millennium in style.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
