<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1863 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-BACALL-BOS &LR;      02-19 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BACALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LEGEND WHO DOESN'T MINCE WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, CALIF. _ Every inch a legend, Lauren Bacall gazed
serenely out at a roomful of interviewers like a cat eyeing a
not-particularly-challenging ball of yarn.
</P>
<P>
   Then one intrepid reporter posed the question: Did Bacall have
to audition for her part in CBS's miniseries ``Too Rich: The Secret
Life of Doris Duke''?
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh. ``Audition!'' hissed Bacall, nostrils flaring, eyes on
fire, playing the affronted movie queen to the hilt. ``Do you think
I spent my nightmare life in this business to audition now?''
</P>
<P>
   Then Bacall smiled to show she was kidding _ sort of. But the
room had been put on notice by the woman whose smoky inscrutability
and sultry yet commanding voice first captivated Humphrey Bogart
(and the rest of the world) in 1944's ``To Have and To Have Not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, you have it backwards,'' executive producer Robert
Sertner put in hastily. ``She auditioned us.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacall plays Duke, a tobacco heiress who died in 1993 under
suspicious circumstances, in a two-part biopic that starts Sunday
at 9 p.m. and concludes on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As the film opens, Duke is hovering near death, and her
caretaker, a sinister butler played by Richard Chamberlain, does
not appear to be exactly rooting for her recovery. In flashbacks
from the heiress's deathbed, viewers see the story of Duke's life,
including her inheritance of $100 million at age 13, and the many
romantic entanglements she succumbed to in a fruitless search for
love.
</P>
<P>
   Bacall said she met Duke only once, so she based her
characterization on biographies and documentaries about the
heiress. ``You get a sense of the kind of person she was, the kind
of life she led, which was not a happy one, in actual fact,''
Bacall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she had a very difficult childhood and she was very
isolated in her childhood,'' Bacall added. `She had a mother who
hated her and was vicious to her. And she had a father who adored
her and overprotected her and told her that no one would ever love
for herself, but only for her money.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacall's own life could scarcely have been more charmed. She has
delivered indelible performances in such classic films as ``The Big
Sleep,'' ``Key Largo,'' and ``Murder on the Orient Express.'' She
won the National Book Award in 1980 for her autobiography, ``By
Myself,'' and she also picked up a pair of Tonys for her work in
``Applause!'' and ``Woman of the Year.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Too Rich'' is Bacall's first miniseries, she has done
a fair amount of other work on television, including a guest stint
on Chamberlain's ``Dr. Kildare'' more than three decades ago.
Married to Bogart for 12 years till he died in 1957, she was also
married to Jason Robards, a union of actors that produced another
actor, son Sam Robards.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain, of course, has a long track record in television as
the star of not just ``Dr. Kildare'' but of many of the medium's
most lavish miniseries (``Shogun,'' ``The Thorn Birds''). He
lamented the decline in the miniseries genre, noting that the
sprawling multinight epic has become increasingly rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's too bad, because they were tremendous,'' said
Chamberlain. ``Or maybe it's not too bad; I wonder if anybody has
the attention span to watch them anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   So would Bacall consent to a television version of her own life?
``Over my dead body,'' she said emphatically, noting she has
rejected offers to film her autobiography. ``Nobody will. I don't
want anyone to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? ``Why?'' she repeated witheringly. ``Because I don't. I did
not live my life so I could be exploited.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed on the apparent contradiction of portraying someone
else's turbulent life and messy death, Bacall insisted that ``Too
Rich'' does not exploit Duke because it's not ``being done in a
negative way at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, the 74-year-old Bacall still seems to have
the typical actor's anxiety about where the next role will come
from. She wisecracked that her dream is ``to stay employed.'' After
her much-lauded stint in Barbra Streisand's ``The Mirror Has Two
Faces,'' Bacall said, she was ``the flavor of the month for about a
month, but then she realized ``how quickly they forget, and they
move on to the next.''
</P>
<P>
   But the next Lauren Bacall will be hard to find. She issued a
pointed reminder of that when Sertner, the executive producer,
tried to explain why he chose Lindsay Frost to play the young Doris
Duke. Sertner said he picked Frost because of her resemblance to
the young Bacall, adding, ``And she has that voice down.''
</P>
<P>
   Seated next to him, speaking in the unforgetable timbre for
which she became famous, Bacall issued a non-negotiable demurral:
``She doesn't have the exact voice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 1630EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
