<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1865 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-THEN&AMP;NOW-1stlede     02-19 2024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-THEN&AMP;NOW-1stlede-0221-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NOTE TO EDITORS: Corrects Bush's position on Clinton scandal in
52nd graph to: ``But Bush has treated the personal conduct issue
cautiously, saying only that President Clinton's sexual scandals
were ``embarrassing,'' but remaining silent on his impeachment.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    'KINDER, GENTLER' GEORGE W. BUSH?
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Feb. 21, 1999
 &HT;    (NOTE: ``Tonight'' in the 16th graph refers to Sunday, Feb. 21.)
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE and KEN HERMAN
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On an airport tarmac at one of the dreary final
stops of President George Bush's failing 1992 reelection campaign,
his eldest son, George W., glowered toward a small pool of
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was seething. He was kind of rocking on his feet,''
recalled John Harwood, a mild-mannered Wall Street Journal reporter
who was surprised to discover that the son's anger was focused on
him.
</P>
<P>
   Although Harwood had written nothing to trigger the reaction,
George W. was venting because Harwood's newspaper had run a
critical article on the business dealings of the three Bush sons.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years later, Bush recalled late last week precisely what
had ticked him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``A six-column story in the Wall Street Journal I thought was a
little much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The tense moments on the tarmac passed, but they left Harwood
with the impression that ``Junior,'' as family friends called him,
was a hothead during his stint as a White House aide to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said Bush, now governor of Texas, but he allowed that he
didn't shy away from offering ``blunt assessment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the son who pulls no punches and tells it like he thinks
it is,'' Barbara Bush told her diary.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the less flattering image of an impetuous George W.
that stuck in some Washington minds after his father's 1992 defeat,
in part because so little was known about the son who had worked so
quietly in his father's shadow for years.
</P>
<P>
   George W. was his dad's alter ego and trusted agent for
unpleasant jobs, such as telling White House chief of staff John
Sununu that it was time to leave and telling off campaign aides he
considered to be disloyal.
</P>
<P>
   Bush rejects talk (''Psychobabble,'' he calls it) of the two
George W.'s: then, a quick-tempered, behind-the-scenes aide; now, a
campaign veteran praised, even by foes, as affable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the same person,'' said Bush, 52.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he is aware of conventional wisdom that pegged him
as impulsive and heading for the boiling point when he took on
popular Democratic incumbent Ann Richards, she of the rapier wit,
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were saying, 'He'll blow his stack,' `` said Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Stack intact, he won and was re-elected governor in a landslide
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, as an invited guest along with other members of the
National Governors Association, he will return to his dad's old
place at 1600 Pennsylvania Ave. as the king of the unannounced
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Associates and observers from Bush's previous Washington stints
are as surprised as Bush claims he is.
</P>
<P>
   Good ol' boy
</P>
<P>
   Some of the inner circle from his father's White House days say
they never dreamed that George W. would soon become a political
force on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stood in the back of a lot of rooms together, watching his
father make speeches,'' recalled Marlin Fitzwater, who served as
the Bush White House press secretary. ``I always thought he had
good sense and good political savvy, but I never thought he'd run
for office because I never heard him talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard him weigh in on issues,'' said Fitzwater.
</P>
<P>
   It was another Bush son, Jeb, now governor of Florida, who
talked politics. George W. preferred regaling listeners with his
encyclopedic knowledge of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't grow up wanting to be president of the United States.
I grew up wanting to be Willie Mays,'' Bush said in what has become
a stock answer to the stock questions about why, having long ago
realized he couldn't hit the curve, he now wants the White House
job.
</P>
<P>
   Fox News anchor Brit Hume, who watched the Bush White House as a
correspondent for ABC-TV, said the younger Bush fit neatly into the
``good ol' boy'' mold.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had some political instincts and advised his father from
time to time, and sometimes did dirty work for his father,'' said
Hume. ``I would not have predicted from knowing him that he would
have emerged as the figure that he has emerged as. I would have
figured that the comer in the family was Jeb.''
</P>
<P>
   The dirty work included the sacking of Sununu, who had played a
key role in getting the elder Bush elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me put it this way. I wasn't freelancing,'' Bush recalled
recently about the firing of Sununu, who the White House thought
had become a liability.
</P>
<P>
   Sununu, now a top aide in the budding presidential campaign of
Dan Quayle, the elder Bush's vice president, claims it won't be a
grudge match if the younger Bush gets in the 2000 race.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, I have no conflict with George W., contrary to
what the press has been saying,'' Sununu, a former New Hampshire
governor, said in his home state this month as he escorted Quayle
to pre-campaign stops.
</P>
<P>
   The lousy time
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the governor and the Wall Street Journal's
Harwood have marveled together at the turn of events that led
another Bush to the verge of a Republican presidential campaign.
Bush smoothed over his 1992 anger toward Harwood by saying he had
``no hard feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lousy time and I was defending my dad,'' Harwood said
Bush told him.
</P>
<P>
   So lousy, in fact, that Barbara Bush's tell-it-like-it-is son
revealed a rough edge on other occasions. At the Republican
National Convention in Houston, he stormed out of an interview with
a Salt Lake City TV station when the reporter asked about his
father's marital fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   Bush remembers walking off, but says it happened after a
reporter questioned the elder Bush's commitment to family values
because ``you have three crooks in the family.''
</P>
<P>
   And when introduced to ``Doonesbury'' cartoonist Gary Trudeau,
he poured out his displeasure at the comic strip creator for
lampooning his father. Bush, who knew Trudeau when they were Yale
undergrads, recently recalled the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``He suggested George Bush had put his manhood in a blind
trust,'' said the younger Bush. ``I told him I didn't particularly
care for that type of assessment of a good man. I don't think I was
rude.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the history of blunt assessing, predictions that Bush
would lose control in his own campaigns proved wrong. In 1994, he
ran a respectful campaign against Richards in the face of her
effort to paint him as a rich kid armed with a famous name and
little else.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing waiting to snap,'' insists GOP consultant Mary
Matalin, who worked closely with George W. in three of his father's
races. ``I thought of it less as anger than as speaking with
authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Correct, says Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never going to fly off the handle as a candidate,'' he
says now, acknowledging he got much closer to the boiling point as
a campaign operative than he did as a candidate for governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if 'fly off the handle' is the right word, but I
occasionally defended my dad's position. Occasionally somebody
needed to be told. When you have somebody (on the campaign) leaking
information to make themselves look big, I told them I didn't
appreciate that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Blunt assessment ``doesn't mean temper,'' Bush insists. ``I
never had a temper. Have I ever been angry? Sure. Haven't you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a pretty straightforward person. Maybe people in
Washington are used to double talk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One former Bush aide in Texas believes the governor's anger
might be tested anew if he gets into the White House derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is going to have to re-learn how to take a punch. And as a
presidential candidate you have to throw some back,'' said the
ex-aide.
</P>
<P>
   The new George W.
</P>
<P>
   Deny it though he might, potential presidential candidate George
W. Bush is a different package than was presidential aide George W.
Bush, according to some in the family's extended political family.
</P>
<P>
   ``If ever there was one who grew politically, it was George
W.,'' said Vic Gold, a close family ally.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it was like Prince Hal and Henry V,'' he said of
Shakespeare's playboy character who became a serious king.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that he ever caroused,'' Gold quickly added.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what George W. might have done in his self-dubbed
``young and irresponsible'' years he has attempted to put off
limits. He does, however, have experience in dealing with sensitive
personal issues. In 1987, he was dispatched to snuff out adultery
rumors about his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer to the 'Big A' question is N-O,'' he told Newsweek.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has acknowledged he drank too much until he quit at
age 40, has declared himself a faithful husband but has not offered
details about his distant past. It's a defensive posture that could
be tested if he runs for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he's saying is 'I don't have anything to hide, but I'm
also not going to spend every day talking about every detail about
my previous life,' `` said Robert Teeter, the pollster who managed
the 1992 Bush presidential campaign. ``I think that works as long
as somebody doesn't uncover something that shows he wasn't telling
the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush has treated the personal conduct issue cautiously,
saying only that President Clinton's sexual scandals were
``embarrassing,'' but remaining silent on his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had two stints as an aide to his father. In 1987 and 1988,
he moved from Midland to be ``kind of a general ombudsman'' for the
Bush presidential campaign. He returned for the 1992 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the eyes and ears for my dad to a certain extent,'' he
said. ``I wasn't a spy, but I was there to keep a watchful eye on
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first stint, his office was across a hall from Lee
Atwater, his father's top political adviser. In her memoir, Barbara
Bush said George W. and the late Atwater were ``great friends.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush says he was never shy about making sure Atwater, like
everyone in the White House, understood the mission _ particularly
after Atwater appeared on the cover of Esquire magazine with his
pants around his ankles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reminded Lee he was working for George Bush. I didn't
appreciate the picture or the story. My dad didn't appreciate the
picture or the story. And worse, my mother didn't appreciate the
picture or the story,'' said Bush. ``My dad expected there to be
certain conduct during the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bush headed to Dallas to serve as managing general
partner of the Texas Rangers baseball team after his father was
elected in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But he returned to Washington for what he calls ``the defense of
the incumbency'' in 1992. His title was senior adviser and he said
his job was to ``make sure of everybody's agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   In a part of Washington that Bush, a loyalty freak, intensely
dislikes, the candidate's agenda is not always the agenda of
everyone in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the agendas get confused,'' he said. ``I had one
agenda, and that was the best interests of George H.W. Bush. I told
some people in the '92 campaign that I didn't appreciate them
trying to climb off the good ship George Bush before it docked.
And, yes, I occasionally told a member of the press corps that I
didn't like the way they were treating my father.''
</P>
<P>
   On Election Day 1992, when the good ship George Bush ran
aground, Barbara Bush got the news from her eldest child.
</P>
<P>
   ``In late afternoon,'' she recalled in her memoir, ``George W.
told us, based on exit polls, it was over. We would lose. Our boys
had killed themselves for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman of the Austin American-Statesman reported from
Austin, Texas. Scott Shepard of the Cox Newspapers Washington
bureau contributed to this article from Manchester, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
