<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1871 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA--HNS &LR; CLEMENS-YANK     02-19 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA--HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   CLEMENS-YANKEES CLEMENS ADDS INVINCIBILITY TO MIGHTY (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ They were the best baseball team of the past half
century, maybe the best team ever, and that wasn't good enough.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees aren't coming off a 162-0 season, so they
had almost no choice but to add a pitcher who is on his way to the
Hall of Fame. Before Roger Clemens gets to Cooperstown, he'd like a
detour to the World Series. Nobody is more qualified than the
Yankees to show him the way.
</P>
<P>
   Arming the Yankees with Clemens to defend their 1998 World
Series championship is like using a sledgehammer to kill an ant. To
make such overkill possible, the Yankees had to subtract
left-hander David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   And lefty reliever Graeme Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   And second baseman Homer Bush.
</P>
<P>
   And ... And ... And?
</P>
<P>
   That's it? That's all the Yankees had to sacrifice to pry
Clemens away from the Toronto Blue Jays?
</P>
<P>
   One day, Yankees pitchers and catchers are getting ready to
descend upon Florida for spring training. The next, the Yankees
have crushed whatever hopes and dreams the rest of the American
League may have had for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are the windshield. The rest of the AL is the bug.
The Yankees are Microsoft. The rest of the AL is Apple. The Yankees
are the Roadrunner. The rest of the AL is the Coyote.
</P>
<P>
   Without compromising their future one bit, the Yankees added yet
another layer to their aura of invincibility. The Yankees went
125-50 without Clemens, who is the only five-time Cy Young Award
winner in major-league history. And it's not like Clemens is
staggering toward the finish line of his career. At 36, Clemens is
fresh off consecutive Cy Young seasons. His record the past two
seasons: 41-13. His earned run average: 2.33.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Brian Cashman was walking around the Yankees'
Tampa headquarters Thursday wearing sunglasses. After what Cashman
pulled over on the Blue Jays, he should have been wearing a mask.
Even at gunpoint, though, it's hard to imagine how the Blue Jays
surrendered _ and that is the operative word _ Clemens without
receiving any of the Yankees' prized young players.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cashman had the good sense not to gloat publicly about
landing Clemens without giving up pitchers Ramiro Mendoza or Andy
Pettitte, outfielder Ricky Ledee or '98 slugging sensation Shane
Spencer. Cashman is 31, and he plans on being around a while. And
you never know. Cashman may need to do business with the Blue Jays
again. The day may come when he needs to pry away Jose Cruz Jr. for
Ledee and/or a case of jockstraps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, you hate to give up players the caliber of the ones
we sent to Toronto, especially David Wells,'' Cashman said. ``But
when you have the chance to add one of the greatest pitchers in the
game to your staff, you have to make sacrifices.''
</P>
<P>
   As sacrifices go, this is on the scale of Roseanne giving up
singing the national anthem in public. Look at what the Yankees
gave up for a right-hander who led the AL in ERA and strikeouts
while tying for the lead in victories: A loopy 35-year-old
left-hander who keeps himself in about as good a shape as the
typical slow-pitch left fielder. A 31-year-old reliever whose
collected works from the '98 regular season and playoffs amounted
to 39 innings. And a 26-year-old second baseman who had 71 at-bats
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: Wells was the leader of the Yankees' staff last
season. He went 18-4, threw a perfect game and was almost
infallible during the playoffs. Wells loved being a Yankee. He
thrived on the atmosphere at Yankee Stadium. He made a love
connection with the raucous fans. He was the best left-hander in
the AL last year, maybe in all of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   His best still doesn't elevate him into the stratosphere of
Clemens. In the year of his life, Wells put up a 3.49 ERA. Clemens
has a career ERA of 2.95. Wells has a career record of 124-89.
Clemens is 233-124, with a career ERA one run lower than Wells.
Boomer is a party animal whose physical skills are liable to erode
overnight. The Rocket is a workout warrior in the Tom Seaver/Nolan
Ryan mold.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let the spin of Blue Jays general manager Gord Ash make
you dizzy. Ash can talk all he wants about the wonders of trading
one player to fill three positions. Lloyd and Bush are strictly
throw-ins. As effective as Lloyd was (1.67 ERA) in spot duty last
season, he was a microscopic part of the Yankees' success. Yankees
manager Joe Torre called on Lloyd to get four outs in 13 postseason
games.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, for his part, put up a .380 average that will prove to be
a mirage. He was Chuck Knoblauch's caddy _ nothing more, nothing
less. Keep in mind, this is what Bush did in his last minor-league
season: .258, five homers, 17 stolen bases. Bush just might turn
out to be a slight upgrade over Craig Grebek. No wonder AL rivals
flinched when word of the trade circulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary, considering what they did last year,'' Detroit
general manager Randy Smith said. ``They're not invincible, but
they've bettered themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only reasonable concern for the Yankees is finding
somebody who will respond to the postseason the way Wells always
has (8-1, 2.33 ERA). Clemens is 1-2 with a 3.88 ERA in nine
postseason starts. He hasn't won a World Series. He hasn't been to
the World Series since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Clemens always had to carry his team to the playoffs
when he was pitching for the Boston Red Sox. His arm was beyond
tired by the time October arrived. Pitching in a rotation that
already has David Cone, Pettitte, Orlando Hernandez and Hideki
Irabu, the only weight Clemens will have to carry is his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he brings a little bit of hunger,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   It's the sort of hunger that will serve the Yankees well. The
rich didn't merely get richer. The rich made themselves as close to
bullet-proof as a team can be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
