<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1884 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SONNY-CHER-$ADV22-     02-19 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SONNY-CHER-$ADV22-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONNY AND CHER -- FROM SONNY'S POINT OF VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, Feb. 22, 1999 and thereafter)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ For his portrayal of the late Sonny Bono in
``And the Beat Goes On: The Sonny and Cher Story,'' Jay Underwood
got to wear _ and here the actor's voice soars past excitement all
the way to awe _ Bono's (itals)original bobcat vest.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   ``The strangest kind of feeling went through you,'' Underwood
marveled as he recalled donning the sacred garment. ``You put on
something like that, how could you not, you know, feel like you're
getting into the part even that much more?''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the creators of ``And the Beat Goes On'' (Monday, 9
p.m., ABC) knew they were getting a true believer when they plucked
the unknown Underwood from a casting call to play Sonny, along with
the equally little-known Renee Faia as Cher.
</P>
<P>
   That's not surprising, given that the docudrama's executive
producer, Larry Thompson, was Bono's attorney, manager, and friend.
Thompson describes ``And the Beat Goes On'' as a ``loving tribute''
to Bono, killed last year in a skiing accident at age 62, and
acknowledges it's the story of Sonny and Cher from Bono's point of
view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man lived through many years when he was `Sonny
Bonehead','' Thompson said. ``He was thought to be the loser of the
group. He lived through decades of that, and certainly proved by
the time of his death that he had many careers in him, and that he
was sort of the guiding light and the tenacity that made Sonny and
Cher happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sonny Bono was a winner, and that's what our movie says,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   But what about Cher? Although Congresswoman Mary Bono, Sonny's
third wife, who replaced him in Congress, had input into the film,
Cher did not. Moreover, the film is based on Bono's autobiography,
and made by a man, Thompson, who represented Sonny in his divorce
from Cher.
</P>
<P>
   Already accused by some of trying to capitalize on Sonny's
death, does Cher now have reason to worry about image damage from
her portrayal in this biopic?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very fair to Cher,'' insisted Thompson. ``I mean,
you have to watch it and make that decision, but it's certainly
truthful and certainly accurate. And I hope Cher is very pleased
with it. I really do . . . I hope she likes it.''
</P>
<P>
   Faia, who plays Cher, said she tried to portray her as ``the
strong presence, this independent, free spirit'' that blossomed
after the early years when ``she did go along with a lot of Sonny's
ideas and dreams, and he encouraged her and nurtured her.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Underwood, he was determined to portray a Sonny Bono for
whom he has ``utmost respect,'' noting that even while he was
dismissed as a lightweight, Bono was orchestrating the duo's
successful career in music and television, and then going on to
forge his own career in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds kind of cliched or just kind of simple, but he never
gave up, you know?'' said Underwood. ``He was absolutely tenacious.
. . . He would never allow himself to be knocked down for very
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Bono himself tried to interest Fox in a four-hour miniseries
about Sonny and Cher several years ago, but the project was put
into ``turnaround,'' Hollywood code for ``don't call us, we'll call
you.'' Thompson acknowledged that Bono's death heightened interest
in his story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Sonny's death brought his face and name and legacy
and Cher to the media's attention,'' he said. ``And there's
certainly a lot more interest in it now than there may have been.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thompson maintained there is a ``timeless'' quality to the
duo's story. ``It's about people who love each other and how they
grow together and how they grow apart,'' he said. ``And it's about
Americana and music during an era that we all have nostalgia for
and love.''
</P>
<P>
   Faia is a former art student who worked as a costumer on
``Seinfeld'' during its first season and came late to acting. She
had only two weeks to prepare for the role from the time she was
cast. So Faia spent late nights studying tapes of Cher's talk-show
appearances, old episodes of ``The Sonny and Cher Comedy Hour'' and
``The Sonny and Cher Show,'' and footage of the duo's early
performances.
</P>
<P>
   Faia laughingly noted that while Underwood had to wear 19
different false noses during shooting to portray Bono, she needed
no such help (though she did wear a dozen wigs, and she does
lip-synch to vocals provided by a professional singer).
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been told I look like a lot of people, and Cher was one
of them,'' she said. ``When this all came about, I knew that I
could do this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
