<SLUG> BC-TV-SONNY-BEAT-$ADV22-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REHASH, TO A SONNY AND CHER BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, Feb. 22, 1999 and thereafter)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
AND THE BEAT GOES ON: THE SONNY AND CHER STORY 
Starring: Renee Faia, Jay Underwood 
On: ABC, Monday, 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember the recipe on the back of Ritz cracker boxes for
something called ``Mock Apple Pie,'' apparently meant for those who
love apple pie but don't like real apples? Well Monday night ABC is
serving up a made-for-TV movie called ``And the Beat Goes On: The
Sonny and Cher Story'' that's about as appetizing and genuine and
fresh as a slice of Ritz's fakeriffic dessert. It's for people who
love biopics, but don't like anything approaching original
dialogue, true-to-life characters, well-observed nostalgia, or
convincing drama. Executive produced by Sonny Bono's widow, Rep.
Mary Bono, ``And the Beat Goes On'' is so hackneyed and skewed in
favor of Sonny that it's almost fascinating to behold its bold
artificiality _ almost. Mostly, watching the movie is like sitting
in for two hours of impersonation workshop.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just that ``And the Beat Goes On'' rehashes only the
most overused tidbits about the singing duo, from Sonny's early
days as a meat delivery boy to the pair's triumphant TV series.
It's that their tale of corrupted innocence, from the manic 1960s
to the fractured 1970s, is presented with minimal gusto or kitsch.
There's only a sense of obligatory forward motion. In a handful of
scenes, Sonny and Cher rise from performing in a tacky bowling
alley to living in a fabulous Bel Air mansion after ``I Got You
Babe'' has reached No. 1 on the charts. And then in a handful of
scenes the duo are down and out of fashion, with Cher bitterly
noting, ``The boy-girl crap just doesn't cut it anymore.'' But
then, in another handful of scenes, they're back on top with ``The
Sonny and Cher Comedy Hour'' and their famous banter. It's all one
big biopic cliche, with a dashed-off voiceover that has Sonny
saying scrappy things like, ``I never quit trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the movie's costumes and haircuts are eye-catching, as
the couple's bell bottoms and vests seem to sprout fur in the very
strangest of places. Cher's hair goes through all the fun and
familiar phases, from her early bangs to her Pocahontas sleekness,
and we even get a glimpse of her doing her ``V-A-M-P, Vamp'' skit
from the early 1970s. Too bad the period color doesn't get any more
vivid than that, as most of the drama seems to take place in a
low-budget vacuum that contains only two characters. Cher's mother
is portrayed (extremely unappealingly) in only one scene, the
couple's daughter Chastity is seen briefly from behind, and Mary
Bono makes a laughably triumphant appearance at the end. There is a
steady flow of actors imitating music celebrities, including Sam
Cooke, Phil Spector, and David Geffen, but the cameos are never
grotesque or clever. Only Walter Franks takes his Little Richard
characterization and runs with it _ exactly where, I can't say, but
at least it's got oomph.
</P>
<P>
   As Cher, Renee Faia has the manner of her character down pat.
She's the best thing to look at in ``And the Beat Goes On,''
shaking her black hair back and tonguing her lips and rolling her
eyes with an almost mechanical precision. Because the point of the
movie is to portray Sonny as the star-maker and Cher as his
ingrateful creation, Faia's Cher gets lots of time to sulk and to
humiliate Sonny with lines like, ``I wish we were really big, like
Dylan or the Stones.'' Finally, when she sues him for divorce based
on ``involuntary servitude,'' the movie seems to have wrapped up
its case against her, and we flash forward to the 1980s, with Cher
looking humble and emotional as she is reunites with Sonny on David
Letterman's show. Jay Underwood's Sonny is less effective, partly
because the real Sonny wasn't as entertaining as Cher, but mostly
because Underwood doesn't quite nail Sonny's knowing cluelessness.
He invests his character with a little too much sunny, childlike
innocence. After all, we can't forget that the tenacious mensch
with the Prince Valiant hairdo did go on to become a Congressman
from California.
</P>
</TEXT>
