A1902 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILFIGER-ROCK-NITEOUT     02-19 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILFIGER-ROCK-NITEOUT-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSICAL GUY DOES A RIFF FOR FALL '99 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21)  
 (Eds: Please note subslug for SUGARRAY-BAND-NITEOUT)  
 (af)  
 By BILL POWERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At a dress rehearsal on Thursday for Tommy Hilfiger's
fall collection at Roseland, on West 52nd Street, Hilfiger watched
models test-walk the runway while the pop band Sugar Ray played him
a love song.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throw your arms around me, Tommy,'' Mark McGrath, the band's
lead singer, crooned. Riffing on the lyrics for the band's 1997
hit, ``Fly,'' he swapped the fashion giant's first name for the
word ``baby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the calm before the storm,'' Hilfiger told his
creative director, Stephen Cirona, as they headed backstage.
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger is calling 1999 ``The Year of Music,'' and although his
clothes have long been staples among hip-hop's cognoscenti, in the
past few seasons he has been recutting his image as a rock
supergroupie. He sponsored and designed the stage clothes for the
Rolling Stones' ``No Security'' tour.
</P>
<P>
   And the scene backstage at his show looked like a Lollapalooza
tour stop, only the road-ies were replaced with cover girls, and
everyone, smoking and drinking Heineken, was better dressed.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Hammett, the lead guitarist of Metallica, surfaced looking
snazzy in a black suit offset by an ivory-colored tie by Hilfiger.
The actress Andie MacDowell arrived in a slim royal blue leather
suit, also Hilfiger.
</P>
<P>
   In between television interviews, the 46-year-old designer
bumped into a childhood friend now known as Michael H., an aspiring
rock star with a group called Bender, dressed in a leather coat
with a fox collar and rose-tinted glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger invited his pal to the after-party at Brown's, a new
restaurant on East 61st Street, promising to make it to Bender's
midnight performance at Continental. Then he turned to Nur Khan,
designer of Sway, a new SoHo nightclub, and offered to stop by
there, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the name,'' Hilfiger said. ``Sway'' is Track 2 on the
Rolling Stones' ``Sticky Fingers'' album.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar Ray kicked off the show promptly at 7:30. When it was
over, Karen Elson jumped onstage with two fellow models, dancing
and head-banging while the quintet finished its hit ``Every
Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a band,'' Ms. MacDowell said, making her way backstage.
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger took a limo to hop a few fashion fetes before he
arrived at his own after-party at Brown's, fashionably late at
10:15 p.m. Well-wishers applauded him. ``Thank you,'' he said to no
one in particular and high-fived Thomas Gibson, the ``Dharma and
Greg'' actor.
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger pushed up the sleeves of his cashmere sweater _ the
only discernible sign he was loosening up. Lenny Kravitz shook his
hand, and then played air guitar to the Rolling Stones' ``Brown
Sugar.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger took a passing glass of Cristal. MTV's Ananda Lewis
offered Andrew Levy of the Brand New Heavies a Tic Tac before
hopping onto his lap.
</P>
<P>
   On the cell phone, Hilfiger told Bridget Hall he was heading to
Continental to catch his friend's gig.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it cool if we roll down with you?'' a model asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cool,'' Hilfiger said over his shoulder as he exited.
</P>
<P>
   At midnight at Continental, Hilfiger waited in the basement line
for the bathroom across from a sweaty teen-ager sporting an orange
Mohawk. After the band ripped through a 20-minute session, Hilfiger
left and found his brother Andy and Hammett waiting for him outside
a nearby McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, we're going out,'' Hilfiger said, herding the crowd
to a first-anniversary party for the TriBeCa club Shine. ``We're
not here for the McVeggie burgers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
