<SLUG> BC-SKI-SAFETY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE DEATH ON SLOPES, SKIING SEEN AS A SAFE SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Larry Glosten thought he taught his nine-year-old
daughter Madeline all he could about skiing safely. He taught her
to be cautious, not to go too fast, not to ski beyond her control.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Madeline lost control as she went down an
intermediate trail at Ski Plattekill in the northwestern Catskills.
According to her father, she had spent most of the day on easier
terrain, and wound up going too fast. She veered off the side of
the trail and crashed into a patch of small, scrubby trees.
</P>
<P>
   She suffered severe head injuries and died a day later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she was feeling a little bit confident,'' Glosten said
from his apartment on the upper west side of Manhattan. ``You can
imagine that I think I didn't make her aware enough. That's the
fact ... she didn't understand. She made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the death of Madeline Glosten, experts say skiing is
predominantly safe _ much safer than bicycling, skateboarding or
recreational boating. But accidents do happen. And more and more,
parents are paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I do is worry,'' said Mary Lane, a non-skier from Clifton
Park, N.Y., whose 13-year-old son Colin skis every week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they're getting the instruction and supervision,'' she
said. ``I know he's got good sense. (But) I'm afraid he's going to
crack his head open.''
</P>
<P>
   Many parents are worried enough to buy ski helmets for their
children. A few years ago, it was rare to see anybody but racers
wearing the light, padded plastic helmets on the slopes. Now,
they're so common store owners have dozens of models to chose from
and say they sell hundreds each year.
</P>
<P>
   But the helmets have their limits _ hit a tree going faster than
about 12 mph and a helmet will probably not make much difference.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Ski Area Association, child fatalities
are rare. Last winter, of 26 fatalities, only one involved anyone
age 10 or younger. The highest number of child fatalities in recent
years were two in both 1996-97 and 1993-94 _ still a small
percentage of overall ski deaths.
</P>
<P>
   A Rochester Institute of Technology professor, who has studied
ski accidents for years, found that the most likely candidate for
trouble is a male in his late teens to late 20s _ a
better-than-average skier traveling fast, usually on the edge of a
trail where the good snow is often found.
</P>
<P>
   Ski resorts say the best way to keep the child skier safe _ and
immune to the seduction of dangerous speeds _ is by taking a class.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't impress upon them the dangers of skiing,'' said Jay
Barranger, director of Jiminy Peak's ski and snowboard school in
upstate New York. ``We impress upon them the act of skiing safe.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes the ubiquitous Skier's Responsibility Code, which
asks all mountain riders to ski in control, give right-of-way to
skiers in front, not to obstruct a trail and observe all warning
signs.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, there is still the risk, noted the mother of
the late Madeline Glosten.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids fall and grownups fall, and there's this tiny percentage
where there's a disaster,'' Diana Shobrys said. ``And we got it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
