<HEADER>
A1913 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOYOMA-BAROQUE-CELLO-     02-19 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOYOMA-BAROQUE-CELLO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YO-YO MA GIVES A CELLO A NEW LEASE ON ITS FORMER LIFE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: The Netherlands)   By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ ``Yo-Yo Ma records on a period cello for the
first time,'' a press release from Sony Classical proclaims of Ma's
latest CD, a collaboration with Ton Koopman and the Amsterdam
Baroque Orchestra in concertos by Boccherini and transcriptions of
Bach. Yes and no. In fact Ma has long played a ``period'' cello, or
rather two of them: the Davidoff Stradivarius, from 1712, and a
Montagnana, from 1733.
</P>
<P>
   So what gives?
</P>
<P>
   Ma's cellos, like most string instruments of similar vintage,
were modernized over the centuries: fitted with end-pins, allowing
them to be propped on the floor rather than cradled between the
knees, wider fingerboards and steel strings, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the Sony recording and for a series of concerts with
Koopman and the orchestra beginning Sunday afternoon at Avery
Fisher Hall, Ma has reversed the course of evolution on his
Stradivarius, restoring it to a condition that he calls ``75
percent virginal.''
</P>
<P>
   A cynic might suspect that Ma simply is looking for an excuse to
take up the six Bach cello suites all over again, now that he has
recorded them a second time in versions released a year ago,
complete with multimedia interpretations on video. Not that anyone
who heard Ma play the suites on the Montagnana instrument last
March at the Church of St. Ignatius Loyola in Manhattan would be
likely to complain if he did so.
</P>
<P>
   Others might accuse Ma of resorting to gimmickry, as some have
done before: notably, a few years ago, when he joined forces with
Mark O'Connor, a country fiddler, and Edgar Meyer, a bassist, in a
Sony crossover album, ``Appalachia Waltz.''
</P>
<P>
   Or is he just trying to keep up with his longtime friend and
colleague Emanuel Ax, who has recently been performing and
recording Chopin concertos on a period piano? Ma explains matters
differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that makes this profession work, to me, is to make
sure that everything you do is special or different, that you never
repeat something,'' the 43-year-old Ma said last week at the
Harvard University Faculty Club here. ``It's the opposite of mass
production.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the stripped-down cello, Boccherini seems to have
afforded at least as strong a motive as Bach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known the Boccherini concertos for years, and I've never,
ever, wanted to play them on a contemporary cello,'' Ma said. ``I
just didn't think they sounded good. Yet I've always yearned to be
able to do them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ma first worked with Koopman and the Amsterdam Baroque Orchestra
some eight years ago, and has since performed with other
period-instrument specialists, including the conductor Roger
Norrington, occasionally borrowing a ``period'' cello for the
purpose. But the prime impetus to alter his playing style and
instrument came, he suggests, from the collaboration with O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, the esthetic of not vibrating unless you really
have to for a particular effect is the same in both fiddling and
Baroque playing,'' he said. ``And in order to play with him, I had
to change my bow stroke, or bow style, which ended up being more
Baroque.''
</P>
<P>
   These changes, fine distinctions in most cases, were effected in
part by gripping the bow a little closer to where it touches the
strings, much the way a baseball player might choke up on a bat to
achieve a quicker, more flexible stroke (with, perhaps, some loss
of power). At the same time that he was working with O'Connor, Ma
said, he was recording the Bach suites, and he altered his playing
more and more in Bach as well.
</P>
<P>
   Many found Ma's recent Bach performances more Romantic than his
earlier ones, in particular, his 1983 recording of the works.
``Inspired by Bach,'' Sony called the new audio and video
recordings, and though not entirely dismissive of the performances,
Allan Kozinn wrote in The New York Times, ``One has to wonder:
shouldn't the set's title have been `Inspired by Casals'?'' ( Ma,
who cites Casals as a formative influence, not so much for any
lingering Romanticism as for his sparing use of vibrato, may in any
case have been flattered.)
</P>
<P>
   But for this listener the greater expansiveness of the St.
Ignatius performances, the more penetrating thoughtfulness, the
added freedom and grandeur of expression all enhanced Ma's
interpretations without mitigating the pinpoint focus and the
clarity of line that have always been hallmarks of his playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word `Romantic,''' Ma said. ``What does it mean? My music
teacher, Lowell Lindgren, used to say that all music is Romantic in
its time.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I tried to do with this round of Bach suites was to be
more courageous in identifying how Bach worked things out
polyphonically. In other words, since you can't really sustain
notes, how do you do it aurally in such a way that it fits
together?
</P>
<P>
   You have to commit yourself to it, so if there's a pedal point
that lasts for 30 measures, even though you occasionally can't hear
it, you make yourself hear it, and then you react accordingly. The
seeming freedom actually comes from a kind of aural discipline, to
say, `I'm going to make sure that I'm reacting to this.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Montagnana cello itself undoubtedly was also a factor in the
impression of bigness, the sense of spaciousness, the ease with
which Ma's sonority filled the church. The instrument's strong
bass, Ma suggested, was crucial to that illusion of long-sustained
notes underpinning the counterpoint. He called the Montagnana an
``earthy instrument that's right for Bach,'' in contrast with ``the
beautiful, Italianate, cultured-sounding Stradivarius.''
</P>
<P>
   That refined Stradivarius, Ma had long thought, was not entirely
happy in its life as a ``modern'' instrument. ``Strads don't like
to be pushed,'' he said. ``It's almost like there's a fine line,
where you push it too hard and it stops giving. I always felt a
little bad putting the Strad under all this pressure, souped up for
maximum horsepower. You're always trying to find the right way to
make an instrument sing.''
</P>
<P>
   So Ma finally decided to give the instrument a lease on its
former life.
</P>
<P>
   The end-pin is a simple matter: don't screw it in when you
remove the instrument from its case to play it. But its fixture
remains in the base of Ma's instrument, part of the 25 percent that
is not ``virginal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ma had instrument makers in London and Paris restore the bridge,
which lifts the strings off the instrument, and the tailpiece,
which anchors them. (Higher bridges are used today, to add tension
and brilliance, as are plastic or metal tailpieces, to add
resonance.) He replaced the steel strings with gut and tuned the
instrument lower, to what is now widely accepted as Baroque pitch.
He commissioned a reproduction of a bow from Bach's time, also with
less tension.
</P>
<P>
   But he stopped short of restoring the narrower fingerboard,
which would also have required changing the neck of the instrument,
where the strings are attached and tuned with posts. Nor did he
strip off the modern varnish.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last summer, he started to practice. The results had his
wife and two children questioning his sanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gut strings are unreliable,'' he said. ``They sound a little
reedy. They squeak and squawk at times, and they constantly go out
of tune. But what I learned is that with less volume, the
experience is more private, more intimate. Playing with less
tension encourages you to think, to reflect more. It's extremely
pleasurable.''
</P>
<P>
   All those modernizations were made with a purpose, of course,
precisely as music was moving from private, domestic and courtly
rooms to ever larger public arenas: in Ma's words, ``to suit a
2,700-seat hall.'' That is, the likes of Avery Fisher Hall. So how
well can Ma and the orchestra expect to be heard on Sunday?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a question of how we take possession of the
space,'' Ma said. ``We need to treat every hall as an instrument.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   So now that Ma and Ax are on the same historical page, more or
less, will they combine their antiquarian pursuits? Both say they
are eager to do so, but the matter is complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still 100 years away,'' said Ax, who has fallen in love
with an 1851 Erard piano in Birmingham, England. ``I'm not so happy
with fortepianos,'' he said of earlier instruments, noting that the
Erard already had the steel frame characteristic of the modern
piano.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we'll experiment with late Romanticism,'' he said,
but he seemed dubious that he and Ma would find common ground on
period instruments in anything later than, say, the Mendelssohn
sonatas and trios of the 1830's and 40's.
</P>
<P>
   What is the next surprise to be expected from Ma?
</P>
<P>
   The next one he is willing to discuss is a festival in 2002 at
the Smithsonian Institution, centering on aspects of the musical
history of the Silk Road between China and the West, as gleaned
from exotic instruments and other artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying to make sense of all the things I see when I
travel, and the things I've picked up from Mark O'Connor about oral
tradition and the like,'' Ma said. ``You realize that there are
these transnational cultures that have somehow moved things around,
and I'm interested in how things have moved along the Silk Road
over the last 2,000 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
