s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLAYBOY-MANSION-$ADV2     02-19 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAYBOY-MANSION-$ADV21-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE BOOGIE NIGHTS: THE PLAYBOY MANSION IS AGAIN A HIP PARTY SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Feb. 21.)  
(lh) 
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This was a mansion party all right: Charlize
Theron flirted with Jack Nicholson by the pool, and vice versa.
Couples canoodled in the Grotto. Humid blondes in Bunny suits
gyrated around a grinning gray-haired guy in silk pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Do Ya Think I'm Sexy?'' Valentine's Day party at the
Playboy Mansion in Los Angeles last weekend was startling evidence
that not only is Hugh Hefner back in action (after separating from
his wife last year), but so is his stately pleasure dome.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Stiller showed up with Rick Rubin, the hirsute rap producer.
The baby Baldwin, Stephen, was in the house, as were Brett Ratner,
who directed ``Rush Hour,'' and Tori Spelling. Liam Neeson came
early and stayed almost as long as Geoffrey Rush, who tore himself
away around 3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin was clearly delighted to be there. ``It's a fun place,
you know?'' he said. ``When I'm in town, it's a cool place to come
and hang out.''
</P>
<P>
   The mansion is once again a major night-life destination for
young Hollywood in search of raw, retro fun. Leonardo DiCaprio,
Cameron Diaz, Courtney Love, the Foo Fighters, Korn and Joaquin
Phoenix have all made the scene. They jammed the New Year's Eve
party, the Halloween party, Hef's Midsummer Night's Dream party,
the ``Saturday Night Fever'' party, Hef's 72nd birthday party. They
mingled with habitues from the old days _ Tony Curtis, James Caan,
Jack _ and frolicked among the Bunnies and other fauna that
populate Hefner's five lush acres high in the Holmby Hills.
</P>
<P>
   This hipster elite could, let's face it, be anywhere. And yet,
they're there, hanging out with this fossil from the Stone Age of
whoopee-making.
</P>
<P>
   A generation that was born during the sexual revolution but came
of age amid a backlash against it seems to be rediscovering the
guilt-free image of sex that Hefner has always preached and sold.
</P>
<P>
   He's lived large for so long that he contains multitudes of
retro references, from the movie ``Swingers,'' to the Rat Pack and
Studio 54.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many young people, male and female, were waiting for me to
be out there,'' Hefner said of his return to circulation. ``It was
like spotting Elvis at the supermarket.''
</P>
<P>
   For twentysomethings well enough connected to be on Hefner's
guest list, boogie nights at the mansion are a heady aphrodisiac,
an intoxicating cocktail of crass and class.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Duritz, the lead singer of the Counting Crows, came to the
Valentine's party with a group that included Alyssa Milano, one of
the stars of the WB series ``Charmed.'' He said: ``Hey, I met Tony
Curtis here. That's cool, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Another attraction: The press is generally not invited. Unlike
so many Hollywood events, mansion parties are not publicity-driven
media ops. Celebrity guests can cavort free from the prying lenses
of the stalkerazzi or ``Entertainment Tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The party's many hungry-looking young dudes _ some sporting
tight red-leather pants and snakeskin boots, others in fishing hats
and elephantine cargo pants _ trolled for Playmates with tattoos
and toe rings. As ever, the joint was stocked like a trout pond
with the sort of women S.J. Perelman once described as ``balloon
smugglers.''
</P>
<P>
   The original Chicago mansion, purchased in 1959, was a mod,
martini-soaked playpen for swells in skinny ties and ``chicks'' in
go-go boots. In 1971, Hefner went west and bought a clubby,
wood-paneled manor in the old Hollywood style. By the late 1970s,
this polyester palace of disco excess boasted butlers passing
around ``dexies'' on silver platters, nude ``Olympics,'' and a
collection of monkeys and rare birds in Hefner's private zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the small study where he receives guests, Hefner
considered his mansion's revival among a new wave of swingers.
``They felt as if they had missed the party,'' he said. ``It
reminds me of when I was growing up during the Depression. I felt I
had missed the party because I looked back at those exciting images
from the Roaring '20s. The short skirts, the jazz. In a similar
way, people of a certain age feel as if they missed the swinging
'60s and '70s. And my part in all that, and my mansion, is a focal
point.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The typical mansion party has always had an eclectic guest list.
In the Chicago days, Norman Mailer might rub up against Miss July.
Lenny Bruce could crack wise with Ella Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   The new Hollywood equivalent is the Academy Award-winner
Geoffrey Rush, star of ``Elizabeth'' and ``Shakespeare in Love,''
mingling with Shana Hiatt, a 23-year-old Playmate and former
Hawaiian Tropic Girl.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he came to be here, a slightly bewildered Rush said,
``I met Hugh at the Four Seasons, and he invited me,'' adding what
a ``marvelously genial'' host ``Hugh'' was.
</P>
<P>
   Rush was apparently unaware that the only person who has called
Hef ``Hugh'' in the last 50 years was his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ms. Hiatt's fiance, Jimmy Van Patten, could be heard
talking trash with Kato Kaelin. Van Patten has written a movie
called ``Flunky,'' about Hollywood hangers-on and wants Kaelin for
a cameo.
</P>
<P>
   Kaelin is, perhaps not surprisingly, a regular. ``I see more
business cards getting passed around here,'' he said, writing out
his phone number on a cocktail napkin and listing various book and
television projects he hopes will pay off in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if networking had replaced debauchery at the mansion,
Kaelin started to describe an R-rated episode in the Game House,
then veered off the record.
</P>
<P>
   A Swedish actress, Sofia Eng, recounted how a friend had warned
her to stay clear of the mansion. ``I told someone I was going
here, and she was like, `Oh, it's so sleazy,''' said Ms. Eng, 24,
who has a part in ``Wild Wild West,'' a movie opening this summer.
``And it's not sleazy at all. Then she was like, `Can I go?' It's
not the easiest thing to get on the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Male plus-ones, for instance, are frowned upon. Swedish
actresses, on the other hand, are not.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is obvious. Consider the following mansion
conversation:
</P>
<P>
   MALE VISITOR: ``Do you have Playboy in Sweden?''
</P>
<P>
   SWEDISH ACTRESS: ``We just got it. In my country, nudity is no
big thing. All the beaches are topless. If you don't go topless,
people stare at you.''
</P>
<P>
   MALE VISITOR: ``Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   How does Hef do it? He is a man of obvious intelligence and
worldliness. And yet he has spent a lifetime in similarly inane,
libido-driven conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to tell you, I have never gotten most of my
intellectual stimulation from parties,'' he said dryly.
</P>
<P>
   In his study, Hefner looked younger in person than in pictures.
He admitted to a little plastic surgery, to nip what he called some
``Thanksgiving turkey'' skin around his neck. Otherwise, the man
comes as advertised _ black pajamas, red smoking jacket, Diet
Pepsi.
</P>
<P>
   Seated on the edge of a heavy leather couch, he jutted his prow
of a jaw over the coffee table in front of him, which is outfitted
with two backgammon boards (his gaming obsession) and didn't seem
at all sleazy. Just a nice old guy with a wicked smile.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, the famous plaque on the front door of the
mansion, with its Latin warning, ``Si Non Oscillas Noli
Tintinnare'' (``If You Don't Swing, Don't Ring''), seemed a sad
anachronism.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the murder of Dorothy Stratton, Playmate of the
Year in 1980, cast a pall over the place. After weathering feminist
attacks, Hefner's Playboy Philosophy came under siege from the
Moral Majority. The chain of once hopping Playboy clubs died. The
magazine's circulation dropped to half of its high of 7 million.
AIDS had become a national crisis, attributed by some critics to
the kind of sexual libertinism associated with Hefner.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Hefner suffered a stroke. A year later, Newsweek
pronounced, ``The Party's Over,'' on a cover featuring a graying
Hef and his girlfriend at the time, Carrie Leigh, who was known to
interrupt business meetings wearing nothing but a live boa. In
1989, Hefner married Kimberly Conrad, a 1988 Playmate, and
cloistered himself among the mansion's other museum pieces, the
Picassos, Pollocks and Kandinskys.
</P>
<P>
   The Hefners had two children.
</P>
<P>
   That sealed it.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Hefner's friends. They do not look back on his married years
fondly.
</P>
<P>
   At the Valentine's party, James Caan recalled his old buddy's
lapse from bachelordom into ball-and-chaindom. ``The idea,'' Caan
shouted over the din, ``that after 40 years, a guy could change his
whole philosophy for what? A blonde?''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Bann, a film historian and Hefner intimate, was equally
appalled. ``Kimberly wouldn't let the Playmates anywhere near the
place,'' he said. ``They had no access to Hef!''
</P>
<P>
   Bann described this unthinkable situation with a historian's
gravity, as if, during the Cuban missile crisis, key Kennedy aides
had been denied access to the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I told Hef what was happening, he couldn't believe it,''
Bann said.
</P>
<P>
   But today, Hefner is back in business. Stock in the company,
which is run by his daughter, Christie Hefner, is at an all-time
high. The first new Playboy Casino in years will open next month on
the island of Rhodes. And 1999 happens to be, as Playboy's new
billboard in Times Square points out, the Chinese Year of the
Rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   Events at the Playboy Mansion in recent months suggest another,
slightly modified, Latin motto for Hefner.
</P>
<P>
   Veni, Vidi, Viagri.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some Viagra parties,'' Hefner said. ``It was the
girls who suggested it.''
</P>
<P>
   His longtime physician prescribed the drug as a 72nd birthday
present, he said. ``The girls'' are Hefner's three concurrent
girlfriends: Brande Roderick, 24, and Sandy and Mandy Bentley,
20-year-old identical twins.
</P>
<P>
   It should come as no surprise that the founding editor of
Playboy magazine would be dating a threesome with rhyming central
casting names: Sandy, Mandy and Brande. This arrangement raises,
among other issues, the question, Are these young women really
comfortable with sharing the same man?
</P>
<P>
   ``More than OK!'' Hefner exclaimed exuberantly. ``It's the
happiest time of their lives!''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roderick confirmed this statement. ``We all love each
other,'' she said of the twins, who were wearing matching red and
black Bunny costumes at the Valentine's party. ``We're like a
family.'' The disco anthem ``We Are Family'' blared over the sound
system.
</P>
<P>
   A parade of pretty women seems to have been a constant in
Hefner's life, but of course they have changed over the years. He
and his magazine changed them. Now, almost all of them look like
Pamela Lee, whose ``Baywatch'' career was jump-started by a Playboy
pictorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you meet an attractive girl today in this town,'' Hefner
said, ``nine times out of 10, they're very interested in getting
into the magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes his three girlfriends. So who's exploiting whom?
</P>
<P>
   The answer hardly seemed important. Not with Hefner surrounded
by 200 of his close, personal friends of the moment, shuffling his
slippers around the dance floor with anyone who can keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't watch,'' Caan said, averting his gaze. ``He makes me
feel too lonely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
