<SLUG> BC-BIRD-FEEDERS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Common bird feeders for the beginner
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A guide to common bird feeders, from the Illinois-based National
Bird-Feeding Society :
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Platform feeders: Next to sprinkling seed on the ground, the
most basic bird feeding arrangement is the platform feeder, which
is a tray, possibly with raised edges to prevent the seed from
falling off. It attracts dozens of creatures, and you can go
through a lot of seeds in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hopper feeders: These feeders feature platforms with
receptacles attached to them to hold the food, and are used by such
birds as cardinals, blue jays, grosbeaks, finches, nuthatches,
chickadees and titmice. On the ground below to snatch up morsels
knocked out of the feeders will most likely be mourning doves,
juncos, various sparrows and towhees.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Window feeders: Generally made of clear plastic, window
feeders attach easily to the glass with suction cups. The benefit,
of course, is that you get outstanding views of birds with window
feeders. A disadvantage is birds sometimes crash into the glass.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tube feeders: There are several variations of tube feeders,
but they all operate in the same way to dispense seed. The size of
the feeder holes on the side of the tube determines the seed to be
used, from large sunflower seeds to smaller ones. Separate perches
put space between the birds, which reduces some of the competition
and squabbling seen among the feathered creatures when they
congregate on platform feeders.
</P>
<P>
   The species of birds you attract depends primarily on the seeds
you offer. ``For finches, we put only thistles in one our
feeders,'' says Victoria Sampson. In general, black oil sunflower
seed is the hands-down favorite of all the birds that visit tube
and hopper type feeders. A tube feeder with black oil sunflower
will attract goldfinches, woodpeckers, titmice, chickadees and
nuthatches. Adding a tray to the tube feeder also will attract
cardinals, white-throated sparrows, jays and house finches and
purple finches.
</P>
<P>
   Some other combinations: A platform feeder or tube feeder and
tray with peanuts will attract cardinals, grackles, titmice, jays,
sparrows, juncoes, house finches, chickadees, starlings and others.
A hanging suet feeder brings in woodpeckers, chickadees, kinglets,
creepers, wrens, nuthatches, thrashers and others. A peanut butter
suet lures woodpeckers, juncos, thrushes, kinglets, wrens,
bluebirds, goldfinches and others.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charles Seabrook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
