A1944 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIRDWATCHING20-COX     02-19 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRDWATCHING20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Backyard Birding
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For John and Victoria Sampson, the joy of nature is
just outside their living room window _ a vibrant red northern
cardinal on a bleak day in February; a ruby-throated hummingbird on
a bright day in May; a bright yellow goldfinch on an apple-crisp
morning in October.
</P>
<P>
   Like millions of other Americans, the Sampsons, who live in the
Shakerag community in north Fulton County, have found that bringing
the joys of nature close to home pays off in hours of pleasure,
fascination and a special kind of serenity.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has given us these beautiful creatures, and I feel like a
child all over again learning about them,'' says Victoria Sampson,
a retired flight attendant with Delta Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The Sampsons are among about 60 million Americans who buy about
$2 billion worth of seed and feeders every year. ``We have six bird
feeders, two of them for hummingbirds,'' says Victoria. ``We also
have two birdbaths _ water is very important for attracting birds _
and we make sure they are full and clean all of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sampsons, in fact, dedicate most of their three acres in
north Fulton to attracting wildlife. For that, the National
Wildlife Federation recently certified their lot as a Backyard
Wildlife Habitat site. Joining more than 22,000 property owners in
the United States and Canada, the Sampsons cultivate trees, shrubs
and flowers to offer a variety of food and cover for birds,
butterflies, frogs, small mammals and other creatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my husband last year that instead of buying me a
regular present like jewelry for my birthday, I wanted some
serviceberry trees for the yard,'' Victoria said. ``Songbirds love
the berries of the tree.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to become part of this popular pastime. Backyard
birding is now the nation's second most popular hobby next to
gardening, says the Illinois-based National Bird-Feeding Society.
There is no best or worst time to start. Start anytime. Right now,
the birds can use your help while their natural seed sources are
scarce. And backyard birding is a great way to teach children about
wildlife and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, the National Audubon Society and the Cornell
University Laboratory of Ornithology are asking everyone,
regardless of skill level, to help in the Great Backyard Birdcount,
which began Friday and continues thorugh Monday. To participate,
simply identify and count the number of birds in each species you
see during at least a 15-30-minute period. Report your tallies to
the Web site http://birdsource.cornell.edu.
</P>
<P>
   Getting started with birdwatching is as simple as getting some
seed and placing it in an easy-to-see spot outside your window. But
if you're serious about attracting birds, you most likely will want
a genuine bird feeder. Any store specializing in birding supplies,
such as Wild Birds Unlimited franchises in the metro Atlanta area,
can recommend feeders. The bird food and the type of feeder _ and
where you place it _ may depend on the birds you want to attract
and your tolerance of pesky squirrels.
</P>
<P>
   If, like the Sampsons, you want to make a more concerted effort
to turn your backyard into a wildlife haven, contact the National
Wildlife Federation at Backyard Wildlife Habitat program, 8925
Leesburg Pike, Vienna, Va. 22184. There is a $12.95 charge for a
packet of materials on how to create a backyard wildlife habitat.
For more information call 703-790-4100 or visit the organization's
Website at www.nwf.org.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Sampson says the colorful and melodious songbirds in
her yard make her a happier person. ``In the springtime, we hear
the 'cheep, cheep' of many little babies all around us, and it is
wonderful,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Seabrook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
