<SLUG> BC-CPR-SATURDAY20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Breathe easy: Free CPR training available
 &HT;    By Amanda Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Charles Exley hears life-and-death stories all the
time. He wants them all to have happy endings.
</P>
<P>
   Just a couple of weeks ago, when he took his daughter's wedding
dress to the cleaners, he heard another.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young man told me that when his son was 3 months old, he
had (breathing) problems in the middle of the night and turned
blue,'' Exley said. ``He told me, `I think my training saved his
life.' And that's why we have CPR Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Exley will be among the certified instructors teaching the
life-saving technique at 14 sites to more than 4,000 metro
Atlantans on March 6. The free annual training session for
cardiopulmonary resuscitation is sponsored by the American Red
Cross and Kaiser Permanente.
</P>
<P>
   A retired Georgia State University recreation instructor, Exley,
58, has been associated with the American Red Cross for more than
50 years, first as a swimming student and later as a volunteer. The
Stone Mountain resident sees CPR training as among the Red Cross'
most vital missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blood services are extremely important, but preparation for
disaster is equally important, and CPR happens at the earliest
stages of disaster,'' he said. ``When a person quits breathing, if
you don't do something to get oxygen to them immediately, it's
going to damage their brain and organs.''
</P>
<P>
   CPR is credited with saving thousands of lives every year,
according to Red Cross spokesman Bill Maddox, though exact numbers
are hard to come by because no agency collects them.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross offers CPR training throughout the year, and more
than 2 million people nationwide complete classes annually. But CPR
Saturday is the only free event, and classes fill up fast. Anyone
age 12 and older can sign up.
</P>
<P>
   Training includes how to recognize the symptoms of a heart
attack or breathing emergency, how to care for an adult who has
stopped breathing or is choking, how to give CPR and how to use the
emergency medical services system effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Classes take a maximum of four hours, but people often can
complete training in an hour, particularly if they're brushing up
on their skills. But don't assume that getting reacquainted with
CPR Annie _ the Red Cross' teaching mannequin _ can be put off for
years at at time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many new things _ we're modifying the techniques
all the time _ that people really should be recertified every year,
certainly every two years,'' Exley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to say that if you're called on to do something for a
family member of friend, you want to be sure you're doing your
absolute best.''
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Husted writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
