<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1948 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIVILRIGHTS-MURDERS21     02-19 2191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVILRIGHTS-MURDERS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pressure builds to reopen the unsolved murders of rights
activists in 1960s
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 21.
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATCHEZ, Miss. _ On Feb. 27, 1967, Wharlest Jackson was driving
home in a downpour from his job at the local tire plant. Three
weeks before, he had been promoted to a position previously held
only by white men. It was a dangerous step up the ladder: Many Ku
Klux Klansmen worked at the plant, and there were rumors that any
black man taking ``white men's jobs'' wouldn't live to enjoy them.
</P>
<P>
   But in the war for equal rights for blacks in Mississippi, as
well as the daily struggle to support a family, the promotion was a
victory that Jackson savored.
</P>
<P>
   A little after 8 p.m., Jackson, a 37-year-old husband, father of
five and NAACP officer, turned his pickup truck onto Minor Street
in the black section of town. That's when the bomb planted in his
truck detonated, blowing the truck and Jackson to bits. Witnesses
said the police had to pick up his body in pieces, which they
placed into plastic bags.
</P>
<P>
   The murder didn't go unnoticed. About 15 FBI agents came to
Natchez and stayed long enough to record more than 6,000 pages of
notes and evidence. But neither the local police nor the federal
agents arrested anyone. The statute of limitations on federal civil
rights cases expired after a decade, so the FBI closed its case and
stored the file in Jackson, the state capital.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no statute of limitations for murder, and for 32
years the case, represented by a thin folder labeled ``Wharlest
Jackson,'' has remained open at Natchez police headquarters. Open
but ignored by five police chiefs, one of whom was black. Then,
last spring, under pressure from the media and a resolution by the
Natchez Board of Aldermen, Police Chief Willie Huff assigned two
officers to travel monthly to Jackson to comb through the 6,000
pages of FBI files. They're looking for something that might lead
to an arrest and a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good two-thirds of the way through, and so far it
hasn't been productive at all,'' Huff said. ``There are a lot of
names in there, but a lot of the names are folks who are dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Dusting off old files
</P>
<P>
   The murder of Wharlest Jackson is one of several unresolved
cases from the bloody, fractious days of the civil rights movement
now being reinvestigated by local police chiefs, district attorneys
and sheriffs. At least seven cases, four in Mississippi, two in
Alabama and one in Louisiana, have been reopened in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   The renewed interest is due in large part to the 1994 trial and
conviction of Byron De La Beckwith for the murder of Medgar Evers
31 years earlier in Jackson. It was Beckwith's third trial for the
slaying: He was tried twice in the 1960s, but both juries
deadlocked. Decades later, evidence surfaced that Beckwith had
tampered with the all-white juries.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last summer, a jury of blacks and whites in Hattiesburg
convicted former Ku Klux Klan leader Sam Bowers of ordering the
1966 fatal firebombing of Vernon Dahmer's home. Dahmer, a voting
rights activist, died protecting his family from carloads of
Klansmen who burned down his house. Another Klansman will go on
trial this year on charges of participating in the murder.
</P>
<P>
   As Beckwith and Bowers, both in their 70s, spend their golden
years behind bars in state prisons, district attorneys and police
chiefs, some too young to remember the '60s, are dusting off old
files, hunting out suspects and trying to jog the memories of
witnesses in other unresolved cases.
</P>
<P>
   Huff was a senior in high school when Wharlest Jackson's truck
blew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't fully understand the situation,'' said Huff, who
added that he took little interest in civil rights issues because
he was too busy ``doing schoolwork and chasing girls.'' But he
remembers that it was a ``tense, turbulent time'' in his hometown
and in the state as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 40 slayings listed on the civil rights memorial in
Montgomery, only two resulted in a first-degree murder conviction
at the time. Several more have been prosecuted in recent years, but
many crimes against civil rights workers remain unpunished, not to
mention countless murders of black people not involved in the
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many people killed _ lynched, hit in the head,
thrown in rivers by white people who had all the power and just
didn't care,'' said Morris Dees of the Southern Poverty Law Center
in Montgomery. ``They just killed them because they were black. My
attitude is you should look at these cases not as simple murder
cases. It was a crime against a whole class of people, like the
Holocaust. You should pursue these cases forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The convictions of Beckwith and Bowers convinced local
prosecutors that such trials are feasible, even with dead witnesses
and lost evidence. And the convictions encouraged the families of
victims to pressure local authorities to reopen cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``That can only come about because of the civil rights
movement,'' said David Ingebretsen, director of the Mississippi
chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union. ``Because blacks won
the right to vote and won the right to sit on juries, they now have
the power to pressure district attorneys to try these cases. That's
what people like Vernon Dahmer died for.''
</P>
<P>
   A fatal accident?
</P>
<P>
   Ollie Mae Brown sits in her small house near downtown Jackson
and waits for justice. She is 80, and surrounds herself with photos
of her four children and her many grandchildren. She takes a
picture of her son Benjamin down from the wall behind the
afghan-covered sofa.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get to talkin' about it, it gets me upset,'' she says
when asked about May 11, 1967, the night her son was shot in the
back.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Brown was an outspoken civil rights worker who led
protests and boycotts even in high school. His death was written
off by the Jackson police as accidental, caused by a stray bullet
meant to be fired into the air to disperse a protest at Jackson
State University. His mother says Brown wasn't involved in the
protest that night; he was walking to his apartment after buying
his pregnant wife a sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   Some witnesses say that not all the police were firing into the
air, but that some put their guns to their shoulders and took aim
at the protesters. But authorities never identified the shooter.
Ollie Mae Brown filed a lawsuit against the city, but because the
police wouldn't release the investigation records, the suit went
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 32 years later, at the request of Jackson City Council, the
city police are re-investigat-
</P>
<P>
   ing Brown's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be glad if they do,'' his mother says. ``I didn't think
it was an accident.''
</P>
<P>
   She remembers that her son often was chased home from his job by
police officers who were just ``mean'' and who, she said, didn't
like his working to better himself.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers her neighbors knocking on her door on May 11,
saying, ``Mrs. Brown, Ben got shot.'' He died a day later, on his
21st birthday. She has said that no one from the city ever came to
her and apologized for her son's death, or even offered an
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was supposed to go to college that fall,'' Brown says. ``I
just want justice, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jackson police say that, so far, they have turned up very
little evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guys are re-interviewing the witnesses they can find to see
if they can find anything not found in previous investigations,''
said Deputy Chief Eddie Wilson. One suspect, a state trooper, is
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Killed by the Klan
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, Michael Schwerner, a 24-year-old Cornell University
graduate, and his wife, Rita, went to Meridian, Miss., to join the
civil rights struggle. As Schwerner, Mississippi native James
Chaney, 21, and Andrew Goodman, 20, of New York were driving home
from the remains of Mount Zion Methodist Church, which had been
burned down by the Klan because of the congregation's civil rights
activities, they were stopped by a sheriff's deputy. They were
handed over to Klansmen, who killed all three and buried them on a
Klansman's farm near Philadelphia, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   It took six weeks of intense searching by a huge team assembled
by the FBI to recover the bodies. The case _ which was the subject
of the 1988 movie ``Mississippi Burning'' _ attracted national
attention and led to the arrests of 21 Klansmen and lawmen,
including Neshoba County Sheriff Lawrence Rainey. Seven Klansmen
were found guilty of federal civil rights violations; Deputy
Sheriff Cecil Price was convicted and sentenced to six years.
Rainey and several others were acquitted. Sam Bowers, now in prison
for Vernon Dahmer's murder, served time in a federal prison from
1968 to 1976 for civil rights violations in the deaths of
Schwerner, Chaney and Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   But the state of Mississippi never charged anyone with those
murders.Some of the Klansmen are dead, but some survive, and
Schwerner's widow, Rita Schwerner Bender, has been pressing the
local district attorney to reopen the case. In January, District
Attorney Ken Turner requested the original FBI files and the
federal court transcript from the 1967 trial.
</P>
<P>
   If arrests and a trial result from a new investigation, it
probably would receive even more national attention than the
Beckwith trial. Another case _ that of four girls who died in the
1963 bombing of the Sixteenth Street Baptist Church in Birmingham _
would also capture the nation. Only one man, a Klansman named
Robert Chambliss, went to prison for that bombing, and that wasn't
until 14 years after the fact. It is widely held that at least four
men, and maybe more, were involved in planting the dynamite. The
case was reopened more than a year ago, and a grand jury has been
hearing evidence.
</P>
<P>
   There is a legal pitfall to pursuing these cases, Dees said. If
the defendant can prove that his rights to a speedy trial have been
violated, the case could be thrown out. That defense didn't work in
the Beckwith and Bowers cases, because they were tried shortly
after the murders. Any delay in seeing justice served was caused by
their own tampering with their juries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big difference between having a hung jury and having
no trial at all,'' Dees said. ``Maybe they didn't try some of these
people out of prosecutorial prejudice or because they knew they
couldn't get a conviction. If that is the case, is there a good
enough reason to retry them now? I'd like to see them all convicted
and in jail until they die, but there are legal realities.''
</P>
<P>
   Learning from painful past
</P>
<P>
   Bender, Schwerner's widow, who remarried and is now a Seattle
lawyer, said that while it's painful to dig up the past, it's
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many years now I have heard people in high positions in
Mississippi say, `That was then and this is now and we have to move
on,' '' she said. ``Then I think about (Senate Majority Leader)
Trent Lott (R-Miss.) and how he is involved with what can only be
described as the reconstructed white Citizens Council _ and I say,
wait a minute.'' (Lott has had many dealings with the Council of
Conservative Citizens, a group accused of racist leanings that is
considered to be the modern version of the Citizens Council, an
unabashedly racist group of the '60s.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the people who would rather forget need to come to terms
with things that continue to happen that, in their own ways,
encourage violence,'' Bender continued. ``The Citizens Council
never got its own hands dirty _ it just created an atmosphere that
allowed the Klan to flourish.''
</P>
<P>
   Although race relations remain a central issue in Mississippi
and elsewhere, everyone agrees that things are better than they
were 30 years ago. Huff is very concerned that outsiders not see
his city, famous for its plantation homes and Old South festivities
centered on the spring pilgrimage, as racist. ``Natchez is not the
Old South anymore,'' he said. ``We're a very open-minded
community.''
</P>
<P>
   The town's new convention and visitors bureau has a black woman
on the staff whose sole job is to ensure that African-American
history and heritage are documented and publicized, Huff said.
</P>
<P>
   At the local tire plant where Wharlest Jackson worked, workers
are still protesting, but for a different cause: A new company has
taken over the plant and wants to quash the local union. Workers
picketed outside in a light rain on a recent afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're opening up all the old murder cases, aren't they?''
asked employee Willie Singleton, 54, who marched outside the metal
fence. ``That's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bender said, the only way to learn from mistakes is to
keep talking about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have recently become more convinced that these murders are
unfinished business and we shouldn't let it go,'' she said. ``This
is national unfinished business _ if we are to learn from our past,
we can't ignore our past.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rochell Konigsmark writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
