<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1950 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LADIES-SUNDAYSCHOOL20     02-19 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADIES-SUNDAYSCHOOL20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The fellowship that wouldn't die
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The fellowship is as sweet as the iced tea around the
long table at Butch's Chicken House in Jonesboro on the second
Thursday of the month.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the Ladies' Bible Class of Mountain View Baptist
Church gathers for an evening out together.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that their church is defunct and their town
disappeared, literally eaten up by Atlanta's Hartsfield
International Airport almost 20 years ago. Two or three dozen of
them, their husbands and other former members of their church drive
in from across south metro Atlanta determined to keep the spirit of
the Sunday school class alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that happened happened at church,'' says Louise
Brown, 74, former lunchroom manager of the old College Park High
School, who now lives in Union City (Ga.). ``We raised all our
children there _ all of us. Everything centered around the church.
We all feel more like brothers and sisters than friends.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a close-knit church up there,'' says Geraldine
Underwood, 72, an Avon cosmetics saleswoman in Riverdale (Ga.).
Underwood lived in Hapeville (Ga.) but attended church in Mountain
View (Ga.). ``A lot of the old families were right there. You
didn't dare say anything about one person, because they might be
related to another one.'' She is now a member of Poston Road
Baptist Church in Jonesboro (Ga.), a congregation established in
1981 from a remnant of Mountain View.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody looked after each other's children,'' says Marjorie
Hood, 75, a retired executive secretary who moved to Mountain View
as a bride 57 years ago. ``Everybody knew everybody and knew
everybody's business, which could be good and could be bad.'' Hood
now lives in Riverdale.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain View, about a 1-square-mile area on the north edge of
Clayton County, was chartered in 1949 as a town and in 1956 as a
city, and was home to about 2,000 people. It was dissolved in the
late 1970s by the Georgia General Assembly upon the recommendation
of the Clayton delegation, which branded it ``a blight on Clayton
County'' because of feuding and corruption in local government. At
the time, Mountain View had legal sales of beer and wine while the
rest of the county was dry.
</P>
<P>
   The death knell of the community was already sounding, in the
form of noise from the jet planes of Atlanta's rapidly expanding
air traffic. Families on the west side of Old Dixie Highway and the
railroad tracks went first, when about 400 homes were bought out
with $16.5 million in federal and local funds in a land acquisition
project that began about the time the city's government ended. In
the wake of their departure, businesses closed and most of the few
remaining residents from the east side followed.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, the former city officially became a part of
Hartsfield when work crews literally dug up part of the area for
fill dirt for runway extension.
</P>
<P>
   The community of Mountain View, which took its name from the
view of Stone Mountain (Ga.) possible on clear, sunny days, long
predated the town's incorporation _ as did the Baptist church,
which was incorporated in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   Hazel Green of Rex (Ga.), a retired hairstylist from the old
Davison's Department Store and now in her 80s, was 15 when she
moved to Mountain View.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a church there then,'' she says. ``Then, we
finally built a church there and everybody began to move their
membership to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Jarrett, 76, moved to Mountain View with her husband in
1955 and helped run his construction business from their home.
``The people there were so friendly,'' she says. ``You felt like
the whole church was just a family.''
</P>
<P>
   As in Sunday schools in previous decades, men and women were in
separate classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, I think there's things you'd like to discuss
that you wouldn't discuss in a coed class,'' says Jarrett. In the
Ladies' Bible Class, she says, ``I kind of felt like all of them
were sisters to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's mother, sister and mother-in-law died while she was a
part of the class at Mountain View. ``They were the most caring
people you would ever find anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   By the fall of 1980, the women and their families were
scattering to about a dozen different churches.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 25, 1980, the women's Sunday school class met in Helen
(Ga.) to talk about how to maintain their friendship. Minutes show
that they voted to organize as the Former Mountain View Club, meet
monthly, and charge dues of 50 cents a month, or $6 a year.
</P>
<P>
   They elected Louise Brown's husband, Walter, former postmaster
of Mountain View, as president of the group. Except for a few
months, he has continued in that office since the inception.
</P>
<P>
   Some things have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back when we were younger, we'd carry a covered dish,'' says
Underwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have barbecues, but the man died,'' says Brown.
</P>
<P>
   And dues have been raised to the whopping sum of $7 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the original members have been lost to death or
distance, and the remaining heads are grayer, but the essential
nature of the group remains the same. Each gathering includes
celebrations of birthdays, news of health and families, an
inspirational reading, prayer and lots of hugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I declare, people had rather miss most anything than that
meeting because we look forward to getting together,'' says Hood.
``I think we've done a pretty good job of keeping in touch. It just
shows you what kind of community Mountain View was.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
