<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1955 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPRESSIONISM21-COX     02-19 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPRESSIONISM21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Impressionists at the High Museum
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 21.
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Organizing an art exhibition is no ivory-tower
endeavor. After coming up with the concept and researching it comes
the real work: securing the works of art on the wish list.
</P>
<P>
   Curators, the men and women who organize the shows, usually hit
the road becoming, in the process, skilled diplomats. They barter.
They schmooze. They debate. They observe body language and gallery
installations. Sometimes they call upon official diplomats to help.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Dumas and Michael Shapiro were the diplomats behind
``Impressionism: Paintings Collected by Europeans Museums,''
opening Tuesday at the High Museum of Art, then traveling to art
museums in Seattle and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impressionism was a great moment in art history,'' said
Shapiro, the High's chief curator. ``People love it. I love it. (A
big impressionist exhibition) hadn't been done here. The trick was
how to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most viewers don't really care how it's done. They just want to
see the paintings. Most museums, however, are weary of lending
these works. Because of the wear and tear of travel and because
these pieces are often the reason people visit their museums,
administrators demand that there be a good reason, a contribution
to scholarship, to merit the loans.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out the premise was no easy task. Impressionism has
been dissected, feted and reassessed more than any period in art
history. In just the past year, American museums have organized
``Impressionism in Winter,'' ``Monet in the 20th Century,'' ``Mary
Cassatt'' and ``Degas in New Orleans.''
</P>
<P>
   One-man shows. Done to death. Seasonal themes. Too close for
comfort.
</P>
<P>
   The High decided to focus on the collectors, dealers and museums
brave enough to purchase and show impressionism in its early years.
The show would consist of examples of impressionist paintings
collected when it was a controversial thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   The museum hired London-based Dumas as guest curator. Now a
free-lancer, she has 20 years of museum experience and recently
organized an exhibition of Degas' art collection at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York. Next, the High developed a
wish list with help from Paris-based researcher Robert Parker, who
had access to European museum catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   Then the footwork began.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not enough to write a letter,'' explained Dumas in an
interview from London. ``You have to go and visit the directors and
curators.''
</P>
<P>
   Dumas always prepared carefully for each visit. She studied each
museum's collection so that she could talk intelligently about it.
If she was meeting with a museum person she didn't know, she found
out about him or her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most important,'' she says, ``is one's commitment to the show.
Essentially, you have to sell it.''
</P>
<P>
   She was happy to discover that many provincial museums were
cooperative because they were pleased by the attention paid to
their institutional history and by the prospect of American
exposure. But even then, there were complications.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked into a museum in Cambrai in northern France to see
that the painting by Marie Bracquemond that I wanted was the
centerpiece of a gallery installation of 19th-century French
portraits. The gallery would fall apart if it were removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The High does not have much in the 19th century to barter
with, so I called upon our co-sponsors and was able to work out an
exchange using a Corot and a Renoir from the Denver (Art) Museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro went along when he felt it would help and engineered
some creative exchanges. The High wanted ``Morning Awakening'' by
Eva Gonzales from the Kunsthalle Bremen in Germany. The Kunsthalle
had an interest in American painter Morris Graves, so Seattle's
agreement to lend some of its Graves holdings for a future
exhibition became the quid pro quo. In other cases, the High sent
its conservator to restore a painting and exchanged consulting
services for pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Henri Loyrette, director of the Musee D'Orsay in Paris, was
skeptical of the premise and engaged the High diplomats in a lively
debate _ in English and French _ on its scholarly merits. Shapiro
may have swayed him with some auxiliary arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I explained that cities outside of New York and Los Angeles
have sophisticated audiences who want to see these things and that
it was his duty to be a good lender. I told him Atlanta was an
up-and-coming center that made up in energy and initiative what it
lacked in its collection. We got six paintings.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro chalked up Oslo's generosity to ``the Gudmund Vigtel
factor.'' (The High's director emeritus is a native of Norway.)
</P>
<P>
   Not all their efforts were successful. The Hermitage in Russia
wouldn't lend. Sometimes a curator from another museum had already
been there. For example, nearly all the late Monets were spoken
for. Shapiro and Dumas stopped asking for any painting with snow.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, 39 museums lent works, and Shapiro is pleased with
the diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be an opportunity to learn about impressionism from
beginning to end. All the major figures are included, from the
early 1860s to postimpressionism. There are also lesser-known
artists and a cluster of women,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro considers the exhibition ``a win-win situation.''
Visitors who want to look no further than the pretty pictures can,
while others can gain a greater understanding of the movement. Says
the curator: ``It won't be the last, but I think it's the best
impressionist show that's ever been here.''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
