<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1956 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPRESSIONISM-FACTS21     02-19 0300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPRESSIONISM-FACTS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Celebrating the `radical' notion of spontaneity
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 21.
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It is difficult to fathom that impressionism, so
beloved in our time, was once so radical and appalling that a
cartoonist depicted a guard urging a pregnant woman not to enter
the galleries.
</P>
<P>
   We are so used to ``scandalous'' art that it takes bullwhips and
dead cows to raise any ire these days, but as Ann Dumas explains,
``Standards were so much more rigid then. It was easier to be
shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   The curator of ``Impressionism: Paintings Collected by European
Museums,'' Dumas recounted the ways that the impressionist defied
the status quo, as defined by academic painters such as Adolphe
Bouguereau. First, the impressionists ignored the existing
hierarchy of subject matter, which favored elevating content, such
as myth or history, in favor of focusing on ordinary life. Second,
they ignored the rules of technique, which emphasized drawing and
anonymous brushwork. They painted directly on the white canvas
instead of applying gesso (a plaster of Paris and glue mix used as
a base for paintings), thus introducing a much more vivid palette
than accustomed.
</P>
<P>
   But what was most disturbing was the brushwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they exhibited looked like an unfinished sketch to the
public,'' she says. ``It was free and spontaneous, a record of
immediacy and luminosity.''
</P>
<P>
   Many critics and visitors were enraged that an artist would
display something so raw. This exhibition celebrates the visionary
people who, early on, recognized its merit.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
