<HEADER>
A1960 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-SMART-ISUZU-ART-$     02-19 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-ISUZU-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'LL BRING OUT THE ALIEN IN YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21)  
 (af)  
 By JAMES G. COBB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imaginative product planners have morphed sedans with pickups,
off-roaders with minivans, military vehicles with station wagons.
Isn't it about time somebody crossed a sport utility with a UFO?
</P>
<P>
   From the looks of it, Isuzu has come close with its Vehicross. A
product of the Star Wars school of design, this stubby two-door
looks like nothing else on the road _ or on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   It could be a piece of construction equipment at a space colony
far, far away, or a giant version of the Transformers, those sci-fi
toys that change form if you twist this part and fold that one.
(``It's an off-road vehicle! It's a mutant flying crab! It's an
intergalactic robot warrior!'')
</P>
<P>
   Isuzu, a Japanese company that left the car market to
concentrate on trucks and sport utilities, calls the Vehicross ``a
techno-design suited to the new millennium.'' A concept vehicle at
the 1993 Tokyo auto show, the Vehicross went into production in
Japn in '97, when it was voted Japanese Car of the Year. It goes on
sale Monday in the United States; Isuzu will import fewer than
3,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Vehicross is a breath of nitrous oxide in a sport utility
market that was starting to take itself too seriously, but it's
good for more than a laugh. Indeed, it's quite competent.
</P>
<P>
   It manages to look both high (it has 8.4 inches of ground
clearance, and its styling makes it seem to hover) and low (the
steeply raked windshield sweeps onto the roof of a cabin that looks
flattened). The roof doesn't just look low, it (italics)is(end
italics) low; I smacked my head on it the first time I got in.
</P>
<P>
   Lower body panels are covered with black plastic affixed with
exposed screws. This thick unpainted band of polypropylene wraps
clear around from grille to cargo door.
</P>
<P>
   The styling quirks go on. The grille has two vertical teeth,
giving the front end the look of a shark after dental surgery.
Halogen headlamps gaze from clear covers with hornlike protrusions
at the top edge. Stare at this face for a while and you may start
to see the serpent from Eden.
</P>
<P>
   The inner part of the hood is matte black to reduce glare, and a
round carrier bulging from the cargo door houses the full-size
spare. There are thick ribs on the side doors, and the fuel filler
mimics a jetliner's. The 16-inch alloy wheels glisten, a clue that
the Vehicross is more likely to preen in Marina del Rey than go
prospecting in Death Valley.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that the Vehicross sends mixed messages, for
Isuzu considers it a combination of sport utility and sports car.
It would be easy to dismiss this as a delusion if the vehicle
didn't perform so well.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the sluggish acceleration, ponderous handling and
vague steering of a small sport ute, the Vehicross has a capable
3.5-liter V6, great road-holding and recirculating-ball steering
that is accurate and nicely weighted, with good feedback.
</P>
<P>
   The Isuzu embraces a curving country road, staying flat on
maneuvers where you'd expect a sport utility to list and stumble,
and it is an effortless cruiser that stays on track. With its
truckish body-on-frame construction, it's no Corvette, but it feels
substantial. On the Interstate it's more Grand Cherokee than Grand
Vitara.
</P>
<P>
   With a wheelbase of 91.8 inches _ an inch and a half shorter
than a Wrangler _ the ride can be rough. Rear and side visibility
is limited by thick pillars and a mirror view blocked by the big
spare carrier and the back-seat headrests.
</P>
<P>
   Isuzu calls its full-time four-wheel-drive system ``Torque on
Demand.'' It has a low gear range for severe conditions, but for
regular driving, the rear wheels get the power until sensors detect
slippage. Then, torque is redirected by varying degrees to the
front wheels. A pictogram indicates which wheels have the power,
and approximately how much.
</P>
<P>
   The setup handled snowy, hilly roads just fine, but it is not
invincible. The Vehicross managed to get stuck in a two-foot
snowbank in my driveway. Using low range and alternately using
forward and reverse gears, I was able to rock it free.
</P>
<P>
   With styling so unusual, not just any old furniture could go in
the cabin. The seats are fancy leather Recaro Trends with
recliners, adjustable thigh bolsters and a bold red-and-black color
scheme. (Exterior colors are black, silver or, for the ``Ironman
Edition,'' white.)
</P>
<P>
   The doors have inserts of plastic ``carbon fiber''; there is
more faux fiber on the too-small gauges.
</P>
<P>
   I had two problems with the Isuzu. Radio reception was abysmal;
just 20 miles from New York the seek function found only one FM
station _ a religious broadcast warning of damnation. And the
folding back seat was next to impossible to use.
</P>
<P>
   The problem isn't the seat, which is adequate, but a lack of
access to it. Scoot a front bucket all the way forward and there is
a tiny gap between the cushion and the door frame that one must
wriggle through. Only small children or supermodels will fit, and
even they can't crawl in gracefully because the door sill is so
high off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet is wriggling back out. Keep a cell phone handy in case
you get stuck and have to be extricated by the local fire
department.
</P>
<P>
   Contortions may not trouble the 20-somethings most attracted to
the Vehicross. (``It's really different _ that's what I like about
it,'' said one young man in a crowd that gathered around it at a
convenience store.) But the price could be a problem. At $28,000,
the Vehicross costs a lot more than a RAV4 or a Wrangler.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it answers those complaints that Japanese cars have no
character. The Vehicross has lots of personality, even if it
sometimes reminds you of your weird cousin Harold.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: Godzilla on wheels. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
