</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIGEST AND MARKETS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do-It-Yourself Investments, on Line
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't just shop at Home Depot,'' signs in the retailer's
760-odd stores will soon say. ``Own a piece of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot, based in Atlanta, is one of roughly 500 companies
that sell shares directly to investors _ both the initial stake as
well as subsequent investments and reinvestment dividends _ without
paying commissions to a broker.
</P>
<P>
   But in late December, Home Depot took its plan a step further by
offering it on its Web site (www.homedepot.com), making it easier
for Internet shoppers to buy its shares than to buy its hammers
(currently not available on line).
</P>
<P>
   The initial cost to participate is $5. Depending on when they
are received, orders are executed at that day's closing price or
the next trading day's close, is deducted from the buyer's bank
account, but proceeds from stock sales are mailed. Shareholders can
also review their accounts on line.
</P>
<P>
   Others companies are expected to follow suit with their own
on-line plans, with Compaq Computer now testing one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really the next logical step'' in the evolution of
dividend reinvestment plans, or Drips, said Charles B. Carlson,
editor of Drip Investor, a newsletter covering the plans.
</P>
<P>
   The aim at Home Depot, of course, is to turn do-it-yourself
home-improvers into do-it-yourself investors, and vice versa. ``We
think a good stockholder will make a good customer,'' said Larry
Menter, the company's corporate counsel and assistant secretary.
</P>
<P>
   _Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Attention Brokerage Firms: This Is Only a (Year 2000) Test
</P>
<P>
   More than 400 brokerage firms, along with securities markets and
clearing organizations, will gauge their Year 2000 computer
preparedness with an elaborate industrywide test of trading and
settlement procedures over six Saturdays in March and April.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities Industry Association, an industry trade group,
said the test would let the brokerage firms check for Year 2000
problems involving their computers' interaction with those of the
stock markets and clearing and settlement organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Computers will be converted to simulate particular dates near
the turn of the year. Simulated stock trading on March 6 will
substitute for Dec. 29, March 13 for Dec. 30, and so on through
April 10, which will substitute for Jan. 3, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The association did not disclose what the price of Yahoo would
be in its simulation.
</P>
<P>
   _Richard Teitelbaum &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
