<HEADER>
A1983 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      02-19 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Public aid for Oz park seems an odd move  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most questionable thing about the proposed Wonderful World
of Oz theme park is how its backers' quest for public-sector
support clashes with the traditional justification for such
subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   The rationale for socializing private investment risk has always
been the promise of jobs. The investors' reward from having
taxpayers share some risk has been deemed acceptable if sufficient
employment opportunities resulted to spur the economy.
</P>
<P>
   It's not merely the jobs created by the subsidized enterprise,
either. It's also the jobs created by the multiplier effect from
the investment. This extends to the construction industry and those
involved in providing the new enterprise with goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   The Oz project, though, finds itself in the paradoxical position
of seeking a public-private partnership when the area labor market
is excruciatingly tight. Therefore, it could be argued that if
government uses its powers of subsidy to help transform the Oz
project from development dream to community reality, there's a
potential for unintended consequences to do as much economic harm
as good.
</P>
<P>
   The area's unemployment rate hit an unprecedented low of 2.8
percent in December. Add to this the fact that the area labor force
participation is unusually high, and the local labor market is
likely a lot tighter than even the jobless rate indicates.
</P>
<P>
   So what happens if Oz backers succeed in getting the public
support needed to make the project a go? The first challenge will
be finding enough quality workers to build it. Once it's built,
where will its operators find enough workers to staff it?
</P>
<P>
   Simple economics suggests an already squeezed labor market will
get squeezed much harder. Wages will be bid up even higher than
they already are. This may be good for workers, but is it fair for
government to go out of its way to create a situation that boosts
labor costs for existing businesses already struggling to keep
enough employees?
</P>
<P>
   Don't misunderstand. It's not as though subsidies don't create
economic inequities even when conditions might justify government's
role in spurring development. This is one of the concept's most
objectionable aspects. Even so, exacerbating these inequities when
there's no compelling justification for government to do so raises
serious questions about the limits government should observe when
taking an economic development role.
</P>
<P>
   Another consideration is how circumstances have changed since
the Oz project surfaced in the early '90s. The economy was then in
the early recovery stages from the 1990-91 recession. Moreover, the
project's proposed site was in Wyandotte County, an area where
recovery could have been expected to lag the overall metropolitan
area.
</P>
<P>
   That was then. Now is now. Next month the U.S. economy enters
its ninth year of expansion, and the area work force is stretched
thinner than it ever has been. In the meantime, the proposed Oz
site has been shifted from Wyandotte County, which can always use a
boost, to Johnson County, one of the most dynamic county economies
in America.
</P>
<P>
   Given all this, it's interesting to ponder what gives Oz
developers so much apparent traction in their bid to partner up
with the taxpayers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 1721EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
