<HEADER>
A2012 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV2     02-19 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV21-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOOTHBRUSH, SANDING WILL GET TO MOLDING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, February 21, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. A paint stripper (5F5) took most of the varnish off four or
five chairs I'd like to refinish, but I can't get the varnish out
of grooves and molding. The stain on the chairs is in good shape
and flat, which means most of the varnish is gone. What else can I
do?
</P>
<P>
   FRANK HIGGINS, Dorchester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. A toothbrush will help get the varnish out the moldings,
using stripper as you go along. Or, fold sandpaper to sand off the
ingrained varnish. A hot air gun will soften the varnish so you can
pick it out. Guard against charring the wood, and do the work
outside.
</P>
<P>
   If the stain is intact and good looking, why not apply a satin,
polyurethane varnish? If you use an oil-based polyurethane, you may
not have to get rid of all the old varnish. This will not work with
water-base polyurethane, unless you take all the varnish off,
because the two types of varnish are not compatible.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer the oil-based because water-based is difficult to work
with and is less forgiving; if you don't keep the coats very, very
thin, the finish is likely to remain cloudy.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to remove the stain to achieve a lighter color or a
different color, you have to sand it off, then restain before
varnishing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a single-pipe steam heating system, which has begun to
bang like crazy. The banging seems to be originating in the boiler.
It all began when my wife overfilled the boiler. I tried reducing
the amount of water in the boiler without success. The banging is
not in the radiators themelves, so I don't think it is a matter of
water remaining in the radiator when the steam comes up. But I
can't figure out what is happening. Can you?
</P>
<P>
   FRUSTRATED CALLER
</P>
<P>
   A. I think you figured it out right, that there is too much
water in the system. Curing it is another matter. I think your only
choice is to contact a plumber-steamfitter. He should be able
adjust the amount of water to where it was before the overfilling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My vacation house in Maine is heated with hot water. Can I
replace the water in that system with an antifreeze when I leave
the house in winter? I drain the domestic water and have a freeze
alarm system, which alerts us to any threat of freezing.
</P>
<P>
   LIESE ELERIN, Dracut, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, you can, but you don't have to replace all water. Add
enough so the water will not freeze; I don't know the formula of
antifreeze in the system; a heating engineer can tell you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the caller who could not get the grout haze off his ceramic
tile floor, the handyman suggested rubbing with a dry cloth.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Steve Buscone of Wilmington, Mass. suggested: ``Use
sawdust. It works wonderfully. I did it as a kid when I helped my
father.''
</P>
<P>
   Good point, Steve Buscone; in fact, any kind of abrasion will
work, and a dry cloth or sawdust (it doesn't have to wet) will
provide just enough abrasion to remove that haze.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I put Homasote on my garage ceiling, but a kind of dusty
powdering is on it now. The garage is heated. Can I paint it to
keep that dusting down? If so, can I use exterior paint that I have
left over from a house job? Can I fill the joints with joint
compound and tape?
</P>
<P>
   D.R., Halifax, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Do not use exterior paints, especially since the garage is
heated, making the space more interior than exterior. A white,
solid color latex stain would be OK for this purpose despite its
being designed for outdoor use. Two coats will do nicely. Or, use a
white latex ceiling paint. Again, two coats. No primer is needed
with the stain or ceiling paint.
</P>
<P>
   Do not try to fill the joints in the Homasote. Cover them with a
wood trim. Homasote is a papier-mache (pressed paper) panel, and
has a rough finish. Any joint compound treatment would make the
joint covers smooth, and they will stick out like sore thumbs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My cesspool (not a septic tank) actually passed a Title 5
inspection, and I guess I am pleased. What kind of maintenance is
needed to keep it healthy and working well?
</P>
<P>
   MARY ELLEN KAIN, Lynnfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Just keep using it, and have it pumped every two years or so.
The interval of pumping depends on how many people use the system.
There is nothing you have to add to to the system; what goes in
naturally will keep it functioning properly. You could put in a
pound or so of baking soda once a month, and while this will do
some good, it is not essential.
</P>
<P>
   A cesspool differs from a septic tank in that it is simply a
hole in the ground, lined with stone; liquids seep out through the
walls into the leaching field, which is simply the ground around
the cesspool. A septic tank is a separate container, with pipes
leading to a specific leaching field.
</P>
<P>
   Cesspools are illegal to install; yours is grandfathered,
meaning that it existed before the law was enacted to outlaw them,
so you don't have to change it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
