<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2021 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-NEWS-CONFEREN     02-19 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NEWS-CONFERENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ASSESSES HIS IMPEACHMENT AND HIS WIFE'S CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, looking ahead to ``two good
years here,'' said Friday his 13-month struggle to survive the
sex-and-cover-up scandal shows that the American people will stand
by a president who sticks to business.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also told a White House news conference that he would
work to elect first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton to the Senate in
2000 if she decides to seek the seat being opened up by the
retirement of Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be strongly supportive of whatever decision she makes
and will do all I can to help, on this and any other decision, from
now on, just as she's helped me for the last 20- plus years,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president made the comments at a joint news conference with
French President Jacques Chirac following their discussions about
the showdown in Kosovo and U.S.-European trade disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Senate acquitted Clinton of perjury and
obstruction of justice last week following the first Senate
impeachment trial of an elected president in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, preparing for a post-impeachment summit with the
bipartisan congressional leadership early next week, said Americans
now expect both the Republican-led Congress and the White House to
``get back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The public expects ``us either not to have any destructive
feelings _ or if we do _ not to let them get in the way of our
doing their business,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that any of us can afford to let what has
happened get in the way of doing our best for our own people and
for the future,'' Clinton said. ``I'm going to do my very best to
do that, and I think that we should all discipline ourselves with
that in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``I expect to have two good years here.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the impeachment struggle triggered by his efforts
to cover up a sexual dalliance with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky shows that the American people will stand by their
chief executive if a president focuses on ``what you believe you
ought to do for the country and focus on it and work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The American people ``will respond if you work at it, and if
they sense that you're doing this for them,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Without elaborating, Clinton said that he had ``learned a lot of
personal lessons'' over the past year. He said he hoped that the
presidency had ``not been harmed'' by his experience, adding: ``I
can't say that I think this has been good for the country. But we
will see.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke shortly after his wife met in the White House
residential quarters with Moynihan to discuss whether to seek his
Senate seat in the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan said the two discussed voting patterns in New York and
other challenges to a potential Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Berry, Mrs. Clinton's press secretary, said the meeting
with Moynihan was a chance for Mrs. Clinton to listen and ``an
opportunity to explore thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   But Berry said Mrs. Clinton would take some time to reach a
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be like watching grass grow,'' Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   The president said she would do ``a fabulous job'' if elected.
</P>
<P>
   But he counseled patience.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has ``just been through a very exhausting year,''
Clinton said. ``I think some time needs to be taken here. I would
like to see her take some time... get some rest, listen to people
on both sides of the argument'' and then make her decision.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent poll in New York for the Senate race in 2000
shows Mrs. Clinton would defeat either of her most likely
Republican rivals _ New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani or former Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A Marist Institute poll completed Jan. 24 showed Mrs. Clinton
leading Giuliani 53 percent to 42 percent in a hypothetical match
up. The poll showed Mrs. Clinton leading D'Amato 57 percent to 38
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
