<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-GOVS-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP GOVERNORS ARE PARTY'S SHINING STARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Feb. 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Republican lawmakers on Capitol Hill
struggling to recover from low poll ratings, the nation's GOP
governors are riding a tidal wave of voter popularity as role
models for the party on Election Day 2000.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part the 31 Republican governors are a practical,
hard-nosed lot with state coffers awash in budget-surplus cash.
Their upbeat mood is in stark contrast to that of congressional
Republicans stung by their failed effort to oust President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that Republican governors enjoy a
popularity that many in Washington can only envy,'' said Clifford
May, communications director for the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   GOP Gov. Marc Racicot of Montana said in an interview that in
the public service arena, being a governor is ``the best job in
America. It puts you close to the people you serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Governors, he said, have to be practical and rely on common
sense. ``They have to produce results for the people they serve.''
He added that ``learning from our experience could be beneficial''
for GOP lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Racicot spoke as the Republican governors, along with their 17
Democratic and two independent gubernatorial colleagues, met here
for the annual four-day National Governors' Association meeting
that began Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Kettl, director of the LaFollette Institute of Public
Affairs at the University of Wisconsin, said statehouse success
stems from the hands-on, problem-solving nature of a governor's job
in contrast to Capitol Hill lawmakers' more nebulous task of
fighting policy wars.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton and the Republican Congress transferring power and
decision-making in many areas to states over the last several
years, ``states are becoming places where things have to happen.
... The governors have seized the possibilities and run with
them,''
</P>
<P>
   Racicot and other GOP governors such as George Pataki of New
York, George W. Bush of Texas, John Engler of Michigan and Tommy
Thompson of Wisconsin have been credited with making the Republican
vision of smaller-but-more-effective government a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after taking office in 1993, Racicot tried to win voter
approval for a 4-percent sales tax to eliminate a $200 budget
deficit. Voters turned him down by a 3-1 margin. So he cut
spending, which eventually produced a $22 million surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson started welfare reform in Wisconsin in 1987, nine years
before Congress approved national legislation limiting the time
recipients can receive aid and requiring most of them to go to
work.
</P>
<P>
   In one form or another, Bush, Pataki and Engler have all cut
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   For these Republican governors, however, achieving political
success has often entailed deviations from GOP orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   Engler of Michigan led the charge in 1993 to eliminate the use
of property taxes to fund education. But when schools faced a
budget shortfall up to $7 billion the following year, he got
Michigan voters to approve a 2-percentage-point hike in the state
sales tax. It was either that or a boost in the state income tax,
he told them.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who bills himself a ``compassionate conservative,'' lost a
battle in his first term to offset a $3 billion property tax cut
with a sales tax increase and a new tax on professional
partnerships including those of doctors and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   After that defeat, he used the state's budget surplus in 1997 to
lower property tax bills by $1 billion. Having won reelection last
year with 69 percent of the vote, he is now proposing a property
and sales tax cut of $2.6 billion. But he also wants to spend $3.6
billion to reimburse school districts for lost tax revenue, as well
as for higher teacher salaries and instructional programs.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has zig-zagged on spending and taxes. With a surplus of
about $2 billion, he called last month for a 1.8 percent spending
increase. Last year he pushed through a 13 percent budget increase,
principally for Medicaid and education _ and easily won a second
term.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Romer, general chairman of the Democratic National Committee
and, until last month, governor of Colorado, said,``You have a
different Republican Party for governors than you do for the House
and Senate. ... Republican governors win out there because they
have an ability to reach toward moderate voters while retaining
their (Republican loyalist) base.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of success has eluded GOP lawmakers in Congress, Romer
said, adding: ``Conservatives have a stranglehold on (Senate and
House members) that they don't have on the governors.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Hill Republicans are still trying to recover from their
political miscues in the impeachment debacle, from the government
shutdowns of 1995 and 1996 and from conservatives' charges that in
their budget agreements with Clinton in 1997 and 1998, they gave
too much to the Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
