<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2052 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     02-19 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV22-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TINKY WINKY FALLOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday Feb. 22)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I think the Rev. Jerry Falwell showed great courage when he
revealed in the National Liberty Journal that the purple Teletubby,
Tinky Winky, is gay.
</P>
<P>
   I have always suspected Tinky Winky was gay but I never told
anyone for fear I would be laughed at or made fun of.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aren't you a little old to be watching Teletubbies?'' is one
of the questions I feared being asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what do you expect of something named Tinky Winky? It's
not exactly a name you'd give to a professional wrestler, you
know,'' is another.
</P>
<P>
   But Falwell has demonstrated many times over the years that he
is not afraid of looking or sounding like a fool. While some people
may wonder why a man of his accomplishments (I still get all tingly
when I think of the time Falwell urged General Motors to withdraw
its sponsorship of the TV sitcom ``Ellen'' after the main character
revealed her homosexuality) would waste his time outing a cloying,
purple puppet that some of your more discerning 2-year-olds have
trouble stomaching, I think Falwell should be congratulated for his
courage and unwavering sense of purpose.
</P>
<P>
   While some conservative televangelists might have just said that
Tinky Winky is gay and let it go at that, Falwell took it one step
further: He offered proof. Not only is the name Tinky Winky
suspicious in itself, but there is the purple coloration. Purple is
the gay-pride color, which is something I did not know but Falwell
obviously did.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the matter of Tinky Winky's antenna. It is shaped
like a triangle. Triangle shapes are another symbol of gay pride,
which is something, again, that I did not know but Falwell
obviously did.
</P>
<P>
   And let us not forget for a minute the far from insignificant
matter of Tinky Winky's purse. Tinky Winky's spin doctors, of
course, denied that Tinky Winky carries a purse but described it,
instead, as a ``magic bag.'' This pathetic attempt at damage
control is unlikely to change anyone's mind about Tinky Winky's
sexual persuasion, least of all the Rev. Jerry Falwell.
</P>
<P>
   The sad thing about all of this is that by ``blowing the
whistle,'' so to speak, on Tinky Winky, Falwell has given the show
free publicity and may have unwittingly enhanced viewership as
curious people tune in in the sick hope of catching Tinky Winky and
Dipsy doing the dirty deed. (This is one example of what the
editorialists term the ``fallout'' of the Clinton scandal.)
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to say what, if any, effect this controversy will
have on the preschoolers who are the core of Tinky Winky's fan
base. Boys might learn that it is unwise to carry a purse when
appearing on national television, at least not during those times
when the Rev. Jerry Falwell is watching. Girls might think twice
about dyeing themselves purple (definitely a good thing) or about
doing up their hair in the shape of a triangular antenna (probably
a good thing).
</P>
<P>
   For parents, the lessons are more obvious. For one thing, you
should never, ever, under any circumstances, name your son or
daughter Tinky Winky. Also to be avoided are the names Dipsy,
Laa-Laa and Po, as these are the names of other Teletubbies on the
show who have come into contact, if you will, with the morally
challenged Tinky Winky.
</P>
<P>
   Parents should also avoid watching ``Teletubbies'' (not that big
a sacrifice, by the way) in case Tinky Winky and his friends are
putting out subliminal messages more nefarious than the usual ones
urging the purchase of sugary cereals and expensive toys.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Falwell did this nation a great service by outing Tinky
Winky. Now, if he could just get something on Barney, we'd be
eternally in his debt.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 1753EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
