u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      02-19 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Feb. 20, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, heavy snow fell in portions of western
North Carolina as a low-pressure system passed through the southern
Middle Atlantic states. Residual moisture on the western flank of
the low may bring a brief period of snow to eastern Virginia and
the Del Marva peninsula early Saturday morning before the low moves
well off the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, this same low will pass several hundred miles off the
New England coast. The projected path will bring the risk for snow
along the immediate coast, particularly across Cape Cod and the
Island. Farther inland, partly to mostly sunny skies will cover the
interior Northeast with chilly breezes from the north developing
during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   As cold air flowing southward from Canadian high pressure
gathers moisture in transit across the unfrozen Great Lakes, light
snow showers will form near the southern shores of the lakes. A
light accumulation of snow is possible in a few locations.
</P>
<P>
   Dry conditions will stretch across the South Saturday from the
Southwestern deserts to the Southeast. Skies will be partly to
mostly sunny throughout the region, though moistening onshore
breezes will cause clouds to increase near the Texas coast.
Abundant sunshine and comfortably warm air will cover Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Thickening clouds will yield to a steady rain over central and
northern California Saturday as a potent Pacific disturbance
approaches the West Coast. Rain will continue Saturday night with
heavy snow affecting the Sierras. Elsewhere, the Northwest will be
partly sunny and seasonably mild.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Erroneous Chill
</P>
<P>
   A state record minimum temperature of -55 that was recorded in
Allagash, Maine, on Jan. 14, was erroneous. The instrument was sent
to a testing facility where it was immersed in a special substance
that remains liquid at temperatures as low as -90. Its readings
were compared to laboratory thermometers that have an accuracy of
one-thousandth of a degree. The thermometer was found to be
increasingly inaccurate as lower temperatures were tested. At an
actual temperature of -38, the Allagash instrument read -55 causing
officials to disallow the apparent record chill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
