</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ In a joint news conference with
President Chirac of France, President Clinton declared that Serbian
leaders will be ``held accountable'' if peace talks on Kosovo
collapse and a NATO bombing campaign is needed. By Elizabeth
Becker.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA-ERGONOMICS (Washington) _ OSHA, the federal agency that
monitors the workplace, moves ahead with draft regulations to help
workers who face ergonomic difficulties. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-ENGINEERS (Northampton, Mass.) _ Smith College, in a bid
to help alter an imbalance and as part of its efforts to shift its
lingering white-glove image, will become the first women's college
to open an engineering department. Its board of trustees is
expected to approve the $12.5 million plan on Saturday with the
first engineering course to be offered in the fall. By Ethan
Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-PENALTY-BIAS (Lincoln, Neb.) _ An American Indian who was
adopted by Quakers and then killed two people and who now faces the
death penalty has become a national cause for Quakers who want his
life spared. He has been granted a stay of execution under a recent
amendment to the Nebraska constitution guaranteeing all Nebraska
citizens equal rights under the law. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ The trade deficit in goods and
services narrowed in December but widened to a record level in the
full year. December's deficit shrank to $13.8 billion from $15.3
billion in November. Exports declined 0.6 percent, reflecting
weaker foreign demand for industrial supplies and auto parts.
Imports fell 2.1 percent, partly because of lower oil prices. In
all of 1998, the deficit expanded to a record $168.6 billion, up
from the previous year's $110.2 billion, in a reflection of the
dollar's strength and the domestic economy's vigor. By David E.
Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   KURD-MANHUNT (Washington) _ The United States worked for four
months to help Turkey hunt down Abdullah Ocalan, the Kurdish rebel
leader, American officials said on Friday. American diplomatic
pressure backed by intelligence-gathering helped drive Ocalan into
an increasingly desperate search for refuge, the officials said. By
Tim Weiner.
</P>
