</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDURAS-MITCH-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN STORM-RAVAGED HONDURAS, MISSIONARIES CARRY STETHOSCOPES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Feb. 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEANNE RUSSELL  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAINEZ, Honduras _ Dr. Henry Moore comes from a world unlike
that of the Hondurans who walk hours to seek his care.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, with his sandpaper Texas drawl, is the first doctor to
visit the village of Lainez since Hurricane Mitch hit last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This won't hurt,'' Moore said in Spanish as he put his
stethoscope inside the thin cloth shirt of Marco Gabriel Gravis,
18.
</P>
<P>
   The young man stared at the foreign doctor with the rough,
gentle hands. His four siblings laughed as Moore demonstrated how
to say ``ahhh.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore sent the family away with aspirin, medicine for pinworms,
lice shampoo, vitamins and cough medicine. ``Adios, familia
buena,'' he said, thumping Marco on his back.
</P>
<P>
   For 14 years, Moore, 66, has traveled to remote hamlets in
Honduras as an Episcopalian medical missionary. He carries basic
remedies like aspirin and pills for diarrhea to peasants.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, he led several doctors and nurses from the San
Antonio area to Honduran subsistence farmers still reeling from
what has been called the worst natural disaster in the Western
Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   The average Honduran here in the southern mountains doesn't own
a bank account. Most cannot read. They farm to feed themselves. If
they could afford a car, they would drive on dirt roads.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the peasants carried babies in their arms for miles to
visit the American doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane called Mitch pummeled the tropical country from
Oct. 25 to Nov. 2, taking more than 5,000 lives and leaving 2
million people homeless. It wiped out the corn and bean fields that
are staples.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of other people died in El Salvador, Honduras and
Nicaragua. The hurricane caused some $4 billion in damage in
Honduras and $1 billion in Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until early February that Moore could arrange for a
13-member medical team to go to El Paraiso, a Honduran state along
the Nicaraguan border. Every day for five days, the team weaved
along winding roads to treat hundreds of villagers suffering from
parasites, head colds and aching bones.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of lives were lost in the cities of Danli and El
Paraiso, although the body count was lower than in the Honduran
capital of Tegucigalpa and along the northern coast. The hurricane
lacerated fields that produce the region's only cash crop, coffee.
The fields will not produce coffee beans until four years after
they are replanted.
</P>
<P>
   Honduran subsistence farmers have tilled the land for centuries,
fashioning corn into tortillas and harvesting beans. The hurricane
left them without food. They won't plant again until September.
</P>
<P>
   Boiling water and washing hands for personal hygiene could
eliminate chronic health problems.
</P>
<P>
   But, Moore said, firewood is costly, and so is soap. The
hurricane exacerbated the poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they weren't badly hurt in the mountains, but we felt
we should say we love you and we know you've been hurt, and we'll
be with you until this is resolved,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the border region of Honduras was battered by the
civil war between the Sandinistas and contras in Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived the war,'' said Alejandro Chirinos, an Episcopal
deacon in the city of El Paraiso. He recalled a period of five
years when children stumbled on hand grenades, mines blew up pickup
trucks and shells fell on the school where he taught.
</P>
<P>
   ``I escaped from the contras and Mitch fell on me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore and his team climbed a dusty road one day to Lainez. The
town is little more than a clearing rimmed with pine trees, home to
84 families, an Episcopal church, a school, a community center and
a sloped soccer field.
</P>
<P>
   Delmi Sagrario Rodriguez and her children hopped in Moore's
pickup truck after walking two hours from her hillside home to see
the American doctors. Her other option was to walk two more hours
to the small city of Yuscaran.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors in Yuscaran's public clinic might prescribe a medicine
for her infant's recurring cough. But, Rodriguez said, the cost
would be beyond her means. She pays the Episcopalian team of four
doctors, three nurses and six helpers five lempiras, about 35 cents
per child.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's diocese, the Episcopal Diocese of West Texas, raised and
sent $30,000 in aid to Honduras. Moore raised an additional $5,444
and spent $800 of his own money for his 13-member brigade, $3,771
for medicine and the rest for plane tickets.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd gathered one day at a community center in Las Crusitas
to wait for the American doctors and nurses. Nearly 730 people live
in hills a 90-minute drive on a dirt road from Yuscaran and the
nearest doctor. On Feb. 9, the Episcopalians treated 232 people,
then braved the potholed and unlighted road after sunset.
</P>
<P>
   Moore began his medical missionary work 14 years ago, after Leo
Frade, the Episcopalian Bishop of Honduras, spoke at St. Andrew's
Episcopal Church in Seguin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was called to do it,'' Moore said. He laughed. ``I thought
the message was very clear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
