<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2111 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEARS-FASHION-$ADV21-     02-19 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEARS-FASHION-$ADV21-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION EDITORS MEET SEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BOB MORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once upon a misty Tuesday evening in February, a
limousine was cruising along the far reaches of Brooklyn,
transporting two impeccably stylish, impeccably thin women in very
high heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir, do you really know where you're going?'' Marin Hopper,
the fashion director of Elle, asked the driver. Unconvincingly, he
said that he did, but that it would take 20 minutes more to get
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does anybody know where we are?'' Nina Garcia, Elle's senior
fashion market editor, asked plaintively. Her question was left
unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   The editors knew they were going to the Sears at the Kings Plaza
mall in Brooklyn, and that was all. Of course, they'd never been to
the Sears at the Kings Plaza mall. Ms. Garcia, in fact, a Latin
American with socialite-straight blond hair and Army-green Daryl K
pants, had never been to any Sears, ever. ``Is it very large?'' she
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' replied Ms. Hopper, the daughter of Dennis Hopper.
``But there's no designer floor like at Macy's. That's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hopper and Ms. Garcia were two of 20 fashion editors
recruited by Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. for a program that set them up as
personal shoppers for a young bank teller who has been off welfare
for a year. Sears found the teller through Dress for Success, a
nonprofit organization that accepts and distributes donations of
professional clothing for low-income women looking for work.
Besides paying for two outfits for each of the 12 women in its own
program, Sears is donating $100,000 to Dress for Success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting to be meeting a bank teller,'' said Ms. Hopper,
who had just returned from the couture shows in Paris, where she
was excited to see Valentino's new embroidered mules for fall.
``Elle's philosophy has always been to keep it real, but we do lots
of fantasy, so this is a chance to get back to the real side of
things.'' Very real, indeed. ``It must be hard to work behind one
of those windows in a bank all day long,'' she mused. ``The
lighting alone is enough to die.''
</P>
<P>
   As they cruised through Brooklyn, they discussed looks for their
``client,'' who, they had been advised, preferred neutrals.
(``Well, we could do white,'' Ms. Hopper said. ``White is
seasonless now.'') They took calls on their cell phones. (``I don't
know why we're going to Sears and not Target, but, OK, I'll check
out the fuzzy slippers,'' Ms. Hopper told a Hollywood caller.) They
even pondered the notion of what ``work appropriate'' means in this
supercasual moment. Then, as they were starting to wonder if they
would ever get there, a big red Sears sign appeared through the
mist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow!'' Ms. Garcia said. ``It's huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Old Navy and Target are on the style trail, it isn't
surprising that Sears has become trend-friendly, too. ``They have
to, or they're going to lose all their customers,'' said Stan
Herman, the president of the Council of Fashion Designers of
America, who was also around when Halston's name was bought and
democratized by J.C. Penney. ``That didn't work because that was
still a time when fashion had to look expensive,'' Herman said.
``Now, everything is coming from the streets and from sportswear.''
</P>
<P>
   Sears may have been one of the last lower-end chains to get with
it, but in the last few years it has been trying to get with it in
a big way, by hiring fashion designers to ``interpret'' the key
trends in any given season and consulting with color and fashion
forecasters. As a result, apparel sales have increased by 50
percent since 1996, said Linda Blakely, a Sears spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the new interest the fashion world has in stretch and
synthetics, however, Sears' old reputation for uninspired,
budget-priced clothes persisted. Something clever had to be done to
get the word out.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Fashion Takes Action, the store's program for pairing
style editors with women ``in transition.'' It also presented a
fashion week photography exhibition, portraits of Dress for Success
star clients _ former prisoners, homeless women and abuse victims
who now have good jobs. ``We have been wanting to get fashion
editors into our stores for a while now,'' said Lana Cain-Krauter,
the senior vice president for women's apparel. ``So this was the
perfect way to do it. It also gives us a presence in New York
during fashion week.''
</P>
<P>
   Opportunistic, sure. But in this day of diminished government
spending for social services, who would dare criticize Sears for
kicking in?
</P>
<P>
   Inside the store at Kings Plaza, Ms. Hopper and Ms. Garcia were
introduced to Rose Grant, a shy young mother of three from Crown
Heights. She was wearing an ochre-colored suit that was a little
large for her diminutive frame, and she seemed slightly overwhelmed
by the photographers, publicity agents, Sears executives and others
who had been at the store all day, monitoring the coming and going
of editors like Renee Sheffey-Brown of Essence and Andre Leon
Talley of Vogue. (Talley had begun shopping with his client in the
handbag department, declaring, ``It's all about the bag!'' and
ended up putting her in silver lame and black velvet.)
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Grant, a survivor of domestic violence, quietly
confirmed that she had just received a promotion at her bank, the
concerned circle around her exploded into supportive applause.
Then, after a photo op, it was time to get down to business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let the games begin,'' someone said.
</P>
<P>
   And they did, although it wasn't much fun at first. ``We
understand you don't like colors,'' Ms. Hopper was saying as she
and Ms. Garcia took Ms. Grant on a quick tour of the store. ``But
what about just a shot of color, maybe in a coat or jacket?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Grant was slow to respond. ``I can't really wear color,''
she said. ``It's too much of a power move.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hopper persisted. ``But you just made a power move. You were
promoted.'' Ms. Grant did not reply.
</P>
<P>
   Coming upon a display of fuzzy slippers in neon colors, Ms.
Hopper exclaimed, ``Look, Rose! Tweetybird slippers! Color! These
are so you at work!'' Ms. Grant, who reads Elle but does not
traffic in fashion irony, seemed to fold up into herself in
confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just kidding,'' Ms. Hopper said remorsefully. Quietly, they
moved on.
</P>
<P>
   After Ms. Grant fell madly in love with the black suede boots
that Ms. Hopper seized for her (``Always start with the shoes,''
she declared, ``and build from there''), the operation picked up
speed. While Elizabeth Crow, the editor in chief of Mademoiselle
shopped nearby with a woman from East New York who now works for
Dean Witter/Morgan Stanley, Ms. Hopper and Ms. Garcia went digging
around like two ferrets on speed. In their quest for just two great
outfits, they were turning the entire store upside down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very Michael Kors,'' Ms. Garcia said of a cardigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``So directional,'' Ms. Hopper said of a skimpy camisole in
lipstick colors. ``Can you wear it to work?'' Ms. Grant thought so,
probably.
</P>
<P>
   ``This denim is so Helmut,'' Ms. Garcia said. ``Even I could
wear it.'' They swooped and scooped, declared and despaired. Love
this! Having a Prada moment here! So modern! Army green! This
stretch is genius! The store, in fact, was a real trend pond. There
were fashion colors, butterfly motifs, cargo pockets, gray options,
twin sets and lots and lots of pleats. ``Actually, I'm over
pleats,'' Ms. Hopper said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As she watched the clothes accumulate on a rolling rack, Ms.
Grant said very little. Mostly she nodded. It worried Nancy Lublin,
the earthy, hands-on founder of Dress for Success, who had put Ms.
Grant in her first suit for work a year ago. ``Listen, Rose, if you
don't like something, you can tell them,'' she said from the side.
``It's your choice. You've got to wear these clothes to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Grant didn't say anything. Ms. Hopper did. ``We've asked her
every single time,'' she said abruptly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just pulling everything for now,'' Ms. Garcia added.
``We'll edit later.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Grant, who had never really thought of shopping at Sears in
the first place (``I'm sort of a snob, and I thought it would be
all polyester stuff,'' she said), was actually starting to have
faith in her dogged personal shoppers. As they scurried around in
their Manolo Blahniks and Jimmy Choo heels for four hours, without
even stopping for a sandwich, she relaxed and let them do all the
work. When there weren't jackets in her size downstairs, they
stormed the boys' department upstairs and found a sensationally
seasonless white blazer.
</P>
<P>
   As the night went on, and more and more excellent options turned
up, Ms. Grant's smiled widened. She had just been promoted at work.
She had free child care for her three sons (through the
professional women's networking group run by Dress for Success).
Now, these two unimaginably glamorous editors had stepped off the
masthead of a magazine that she read, and they were going all out
for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a dream come true,'' she said. ``These women really
understand what I like.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was in 1996 that Ms. Lublin, then a New York University law
student, inherited $5,000 from a great-grandfather and started
Dress for Success out of her apartment. When The New York Times
published an article about the organization last winter, things
exploded. Beautiful clothes came pouring in. Candice Bergen even
sent a couple of Murphy Brown suits. Since then, 2,000 women have
come to a church basement on West Fourth Street to pick out gently
used or new suits, new shoes (courtesy of Coach and Nine West) and
an invitation to join a networking group for a new life. There are
now 25 Dress for Success programs in this country and Canada, and a
Web site: www.dressforsuccess.org.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were a for-profit organization, we'd be on the stock
exchange,'' said Ms. Lublin, 27, who oversees the local and
national effort, and is organizing a benefit masquerade ball and
auction on March 13 at the Waldorf-Astoria. Although a fashion
outsider, she is impressed by the generosity of the fashion world.
``Eileen Fisher invites two of our clients to her store in SoHo to
shop every week,'' she said. ``She does that quietly, without
asking us to promote it at all. Ferragamo dumped a ton of clothes,
shoes and jewelry on us, too. They asked for nothing in return.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fisher and Ferragamo, of course, aren't alone in quietly
doing good for New York. Not long ago, Norma Kamali set up a
T-shirt business with the students of Washington Irving High
School. The Gap has a mentoring program for students as well. Bobbi
Brown, the makeup mogul, has adopted one shelter, and Lane Bryant
has adopted another. Donna Karan and Stan Herman, meanwhile, have
designed spiffy uniforms for business improvement district workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' Herman said, ``the city has to look good to feel
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking and feeling very good at Sears, Rose Grant was ecstatic
with her new day wear _ a black-leather-jacket-driven look that had
both spunk and class and a flattering brown and burgundy ensemble
that was as directional as it was professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so you,'' said Ms. Garcia, who was slumped over in a
dressing room as if she'd just given birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the new way of dressing for work,'' Ms. Hopper added.
</P>
<P>
   Later, near the door, Ms. Grant was speaking to a friend who had
just been dressed by Mademoiselle. ``I learned so much tonight,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like what?'' her friend asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burgundy and brown, girl,'' Ms. Grant replied. ``It's a
combination I never thought I'd wear.''
</P>
<P>
   Riding home, the two exhausted fashion editors felt triumphant
about teaching someone not to be so afraid of color. ``She was
nervous at first, but in the end, she really got it,'' Ms. Garcia
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hopper, who thinks that brown is having a resurgence and
will be important again for fall, nodded. ``It's really fun to get
someone excited by showing them something new,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what fashion is all about, isn't it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 1857EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
