A2125 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-WATER-HEALTH20-C     02-19 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-WATER-HEALTH20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Can't beat the tap
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Remy del Rosario wants a sip of refreshing water,
she gets it the old-fashioned way _ at the sink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drink eight to 10 glasses a day and I wouldn't do that if it
wasn't safe,'' says del Rosario, Atlanta's Commissioner of Water.
``The tap water we produce is the best. Tap water is tested every
day (for contaminants), sometimes every hour. It's free of bacteria
and it's disinfected. Why would I waste my money buying bottled
water?''
</P>
<P>
   OK, as the city czar who oversees the daily disbursement of 125
million gallons of water, she may be biased. But del Rosario sees
no reason for Americans to be spending $4 billion annually on
packaged water.
</P>
<P>
   Though most Americans buy bottled water because they think it
contains fewer impurities than tap water, that may not be the case.
</P>
<P>
   Tap water is closely monitored by the Environmental Protection
Agency and the city water department. The site and source of
bottled water, on the other hand, could go three years between
inspections by its regulatory agency, the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, deadly bacteria still sneaks into tap water. In
1993, 69 people died from cryptosporidium in Milwaukee's water.
</P>
<P>
   Chlorine and fluoride are the two substances most often cited by
health experts as differences between tap and bottled water.
</P>
<P>
   Municipal water systems use chlorine to stop the growth of
bacteria. Bottled water contains no chlorine, unless its source is
not a mountain spring or a deep well. One study found that the
source of 25 percent of bottled water actually came from the same
place as tap water: municipal water systems. Many bottlers then
filter and purify the city water, as Coca-Cola plans do to with its
new product, Dasani.
</P>
<P>
   While health-conscious trendy types clutch bottled water like a
baby clings to a pacifier, their avoidance of tap water may come
back to bite them _ in their teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Bottled water contains no fluoride, a fact that's beginning to
worry dentists because consumption doubled in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   When fluoride was added to the country's water supply decades
ago, the rate of cavities decreased by 25 percent, said Dr. Susan
Muller, an oral pathologist at Emory University School of Medicine.
``What's being hypothesized is that with the increased use of
bottled water it could potentially increase the cavity rate
again,'' said Muller.
</P>
<P>
   Some water companies have added fluoride to their products for
children. But fluoride is not just for kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps adults as well, assuming they have all their natural
teeth,'' said Dr. Scott Presson of the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention. Coca-Cola's new product will not contain fluoride,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
