</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-WATER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke dives into bottled water market with Dasani
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Coca-Cola Company would like you to know that
Dasani is not a knock-off of an Italian fashion line or a spicy
Indian dish. It's water.
</P>
<P>
   The company confirmed Friday that it is entering the U.S.
bottled water market, a $4.3 billion segment that grew faster last
year than the much larger market for carbonated soft drinks. Coke's
noncarbonated water will be called Dasani _ a word made up to fit
the product. The drink will be on shelves by midyear in the United
States and Canada. The company declined to discuss specifics of
which markets it would roll out in first or what sales goals it has
set.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the distribution capability of Coca-Cola and
bottlers will help to quickly make the product available across the
country,'' company spokeswoman Polly Howes said.
</P>
<P>
   The water will come from municipal water systems. But the
company said it will further clean the water and add minerals. The
final product won't have fluoride. Dasani will be packaged in light
blue bottles in 20-ounce, 1-liter and 1.5-liter sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Coke said it test-marketed the name Dasani to see how it would
go over with consumers. ``It conveyed a lot of the attributes we
want to build around the brand as far as its pureness, its
crispness,'' Coke's Howes said. ``It's something we can build the
meaning in connection with the product itself.''
</P>
<P>
   She quoted Coke Chairman and CEO M. Douglas Ivester as jokingly
saying the product was named after the ``Roman god of water.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting the right name for a consumer product is always
important. When it comes to bottled water, it's particularly
crucial, says Ira Bachrach, president of NameLab Inc., a San
Francisco, Calif.-based company that has come up with names such as
Acura, Geo, The Olive Garden and Slice.
</P>
<P>
   ``All water is basically the same. It's the packaging. It's an
idea,'' Bachrach said. ``The name is even more important than it is
for colas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bachrach praised the name, adding that his company has named
three competing brands of water on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Naming professionals size up names with the discrimination that
connoisseurs use to assess vintage wines.
</P>
<P>
   Bachrach finds in Dasani ``smooth rolling sounds which suggest
it seems to mean pleasant but not aggressive flavor.'' It is also
``suggestively Italian.''
</P>
<P>
   Naming consultant James Dettore, president of the Miami-based
Brand Institute, said Dasani ``sounds like it could be a
destination, an exotic destination. I would see it as a very
emotional type of personality to it. Very warm. Very approachable.
Very consumer friendly. At the same time it is exotic enough with
the vowel ending that it could bring a premium association with the
name which could allow a superior position and type of higher
pricing strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 'D' is a harder sounding prefix. It could allow itself to
be understood as more refreshing,'' he said. ``The actual 'sani'
grounds itself with a mystical type of suffix that could take your
imagination into almost any part of the world as far as its origin
is concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   That could help if Coke ever wants to take the Dasani name
international, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coke says it doesn't plan to. Howes said that outside the United
States and Canada, the company will stick to its existing BonAqua
bottled water brand. She said the company could not get the
trademark for BonAqua in the United States or Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
