A2129 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-NEWSPAPERS20-C     02-19 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-NEWSPAPERS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online newspapers should stress utility, executive says
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Memo to online newspapers: News isn't nearly as
important as you think it is.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the Web, you have to be ready to present and
parse that information in different ways for a different medium.
</P>
<P>
   That was the message from keynote speaker Peter Winter,
president of Cox Interactive Media, to the 1,300-plus attendees at
the Editor and Publisher Interactive Newspapers '99 conference at
Atlanta's Hyatt Regency hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most newspapers are building online extensions of
themselves,'' Winter told the group. ``They are two-dimensional and
textual. They're not meeting the product challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than remodeled newspaper content for the Web, Winter and
Cox Interactive Media favor creating self-sustaining Internet
brands in each of the markets where Cox Enterprises has a presence.
(Cox Interactive is a unit of Atlanta-based Cox Enterprises Inc.,
which also owns The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.).
</P>
<P>
   Access Atlanta (http://www.accessatlanta.com) is an example of
Winter's philosophy at work. The site includes news, but packaged
with search, chat, community and commerce areas unique to the
Internet and helps users find what they are looking for quickly,
whether its news, sports scores or movie times, phone numbers or
even horoscopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in informing (users),'' he told the
obviously surprised audience, composed of experts in informing
people. ``I want to save the user time. It's about utility. It's
about helping busy people manage their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   To prove his point, Winter pointed to recent Media Metrix data
illustrating how local newspaper sites fared in their own markets.
</P>
<P>
   AccessAtlanta was 10th in the Atlanta market compared with all
Web sites. Newspaper sites in other cities, with the exception of
The Washington Post, ranked lower in their respective markets.
</P>
<P>
   Winter's theme of utility paired with Thursday's conference
themes of content and community seem to be working for many online
papers. Analysts agree newspapers must adapt to the new medium to
stay competitive with everyone from Yahoo! to MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just about news. There must be some utility,'' says
Jupiter Communications analyst Patrick Keane. ``I do think
newspapers have to transfer a lot of their other businesses online,
like classifieds. But I do believe brand recognition in local
markets will drive users to newspaper sites not just for local, but
national and international news from a paper and reporters they
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
