<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS NEED A QUICK FIX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Ristuccia Center in suburban Wilmington was
deserted Friday morning at the time the Bruins were scheduled to
practice. A late-arriving flight from Ottawa, along with the fact
that the team doesn't play again until Sunday in Chicago, accounted
for the cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   Much has gone wrong for the Bruins of late. Some of it is easy
to explain, some hard to fathom. Whatever is ailing them, they need
to find a solution and soon.
</P>
<P>
   There are 27 games left in the regular season, one third of the
schedule. That may sound like a lot of time, but the Bruins are
losing ground every day. In its last 13 games, Boston has stumbled
to a 2-9-2 record, including losses in its last three games.
</P>
<P>
   Against Ottawa Thursday night, the defense wasn't bad but the
offense was nonexistent. The result: a 2-0 loss.
</P>
<P>
   A check of the standings Friday morning showed the Bruins in
last place in the Northeast Division. Their 53 points were good for
only 10th place in the Eastern Conference. In other words, if the
playoffs were to begin today, the Bruins would be out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   Down the stretch last season, the Bruins were 16-9-2 in their
final 27 games and finished fifth in the conference. This season,
however, with the East in such a dogfight, that may not be enough
for the Bruins to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns has never missed the postseason in his 10-year
coaching career and said he has no intention of being shut out this
time. But in order for him to keep his record unblemished, the
coach will have to get his team to play a complete game, something
it hasn't done all season.
</P>
<P>
   Contract squabbles disrupted the first part of the season.
Injuries have derailed a number of players' seasons. Inconsistency,
especially on the top scoring line, has been a killer, especially
when you consider that the Bruins have not had a regular second
line all season. Joe Thornton has been the second-line center for
much of the season, though sometimes he's been pushed to the wing;
but for the most part, the wing positions on the second line have
been a revolving door of legitimate NHLers and auditioning hopefuls
from the American League.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's loss to the Senators was particularly dismal in
that the Bruins looked like they just didn't have it from start to
finish.
</P>
<P>
   There's no fire, no chemistry, no results. Unlike last year's
squad, which seemed determined and had a feisty attitude, this
year's looks tentative, lacking in confidence, and out of sync. The
problem has nothing to do with effort _ the players are trying. But
if last year's team was a well-oiled machine firing on all
cylinders, this year's is a backfiring model that could use a
tuneup.
</P>
<P>
   When the goaltending or defense is solid, the offense produces
no goals. When the offense is clicking, there is no defense. As
Burns and his staff search for answers, the Capitals continue to
gain ground, as they did Thursday in a 2-2 tie with Carolina. The
Florida Panthers, too, picked up a point on Boston in a scoreless
tie with St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   An even bigger blow was the Canadiens' big victory over the
East's best club, Philadelphia, which gave Montreal 54 points,
pushing the Habs a point ahead of the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Burns is doing what he can with the roster he has, often having
to put players in roles in which they don't belong. In Ottawa, he
dropped right wing Dmitri Khristich, who is struggling badly, off
the top line and installed Anson Carter with Jason Allison and
Sergei Samsonov.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to try something,'' said Burns. ``We still had no
goals to show for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two thirds of the season is gone. The stretch run is here.
Goalie Byron Dafoe says he and his mates have to hurry up and get
on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   But can they? Burns said he's heard all the right things from
his players, that it's time to take charge, it's time to make a
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on my knees for a while now saying, `C'mon, let's
go,' '' the coach said. ``We need everybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
