<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ The trade deficit in goods and
services narrowed in December but widened to a record level in the
full year. December's deficit shrank to $13.8 billion from $15.3
billion in November. Exports declined 0.6 percent, reflecting
weaker foreign demand for industrial supplies and auto parts.
Imports fell 2.1 percent, partly because of lower oil prices. In
all of 1998, the deficit expanded to a record $168.6 billion, up
from the previous year's $110.2 billion, in a reflection of the
dollar's strength and the domestic economy's vigor. By David E.
Sanger.
