<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Protection Likely For Two Tax Credits &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Middle-class families seeking a $500 tax credit this year for
each child under 17 may soon rest easier that they won't lose part
of that benefit by falling under the alternative minimum tax.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a similar problem was averted when Congress adopted a
bill sponsored by Rep. Richard E. Neal, D-Mass., to exempt from the
AMT both the child credit and the new education tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   Neal's law was only for 1998. But there is agreement between
President Clinton and Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who is chairman of
the House Ways and Means committee, that another fix is needed.
</P>
<P>
   The AMT, passed 30 years ago to make sure that the wealthy did
not escape all federal income taxes, has its own rates and tougher
rules. It has been a growing burden on the middle class because
Congress has not amended the law to account for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   This year, people making as little as $27,404 can be subject to
the AMT, if their tax credits and personal exemptions are high
enough. And, without a fix for the child credit, the tax could also
affect a single parent with two children and income of $50,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's proposed budget includes a two-year
extension of the 1998 moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   Archer wants to eliminate the AMT, which has failed in its goal
of zero tolerance for tax avoidance by people making more than
$200,000 a year. About 2,500 families a year make more than
$200,000 but pay no federal income taxes, up from 155 families when
the law was passed.
</P>
<P>
   David Cay Johnston &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shopping, and Giving, on Line &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From E-commerce now comes E-charity: In a campaign to turn the
explosion of on-line retailing to the benefit of nonprofit
organizations, new Web sites are allowing shoppers to designate
some of their on-line spending for charitable groups.
</P>
<P>
   For the shoppers, no extra money is involved: They simply visit
sites like &QC; Socialgoods.com and Shop2give.com and designate
charities they want to support. The sites have shopping links to
retailers that have agreed to send the charities part of the
shopper's payment.
</P>
<P>
   Socialgoods.com has charitable partners including CARE and Oxfam
America, an international relief agency, and shopping links to
companies like Etoys and Amazon.com. Shop2give.com lets shoppers
designate any of the nation's charitable nonprofits, with shopping
links including J. Crew and Barnes &AMP; Noble. Charities typically
receive about 5 percent of the amounts spent.
</P>
<P>
   A new entry, Greatergood.com, takes a different tack, creating
shopping links at the sites of individual charities. Users then
click from the charities to the retailers.
</P>
<P>
   For charities, the potential is enormous: On-line retailing is
expected to grow to $18.1 billion this year, up from $7.8 billion
in 1998, according to Forrester Research, and to $108 billion by
2003.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Hallett, an Internet consultant whose E-commerce company,
NMP/Appnet, develops Web sites for charities, says charities will
ultimately attract more users through their own sites, with links
to retailers, than through more general sites that offer access to
several charities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who become serious supporters of any cause or
charity have a passion and a concern for what that organization is
dealing with,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Todd Cohen
</P>
</TEXT>
