<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEING WITH RED SOX GOOD THERAPY FOR COLEMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ He was, in many ways, as reluctant to see a
psychiatrist as the Matt Damon character was to see Robin Williams
in the film ``Good Will Hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't Michael Coleman's idea. It had been sprung upon him,
he said, after a July game in Pawtucket, when PawSox manager Ken
Macha told him that Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette wanted him
to undergo counseling. If he didn't, Macha said, the manager had
been instructed to bench him.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, who had been in the big leagues at the end of the 1997
season and was a candidate for an outfield job last spring, was in
need of an ``attitude adjustment,'' in the words of Duquette. It
appeared that he hadn't gotten over not sticking with the major
league club, especially when his roommate, Donnie Sadler, was on
the Opening Day roster.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette felt he wasn't giving the PawSox the effort or
performance the organization expected _ he appeared to be coupling
a big leaguer's arrogance with a bush-league indifference. ``Prime
Time'' nickname, nowhere game.
</P>
<P>
   There was the game in Ottawa in which he hit a home run and took
his time circling the bases. When he slowed to a walk between third
and home, he nearly touched off a brawl. And there were too many
times when he jogged to first, let a ball drop in front of him in
the outfield, or threw to the wrong base.
</P>
<P>
   It had to stop. Macha had spent futile hour upon hour talking to
Coleman, trying to explain what was at stake, and finally Duquette
decided some sessions with a psychiatrist were in order.
</P>
<P>
   But for more than a week, Coleman chose to sit on a bench
instead of a couch. ``I just didn't know how to react to it,'' he
said. ``Nobody's fault, but it just caught me off guard. It was
like a slap in the face.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like there was something wrong with me, but that's just
how I am. Being cocky, being the way I am, that's just the football
mentality I have. It was like they wanted me to change, for them,
for Boston, for the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then I felt like I couldn't let the season go to waste, I
had to suck it up and do it. It was like I didn't have any rights,
but I felt like you're the man, you're signing the checks, I'll do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman went to see a Providence-based psychiatrist to whom he'd
been referred by the club. In their first meeting, Coleman said,
neither man spoke more than a few words, much like the initial
Damon-Williams encounters. But gradually, said Coleman, he opened
up. Some trust formed, and the words began to flow. He brought with
him notecards filled with things he'd jotted down at the ballpark.
With the help of the psychiatrist, he began grading himself on his
performance, on and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Where there had been hurt and confusion, understanding crept in.
Coleman still wishes the club had not tied counseling to an
ultimatum, but he acknowledges that what had once seemed an insult
eventually became something to which he looked forward. Coleman and
his psychiatrist talked by phone at least once every couple of
weeks, and last month, when Coleman was sent by the Sox to the
major league rookie development seminars, he talked openly of his
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys would have been ashamed to talk about it,'' he
said. ``Not me.''
</P>
<P>
   But whereas Coleman was once considered the Red Sox center
fielder of the future, he barely draws a mention these days. Scouts
from other teams would pass through Boston last summer raving about
his natural ability but saying their clubs wouldn't touch him.
Coleman remains on the Red Sox roster, but when the open right
field job is discussed, Duquette refers to rookie Trot Nixon as the
heir apparent, not Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK,'' Coleman said Friday. ``Last year, I heard the
same words about me. I came into last spring thinking this is my
job to lose, and it really wasn't. I really wasn't given a shot to
win a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm just as good as the outfielders out there that I'm
in competition with. I just want a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman acknowledges doubts as to whether he'll get a fair
shake. He knows he alienated Duquette with his initial rebuff of
counseling, and he suspects he rubbed Jimy Williams the wrong way
last spring, when he went into the manager's office, demanded to
know his status, and told Williams that if he was going to be sent
down, make it now rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he liked that,'' Coleman said. ``If I was going
to go down, I wanted to go and get my head right, but it may not
have come across that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman hit just .253 with 14 home runs at Pawtucket last
season, a season in which he came back too soon from arthroscopic
knee surgery. But he rehabilitated all winter at a clinic near his
Nashville home, spent some time here working out, and was among
this week's early arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to come down here, keep my mouth shut, and play,''
he said. ``If I bust my butt and I have a bad spring, then it's on
me. All I ask for is a shot, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Affixed to his locker is a photo of an infant. ``That's my
daughter, Mykyla,'' he said. ``Six weeks old today. I think she
changed a little bit of everything. I've got to look after her, No.
1.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette assigned his aide, Lee Thomas, to speak with Coleman
through this winter, urging him to prepare for spring, encouraging
him to step up his game.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman is considering another option if things do not work out
in baseball. A high school All-America running back and defensive
back, Coleman turned down a scholarship to Alabama to accept a
modest $50,000 bonus from the Red Sox when drafted in 1994. ``If
he'd gone to Alabama,'' says his high school coach, James ``Bubba''
Spears, ``he would have won two or three SEC football
championships, gone to the College World Series, and probably would
have been drafted by both sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, when he was at a low point in Pawtucket, Coleman
called Spears on numerous occasions, asking him for help to get
back into football. He'd done the same thing his first year in pro
ball, when he was so homesick he was ready to quit. This winter in
Nashville, Coleman ran into Ronnie Cottrell, Alabama's assistant
head football coach and chief recruiter. Cottrell had tried to
recruit Coleman for Florida State out of high school, but was now
in Tuscaloosa. ``He said, `Are you ready now to play football?' ''
Coleman said. ``I was laughing, but he was dead serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Spears said that he has no doubt Alabama would want Coleman, who
has 4.4 speed in the 40, if he elected to play football again. ``If
baseball gave Michael the pink slip, I'd be calling coach
Cottrell,'' said Spears. ``And there'd be other schools that would
want him, too. As a cornerback, Michael will knock your breath
loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, who turns 24 in August, acknowledges that the idea has
some appeal. ``I have no doubt that I could play and start,'' he
said. ``Other guys have gone back, like Josh Booty. And who knows
down the road, maybe the NFL?''
</P>
<P>
   Booty, a former high school All-America quarterback, was the
Marlins' No. 1 pick in 1994, but he quit this winter so he could
play football at Louisiana State.
</P>
<P>
   But Coleman said he's not ready to give up on baseball. There's
also Mykyla to think about. ``I don't want to feel like I gave up
too easily,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Spears hopes he continues to play baseball. ``Michael's a good
kid,'' said the coach. ``He's been immature, but his first love is
baseball. He'd run through a wall to play baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to go to Alabama out of high school, but when
you're from the inner city, that baseball contract looks like a lot
of money. But he's put five years in it now, and he can play
baseball. I know he still wants it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
