<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2139 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV     02-19 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TALE OF TWO MARKETS, AND TWO SETS OF PROTECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21)  
 (Eds: The (star) word should be replaced with the symbol)  
 (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It has become fashionable for investors to think they
no longer need brokers to help them with their investments. A
computer, a modem and an on-line account, so the thinking goes, are
all you need to make a fortune in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that a big part of an honest broker's job is keeping
his or her customers away from investment mistakes, a task that not
even the smartest machine can do.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, today's electronic access to stocks requires of
on-line investors a heightened responsibility for their own
actions. Few investors may yet realize just what this
responsibility involves.
</P>
<P>
   Investors may not know, for example, that if their on-line
trading firm is a member of the National Association of Securities
Dealers and problems crop up in their accounts, they may be left
holding the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Some 100 brokerage firms offer on-line trading services. Those
that are members of the New York Stock Exchange abide by its rules;
firms that belong to the NASD follow its regulations.
</P>
<P>
   A little-known but crucial difference between the two sets of
rules leaves investors who use NASD brokers more vulnerable. The
difference involves ``suitability,'' a pillar of the securities
laws.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Stock Exchange essentially requires its members to
make sure that an investment is suited to a client's needs and
circumstances before making the sale, even if the transaction was
the investor's idea, not the broker's.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, if a customer trading through an NASD firm buys a
stock that has not been recommended by the broker, the firm is
under no obligation to evaluate whether the investment is
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Although this difference has existed for years, the recent
popularity of on-line trading makes it a deeper concern. A customer
of an NASD member firm who trades his way into huge losses from an
inappropriately risky investment cannot sue the firm to recover on
suitability grounds unless the firm recommended the investment.
(Clouding the issue is the fact that many on-line firms offer
research reports that make recommendations.)
</P>
<P>
   The NASD rule creates a major gap in investor protection, said
Lewis D. Lowenfels, an expert in securities law at Tolins &AMP;
Lowenfels, a law firm in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the nation's on-line trading is done at NASD firms. Of
the top 15 on-line brokerage firms in the United States, according
to Gomez Advisors Inc., eight are members of the NASD. These
include the giants Ameritrade, E(star)Trade, Datek and Suretrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suitability is one of the main avenues of protection under
federal securities laws for investors,'' Lowenfels said. Indeed,
the issue of suitability looms large among investors unhappy with
their brokers' performances.
</P>
<P>
   According to the NASD, an average of 29 percent of arbitration
cases filed with it each year since 1995 involved investments
alleged to have been unsuitable for the customer who bought them.
</P>
<P>
   The NASD says it is re-examining its rule, given the recent
surge in on-line trading. ``The technology offered by these firms
is very enticing,'' Lowenfels said. ``With that enticement,
shouldn't their responsibilities rise to what the New York Stock
Exchange requires?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 1923EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
