<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2144 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REALTORS20-COX     02-19 0347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REALTORS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Realtors face influence of technology
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Technology and Internet-based listings are the latest
major influence on the residential real estate industry this
century.
</P>
<P>
   That's the message Sharon Millett, president of the National
Association of Realtors, will give an audience today at the NAR's
midwinter meeting in Atlanta. About 3,000 people are expected at
meeting, which runs through Monday at the downtown Hilton Hotel and
Towers.
</P>
<P>
   The other forces, both of which occurred during the first half
of the century, were the licensing of real estate agents and the
founding of multiple listing services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, about five years ago, we came to grips with the fact
that technology is real and challenging, and we had the ability to
move (to embrace it),'' Millet, a broker from Poland Springs,
Maine, said during an interview Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Realtor.com, the NAR's Internet site established in 1996, had
430 million hits in January as 9 million consumers logged on
looking for house listings, she said. With 1.3 million homes
online, Realtor.com offers a look at 95 percent of the properties
listed in the country, Millett added.
</P>
<P>
   Although she acknowledged that the Internet may be the wave of
the future, she said Realtors' demands on it probably exceed its
current ability to meet their needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brokers need speed, accessibility and constant availability of
data,'' Millett remarked, ``and the Internet may not yet be ready
for us. It can be slow.''
</P>
<P>
   Another pending development is the ``e transaction.'' This
technology would take sales contract information and make it
available to a network for participating parties. These might
include lenders, credit and title agencies, inspectors, appraisers
and attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think you could shrink $21 billion from closing costs and
improve buyers' ability to buy, if you automated the paper trail
created for each home sale,'' Millett said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 1925EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
