<HEADER>
A2146 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KURD-GREECE-660&AMP;ADD-N     02-19 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KURD-GREECE-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEKS EXPRESS SHAME AT GOVERNMENT HANDING OF OCALAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece _ In the cafeteria of Pantion University, three
students spoke morosely about national pride and how they felt
robbed of it. Across town, in Zonar's cafe, three retired
executives, old enough to be the students' grandfathers, spoke in
the same angry, wounded tones about the events that allowed Turkey
to wrest a Kurdish rebel leader, Abdullah Ocalan, from Greek
protection.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth friend, a retired army officer, refused to join in,
muttering, ``I'm ashamed to be Greek,'' as he moved away.
</P>
<P>
   Since Turkish security forces seized Ocalan in Nairobi, Kenya,
where he had been hiding in the Greek Embassy, and triumphantly
hauled him, blindfolded, to Turkey for trial on charges of
terrorism, Greece has been nurturing a deep identity crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Greeks are concerned for Ocalan, whose fight for Kurdish
independence from Turkey is one that many Greeks view as an echo of
their own effort nearly 180 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And there is disgust with the government of Prime Minister
Costas Simitis, whose bungled effort to protect Ocalan in secret
was viewed as so humiliating that it forced the resignation of
three top ministers on Thursday. A fourth , the intelligence chief,
was ousted Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Greeks have renewed loathing Turkey, seen as gloating over its
victory, and have expressed anger at the United States, because
many say they believe Washington had a hand in Ocalan's capture.
There is a sense of betrayal, because Europe stood by and did
nothing to help Greece out of its predicament.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath all that, the Ocalan affair has provoked a national
conversation on shame, pride and the Greek identity.
</P>
<P>
   One word keeps cropping up, ``philotimo,'' a Greek word for
inner pride or self-esteem that people say is too intrinsically
Greek a concept to translate accurately. Greeks love to remind
foreigners that they invented democracy. They also stake a first
claim on national pride.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs, they say, is 3,000 years old and like no other. ``This
was a direct hit at our philotimo,'' Yannis Kapsis, a former
foreign minister and a parliamentarian from Simitis' Socialist
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Kapsis, who has been one of the government's harshest critics
over the Ocalan case, said such a blow to Greek pride could not be
surmounted easily. ``The side effects will be felt for months, if
not years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The concern about pride, echoed on television talk shows and in
newspapers, as well as in cafes and kitchens, stretches across
generations and sexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel awful,'' said Paghona Simou, a 21-year-old student in
public administration. ``This is something that leaves us with no
honor.''
</P>
<P>
   The embattled prime minister struggled Friday to regain some of
his, making his first public appearance since the scandal unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Simitis told reporters that his government had made mistakes,
but he also cast some blame on his European colleagues. He
reproached European nations for refusing to act together to seek a
solution to the problem and, instead, turned Ocalan away when he
flew from airport to airport in search of a safe haven.
</P>
<P>
   ``They also share responsibility for subsequent developments,''
Simitis said. He announced that Greece would push European
governments and the European Parliament to pressure Turkey to
accept international observers at Ocalan's trial. He said that he
would also ask them to put Kurdish rights at the top of the
European agenda with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed highly unlikely that Simitis' statement would comfort
many countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a Socialist, I vote for the government party,'' said
Christos Emmanuel, 19, a social anthropology student at Pantion.
``But I believe they did not give Ocalan to the Turks by accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a small county. We need money and protection. I feel
like our old character, our Greek identity, has disappeared. I
never expected this from a Socialist government. My ideals are
shaken.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Emmanuel and his friends said they thought idealism was part of
the national character. ``Ours is a history of struggle for
democracy, and this is not in line with that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some saw the loss of face in slightly less idealistic terms. ``I
felt frustration,'' said Jason S. Stratos, the president of the
Federation of Greek Industries. ``No matter what we do, Turkey
manages to get the upper hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Very few Greeks say they think that Greece should have offered
Ocalan asylum, an act that would have been tantamount to a
declaration of war with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they bemoan Greece's weakness, first in failing to
prevent Ocalan's supporters from sneaking him into the country and
then for lending him ineffectual secret support that landed him in
a Turkish prison.
</P>
<P>
   He came here as an ``iketis,'' Kapsis said, using a word meaning
``supplicant'' that is derived from a religious law in ancient
Greece which required sanctuary be given to those who sought it in
a temple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he got into our country, we were morally obliged to
shelter him,'' Kapsis said. ``The mistake was letting him in. There
was no moral obligation until he set foot here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
