<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2148 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV21-B     02-19 1629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV21-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEXT GENERATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, February 21, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Venture capitalist Mitt Romney's willingness to take over the
Salt Lake Organizing Committee for the 2002 Winter Olympics should
be of more than passing interest to the business community _ and
not just as an opportunity to restore luster to a somewhat damaged
brand.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue mission also offers a glimpse of hope for the future
of the Republican Party, in the form of an intellectual and
spiritual program far more robust than the ``neoconservatism'' that
recently has brought the GOP low.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, Romney is just another specimen of one of those
intergenerational parlays that, when they work, work well. His
father, George, was a familiar feature of the political landscape
during the 1960s. A former chairman of American Motors Corp. and a
three-term governor of Michigan, Romney was an unsuccessful
candidate for president in 1968. He was noted for small cars and
doubts about the Vietnam War. Well-respected, he died in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Mitt Romney was the youngest of four children. He enrolled at
Stanford University in 1965. After a couple years in France, he
transferred to Brigham Young University, married, and graduated as
valedictorian of his class. He then entered a joint degree program
at Harvard's law and business schools, graduated in 1975, and
joined the Boston Consulting Group when it was at the height of its
fame.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years later he walked out in the famous separation
that led to the founding of rival consultants Bain &AMP; Co., and in
1984, with several friends founded Bain Capital, a small firm that
had enormous successes in the next decade fueling the growth of
start-up firms such as Staples, Bright Horizons, and Domain Inc.
Despite the success (or perhaps because of it) his interest in
politics grew, and in 1994 he ran a pretty good but unsuccessful
race against perpetual incumbent Senator Edward M. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The other thing to understand about the Romneys is that they are
members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints _
Mormons, as they are known, after their book of revelations. That
means the Romneys don't drink, smoke, or swear. It means they marry
for life and refrain from sexual relations until they do. It means
they contribute 10 percent of what they earn to their church.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, that means they are believers in a faith
revealed to Joseph Smith in upstate New York in the 1820s,
including the history of a lost tribe of Israel in North America
whom Jesus had visited immediately after his resurrection. Its
adherents suffered remarkable persecution for their beliefs _ Smith
himself was murdered by a mob in Nauvoo, Ill. _ until they found
safety beside the Great Salt Lake in 1847. The combination of
revelation and experience led the Mormons to a creed that is
remarkable for its many secret rites _ and its emphasis on family
values, industry, thrift, hierarchy, and collective action.
</P>
<P>
   The story usually told about the Mormons today has to do with
the extraordinary proseletyzing that has made it one of the world's
fastest-growing religions. The church has added more than a million
members in the last decade, bringing its membership to 5 million or
so, thanks to young members for whom two years of knocking on doors
as missionaries is a rite of passage into adulthood. (That's what
young Mitt Romney was doing in France.) Immigrants in particular
and the poor in general are drawn to the sense of community and
longer-term order that it provides.
</P>
<P>
   It is equally the case that members of the LDS church (as the
Latter Day Saints are more familiarly known) have been very
successful during the last 30 years or so working at the very high
end of American life _ business, medicine, and education in
particular. Romney is a conspicuous example. Several leaders of the
Harvard Business School are LDS members, including Kim Clark, an
economist who serves as dean. Boston therefore has a large and
vigorous church; business school professor Clayton Christensen is
preparing a history of it, and the congregation is building a large
new temple in suburban Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   The Church of Latter Day Saints has been undergoing a slow but
remarkable evolution in recent years. A hundred years of isolation
in Utah permitted all the exotic aspects of the Mormon faith to
flower. Polygamy long has been a thing of the past, but firm
beliefs persist among the faithful in a hierarchy of heavens, the
necessity of baptizing long-dead ancestors, and the durability
throughout eternity of both personality and the bonds of marriage.
Women were relegated to subordinated roles for many years. Until a
special revelation in 1978, African Americans were forbidden to
serve as priests.
</P>
<P>
   All that has been slowly changing. Mormonism itself is moving
toward the religious and cultural mainstream, according to the
authoritative Christian Century magazine. For one thing, the church
now has more members outside the United States than in; it is
growing especially quickly in Africa. Gordon Hinckley, the
octagenerian president of the church (and also its prophet, seer,
and revelator) has taken advantage of his early work in radio to
make landmark appearances on ``60 Minutes'' and the Larry King
show. Saints now refer to themselves as members of the Church of
Jesus Christ; they emphasize their Christianity, instead of their
differences with Catholic and Protestant churches.
</P>
<P>
   To find anything like this Mormon metamorphosis, you have to go
back to the Society of Friends in 17th century England. For the
first quarter century or so after the sect arose in the ministry of
George Fox, the ``Children of Light'' and ``Friends of Truth'' also
presented society with extreme beliefs. They declined to pay
tithes, to take off their hats, or to knuckle under to what they
called a ``hireling ministry.'' So obstreperous were the Quakers in
pressing for the ``rule of saints'' that four were hanged in Boston
between 1659 and 1661.
</P>
<P>
   Persecution and repression brought a huge turnaround. Prevented
from holding office or attending Oxford or Cambridge, young Quakers
went into business _ and flourished. Their strict code of conduct,
ruthlessly enforced, led people to trust them with their money.
Their insistence on fixed prices instead of bargaining strengthened
their reputations for integrity and broadened their markets. And
frugality and family values led to large fortunes. What had begun
as a radical egalitarian sect in one century re-emerged in the next
as a creator and purveyor of mainstream values. Wholesome,
admirable Quaker qualities were played up; radical Quaker beliefs
were played down.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take much imagination to see the resemblances. Mitt
Romney is about as different from the older generation of Mormons _
Utah senators Orrin Hatch and Robert Bennett, for example _ as it
is possible to be while still holding fast to the same core
beliefs; as different, say, as William Penn from George Fox.
Indeed, Romney maintains an very different political stance from
the ``neoconservatives'' who have prated about civic responsibility
since the early 1970s. Let me mention just two examples.
</P>
<P>
   Romney ran against Ted Kennedy in 1994 without attacking him
personally. He told the Globe's Ben Bradlee Jr. at the time that he
wouldn't have bothered to oppose John Kerry, Massachusetts' other
Democratic Senator, because Kerry's ``political views will come and
go.'' Kennedy, on the other hand, ``is really the champion for a
political philosophy for an entire country whose time has passed.''
Compare that principled willingness to offer an alternative to the
recent orgy of Clinton-hating!
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Romney spent $50,000 of his own money for a series of
newspaper ads during the 1996 presidential primaries in Iowa, New
Hampshire, and Massachusetts. He asserted that GOP candidate Steve
Forbes' flat tax plan would mainly benefit the rich. ``It's a tax
cut for fat cats,'' Romey said, ``a zero tax on the wealthy and a
17 percent tax on working Americans.'' Compare that willingness to
shoulder the financial burdens of democracy with the incessent
whining about taxes that has characterized the right wing of the
GOP for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when you think about it, the Mormon religion has been
practicing the very virtues that the neoconservative moment has
been merely preaching in recent years. Fiscal responsibility,
business integrity, philanthropic generosity, family values,
tolerance within its sphere, the ethical treatment of others:
Mormons could well serve as exemplars for us all. That is all the
more reason for why the Salt Lake City Winter Olympics turnaround
will be worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, one big difference between the Quakers and
the Mormons. Because of their beliefs about the Inner Light,
Quakers were ultra-Democratic and anti-intellectual. Mormons, on
the other hand, emphasize the need of external authority, such as
the Ten Commandments, the Bible, and the Elders of the Church.
</P>
<P>
   And in this, they more nearly resemble the puritan Yankees of
New England, of whom the sociologist E. Digby Baltzell in his
classic ``Puritan Boston and Quaker Philadelphia'' wrote years ago,
``By and large, in a society that is led by an established and
authoritative class there will be more self-respect and pride,
among both the leaders and the led, than will be the case where a
privileged class falls back on its wealth, leaving the reins of
society to an egalitarian and democratic elite.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
