<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIDNEY POITIER HELPS DAUGHTER MAKE A NAME FOR HERSELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``Tamiia'' is wedged in there to break up the obvious, but
c'mon. Sydney Tamiia Poitier is Sidney Poitier's daughter, from the
dancing eyebrows to the disconcerting smile to her penchant for
making the lightest of dramatic moments appear life-altering.
``It's strange,'' Sydney says by phone. ``My parents never said
`don't' do this and they never said `do' this ... they just kind of
let me know in uncertain terms that (acting) wasn't the most stable
thing you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Sydney, one of six Poitier daughters, three of whom
decided to try that life of instability, was working as a
record-company assistant when Dad called to ask, ``Are you sitting
down?''
</P>
<P>
   With little success, he'd been peddling the script of ``Free of
Eden,'' a talkie, female version of ``Straight Out of Brooklyn''
(or an inner-city rendition of ``Lilies of the Field,'' take your
pick). What probably scared off studios was its commercial
unfeasibility. It opens with a big gun-toting hoodlum mowing down a
couple fast-food workers for a few bills. But from there, gang
activity or gunplay is nil. Hollywood minds must have been
pondering: Who will pay to see this?
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ``Free of Eden,'' premiering at 7 p.m. CST Sunday night
on Showtime, is a touching, uplifting drama about the relationship
between a teen-age girl from the projects and the rich businessman
she asks to rescue her from hopelessness.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime, in a fierce footrace with HBO for stars and fresh
concepts, saw both in ``Free of Eden.'' Sidney Poitier wanted the
lead role, and one can only imagine the marketing ideas going off
in producers' heads when he strolled in with the audition tape of
his 25-year-old daughter for the other lead.
</P>
<P>
   Her resume was feather-light. She'd had tiny roles in tiny
theater productions like ``Titus Andronicus,'' ``Hello, From
Birtha,'' and ``Our Town,'' where everyone played every character.
</P>
<P>
   On the upside: She had studied at New York University's Tisch
School of the Arts and the Stella Adler Conservatory.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it matters how much experience the daughter of Sidney
Poitier has. When her dad called to say ``They want you for the
lead,'' she, like the young woman she was being hired to portray,
sat down and thought hard about her life.
</P>
<P>
   Most hard-working people don't summon up a lot of sympathy when
Sydney talks of the difficulties of growing up with a door-opener
named Sidney Poitier. ``It's a help, it's a hindrance, it's a
burden, it's a joy,'' says Sydney, who landed a small role in Clint
Eastwood's ``True Crime'' but who drew a bigger one in the May
miniseries ``Noah's Ark'' with Jon Voight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that casting directors are eager to see
you. But there's no question that these unbelievable expectations
are placed on you. I'm just starting out, but people expect me to
be as good as my father. That's kind of insane.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydney admits that acting has a glamorous appeal _ if a
distorted one _ for offspring of successful actors. She saw the
riches and acclaim of her father, but rarely got a glimpse of the
struggles, even when he went through long dry spells during the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   As a junior in high school, she started to think seriously about
acting, and by then it was clear that her advantages came with a
psychological price.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started at NYU, I was nervous, worried that
people would question my qualifications for being there,'' says
Sydney. ``After a while I let those insecurities go, and now don't
carry them around anymore. Now I just worry about what everyone
else worries about: Am I too old, too young, too tall?''
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Free of Eden,'' it's a watchable production that seems
a lot like Sidney Poitier the actor _ it tries awfully hard to make
us feel every uttered word.
</P>
<P>
   After Sydney's Nicole Turner witnesses a murder _ the robber
fails to see her hiding behind the counter _ she decides that
enough is enough. She wants out of the environment that has trapped
her and has her mother convinced that getting a minimum-wage job is
more valuable than getting an education.
</P>
<P>
   Poitier's Will Cleamons grew up in those projects but left his
ideals behind long ago, after becoming discouraged by a failed
teaching career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Free of Eden'' focuses on the teacher/student relationship
between them, and its best moments are when the two banter over
generational differences and, of course, Ebonics.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney will undoubtedly get some flack for her meek portrayal of
a hard-edged sister from the streets. Experience will teach her how
to disappear into a character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I did a good job with the speech patterns and the
mannerisms,'' Sydney says. ``But, you know, these things will come
in time. I'm in this for the long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
