<HEADER>
A2157 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GIULIANI-BOS &LR;      02-19 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONEYMOON OVER FOR GIULIANI? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Perhaps more than any other neighborhood of
Manhattan, the Upper East Side is Rudy Giuliani country. Mostly
white and white-collar, the wealthiest Zip code in America, its
residents voted to reelect him as mayor by a 4-to-1 ratio a little
more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, many of them are growing a bit tired of the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted for him, I think he's done a lot of good things, but I
think he's gotten a little out of control,'' Tim Devitt, a director
of TV commercials, said Friday as he left Eli's Manhattan, an
upscale food emporium on 80th Street and Third Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   George Blumenthal, a retired business executive who also voted
for Giuliani, said much the same: ``New York City has made
tremendous achievements under his term, but the man is very
autocratic. He lacks the grace that you need in a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   All over the city, Giuliani seems to be slipping. The biggest,
or most immediate, cause seems to be the way he responded to the
police shooting of an unarmed African immigrant in the Bronx. But
judging both from polls and from people's comments, the reaction to
that response may be an extreme instance of a disturbing trend.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey taken last week by the Quinnipiac College
Polling Institute, only 44 percent of the city's residents approve
of the way the mayor is doing his job, down from 60 percent three
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   He is still favored by most white residents, but even among
them, his positive rating has fallen, from 84 percent to 63
percent.
</P>
<P>
   This decline comes at a time when Giuliani is being seriously
discussed as a contender for higher office _ as a US senator, or a
Cabinet officer, or even a vice president in a Republican-occupied
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Friday on the ``Today'' show that he was giving
``careful consideration'' to a Senate race, but that several things
must come together first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fund-raising has to come into place. You have to feel you
have the support,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Giuliani runs for Senate, as many suspect he will, just 18
percent of the city-dwellers surveyed said they are likely to vote
for him. Another 18 percent said they were ``somewhat likely'' to
do so. But 49 percent said they were ``not at all likely'' to pull
his lever in the voting booth, and another 11 percent said they
were ``not very likely.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Carroll, director of the Quinnipiac institute,
attributed much _ but not all _ of the decline to the killing on
Feb. 4 of Amadou Diallo, a much-liked, hard-working and unarmed
African immigrant, by plainclothes police who fired 41 bullets at
him as as he stood outside his apartment house in the Bronx shortly
after midnight on Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Giuliani's foes, not least the Rev. Al Sharpton, blamed
the mayor for the killing _ or at least for its excesses. The view
was that in his zeal to cut crime, he has encouraged aggression and
arrogance in his police force.
</P>
<P>
   At least on a level of political perceptions, Giuliani made
matters worse. He voiced public regret for, but did not condemn,
the action. He did not suspend, much less arrest, the four
officers. He did little to reach out to the black community. And he
called a news conference to lay out statistics showing that New
York's police are less hair trigger than other cities' forces _
which, though apparently true, seemed strangely tone-deaf.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Diallo's parents arrived in New York to retrieve
their son's body, Sharpton was in control of events, leading big
rallies, speaking in passionate but dignified and moderating
language, while Giuliani was so isolated, the parents declined to
see him when he came to call.
</P>
<P>
   The shoppers on the East Side all cited Giuliani's mishandling
of the Diallo affair as one reason for their growing disenchantment
with the mayor _ but just one reason.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Blank, a lawyer, said, ``He's gone a bit far generally.
Diallo is just an example.'' She cited, as others, the barricades
he has placed around City Hall and his grandiose plans a few months
back to build a high-tech command post in case of terrorist
attacks. ``It sounded so weird,'' she said. ``He's not my style.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's style _ blunt, scrappy, unabashedly in-your-face _
has been appealing to many New Yorkers, especially when it was
accompanied by results, most notably the city's drastically lower
crime rates.
</P>
<P>
   There were nearly 2,000 murders in New York City in 1994, the
year Giuliani became mayor. Last year, there were just over 600.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, the Quinnipiac pollster, acknowledged that the mayor's
falling ratings ``might be a short-term thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mal Eisenberg, a teacher, was one of a few people coming out of
Eli's Friday whose admiration for the mayor has not diminished.
``Sure, he's obnoxious and rude,'' Eisenberg said. ``But we voted
for him, knowing this _ just like people voted for Clinton, knowing
about him. He's done a lot for this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Siegel, professor of urban history at Cooper Union College,
said Giuliani's current political problems might be caused, in
part, by this success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more crime goes down and the more you try to reduce crime
further,'' he said, ``the more interactions you'll have between
police and people who are not engaged in criminal activity _ and
this unavoidably creates problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel said, ``Is there some level below which you can't reduce
crime any further without creating an intolerable situation?
Giuliani is running into that level.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Giuliani's critics say his hard-nosed style makes it
difficult for him to deal with the alienation.
</P>
<P>
   Former mayor Edward I. Koch, who says he agrees with 80 percent
of Giuliani's policies but disagrees with 90 percent of the way he
carries them out, put the matter bluntly: ``Rudy has built no
reservoir of good will toward him. When he starts to go down, all
the people who suffered will kick him down the steps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 1946EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
