<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2158 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0220     02-19 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0220 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, MILOSEVIC FACE OFF OVER KOSOVO, AS DEADLINE LOOMS FOR
NATO AIRSTRIKES
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trim at 600 words.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With additional U.S. warplanes bound for the
Balkans, President Clinton warned Friday that American forces are
ready to strike Serb positions if Belgrade misses a Saturday
deadline for making peace in war-torn Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared to rule out an extension of the deadline -- 6
a.m. (EST) Saturday -- saying ''it would be a mistake'' to give
Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic another chance to avoid
air strikes the White House first threatened last October.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, however, was defiant, refusing to meet with U.S.
envoy Christopher Hill, who traveled to Belgrade to issue a
last-ditch ultimatum to the Serb leader.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will not give away Kosovo, not even at the price of
bombing,'' Milosevic was quoted as saying by the official Tanjug
news agency, a government mouthpiece in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, Clinton responded, saying that Milosevic faces a
stark choice between war and peace, on U.S. terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is an option,'' Clinton said during a
White House news conference with French President Jacques Chirac,
following a meeting focused on NATO's plans for dealing with the
Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there is an effective peace agreement, NATO stands ready to
help implement it,'' said Clinton. ''We also stand united in our
determination to use force, if Serbia fails to meet its previous
commitment to withdraw forces from Kosovo and if it fails to accept
the peace agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing at Clinton's side in the ornate East Room, Chirac
echoed Clinton's threats, saying the two were in agreement
''without the shadow of a doubt,'' and that Serbs would face ''very
serious consequences,'' if Saturday's deadline is missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want our continent to be at peace,'' Chirac said, through
an interpreter, ''and we will not accept that a situation such as
the present situation in Kosovo should continue.''
</P>
<P>
   As the men spoke, some 200 U.S. warplanes were already within
striking distance of Serbia, and dozens more were preparing to join
them from the United States in what would be called Operation:
Determined Force.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ordered six giant B-52 bombers -- capable of launching
long-range cruise missiles at Serb targets from hundreds of miles
away -- to fly from Barksdale Air Force Base in Louisiana to the
Royal Air Force Base in Fairford, Britain. They were expected to
leave over the weekend if Saturday's deadline passes with no
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Also earmarked to got to the region were a dozen F-117 stealth
bombers, 10 EA6B Prowlers, used to jam electronic air defense
systems, and 29 tankers used to refuel warplanes in the air.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there were at least five U.S. warships -- each
capable of launching long-range cruise missiles into Serbian sites
-- in the Mediterranean Sea, along with the aircraft carrier, the
U.S.S. Enterprise, at port in southern France.
</P>
<P>
   In total, the United States would have some 260 warplanes in the
region by early next week. Air strikes, however, could begin before
that.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton issued an activation order last October, in effect
giving NATO authority to order air strikes, with U.S.
participation, against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   If launched, the attacks would likely begin with the launch of
scores of cruise missiles targeting Serb anti-air defense systems
and support facilities. The idea would be to help clear a path for
warplanes, should additional strikes deep into Serbian territory be
required.
</P>
<P>
   Without describing the specific targets, Clinton said the
strikes would follow a ''strategy which would at least reduce
(Milosevic's) capacity to take further aggressive military action
</P>
<P>
   against the Kosovar Albanians.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid talk of war, however, there was a last-ditch effort at
diplomacy underway.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sent Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to
Rambouillet. She was to arrive just hours before the Saturday
deadline to try to eke out a last-minute deal that might avert NATO
airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators representing the Serb Republic, Yugoslavia's
dominant republic, and ethnic Albanians from its southern province
of Kosovo have been meeting this week in a 14th Century castle in
Rambouillet, France.
</P>
<P>
   Under a U.S. plan, Serbs have been told to pull their security
forces out of Kosovo and allow autonomy there for the majority
ethnic Albanians, or face NATO air strikes. In exchange, ethnic
Albanian rebels have agreed to lay down their arms.
</P>
<P>
   If the Serbs agree to withdraw, some 28,000 NATO troops -- about
4,000 of whom would be Americans -- would go into Kosovo
immediately to ensure compliance with the three-year agreement and
safeguard the peace.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million
people, have chaffed at the repressive rule of the minority Serbs
ever since Milosevic stripped the region of its autonomy in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, open warfare has broken out between Albanian
rebels operating as the Kosovar Liberation Army, and Serb security
and para-military forces.
</P>
<P>
   The United States blames the Serbs, however, for the vast
majority of atrocities that have taken place in the province, where
some 2,000 people have been killed and hundreds of thousands forced
from their homes during the harsh winter.
</P>
<P>
   The terror in Kosovo has followed the pattern Serbs used to kill
or run off hundreds of thousands of ethnic Muslims and Croatians in
nearby Bosnia and Croatia from 1992 until November 1995, when NATO
airstrikes and U.S. diplomacy forced the parties to sign a peace
treaty near Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three years, a U.S.-led NATO peacekeeping force
has overseen the fragile peace in Bosnia. Clinton has warned that
the fighting in Kosovo threatens the stability in the volatile
region and must be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Under the peace plan the United States is insisting that
Milosevic agree to, Kosovo would remain -- for at least three years
-- as a part of Serbia, but ethnic Albanians would replace Serbs as
the controllers of the provincial government, legal and security
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton suggested on Friday that the alternative would be
independence for Kosovo, which is widely supported by ethnic
Albanians and rabidly opposed by Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally believe it's the only way (Milosevic) can
preserve Kosovo as a part of Serbia,'' Clinton said. ``We're trying
to give this a chance to work, not trying to
</P>
<P>
   provide a wedge to undo Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has not officially endorsed independence for
Kosovo and has instead insisted that all parties respect the
territorial integrity of present-day Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a time out here,'' said Clinton. ''We need a process
within which we can get the security forces out, as Mr. Milosevic
said he would do before, and build some internal institutions
within Kosovo capable of functioning, and then see how it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
