<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ANALYSIS-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., MEXICO STRUGGLE WITH `FAMILY' PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Feb. 21)   News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERIDA, Mexico _ When all was said and signed, when the
presidents of Mexico and the United States left and this sun-filled
colonial city in the Yucatan Peninsula returned to its customary
revelry, this question arose: Now what?
</P>
<P>
   In a whirlwind visit last week that barely lasted 23 hours,
President Clinton, Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo and their top
Cabinet members signed nine ambitious accords dealing with most of
the contentious issues dividing the two neighboring nations.
</P>
<P>
   Amid smiles, bear hugs and the wailing of Clinton's saxophone _
he played ``My Funny Valentine'' for first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton at a private dinner _ the two leaders said they were
embarking on a new era of mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are more than neighbors,'' Clinton said Monday. ``We belong
to the same family.''
</P>
<P>
   The family problems of drugs, immigration, border violence, law
enforcement, wildfires, tuberculosis and a generous credit line of
$4 billion _ so Mexico can buy U.S. products _ were seemingly dealt
with, at least on paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today between Mexico and the United States there is a new
understanding, based on respect, dialogue and friendship,'' Zedillo
said after the accords were signed. ``A new understanding that
makes the relationship between Mexicans and North Americans strong
and mutually advantageous.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now is how.
</P>
<P>
   The accords established good will, but it remained to be seen
how they will go into effect.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, similar agreements were signed between Clinton and
Zedillo in Mexico City. And in the two years since, U.S.-Mexico
relations have in many ways become frostier, particularly in the
areas of immigration and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is better to have accords than to not have them,'' said
researcher Jorge Bustamante, former president of the Tijuana-based
Colegio de la Frontera Norte, a nonpartisan think tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is an enormous distance between what is said and
what is decided in the legislative branch. In the United States,
the power doesn't rest so much with Clinton as with Congress,''
Bustamante said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit was timed to occur before he decides whether to
certify Mexico as an ally in the war on drugs, an annual ritual
that this year could be rejected by Congress. If a country fails to
win certification, it can face economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The certification process, in effect since in 1987, rankles the
30 countries that endure it each year. Mexico has always been
certified. Colombia and several other countries have not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems have become politicized ... there are elements of
xenophobia, superiority and racism,'' Bustamante said. ``Many
Republicans treat Mexico as if it were an enemy, not a partner.
There is a huge gap between politics and reality.''
</P>
<P>
   But to opponents of certifying Mexican compliance, Mexico is
clearly not doing its share. Shortly before the Merida summit
between Clinton and Zedillo, the Zedillo government announced a
$500 million program to combat trafficking by investing in
high-tech equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems these are the same feel-good agreements we have every
year, and they never result in anything,'' said Rep. Lamar Smith,
R-Texas. ``Last year the president certified Mexico and said the
flow of drugs would decrease. Well, the drug flow has increased ...
the arrests of drug dealers have gone down, and Mexico is refusing
to extradite known drug dealers.''
</P>
<P>
   Immigration is another touchy issue. The accord signed by the
two leaders promises cooperation in resolving border violence.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican and American human rights groups blame hundreds of
deaths on increased U.S. vigilance along the border, including the
so-called Operation Guardian, a policing program that centers on
populated border crossings.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, immigrants have veered off to more deserted
stretches, going longer distances without food or water. Last year,
360 immigrants died of thirst, hunger, drowning or exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, co-sponsor of a 1996 bill that revamped and strengthened
U.S. immigration laws, said blaming American policies and the
Border Patrol for the deaths ``is like blaming victims of crime for
the crime.''
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, the various measures and accords send mixed,
confusing signals.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many, the immigration laws are too severe. They shouldn't
lead to fatalities,'' said Carlos M. Sada, the consul-general for
Mexico in San Antonio. ``I hope these accords translate into action
that benefit Mexicans who aren't criminals but are coming across
because of economic necessity.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Santibanez, an immigration specialist who is the new
president of the Colegio de la Frontera Norte, said the Merida
accords have advanced the immigration issue on at least two fronts.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, they establish that immigration is a problem of the two
countries and that both of them are prepared to address it,'' he
said. ``Second, they recognize the importance of the border as a
joint region. That's completely new. We'll have to see how they do
it. It's an open question.''
</P>
</TEXT>
