<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2165 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LILY-FASHION-$ADV21-A     02-19 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILY-FASHION-$ADV21-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING (SORT OF) FOR VINTAGE HAUTE COUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Feb. 21)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ ``Ninety percent of our clientele is
celebrities, the tall-and-thin club,'' Rita Watnick says.
</P>
<P>
   Now she tells me.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the rest of America, I watch the fashion parade every
year at the Oscars, while delivering a commentary that makes Joan
Rivers seem kind. At each commercial I'm on the phone to my sister
shrieking, ``Did you see that?''
</P>
<P>
   But over the last few years, certain stars _ Demi Moore, Wynona
Ryder, Nicole Kidman _ have been wearing the most delicious gowns,
drop-dead elegant and fitted like a dream. When asked where they
came from, they say, ``Rita, from Lily.''
</P>
<P>
   Lily is shorthand for Lily et Cie, possibly the most opulent
collection of vintage haute couture and top-end manufacturers from
the 1920s to the 1970s assembled in the country. Even Tiffany
Dubin, the fashion director at Sotheby's, calls it ``phenomenal,
the Madison Avenue of vintage.'' Movie stars who need a rest from
staid Armani or splashy Versace come here to ogle mint-condition
Pierre Balmain, Balenciaga (Tea Leoni married David Duchovny in
one), Christian Dior and Norman Norell.
</P>
<P>
   In the 20 years since Ms. Watnick has been in business, she has
spent millions building her inventory. Between her store at 9044
Burton Way and her warehouse, she now has 500,000 pieces _ 100,000
dresses, gowns or suits, including the largest collection of Rudi
Gernreich in the country, 450 pieces. The rest are hats, bags,
scarves, shoes and accessories _ everything from gloves to bras to
unworn stockings from the '20s and '30s.
</P>
<P>
   To walk into Lily et Cie is to experience a thoroughly romantic
time warp. Within minutes I'm yearning to carry a hatbox to lunch.
One wall is lined only with little black dresses _ ``cocktail
clothes from the '50s and '60s,'' Ms. Watnick says _ with labels
like Pauline Trigere, Bill Blass for Maurice Rentner and Miss
Sophie, Saks Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   One couture dress has no label, but its seams are hand-stitched,
the slip constructed from horsehair and tulle. There are bouffant
skirts, slim skirts, netting and sequins and beads and lace, each
more intoxicating than the next. Cinderella's fairy godmother
definitely shopped here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love these!'' I shout, presenting Ms. Watnick with three I
want to try. Never mind that they're each from $500 to $900 _ and
this is the cheap rack. Some designer gowns go as high as $45,000.
I can feel that shopping high coming on, where the real world
evaporates and I'm suddenly convinced that Tracy Lord in ``The
Philadelphia Story'' is my best and closest friend.
</P>
<P>
   But not so fast. Ms. Watnick shakes her head. ``Too small,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   I am crestfallen. How can she tell? She holds the waist of each
dress against mine, explaining it would have to go halfway around.
None do. And she is adamant about the trying-on policy: No one
tries on anything unless she says so. Each dress is one-of-a-kind,
and the wear and tear of forcing a seam over a too-thick waist or a
too-wide hip can damage the garment. This is not Antique Boutique.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another jump up altogether from what people call
vintage,'' Ms. Watnick explains in her husky, authoritative voice.
A 50-ish Los Angeles native with movie star skin and a Lhasa apso
named Trouble by her side, she is able to cast one look at a dress
or person and make a pronouncement that is instant and unerring. If
one of her assistants speaks, she speaks louder. ``I interrupt all
the time,'' she says. ``It's my favorite thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the 1,000 customers she sees only by appointment seems
to mind. ``They either buy the first dress I put on them or they
buy everything I put on them,'' she proclaims. These women include
Naomi Campbell, Kate Moss and Cameron Diaz, who actually fit into
one of the doll-size dresses on the front rack that I couldn't, a
hand-beaded silk chiffon. Ms. Watnick's customized ministering has
even included assisting Wynona Ryder with jewelry choices at Harry
Winston.
</P>
<P>
   Everything that leaves the store is meticulously altered, since
she prides herself on her eye for the perfect fit. ``I've sold
150,000 pieces of clothing over 20 years, and I know more about the
construction of clothing than anyone who works for me,'' she says.
``I'll say, `It's an eighth of an inch off,' and I'm right.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Time to put her claims to the test. I go to try on the gowns Ms.
Watnick has preselected for me, but before I can start, Sarah
Jessica Parker comes in. She needs an evening bag for the Golden
Globe Awards, to match her light blue Donna Karan gown. She has not
brought the dress, only a photo, and is wearing workout clothes, a
tank top and clingy pants. She is so taut and tiny she looks as if
she's been constructed from bobby pins. Just standing next to her I
feel like I've expanded to three times my size and should be
manning a steam table, dishing out beans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeez Louise,'' Ms. Parker says daintily when confronted by a
stunning array of choices. There is an Austrian crystal handbag
with a sterling silver chain, a hand-beaded bag made of pearls and
embroidered with tiny flowers, a white reptile Judith Leiber bag
flashing rhinestones. She holds each one next to the picture while
everyone offers an opinion _ Ms. Watnick, her assistants and Ms.
Parker's publicity agent _ but she still can't decide. Ms. Watnick
allows her to take the Leiber and crystal bags home to try with the
dress, so she can send back the one she doesn't use. She leaves
happy (and eventually chooses the crystal).
</P>
<P>
   I, however, am still feeling bloated from the encounter, and
when I go into the dressing room with one of Ms. Watnick's
assistants to try the first gown, I am amazed there's room for both
of us. The dress, a navy brocade priced at $4,800, is by Michael
Novarese. It is a sleeveless column with a deep V-neck that has an
elaborate overskirt with way too much material for me. I look
upholstered.
</P>
<P>
   Next, we try a strapless white beaded Dior for $5,800. This
time, I won't even leave the dressing room. It is tourniquet tight
and from the back, way too Jennifer Lopez for my taste. Sitting
would be out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Watnick then suggests an Adrian multicolored chiffon. It is
a museum piece, she says, and sells for $4,200, which could be
considered a bargain. As Ms. Dubin of Sotheby's explains, ``An
Adrian dress with the label in perfect condition is irreplaceable,
a part of Hollywood history.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, let history show that I can get it on, but it looks just
awful. I am not tall enough and the Play-Doh colors make my face
and arms look pasty. It occurs to me that this is the opposite of
playing dress-up as a kid, where you put on your mother's old
clothes and they are all too big. With these, I've already outgrown
them.
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly disheartened, I try a black satin strapless Nicholas
Ungar column. Way too tight across the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Watnick seems annoyed. ``Look,'' she says, ``I'm your
friend, but you have a tiny bit of a negative self-image. It's not
that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's not, but for $1,125, I'm looking for better than
``not that bad.'' My shopping high gone, I have turned back into a
pumpkin. Or more to the point, my stomach has turned into a
pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   I leave humbled and exhausted after three and a half hours of
being girled to death _ poked and prodded and found wanting, in
style, confidence and measurements, not to mention age. When you're
20, you look good in anything.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I arrive at lunch, though, I have an epiphany: I am
not now nor will I ever be a movie star. So what? I can still
gather myself together, rise up and live a full and happy life _
thanks to whoever invented the elastic waistband.
</P>
<P>
   I study the menu, and when the waiter appears, I muster a smile
and utter the one word I see there even more beguiling than
Balmain: ``lasagna.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
