<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2170 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     02-19 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS MAY BE GREEDY, BUT THIS WASN'T ABOUT $$$
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For maybe the only time in his adult life, Tom Hicks' blood was
not flowing burnt orange this week. More like fiery red, actually.
</P>
<P>
   His University of Texas connection had failed him. His UT link
with fellow former Longhorn Roger Clemens, a link that had seemed
so Eyes-of-Texas like, suddenly was blinded by Broadway lights.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks lost one _ a big one _ he thought he was going to win when
Clemens stepped right around the Rangers on his way to accepting
this week's trade to the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   When there's a UT tie-in, Hicks is not going to lose often.
Officially a member of the school's board of regents, in reality
he's the secret athletic director. The current upswing in the Texas
athletic department is to Hicks' credit, with DeLoss Dodds serving
only as a Howdy Doody front man.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Rangers' owner, Hicks worked tirelessly this
off-season to arrange a Clemens arrival in Arlington for early
April. He had UT pipelines to Roger, he had mutual UT friends with
Roger. More than anything he truly believed all the Clemens
propaganda _ that Roger wanted to pitch in Texas Our Texas, and
wanted to stay in the American League to finish his Hall of Fame
career. To Hicks, that said Arlington more than Six Flags said
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks playfully chided a certain media member _ it was me _ over
a December column that the Rangers were out of the Clemens chase.
That column was based on Doug Melvin not having as much to give
Toronto, player-wise, as say the Houston Astros. (The Yankees I
never really had in the final mix).
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you check where Roger's wife is from and where her
family lives?'' he asked. Yeah, Tom, where? ``Arlington.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything was right and ripe for this deal, so thought Hicks.
And sure enough, Melvin did have a trade cut with Toronto this
week. It was a deal without one frontline player or rotation
pitcher being involved.
</P>
<P>
   Two obstacles jumped in the Rangers' way, the least being that
George Steinbrenner, against the wishes of his baseball people, put
pitcher David Wells in the New York trade package to Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays leaped on George's offer, and rightfully so. But
Clemens, if he had wanted to pitch for an American League team in
the greatest state God ever created, had the contractual right to
tell the Blue Jays ``no.'' If he had desired for Arlington to be
his new home, so close to his Katy roots and his Austin roots and
his wife's roots, Clemens could have made it happen Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, however, immediately flung himself into George's
waiting arms.
</P>
<P>
   It's not sour grapes for Hicks to be angry or for Melvin to be
angry. They felt misled by Clemens, and they are right.
</P>
<P>
   But just because Clemens is a greedy, self-serving,
double-dealing super-star, that also doesn't make him bad people.
At least not bad people by baseball, or pro sports, standards.
</P>
<P>
   As a free agent three winters ago, Clemens preached the
``I-want-to-be-in-Texas'' sermon, then signed with Toronto. He went
where the most money was being offered, meaning 8 million in U.S.
dollars per season. If Hicks had owned the Rangers then, Clemens
would have been here. At the time, however, the Rangers didn't play
big-league hardball when it came to luring free agents, even a
Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it wasn't about dollars. Hicks could and would match
Steinbrenner in any type of contract. This time Clemens went where
he thought he had the best chance to win a World Series.
</P>
<P>
   I don't blame Clemens at all. But by now, he's made everyone
tired, and made himself look cheap, with his ``pitch in Texas''
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   But for a true slice of today's sordid life in the big leagues,
please examine the other major figure involved in this week's large
trade. That would be David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   How could anyone do more for an owner and a team than Wells did
for the Yankees in '98? Great season, great postseason, but it also
goes beyond Wells' stellar work on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   This is a half-crazy, fun-loving, biker-bar loving, good guy,
who was a perfect fit in New York, and also loved everything about
pitching in New York. Not many can say that. Wells could. And if
Clemens is a financial bargain at $8 million a season, consider
that Wells' contract is for half that. He's a better bargain.
</P>
<P>
   But when Steinbrenner was overcome with concern over how good
the Rangers could be if Clemens was in their rotation, well . . .
</P>
<P>
   George ordered Wells gone in about the same split-second it took
Clemens to OK the trade to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner and Clemens were feeding out of the same plate of
me-myself-and-I. And that's the standard menu in the big leagues of
today. Either eat or be eaten.
</P>
</TEXT>
