<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-FAMILIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN LEADER'S VISIT TO PAKISTAN SEEN AS HEALING EVENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAHORE, Pakistan _ More than half a century since the leaders of
India redrew borders and uprooted millions of lives, Abdul Aziz
Khan still feels as divided as the day he went to sleep in India
and woke up in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947, Khan was a young railway worker in Dhaka, a city that
became part of Pakistan under a partition agreement that carved up
India to create a Muslim homeland for India's largest minority
group. Khan's family lived in Uttar Pradesh, which remained part of
Hindu-majority India, and although the Khans were Muslim, they _
like tens of millions of others _ chose to stay in India rather
than abandon their property and community.
</P>
<P>
   But places like Dhaka were wracked by communal violence, and
Khan could not return home safely. Millions of Hindus and Muslims
who lived on the wrong side of sensitive border areas fled, and
people like Khan, old enough to remember, recall refugee trains in
both directions arriving at border stations full of corpses, the
victims of barbaric ambushes.
</P>
<P>
   It is well-known that partition claimed as many as one million
lives and inaugurated a deep-seated enmity that has ignited three
wars between two nations that were separated at birth. It is
sometimes forgotten that millions more, like Khan, survived
partition - but as members of families separated by one of the
world's most fortified and volatile borders. For them, partition
and the enduring hostility have brought practical problems:
restricted travel and contact with loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   The visit Saturday of Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee
_ the first to Pakistan by an Indian leader in a decade _ is being
hailed as an historic opportunity for peace. Politicians,
businessmen and foreign observers hope the meeting will open trade
and help resolve the dispute over Kashmir, a strategic Himalayan
region that both sides claim.
</P>
<P>
   There are fundamentalists on both sides who oppose
rapproachment, but for most _ and especially for divided
``mohajir'' or migrant families _ the visit to inaugurate an
Indo-Pakistani bus route is as much a chance to mend emotional
fences as diplomatic ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``India is my homeland _ how can I forget it? Even birds return
to their nest after spending their days somewhere else,'' said
Khan, 73, his voice rising with emotion. ``Pakistan is our state,
but India is my home. Yet when I go to India to visit my family,
everyone asks, `Why do you want to go there?' `Why are you coming
here?'''
</P>
<P>
   Many who visit the other side complain of headaches from visa
authorities and security forces, and the need to register with
local police wherever they go. The Khans say they have to save all
year to pay exorbitant bribes demanded by officials on both sides
of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Khan's daughter-in-law is a Muslim Indian, a niece who married
his son and emigrated 12 years ago. She cries when asked about
living away from her family. ``My young sister died and I couldn't
attend her funeral,'' said Mujasim Bibi, 33. ``I don't care about
politics, but I hope the prime minister's bus trip will mean we can
all travel more freely.''
</P>
<P>
   0 Khan's wife, Nazuk Begum, 67, says all her family and friends
are in India. ``I cannot live without them,'' she said sadly. ``I
am old now and I want to die there, to be buried in my ancestral
graveyard.''
</P>
<P>
   But her sons _ who were born in Pakistan _ will not move. Their
attitudes reflect some of the prejudices that 51 years of distance
and enmity have instilled in the next generation.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Haider Zaman, 33, explains that his parents ``feel
the association with India, because they were born there. But we
don't feel any. We feel this is home, this is our country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any love for India. I feel proud to be Pakistani
instead of Indian. Hindus deprived us of our property. We can't
live with them,'' he said emphatically. ``Now we visit every year
because of my parents. But the bond will be finished when they
expire.''
</P>
<P>
   That view is echoed by many whose parents emigrated under bitter
circumstances, and raises the question of how warm future ties
could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Vajpayee's visit can help solve the Kashmir
issue, because both sides have been discussing it for years and
have failed to reach any decision. Many young people think the only
way to solve it is by waging war,'' said Salman Aslam, 32, a writer
and English teacher whose father fled from Indian Punjab to the
Pakistani side.
</P>
<P>
   His father's family abandoned a lucrative export business, and
of 100 relatives who fled six miles on foot to the border, only 25
survived ambushes by sword-wielding Sikhs, a religious sect that
sided with Hindus at partition. Twenty relatives stayed behind, but
he has not seen them since.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came with empty hands. Sikhs seized our valuables, cash,
ornaments. We went from upper-middle class to a hand-to-mouth
existence,'' said Aslan's father, Mohammad Aslam Khan, 70, who
eventually started his own construction business. ``We lost what we
had, but we thanked God that we got a homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Pakistanis echo his view that the pain of partition was
worth the reward of a land where Muslims can run their own
government and economy and not feel like second-class citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the legacy of bitterness between the neighbors, Khan
says, ``Common people are pinning hope on this visit. I want peace
and trade with India. And I would feel fortunate to meet my
relatives after all these years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
