<HEADLINE>
MODERN NASCAR MULLING TV DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometime in the next few weeks, NASCAR executives will decide
whether to package the television broadcast rights to the 34
Winston Cup race weekends for sale to the networks.
</P>
<P>
   For racetrack owners, drivers and NASCAR itself, the
evolutionary move would mean hundreds of millions of dollars a year
in extra revenue, plus the added TV exposure needed to cultivate
the sport's mushrooming fan base.
</P>
<P>
   For racing fans, such a deal would mean more and better NASCAR
programming options than are now available.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of NASCAR's development into a modern,
sophisticated marketing operation.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, each track operator who is host to a Winston Cup race
sells its TV rights individually for whatever it can to whatever
network is interested. This year, CBS, ABC, NBC, ESPN, TBS and The
Nashville Network offer NASCAR races.
</P>
<P>
   The Daytona 500 sells its rights for an estimated $15 million,
while smaller races sell their rights for something closer to $1.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Track owners like Speedway Motorsports Inc., operator of Texas
Motor Speedway in Fort Worth, believe that rights fees would soar
if the entire Winston Cup series were sold collectively, making
every track owner's total take larger.
</P>
<P>
   At present, NASCAR races generate about $100 million in TV
rights fees each year. That's a long way from 1985, when NASCAR
received just $3 million for the TV rights to 28 races.
</P>
<P>
   But it's even further away from the $400 million annually that
NASCAR might earn if its races were bid collectively.
</P>
<P>
   Said Texas Motor Speedway executive vice president and general
manager Eddie Gossage, ``We don't think we're getting enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're getting now is chump change,'' said John Mansell,
a sports business analyst with Paul Kagan &AMP; Associates, speaking to
Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're terribly underpriced,'' added Bruton Smith, chairman and
chief executive officer of SMI.
</P>
<P>
   All the major U.S. professional sports leagues sell their TV
rights collectively, and the NBA and the NFL, especially, have
shown just how lucrative that strategy can be. More than leverage,
a packaged sale to a limited number of networks would make TV a
real partner in growing the NASCAR business, increasing the
marketing value of the sport and, therefore, the value of NASCAR's
broadcast rights.
</P>
<P>
   The time is right to make a move. Interest in NASCAR is at an
all-time high. NASCAR is the only national sports TV property to
increase its viewer ratings every year since 1990, said Mel Poole,
president of SponsorLogic, a sponsorship consulting management and
events agency in Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the hottest sports-marketing property of the decade,''
Poole said, ``and you want to negotiate when demand is highest.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR offers not only a growing fan base, but one that is
wildly supportive of its sponsors. Such advertiser loyalty is well
appreciated by network executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``You watch the bidding \Ramong TV networks\S when they put this
out,'' said Tom Cotter, chairman of the Cotter Group, a Charlotte
motorsports marketing and communications company.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said the increased revenue also will help track
operators, who currently keep 65 percent of TV money (drivers get
25 percent and NASCAR 10 percent), hold the line on ticket prices,
ensuring that there are always some lower-cost seats available.
</P>
<P>
   Stock car racing fans will benefit in noneconomic ways, too,
said Bray Cary, vice president of broadcasting for NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   By packaging race rights, NASCAR can probably persuade its
broadcast partners to provide additional programming such as
prerace and postrace coverage, much as Fox, CBS and ESPN do for the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is a 24-hour-a-day digital NASCAR channel
that would broadcast live from the track. Fans could go where
they've never been before, sitting in, for example, on the prerace
drivers' meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Other NASCAR divisions could have their races televised as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, we want to give our fans a greater opportunity to
interact with our sport,'' Cary explained. ``This really isn't
about money. It's about how to position the sport so that the
immense popularity of NASCAR can be used to grow the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR, Cary said, will decide unilaterally whether to package
broadcast rights or continue to allow operators to cut their own
deals. Because of existing broadcast contracts, viewers aren't
likely to see any changes for at least two more years.
</P>
<P>
   But the sale of TV rights on an individual track basis, Cotter
said, is ``the one area where NASCAR is back in the 1960s.'' The
sport, he said, ``has gotten too sophisticated for that freelance
approach now.''
</P>
<P>
   Expect that to change.
</P>
</TEXT>
