<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A ROOKIE ALMOST MEETS A LEGEND  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., La., N.C.)   By HAVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ The rookie noticed when David Wells came into the
room, first thing Thursday morning. Couldn't miss the big guy,
author of New York Yankee perfection, embodiment of a team that did
everything but bat a thousand in the standing.
</P>
<P>
   From across the clubhouse, No. 85 in your spring training
program stole a glance at Wells' familiar and ample figure, and
told himself there would be a moment, soon enough, when he would
take the opportunity to stroll across the blue tweed carpet to
introduce himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed Yarnall,'' he would say, extending his left arm, his
pitching arm. Then he would recount to Wells, well-traveled
southpaw in his own right, how he had gone from the Mets'
organization last summer to Florida in the Mike Piazza deal, then
back to a New York state of mind when the Yankees shipped their
third-base prospect, Mike Lowell, to the Marlins early this month.
</P>
<P>
   After his three months in the employ of one of baseball's five
and dimes, Yarnall actually considered saying something that Wells
would have appreciated before he was told to pack up everything but
the memories. It was something about how the business of baseball
can turn one's life into a dizzying blur but turn out all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was already sitting over here when he came in,'' Yarnall
said. ``He's, like, right over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall raised his chin in the direction of a dressing stall
that had had its name plate removed, revealing a piece of weathered
tape with a number, 36, and a name, Keel, scrawled in pen.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then,'' Yarnall said, ``he's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone, David Cone reported Friday, to Miami for a few rounds of
therapeutic golf. Bent out of shape, according to Cone, like one of
his snappiest breaking balls. Traded to Toronto, again according to
Cone, without so much of a clue, for George Steinbrenner's newest
trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first I heard of the deal,'' Yarnall said, ``was when
someone down the row here said he heard they'd dealt Wells for
Roger Clemens. I said, `No way that happens.'''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome, Ed Yarnall, to a Yankee-style homecoming. Welcome to
your first major league training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walked out on the field and there were reporters all over
the place,'' he said. ``It was cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Cool? Yes, that's what he said. The high-voltage trade through
the eyes of a babe. Yarnall, 23, was born near Philadelphia, grew
up near Fort Lauderdale, played at Louisiana State University,
signed with the Mets and now, three years later, finds himself
auditioning for a team that wins 125, then trades its ace. Yankee
scouts think of Yarnall as a potential third or fourth starter. He
began last season with the Mets' Class AA team in Binghamton, N.Y.,
and was in Charlotte, N.C., the Florida Marlins' Class AAA
affiliate, by season's end. In Binghamton, he was 7-0, with an
earned run average of 0.39. In Charlotte, the corresponding numbers
were 4-5, 6.20. That's why he said he was thrilled to escape the
Florida disorganization, where anyone with a live arm or quick bat
is a candidate to be rushed along and, as Yarnall put it, have his
``confidence crushed.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has noticed that Wells' sudden departure leaves the
Yankees with one left-handed starter, Andy Pettitte, on their
25-man roster, and two _ Yarnall and his clubhouse neighbor, David
Carroll _ nonroster left-handed starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, they could go out and get a left-hander,'' he said.
``I mean, they're the Yankees, George Steinbrenner ...''
</P>
<P>
   He left us to finish the sentence. ``Clemens, well, how can you
argue with that?'' Yarnall said. ``He's going to add a lot to the
team _ if there's anything that can possibly be added.''
</P>
<P>
   After two days, after witnessing the dispatching of Wells as if
he were a stack of last season's newspapers, Yarnall has grasped
the Yankee paradox. This may not be Oz, but it's not Pro Player
Stadium. A perfect game pitcher is not sold off to reduce the
payroll. On jogs the juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Yarnall was 11 when Clemens failed to go the distance against
the Mets in Game 6, and took to the Shea Stadium visitors' dugout
his best chance at a World Series ring.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Clemens is scheduled to walk into a clubhouse of
champions, minus David Wells. The rookie looks forward to his next
cool Yankee adventure. He waits for the right time to walk over and
say hello.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
