<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SHOWDOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREAT OF KOSOVO AIR STRIKES INTENSIFIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN AND LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic refused to meet
Friday with the US envoy sent to Belgrade to help resolve the
Kosovo crisis, ensuring that efforts to reach an agreement between
warring factions in the Serbian province will go to the wire
Saturday against the threat of NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton increased pressure on
Milosevic, saying that NATO's threat to use airstrikes against
Serbian military targets should not be extended beyond Saturday's
deadline at noon, Paris time (6 a.m. EST).
</P>
<P>
   Unless one side finds a way to compromise, the airstrikes that
appeared improbable earlier in the week now assume an aura of
inevitability. As one US official put it, ``Someone's got to blink,
and it's not going to be us.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton made this clear in Washington Friday during a
joint news conference with French President Jacques Chirac. ``I
have ordered our aircraft to be ready to act as part of a NATO
operation, and I will continue to consult very closely with
Congress,'' he said at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Both presidents made a final plea to Milosevic to agree to a
three-year cooling-off period during which Kosovo's autonomy would
be reestablished, its civic institutions strengthened and a
solution found to stop the unrest in the Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   During his remarks, Clinton repeatedly referred to Kosovo's
``autonomy'' which he said was stripped away by Milosevic a decade
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serbia's leaders now have a choice to make,'' he said. ``They
can join an agreement that meets their legitimate concerns and
gives them a chance to show that an autonomous Kosovo can thrive as
part of their country, or they can stonewall. But if they do that,
they will be held accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that he had ``respect for the position of Russia''
but did not comment on Russian President Boris Yeltsin's statement
in Moscow Thursday that Russia would not allow NATO airstrikes to
take place.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac said that he and Clinton are in ``complete agreement''
and made a special plea to Milosevic who, he said, ``holds more or
less the key to the solution'' to ``shoulder all his
responsibilities and to choose the path of wisdom and not the path
of war, which would bear very serious consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want our continent to be in peace,'' Chirac added. ``And we
will not accept that a situation such as the present situation in
Kosovo should continue.''
</P>
<P>
   As is his custom, Milosevic appeared defiant in the face of a
looming deadline. In a sign of brinksmanship or inflexibility, he
rebuffed Christopher Hill, the US envoy to Kosovo who traveled
Friday to Belgrade in a last-ditch effort to convince Milosevic to
accept a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic maintains that he will not allow up to 30,000 NATO
ground troops into Serbian territory to police the deal that
diplomats are trying to seal in Rambouillet, 35 miles southwest of
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not give away Kosovo, not even at the price of
bombing,'' Milosevic said. Such defiance, which collapsed last
October in the face of NATO airstrikes, appeared more vehement this
time.
</P>
<P>
   Hill had to settle for a meeting with Yugoslav Foreign Minister
Zivadin Jovanovic. Philip Reeker, a spokesman for Hill, said that
the envoy told Jovanovic, ``There could be no half-deal, no
political settlement without the military implementation.''
</P>
<P>
   As US and NATO officials rattle their sabres publicly, Western
diplomats worry privately that airstrikes will embolden and
strategically assist the ethnic Albanian separatists in the Kosovo
Liberation Army. The KLA poses difficult challenges for negotiators
as well as Milosevic. Many in the KLA ranks refuse to accept
anything short of complete independence from Belgrade and vow never
to relinquish their weapons, as called for in the proposed
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House press conference, Chirac said, ``It goes
without saying'' that if the ethnic Albanians prove to be the cause
of a breakdown in negotiations at Rambouillet, sanctions or other
measures would be taken against them.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats also expressed fear that bombing would only
strengthen Milosevic, who traditionally has used Western threats to
rally nationalist fervor.
</P>
<P>
   If Milosevic does not blink, bombing could begin sometime
Saturday, despite the continued presence of some 1,300
international observers and support staff in Kosovo, led by the US
diplomat William Walker. In the past, the Serbs have threatened to
take the observers hostage if NATO bombs them.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which
is running the international monitoring mission, was preparing its
people for a fast pullout from the province. Some 2,000 troops are
stationed in neighboring Macedonia to help accomplish that mission
if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Against the backdrop of threats and defiance from both sides, US
Secretary of State Madelaine Albright is expected to arrive in
France Saturday to help French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine and
British Foreign Minister Robin Cook search for an agreement.
American, French and British officials played down suggestions that
Albright, Vedrine or Cook would make a last-minute dash to Belgrade
Saturday to convince Milosevic to accept an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   French and British diplomats at Rambouillet were gloomy, saying
they did not expect a deal by Saturday's deadline. The main
obstacle to a settlement centers on the text that outlines autonomy
for Kosovo and the deployment of NATO troops to police the
agreement that would end the fighting. Under such a deal, ethnic
Albanians, who make up 90 percent of Kosovo's population of 2
million, would be given self-rule: more than Milosevic wants to
give and less that the ethnic Albanians want to accept.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,000 people, most of them ethnic Albanian civilians, have
died in fighting between the KLA and Serbian security forces in the
last year and hundreds of thousands have been made homeless.
</P>
<P>
   As negotiators doggedly worked for a last-minute deal in which
all sides could save face, the specter of a bombing campaign loomed
large.
</P>
<P>
   Some 430 NATO warplanes, including 260 jets, are on standby. Six
American B-52 bombers are expected to land in Britain early
Saturday and presumably would be part of the bombing campaign if it
takes place.
</P>
<P>
   European diplomats Friday began leaving Belgrade, the Yugoslav
capital. American officials said they were preparing to evacuate
some 130 US diplomats and their families in Yugoslavia to Budapest
Saturday, and to help an estimated 4,000 other US citizens in
Yugoslavia leave before the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(evin Cullen reported from London and Louise D. Palmer from
Washington.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
