<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FACES PRESS FOR FIRST TIME SINCE TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his first news conference since the Senate
acquitted him of impeachment charges last week, President Clinton
acknowledged Friday that the Monica S. Lewinsky sex-and-lies
scandal had not been good for the country, but that he expected to
have ``two more good years'' in office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said he believes his 13-month-long ordeal had
``re-ratified'' the Constitution and left the presidency undamaged.
It had, he said, been instructive for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I have learned a lot of personal lessons, most of
which I have already discussed _ and presidents are people too,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the American people expect the Congress and me to get
back to work, expect us either not to have any destructive
feelings, or if we do, not to let them get in the way of doing
their business,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   With enormous domestic and international responsibilities to
attend to, he said, the country cannot afford to let the scandal
get in its way.
</P>
<P>
   The president was asked about whether Hillary Rodham Clinton
would run for a Senate seat from New York in the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   His first response was, ``I think it's important that you all
understand ... this is nothing that ever crossed her mind until
other people began to mention it to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he had advised his wife to ``take some time, get
some rest, listen to people on both sides of the argment, try and
decide exactly what you think is right to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to say she would do a ``fantastic job'' if she ran
and was elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be strongly supportive of whatever decision she makes
and will do all I can to help on this and any other decision, from
now on, just as she has helped me for the last 20-plus years.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton also added a word of caution, pointing out the
Senate election will not occur until November 2000. ``She has just
been through a very exhausting year, and there are circumstances
which have to be considered. And I think some time needs to be
taken here,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice has been to take some time, get some rest, listen to
people on both sides of the argument, try and decide exactly what
you think is right to do, and whatever she decides, I'll be for,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   The president's comments came a few hours after Mrs. Clinton had
a private meeting at the White House with Senator Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, the New York Democrat who announced in November that he
would not seek a fifth term.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan afterward told The Associated Press that the numbers in
New York ``look very good for her,'' and that he would support her
if she ran, but that voting patterns and demographics in the state
were very ``complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party officials are pushing for Mrs. Clinton, whose
popularity has soared in the past year, to seek the nomination in
New York. But because candidates are expected to raise between $10
million and $20 million to run successfully, they are urging her to
announce soon _ something she has said she is not inclined to do.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Mrs. Clinton said she was giving a run ``serious
consideration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
