<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-NEWS-CONFERENCE (Washington) _ President Clinton,
looking ahead to ``two good years here,'' says his 13-month
struggle to survive the sex-and-cover-up scandal shows that the
American people will stand by a president who sticks to business.
Clinton also told a White House news conference that he would work
to elect first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton to the Senate in 2000 if
she decides to seek the seat. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHIRAC (Washington) _ French President Jacques Chirac
and President Clinton discuss economic and military matters at a
brief summit. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-PORT (Houston) _ A state-backed effort now being
formulated will pit Texas against heavily favored Florida and
California and 13 other states for a potentially lucrative prize: a
commercial space port for the launching of rockets rising on either
equatorial or polar trajectories. Lockheed Martin Corp., which is
developing a radical new rocket called VentureStar, is behind the
spaceport idea. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-TRIAL (Jasper, Texas) _ DNA tests show body fluids found
on shoes and clothing recovered from the apartment of murder
defendant John William King, 24, match those of dragging victim
James Byrd Jr., an FBI analyst testifies at King's trial. Also, an
FBI forensics examiner says bloodstains on tires from the truck
prosecutors said was used to drag Byrd to his death matched DNA of
the victim. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ALOU (Kissimmee, Fla.) _ Moises Alou of the Houston Astros
injures his knee in the Dominican Republic and will return to
Houston for an MRI examination. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-GOVS (Washington) _ With Capitol Hill Republicans suffering
low opinion poll ratings over their impeachment performance, the
nation's 31 GOP governors are riding a tidal wave of voter
popularity. We look at the GOP stars as all 50 governors gather in
Washington for the annual National Governors' Association meeting.
By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   STAR-WARS (Washington) _ In 1983 President Ronald Reagan
envisioned an elaborate space-based shield known as ``Star Wars''
to protect U.S. cities against a doomsday nuclear missile attack.
While such a defense has remained elusive for the last 16 years,
the Clinton administration is edging closer to fulfilling Reagan's
dream. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-POLITICS (Panama City, Panama) _ Panama's leading
presidential candidates are milking the mystique of their political
families as they barnstorm for votes. The front-runner is the son
of Gen. Omar Torrijos, the cigar-chomping military ruler who became
a national hero by negotiating the Panama Canal treaties. Trailing
close behind is the widow of Arnulfo Arias, a firebrand three-time
president who was Panama's most famous civilian politician. By JOHN
OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   HONDURAS-MITCH (Lainez, Honduras) _ Dr. Henry Moore comes from a
world vastly different than that of the Hondurans who walk hours to
seek his care. Moore, with his sandpaper Texas drawl, is the first
doctor to visit the village of Lainez since Hurricane Mitch
devastated this Central American nation last fall. By JEANNE
RUSSELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ANALYSIS (Merida, Mexico) _ In a whirlwind visit last
week, President Clinton, Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo and
their top Cabinet members signed nine ambitious accords dealing
with most of the contentious issues dividing the two neighboring
nations. But it remains unclear whether all the deals can resolve
some persistent problems: drugs, immigration and border violence.
By SUSANA HAYWARD. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ President Clinton has stressed
that he wants to leave a legacy other than his impeachment. To
achieve that, his actions now must benefit the people, safeguard
the republic and demonstrate that he can be trusted. We look at how
the country has survived other weak presidencies. By ROBERT E.
THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
