<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFI-HOFFMAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFI AWARD CAPS `GLORIOUS, MAGNIFICENT ORGY' OF WORK FOR HOFFMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(For use Sunday, Feb. 21 or thereafter) 
 
  
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Accepting the American Film Institute's 27th Life
Achievement Award Thursday night, Dustin Hoffman humbly but
amusingly noted that it was ``overwhelming to hear these things
said, to have my reputation turned to positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman was not, of course, referring to his worthiness as a
recipient of the prestigious award, which since 1973 has been
bestowed on such Hollywood legends as John Ford, Orson Welles,
Bette Davis, Alfred Hitchcock, James Stewart, Fred Astaire, Jack
Nicholson, Steven Spielberg and Martin Scorsese, among many others.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of two best actor Oscars (for ``Kramer vs. Kramer''
and ``Rain Man'') and star of such historic films as ``The
Graduate,'' ``Midnight Cowboy,'' ``All the President's Men,''
``Tootsie'' and ``Wag the Dog,'' the 61-year-old Hoffman is
inarguably one of the great stars of his generation. He is also
perhaps the most influential, since he almost single-handedly
expanded Hollywood's concept of a leading man from narrow notions
of masculine perfection to include more average-looking,
emotionally troubled individuals.
</P>
<P>
   That aspect of Hoffman's legacy was duly noted by many of the
younger, character-focused actors who paid tribute to their mentor
at the black-tie event, which was held at the Beverly Hilton Hotel
and will be broadcast as an hourlong ABC special in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Norton, currently an Academy Award nominee for his role
in ``American History X,'' referred to the Pasadena-bred Hoffman as
``the saint of off-Broadway actors,'' acknowledging the many years
he spent perfecting his craft on the New York stage before hitting
it big with ``The Graduate'' in 1967. Comedian Jon Lovitz, noting
his physical resemblance to Hoffman, joked that the star always
promises to put him in his next movie (but never does). Liev
Schreiber, who appeared in Hoffman's most recent feature film
``Sphere,'' admitted that ``for the last five or 10 years, I've
basically been ripping him off as an actor.''
</P>
<P>
   Left barely mentioned throughout the nearly three-hour
presentation, however, was the trait Hoffman acknowledged in his
opening remarks: his reputation as a prickly perfectionist. Indeed,
past collaborators such as Jessica Lange, Kathy Bates, Geena Davis
and Jon Voight mostly characterized Hoffman's obsessive dedication
to the art of acting as an inspiration that improved their own
work.
</P>
<P>
   None of which means that the evening suffered from
overpoliteness. It was indeed a sometimes raucous, often hilarious
affair.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's friend and two-time co-star Warren Beatty (``Ishtar,''
``Dick Tracy'') set the tone with his introductory speech, a
deceptively befuddled self-parody of his notorious egocentrism. A
high point soon followed when Anne Bancroft, who played the
cradle-robbing Mrs. Robinson to Hoffman's callow Graduate, gave the
actor a big passionate kiss, then, echoing a famous scene from the
movie, handed him a hotel room key and said, `It's been a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Faye Dunaway told an off-color story about irrepressible
prankster Hoffman adding extra, unexpected oomph to their legendary
bathtub scene in ``Litle Big Man.'' Reba McEntire, who serenaded
Hoffman with ``Midnight Cowboy's'' theme song ``Everybody's
Talkin','' couldn't get the reluctant thesp to croak out more than
one line with her, but he did gallantly waltz her around the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Even Hoffman's five children, in a charmingly rambunctious
videotaped segment, eagerly exposed blush-inducing personal data
about their father, such as his tendency to bark back at dogs and
their perception of their parents' sex life as darn healthy.
</P>
<P>
   But the evening's king cutup, hands down, was Hoffman's
contemporary and iconic equal Jack Nicholson. Appearing on stage
twice, first to archly recite (and uproariously comment upon) a
congratulatory letter from their mutual leading lady Meryl Streep,
then to actually present the award to Hoffman, Nicholson had the
crowd of 1,100 roaring at his every inflection.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is range,'' Nicholson said of Hoffman as he finally got
down to business, then ticked off a litany of superlative
adjectives (``uncompromisimg, probing, simple, complex...'') that
he capped with, ``and gorgeous. You do tremendous hair work.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own subdued acceptance speech, read with sometimes
choking emotion from a few handwritten pages, Hoffman thanked
collaborators, family, friends and the AFI _ which he noted was
formed in the same year, 1967, as his own movie breakthrough _ for
taking care of both himself and of the nation's film heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a glorious, magnificent orgy to be a part of, this
20th-century American film,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, exhibiting the kind of self-honesty that has always been a
crucial element of his great performances, Hoffman seriously
addressed the issue his avid admirers had tiptoed around all night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry that I've hurt the few people that I have,'' he
said. ``I did it only in the search for authenticity in my
work.''!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
