<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2185 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PESTICIDES-CHILDREN-B     02-19 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PESTICIDES-CHILDREN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNING ON CHILDREN, PESTICIDES SPURS DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new study on pesticide residue may cause American parents to
think twice before telling their children, ``Eat your spinach.''
But health officials say the public should not overreact to these
warnings about produce.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh spinach and seven other types of produce were identified
as containing high levels of toxic pesticides that may be
particulary harmful to young children, in a study released by
Consumers Union, the nonprofit consumer advocacy group that
publishes Consumer Reports.
</P>
<P>
   The other seven were peaches, winter squash, grapes, apples,
green beans, pears, and celery.
</P>
<P>
   The study results also challenged a common perception that
American-grown produce is generally safer than imported fruits and
vegetables. Researchers found many instances in which domestic
produce, such as peaches, fared far worse than foreign-grown fruits
and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   The study's author said that he is not encouraging parents to
avoid the produce aisles of grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not taking about fear of food, but informed choices,''
said Edward Groth, a biologist with Consumers Union based in
Yonkers, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Groth's study was based on data from the US Department of
Agriculture from 1994 to 1997. It found some produce had
consistently low levels of pesticide, such as broccoli, canned
corn, bananas, and frozen peas. The study focused on 27 foods,
primarily produce, but also milk and juices.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumers Union study comes as public health and
environmental officials are grappling with how to ensure that the
amount of pesticide used on produce is safe. Some scientists say
these chemicals damage the still-developing neurological and other
systems of young children.
</P>
<P>
   While previous studies have found high pesticide levels on
produce such as peaches, grapes, and apples, the Consumers Union
study is the first to incorporate the most recent federal
inspection data, along with the updated Environmental Protection
Agency guidelines on acceptable pesticide levels for children.
</P>
<P>
   This study seems likely to fuel the debate on the effect of
pesticides on children. Hard scientific data on the issue is
scarce, and scientists differ on whether there is cause for alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, reports from advocates on both sides of the issue
will be released during the 10th anniversary of the Alar apple
crisis. That crisis began with the Feb. 26, 1989, airing of a ``60
Minutes'' episode in which some scientists linked the
color-enhancing chemical to cancer risks for children.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lynn Goldman, a pediatrician who formerly directed the EPA's
pesticide program, is convinced that the federal government hasn't
gone far enough to protect American children from pesticide risks.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said she was delighted that Consumers Union had focused
on the issue. She said she hopes the new study will accelerate
government efforts to curb pesticide use by farmers.
</P>
<P>
   But she also cautioned parents against overreacting to the
information by withholding produce or excessive scrubbing or
peeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern about pesticides relates to long-term exposure, as
opposed to the meal you eat tomorrow morning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said she feeds her 2-year-old daughter apples. Peeling,
while reducing some pesticide exposure, can unnecessarily eliminate
the vitamin-rich skin, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumers Union study analyzed 27,000 samples of domestic
and imported produce, including 27 foods. The researchers analyzed
the level of pesticides found on the foods, as well as how toxic
the chemicals were. Fresh American-grown peaches from 1995 got the
highest toxicity score, 5,376, due largely to the presence of the
chemical methyl parathion. That pesticide was identified by the EPA
late last year as posing an ``unacceptable risk'' as currently
used.
</P>
<P>
   In one chart prepared for the study, researchers showed the
likelihood that a serving of a particular fruit or vegetable would
expose a typical 5-year-old child, weighing 44 pounds, to an unsafe
daily amount of a pesticide, based on the new EPA guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the study estimated that 77 percent of children of
that age and weight who ate US-grown winter squash from 1997 would
get more than the safe limit of pesticide as set by the new EPA
standards. The study estimated that 41 percent of such children
would ingest an unsafe amount of pesticide if they ate US peaches
from 1996, under the EPA standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest surprises'' of the study was the finding
that American-grown produce has as much, if not more, pesticide
residue than imported produce, Groth said.
</P>
<P>
   American-grown peaches, for example, had consistently high
levels of pesticides, including methyl parathion. The peaches from
Chile also had almost 10 times less, although the level was still
considered high.
</P>
<P>
   Groth urged consumers to wash produce carefully and consider
buying organically grown produce if possible. He noted that an
individual's risk of pesticide depends on age, susceptibility to
the effects of a compound, and how much is eaten relative to a
person's body size.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that while spinach may not be on the top of his
list of recommendations, he thinks parents might consider telling
their children, ``Eat your broccoli.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
