</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-POLITICS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL HOPEFULS COURT HOLLYWOOD POWER BROKERS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ariz., Mass., N.J., Texas, Neb.) (mk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who is putting together a
presidential campaign, dropped in on Hollywood this week for lunch
with Barry Diller and dinner with Michael Eisner. At the same time,
Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., who is considering a White House bid,
mulled over the situation with Norman Lear.
</P>
<P>
   And Vice President Al Gore, who is definitely in the
presidential race, has been chatting over the phone and meeting the
trio of Democratic moguls running the entertainment company
Dreamworks: Jeffrey Katzenberg, Steven Spielberg and David Geffen.
</P>
<P>
   It's that time again in Hollywood, when that mostly Democratic
community focuses on the potential presidential candidates who
troop in almost every week to gather support from the rich and
super-rich.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, two of the super-rich, Eisner, chairman of Walt Disney
Co., and Diller, chairman of USA Networks, are teaming up for a
high-profile event on Thursday at the Coldwater Canyon home of
Diller. The two have invited leaders of the entertainment industry
and other businesses to meet former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey
_ but not to contribute to his presidential campaign. The two
moguls are longtime friends of Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways the event is an early kick-off to Hollywood's
presidential sweepstakes, a sometimes serious, sometimes farcical
drama in which movie stars and candidates are often mirror images
of each other in terms of ego, vanity and power.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole relationship between Hollywood and Washington is as
natural as a marriage,'' said Lear, the television producer who
created such shows as ``All in the Family,'' and who is a longtime
advocate of liberal causes. ``We're basically in the same business.
We're coveting the audience's attention. We're all really looking
for affection and approval. And Washington's a company town and
we're a company town.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is a town, of course, with deep pockets. In the 1996
presidential campaign, for example, three of the top Democratic
fund-raisers _ Geffen, Lou Wasserman, the former chairman of MCA
Inc., and Ron Burkle, the wealthy businessman _ and others raised
more than $8 million from the entertainment industry for President
Clinton's re-election.
</P>
<P>
   But a more downbeat view about the Hollywood-Washington axis was
voiced by Steve Tisch, a producer of such movies as ``Forrest
Gump,'' and a big contributor to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of being asked,'' said Tisch. ``All these charities
and political fund-raisers _ I have a list of solicitations on my
desk. If I responded to everyone, I'd be personally in Chapter 11.
It's enough! When I'm ready to write a check, I'll write a check.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner emphasized that, for Bradley, the event on Thursday would
not be a fund-raiser but a stage from which the former senator
could meet the town's power brokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is I'm not supporting anybody,'' said
Eisner, whose company, Disney, is the parent of ABC, ``because of
ABC News _ it would be inappropriate. We're going to try and
assemble people for all the reasonable candidates so our community
can be well informed _ we want to stimulate discussion on
meaningful subjects.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner acknowledged that he was a good friend of Bradley's _ the
two met when Eisner went to Lawrenceville School in New Jersey and
Bradley attended nearby Princeton University. Eisner said he and
Diller, who has also known Bradley for years, had decided to
``reintroduce'' the presidential candidate to the show business
community _ or at least its leaders _ because Hollywood was
starting to focus on the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to have Al Gore as well as Bill Bradley as well as
Bush and John McCain here,'' said Eisner, referring to Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas. ``Maybe they still only want to see us because of
the potential ability to raise funds, but that's not what Barry and
I are offering.''
</P>
<P>
   The event _ and others like it in Hollywood _ have definite
pitfalls for the candidates. An evening Diller arranged years ago
for Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., for example, misfired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lackluster speech with no energy _ the air went out
of the balloon,'' said a prominent producer who attended the event.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Diller said he was opening up his home to enliven
the presidential dialogue in Hollywood, especially among Democrats.
Without endorsing Bradley, Diller made it clear that, at this
stage, he believed it was ``unhealthy'' to assume that there was
only one Democratic candidate, Gore.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``A one-horse race is unhealthy to me,'' said Diller, who is a
Democrat. ``I would like to see much more dialogue at this stage
than money positioning. The process is just much healthier if it's
not a process of acclamation but one where people can see
candidates and get enthusiastic or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Diller, like others in Hollywood, said he was weary of the
constant flow of political fund-raisers here for local, state and
national candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just get plucked like chickens,'' he said. ``It's our own
fault.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing,'' Diller added, ``is simply a reaction to
the emptiness of the current retail political process.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Bradley, a former basketball star for the New
York Knicks, has also been close to several other prominent
entertainment industry figures. They include one of the founders of
the powerful Creative Artists Agency and the former Disney
president, Michael Ovitz, and the director Sydney Pollack (``The
Way We Were,'' ``Out of Africa''), who friends said had advised the
candidate on loosening up his solemn speaking style and television
persona.
</P>
<P>
   But at this point, Gore seems, by far, the front-runner in
Hollywood, as well as the entire state of California. As vice
president, Gore has visited California, with its 54 electoral
votes, and built up a substantial organization. California has
moved up its primary to join New York and eight other states on
March 7, 2000, just a few weeks after the Iowa caucuses and the New
Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's Hollywood constituency includes, among others, Geffen,
Spielberg and Katzenberg, who have met with him frequently, as well
as John Cooke, executive vice president of Disney.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Hollywood it's definitely Al Gore's to lose,'' said Marge
Tabankin, who formerly headed the Hollywood Women's Political
Committee, which has now disbanded. ``Gore has carefully built up
relationships over the last six years with many people in the
entertainment industry and people like him and respect him and
support him.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the Republican side, which is not especially
strong in Hollywood, has been slow off the mark, largely because
donors and supporters seem to be waiting to hear whether Bush will
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's middle of the road and he can win,'' said Tom Strickler,
a partner at the Endeavor talent agency who is active in Republican
circles.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans here _ and it is not clear whom they support _
include the actors Kevin Costner and Arnold Schwarzennegger.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the presidential race, people active in politics here
have become motivated to defeat House Republican floor leaders and
other lawmakers who sought Clinton's impeachment and removal from
office. Lear's organization, People for the American Way, has begun
a group, Recall 2000, that will, in his words, ``work on a
grass-roots level to defeat, among others, the 13 House managers''
in the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Carrick, a prominent Democratic political consultant in Los
Angeles, said the campaign to wrest control of the House from
Republicans and defeat impeachment leaders only increased the need
for more money from Hollywood. . ``The entertainment industry has
generally focused on presidential candidates and Senate candidates,
big names like Teddy Kennedy, Dianne Feinstein, Bill Bradley,''
Carrick said. ``The House has always been given short shrift. It
doesn't have as many stars.''
</P>
<P>
   But the impeachment aftermath, Carrick said, has ``riveted this
community and they want to get the Democrats back in the House
majority.'' The result, he added, was that there was now intense
competition for Hollywood money not only among presidential and
Senate candidates, but also among House candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a whole new player on the block,'' Carrick said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
