<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAVIS-CREATOR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIKE JUDGE DRAWS FROM OBSERVATION OF PEOPLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(For use Sunday, Feb. 21 or thereafter) 
 
  
By MARLA MATZER 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES &UR; _  &LR; Mike Judge can't wait to go home. The creator of
TV's animated ``Beavis &AMP; Butt-head'' and ``King of the Hill'' has
flown in from his home in Austin, Texas, for a half-day of
interviews at the 20th Century Fox lot in Los Angeles. He's here to
promote ``Office Space,'' his first live-action feature film. But
fidgeting in a publicist's office, with his packed-and-ready duffel
bag sitting a couple of feet away, it's clear that he'd rather be
almost anywhere than Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for us, Judge hasn't lost touch with the real world.
``Office Space,'' an office satire-cum-industrial espionage story,
is full of the kind of small observations of humanity that have
earned Judge an admiring audience for his animated work over the
last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Judge was even able to persuade Fox to let him shoot the movie
in Austin, which, he figured, could easily double for just about
anywhere else. ``I noticed that office parks, wherever they were
situated, all have the same look to them,'' Judge says, ``And
that's what I was going for: an `Anytown, USA.'''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of Judge's attention to detail, the whole production
has a ring of authenticity. He insisted that the fictional
Initech's beige cubicles not look like an overdone Hollywood set.
Judge admits he likes to do things his way, that collaboration
isn't his strong suit. The upside of that for his fans is a sense
of cohesion to his work: those who enjoy ``Beavis'' and ``King''
will see those same sensibilities at work in ``Office Space.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a lot of me in everything I do,'' says
Judge, who voices _ and slightly resembles _ a number of his
animated characters, including ``King of the Hill's'' Hank Hill.
``There's also a lot of people I've met (incorporated into the
characters). A lot of your inspiration, you don't even realize at
the time where it's coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   For the man who brought you the moronic mayhem of ``Beavis &AMP;
Butt-head,'' Judge is more thoughtful and low-key than you might
expect. He takes time with his answers, often cocking his head to
one side and speaking in a slow baritone. Wearing jeans, tennis
shoes and an untucked sports shirt, the 36-year-old Judge looks
like any dad at a Saturday soccer game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Office Space,'' which hit theaters Friday, originated as an
animated short. The crudely drawn cartoon had only two characters,
the put-upon Milton and his oily, mealy-mouthed boss, Bill
Lumbergh. The basic plot is: Lumbergh tells Milton they'll need to
store boxes in his office/ask him to go home early to save the
company money/or some other indignity, while Milton makes
under-his-breath complaints and threats. If ``Dilbert'' is a shared
giggle about workplace foibles, ``Office Space'' is a primal
scream.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the shorts were eventually made, being shown at
animation festivals and on TV's ``Saturday Night Live'' and Comedy
Central. Judge says he realized only after creating two of the
shorts where the character of Milton originated.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was riding the bus all the time in college, there used
to be this guy from the VA hospital, who had the whole bus schedule
memorized,'' Judge recalls with a laugh. ``He'd complain about the
bus being two minutes late. He was always complaining.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from the University of California, San Diego _
and spending a brief stint as a cubicle dweller, working for an
aerospace company _ Judge decided to become a musician, stressing
this was a real job.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have often made it sound like I was playing in garage
bands,'' he says, ``but I'm actually a pretty practical person. For
me, playing music was a way to make money without working in a
cubicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing stand-up bass with such artists as Texas blues guitarist
Anson Funderbergh, Judge started subconsciously harking back to the
malcontent at the bus stop to relieve the stress of touring. ``We'd
get someplace, and they hadn't given us what they were supposed to
give us. And I'd start muttering about burning the place down,''
Judge says.
</P>
<P>
   Judge even considered playing Milton himself, though he opted
instead for a cameo role as a dumb restaurant manager who
constantly berates Joanna, played by ``Friends'' star Jennifer
Aniston. You won't recognize Judge _ he's in full disguise _ and
you won't see his name on the credits. The actor is credited as
William King.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Milton was more grounded in reality is one reason
Judge says he was able to imagine ``Office Space'' as a live-action
movie. It was a different story when there was early talk of making
``Beavis &AMP; Butt-head'' with real actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people first started talking about doing a live-action
`Beavis &AMP; Butt-head' movie, it was only a week or so after the show
first aired, I wasn't going to close the door on anything back
then, because I thought the show was going to be over in a few
weeks,'' Judge says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the more I thought about it,'' he continues, ``the more I
was imagining the reality of getting a couple of 14-year-olds in
there ... It just didn't seem to make sense. Also, `Beavis &AMP;
Butt-head' is also a little more over the top, and its voices are a
little further from reality than `Office Space.'''
</P>
<P>
   Despite recent reports that a sequel to the hit animated movie
``Beavis &AMP; Butt-head Do America'' is imminent, Judge says the
project is ``a long ways away.'' For now, Judge is concentrating on
``King'' and on developing other potential projects under an
overall deal with Fox. He says though there's been ``a little''
talk of a ``King of the Hill'' movie, there are as yet no definite
plans. ```King of the Hill' (the TV show) worked out so well, I'm
really enjoying it,'' Judge says. ``It just feels now like one of
those shows where you just want to check in with the characters
every week or two, and see how they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   As to movies vs. TV, Judge says he has little preference, though
the grass always seems to be greener on the other side when he's
hard at work. ``I guess when I'm doing TV, I want to do movies, and
when I'm doing movies, I want to do TV,'' Judge says with a
smile. &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
