<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-WHITAKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITAKER TO FACE DEFLATED TRINIDAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pernell Whitaker doesn't want to see much of Felix
Trinidad Saturday night at Madison Square Garden. Fortunately for
him, he won't have to.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad staggered into Friday's weigh-in for Saturday night's
IBF welterweight title fight a half hour late looking gaunt and
worried. For weeks rumors had swirled that the IBF champion was
battling to get down to the 147-pound limit, something that had
been giving him trouble even before a 10-month layoff that will
finally come to an end against the elusive Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors are as much a part of boxing as right hands however and
most of the time they are lies or pipedreams, so it was easy enough
to discount them until Trinidad showed up at a Wednesday press
conference in Manhatta looking like a guy fighting for the super
welterweight (154 pound) title rather than someone ready to defend
the welterweight championship.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation was that Trinidad was still in the mid-150s three
days before the biggest fight of his life and the fact that he was
reportedly holding closed-door, three- to four-hour workouts last
week when most fighters wind down their schedule only fueled this
fascination.
</P>
<P>
   ``You show up a half-hour late for the weigh-in, it ain't a
psych job,'' said long-time New York boxing manager and booking
agent Johnny Bos Friday. ``You show up a half hour late it's 'cause
you didn't make it (on time).''
</P>
<P>
   A clearly dried out Trinidad finally did hit 147, as promoter
Don King promised he would, but by the time that happened whispers
had begun to grow among guys who wear the wide-brimmed hats and
smoke big cigars that the 35-year-old Whitaker was no longer a
sacrificial 4-1 underlamb but now a live underdog in his first
fight in nearly 17 months.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker had never doubted that, even before the 26-year-old
champion began to fight the battle of the bulge. He never doubted
it even after he twice tested positive for drugs, tests that
resulted in his being suspended for a year and left without a fight
since defeating Andre Pestriaev on Oct. 17, 1997 at Foxwoods, the
same night he failed the first of those tests.
</P>
<P>
   To Whitaker, the fighting has always been the easy part of his
job, dating back to his winning of an Olympic gold medal in 1984.
His defensive mastery has led him to a 42-2-1 record in which both
losses and the draw were widely (and rightly) disputed and it has
prevented him not only from ever taking a beating but has saved him
from something even more remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Pete has ever been hit by a combination,'' said
his Olympic teammate and long-time friend, Evander Holyfield,
shaking his head in amazement. ``He's been blessed with remarkable
skills. It's a gift.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a gift some say he has abused recently after long-ago
winning titles as a lightweight, junior welterweight, welterweight
and super welterweight during an often brilliant 14-year career.
Even Whitaker seemed to acknowledge that recently in his own way,
while still vehemently denying that he ever had a drug problem
despite the failed tests and a 30-day stint in rehab.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only person who beats Pernell Whitaker is Pernell
Whitaker,'' Whitaker said while relaxing in his hotel suite, ``but
I'm not a drug user. I'm not a drug addict. I never took drugs
before a fight. I don't have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've done is down on paper. I'm happy with my 13 years in
boxing so if the tools aren't there on Feb. 20, I won't do this
again. If it's not there, I know it won't be there the next time
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Whitaker believes it will be there at Madison Square Garden
as it always has been. The speed, the elusiveness, the annoying
ability to break an opponent down without hitting him, the gifts
Holyfield spoke of. They will all be there, he believes, whether
Felix Trinidad is fit or fat.
</P>
<P>
   And if they are, he points out, the rest is already set in
stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hoping to do what everybody else has been trying to do
for so long and that's put me on the canvas,'' Whitaker said. ``But
he didn't want to come to me. He didn't want to fight Pernell
Whitaker. He had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needed a fight like this but he didn't want to get in with
me because every fight I've competed in I was the winner. People
know there's no way that kid (Oscar) De La Hoya beat me (in a close
decision that cost Whitaker his WBC welterweight title nearly two
years ago but which many at ringside disputed). He hung in there
but I was in control the whole fight. I put my hands on him many
times. I knocked him down. It was my title and I lost it like that?
No way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Trinidad watched that fight and thinks he can knock me out,
somebody needs to tap him on the shoulder and wake him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad (33-0, 29 KOs) is hoping someone will have to wake up
the aging Whitaker instead, as they have had to do to so many of
his other opponents yet he also knows he has his own Achilles heel
and it is not at his waistline. if Whitaker has a self-inflicted
nose problem he is denying after testing positive for cocaine,
Trinidad has a documented chin problem that has resulted in his
being knocked down six times, coincidentally always in Round 2.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker has only 17 knockouts and is anything but a power
puncher so a knockout of even a weakened Trinidad seems unlikely,
but he doesn't need punching power to win. Whitaker needs only
still be Sweet Pea for one more night to do that because if he is
he's still deadly to any welterweight, fat or thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``My defense is my offense,'' Whitaker explained. ``Ain't nobody
can do what I do. After 12 rounds, you don't ever want to see
Pernell Whitaker again. I mess them up mentally more than
physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to break them down mentally. They can't hit me. They get
frustrated. They make mistakes. They get hit. They still can't hit
me. It don't make any difference how long it takes. I get to them.
I'll get to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compare his record (of opponents) to mine. This kid has been
hit and down FLAT ON HIS FACE! This boy don't want to see me.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night he will have no choice. He will see Pernell
Whitaker and have to chase him with a body already weakened from
chasing off nearly 20 pounds of fat in two months. He will chase
him intent on knocking him out. If he does, Felix Trinidad will
move to the top of the ranks of welterweights, even eclipsing De La
Hoya's stirring victory over Ike Quartey just a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Pernell Whitaker believes Felix Trinidad will only get to do
half that job. He'll only get to chase him...chase him until he
drops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
