<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SERIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU THOUGHT THE TV-BASED-MOVIE WELL HAD RUN DRY ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(For use Sunday, Feb. 21 or thereafter) 
 
  
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONFIDENTIAL MEMORANDUM
</P>
<P>
   TO: ART MIMIC, PRESIDENT, WORLDWIDE PICTURES
</P>
<P>
   FROM: JOHN D. RIVATIVE, VICE PRESIDENT, DEVELOPMENT
</P>
<P>
   RE: TV-BASED MOVIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I've given some thought to our conversation yesterday. Yes, the
number of available TV series we can turn into movie franchises is
dwindling. The fact that ``My Favorite Martian'' is playing in
theaters right now is proof of that. But there are still some good
titles out there. Look at the play Warner Bros. is getting for
``The Wild, Wild West.'' The way it's being hyped, you'd think
they'd discovered gold or something. But any studio could have had
it! We could have had it!
</P>
<P>
   Believe me, Art, there's still more gold in them thar hills.
Just look at the list of titles we have in development, waiting for
the green light. Let's do lunch soon and discuss!!!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hogan's Heroes: &LR;  OK, I know the PC police have come down hard
on this one what with its wacky Nazis and stuff. But what if we
totally reimagine the show a la ``The Brady Bunch Movie''? See if
you follow this: Private Ryan (Matt Damon) gets captured and sent
to Stalag 13. And he doesn't appreciate the cavalier attitude that
Hogan (Mel Gibson?) and the other prisoners have toward the
Germans. Tensions explode when Ryan refuses to give Sgt. Schultz a
bite of his strudel. Eventually, Ryan follows his conscience and
escapes, leaving behind Hogan and his archaic ways. Bonus: Patrick
Stewart has already signed on to play Col. Klink!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gomer Pyle, U.S.M.C &LR; .: I know, I know, another war movie. But,
hey, they're hot. Look at ``Saving Private Ryan'' and ``Thin Red
Line.'' Here we take two guys who just can't get along _ bumbling,
naive Pyle and his gruff nemesis, Sgt. Carter _ and put them in the
middle of some kind of Gulf War conflict. Faster than you can say
``semper fi'' these guys develop a grudging, mutual respect for
each other as they battle an evil Arab dictator and his cadre of
terrorists. Nicolas Cage wants to play Gomer, and if we get him, I
think Nick Nolte will come on board as Sgt. Carter. Sha-zam!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; I Dream of Jeannie: &LR;  One of several (hundred) teen-oriented
projects in development. When high school senior Tony Nelson
(Freddie Prinze Jr.) opens a mysterious bottle he finds buried on
campus, he unleashes a sexy, spunky genie (Sarah Michelle Gellar)
eager to grant his every wish. Needless to say, this doesn't go
over to well with Tony's jealous girlfriend (Rose McGowan), who
conspires to put Jeannie in her place _ and back in her bottle!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The $25,000 Pyramid Scheme &LR; : Dick Clark has been pushing this
project about a slimy Amway salesman (Alan Rickman) who leads his
unsuspecting followers into a shady deal involving defective
Chinese satellites. A plucky federal agent (we're angling for Demi
Moore) arrives just in time to save the day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Green Acres &LR; : When the president of the United States (Michael
Douglas) is voted out of office, he decides to get back to nature
and buys a farm outside of a town intriguingly named Hooterville.
His wife (Joan Allen) has a hard time adjusting to the rural
lifestyle, though, and eventually leaves him to run for a Senate
opening in New York. The president soon follows, after coming to
the sad realization that Hooterville's female denizens aren't quite
as bodacious as he thought they would be.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WKRP in Cincinnati &LR; : Howard Stern plays a shock jock who sets
up shop at a conservative midwest radio station full of quirky
characters. Among them: a right-wing newsman, Les Nessman (Joe
Pesci), who repeatedly clashes with Howard's in-your-face style,
and a couple of lesbians _ secretary Jennifer (Pamela Anderson Lee)
and assistant Bailey Quarters (Jennifer Love Hewitt) _ who always
seem to be disrobing for no apparent reason. With Billy Bob
Thornton as Dr. Johnny Fever.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Andy Griffith Show &LR;   &UR; Movie &LR; : Sheriff Andy Taylor presides
over the small town of Mayberry with a gentle hand and a loving
heart. That changes when a drug cartel takes over Floyd's barber
shop and starts selling crack out of the back room. And to top it
all, they use Andy's son, sweet little Opie (code name: Opium ...
Jonathan Lipnicki), as an unsuspecting drug runner. When Andy finds
out what's going on, he rolls up his sleeves and proceeds to kick
some serious butt. With Jackie Chan playing Andy and Chris Tucker
as his smart aleck sidekick, Barney Fife. Andy Griffith may make a
cameo appearance as Otis, the town drunk who now must confront
demons more powerful than Jim Beam.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Waltons &LR; : James Cameron directs this futuristic tale of a
close-knit family that operates a space station orbiting Saturn.
When John Boy (James Van Der Beek) intercepts a message from
marauding aliens hell-bent on destroying the galaxy, the family
kicks into action, enlisting the help of a sympathetic Saturnite
couple (Jenna Elfman, David Arquette) along the way. Budgeted just
shy of $750 million, most of the movie will be filmed in actual
outer space, as per stipulations in Cameron's contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
