<HEADER>
A2202 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MOOD-ART-520&AMP;A     02-19 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MOOD-ART-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANXIETY MOUNTS AS DIPLOMATS AND OTHERS LEAVE YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-TALKS, KOSOVO-ENVOY, KOSOVO-U.S.) 
(ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ _ Friday morning, as U.S. monitors of
Kosovo's fragile cease-fire prepared to pull out of Yugoslavia
before the Saturday deadline for a peace settlement, a Yugoslav
MiG-21 flew a low barrel-roll over the Americans' headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The MiG was no more than 500 feet above the roof of the Hotel
Herzegovina in Kosovo Polje, just outside Pristina. ``It's just a
`Hi, how are ya? We know you're there,' from Milosevic,'' a U.S.
diplomat said, once the noise faded.
</P>
<P>
   As the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, pondered the
West's threat of air strikes and rebuffed a visit from a U.S.
envoy, Christopher Hill, U.S. and Western diplomatic and aid
workers began to leave Yugoslavia in preparation for potential NATO
bombing in the event the Kosovo peace effort fails.
</P>
<P>
   In an anxious Belgrade, citizens went about their normal
business. But a senior Western official said the situation was
becoming dicey, ``and the prospect for bombing is taking on a kind
of momentum, especially from the Americans.'' He said Milosevic
``appeared to be unsure of what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bombing is not expected immediately after the deadline expires,
another senior diplomat said, but could follow within a day or two,
and he did not rule out a visit here on Saturday morning from the
British and French foreign ministers, Robin Cook and Hubert
Vedrine, possibly joined by a reluctant U.S. secretary of state,
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most Western diplomatic staff prepared to leave Belgrade
on Saturday in a coordinated departure intended to underscore the
seriousness of the threat _ and to avoid possible retaliation or
hostage-taking from angry mobs or the police if bombing does occur.
</P>
<P>
   In what the U.S. Embassy called an ``authorized departure,''
meaning the paid travel out of Yugoslavia for most dependents and
nonessential embassy workers, about 65 percent of the staff were
ready to leave on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive equipment and files have already been moved out or
packed, and the top U.S. diplomat in Belgrade, Richard Miles, on
Friday visited Yugoslav officials to remind them of their
obligations to protect foreign diplomats and embassy buildings
under the Vienna conventions.
</P>
<P>
   All official U.S. personnel in Kosovo, including the six or so
diplomatic personnel still attached to the American Kosovo
Diplomatic Observer Mission, left, mostly for the short drive to
Skopje, the capital of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   They were joined by large numbers of aid workers from
international agencies like the International Rescue Committee and
Catholic Relief Services, easily recognizable in the big white
four-wheel drive vehicles that normally crowd Kosovo's narrow
roads.
</P>
<P>
   The aid agencies were leaving skeleton staffs in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Information Service office in Pristina was empty except
for security guards, and its office in Montenegro was also closed.
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. diplomats had said it would send ``the wrong signal''
to leave before the Saturday deadline passed, they were ordered to
do so anyway.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Friday night, the monitors of the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe held an evacuation exercise, packing
their bags and leaving the dreary, Soviet-style Grand Hotel in
Pristina, then returning less than an hour later.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,200 or so monitors had worked normally Friday across
Kosovo, and officials of the OSCE said they were still hopeful that
a deal would be struck between the Serbs and the Kosovo Albanians
in the peace talks. The foreign monitors are reluctant to leave,
believing that they provide a measure of protection to the ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo from Serbian security forces.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Serbian forces were more in evidence in Kosovo, in an
apparent show of force, similar to the MiG barrel roll.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, Canadian diplomatic families packed into cars and
headed for Budapest, the Hungarian capital. The Canadians were
leaving their visa office open, however. Staff in the Dutch Embassy
left, as did the nonessential British staff and the families of
British diplomats. Ordinary Western citizens were advised by their
embassies to leave Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   There was a similar drawdown in October, when NATO also
threatened to bomb Serbia. That threat was defused by an agreement
between Milosevic and Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. envoy. But
Serbian violations of that agreement, including killings of ethnic
Albanian civilians, have brought this latest crisis to a more
decisive moment, with Kosovo's future hanging in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians on the streets of Pristina on Friday expressed
concern about Serbian retaliation against them in the event of NATO
strikes, especially if no Western observers are in place to at
least witness what happens.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, there was more fatigue with Milosevic's endless
diplomatic games and crisis manipulation. ``Most people think the
West is serious and Milosevic will deal,'' said Lubisha Ivanovic,
who had just returned from a week in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything will be okay so long as Kosovo doesn't secede,'' he
said. ``As we say, Serbs will do anything for Kosovo except live
there.'' He suggested that the Serbian reaction, if there is
bombing, might be vocal but not so widespread.
</P>
<P>
   ``People know that NATO doesn't want to bomb ordinary Serbs,''
he said. ``But a lot of people also feel that this is our internal
problem and foreigners have no business here. That's the string
Milosevic is playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, on state television, Milosevic did play that
string, telling a visiting Cypriot delegation: ``Threats of
bombarding our country if it does not allow foreign occupation of
its territory should be a warning for the whole world. This should
be a warning for everyone who cares about peace and freedom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
