<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DeKalb budget revives libraries, pool
 &HT;    By Ben Smith III
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DeKalb County commissioners have reached a budget deal that
could reopen closed libraries and prevent a swimming pool and a
recreation center from closing.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the now-closed Embry Hills and Hairston
Crossing neighborhood libraries would be reopened and Sunday
service for three other libraries will be restored. Meanwhile, the
Murphey Candler Pool in north DeKalb would open this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Two staff positions have been restored to the Hamilton
Recreation Center in Scottdale, and county officials have pledged
to find funds to repair the gym floor so that the center will stay
open.
</P>
<P>
   The DeKalb commission is scheduled to vote on the 1999 budget on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty good about it,'' said Commissioner Gale
Walldorff. ``We did work with the administration (of Chief
Executive Officer Liane Levetan), and everybody had to give a
little bit to come up with the bottom line at the end of day.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission and Levetan had been fighting over $12 million in
sales tax funding slated for road improvement projects that the CEO
wanted to use to balance the 1999 budget. Most commissioners had
argued that sales tax money and the interest collected from it
should only be used for public improvement projects, not county
operating expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, sales tax funding will be kept out of the
budget. But commissioners relented on using interest on sales tax
funds, estimated to reach $5.5 million by the end of year.
</P>
<P>
   That, along with a half percent across-the-board cut for county
departments, the cutting of many unfilled positions and a lower
estimate of what it will cost the county to fund a 100 percent
homestead exemption on property taxes that will be financed with
sales tax money, helped make up for most of the shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to cut the sales tax revenue from the general
budget ``was probably the right thing to do because the budget is
going to be tight next year,'' said Commissioner Ken Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who chairs the budget committee added: ``Cutting $10
million to $12 million now, will make it easier next year.''
</P>
<P>
   But county parks officials say it may not be easier for them. By
offering to spend $100,000 on a new liner for the decaying but
popular Murphey Candler Pool, the county is delaying a decision on
a permanent solution.
</P>
<P>
   There will still not be enough money to open Brook Run, the
former state home for mentally retarded adults, as a county park.
Also, the baby pool at Tobie Grant recreation center and tennis
courts at Lynwood, Briarwood and Chapel Hill recreation centers
will remain closed because of needed repairs.
</P>
<P>
   But DeKalb library director Darro Willey said full library
service will be restored once the 10 unfrozen positions are filled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly do feel better,'' said Levetan. ``Libraries are
quality of life issues. ... A community without libraries is
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
