<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYONS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Co-defendant in Lyons case admits lying
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LARGO, Fla. _ Far from denying she spent money on a lavish
lifestyle, embattled Baptist leader Henry Lyons' co-defendant
testified Friday that she ``was like a little kid in a candy
store'' after receiving huge checks from corporations that hoped
Lyons could help them open new business opportunities among
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought these things because I worked hard to earn the money
and it was my chance to buy things I had always wanted,'' Bernice
Edwards told the all-white jury, referring to expensive jewelry,
homes and a car. ``I wanted to provide a better life for my
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards and Lyons face racketeering and grand theft charges
stemming from deals they made with companies that wanted to sell
funeral services, insurance and credit cards to members of the
National Baptist Convention USA, one of the nation's largest black
denominations. Lyons is the group's president and Edwards was its
public relations director.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic testimony came as the month-old trial is drawing to
a close. Because Lyons chose not to testify, Edwards' appearance is
likely to be a linchpin of the defense's case.
</P>
<P>
   But it was far from an untarnished performance.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards made what appeared to be several damaging admissions,
including her use of multiple Social Security numbers to open bank
accounts to handle the money and her failure to report the money to
her probation officer. Edwards was on probation for embezzlement
when Lyons hired her, and was required to report all her income to
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   She said she used as many as five different Social Security
numbers because she simply forgot her real number. Edwards sparred
repeatedly with prosecutor Bill Loughery. Loughery hammered at
Edwards' alleged romantic affair with Lyons, a key to the
prosecution's claims that the pair conspired in a racketeering
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards adamantly denied an affair, even as she admitted she and
Lyons jointly purchased a luxury $700,000 waterfront home in St.
Petersburg, Fla., a time-share condo in Lake Tahoe, Nev., and took
trips to Hawaii and Nassau.
</P>
<P>
   The house, the time-share and the trips were strictly for
Baptist business, Edwards insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you know Deborah Lyons, Rev. Lyons' wife,'' Loughery
asked. ``What did you tell her about the house you bought
together?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a business agreement with Dr. Lyons,'' Edwards
replied. ``Dr. Lyons did not share the house with me. I was not
aware of what Dr. Lyons told his wife about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards admitted she turned away a couple one night when they
visited her at the luxury Don Cesar Hotel in St. Petersburg, coming
to the door in her pajamas and saying Dr. Lyons was in the room
with her.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said she lied about having Lyons in the room with her
because she wanted to get rid of the couple.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards also admitted lying about her educational background,
telling one executive from one of the companies she had a degree
from Columbia University, and another that she had done graduate
work at Cornell, despite having no college degree.
</P>
<P>
   She admitted telling that lie often.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found myself often in a situation where people felt you've
got to have a degree to have a job,'' she said. ``It was to
establish who I was and what I was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards also tried to turn the tables on the company executives
who claim she and Lyons agreed to sell them a list of the
convention's supposed 8.5 million members though they knew no such
list existed. The executives also knew there was no list, but
continued providing money to help Edwards and Lyons compile it, she
testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no complaint and it was my understanding they were
very pleased,'' she said, referring to Globe Insurance Co., which
paid the pair $1 million for the names.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards also said executives from Loewen, a Canadian funeral
services company, hoped she might help them get an unfavorable
civil court ruling in Mississippi reversed.
</P>
<P>
   The company lost a huge judgment to black funeral homes, who
claimed it was buying up their businesses unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards went to Mississippi at Loewen's request, where she met
an attorney who gave her names and addresses of the jurors and
asked her to get them to say they were bribed to rule against
Loewen, she testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (a Loewen executive) I was not going to tamper with
that jury in Mississippi,'' Edwards testified.
</P>
<P>
   But a month later, Edwards took a $1 million payment from the
company and continued doing public relations work to try to repair
its image, she testified.
</P>
<P>
   The case is expected to go to the jury sometime next week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
