<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MEANINGLESS TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Know what Roger Clemens being traded to the Yankees means?
Absolutely nothing. The Yankees won the AL East by 22 games last
year. So what if they win by 23 games this year? All this trade
means for the Yankee is that they added $3 million to their payroll
to buy insurance for a pennant. For the Blue Jays, it means they're
off the hook for $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Let me get this straight. Toronto trades Clemens to the Yankees,
and the Boston media kick the Red Sox and Dan Duquette all over the
place. What did the Red Sox have to do with the Toronto-New York
trade?
</P>
<P>
   Think Blue Jays fans are as busted up over Clemens leaving town,
even after he won back-to-back Cy Young Awards? For an answer,
consider what Clemens, in all his greatness, did to get Toronto
closer to a pennant. Absolutely nothing. The Blue Jays finished
farther behind in the East _ and lost more money _ than before his
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   And as a bonus, Clemens stuck the Jays with Tim ``Rambo''
Johnson, his personal choice for manager when he was calling the
shots for the organization. Johnson, who invented for himself a
phony career as a Vietnam war hero, remains in Toronto even after
his sponsor, the Texas Con Man, is gone.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of the Clemens deal is yet to come. We'll see his
real act about halfway through the season, when he doesn't want to
stay in the same hotel with his teammates or ride on the same bus,
or wants permission to go home to Houston for a weekend so he can
be with his kids. We'll see how Mr. Me fits in with a Yankee team
that reportedly is close and played like it a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   More baseball:
</P>
<P>
   --Funniest line of the week came from an Associated Press story
out of Arizona: ``I wanted to come by and say hello to the
fellas,'' said Mo Money, showing up early at the Angels training
camp, ``and let them know work starts now.'' Wow. What a
revelation. I'm sure this greeting by Mo Vaughn fired up his new
teammates. They probably didn't realize what a physical
fitness/weight conscious/nutrition devotee he is. Why, he might
even weigh in this year, something he wouldn't do with the Red Sox
even though the Sox claim they had a weight clause in his contract
that Mo Money chose to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   --This Andres Galarraga development could be bad news for the
Red Sox. They have been talking with the Chicago White Sox about a
trade for slugging first baseman Frank Thomas. The White Sox have
told interested teams that they might deal Thomas after spring
training, when they can look at the prospects of the interested
teams. Colorado and Seattle are already in the hunt along with
Boston. But, just like the Yankees, when the Braves need a player
they usually buy one with Ted Turner's money or make a trade for
one. With Galarraga gone for at least a year because of a cancerous
tumor in his back, Atlanta will be looking for someone to play
first base.
</P>
<P>
   --Last fall, after Mo Money left town, I spoke with Carl
Yastrzemski and he made a statement that every Red Sox fan should
read carefully: ``The Red Sox are a good four or five solid players
away from the Yankees. One guy is not going to make the difference.
The Yankees just have far more talent than the Sox do right now.''
Mo Money, Pedro Martinez, Nomar Garciappara, and some other Boston
players had fantastic seasons last year, and the Red Sox still
finished 22 games behind.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line. Until the Red Sox can get a new ballpark to
generate the same revenue as the Yankees, Baltimore, and Cleveland,
they will not be able to compete with those clubs. For now, the Sox
are in the same boat as about 25 other major league teams, all of
whom have no chance of winning the World Series because they can't
compete, in spending, like the top revenue-generating teams.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Giants are opposed to the Patriots moving to
Hartford and will vote against it when the time comes. The Giants
consider Hartford to be their market and feel the Patriots' move
would violate some of the critical elements of the NFL's guidelines
on team relocation. While Giants Stadium was being built in the
mid-1970s, the Giants played their home games at Yale Bowl in New
Haven, which is essentially the same market at Hartford. If the NFL
considered that part of Connecticut was a Patriots market, there is
no way the league would have allowed the Giants to play
regular-season home games there. In fact, in 1974 the Patriots
played a regular-season game in Yale Bowl vs. the Giants, as the
VISITING team.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bruins boss Harry Sinden is not happy with the team's fade over
the last 17 games (3-11-3). ``I'm shocked and totally surprised,''
he said. ``I never thought something like this could happen to our
club. Before the year, we thought we had the most promising young
team in the league. We had 93 points last year. We thought our
biggest problem could be Joe Thornton. We wondered if he could come
along and be the center we thought he could be. Thorton has done
that. He's become a heck of a center, playing better every game.
Our goalies and our defense have played well. It's the forwards who
have fallen apart. We're not scoring. We've got nothing out of a
power play that a year ago was pretty good and we thought would be
better. We've got to get things turned around here before the
playoffs. I think we can do it. And if we start playing the way we
can coming down the stretch, then we could got into the playoffs
playing well and do some damage. This team is too good to play the
way it is playing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ben Lipson, an insurance expert who often writes for this
newspaper, is right on the money when he says, ``The Robert Edwards
case should make every agent and every player aware of how
important insurance can be. The agents should see to it that every
player with a substantial future is covered not only for his
present contract but for whatever his insurable interest is for the
future. To do something like this to protect athletes away from the
playing field against disabling injury does not cost a lot of money
and would be money well spent.'' Edwards, who probably lost his
career to a disabling knee injury at a rookie beach flag football
game in Hawaii during Pro Bowl festivities, is covered by an
insurance policy for the remaining four years of his contract.
However, if he had stayed healthy he would have almost assuredly
been able to have a 10-year career in the NFL. That is six years
more of coverage he could have had but didn't.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston College is trying to work out a five-year extension of
its football series with Notre Dame. The present arrangement runs
out in 2004. The new proposal would extend the series to at least
2009, with Notre Dame getting three of the five home games . . .
April could be an interesting month in local courthouses. Drew
Bledsoe is due to go to court April 5 for the Paradise stage-diving
episode, and jury selection in the Reggie Lewis malpractice case is
scheduled to begin April 26 . . . Dumb and Dumber Department: Some
of the hosts on the local sports talk show station, NWR (Nit-Wit
Radio), were at it again this week, getting excited about Samuel L.
Jackson's one-liner knocking the Red Sox for spending so much money
on Jose Offerman. Fellas. Samuel L. wouldn't know Jose Offerman
from Jose Feliciano. All the material for ESPY Awards presenters is
written by professional writers, some of them from ``Saturday Night
Live.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Question for the Patriots: A week ago you had short money under
the salary cap (less than $200,000) to sign center Dave Wohlabaugh,
your best offensive lineman and one of the most important players
on your team. Wohlabaugh signs with Cleveland as a free agent. This
week you restructure the contracts of Chris Slade and Vincent
Brisby to give you more money to spend, money that could have been
used to sign Wohlabaugh. Why didn't you restructure a week ago? Or
do you need the money to strike a new deal with Ty Law or Lawyer
Milloy? The new Slade and Brisby deals have created more than $2.1
million for the Patriots . . . The Saints reportedly offered to
trade running back Lamar Smith to the Patriots for draft choices,
but the Patriots didn't want any part of the deal . . . Some of the
top businessmen in the city attended a get-together hosted by Chad
Gifford, top gun at BankBoston, to tell Red Sox CEO John Harrington
that they wanted to help the Sox build a new ballpark, and to tell
the Sox to reach out for their help when necessary. The Red Sox
still have not completed the financial part of the deal, which is
why they have not come forward with their plans for a new Fenway
Park.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
