<SLUG> BC-LIBYA-UN-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBYA ASKS U.N. TO CLARIFY PAN-AM TRIAL RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Libya has asked Secretary-General Kofi Annan to
clarify assurances that he has given to try to persuade Libya to
turn over two suspects in the bombing of a Pan American flight over
Scotland in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the United Nations, Fred Eckhard, would not
comment on the nature of Libya's apparent unhappiness with the
assurances given to its leader, Col. Moammar Gadhafi, nor would he
say what clarifications or assurances Gadhafi was seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Eckhard said only that Libya had made ``preliminary
observations'' about the letter sent this week to Tripoli via the
Libyan mission to the United Nations. He added that the
secretary-general was studying the Libyan response, which was made
``orally and informally.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials, along with U.S. and British diplomats, have said
little about the contents of Annan's letter, which offered
assurances made on behalf of the United States and Britain, which
for years have been struggling to arrange a trial.
</P>
<P>
   But diplomats have said the secretary-general had assured
Gadhafi that the economic sanctions imposed in 1992 would be
removed if the two suspects were turned over to a Scottish court
for trial in the Netherlands and that they would be fairly and
properly treated at the trial and in jail, if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Annan is also said to have assured Tripoli that the trial will
involve ``no attempt to undermine'' the Libyan government, the
diplomats added.
</P>
<P>
   That last assurance has led some relatives of the 270 people
killed in the bombing over Lockerbie to contend that the Clinton
administration is making concessions that would avoid implicating
top Libyan officials in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   A group of families led by Susan Cohen of Cape May, N.J., issued
a statement that criticized the assurances and said that the
administration appeared to have made a further commitment that
would delay justice. ``The limitations that will be placed on the
prosecutors,'' the group said, ``will make the conviction of the
two suspects much more difficult and, perhaps, impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``defense,'' the families added, ``could insist that many
lines of inquiry would undermine the Libyan regime and must be
excluded from the trial.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Daniel Cohen, father of a 20-year-old killed in the blast, said
officials had told him that if convicted the suspects would be kept
in the Netherlands until the appeals process had been exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   If the men are convicted, exhaust their appeals and eventually
reach Scotland, Cohen said, ``they will be housed in their own
special jail wing, which will in a variety of ways essentially be
under the supervision of the United Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   He argued that those steps would set a dangerous precedent.
``Will all future terrorist prisoners be able to call for
comfortable conditions and U.N. supervisions?'' Cohen asked.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the victims' relatives agreed. Some said they were not
unhappy with the assurances if they can persuade Gadhafi to let the
suspects be tried. Others said they would wait and see what
assurances Annan has made on behalf of the British and Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is to begin reviewing the economic sanctions
against Libya next Friday. The Clinton administration has warned
that unless Gadhafi has turned over the suspects by then, it will
press to expand the sanctions.
</P>
</TEXT>
