r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     02-19 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLANDSWORTH WILL BIDE HIS TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ On the first day of official workouts,
Dodgers outfielder Todd Hollandsworth rescinded his offseason
request to be traded. Sort of. Well, at least until the outfield
situation plays itself out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's a dead issue because there's nothing to do
except go out and play,'' Hollandsworth said Friday. ``We get a
month into the season, two months into the season, we'll see where
we're at. That's the only way I can look at it right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the offseason, if you could change the situation then, it's
a good time to change it because nothing is going on. But here we
are now, I have a job that I have to focus on and get it done, so
that's what I focus on.''
</P>
<P>
   During the offseason, Hollandsworth's agent, Jeff Moorad, said
his client wanted to be traded because Hollandsworth didn't want
the tag of being a fourth outfielder at the age of 25.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth, the National League Rookie of the Year in `96,
wants to be an everyday outfielder but for now is content _ or
somewhat so _ to remain with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   It could be difficult for Hollandsworth to break into the
starting outfield, which consists of Devon White, Raul Mondesi and
Gary Sheffield. But he could get more playing time than the average
extra outfielder since, during the last five years, White has
averaged 113 games and Sheffield has averaged 115 games while
battling injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job right now is to make (manager) Davey Johnson's job very
difficult and that's what I intend to do,'' said Hollandsworth, who
batted .269 last season but missed the final 103 games with a
cartilage tear in his left shoulder. Hollandsworth, a career .269
hitter with 24 homers and 123 RBI in 351 games, said he'll wait a
few months, see how often he plays and how he performs, before
bringing up the trade situation again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play, that's the bottom line,'' Hollandsworth said.
``I love the Dodgers. I've been in the Dodgers organization for a
long time. I know this clubhouse, I know L.A.'s clubhouse. I know
the L.A. area. I like it and nothing is wrong with any of it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Late arrivals: The most notable pitcher not in camp was
right-handed closer Jeff Shaw. He was granted permission by the
club to remain home in Washington Court House, Ohio, with his wife,
Julie, who is expected to give birth to the couple's third child
any day. Also, right-handed pitching prospect Luke Prokopec, the
Dodgers' Minor League Player of the Year last season, had visa
problems in his native Australia and wasn't expected in until late
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   __ Looking ahead: If nothing else, Dodgers general manager Kevin
Malone certainly knows how to give a sound byte that is sure to get
noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about the Yankees acquisition of Roger Clemens, Malone
said, ``It'll be nice to see Kevin Brown and Roger Clemens match up
in October. That's my goal, anyway. You have to have vision.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Camp talk: While the workout was mostly set for pitchers and
catchers, seven other players who are rehabbing injuries were in
attendance. They were outfielders Hiram Bocachica, Hollandsworth
and Kevin Gibbs and infielders Eric Young, Jose Vizcaino, Adam
Riggs and Tripp Cromer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 2040EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
