<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2211 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-LOUGANIS21-COX     02-19 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-LOUGANIS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keeping to a medication schedule is crucial for HIV patients _
but hard. A new program aims to make it easier.
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 21.
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greg Louganis knows the value of sticking to a routine. He
didn't collect five Olympic medals _ four gold, one silver _ and
earn acclaim as the world's greatest diver without vigilant
self-discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when it came to taking daily HIV medicine, Louganis could be
just as lax as the next person.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was on a three-a-day dosing schedule, it was usually
the `nooner' I'd forget,'' the 39-year-old diving legend admitted
during a recent interview. ``The one dose everyone misses is the
one in the middle of the day, and I've been guilty of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Louganis is promoting a new program, ``Gaining Optimal Adherence
for Life,'' or GOAL, aimed at improving compliance with HIV drug
regimens. The program was developed by Hoffmann-La Roche, the
manufacturer of two HIV drugs, Fortovase and ddC, and is free to
patients taking Fortovase.
</P>
<P>
   With any other disease, skipping a few drug doses wouldn't
matter so much. With HIV medications, however, missed doses can
quickly result in drug resistance _ a serious problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some evidence to suggest that even small amounts of
missed doses can affect the effects of the drugs,'' said Dr. Cal
Cohen, research director at CRI New England, a community-based
research group near Boston. ``People who miss even 5 percent of
their doses have less success.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 survey found that 43 percent of patients admitted not
properly taking their HIV medicine. The same survey reported that
HIV specialists estimated that 54 percent of their patients weren't
adhering to their regimens.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for poor adherence vary. In many cases, patients simply
forget a dose. Some take ``drug holidays,'' during which they stop
HIV drugs because of debilitating side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Young children with HIV pose special difficulties, said Dr.
Steven Nesheim, medical director of pediatrics in the infectious
diseases program at Grady Memorial Hospital's Ponce de Leon Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person giving the medicine is a third party, as opposed to
an adult who can take it himself,'' Nesheim said. ``You have to
rely on the mother, who also is probably the mother of more than
one child.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that infants and young children will reject
medicine if they dislike it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids vomit it back up if it tastes really bad,'' Nesheim said
wryly. ``It's hard to keep forcing medicines on them.''
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of Nesheim's young patients are no longer
responding fully to their HIV drugs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And while a limited number of drug options are available for
adults, even fewer can be used in children. Not all HIV drugs are
available in liquid formulation; capsules and pills are harder for
young children to take, especially since several must be taken at
once.
</P>
<P>
   Louganis learned about the importance of adherence the hard way,
when he developed resistance and had to switch drugs. He had
experienced harsh side effects from his previous drugs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In developing a new regimen, he was careful to consult with his
doctor about a regimen that he could tolerate and that would suit
his lifestyle. Together, they decided on a combination of drugs
that required only two daily doses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to find a regimen you can live with,'' said Louganis,
who lives in Malibu, Calif., but travels often. ``So you have to be
honest with yourself, you have to be honest with your doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   Louganis, who has been HIV-positive for more than a decade, said
he's feeling ``great'' and exercising daily, although he appeared
somewhat drawn and tired during a recent interview in Chicago.
``Everything's pretty stable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the GOAL program receive five mailings over 21
weeks, which include a pillbox, a diary for tracking daily doses
and a videotape featuring Louganis talking about adherence.
</P>
<P>
   The pillbox is a nifty contraption made of 21 interlocking boxes
that separate a week's worth of drugs into individual doses. The
whole thing disassembles, allowing people to carry individual
doses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If health care providers sit down and take the time to explain
the dosing and why it's important, and offer tips on how to achieve
this, patients tend to have better adherence,'' said Dan Dunable, a
treatment resource specialist at the AIDS Survival Project in
Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   Both pillboxes and diaries are considered invaluable tools,
Dunable said. Many people also need daily reminders to take their
drugs. Dunable suggests people leave notes to themselves or enlist
friends or family members to remind them.
</P>
<P>
   He himself depends on a wristwatch alarm to stay on schedule.
Dunable takes a total of 22 pills a day, of which only 10 actually
are anti-HIV drugs. The rest are antibiotics and other drugs
prescribed to ward off the infections that take advantage of
HIV-weakened immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his medicines, Dunable takes supplements such as
vitamins and anti-oxidants, which he believes are helpful.
</P>
<P>
   It all adds up to five different doses per day. Two should be
taken with meals, three must be taken on an empty stomach _ no food
for two hours before or one hour after the dose.
</P>
<P>
   It's the most restrictive drug regimen Dunable has had in his 10
years of HIV therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten used to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Five times a day the watch beeps. He wakes to the 7 a.m. alarm
and takes his morning dose. At noon the watch beeps to warn Dunable
he has one hour left to eat lunch, before his second dose. It next
goes off at 3 p.m. for the third set of pills, then again at 8 p.m.
to remind Dunable he has one hour left to eat dinner before taking
the fourth dose. The last alarm sounds at 11 p.m. for his bedtime
pills.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this watch ever goes bad, I'll have to go out and find
another one,'' Dunable said.
</P>
<P>
   Louganis will be in Atlanta Wednesday to sign copies of his new
book, ``For the Life of Your Dog,'' a guide for dog owners. The
book signing will be at 7 p.m. at the Chapter 11 bookstore in
Atlanta. For details call 404-872-7986.
</P>
<P>
   Those interested in the GOAL program should consult their
physician or pharmacist for confidential enrollment forms, or call
1-800-910-4687. For other information on adherence, contact the
AIDS Survival Project at 404-874-7926.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
