<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-FALLNOTES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tastemakers go with flow as styles shift, trends evolve
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pity the fool who's a self-described ``fashion
know-it-all.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's any lesson to take away from the Fashion Week
experience, it's that everyone here knows something about looking
good, but no one knows everything.
</P>
<P>
   Vogue editor Anna Wintour doesn't always wear her infamous
sunglasses at the most appropriate times. And sometimes, the
get-ups groupies wear in hopes of gaining back-door entry into a
show don't look so ridiculous after all.
</P>
<P>
   The more times one attends Fashion Week in one of the world's
fashion capitals, the greater one's realization of how much more
there is to learn from the jet-setters who (supposedly) know the
most about style.
</P>
<P>
   Read on if you're interested in a few style pointers gleaned
from a week spent hobnobbing with the people whose tastes determine
what will be available for you to wear.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Change is good: Styles evolve. Paths alter. Get used to it.
Everything that's fashionable is in flux right now: from the
advertising campaigns designers can dare risk, to the colors and
styles they think they can compel people to wear, to the corporate
conglomerates controlling the clothing industry. The best response
to all that change, say Anne Klein design chiefs Ken Kaufman and
Isaac Franco, is to relax and do what comes naturally.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Here comes the bride, all dressed in . . . Tahari:
</P>
<P>
   That's how Atlanta native Rory Green, 26, should be serenaded
when she weds forward-thinking designer Elie Tahari sometime this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Tahari, 46, said he's in the process of designing the gown his
bride _ daughter of Barbara Portman and advertising executive Keith
Green _ will wear on their wedding day. And at lunch Friday in the
Tahari showroom, Green said there'll be little room for any other
designer label in her closets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swear, when I walked in and saw his collection for fall for
the first time, tears came to my eyes,'' she said. ``I'm so proud
of him. He really blew me away. And I'm so happy I'm his fiancee
because I get to have every single piece of it!''
</P>
<P>
   What Tahari sends to stores for fall will represent his most
modernistic men's and womens wear to date. It centers on stretch
fabrics with jackets that wear as easy as shirts, and pants and
skirts with silhouettes as clean and fluid as filtered water.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how living with Green has influenced his design approach,
Tahari responded (half jokingly): ``Every day she tells me
something like, `That doesn't fit right,' or `What were you
thinking when you designed this?' It's mostly complaints. On the
other hand, she used to wear clothes for old ladies. And now I've
got her wearing (the bridge line) Theory, and she looks younger and
looks better.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
