A2213 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-NYSHOWS20-COX     02-19 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-NYSHOWS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Talking about Tommy: Hilfiger's mixed bag
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In order to have live musical accompaniment for his
fall/winter show at the Roseland Ballroom on Thursday night,
Hilfiger had to turn to the ``it'' band, Sugar Ray.
</P>
<P>
   What a pity. Sugar Ray's current hit, ``Every Morning,'' is
unquestionably catchy, but it didn't suit Hilfiger's show as well
as the The Rolling Stones', ``It's Only Rock and Roll (But I Like
It),'' might have.
</P>
<P>
   In a round-about way, Hilfiger hinted after the show, for both
men's and women's styles, that he was less intent on unveiling what
would make it to major department stores this fall than on showing
buyers, editors and groupies something worth talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I only showed our jeans and our sportswear, you'd all be
bored,'' Hilfiger said.
</P>
<P>
   Not entirely. Hilfiger bit into the trend toward zippered hems,
cuffs and closures wholeheartedly, and it's intriguing the way his
zip-legged, studded jeans offer wearers the choice of straight or
flared legs to suit their footwear. (In keeping with the show's
rock-and-roll theme, most models in the show wore rowdy-looking
biker boots.)
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger refered to the clothes he showed as, ``a mixed bag
consisting of our jeans, sportswear and Collection (with a capital
``C'').'' The jeans and sportswear will actually make it onto
mainstream stores' sales floors, while most of the collection will
go only to the toniest of retailers, and Hilfiger's imposing
flagship store on Beverly Hills' Rodeo Drive.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to distinguish the upscale goods (i.e. French-cuffed
shirts and pin-tucked leather dresses) from the clothes meant for
the masses (T-shirts and track pants) because of the way Hilfiger
combined them. Cashmere jackets were worn over nylon ski pants.
Nylon ``parachute'' skirts were paired with cashmere tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I constantly have to ask myself, 'What makes us different?',''
Hilfiger said. ``And the answer is that we're mixing high and low
as we have always done. A cashmere sweater from Collection with a
pair of nylon pants from the Tommy Jeans line. That is what I
consider modern.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan: In her attempt to define a look for the millenial
woman, Donna Karan's gone back to the future.
</P>
<P>
   Karan returned to the opaque black stocking that was her
hallmark when her best designing days were ahead of her, and used
it as the basis of a skirt-heavy fall/winter collection. These
weren't just any skirts: they were more like blankets made of the
finest cashmere, and wrapped sculpturally around the waist for
freedom of movement and dramatic visuals. The swaying of the skirts
was tempered by the slim-shouldered jackets and second-skin
sweaters Karan designed in keeping with the trendy A-line
silhouette. Her color scheme consisted of black, dark brown, greys,
off-whites and pale camels. Fabrics ranged from multi-ply cashmeres
to leathers to silks (for her slim, creased pants) and nylons that
glistened like glass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
