<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The flared leg flattering for men
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The thighs have it. Menswear designers are trying to
usher in a new silhouette for casual pants in which there's a
gradual flare out from the knee.
</P>
<P>
   Style-conscious men might view this look as skeptically as they
did the slim, flat-front slacks of recent seasons. But as designer
John Bartlett demonstrated with the outfit (a skintight black
leather blazer, cashmere turtleneck and flared moleskin jeans) he
wore to the Saks Fifth Avenue party, the flared-leg look is
flattering on men with muscular thighs, a slim waist and broad
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   As Bartlett cruised the party, the cartoon character Popeye kept
coming to mind.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
