<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2215 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-SURVEY20-COX     02-19 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-SURVEY20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Digging into gardening
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What's up with these people who spend hours in
Internet chat rooms dishing the dirt on daisies?
</P>
<P>
   Who sets their clock for 6 a.m. Saturday so they can beat other
callers to radio talk shows seeking solutions to problems with
aphids, black spot and powdery mildew?
</P>
<P>
   Whose idea of shopping is dragging a squeaky wagon behind them
laden with 40-pound bags of compost that straddle the sides like
love handles on a baby boomer?
</P>
<P>
   Americans have gone gaga over gardening, and metro Atlantans are
no exception. ``It's big, really big here,'' said Walter Reeves,
the Georgia Extension Service's horticulture educator.
</P>
<P>
   Just how much do you dig it?
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution wants to know your horticulture
habits. Please take a few minutes to complete our questionnaire
below and mail it to us.
</P>
<P>
   Participation makes you eligible to win one of three $100 gift
certificates to a garden center. And what gardener can't use that
kind of green stuff this time of year?
</P>
<P>
   We'll share the survey results in April and call you if you win.
</P>
<P>
   We want to know what drives you to garden, how much time and
money you devote to it, and what you ultimately gain from it.
Research shows:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gardening is the No. 1 hobby in America, practiced by 72
million people. It is a $76 billion-a-year industry; golf, by
comparison, weighs in at $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Annual retail sales of flowering plants jumped more than 41
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The number of Americans who identify themselves as gardeners
has risen more than 30 percent in the past three years, and baby
boomers make up 60 percent of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just Grandma anymore,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
