<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2217 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TREASURY-THEFT-BOS     02-19 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-THEFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY WORKER CHARGED IN ALLEGED THEFT   SCHEME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Lottery-Theft)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE AND MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A supervisor in the Massachusetts treasurer's office
was charged Friday with conspiring with a New Hampshire ``heir
hunter'' to steal $6.5 million in unclaimed state checks. The
scheme, which authorities hinted may be part of a much larger
conspiracy, was carried out in a department plagued by lax controls
and poor supervision, Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly and new
Treasurer Shannon O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   John Trischitta, 47, of Stoneham, surrendered Friday and pleaded
not guilty at Boston Municipal Court to charges that he accepted
$50,000 in bribes to forward $6.5 million in state checks to a bank
account set up by Martin Robbins, 51, of Lincoln, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins, who tracks owners of unclaimed money for a percentage
of the funds, was arrested Thursday night at his home. Skeptical
administrators at BankBoston, where Robbins allegedly deposited the
money, blew the whistle when he attempted to withdraw the money on
Feb. 10, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said Friday it is unknown whether other money has been
fraudulently funneled from the state's unclaimed fund account. But
he characterized the alleged scheme as a startlingly easy maneuver
in a department found to have had ``no real checks, no real
balances and no controls to speak of.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not Mr. Robbins' money,'' Reilly said at a news
conference. to ``This was the people's money. This was nothing
other but a ripoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta, a 20-year employee of the treasurer's office, was
elevated about eight years ago during former Treasurer Joseph
Malone's administration from a teller's job in the State House to
be a supervisor in the unclaimed check department. In that
position, the attorney general's office said, he had sole
responsibility over the unclaimed check fund.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say Trischitta authorized the transfer on Nov. 6,
1998, of two checks _ for $5.3 million and $1.2 million -- from the
state fund to an escrow account established by Robbins. State
government sources said that procedures to verify claims on
unclaimed monies had been relaxed in July, when Malone still
controlled the office.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien ordered an indefinite freeze on transactions involving
unclaimed checks.
</P>
<P>
   According to Reilly and O'Brien, the alleged scheme worked this
way: Robbins was tipped off that $6.5 million in state funds for
the Economic Development Investment Corp., an organization run by
the Boston Redevelopment Authority, had been unclaimed since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins then mailed five letters to Trischitta to press his
claims on the money, primarily on behalf of the Cambridge Economic
Development Corp., a now-defunct agency. He produced fraudulent
documents granting him power of attorney for the claimant, Reilly
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the unclaimed check for the EDIC did not match the name
of the purported Cambridge claimant, O'Brien said the similar
initials may have provided cover for Trischitta to approve Robbins'
claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Trischitta was basically Mr. Inside, and Mr. Robbins was
Mr. Outside. They almost got away with it,'' Reilly said. ``It was
pretty simple, and it was pretty easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The men have known each other for about 20 years, O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly and O'Brien, both of whom took office last month, said
they were appalled when they discovered the quality of management
in the treasurer's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have to be proper controls in place and that just was
not the case (under Malone),'' O'Brien said. ``But this is a really
sad day for me. I'm not gloating.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone, reached at home, defended his oversight of the office.
Management techniques were routinely audited by outside firms, and
deficiencies were corrected promptly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Malone also said he believed that the payment of any check over
$500 from the fund needed approval from two officials before it
could be released.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these allegations are true,'' Malone said, ``this employee
had to be out of his mind to think he could get away with it. He
would have had a better chance of robbing his fellow employees at
gunpoint than getting away with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he has never met Trischitta, was not responsible for
his promotion, and has not been contacted by the attorney general's
office or the State Police.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the scandal broke, O'Brien pleaded for funds for a
``top-to-bottom'' audit of the treasurer and Lottery offices.
</P>
<P>
   In her first, failed campaign for treasurer in 1994, when
O'Brien was running against Malone, she sharply criticized the
incumbent for his lax management style. Malone, however, won
reelection with over 60 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by reporters Friday about why it took a call from the
bank before such a large theft was discovered, O'Brien noted that
the problems occurred under the Malone administration. Unclaimed
checks are supposed to be held in the fund supervised by Trischitta
for no more than one year, officials said, instead of the four
years the $6.5 million had languished there.
</P>
<P>
   Because the two checks were for such large amounts of money,
city officials believe the money may have represented part of the
state's payment to the city for land taken for the Central Artery
project.
</P>
<P>
   But those officials said EDIC is not missing that much money. So
it is likely that either the alleged conspirators were able to cash
a duplicate check, or the city was never informed it was due more
funds for the Central Artery land takings.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta, whose home was searched Thursday night by State
Police, was granted $10,000 cash bail Friday during his
arraignment. One of his lawyers, James A. Brescia, described
Trischitta as a ``wonderful, gentle, soft-hearted, soft-spoken
man.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said that because Trischitta was well-regarded in the
agency, the decision was made to retain him when she took office.
Trischitta was suspended with pay.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins, charged with larceny and forgery, waived extradition
Friday and was held on $1 million bail.
</P>
</TEXT>
