<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2221 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-725&AMP;ADD-N     02-19 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON INCREASES PRESSURE ON MILOSEVIC AS DEADLINE NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: France, Great Britain)  (Eds: See also KOSOVO-TALKS, KOSOVO-MOOD) 
(mk) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton warned President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia on Friday not to ``stonewall'' a peace
settlement in Kosovo and threatened to bomb Serbia if Milosevic
misses the Saturday deadline for an end to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Intent on increasing the pressure on Milosevic, Clinton said it
would be a mistake to extend the noon deadline (6 a.m. ET) and
praised the ``courage'' of the negotiators representing the
Albanian Kosovars at the talks in Rambouillet, France. But the
president set no clear timetable for military action.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic refused on Friday even to meet with the American
ambassador, Christopher Hill. Clinton said that allowing a peace
agreement and permitting NATO peacekeepers into Serbia was the best
way to guarantee that Kosovo remains part of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   With President Jacques Chirac of France at his side during a
White House news conference, Clinton emphasized that an agreement
in France, which has been endorsed in broad outline by the Albanian
Kosovar delegates, would compel the Albanian Kosovars to give up
their demands for independence for at least three years.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the U.S. and France ``stand united in our
determination to use force, if Serbia fails to meet its previous
commitment to withdraw forces from Kosovo and if it fails to accept
the peace agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is an option'' other than NATO airstrikes,
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, who has remained in Belgrade during the negotiations
in France, repeated Friday that he would not accept an
international peacekeeping force inside the Serbian province of
Kosovo. He refused to meet with Hill, declaring, instead, that he
would not surrender Kosovo ``even at the price of bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, Clinton telephoned British Prime Minister Tony
Blair and the two leaders agreed that Milosevic ``should be under
no illusion about our resolve should he prevent a deal'' on Kosovo,
according to a White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference Friday, Clinton underlined that the NATO
allies would not allow Milosevic to talk his way out of a real
troop withdrawal, as he did last October.
</P>
<P>
   Then, NATO also threatened the Serbian leader with airstrikes if
he did not pull back his forces following their bloody summer
offensive that led to the massacre of well over 1,000 Kosovo
civilians, the destruction of 200 villages and the driving from
their homes of some 400,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   But after nine straight days of negotiations in Belgrade between
the American envoy, Richard Holbrooke, and Milosevic, NATO ended up
settling for an unarmed monitoring mission rather than a full
withdrawal down to the agreed- upon level of 15,000 Serbian troops
and police.
</P>
<P>
   Both the French and British withdrew their nonessential embassy
staff from Belgrade on Friday. The United States authorized the
departure of family members and nonemergency employees at its
embassy but withheld ordering a nearly full departure. That could
very well come Saturday if Milosevic does not meet the noon
deadline, according to a State Department official.
</P>
<P>
   Both the United States and Britain also issued advisories Friday
against travel to Yugoslavia, with the British citing ``the
increasingly volatile situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The members of the Kosovo Verification Mission, established by
last October's negotiations, are also expected to be withdrawn by
NATO troops in neighboring Macedonia, according to allied
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be a mistake to extend the deadline,''
Clinton said Friday at the joint press conference, the first since
his acquittal on impeachment charges one week ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have ordered our aircraft to be ready to act as part of a
NATO operation,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no agreement and NATO decides to strike, it could
take 48 to 72 hours before the bombing begins, according to Clinton
administration officials. In late January, NATO gave its
authorization for strikes against Serbian military targets in
Kosovo and Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, the Pentagon ordered more B-52s to join NATO
forces in Europe to prepare for a possible bombing mission against
Serbia. In addition, the United States this week sent F-117 Stealth
fighters and refueling aircraft.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The planning for a bombing campaign has been drawn around two
phases, according to Pentagon officials. The first would be an
attack by Cruise missiles launched from battleships on the Adriatic
Sea.
</P>
<P>
   If Milosevic continues to resist accepting a settlement, this
attack would be followed by concerted allied air attacks on the
Serbian air defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics of the administration's Kosovo policy say NATO
seems to be serious about striking Serbia this time, although it
has threatened strikes before only to extend deadlines to persuade
Milosevic to end the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now NATO's credibility is truly on the line,'' said Ivo
Daalder, a Balkan specialist formerly at the National Security
Council. ``Not to follow through on a serious threat tied to a
serious deadline would fundamentally undermine the alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Allied diplomats and administration officials say Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, the French foreign minister, Hubert
Vedrine, and the British foreign minister, Robin Cook, may go to
Belgrade over the weekend if it appears that such a high-level
delegation could convince Milosevic to accept the peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   While allied leaders were threatening Milosevic, their military
forces were moving closer to Kosovo to take part in a peacekeeping
mission should an agreement be reached. Last weekend the United
States joined the British and French in making formal troop
commitments for the initial force that could arrive in the Kosovo
capital of Pristina as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 2,000 Marines are sailing toward the Greek port of
Thessaloniki on the Aegean Sea, where British ships are also
expected to land and unload heavy equipment for their troops.
British soldiers will be flown into the airport in Macedonia and
then driven into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The United States will also provide the NATO headquarters in
Pristina with command &AMP; control, telecommunication and intelligence
experts, according to Pentagon officials, for the initial phase of
the peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are preparing for war and we are preparing for peace,''
said Kenneth Bacon, the Pentagon spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   At the afternoon news conference, Clinton was also asked what he
had learned from the past year of investigation and impeachment.
Adopting a thoughtful expression, he said he came away with an
enhanced respect for the Constitution and its framers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Constitution has been, in effect, re-ratified,''
Clinton said. ``And I hope the presidency has not been harmed. I
don't believe it has been.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he added, ``I can't say that I think this has been good
for the country. But we will see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 2055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
