<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2222 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-ABORTION-NYT &LR;      02-19 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSPECTION OF ABORTION CLINIC PROMPTS A CLAIM OF HARASSMENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La.)   By TAMAR LEWIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Louisiana's latest skirmish over abortion began with an
investigative report on television and has moved into the courts.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 5, the day after WAFB, the CBS affiliate in Baton Rouge,
broadcast a report on unsanitary conditions at a local abortion
clinic, Gov. Mike Foster declared a health emergency and issued an
executive order telling public health officers to inspect the
clinic and ``all other medical and health-related facilities in the
state of Louisiana which are not being regularly inspected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The pictures they showed were pretty grotesque,'' Trey
Williams, the governor's deputy press secretary, said of the
report. ``There were instruments that had rust on them. There were
drops of blood on the floor, on the tables. It was appalling. The
governor is pro-life, that's no secret, but that's not what this is
about. Abortion is legal in the United States, it's legal here in
Louisiana, and we want to make sure that the women who receive
these procedures have them in a sanitary, safe medical way.''
</P>
<P>
   Abortion-rights advocates, however, saw the governor's move as
an effort to harass abortion clinics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake about it, this latest attack on abortion by
the State of Louisiana is not about protecting women's health, but
is intended to shut down abortion clinics,'' Robin Rothrock, the
administrator of a Shreveport clinic, said.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Ms. Rothrock and others filed a lawsuit in U.S.
District Court, challenging the order as a politically motivated
and unconstitutional attempt to put obstacles in the way of women
seeking abortions. The complaint charges that the governor unfairly
singled out abortion clinics, subjected them to unlawful search and
seizure and violated women's rights by providing no protection for
their privacy or the confidentiality of their records.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 5, the day of the executive order, public health
officials inspected the clinic shown in the televised report, Delta
Women's Health Clinic, but found no cause for action.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started out saying they'd inspect all kinds of medical
offices, but when doctors objected, they said it would only be
tattoo parlors, body-piercing places and abortion clinics,'' said
Margie Kelly, a spokeswoman for the Center for Reproductive Law and
Policy, a New York advocacy group that is among those filing the
complaint. ``There's no health reason to single out abortion
clinics.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I don't know about the veracity of the film, I do know
they had inspected this very clinic four months earlier and found
everything in order,'' Ms. Kelly said. ``And the day the order was
issued, they did another surprise inspection and found nothing
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said only the Delta Women's Clinic has been inspected,
and no further surprise inspections were likely unless there are
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``The executive order is broad, intentionally, to allow us to go
in and inspect any facility where we need to protect health, which
would include tattooing parlors, ear-piercing places or medical
offices,'' Williams said. ``But we're not going to go around
busting down doors to get into places where we haven't had any
complaints. This was an emergency situation, but we basically want
to leave the issue to be dealt with by the legislators in their
upcoming session, if they think there's a need.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks a court order preventing enforcement of the
executive order, and awarding damages to the Delta Women's Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the clinic could not be reached.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 2056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
