<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2226 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIVETTI-TELECOM-625&AMP;     02-19 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIVETTI-TELECOM-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVETTI TO CONSIDER BID FOR TELECOM ITALIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany)   (EDS: Skedded as ITALY-PHONE on some advisories.)  
(js) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE and LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Olivetti SpA, the No. 2 Italian telephone company, said
Friday that its board would meet Sunday to discuss a $60 billion
bid to acquire its domestic rival, Telecom Italia &UR; ,  &LR; which is seven
times Olivetti's size.
</P>
<P>
   The bid, if carried out, would be the biggest financial
transaction ever in the European telecommunications industry, and
the first hostile takeover attempt against any of Europe's big
formerly government-owned telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   After the Olivetti board meets, a letter will be sent to Telecom
Italia outlining the bid. Whatever form the offer takes, though, it
is sure to be complicated. People close to the company said it
would be a tender offer for all shares.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be contingent upon Olivetti selling its interests
in two properties _ Infostrada, a new fixed-line operation, and
Omnitel Pronto Italia, a mobile phone provider _ for about $10
billion to Mannesmann AG of Germany, said people close to the
companies. Mannesmann shareholders would have to approve those
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is also expected to be financed in part by
issuing additional shares and through debt. Olivetti has secured
financing from several investment banks, some of which are advising
it on the takeover as well. These include Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette, Lehman Brothers, Italy's Mediobanca and Chase Manhattan
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement that Olivetti's board would discuss a
``significant strategic financial operation'' on Sunday sent
Olivetti shares surging 8.4 percent on the Milan stock exchange, as
speculation rose that it was set to initiate the bid for its far
larger rival. The reports pushed Olivetti's share price up 26 cents
of a euro, to 3.25 euros. Telecom Italia shares were also up, by
2.4 percent, to 9.09 euros.
</P>
<P>
   In what could be the first move of a complex strategy, Olivetti
announced earlier Friday that it had pocketed $375 million from
Mannesmann in exchange for a 12.4 percent stake in Oliman NV, the
Netherlands-based holding company that controls Omnitel and
Infostrada. The deal raised Mannesmann's stake in Oliman to 49.9
percent, with the remainder held by Olivetti.
</P>
<P>
   Should a deal be approved, the financial daily Il Sole 24 Ore
reported Friday, Olivetti might also raise additional cash by
selling Telecom Italia assets.
</P>
<P>
   According to the reports here, Olivetti's chief executive,
Roberto Colaninno, has assembled a consortium of Italian and
international investors to bid for Telecom. The board of Olivetti,
which is based in the northern Italian city of Ivrea, is expected
to approve the plans in its meeting Sunday. The company said the
decision regarding Telecom Italia was the only thing on the board's
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the companies said representatives of Olivetti
had recently contacted Italian government officials and several
Telecom Italia board members seeking support for the takeover.
Telecom Italia's board members are believed to be willing to
consider an offer, but no commitments have been made, these people
said. Government officials have not publicly given Olivetti their
blessing, but they, too, are said to be keeping open minds.
</P>
<P>
   The takeover attempt, if approved by the board, is not
guaranteed success. It is likely to run into resistance from Franco
Bernabe, the tough former head of the big Italian oil company Eni,
who took the reins at Telecom late last year as part of a
management shakeup _ the third in 18 months. Bernabe has not been
involved in merger discussions with executives at Olivetti, people
close to the company said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is far from over,'' said one person close to Telecom
Italia. ``It has just begun.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The deal could also encounter bitter resistance from Telecom
Italia's current major shareholders, who include the powerful
Agnelli family of Fiat. Nor is it known whether other bidders might
join the fray.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian government, which retains a crucial 3.4 percent
stake in Telecom Italia, the national phone company before its
privatization, would have to approve any such deal. And government
approval would probably help any investor group overcome eventual
obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   One of the concerns of government officials, said a person close
the companies, was that Telecom Italia remain an Italian concern. A
handful of foreign companies have had informal discussions with
Telecom Italia, including Vodafone Group PLC, which recently agreed
to acquire Airtouch Communications, the largest wireless company in
the United States. Telecom Italia was interested in Vodafone, but
those talks went nowhere, said the person.
</P>
<P>
   Massimo D'Alema, the Italian prime minister, told reporters
Friday evening that Olivetti executives ``may be biting off more
than they can chew.'' But he said the government would evaluate the
bid, and he added: ``I'd like to express my appreciation of their
courage.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema has said repeatedly that the government would divest
itself of its remaining ``golden share'' sometime this year.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Telecom Italia would not confirm the reports.
Olivetti, in a statement, said only that any question regarding
Telecom Italia ``is a matter exclusively for the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti generates more than two-thirds of its $3.95 billion in
annual revenues from its phone businesses, which it controls
together with Mannesmann.
</P>
<P>
   For the Italian government, the takeover could be a welcome way
of leading the company, the world's sixth-largest phone company, to
a more stable management path. Colaninno is expected to refocus
Telecom, increase efficiency and cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal would also help redesign the landscape of the
European telephone business by affording Mannesmann a gateway to
the southern European phone market. Mannesmann, once noted for
steel pipes and heavy machinery, has emerged in recent years as a
powerful telecommunications group and the main challenger to
Europe's largest phone company, Deutsche Telekom AG.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two months, rumors of an impending deal had
swirled around Olivetti, despite the company's insistence that
reports of a takeover of Telecom Italia were ``unfounded and
impracticable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Italian stock market regulator, Consob, said Friday that it
was examining that denial in the light of the day's developments.
It added that it had opened an inquiry into possible insider
trading of Telecom Italia shares because of especially heavy
trading on Thursday, when roughly two percent of Olivetti's total
capitalization, or about $1 billion, changed hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
