<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHIRAC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HOPES `PRESIDENCY HAS NOT BEEN HARMED' BY SCANDAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Appearing weary and pensive, President Clinton said
Friday the Constitution was ``in effect re-ratified'' by the
impeachment process that finally acquitted him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, joined by French President Jacques Chirac, held his
first news conference since the Senate last week rejected charges
of perjury and obstruction of justice made by House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The president also renewed his endorsement of his wife, first
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, should she decide to run for the
Senate from New York, saying she would ``do a fabulous job.''
</P>
<P>
   The president was asked if he had learned any lessons following
the ordeal of his 13-month scandal involving his affair with a
former White House intern and his attempts to hide it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I've learned a lot of personal lessons, most of
which I have already discussed. And presidents are people, too. I
have learned, again, an enormous amount of respect for our
Constitution, our framers and for the American people,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Constitution has been, in effect, re-ratified. And
I hope that the presidency has not been harmed. I don't believe it
has been,'' Clinton said. ``I can't say that I think this has been
good for the country. But we will see.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate failed to muster a majority vote for the two
impeachment charges. The Constitution requires a two-thirds vote to
remove a president from office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Andrew Johnson are the only two presidents to be
impeached and tried by the Senate. Both were acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he expected to ``have two good years'' left at the
White House and again called on Congress to join with him in
getting back to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the American people expect the Congress and me to get
back to work, expect us either not to have any destructive
feelings, or, if we do, not to let them get in the way of our doing
their business,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac remained silent as Clinton answered the personal
questions but earlier this week voiced support for the president.
</P>
<P>
   The president appeared tired and somber as he spent the day in
meetings with Chirac. Clinton and other European leaders have
threatened to use force against Yugoslavia for blocking a peace
agreement with its province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also cautioned against pressing his wife to make a quick
decision about whether to run for the Senate in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has just been through a very exhausting year,'' Clinton
said. ``I think some time needs to be taken here.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about the first lady's political ambitions have hit
a fever pitch as she acknowledged publicly for the first time this
week that she is considering entering the race.
</P>
<P>
   She met with retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan on Friday and
plans to travel to Long Island on Saturday. Moynihan provided the
first lady with demographic information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I would support her if she did (run),'' said
Moynihan, who has been an occasional critic of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that he, too, would back the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be strongly supportive of whatever decision she makes
and will do all I can to help, on this and any other decision, from
now on, just as she's helped me for the last 20-plus years,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said his advice to his wife has been ``to take some
time, get some rest, listen to people on both sides of the
argument, and decide exactly what you think is right to do. And
then whatever she decides, I'll be for.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, considered a Republican
prospect for the Senate, said he has ``great respect'' for the
president and first lady but added that she should be given time to
decide.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on CNN, Giuliani said, ``I don't know her philosophy,
but I think should we run against each other there would be some
very, very big differences in terms of issues and positions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
