<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is There a Lonely Heart For Every Deal on Wall St.? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, an article in the Money &AMP; Business section
described the work of Janis Spindel, a matchmaker who charges busy
Wall Street executives $10,000 to be set up on a dozen dates over
the course of a year. (That's the fee for men; women, who seem to
need less help, pay half.)
</P>
<P>
   In the days that followed, the author of the article was
besieged with 40 phone calls from romance-hungry readers or their
anxious kin. The supplicants ranged from a 29-year-old tax lawyer
in Chicago who thought he might try his luck, despite the distance,
to an investment banker at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette with an
exceedingly quiet social life _ ``but I got a big bonus last
year,'' he said with enthusiasm. Then there was the 74-year-old
woman who wondered if ``any of these nice boys had grandfathers.''
</P>
<P>
   An intriguing pattern emerged: Women tended to ramble on about
their love lives and explain why they were seeking Ms. Spindel's
services, while men left curt messages giving only their names,
phone numbers and exhortations to return their calls promptly.
</P>
<P>
   One woman _ with a single daughter at Morgan Stanley _ called
from Boca Raton, Fla. ``But please, please don't use my name,'' she
said. ``My daughter would be so mad at me. She's successful,
good-looking and having a hard time finding a quality person out
there. So I thought I would do a little detective work. Call me
your typical Jewish mother.'' And who would pay the fee? ``Oh I
would,'' she said. ``And don't you tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Kuczynski &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Friendship Gone Flat  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a small world after all. After a lawsuit by a Maryland
distributor against Coca-Cola Enterprises _ accusing it of unfair
pricing moves, fraud and other offenses _ was publicized last
month, the bottler enlisted John H. Downs Jr., a 12-year veteran of
its public affairs office, to answer questions from the news media.
As it turns out, Downs and the plaintiff, the B.K. Miller Co., go
back a way.
</P>
<P>
   Downs' father was a county official from Anne Arundel County,
Md., where B.K. Miller is based, and David Miller, B.K. Miller's
president, said his family and the Downses had known each other for
years.
</P>
<P>
   He said his brother, Thomas V. Miller, the company's lawyer and
the president of the Maryland Senate, had been especially friendly
with Downs. Before filing his lawsuit, he added, he called Downs to
see if things could be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Downs told him that he ``didn't have much to do with sales,''
Miller said. ``So when he re-emerges as their spokesman, this
public relations expert who dogs me in the press, that was
disconcerting to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Downs shrugged off the connection, calling the Millers
``acquaintances.'' Coca-Cola Enterprises says the lawsuit, filed in
1997, is without merit.
</P>
<P>
   Constance L. Hays &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Practicing What He Preaches? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If all gamblers were like Gary Loveman, the chief financial
officer of Harrah's Entertainment Inc., the casino empire, Loveman
wouldn't have much to oversee. The most he ever won at the betting
table was $180 in blackjack at Caesars Palace. And the most he
lost? ``Probably $100, never more. I'm a pretty lame customer.''
</P>
<P>
   At least he was taking money away from the competition; Caesars
is owned by Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide. But the real
value that Loveman, 38, brings to the job he took last March is his
commitment to fostering customer loyalty _ ``the service-profit
chain,'' as he calls it.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem casinos face, in his view, is the fickleness
of gamblers. When they are on a losing streak _ and most usually
are _ they tend to head for the exits to try their luck elsewhere.
``If you ask a customer, `How are you doing tonight?' most will
say, `I'm losing,' because they are,'' he said. ``We've never
taught the employee how to deal with that.''
</P>
<P>
   He would like to stem the exodus by giving even low-level
employees the authority to dole out coupons for free drinks, chips
and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Loveman has already made a mark at Harrah's, helping to
orchestrate its purchase last month of the Rio Hotel and Casino in
Las Vegas, Nev., for $890 million and playing a role in the
company's investment last July in a new airline to ferry visitors
to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Until a year ago, he was a consultant and a professor at the
Harvard Business School with little hands-on experience. ``I had
spent a great deal of time dispensing advice,'' he said in a phone
interview from somewhere in the sky on Harrah's private Hawker
800-XP jet. ``There comes a time to see if you can actually do what
you tell others to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy Furchgott &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 2111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
