<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2236 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKER-SHOOTS-SON20-C     02-19 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKER-SHOOTS-SON20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Murder-suicide stuns Texas community
 &HT;    By Chuck Lindell
 &HT;   c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGETOWN, Texas _ Justice of the Peace Jimmy Bitz knew Joe
Ross Duncum from the Kiwanis Club, where they attended breakfast
meetings together and co-chaired the club's annual Special Olympics
event.
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday morning, Bitz drove to Duncum's house for an
unimaginable task _ to verify the death of Duncum, who shot and
killed his 16-month-old son before turning the shotgun on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the kind of guy who'd do anything in the world for
you,'' Bitz said. ``I'm just sitting here like everyone else is,
trying to figure out why. We might never know why.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncum, a prominent Georgetown banker, had fired two blasts from
a 12-gauge shotgun shortly after sheriff's officers had entered his
home in the Serenada neighborhood west of Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   The officers, who were responding to a report of family
violence, kicked open the locked door to the master bedroom.
Inside, they found the infant, Hunter, dead on the bed. Duncum, 44,
was lying several steps away, also dead.
</P>
<P>
   It was shortly after 4 a.m. Several hours later, stunned
business and civic leaders began breaking the distressing news of
the murder-suicide. Duncum was vice president of lending for
Walburg State Bank and treasurer of the Georgetown Chamber of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody we talk to is just utterly devastated,'' said Gordon
Baker, chairman-elect of the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``The immediate reaction was, `I just talked to him the day
before,' or `I just talked to him the week before,' and then
literally there's just complete shock,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Such an act seems entirely out of character for a well-liked and
respected man known to all by his middle name, Ross, said Molly
Alexander, president of the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the shock is so great because I never remember a time
when Ross didn't think he could get anything accomplished,'' she
said. ``When it comes from Ross, it usually came passionately.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends and co-workers described Duncum as warm, compassionate
and competitive in a good-natured way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody said we all have our demons,'' Alexander said with
tears in her eyes. ``We think we know people, but we obviously
didn't know him as well as we thought we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncum and his wife, Carmen Monique Duncum, were raising three
children in the home _ two teen-agers from Carmen Duncum's previous
marriage and Hunter, the only child they had together. Ross Duncum
has two children from a previous marriage, but they did not live
with him.
</P>
<P>
   Events began early Friday when Carmen Duncum, 38, arrived at the
Williamson County sheriff's office in Georgetown with a black eye,
bruises and a cut to her face, said Capt. Linda Bunte.
</P>
<P>
   After reporting her husband for assault, Carmen Duncum was taken
to Georgetown Hospital, where she was treated for minor injuries,
Bunte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Duncum came to the door but wouldn't open it,'' Bunte
said. ``He kept talking to them through the door, but they couldn't
hear what he was saying.''
</P>
<P>
   The officers entered the home through an unlocked garage door,
and Duncum ran to the master bedroom. Officers were escorting
Carmen Duncum's two teen-agers out of the house when the first
gunshot sounded, Bunte said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers pounded on the door but received no response. A deputy
went outside to look through a bedroom window and, through a small
crack in the curtain, saw blood in the room, Bunte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, they kicked the door open and went in,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the room, investigators found Duncum lying across the
entrance to the master bathroom, where he had placed the gun to his
forehead and pulled the trigger, Bitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Duncum had a prior arrest in November 1997 for assaulting his
wife, Bunte said. Duncum completed anger-management counseling, and
his misdemeanor case was dismissed at the request of the county
attorney's office, Bitz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty common in these assault issues. We try to fix
things instead of assess a penalty,'' Bitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Duncum worked in the downtown Georgetown branch of Walburg State
Bank, where he was hired in October 1997, said bank President Gene
Lawhon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked side by side for a year and a half. He'll definitely
be missed,'' said Lawhon. ``It's really a family matter. They have
our deepest sympathy.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncum was appointed to the chamber board on Jan. 1 and served
last year on the Urban Design Working Group, which produced
guidelines to help preserve Georgetown's small-town character.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just devastated,'' said Jon Pfau, chamber of commerce
chairman. ``We've lost somebody who means a lot to us. We're all
praying for his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
