</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEC-RESTRUCTURE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEC ANNOUNCES RESTRUCTURING, 11,600 JOBS TO BE ELIMINATED 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ NEC Corp., one of the world's largest semiconductor
manufacturers and an emblem of Japan's business success, announced
a broad restructuring Friday that will include one of the most
sweeping labor reductions ever undertaken by a major Japanese
company.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring, which will cause the elimination of 11,600
jobs, including 9,000 in Japan, could lead to sharp changes in
NEC's strategic direction.
</P>
<P>
   NEC also greatly increased its estimate of losses it expects for
the current fiscal year, which ends March 31. It forecast a group
net loss of 150 billion yen, or $1.3 billion, well above its
previous forecast of a deficit of 35 billion yen. The company
expects sales to decline 4 percent, to 4.7 trillion yen.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Friday's announcements, NEC announced a management
overhaul, which had been expected.
</P>
<P>
   The elimination of the 9,000 jobs in Japan, to be achieved
through attrition and early retirement over the next three years,
will be one of the biggest single employment cutbacks announced
here, even during a year in which many companies have cut workers.
</P>
<P>
   The reverberations will no doubt be closely watched by the rest
of corporate Japan, which has been struggling to overhaul itself
under the constraints of a tradition of lifetime employment.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the job cuts will come largely from NEC's
operations in Asia and Ireland. NEC had earlier cut 3,000 jobs at
its Packard Bell NEC subsidiary and 400 jobs at NEC Electronics, a
subsidiary in California.
</P>
<P>
   NEC has been slower than its competitors to address its
structural problems, in part because it was the last of the major
high-technology companies here to feel the pain of excess capacity,
falling semiconductor and personal computer prices and over
employment.
</P>
<P>
   Both Toshiba and Hitachi have embarked on overhauls that are
significant by Japanese standards, and Fujitsu revamped its
operations some time ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday's announcement left no doubt that NEC plans to move
quickly to correct its problems.
</P>
<P>
   The one lingering area of concern is likely to be the company's
personal computer business, which has been losing market share in
Japan and has stumbled badly in the United States at Packard Bell
NEC.
</P>
<P>
   NEC said it would write off 189 billion yen, or about $1.6
billion, of its more than $1.8 billion investment in Packard Bell
and pay $450 million to buy 80 percent of Packard Bell's European
operations, which effectively amounts to yet another cash infusion
for the troubled unit.
</P>
<P>
   Packard Bell's European operations, which are profitable and
growing, will be brought directly under NEC's control. Bull SA,
NEC's partner in Packard Bell, will take a 20 percent stake in the
European business.
</P>
<P>
   NEC said Packard Bell had already benefited from restructuring
measures taken in the last year, including the layoffs and a
sharper focus on selling products with higher profit margins. It
estimated that the subsidiary would lose $80 million in the current
fiscal year, compared with a $500 million loss in the previous
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   NEC also unveiled a potentially significant change in its
boardroom. Hajime Sasaki, the senior executive vice president in
charge of its semiconductor business and a favorite among foreign
analysts and investors, will become the company's new chairman.
</P>
<P>
   And Kouji Nishigaki, the executive vice president who heads up
its systems integration business, will become president, replacing
Hisashi Kaneko, whose job has been in question since NEC became
embroiled in a major military-procurement scandal last year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The choice of Nishigaki as president suggests that NEC plans to
increase its emphasis on value-added services like those offered by
Fujitsu, IBM, Cisco Systems and Lucent.
</P>
<P>
   The company has worked hard to build its systems integration
business _ the integration of computers and communications
capabilities _ but it has always been known more as a maker of
computers, semiconductors and telecommunications equipment _
products that are rapidly becoming commodities with razor-thin
profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   NEC said it would continue to develop the nuts-and-bolts
businesses that support systems integration, but warned that some
of those operations have ``insufficiently clear long-term profit
potential.'' Those businesses, the company said, would be
reorganized, sold or spun off.
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki, who, having run NEC's U.S. operations, has a good
understanding of the standards by which Western companies are
judged may push the company toward adopting some of those same
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced Thursday that it hoped to bring its
debt-to-equity ratio down to 1.5 to 1, from the current 1.87 to 1,
and to raise its return on equity to 15 percent, a target almost
never mentioned by Japanese companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 2118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2243 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLIPPER20-COX     02-19 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLIPPER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Military officer's name finally cleared after posthumous pardon
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During the last half of his life, Lt. Henry O.
Flipper traveled to Washington almost every year to urge Congress
to overturn his dishonorable discharge from the Army in 1882.
</P>
<P>
   Flipper, who was born into slavery in Thomasville, Ga., in 1856
and died in Atlanta in 1940 at the age of 84, never lived to see
his quest realized.
</P>
<P>
   But his 117-year search for justice finally ended Friday when
President Clinton pardoned Flipper posthumously, erasing the stigma
on an extraordinary military and professional career.
</P>
<P>
   Flipper was the first black graduate of West Point and the
Army's first black commissioned officer before his dishonorable
discharge on trumped-up charges.
</P>
<P>
   Four generations of Flipper's descendents from six states
gathered in the White House as Clinton inked his name to the
presidential pardon, the first posthumous pardon ever given by a
U.S. president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's ceremony is about a moment in 1882 when our government
did not do all it could to protect an individual American's
freedom,'' Clinton said. ``This good man has now completely
recovered his good name.''
</P>
<P>
   William King, a doctor whose mother in Valdosta began her own
campaign to clear Flipper's name in 1975, told Clinton the family's
struggle had been ``a long journey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can find a lot of anger in any members of
the family,'' King said. ``We learned from Lt. Flipper that anger
will not get you anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The blot on Flipper's military record stemmed from a charge that
he embezzled commissary funds while stationed at Fort Davis, Texas.
Flipper was acquitted of the embezzlement charge but convicted of
conduct unbecoming an officer.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, thanks to the efforts of King's mother, Irsle King, and
Ray MacColl, a white teacher from southwest Georgia, the military
reversed the dishonorable discharge that resulted from the
conviction. But the Army Board for Correction of Military Records
had no authority to expunge the conviction.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, lawyers at a large Washington law office got involved
and began the legal case to win Flipper a presidential pardon,
filing a formal petition of pardon in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Smith, a partner at Arnold &AMP; Porter and a West Point
graduate, said he wanted to win the pardon in part to show military
men and women that past wrongs can be righted.
</P>
<P>
   None of the 16 descendants who attended Friday's ceremony ever
knew their trail-blazing relative. But most grew up with the
stories of his perseverance and accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Flipper graduated from West Point against seemingly
insurmountable odds. He was shunned by his fellow cadets and
endured a largely solitary life on the banks of the Hudson River.
Flipper wrote an autobiography of his experience at the age of 22.
</P>
<P>
   After his discharge, Flipper pursued a prolific career as an
engineer and land surveyor in the western United States and in
Mexico, later serving as a special agent with the Justice
Department's Court of Private Land Claims. He spoke French and
Spanish and wrote two more books.
</P>
<P>
   Flipper's story inspired William Davis, a great-grandnephew, to
attend the Air Force Academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about the burdens that he carried and what he did and
then I stop complaining,'' said Davis, now a Delta pilot from
Dallas. ``He had the character to go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Flipper, another great-grandnephew, said he and his family
were told that Flipper never held any bitterness toward the Army,
even as he worked so many years to have his name cleared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure today he is smiling down on us and at last feeling
the reward and recognition for his service,'' said Carl Flipper.
``Justice has been denied Henry for too many years. But justice has
been done now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
