<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2248 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      02-19 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT MAY HAVE SHARED CIGARETTE WITH VICTIM OF DRAGGING DEATH,
EXPERT SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ A white supremacist may have shared a cigarette
with James Byrd Jr. just before the black man was chained to a
pickup and dragged to his death, a DNA expert testified Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Baechtel, a forensics examiner with the FBI in Washington,
also told jurors in John William ``Bill'' King's capital murder
trial that Byrd's blood was found on shoes and clothing from King's
apartment, linking King and co-defendants Shawn Allen Berry, 24,
and Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr., 31, to Byrd's killing June 7.
</P>
<P>
   King, 24, could face death by injection if convicted. Berry and
Brewer will be tried separately later.
</P>
<P>
   Baechtel testified that a cigarette butt found at the crime
scene in a wooded area east of town contained King's genetic
blueprint, as well as someone else's.
</P>
<P>
   ``King was the primary smoker, and someone else took a drag off
of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baechtel could not positively identify Byrd as the second
smoker, but he could not rule him out as he did Berry and Brewer.
He said it is easier to exclude an individual than it is to
positively identify someone when dealing with a small amount of
DNA.
</P>
<P>
   The witness also testified that ``less than one drop'' of Byrd's
blood was found on the strap of King's sandal, and that the
victim's blood also was recovered from Berry's shirt, jeans and
boot, and from Brewer's tennis shoe.
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, Baechtel said it was possible, but not
likely, that the tiny speck of blood on the sandal could have been
spilled as investigators collected samples at the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   And he conceded that King and an unknown person could have
shared a cigarette earlier in the evening, and left it in the
ashtray of Berry's pickup. It later could have fallen to the ground
at the crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, 25-year-old Louis Berry, the brother of
co-defendant Shawn Berry, identified a cigarette lighter engraved
with King's prison nickname, ``Possum,'' and a triangular symbol of
the Ku Klux Klan, that was found at the crime scene. Louis Berry
said King had handed him the lighter at his apartment on the
afternoon before Byrd's killing, and he used it to light a
cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   Berry was the second witness this week to testify that the
lighter, which King has said he lost the week before, was at his
apartment June 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lighter was lost a week or so before,'' Louis Berry
explained, ``but it was returned to him by Lawrence Brewer.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Berry also brought his own sandals to the courtroom to
distinguish them from King's, and he testified that a tennis shoe
with the initials ``L.B.'' written on the tongue was not his, but
Brewer's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be way too small for me,'' Louis Berry said of the
shoe, which was found at King's apartment, where Louis Berry and
the three suspects were all staying the weekend Byrd was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Berry also testified that he had argued with King the
night of Byrd's killing because King didn't like the fact that
Berry's rock band includes a black bass player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't understand that,'' Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone suggested you had anything to do with James Byrd's
murder ...'' asked federal prosecutor Johnny Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would be wrong,'' Louis Berry answered. ``I don't agree
with it. I don't think that should happen to anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see getting into a fight with somebody, or beating
someone up, but I don't agree with it. And the people I associate
with, friends and family, they don't agree with it either.''
</P>
<P>
   The predominantly white jury was sent home early Friday
afternoon and will return to court Monday. Jasper County District
Attorney Guy James Gray estimates he will wrap up his part of the
case by noon Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said he was pleased with the first week of testimony but
added, ``We've still got to prove Mr. Byrd was alive when they
chained him to the truck.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have said the condition of Byrd's remains indicate
he was alive and fighting to keep his head off the pavement as he
was dragged down Huff Creek Road. If jurors believe that, they
could decide King kidnapped and killed Byrd. Both crimes must be
proved for a capital murder conviction.
</P>
<P>
   King's attorneys refused to attend the regularly scheduled
afternoon news conference Friday, but Byrd's sister, Clara Taylor
of Houston, and his 28-year-old daughter, Renee Mullins of Hawaii,
approached the microphone to talk to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, we think the prosecutors have done an excellent job,''
Taylor said, ``but we know they have to prove kidnapping.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said King should get the death penalty, but said she
would accept the jury's punishment decision, as long as King is
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said her mother, Stella Byrd, ``is very distraught and
upset'' but that the family's strong religious beliefs will see
them through the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that God can undo any harm in his own time,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mullins said she hopes her father's death will not be used to
further divide the races, and she hopes he will be remembered as a
happy people person.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never hurt anyone,'' she said of Byrd. ``He would talk to
you all day if you had the time. He was an entertainer. He played
dominoes. He loved to live.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 2126EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
