A2252 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLIPPER-PARDON-ART-NY     02-19 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLIPPER-PARDON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST BLACK GRADUATE OF WEST POINT RECEIVES PARDON FOR 1881
CONVICTION
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fifty-nine years after his death, the first black
West Point graduate received a presidential pardon on Friday for a
crime that most who have studied the case say he did not commit.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton granted the pardon to Henry O. Flipper, who
graduated from West Point in 1877 despite being ostracized by his
white classmates. He was court-martialed in 1881 on thievery
charges that appear to have been trumped up, then was drummed out
of the service the following year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome you all to an event that is 117 years overdue,''
Clinton said at a White House ceremony attended by several dozen
people, including military officers and Flipper's descendants.
Among those watching was Gen. Colin Powell, retired chairman of the
Joint Chief of Staffs, who has said that he kept a picture of
Flipper on his desk for inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted that the Army had formally exonerated Flipper in
1976, changing his discharge to honorable and reburying him with
full honors in Thomasville, Ga., where he was born.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's ceremony was largely symbolic, and Clinton embraced it
as ``a moment in 1999 when we correct the error and resolve to do
even better in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing remained to be done, and now it will be,'' the
president continued, holding a pen over the pardon document. ``This
good man now has completely recovered his good name.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of Flipper's descendants applauded. ``Like the rest of
the family, I'm relieved that this has come full circle,'' said Dr.
William King, a great-nephew of Flipper. King's mother, Irsle
Flipper King, had been pushing for a pardon for some 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   As a young second lieutenant, Flipper was accused of embezzling
some $2,500 in commissary money while he was stationed in Texas. He
was acquitted of that charge but found guilty of conduct unbecoming
an officer for lying to investigators and was given a dishonorable
discharge in 1882.
</P>
<P>
   Born a slave in 1856, Henry Ossian Flipper entered West Point
when he was 17. Most of his classmates were hostile to him, and he
lived in social isolation. When he graduated 50th in a class of 76
in 1877, he became the first black man commissioned as an officer
in the U.S. Army.
</P>
<P>
   Flipper joined the 10th Cavalry, one of two all-black Army
units, at Fort Sill in the Oklahoma Territory. He soon perfected a
system for draining off the mosquito-infested stagnant water that
had caused malaria outbreaks at the fort for more than 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   After being transferred to Fort Davis, Texas, he ran afoul of
his commanding officer, who brought the charges that led to
court-martial. After reviewing the trial record, the judge advocate
general of the Army concluded that Flipper had been persecuted
because of his race, that the charges were dubious at best and that
leniency was appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   But under military procedures at the time, there was no judicial
process to set aside the conviction. The authority to affirm or
overturn the conviction rested with President Chester A. Arthur,
who chose to affirm it.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the Army, Flipper became a civil and mining
engineer, working in the New Mexico and Arizona Territories. U.S.
Attorney Matthew Reynolds named him a special agent for the
Department of Justice, a post he held for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Reynolds wrote of Flipper's ``fidelity, integrity
and magnificent ability.'' Declaring that he did not believe
Flipper was guilty of the court-martial charges, Reynolds said he
had compiled a record ``of which any man might well be proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Flipper became a special assistant to the secretary of the
interior, planning railroads in the Alaska Territory and was
employed by several large corporations as a mining engineer and an
expert on Mexican and South American mineral laws. He died in 1940
at the age of 84.
</P>
<P>
   Though it never became an international sensation, the Flipper
case was similar in broad ways to the Dreyfus affair in France.
Capt. Alfred Dreyfus, a French army officer, was court-martialed on
espionage charges in 1894. He was eventually exonerated, and most
historians believe the charges arose because he was Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Flipper's name is honored at the U.S. Military Academy,
where he endured so much. An annual award is given in his name to
an outstanding cadet, and a portion of the West Point library
honors him.
</P>
<P>
   ``With great pleasure and humility, I now offer a full pardon,''
Clinton said on Friday. Then he handed the pen to King, who held it
high in triumph as relatives crowded around the president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
