<HEADLINE>
KENYA'S FINANCE MINISTER VOWS TO KEEP REFORM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By IAN FISHER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The new finance minister of Kenya sought Friday
to reassure investors and donors of foreign aid that he would
continue on the path of fiscal reform a day after his
corruption-fighting predecessor quit in a major Cabinet shake-up.
</P>
<P>
   The statements from the new minister, Yekoyada F.O. Masakhalia,
seemed primarily aimed at the International Monetary Fund.
Officials from the fund are scheduled to visit Kenya this month to
decide whether to reinstate an important $205 million package of
financial aid that was frozen in 1997 largely because of corruption
and mismanagement of public money.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts here said they believed that the package would be
restored as a result of improved fiscal policies put into effect by
the departing finance minister, Simeon Nyachae. On Friday,
Masakhalia, 61, an economist with a master's degree from Harvard
University, said that he would seek few substantive changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to emphasize there will be no change to the
ongoing policy thrust,'' he said at a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
   Nyachae resigned Thursday in a surprise move. He is a leading
politician, often mentioned as a potential successor to President
Daniel arap Moi, who had, since he was appointed in January 1998,
cut government spending and brought down interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   He also waged a highly public battle against corruption, even
issuing the names of prominent Kenyans who had not repaid national
bank loans.
</P>
<P>
   He quit the post rather than accept Moi's decision for him to
swap jobs with Masakhalia, who had been industrial development
minister. Moi shifted six other ministers and dismissed a few
others, notably Immigration Minister Frank Kwinga, whose department
controls arrivals like that of a Kurdish leader, Abdullah Ocalan.
Ocalan was smuggled into Kenya on Feb. 2 and sent to Turkey.
</P>
</TEXT>
