<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 S.F. Brewery Yanks Beer Ads in Harlem  &HT;       
 By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
A San Francisco brewery agreed this week to remove promotional
posters from liquor stores in Harlem after civil rights advocates
complained the ads were offensive and targeted poor, black people.
</P>
<P>
   The posters, promoting Steel Reserve High Gravity Lager, show
rhinoceroses and giant turtles fornicating next to the tag line
``Research Says Sex Sells Beer.''
</P>
<P>
   The beermaker, Steel Brewing Co., said it asked its New York
distributor to remove posters from liquor stores there. But the ads
remain posted in other liquor outlets around the country, including
in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Steel Brewing is owned by San Francisco's McKenzie River Co.,
which was fined in 1992 for violating federal alcohol-advertising
laws with ads for St. Ides malt liquor.
</P>
<P>
   Steel spokeswoman Gee Roman said the company has no regrets
about the campaign, which was developed in-house. ``We didn't
design the campaign to offend anyone. We're sorry if it offended
any person or any group.''
</P>
<P>
   Roman said High Gravity Lager is a ``general market beer,'' not
a malt liquor. But the alcohol content, 8.1 percent, is at the high
end for malt liquors. Beer averages 4.5 percent alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four-ounce containers of the Steel lager are sold at Bay
Area liquor stores for 99 cents, which is also a typical price and
size for malt liquors.
</P>
<P>
   Roman said Steel is not targeting any particular demographic
with its posters. But as a practical matter, malt liquor is
consumed primarily by young, low-income African Americans living in
urban areas, said Laurie Lieber, director of the Center on Alcohol
Advertising in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very easy to go after inner-city youth because they're
very concentrated,'' said Lieber. ``Using point-of-sale materials
is a fraction of what it costs to go on the broadcast media and
reach middle-class people in their living rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   The beer and posters were distributed in September, drawing the
ire of community leaders such as the Rev. Calvin Butts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see this in store windows on Park Avenue or in the
community of Scarsdale,'' Butts said.
</P>
<P>
   The issue came to a head when representatives from Steel met
with New York City Councilman Bill Perkins recently and promised to
take the posters down.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Perkins said the Steel executives dismissed the ads as
satire. ``They have no regard for the values and sensitivity for
our community,'' said Perkins. ``It's not funny _ especially when
it's posted across the street from an elementary school.''
</P>
<P>
   If all posters are not removed, Perkins said he would call for a
boycott of Steel and any uncooperative liquor stores.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Smikle of Target Market News, a Chicago market research firm
specializing in black consumers, said the beer company is hurting
itself with the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of humor will never play well in the African
American community, particularly when there's a chance that
children will be exposed to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The manufacturer needs to really stop and look at how a
campaign like this will jeopardize a significant portion of their
business and create ill will with consumers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 2131EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0362 </DOCNO>
