r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EBAY-SFCHRON &LR;      02-19 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EBay Halts Sales Of Guns, Ammo Over Internet  &HT;       
 By Jamie Beckett 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Online auctioneer eBay said yesterday it will no longer allow the
sale of guns or ammunition, saying ``the Internet is not an
appropriate venue for this kind of merchandise.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose company said firearms sales had been an area of
``growing concern'' because online sellers cannot readily guarantee
that buyers meet all the qualifications and comply with the laws
governing firearms sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started, the firearms categories were targeted
primarily to serious collectors,'' said Steve Westly, vice
president of marketing and business development at eBay. ``Now
we're starting to see standard-issue firearms that are not
collectible and are not appropriate for sale online.''
</P>
<P>
   Westly said he and other executives felt there was too little
control over the sale process to allow trading of these types of
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Some types of guns and ammunition are illegal to sell in some
states, for example. In addition, federal laws govern many aspects
of firearms purchases, including how certain weapons can be shipped
and who may purchase them.
</P>
<P>
   EBay, the leading online auction house, has been criticized
several times in recent months as law enforcement officials in at
least four states investigated the use of the service by con
artists.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has hosted some 49 million auctions since
1995, will still run auctions for gun-related goods such as
holsters, scopes, books and clothing. But beginning March 5, no
more gun or ammunition auctions will be allowed. EBay will stop
taking listings for those items on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   EBay has tried to address the problem of firearms sales before.
Last year, it moved the auctions to the ``adults only'' category
and began requiring credit card verification before allowing users
to buy or sell in that section.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent clampdown disappointed some eBay users, who were
vocal with their criticism on eBay message boards yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been fun using eBay, and I have dealt with many nice
people, but I will no longer allow a company with a policy like
this to profit from my activities,'' said Will Middelaer, an eBay
customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``EBay has decided that firearms and other self-defense products
are unwelcome on their site. I have decided that eBay is not
welcome in my home,'' said user Harold Cook. ``There are other
auction sites that will provide the service, take eBay's place and
grow. So long, eBay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there are users that are upset about this, but we
think it's the right thing to do,'' Westly responded.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of EBAY20 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Many of the largest online auction sites do not carry firearms,
or carry only limited listings. Yahoo Auctions and AuctionUniverse
carry collectible guns. Many sites, such as Excite Auctions and
AuctionAddict, have no gun category but may allow some firearms
sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We filter for firearms, ammunitions and guns, so when those
ads do come up, our staff can take a look at it and determine
whether it's appropriate,'' said an Excite spokeswoman. Like most
sites that allow firearms sales, Excite requires that sellers be
licensed.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts applauded eBay's move.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just responsible retailing,'' said Jae Kim, who
follows Internet businesses for Paul Kagan &AMP; Associates in Carmel.
``If eBay cannot guarantee with 100 percent assurance that the
people who are purchasing firearms should be allowed to possess
them, they shouldn't provide a forum for them to be marketed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you continue with firearms sales, it's not a question of if
something bad will happen, but when,'' said Mark Dodd, who runs
AuctionWatch, an online auction information service. ``As any
corporation gets big, it wants to cut out the fringe elements.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, eBay has instituted a number of policies aimed
at curbing fraud on its site. It's also providing insurance to
users through Lloyd's of London.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of guns and ammunition represent a tiny fraction of eBay's
overall business. Of nearly 1.6 million auctions yesterday, fewer
than 3,000 were for guns or ammunition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
