<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVESFEATURE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Perez discloses Galarraga sounds 'real, real down'
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ The emotions were still raw Friday
morning as Braves pitchers and catchers reported to the clubhouse
for workouts.
</P>
<P>
   The sentiment was still very much shock that their first baseman
and resident ``Big Cat,'' Andres Galarraga, is fighting a form of
cancer named non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really shook me,'' catcher Javy Lopez said. ``It felt like
it was me that was the one who got cancer. For one second, I felt
like I was in his position. ... We're all going to do the best we
can to try to win, so we can dedicate the season in the name of
Galarraga.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say they are optimistic that Galarraga will recover
fully after a six-month course of chemotherapy and radiation
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another slap of reality,'' Tom Glavine said. ``Over the
last few years, as I've gotten older and become a parent, baseball
has taken on a different perspective. This is another example of
how there are bigger things in life than baseball. It's devastating
when you hear it. It puts baseball in its proper perspective. It's
hard to believe a guy in as good a shape as Cat is and as happy as
he is _ that's not a guy you'd think ends up getting sick like
this. But it goes to show nobody is immune from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux said, ``It's just sickening. It's brutal. You just
hope for the best for him and his family. You just hope he can
rally.''
</P>
<P>
   The news is especially hard on Latin players in the Braves
clubhouse, because of the guiding influence that Galarraga, a
native Venezuelan, had on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people look at the way he plays,'' said catcher Eddie
Perez, one of Galarraga's closest friends on the team. ``The way he
treats people. He's a great guy to have around. I'm really going to
miss him.... We have to play harder for him, make him feel proud of
us, happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez talked to Galarraga on Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't sound so good,'' Perez said. ``His wife was crying.
... I told him, `We'll be waiting for you here next year. You just
have to forget about baseball and think about your wife and kids.'
He sounds real, real down. He wanted me to say `hi' to everybody.
He said, `Have a good season for me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Braves hitting coach Don Baylor, the man who helped revive
Galarraga's career as his manager in Colorado, already had
Galarraga's No. 14 written in white ink of the side of his cap
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a special person,'' Baylor said. ``His zest for the game
has always been something I enjoyed. He gives you that energy day
in and day out. I was looking forward to being here, seeing him
play, seeing him produce again. Now he has his own battle.''
</P>
<P>
   With five weeks of spring training ahead, the Braves have their
own work to do to counter this loss on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people considered us to be the front-runner in the National
League, we just came back to the pack,'' Chipper Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
