r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHWAB-SFCHRON &LR;      02-19 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHWAB-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Schwab Expands Network of Branches as It Strives to Protect  Online
Lead   By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Stephen Seewer is the kind of investor who has propelled Charles
Schwab &AMP; Co.'s business to new heights.
</P>
<P>
   Like more and more of Schwab's clients, Seewer trades on the
Internet, buying and selling shares of technology, drug and
financial services companies about six times a month.
</P>
<P>
   But once or twice a week, usually when he's walking Dakota, his
golden retriever, the 31-year-old Parkside resident stops by
Schwab's branch in San Francisco's West Portal neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like the online service, but the branch is pretty
close to my home,'' Seewer said. ``It's a convenient way to go in
and check my positions or do any sort of maintenance.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwab, the nation's largest discount broker, believes its mix
of online investing, telephone service and branches helps it stand
out from the burgeoning ranks of electronic brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, San Francisco's Schwab operated the
old-fashioned way, with live brokers taking most orders by
telephone. Clients who wanted to trade by computer had to install
Schwab's special software and dial into the firm's computer.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Schwab has reinvented itself by shifting most of its
business to the Internet. In less than three years, the firm has
gone from zero to an average of more than 150,000 Web-based trades
a day. That's nearly two out of every three transactions Schwab
carries out.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab turned to the Internet because it's a cheaper and more
efficient medium for processing orders and delivering information
to investors.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even as it has jumped into the Web, Schwab has pumped up
its branch network. The company now has 293 retail offices
throughout the United States and plans to open as many as 200 more
over the next few years. That's well ahead of Waterhouse
Securities, a broker with a similar strategy, which operates about
150 branches and plans to grow to 200 next year.
</P>
<P>
   Now that online investing has captured the public mind, why
would Schwab shell out the bucks needed to keep up its branches?
</P>
<P>
   Schwab officials stress that giving customers the choice of
going to a nearby office or calling a live broker on the phone is
one of the key things that differentiates the firm from the pack of
all-electronic competitors nipping at its heels, such as E-Trade,
Ameritrade and Datek.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the big advantages we have is our other channels
through which customers can reach us,'' said Daniel Leemon,
Schwab's chief strategist.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab has to provide branches and telephone service to stick
out, since its Internet trading fees are higher and its offerings
of research, news and investment tools not much different from what
other online brokers serve up.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of SCHWAB20 (25451 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The firm's $29.95 Internet commission is as much as six times
higher than what the lowest-price competitors charge. And while a
survey shows the quality of Schwab's Internet service is improving,
it still rated only fifth best, according to Gomez Advisors, a
Massachusetts consulting firm that tracks Web-based brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to differentiate itself on the Internet, Schwab is losing
online ground to some electronic rivals.
</P>
<P>
   In the quarter that ended in December, Schwab carried out 27.6
percent of the average 337,000 online trades carried out each day
in the United States, according to Piper Jaffray, a Minneapolis
brokerage firm. That was more than double Waterhouse, its nearest
competitor, but down from Schwab's share of more than 30 percent a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab officials are touchy about data showing the firm's
shrinking online lead. They point out that Schwab targets long-term
investors rather than the hyperactive day traders who pump up the
trading figures of some competitors.
</P>
<P>
   They also say that the amount of money clients invest with the
firm is more important than the highly volatile trading volume
figures. ``The most fundamental measure we look at is net new
assets,'' said Chief Financial Officer Steven Scheid.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, those assets have skyrocketed lately. In the year ended
January 31, the holdings of Schwab's customers leaped 43 percent to
$521 billion. In January alone, those holdings rose 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Schwab's market share is slipping, the overall market,
propelled in part by Internet stock mania, is booming. And that
translates into a huge increase in trading volume for Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   With electronic trades leading the way, the firm's average daily
securities and mutual fund transactions doubled in a year and
surged an eye-popping 48 percent in January alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're growing by leaps and bounds, by every sort of
measure,'' said Bruce Brewington, a San Francisco analyst with the
firm Putnam, Lovell, de Guardiola &AMP; Thornton. ``Even though
Schwab's market share is smaller, the pie is so much bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Schwab earned $348.5 million, up 29 percent from
1997, on $2.74 billion in revenue. After stagnating for more than a
year, the company's stock took off at the end of October. Since
then, it has almost tripled, closing yesterday at $69.06.
</P>
<P>
   While Schwab is slugging it out online, its branches give it an
edge rivals can't match.
</P>
<P>
   In January, under the strain of record trading demand, Schwab
and other online brokers were plagued by Internet service
breakdowns. At West Portal, frustrated clients flooded in to place
orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had very heavy walk-in traffic,'' manager Martin Briesach
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   While the branches can handle orders, they are designed as sales
centers. Some 70 percent of the new customer money coming into
Schwab enters through the branches.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Schwab has big plans for its new Signature premium
service program for its best customers. Many of those services,
such as special investment planning help, are being offered through
the branches.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of SCHWAB20 (25451 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The West Portal branch opened two years ago, based on a standard
model for Schwab's newer offices.
</P>
<P>
   It is small and well lighted. With few interior walls, it has an
open feel. Near the entrance, there's a computer linked to the
Internet, part of Schwab's plan to make customers comfortable with
online investing.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers work at curved desks so clients feel they are sitting
next to them, not across a table. In keeping with Schwab's business
model, brokers offer clients investment-selection tools, but don't
recommend particular stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Steven Choy, a 32-year-old San Francisco
accountant, came into the West Portal branch to open an account for
his parents. Choy, who already trades with Schwab, says he goes
online every day to check his holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is a veteran Internet trader, Choy said he
appreciates having a branch near his home. ``You can speak to a
real person,'' he explained. ``I like the personal touch.``
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of SCHWAB20 (25451 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
