<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAISER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Kaiser HMO in Red Again  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Reporting its second loss in as many years, the Kaiser Foundation
Health Plan yesterday hinted at more premium rate increases over
the next 12 months as the giant HMO struggles to get back in the
black.
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland health giant, which all but nixed layoffs to staunch
the red ink, reported an operating loss of $434 million on revenues
of $15.5 billion in 1998. That loss, which equalled 2.8 percent of
revenues, was narrower than Kaiser's 1997 shortfall of $447 million
on revenues of $14.2 billion. The 1997 loss was the first in
Kaiser's 54-year history.
</P>
<P>
   This year's losses occurred even though Kaiser saw its
membership grow 5 percent last year to 8.6 million because premiums
from new members didn't offset their costs. In California, for
instance, Kaiser's operating losses actually widened from $212
million in 1997 to $354 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Financial Officer Dale Crandall said although Kaiser
instituted rate hikes averaging 10 percent in California for 1999,
the increases came too late to offset the rising costs of drugs and
hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   In an hourlong press call, he finessed questions about future
rate hikes, saying only ``we're playing a little bit of catchup''
relative to other HMOs that raised premiums earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But he virtually ruled out large-scale cuts in Kaiser's
90,000-person workforce to stem the losses, saying membership
growth actually forced Kaiser to hire nurses and other staff.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Greg Crawford, who follows health care for the Fox-Pitt,
Kelton investment bank in New York, said ``Kaiser needs to increase
rates aggressively for the next few years.'' He estimated the HMO
would try to get hikes close to the 10 percent it averaged this
year.
</P>
<P>
   But analyst Wanda Jones, with the New Century Health Care
Institute in San Francisco, said competition from other HMOs _
which have been seeking increases in the 5-to-7-percent range _
would influence what Kaiser can get.
</P>
<P>
   CFO Crandall said Kaiser expects to make a small profit in 1999,
owing largely to two factors. First, the rate hikes negotiated in
current health plans will begin to bring premiums into line with
rising health care costs. Kaiser also will slash capital spending
to $900 million this year, down 30 percent from the $1.3 billion it
spent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Crandall acknowledged Kaiser can't defer capital spending for
long, given its membership growth and the fact that it needs to
spend $1.5 billion in the coming years to meet state mandates for
earthquake retrofits on some of its hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Crandall addressed some of the ironies of Kaiser's current
predicament. The company says one reason for its losses is due to a
surge in membership in Southern California that has forced it to
divert some members to non-Kaiser hospitals that cost more than
Kaiser facilities.
</P>
<P>
   But oddly enough in Oakland, Kaiser says it is seeking favorable
long-term deals by shutting down its 271-bed facility and sending
some patients to Oakland's Summit Medical Center and Berkeley's
Alta Bates hospital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
