<SLUG> BC-PURPLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Girls' Software Pioneer Purple Moon Closes Down  &HT;       
 By Dan Fost 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Purple Moon, a firm that pioneered software for young girls, closed
its doors this week, throwing 40 people out of work.
</P>
<P>
   The company cited the challenge of competing in a market
dominated by increasingly large companies.
</P>
<P>
   Half of Purple Moon's employees worked out of the company's
Mountain View headquarters, and the other half worked in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials declined to comment yesterday, sticking
instead to a terse two-sentence press release.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors started flying last week, when the Industry Standard, a
trade magazine, reported on its Web site that Purple Moon was about
to shut its CD-ROM operations.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Gould, a company spokeswoman, said at the time that four
staffers were laid off and the company was possibly putting itself
up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The company was spun out of a Silicon Valley think tank backed
by Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen in 1996. Founder Brenda Laurel
had pioneered research showing that the high-tech industry was
overlooking girls' interests.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the company had estimated sales of $4.7 million,
according to market researcher PC Data of Reston, Va. That only
gave Purple Moon 5.7 percent of the girls' software market, putting
it in a distant fourth place.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the top 10 titles in girls' software were related to
Barbie, the iconic doll made by Mattel Corp., according to Roger
Lanctot, director of research at PC Data. The other four related to
Madeline, a popular figure from children's books, who stars in
software made by the Learning Co. of Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Mattel _ which commands 64.5 percent of the revenue
in the girls' software market, Lanctot said _ agreed to buy the
Learning Co., which racked up 21.6 percent of the revenue.
</P>
<P>
   While Purple Moon lamented such consolidation, Lanctot said size
wasn't what killed the company. Instead it was a lack of brand name
products like Barbie and Madeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just swamped by product that was much more
recognizable to consumers,'' Lanctot said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 1 of PURPLE20 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
