<HEADLINE>
HEALTHY HINES BACK INTO GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA reserve guard Rico Hines has recovered from a
broken right foot and will rejoin to the rotation a few minutes at
a time, perhaps beginning Sunday against Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Hines has not played since the Oregon road trip in early
January. At the time, he was averaging 3.3 points and 16 minutes
per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us another experienced guy coming off the bench and
we need that out there,'' said guard Baron Davis, Hines' roommate.
``Rico gives us consistently solid play and we've missed that.
We've missed his defense. He does the intangibles.''
</P>
<P>
   Hines, a sophomore, turned 21 on Wednesday and is one of UCLA's
most vocal leaders, both on the court and in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys kid Rico that he fought in the Korean War,'' coach
Steve Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Moiso update: Freshman forward Jerome Moiso will play Sunday
but for limited minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been two weeks since I've felt this good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso has missed two games and played poorly in two others
because of tendinitis in his right foot. He is UCLA's third-leading
scorer, averaging 12.2 points per game, but was 1 of 12 in his last
game, Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman center Dan Gadzuric, hobbled by tendinitis in his
knees, will play. Gadzuric has scored 16 points in his last three
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Dan and Jerome, it's moment-to-moment as to whether they
can go,'' Lavin said. ``We knew coming in that there would be some
growing pains. Our whole approach is that it will take two or three
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like we expected, it's been up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Mr. Opposite: Freshman forward JaRon Rush stands 6-foot-5,
weighs 210 pounds and sometimes loses his balance at the first hint
of contact. But he's UCLA's best rebounder and one of the best in
the Pac-10, averaging 7.6 per game in conference play. He has four
double-figure rebound games this season.
</P>
<P>
   His secret: go where the shooter isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to go to the opposite side of where the shooter is,'' he
said. ``The majority of rebounds go long, so I try to use my
quickness to get there and then outhustle people.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The roulette continues: Lavin expects to start Rush,
Gadzuric, Earl Watson, Baron Davis and Sean Farnham against
Syracuse. It will be UCLA's 19th different starting lineup of the
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 2134EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
