<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS DEADLINE LOOMS, NO AGREEMENT EXPECTED IN KOSOVO TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ As the Kosovo peace talks neared a fever pitch Friday,
the Clinton administration seemed resigned to not having a peace
settlement by the deadline of noon Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My assessment is that there is no reason to think we will get
an agreement tomorrow,'' a senior administration official said
Friday, adding that there was ``no evidence the Serbs have moved on
the main points.''
</P>
<P>
   While officials are hopeful that the ethnic Albanian delegation
will sign a peace settlement, the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic, remained publicly defiant, sending no signals that he
was willing to bend.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in a display of brinkmanship Milosevic refused to see
the chief U.S. negotiator, Christopher Hill, who flew to Belgrade
Friday to speak with him. Instead Hill was relegated to meeting
with the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic also increased his propaganda against NATO deployment
of peacekeepers in Kosovo, saying in a statement that Serbs would
never give up Kosovo, the southern province of Serbia, even if
meant being bombed.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Washington and its European allies have insisted that if
Milosevic refuses to sign a peace agreement by noon Saturday _
which would bring NATO-led peacekeeping troops to Kosovo _ NATO
would commence air-strikes against Serbian military targets.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how the Clinton administration and its allies
would respond if the deadline passed without a settlement.
President Clinton has said the deadline would not be extended, but
the option exists to simply allow it to lapse informally.
</P>
<P>
   Even as negotiators and delegates toiled over revisions in the
political text of the settlement in an all-night session at
Rambouillet, diplomats said that Saturday's decisions remained
unclear.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright planned to go to
Rambouillet Saturday to meet with the two sides where, if all had
gone according to plan, there would have been a settlement.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She was reasonably optimistic, an official said Friday
afternoon, that the ethnic Albanians would be prepared to sign an
agreement on the political arrangements for self-governing in
Kosovo and acceptance of 28,000 NATO troops. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators have been trying to assure the signature of the
ethnic Albanians by Saturday because that would dramatically
increase the pressure on Milosevic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But by Friday evening, the ethnic Albanians appeared to be
increasingly unhappy with new insertions in the political text of
the agreement that they said tilted too far in favor of the Serbs.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the ethnic Albanians were upset with more
references to the sovereignty of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia
in the text of the proposed constitution. For them self-government,
rather than Serbian direct rule, is the key to the new political
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers of the Contact Group, the group of six
nations which have organized the talks, are likely to meet in
Rambouillet after the noon deadline has passed.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the 16 ambassadors of NATO countries are to
meet in Brussels, Belgium. The secretary general of NATO, Javier
Solana, was empowered two weeks ago by the NATO members to order
airstrikes if Milosevic did not agree to a peace settlement.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But before making any decision on bombing, Solana planned to
consult the members and probably consider the assessment of the
Contact Group, NATO officials said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The talks, of which Albright has been a driving force, appeared
to put her in a potentially awkward situation as they reach the
final stages.
</P>
<P>
   She did not want to be seen going to Belgrade begging Milosevic
to agree to the peace accord _ and in particular, the presence of
NATO troops in Kosovo _ but nor did she want European ministers to
complete the deal, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   It was possible, they said, that she might end Saturday by going
to Brussels to meet with Solana. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Serbian officials have said that Milosevic would be pleased to
see the Clinton administration's special envoy, Richard Holbrooke,
a diplomat that Milosevic has negotiated with on many occasions.
Holbrooke has been involved in the Clinton administration's major
discussions on Kosovo this week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But a Clinton administration official said that it had been
decided Holbrooke was not the man for negotiating with Milosevic at
this time. Holbrooke has is facing upcoming confirmation hearings
to become ambassador to the United Nations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The rebuff by Milosevic, less than 24 hours before NATO is to
decide whether to go ahead with airstrikes, is not unusual behavior
for him.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, who after endless visits by politicians kept the West
at bay through four years of war in Bosnia, is recognized as a
master of getting the most out of a difficult diplomatic situation.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic will require more visible attention and courting,''
a Western diplomat involved in the negotiations said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If several foreign ministers from the Contact Group went to
Belgrade, there were no plans for Albright to join them,
particularly since it was unclear that such a journey would produce
an agreement, Clinton administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Albright doesn't want to do this unless there is a deal,'' an
administration official said of a trip to Belgrade.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Almost certainly a price Milosevic will ask for in signing a
Kosovo agreement is the removal of economic and diplomatic
sanctions against his country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A senior Clinton administration official said that Washington
would not object to investment bans, travel bans and other
sanctions placed on Serbia last summer being lifted if Milosevic
pledged to implement a peace agreement with NATO troops in Kosovo.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the more severe set of sanctions, which are of the greatest
interest to Milosevic's cash strapped regime, involve bans on loans
from international financial institutions. So far, the Clinton
administration has said it would not budge on these sanctions.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who has supported the ethnic
Albanian cause in Kosovo, criticized the negotiators Friday night,
saying they had gone too far in accepting suggestions from
Milosevic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
