<SLUG> BC-WASHINGTON-NY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE WASHINGTON SLEPT HERE, AND NEW YORK IS BOASTING ABOUT IT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va. , Mass.)   By RICHARD E. MOONEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ George Washington mused on ``the roar of cannon and
the loud acclamations of the people'' as he was rowed across the
Hudson River for his inauguration in the new nation's first
capital, New York City. In his diary that day he said his mind was
``filled with sensations as painful . . . as they are pleasing.''
He had been to the city several times as a soldier, before and
during the Revolution, again as a stepfather putting his wife's son
in college, and now on April 23, 1789, as president-elect. He would
stay for 17 months, until the capital was moved south.
</P>
<P>
   Washington first slept here in 1756, when he visited for a week
as a 23-year-old colonel and took a tumble for the beautiful and
rich Polly Philipse. Twenty years later as General Washington, he
came three times, most famously in 1776 when his troops were
thrashed by the English on the Brooklyn Heights. As president he
faced new hordes. No fewer than 18 members of the prominent
Livingston family petitioned him for jobs (ancestors of Rep. Robert
L. Livingston, who was, for a brief moment, speaker-designate of
the House).
</P>
<P>
   Martha Washington wasn't at all happy about coming to New York.
After a few months she wrote to an in-law back home in Mount Vernon
(the spellings are hers): ``I live a very dull life hear. . . . I
never goe to the publick place _ indeed I think I am more like a
state prisoner than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole span of Washington's life and times in New York is on
display in a new exhibit at the Museum of the City of New York,
including a piece of the rump of George III's horse from the statue
on lower Broadway that was toppled in celebration of the
Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Washington may have had thoughts of marrying Polly Philipse, but
things took a different turn. She married his friend and former
comrade in arms, Roger Morris, who was loyal to the crown. Their
mansion in upper Manhattan _ the Morris-Jumel mansion, open now to
the public _ was taken over by Continental forces and was
Washington's headquarters after the defeat in Brooklyn in August
1776.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, in the midst of the battle for Manhattan, he
wrote a remarkably revealing letter from that house to his cousin
Lund Washington, laying out his dual concerns for self and home.
``In confidence I tell you,'' he said, speaking of his mood, ``that
I never was in such an unhappy, divided state since I was born.''
</P>
<P>
   He goes on, despairing over the conduct of the Revolution, but
then jumps to matter-of-fact instructions about building ``the new
room'' at Mount Vernon, where to place the chimney and other such
details. In another letter from the house, this one to Polly
Philipse Morris' aunt, he added a poignant postscript: ``I beg the
favor of having my compliments presented to Mrs. Morris.''
</P>
<P>
   When he came as president, Washington and his wife first lived
in a three-story house on a section of Cherry Street buried under
the Brooklyn Bridge that the French ambassador called squalid. In
February 1790 they moved to a four-story house at 39 Broadway, with
large rooms for receptions and a river view from its rear balcony.
When Washington was bedridden with life-threatening pneumonia in
May, his wife had straw spread out front to muffle the sound of
passing carriages.
</P>
<P>
   After the pneumonia, his doctor told him to exercise more and
work less, which helps explain the following terse entry in his
diary: ``Exercised on Horseback; &AMP; called on the vice president. In
the afternoon walked an hour.'' It is Vice President John Adams'
saucy wife, Abigail, who gives fuller descriptions of the
president's courtly habits. In one of her chatty letters to her
sister, she says he never went out in his carriage without a team
of six horses, four servants and two gentlemen.
</P>
<P>
   The Washingtons declined invitations to dinner but entertained
frequently. At one meal a senator noted that the president drummed
on the table with his silverware between courses and that there was
almost no talk until everyone had eaten.
</P>
<P>
   Longer entries in Washington's diary show constant thoughts of
home, in this case, the plantings: ``I set off about 9 Oclock in my
Barge to visit Prince's fruit Gardens &AMP; shrubberies at Flushing on
Long Island.'' He was disappointed by the flora, but noted the
fanfare: ``The inhabitants of this place shewed us what respect
they could, by making the best use of one Cannon to salute.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington left no memoirs but a memorable explanation of why he
didn't: In a letter to a friend he said, ``I had rather glide
gently down the stream of life, leaving it to posterity to think
and say what they please of me, than by any act of mine to have
vanity or ostentation imputed to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
