<HEADLINE>
ELS FIGHTING MEMORIES OF TOURNAMENTS PAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Until Bob Estes wrested the lead from Ernie Els
and three others late Friday afternoon at the Nissan Open, Els was
prepared to tiptoe to the first tee today. How else was he going to
avoid awakening the ghosts of his Riviera past?
</P>
<P>
   The last time Els, 29, led an event here, it ended
nightmarishly. At the 1995 PGA Championship, he shot a final-round
72 (after establishing a 54-hole tournament record with three
sub-70s) to drop to third. He finished two strokes behind Steve
Elkington, who overcame a six-shot deficit to beat Colin
Montgomerie with a birdie on the first playoff hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to think about that too much,'' Els said Friday
after adding a 66 to his opening 68. ``It's not a very good memory.
It was kind of hard to swallow. If I had shot anything under 70, I
would have won.''
</P>
<P>
   Els captured the attention of the American public with all the
subtlety of a gunshot in 1994 when he won the U.S. Open four months
before his 24th birthday (he added a second U.S open crown in 1987
to become the first foreigner in 84 years to win a Grand Slam title
twice).
</P>
<P>
   He has long been a headliner in his homeland of South Africa,
making a name for himself as a top junior tennis player before
unleashing his athleticism on the golf course. His breezy demeanor
has earned him the nickname ``Big Easy,'' though to be as big as he
is in South Africa is, in fact, hard.
</P>
<P>
   If Els goes more than a few weeks without winning, the sharks in
the press, smelling blood, start circling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's big-time pressure,'' he said amiably. ``What Tiger
(Woods) is in this country, I'm the equivalent (in South Africa). I
get my fair share of comments. They're probably more vocal over
there than the people are here with Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Els has played this week, he hasn't given the folks back
home much flak fodder. He is 3-under par on the three par-5s and
needed only 24 putts Friday, six fewer than in his first round. He
has missed 11 greens in regulation and eight fairways, but who's
quibbling?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not Els, who said, ``So far I've been playing quite
consistent. It's been perfect. Right now I'm 8-under. I'll take
another 8-under (the last two rounds).''
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't? Sixteen-under-par is lower than all but three of
the winning scores in the 36 previous regular PGA events that
Riviera Country Club has hosted.
</P>
<P>
   But don't look for Els to get too far ahead of himself. After
surrendering the lead on the third-to-last hole here at the PGA
Championship four years ago, he knows how long those final 36 holes
can stretch.
</P>
</TEXT>
