<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN WILL PAY WORKERS WHO SHOWED UP DURING SICKOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN REED 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ American Airlines said Friday that it will
pay the pilots and flight attendants who reported for work during
the 10-day pilot sickout, even if their flights were canceled.
</P>
<P>
   The airline also said that it will give $50 gift certificates to
airport and reservations agents who helped customers rearrange
their travel, and to operations employees who dealt with the
scheduling chaos caused by 6,700 canceled flights.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there were no talks Friday between management and the
Allied Pilots Association. The talks are expected to continue next
week, after union negotiators brief members of the union's board.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots staged a sickout Feb. 6 through Monday to protest
American's plans for integrating 300 pilots from Reno Air into
American's 9,300-member pilot corps. The dispute centers on timing.
The airline has said it would take 12 to 18 months to complete the
integration, and it wants to roll out raises as pilots are trained
for their new duties.
</P>
<P>
   The union has said it wants the raises for Reno's pilots and any
American pilots who would be promoted because of the merger to be
retroactive to Dec. 23, when American took financial control of the
airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony of this whole matter,'' American spokesman John
Hotard said, ``was that if you were a pilot who showed up for work,
and the other pilot didn't, you got sent home without pay, while
the fellow who called in sick got sick pay, assuming he had sick
days available.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the same thing was true for flight attendants, who showed
up prepared to work but got sent home because we couldn't get a
complete cockpit crew to fly the plane.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the airline decided to pay the pilots and attendants
rather than allow them to be unintended financial victims of the
sickout. Hotard would not say how much the additional pay will cost
the airline.
</P>
<P>
   Cecil Ewell, American's vice president of flight and chief
pilot, told American's pilots of the decision Friday in a message
on his telephone hot line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm well aware the turmoil of the last couple of weeks has
caused some of you to experience some financial hardship through
circumstances that were beyond your control,'' Ewell said on the
hot line.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company will not require those pilots to make up the
lost time. But he asked pilots to volunteer to fly currently
unassigned trips this month.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its normal pilot scheduling, American leaves a
percentage of its flights unassigned and depends on pilots who want
to earn extra money to volunteer for those assignments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to try to salvage the back half of the month,''
Ewell said, referring to the airline's efforts to regain consumers'
trust and loyalty in the wake of the sickout, which inconvenienced
about 670,000 travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Hotard said a number of operations staff members, particularly
those who work in the crew scheduling department, put in long hours
under trying circumstances during the sickout.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that the reservations agents, who handled calls
from travelers, and the airport agents, who had to deal
face-to-face with displaced passengers, deserved appreciation in
addition to any overtime pay they earned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people at the airports and on the reservations lines had
to face a lot of upset and angry travelers,'' Hotard said, ``and
they represented the company well in the midst of a bad
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
