<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AN INCURABLE STATUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Kenneth Starr conducted his relentless
investigation of President Clinton, many Americans were troubled.
``What can we do about it?'' they asked in frustration. But they
could do nothing, because Starr was not accountable to our
political process.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia foresaw the problem when he dissented
from the Supreme Court's 1988 decision upholding the
constitutionality of the Independent Counsel Act. If an ordinary
federal prosecutor focuses huge resources on someone in a way
unjustified by the gravity of the alleged offenses, he said, ``the
unfairness will come to roost'' where political responsibility
lies: on the prosecutor's boss, the president. But with an
independent counsel, he said, there is no accountability.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just Starr who has proved Scalia right. Other
independent counsels have used enormous resources in obsessive,
vindictive investigations of their targets.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Smaltz spent four years and $17 million investigating
Mike Espy, the former secretary of agriculture. He had Espy
indicted on 30 counts for accepting football tickets and other
``gratuities.'' A jury acquitted him on all counts. But that did
not stop Smaltz. He said: ``The actual indictment of a public
official may in fact be as great a deterrent as a conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Espy's chief of staff, Ron Blackley, was less lucky _
pathetically so. He failed to put down on his financial disclosure
form $21,000 he made from his former business in Mississippi. The
Justice Department declined to prosecute, but Smaltz did and won a
conviction. Blackley was eligible for probation under the federal
sentencing guidelines, but Judge Royce Lamberth gave him a sentence
of 27 months in prison, upheld on appeal. Before the appeal, Smaltz
tried to keep Blackley from going to Mississippi for his son's high
school graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Many who were not convicted, or indicted, by independent
counsels have been punished by impoverishment. Dozens of innocent
people have been financially broken by being called as witnesses.
Betty Currie, for example, the president's secretary, has
reportedly had lawyers' bills of about $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court majority said the act was constitutional
because it made an independent counsel removable by the attorney
general for wrongdoing. But despite abuses, none have been removed.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is now considering several instances of
possible wrongdoing by Starr. But he argues that any investigation
should be conducted by another independent counsel. He suggested
former Attorney General Griffin Bell, who with him defended tobacco
interests.
</P>
<P>
   The American Bar Association used to be a strong supporter of
the Independent Counsel Act. The other day its House of Delegates
voted overwhelmingly to oppose the law. The danger, it said, is
that independent counsels lose perspective and force their targets
to ``mortgage their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The act expires on June 30. Various proposals have been made to
amend this provision or that. But abuse is inherent in the concept
of an unaccountable prosecutor with unlimited resources.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Dash, who was Starr's ethics adviser, wrote in The New
York Times that the provision calling on a counsel to refer
possible impeachment grounds to the House had been wrongly
interpreted ``as giving the independent counsel the role of
initiating the impeachment process _ a role Congress never intended
because it would be unconstitutional.'' Where was Dash when Starr
sent his one-sided, prosecutorial referral to the House? He had
helped to write it!
</P>
<P>
   Without the Independent Counsel Act, Dash wrote, ``there is no
way to investigate possible crimes by the president.'' But
Archibald Cox and Leon Jaworski carried out the Watergate inquiry
as ad hoc special prosecutors, with no statutory basis.
</P>
<P>
   The statute invites us to take political matters to the criminal
law: a terrible mistake. Walter Dellinger, former acting solicitor
general, made the point wisely in a recent talk. ``The independent
counsel system does not work and the impeachment process does,'' he
said, ``because the latter is run by people who are politically
accountable. Politics, for all its faults, is the only way you can
run a free country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
