<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIM'S BLOOD FOUND ON CLOTHING OF DEFENDANTS IN DRAGGING DEATH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Tiny flecks of James Byrd Jr.'s blood were found
on the boots, sandals and running shoes of three white men accused
in the black man's gruesome dragging death, an expert on DNA
analysis testified on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   FBI forensic analyst Frank S. Baechtel also said that
individually unique genetic material from the three defendants was
discovered on three cigarette butts at the crime scene where Byrd
was chained behind a pickup on June 7.
</P>
<P>
   One cigarette contained DNA trace material that suggested that
Byrd might have shared a puff with defendant John William King, 24,
the first of the trio to stand trial on a capital murder charge,
said Baechtel, a 16-year veteran of the FBI's main forensic
laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The DNA sample recovered was insufficient to prove conclusively
that it was Byrd's, but it could not have been from any of the
three white men, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom, District Attorney Guy James Gray said the
test result could mean that Byrd was offered a ceremonial last
smoke that a condemned man was traditionally given before
execution.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, he described the DNA testimony as some of the strongest
evidence of the trial, which finished its fourth day of testimony
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it proves what those guys are charged with,'' said
Gray, who is prosecuting his first capital murder case.
</P>
<P>
   His opponent, defense attorney C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs,
pointed out the difficulty of his task.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this stuff you can't get around,'' he conceded during
a break after Baechtel testified. ``Hell, how can you get around
this?''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution has contended that King had planned to kidnap
and murder a black man before launching a hate group on July 4,
1998, in this East Texas community of 7,100. Handwritten documents
carrying his signature said the group was to be called the Texas
Rebel Soldiers Division of the Confederate Knights of America.
</P>
<P>
   King has maintained his innocence, insisting before the trial
that another of the defendants, Shawn Berry, killed Byrd over a
steroid drug deal. King insisted that Berry had dropped him and the
third defendant, Lawrence Russell Brewer, at the apartment shared
by the three ex-convicts.
</P>
<P>
   But the finding of Byrd's blood on King's Outback-brand sandal
contradicts that account, attorneys argued. And a Bud Lite longneck
found at the crime scene contained a trace amount of Brewer's DNA,
Baechtel said.
</P>
<P>
   The defense's case appeared to be further weakened as the day
progressed.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Berry, 25, brother of Shawn Berry, testified that King
briefly lent him his Zippo-style lighter just hours before Byrd was
slain. That conflicted with King's statement, in a November letter
to a newspaper, that he had lost the lighter a week before Byrd's
death.
</P>
<P>
   The lighter, inscribed with King's prison nickname, ``Possum,''
and carrying a Ku Klux Klan symbol, was found at the crime scene by
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   During cross-examination of witnesses, defense attorneys have
suggested that Louis Berry might have participated in Byrd's
slaying and that a pair of white Nike running shoes with the
initials ``LB'' might be his.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, Louis Berry identified three bloodstained pairs
of shoes as belonging to the three defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, who wears size 11 shoes, said he couldn't fit his foot in
the Nikes, which are size 7. He said they belonged to Lawrence
Brewer. Earlier, the FBI's Baechtel said a spot of Byrd's blood was
found on the shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Berry also said that a pair of Ralph Lauren Polo boots were his
brother's and that the sandals, a size smaller than identical ones
his brother owned, belonged to King.
</P>
<P>
   He said that on the night of June 6, hours before Byrd was
killed, King and Brewer stopped by a barbecue in nearby Burkeville.
But they refused to leave their vehicle when they heard of the
presence of a black guest, a guitar-playing jamming partner of
Louis Berry's.
</P>
<P>
   Berry said he was angered and left the party to confront King
and Brewer back in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude upset me,'' said Berry, who had recently worked
with King and Brewer cutting trees. ``They wouldn't come in because
a black guy was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry said King's term in prison for burglary of a video store
had changed him. After his release, King ``would put down black
people,'' said Berry, who has known King for nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes King would display his tattoos, including one of a
lynched African-American, Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier witness, 16-year-old Heather Hough, testified that
King once had shown her the same tattoo and used a racial slur to
describe it.
</P>
<P>
   King said before the trial that he was unaware of the tiny
marking, which he described as filler that a prison tattoo artist
worked into a complicated, ``full sleeve'' design on an arm.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution has contended that the tattoos, which include
Klan, Nazi and satanic symbols, reflect King's racist views.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has maintained that the skin art, popular among many
inmates, was done to help King, who is 5-foot-7, look tough enough
to protect himself in an overwhelmingly black cell block.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution is expected to wrap up its case against King on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
