<HEADLINE>
WHITAKER TRIES TO TURN BACK TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pernell Whitaker believes he has turned back the
clock some 14 years. He believes that when Felix Trinidad steps
into the ring against him Saturday night at Madison Square Garden,
Trinidad will not be facing a 35-year-old boxer who has not fought
in 16 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like it's 1984 and I'm going for the gold again,'' said
Whitaker, a gold medalist in the 1984 Olympic Games. ``I've feel
like I've got everything back on keel. I got my legs back. I got my
eyesight. I've got my skills.''
</P>
<P>
   But Trinidad and his father-manager-trainer, Felix Sr., have a
different view of Whitaker. They believe that Whitaker is a past
champion with a tremendous amount of pride, but that his skills
have greatly diminished. They believe that his hard-partying life
away from the ring has caught up with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still a good boxer, but the drugs and the alcohol have
taken their tolls,'' Felix Sr. said. ``But he still has his
pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker's 16-month absence from the ring included two
suspensions from boxing for failed drug tests and a drunken-driving
arrest; that charge is pending. He tested positive for cocaine
following his Oct. 17, 1997, bout against Andrei Pestriaev at
Foxwoods Resort Casino in Connecticut. He was suspended for six
months and ordered to undergo periodic testing. Before a proposed
bout against Ike Quartey last April, he again tested positive for
cocaine and was suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker said he did not have a drug or alcohol problem, and he
refused to talk about his suspensions or what he gained from his
stint in a drug rehabilitation center. Whitaker prefers to look
ahead because he says there is nothing to be gained from looking in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   For his return to the ring, however, Whitaker reached into the
past and brought back the trainer Tommy Brooks, who with George
Benton trained Whitaker right after he turned professional 15 years
ago. Brooks replaces Ronnie Shields.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy is like a drill sergeant; he says do this or do that,''
Whitaker said. ``It's like he's a teacher and I'm a student. Ronnie
is a good trainer, but with Ronnie I found that I would do a lot of
ad-libbing in the ring during fights. I didn't do any of the things
that we had worked on in training. With Tommy it's been like
school. He's been teaching and I've been learning, focusing in on
what we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said there was ``a lot of evidence'' that Whitaker had
turned the clock back. ``We had a kid named Juan Lescano in camp,
who is a good fighter,'' Brooks said. ``But if he had a handful of
rice, he still couldn't hit Pernell.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said there was no evidence that Whitaker's skills had
been diminished by drugs or alcohol abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It remains to be seen,'' Brooks said. ``But I've seen a lot of
alcoholics and drug addicts come back. You give up on yourself,
nothing is going to come of it. But if you have pride in what you
do, you'd be amazed what you can do. I'm not a doctor or a
psychologist or a therapist, but from what I see in the gym it
hasn't had an effect on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker has been noted throughout his career as a defensive
specialist who took more joy in making an opponent miss than in
knocking him out. But Brooks said they had been working on some
offensive strategies that would surprise Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pernell has never had a lot of faith in his punching power,
but that didn't mean that he didn't have it,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he is a considerable underdog against the
26-year-old Trinidad, the International Boxing Federation
welterweight champion, Whitaker said he felt so good physically and
mentally, he felt invincible.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I feel like this, at my best, it's tough to beat me,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation that Trinidad, who has been off for
10 months and has fought only eight rounds in the past two years,
has had trouble making weight for this bout. His workouts have been
closed. But he made the prescribed weight of 147 pounds at the
weigh-in Friday. Whitaker also weighed in at 147.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad expects to be able to walk through Whitaker, who is one
of the shiftier left-handers in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will be a problem,'' Trinidad said. ``I've
fought left-handers before. I wouldn't be surprised if he comes
after me. If he comes after me, I'll be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   PUNCH LINES  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The PERNELL WHITAKER-FELIX TRINIDAD &UR;  &LR; bout will be broadcast on
HBO as part of a welterweight doubleheader. The first bout, which
will begin at 9:30 p.m., will be a rebroadcast of last week's
welterweight showdown between OSCAR DE LA HOYA and IKE QUARTEY. . .
. There were still tickets available at Madison Square Garden for
the Whitaker-Trinidad bout. As of Friday more than 11,000 tickets
had been sold. Tickets range in price from $400 for ringside to
$50.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
