<HEADLINE>
UNCOVERED SHORT SALES SLIP 0.8 PERCENT ON NEW YORK EXCHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Open positions on the New York Stock
Exchange &UR;  &LR; decreased eight-tenths of 1 percent last month, to 3.63
billion shares, the exchange said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   On the American Stock Exchange, recently acquired by the
National Association of Securities Dealers' &UR;  &LR; Nasdaq market,
uncovered short sales increased 7.9 percent, to 173 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Uncovered short sales, or those with open positions, represent
shares that have been borrowed and sold but not yet covered by
repurchases. If the price of a share sold short falls, an investor
can profit by buying a share at a lower price to replace the
borrowed ones.
</P>
<P>
   On the Big Board, the short-interest figure for the month ended
Feb. 12 was equal to 1.5 percent of the total shares listed on the
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The total for the month was well below the record of 4.21
billion shares set in the month ended Sept. 15, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies, North America's largest communications
equipment manufacturer, had the lrgest increase in short interest
in the month. Short sales of Lucent, which had a 2-for-1 stock
split on Feb. 12, more than doubled, to 34.79 million shares from
13.49 million.
</P>
<P>
   The largest decrease in short interest was for Cardinal Health,
a drug wholesaler. It fell 66 percent, to 5.89 million from 17.5
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
