<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-TRYON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LORIN TRYON, CLASSIC CAR CONNOISSEUR, DIES AT 71  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mich.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lorin H. Tryon Jr., whose lifelong love of cars made him a
leading connoisseur of classic automobiles, died on Feb. 12 at the
San Ramon Valley Medical Center in San Ramon, Calif. He was 71 and
lived in Danville, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, said a representative of the
Blackhawk Automotive Museum, of which Tryon was president.
</P>
<P>
   He was best known for his 27-year involvement with the Pebble
Beach Concours d'Elegance, an annual car show that is regarded as
the leading event of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   As co-chairman of the judged competition, along with Jules
Heumann, Tryon oversaw its growth from a small regional event on
the Monterey Peninsula to one that attracts classic car aficionados
and entries from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Tryon, a third-generation Californian, was born in San Francisco
in 1927 and served in the Army in World War II before graduating
from the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   His paternal grandfather was one of California's first
automobile dealers; at the age of 7, his friends say, Lorin Tryon
was running his own 10-cent car wash at his family's home, picking
up and delivering his customers' cars, driving them himself when he
was barely tall enough to peer over the dashboard.
</P>
<P>
   Tryon's involvement with Pebble Beach happened by chance.
Heumann said that while he and Tryon were at another car show in
1971, they discussed various ways they would improve the Pebble
Beach competition if they were in charge. One organizer of the
event overhead them and challenged them to make good on their
words.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, when they took over the Concours, Heumann and Tryon
instituted a change in vehicle judging that was regarded then as
revolutionary, asking experts from each class of automobiles
presented to do the judging. Previously, generalists rather than
specialists had judged each class since the Pebble Beach
competition started in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, Tryon and Heumann continued to upgrade both the
quality of the cars in the competition and the manner in which they
were judged; eventually, the phrase ``restored to Pebble Beach
standards'' entered the car collector's lexicon as a synonym for
the highest quality.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Jerry Seinfeld entered examples of the first and last
generations of the Porsche 911. The 1990 best-of-show winner was a
1938 Bugatti Type 57SC Atlantic, owned by Ralph Lauren. Jay Leno
also has entered cars in the competition, which is held every
August on the 18th fairway at the Lodge at Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Tryon was president of the Blackhawk Automotive Museum, which
displays cars manufactured from 1925 to 1948 in Danville, site of
the 1997 conference of the Fifth World Forum for Motor Museums and
the first International Automotive Design Forum at Blackhawk, to be
held next Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Tryon and Heumann were co-recipients of the Meguiar's
Award, given annually to car collectors for outstanding
contributions to the field.
</P>
<P>
   Tryon is survived by his wife, Dolores; a daughter, Catherine; a
son, Bill, and stepchildren and grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Tryon himself had owned a large number of classic cars, among
them a 1930 Duesenberg Murphy Town Car, a 1931 Cadillac V16
Fleetwood Landaulet and a 1932 Packard 12 Dietrich Runabout.
Heumann recalled that the Cadillac ``had an unusual high-speed rear
end, and Lorin loved to drive it at 100 miles per hour.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
