<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 2/19/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) WOODSTOCK, N.Y. -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- INTERNET-LANGUAGE,
2-19 -- On his computer screen, Andrew Walker, 12, displays
abbreviations he uses in his cyberchat: ``What's up,'' ``Not too
much'' and ``Got to go.'' The protocol of informality that marks
electronic communication for Andrew and millions of others has set
off a debate about whether the Internet invigorates language or
strips it of its expressive power. (Chris Ramirez/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) LAPASTICA, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MOOD,
2-19 -- As diplomats debate, troops in Kosovo stay on alert. At
Lapastica on Friday, ethnic Albanians man a trench near Serbian
positions. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- KOSOVO-U.S., 2-19 -- With
President Jacques Chirac of France at his side during a White House
news conference, President Clinton warns President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia on Friday not to ``stonewall'' a peace
settlement in Kosovo, threatening to bomb Serbia if Milosevic
misses the Saturday deadline for an end to the talks. Clinton says
that the U.S. and France ``stand united in our determination to use
force,'' if deemed necessary. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- FLIPPER-PARDON, 2-19 --
At a ceremony Friday to pardon his great uncle, Henry O. Flipper,
Dr. William King displays the pen used by President Clinton to mark
the deed. Despite being ostracized by his white classmates, Flipper
became the first black West Point graduate in 1877. He was
court-martialed in 1881 on thievery charges that appear to have
been trumped up, then was drummed out of the service the following
year. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) STEAMBOAT SPRINGS, Colo. -- Feb. 19, 1999 --
RETIREES-TRAVEL-3, 2-19 -- Charles ``Chick'' Lebow , now 75, during
a ski race at Steamboat Springs. Lebow, a semiretired furniture
store owner, has a passion for skiing which keeps him away from his
wife for at least a month almost every year. He is emblematic of
the growing number of ``mature travelers'' who have not let age
curb their desire to visit exotic locales. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) JASPER, Alberta -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- RETIREES-TRAVEL-2,
2-19 -- Globus &AMP; Cosmos features escorted adventures like this
rafting trip on the Athabasca River in Canada. These days, many
older people, even octogenarians, can be found riding elephants in
India, horseback riding in Costa Rica and bungee jumping in New
Zealand. And the adventure-travel industry is rushing to
accommodate them. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) QUEENSTOWN, New Zealand -- Feb. 19, 1999 --
RETIREES-TRAVEL-1, 2-19 -- Mrs. Louise F. Wollan, now 88 years old,
preparing to bungee jump in Queenstown in 1994. Retirees have
always been big travelers, but now they are showing a penchant for
high-adventure travel more typical of those half their age. (New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- CLINTON, 2-19 -- French
President Jacques Chirac and President Clinton during a Friday
press conference at the White House. ``I hope that the presidency
has not been harmed,'' Clinton says of the results of the year-long
sex scandal which nearly resulted in his ouster. ``I don't believe
it has been. I can't say that I think this has been good for the
country, but we will see.'' (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SAIPAN, Northern Mariana Islands -- Feb. 19, 1999 --
SAIPAN-WORKERS-2, 2-19 -- The factories are barren but not awful,
as a class-action suit alleges. Chinese workers have propelled the
remarkable success of the garment industry here, pushing sales to
nearly $1 billion in 1998. But the class-action suit, filed here
and in California, accuses garment makers and major U.S. retailers
of systematically underpaying and mistreating workers. (Seth
Faison/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SAIPAN, Northern Mariana Islands -- Feb. 19, 1999 --
SAIPAN-WORKERS-1, 2-19 -- Federal officials say American companies
in Saipan exploit workers who, like these women, are overwhelmingly
immigrants from China. But many workers save enough in two years to
return home quite well off. (Seth Faison/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) JINXIANG, China -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- CHINA-BADGEMAKER,
2-19 -- Chen Jiashu, 46, is the owner of China's biggest
manufacturer of badges and pins, a world leader in the field. ``In
recent years we've been making insignia for Ford, badges for U.S.
police forces, emblems for the U.N. forces and for the U.S.
military too, I'm pretty sure,'' Chen says. ``Though I'm not really
sure which is which, of course, since I can't read any of them.''
(Elisabeth Rosenthal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- BOX-WHITAKER-TRINIDAD, 2-19
-- Pernell Whitaker during a press conference setting up his
Saturday night fight against Felix Trinidad at Madison Square
Garden. ``This is one of the best training camps I've ever hand,''
says Whitaker, whose drug and alcohol rehabilitation and have kept
him from fighting since 1997. Despite any self-inflicted erosion of
his formidable skills, Trinidad's father (and trainer and manager)
knows Whitaker ``still has pride.'' (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NORTHAMPTON, Mass. -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- WOMEN-ENGINEERS,
2-19 -- Hunched over their oscilloscopes and diode circuits on the
third floor of McConnell Hall at Smith College on a wet, gray
morning, all 12 students in professor Nalini Easwar's electronics
class say they hope to pursue careers in physics or engineering.
Smith, a women's college, has long had a contingent of hard-science
majors, but five out of six engineering students across the country
are male. (George Ruhe/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) TAMPA, Fla. -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-PITCHERS-2,
2-19 -- The Yankees traded Thursday for Roger Clemens, regarded as
perhaps the greatest pitcher of his era. ``He's (normally) so
upbeat. He was pacing around and couldn't sit down,'' says David
Cone of fellow pitcher David Wells, who was part of a package dealt
to Toronto for Clemens, and with whom Cone spent four hours
Thursday. ``He was very disappointed. He truly loved playing for
the Yankees.'' (Jon Adams/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) TAMPA, Fla. -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-PITCHERS-1,
2-19 -- In their most significant deal since the purchase of Babe
Ruth 79 years ago, the Yankees traded Thursday for Roger Clemens,
regarded as perhaps the greatest pitcher of his era. David Wells,
who was swapped for Clemens (along with Graeme Lloyd and Homer
Bush), walks by reporters Thursday after having learned of his
being moved to the Toronto Blue Jays. (Jon Adams/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 21 --
HILFIGER-ROCK-NITEOUT, 2-19 -- Tommy Hilfiger gets a touch-up on
the night of his fall collection. ``This is the calm before the
storm,'' Hilfiger tells his creative director, Stephen Cirona.
Hilfiger is calling 1999 ``The Year of Music,'' and although his
clothes have long been staples among hip-hop's cognoscenti, in the
past few seasons he has been recutting his image as a rock
supergroupie. (Miles Ladin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
FEB. 21 -- LILY-FASHION-2, 2-19 -- A Norman Norell dress. Rita
Watnick, owner of Lily et Cie in Beverly Hills, says her clothes
are ``another jump up altogether from what people call vintage.''
Even Tiffany Dubin, the fashion director at Sotheby's, calls the
store ``phenomenal, the Madison Avenue of vintage.'' (Marissa
Roth/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
FEB. 21 -- LILY-FASHION-1, 2-19 -- Lily et Cie's inventory of
100,000 dresses at their Beverly Hills store includes this one by
Jean Desses. ``Ninety percent of our clientele is celebrities, the
tall-and-thin club,'' says the owner, Rita Watnick. (Marissa
Roth/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ORANGETOWN, N.Y. -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB.
21 -- BIZ-HOMEOWNERS, 2-19 -- The writer with his wife, Elaine
Silver, in the basement of the investment that keeps their money
too busy to join the stock run-up. Houses are the slow-moving
steamships of assets. Adjusting for inflation, the resale values of
existing single-family homes have hardly budged since 1980.
(Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WELLINGTON, Fla. -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB.
21 -- BIZ-HORSESHOER, 2-19 -- Arnie Gervasio, whose business is
shoeing horses, works on Everest, a horse sometimes ridden in
competition by its owner, the Olympic equestrian Robert Dover.
Katherine Bateson assists. When Gervasio was 7, his family moved
next door to a Ewing, N.J., horse farm. Spending all his spare time
there, Gervasio, who is now 50, knew from Day 1 that he would
devote his life to working with horses. (Susan Greenwood/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SAN CARLOS, Calif. -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
FEB. 21 -- INVEST-ONLINE-MESSAGES, 2-19 -- David M. Schwartz,
president and chief executive of Imaginon Inc., a California
software developer, posts his own messages on the Yahoo Finance
board in an effort to squelch rumors about his company. As stock
message boards grow in popularity, pressure is mounting to rid the
boards of people who use them to illegally tout stocks and spread
false information. (Anne Dowie/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CHICAGO -- Feb. 19, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 21 --
BIZ-PROFILE-MILLER, 2-19 -- Merton H. Miller, defender of free
markets, Nobel Prize winner and most emphatically not a partner in
Long-Term Capital Management, at his desk at the University of
Chicago. ``I make my money writing about the market, not
participating in it,'' he says. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
