<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2294 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-WELLS-ART-N     02-19 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-WELLS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE CALLS ON A FRIEND: WELLS, THE BLUEST OF BLUE JAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: See also BBA-YANKS-PITCHERS, BBA-ARATON-COLUMN) 
(ART ADV: A photo of Wells was sent with Yanks-Pitchers.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ David Wells paced around his spacious home in Palm
Harbor, Fla., for hours on Thursday, feeling dejected and rejected.
Over and over, Wells talked to David Cone about his baseball life
being startlingly uprooted and about how his ultimate dream of
playing for the Yankees vanished after one fateful visit into Joe
Torre's office.
</P>
<P>
   For four memorable hours, Cone said, he had ``a wild and
rambling conversation'' with a player who considered himself a
rebel in a Yankee uniform. Wells was depressed and devastated,
unable to understand why the Yankees, his beloved Yankees, had
dealt him, Graeme Lloyd and Homer Bush to the Toronto Blue Jays for
Roger Clemens late Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in a state of shock,'' Cone said. ``Literally in a
state of shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells was so hyper, Cone said, that he hopped on a plane to
Miami on Thursday night to go on a golfing vacation. Given an extra
weekend of freedom because the Jays do not hold their first workout
for pitchers and catchers until Monday, Wells bolted to find some
solitude. After witnessing Wells' behavior, Cone predicted it would
be a long time before Wells found peace with his trade. If he ever
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been Roger Clemens, it could have been Satchel
Paige,'' Cone said. ``He feels rejected right now. He equates this
to being fired.''
</P>
<P>
   As Cone sat and Wells paced, the telephone rang continually with
friends of the 35-year-old left-hander asking him what had
happened. When two reporters showed up on Wells' doorstep, he went
ballistic and called the sheriff on them. Cone laughed as he
recalled Wells' yelling at the two reporters and then complimenting
one for being so intrepid. But, other than that outburst, Cone
described Wells as morose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I've ever seen him down like that,'' Cone said.
``He's always so upbeat. To see him so clearly and visibly upset
was a tough thing. He didn't take it well at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone said Wells received a call from Gord Ash, Toronto's general
manager, but they spoke ``very briefly'' and that puzzled the
pitcher. So Cone theorized that maybe the Blue Jays were
contemplating trading Wells to another team, like Cleveland, and
the notion of playing for the more powerful Indians gave Wells some
solace. But not for long. He loved being a Yankee and, besides, Ash
was adamant about keeping Wells.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is zero chance that we're going to move him,'' Ash told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Although some Yankees said they tried to call Wells, Cone was
the only player who trekked the 15 minutes to visit him. Cone
initially reasoned that he was the only player who had the address.
After some prodding, Cone conceded, ``They could have found him.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter said, ``I left him a message, but I haven't heard
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   After Darryl Strawberry underwent his first chemotherapy
treatment for colon cancer in Florida Friday, he visited Legends
Field for the first time and smiled when he talked about Wells.
Like him or dislike him, Wells was entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``You love to have a pitcher like him,'' Strawberry said.
``We'll probably never have another guy like him. He was one of a
kind.''
</P>
<P>
   But baseball players are notorious for gazing to the future
after their teammates are traded, and Andy Pettitte did just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody hates to see him go,'' Pettitte said. ``But I think
everybody is like: `OK We'll see you later. You got traded. We'll
see you when we play Toronto.' ''
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner was still talking about Wells like a son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that David understands how I feel about him,'' said
Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner. ``This is baseball. It
happens every day. It happened when Boston traded Babe Ruth to the
Yankees. I hate to keep reminding them about that, but it's true.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
