<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-POLITICS-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES UTILIZE MYSTIQUE OF THEIR FAMOUS KIN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ As they barnstorm for votes, Panama's
leading presidential candidates are milking the mystique of their
famous families.
</P>
<P>
   The front-runner for the May 2 election is Martin Torrijos, 35.
He is the son of Gen. Omar Torrijos, the cigar-chomping military
ruler who became a national hero by negotiating the Panama Canal
treaties that will give this country full control of the waterway
Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Running second, according to polls, is Mireya Moscoso, 53. She
is the widow of Arnulfo Arias, a firebrand populist, three-time
president and Panama's most famous civilian politician.
</P>
<P>
   Banker Alberto Vallarino, a political newcomer, is in third
place.
</P>
<P>
   Torrijos, a graduate of Texas A&AMP;M University in College Station,
has little government experience, and Moscoso has none.
</P>
<P>
   However, their ties to influential rulers of the past apparently
are more important to voters.
</P>
<P>
   Torrijos' campaign headquarters is plastered with posters of his
father. Moscoso heads the Arnulfista Party, which is named after
her late husband.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts shave said that the nostalgia stems from Panamanians'
disappointment with recent governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do we remember the past? Because our present leaders have
given us nothing,'' said Francisco Alvarez, a volunteer in the
Moscoso campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Omar Torrijos, who came to power in a 1968 coup that overthrew
Arias, is blamed by critics for ushering in 21 years of military
rule.
</P>
<P>
   Torrijos took under his wing a young National Guard lieutenant
named Manuel Antonio Noriega, who later became dictator and was
ousted in the U.S. intervention in the Panama crisis of 1989.
</P>
<P>
   But Torrijos also brought minorities into government for the
first time. He built schools and public housing. He negotiated the
canal treaties with then-President Carter.
</P>
<P>
   A restless leader who loved the countryside, Torrijos waded
across rivers to visit Indian villages and landed his helicopter in
fields for impromptu town meetings. He was killed in a plane crash
in 1981, but there are reminders of him throughout Panama.
</P>
<P>
   In Panama City are a Torrijos museum and a neighborhood called
Torrijos-Carter. After several visits to Panama in the 1970s,
British writer Graham Greene wrote a complimentary book about
Torrijos called ``Getting to Know the General.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Omar Torrijos achieved the national goal in the 1970s of
recuperating the Canal Zone. Back then, the objective was clear,''
said Juan Jovane, an economist at the University of Panama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that that's happened, what is the national project? All
three candidates are looking for the key.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What the people yearn for is the simplicity of that
government, its accessibility and its willingness to listen,''
wrote Nils Castro, a columnist for the Panama City daily La Prensa.
</P>
<P>
   Current President Ernesto Perez Balladares is widely viewed as
aloof. Although he heads the Revolutionary Democratic Party, or PRD
_ a leftist party founded by Omar Torrijos _ many have said that he
has turned a blind eye to Panama's social problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel cheated,'' said one PRD member, explaining that he had
expected a more populist government. ``He spends all his time with
bankers.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez Balladares has modernized the economy and privatized
inefficient state companies. Panama has enjoyed robust economic
growth throughout much of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   But the economic measures have hurt industries and farmers.
Unemployment is about 14 percent and the gap between rich and poor
is growing. There are concerns about Panama's ability to run the
canal and to develop Canal Zone properties.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, voters soundly defeated a referendum to change the
Constitution and allow Perez Balladares to run for a second
consecutive five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   The result left the PRD scrambling for a candidate to shore up
the party's working-class base. In the primary, Martin Torrijos
defeated his half-brother, Omar Torrijos Jr., and his cousin, Hugo
Torrijos.
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Marco Gandasegui questioned whether Martin
Torrijos is prepared for the rough and tumble of a political
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have the charisma of his father,'' Gandasegui said.
``He's a nice guy, but he's not a politician.''
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, Torrijos joined a brigade of Panamanian
volunteers who fought in the 1979 Sandinista uprising against
Nicaraguan dictator Anastasio Somoza.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he graduated from Texas A&AMP;M with degrees in economics and
political science. He was a manager for McDonald's in Chicago, then
returned to Panama to serve as vice minister of government and
justice under President Perez Balladares.
</P>
<P>
   Torrijos has pledged a kinder, gentler brand of government,
although he has acknowledged that Panama lacks the resources to
resurrect the populist programs for which his father's government
was known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our party is founded on the ideology of `Torrijismo,' but we
understand that there is a new reality, that this isn't the
1970s,'' Torrijos said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a globalized world that requires excellence and
efficiency,'' he said. ``But what is valid is the method that Gen.
Torrijos used of consultation and participation.''
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso also has the common touch. During a recent campaign
swing through a poor Panama City neighborhood, she wore jeans and a
red sweatshirt. She was followed by a three-man band playing an
accordion, maracas and drums.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, her late husband, Arnulfo Arias, often was seen as
bombastic and arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   He threatened to rescind the citizenship of Panamanian blacks
and to dissolve the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   He also experienced the wrath of the United States during World
War II by refusing to allow the installation of military bases
outside the Canal Zone.
</P>
<P>
   But Arias also extended the right to vote to women, established
a social security system and pushed through land reform and a
progressive income tax.
</P>
<P>
   Arias became a kind of martyr for civilian government because
all three of his presidential terms were cut short by coups. He is
believed to have won the fraud-tainted 1984 presidential election
in which Noriega's hand-picked candidate was declared the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arnulfo Arias was involved in politics for 75 years. He left
behind a doctrine which was to work for the poorest people in this
country,'' said Moscoso, as she shook hands with supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is our guide. It's like a religion,'' said Alvarez, the
campaign volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso met Arias in 1964 when he was in his 60s and she was a
teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   The two were married in 1969 in the United States, where they
lived in exile for a decade. Arias died in 1988. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Two years later, Moscoso helped found the Arnulfista Party. She
narrowly lost the 1994 election to President Perez Balladares.
</P>
<P>
   Although she is a tireless campaigner, Moscoso has never held a
government job.
</P>
<P>
   She holds a diploma in interior design from a Florida community
college and has worked as an executive secretary and as a sales
manager for a coffee distributorship.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the influential wife of the Argentine populist
leader Juan Domingo Peron, one analyst described Moscoso as ``Evita
Peron lite.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
