<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rain delays Rockingham qualifying
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKINGHAM, N.C. _ Qualifying for Sunday's Dura-Lube/Big Kmart
400 at North Carolina Speedway was postponed Friday because of
rain.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup qualifying was rescheduled for 10:45 a.m. today,
with the Alltel 200 Busch race slated to start at 1 p.m. An hour of
Cup qualifying will follow the Busch race, time permitting.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts called for snow flurries in the Rockingham area this
morning. If Winston Cup qualifying is canceled, the 43-car field
will consist of the top 30 cars based on last year's owner
standings points, the six remaining drivers with the earliest
postmarks on their entry forms and seven provisional spots.
</P>
<P>
   Some drivers were welcoming the cold weather, minus the
precipitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes the track a little better,'' Dale Jarrett said.
``Obviously, this track is worn quite a bit, so the cooler it is,
the better it'll be in that respect. It shouldn't wear the tires
quite as bad, so it should be better racing. You'll have to work
with the setup a little bit because it should be a tighter race
track.''
</P>
<P>
   NO BAD BLOOD
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett says he holds no hard feelings against Yates Racing
teammate Kenny Irwin, who knocked him out of last week's Daytona
500. On the 135th lap, Irwin tapped the left rear of Jarrett's No.
88 Ford, sending Jarrett sideways and causing a 13-car pileup
between turns 3 and 4.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, a two-time winner in the 500, finished 37th; Irwin,
last year's Winston Cup rookie of the year, was third.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing about the whole situation is Kenny is not
getting to enjoy his best run as a Cup driver,'' Jarrett said. ``He
did a tremendous job and put himself in a position to win the
Daytona 500, and people aren't letting him enjoy that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did touch. Yes, that did happen, but it was racing, and
it's as much my fault as anybody's. I put myself in a position for
something like that to happen, so everything is fine between Kenny
and I.''
</P>
<P>
   NO SECOND THOUGHTS
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace, who led more than half the Daytona 500 before
losing the lead and race to Jeff Gordon, says he has no regrets
about letting Gordon back in line with only 10 laps remaining. If
Wallace hadn't moved over, Gordon probably would have crashed into
the rear of Ricky Rudd's slow-moving No. 10 Ford on the apron in
the first turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only thing I could have done, in my mind,'' Wallace
said. ``I mean, it was a Catch-22. ... It would have been the
biggest fire in the world, and we wouldn't have needed that. A
couple of people could have died on that one, so there's nothing I
could do, really. I still stand by what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSCH LINEUP
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt Jr.'s fortunes at ``The Rock'' changed Friday
when he drew the pole for today's Alltel 200 after qualifying was
canceled. Earnhardt Jr., the defending Busch champion, finished
16th and 14th in last year's events here.
</P>
<P>
   The top 33 drivers in last year's standings points made the
field, along with Johnny Benson, the '95 Busch champion, who got a
provisional. The other nine drivers were determined by the date of
the postmark on their entry forms.
</P>
<P>
   Among those missing the field were Jeff Green, who finished
second in last week's Busch race at Daytona, Adam Petty and Cup
regulars Bobby Labonte, Mike Skinner and Dick Trickle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
