<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-INFRACTION20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Garner reprimanded for recruiting violation
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia defensive line coach and recruiting
coordinator Rodney Garner was reprimanded by athletics director
Vince Dooley and restricted to on-campus recruiting for a week
after committing a secondary NCAA violation, according to documents
obtained by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Garner, who was credited for much of the Bulldogs' recruiting
success this winter, contacted a recruit from South Carolina at the
Shrine Bowl high school all-star football game in North Carolina in
December, a period when recruiting is restricted. After realizing
he'd made improper contact, Garner reported the violation to
Georgia's compliance office, which reported it to the SEC and the
NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   Garner was forced to forgo the final three of seven personal
contacts allowed with the prospect (defensive back Brian Mance of
Manning, S.C.), received a letter of reprimand from Dooley and had
to stay on campus for seven days in early January. Mance eventually
signed with Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   Because it was a secondary violation and Georgia self-reported
it, no other action was taken by the SEC or NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia reported another secondary violation in January in which
two student managers donated the Bulldogs' discarded practice pants
to their respective high schools without the knowledge of UGA
administrators. As a result, the football staff was directed to
reduce by two the possible recruiting visits to Irwin County High
in Ocilla and Palmetto High in Williamston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia just completed the second year of a two-year probation
for recruiting violations that occurred under former head coach Ray
Goff. But Dooley emphatically denied that the Bulldogs have a
compliance problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are secondary violations, we reported them, we took
action and (the NCAA) approved of what we did,'' Dooley said. ``We
tried to nip it in the bud, and that's what self-policing is all
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has these secondary violations. It may look like
you're doing all these things wrong. But there are so many rules in
the (NCAA manual), you're bound to inadvertently break one.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
