<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2316 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UGA-JIRSA20-COX     02-19 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGA-JIRSA20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dooley lends support to Jirsa
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia athletics director Vince Dooley made two
things clear Friday: One, he's not satisfied with the job coach Ron
Jirsa is doing with the basketball program and, two, he's not going
to fire Jirsa anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' was Dooley's flat answer when asked if there was a
chance Jirsa could lose his job before next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stance is I'm disappointed, just as coach Jirsa is, just as
the team is,'' Dooley said. ``But we hired him, and we've got a
commitment to him, and we're going to do everything we can to help
him succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dooley offered no mandate like the one he gave former football
coach Ray Goff in 1994, in which he said the team needed to make
``significant improvement'' the following season for Goff to be
retained. But he did say that if the Bulldogs' fortunes don't
improve next season, he might ``have to make some decisions about
(Jirsa's) contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, basketball coach Hugh Durham was critical of
Dooley's handling of his contract situation. Dooley chose not to
extend Durham's deal after the 1993 and 1994 seasons, and Durham
claimed that it put him at a disadvantage in recruiting. Durham was
fired in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Jirsa is in the second year of a five-year contract, so he will
have three years remaining after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's fair to go into (recruiting) with one year
left,'' Dooley said. ``We've got a commitment to him. He's got
(three) years left and I think that's fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Jirsa said he appreciated Dooley's vote of confidence and is
unconcerned about his contract status.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the opportunity Coach Dooley gave us here,''
Jirsa said. ``He gives all our sports an opportunity to succeed.
The basketball program needs to take advantage of that and make it
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs, who returned four seniors and SEC
player-of-the-year candidate Jumaine Jones from last year's NIT
semi-finalists, have fallen short of expectations. They enter
Saturday's home game against LSU with a 14-11 overall record _ 5-8
in the SEC _ and they're 0-6 against ranked teams this season.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Jirsa has been the object of increased criticism by
newspaper columnists, on radio talk shows and in Internet
chatrooms. On his syndicated radio call-in show Thursday night,
Dooley found himself defending Jirsa for much of the hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Georgia Tech had fired Bobby Dodd after two years, that
program would have never done what it did,'' he told one
particularly irate caller. ``And coach Dodd's career got off to a
rugged start.''
</P>
<P>
   Jirsa said he is aware of all the criticism but insists that he
uses it as motivation rather than let it get him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm human,'' he said. ``It hurts sometimes. But I know which
direction this program's going in. I've been an athlete and a
coach, and I believe in myself and the people in our program, from
our coaches and staff to our players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs' low point of the year came Wednesday when they
were blown out by Kentucky, a team it extended to overtime before
losing in Athens on Jan. 26. Although Jones, the SEC's leading
scorer and Georgia's leading rebounder, was injured and played only
16 minutes in the game, his absence was not enough to justify
Kentucky's 25-3 rebounding advantage in the first half and 49-24
for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Rebounding is considered a hustle statistic and accusations
quickly arose that the Georgia players have quit on Jirsa. Dooley
discounted such a notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I think Jumaine got hurt,'' Dooley said. ``Kentucky will
blow out a lot of teams in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior Ray Harrison, a three-year starter who was benched three
games ago in favor of hot-shooting freshman D.A. Layne, said the
players remain committed and have no problems with Jirsa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Jirsa has been there for us, and we're going to be there
for him,'' Harrison said. ``He takes a lot of criticism that should
probably be directed at us players. Coach Jirsa's a great person
and a great coach. We haven't quit believing in him.''
</P>
<P>
   If Georgia is to achieve its stated goal of reaching the NCAA
Tournament this season, it needs to win its last three
regular-season games and two or three more in the SEC Tournament.
And that still might not be enough to land an at-large bid.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the final outcome is, Dooley said it won't
influence his decision. But his comments make it clear that next
season will be an important year for Jirsa. Considering that the
Bulldogs lose four seniors to graduation and possibly Jones to the
NBA draft, that might not be good news.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Jirsa's still thinking about this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we are disappointed in the season to this point,'' he
said. ``But the season's not over.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
