</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COMBINE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trade talk heats up at combine
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Over the past few years, while the number of
prospects who participate in the on-field drills has dramatically
decreased, the annual NFL scouting combine has become as much about
rhetoric as running.
</P>
<P>
   Aptitude tests and individual interviews with players have
replaced the 40-yard dash as priorities for most teams, who know
the top-rated performers will work out later in the spring. But
this year's combine, which began Friday, might produce even more
talk than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time free agency started before the combine
was held, so you'll have a lot of agents here trying to do
business,'' Tennessee general manager Floyd Reese said Friday.
``There might not be a lot of action as far as (completing) deals,
but there will be plenty of talk.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, who probably can afford one high-profile signing
and perhaps the addition of a few role players, will be involved in
some of that discussion. Denver agent Peter Schaffer will meet
today with Falcons general manager Harold Richardson about several
of his clients, notably cornerback Ronnie Bradford, former Denver
safety Steve Atwater and former New York Giants wide receiver Chris
Calloway. Club officials have indicated interest in all three.
</P>
<P>
   Schaffer huddled Friday with Bengals owner Mike Brown, who is
interested in Bradford. The six-year veteran, who started 24 games
in two years with the Falcons, will visit Kansas City next Tuesday.
Atwater, released earlier this week by the Broncos, already has
attracted strong interest from the Chiefs and New York Jets.
Calloway is a good fit for the Falcons because he won't command a
high price and the team could use another veteran wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   THE ZEIER WATCH
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Ravens personnel director Ozzie Newsome all but
confirmed Friday that the team is shopping backup quarterback Eric
Zeier. Asked if he had discussed a deal with the Falcons, Newsome
said: ``No, not yet. But as soon as I see (Richardson), I plan to
get things going.'' One major hurdle is that the Ravens are seeking
a second-round pick for Zeier. The Falcons don't have a
second-rounder, having sent it to San Diego in the trade for wide
receiver Tony Martin.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-END TACKLES
</P>
<P>
   Georgia offensive tackles Matt Stinchcomb and Chris Terry took
their physical exams Friday and will work out today in the RCA
Dome. Scouts seem split over which of the two will go higher in the
draft. The prevailing opinion is that Stinchcomb is the more
polished, while Terry is a better athlete and could become a better
player in the long-term. ``It's a pretty good year for tackles, but
both those guys are in the top group on everyone's list,'' said Bob
Palcic, Cleveland Browns offensive line coach. ``You probably can't
go wrong with either one, although the consensus seems to be that
Matt is more ready to play immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   BAILEY WON'T RUN
</P>
<P>
   Scouts will be disappointed that Georgia cornerback Champ
Bailey, who arrives today, won't run the 40-yard dash when
defensive backs work out Monday. Bailey suffered a hamstring injury
running track and probably needs about 10 days to fully recover.
He'll work out for scouts in Athens on March 17 and 24. ``From
everything that I've seen on film, he's the real deal,'' Minnesota
defensive coordinator Foge Fazio said. ``He's one of those `eraser'
cornerbacks. Put him on a receiver and the guy disappears.'' Bailey
is a consensus top 5 pick, and the only players most teams rate
ahead of him are Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch and Texas tailback
Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ETC. ...
</P>
<P>
   Couch is not expected to throw when quarterbacks work out
Sunday. ... Georgia Tech punter Rodney Williams had a solid
workout. ... Angelo Wright, the agent for Falcons free agent
defensive end Antonio Edwards, met with Carolina officials here
Friday. ... Giants officials confirmed they've agreed to terms with
quarterback Kerry Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
