<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2319 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-GIFTS20-COX     02-19 1450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GIFTS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bid inquiry: Come clean? We are clean, Atlanta says
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Stung by the Olympic bribery scandal in Salt Lake
City, U.S. Olympic officials are urging Atlanta to come clean on
any improprieties connected with its bid for the Centennial Games.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta bid leaders have told the U.S. Olympic Committee their
process was free of abuses and that they have ``nothing to report''
about corruption.
</P>
<P>
   However, widely publicized reports of excessive gifts for the
International Olympic Committee and multiple visits to Atlanta by
IOC members and their families have prompted USOC officials to seek
more information about the Atlanta bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll try to make as accurate a report as possible,'' USOC
Executive Director Dick Schultz said Friday in a telephone
interview. ``The people we have looking into it will get to the
bottom of whatever is there.''
</P>
<P>
   The USOC delayed a formal response to an IOC inquiry into the
Atlanta bid last week, noting it was preoccupied with other
investigations into the Salt Lake City scandal. But at that time,
the USOC said Atlanta Olympic officials provided no information
about improper actions by IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Payne, president of the Atlanta bid committee, still
contended Friday that the bid effort was free of bribery and
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Payne acknowledged that some gifts cost more than the $200
guideline set by the IOC, and that some members came to Atlanta
more than the one-visit limit. But he characterized the gifts and
extra trips as gestures of good will toward friends from Atlanta
officials, and not demands by IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have said we were not perfect. We used our judgment of what
was right and fair and we did that effectively,'' Payne said. ``We
did not bribe anyone. We were not extorted by IOC members. We did
not make cash payments. We did not give outrageous gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Atlantans were proud of their effort to find
personal and creative gifts, regardless of the cost, for individual
members.
</P>
<P>
   They gave the late IOC member from Cuba a live bulldog after he
expressed admiration for a ceramic bulldog in Payne's office.
</P>
<P>
   For the Romanian member interested in European history between
World Wars I and II, they found three books on the topic.
</P>
<P>
   To the horse lover from Germany, they gave a lithograph of
Citation.
</P>
<P>
   Several members received a golf club _ a driver _ following
outings at Augusta National Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Before a formal dinner in Savannah, bid official Charlie Battle
purchased a sports coat for a guest accompanying the IOC member
from Swaziland who had brought no coat or tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what any of that was worth,'' said Battle, weary
on Friday after being besieged with inquiries following a
front-page Washington Post story on Atlanta's bid. ``We didn't do
anything wrong. We were not trying to abuse the process. We didn't
give any $10,000 guns. We gave what we felt like were appropriate
gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   Gift-giving was a preoccupation for the small bid team. Presents
were handed out every time a member came to town and were offered
en masse at every official gathering. Atlanta bid members packed
their suitcases for out-of-town meetings with logo-embossed ties,
scarves and watches.
</P>
<P>
   They tried home-style mementoes, such as glass sculptures and
hand-carved wooden bowls from a North Georgia artist. There were
slippers, embroidered pillow cases, alarm clocks and portable CD
players with an Atlanta Symphony Orchestra disc for every IOC
member.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not remotely akin to what we have been reading about,
such as giving cash inducements or scholarships for the purpose of
influencing votes,'' said Payne.
</P>
<P>
   A Salt Lake City ethics committee disclosed last week that its
bidders made improper cash payments and gifts _ including expensive
guns _ totaling more than $1.2 million to some 24 IOC members,
roughly one-fifth of the committee. Nine IOC members have resigned
or been expelled.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, the IOC said it had received more than 20
responses from the 28 letters it sent in late January to national
Olympic committees and former bidding committees, seeking evidence
of further wrongdoing in the wake of the Salt Lake City scandal.
The USOC, which is responding on behalf of Atlanta, requested an
extension until March 1.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz said he expects USOC lawyers to re-interview Atllanta
bid officials so the committee can send its response to the IOC
early next week. ``I don't know what that response is yet,'' he
said, adding ``obviously it will have to'' detail any wrongdoing on
the part of the bid committee or IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC specifically asked bid committees to report whether its
members or their
</P>
<P>
   relatives accepted money, gifts, medical services scholarships,
employment or excessive hospitality. It wants to know if any IOC
members accepted multiple visits or brought more than one guest.
</P>
<P>
   Several Atlanta bid team leaders acknowledge that some IOC
members visited more than once, and five of them have been
implicated in the Salt Lake scandal: Jean-Claude Ganga from the
Republic of Congo, Phil Coles of Australia, Willi Kaltschmitt of
Guatemala, Agustin Arroyo of Ecuador and Vitaly Smirnov of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Some members brought several relatives with them, typically a
spouse and child. Visits are supposed to be limited to a member and
one guest.
</P>
<P>
   Payne does not view those visits as violations of the IOC's
bidding rules. The extra guests came at the invitation of Atlantans
and were not demanded by IOC members, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not extorted. They were nice people. They were our
friends,'' Payne said. ``There was nothing wrong with it. It didn't
violate the integrity of the process. It was being responsive to
friendships that were developed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta bidders treated their friends like royalty here.
They flew first-class, stayed in luxury hotels and were provided a
car, driver and hostess. They were feted in private homes. The
wives went shopping at Phipps Plaza and Lenox Square while the
husbands took tours of venues.
</P>
<P>
   They attended Braves baseball and University of Georgia football
games. They took in concerts at Chastain and the Fox Theatre. One
member was treated to the Georgia-Florida football game in
Jacksonville after a visit to Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   Every visiting member was offered a one-day trip to Disney
World, though only a few took advantage of the opportunity, Payne
said. Disney World was one of Atlanta's selling points during the
bid. All 10,000 athletes were promised a Disney visit during the
Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to do two shuttles every day from the Olympic
Village. We sold that big-time,'' Payne recalled. ``We ended up not
doing it because we ran out of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the athletes may not have boarded planes for a special
trip, IOC members hopped on corporate jets _ donated by the likes
of Cox Enterprises and Coca-Cola _ to Augusta, where Payne proposed
staging Olympic golf, and Savannah, where yachting would take
place.
</P>
<P>
   While there, they were toasted in high style. In Augusta, they
played at the exclusive course where the famed Masters tournament
is held, typically as guests of a club member such as Atlantan
Charlie Yates.
</P>
<P>
   From Savannah, former presidential candidate Steve Forbes
captained a half-dozen IOC members on a cruise aboard his father
Malcolm's fabulously appointed yacht. Fireworks and champagne
enhanced the experience.
</P>
<P>
   Payne and other Atlanta bid team members are incensed that
anyone would suggest such visits and entertainment were out of
line.
</P>
<P>
   He promised to cooperate with any further inquiries by the USOC
but does not believe he has anything more to report.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Atlanta's rivals for the 1996 Olympics have submitted
reports, which contain little new information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've written the IOC a three-page letter that says,
essentially, nothing to report,'' said Bob Scott, the head of
Manchester's unsuccessful bids for the 1996 and 2000 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Henderson, who headed the Toronto bid, said the report from
his committee contains essentially the same information it
submitted eight years ago during a review of the bidding campaign
for the 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
   Both said they would be reluctant to identify violators because
they fear the legal repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I'm a private citizen,'' Henderson said. ``What's to
stop some IOC member from filing a libel lawsuit against me if I
make some accusation against them that I can't actually document?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bert Roughton Jr. contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
