<SLUG> BC-BBN-GALARRAGA20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Galarraga cancer has spread slightly
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Doctors have determined that Braves first baseman
Andres Galarraga has stage II non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, in which the
cancer has spread locally but still has a favorable prognosis.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Henderson, Galarraga's oncologist, said Friday that
the cancer has affected the third lumbar vertebra of the spine and
part of the fourth lumbar vertebra, which are located in the lower
back, as well as two small adjacent lymph nodes.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson reiterated his optimism that Galarraga's treatment,
which will begin next week after he returns to his home in West
Palm Beach, Fla., will be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has an excellent chance of being cured, not just
recovering, but of being cured,'' Henderson said. ``He's one of the
most healthy-looking people I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma has four stages, with stage I being the
earliest. In stage II, cancer is found in more than one lymph node
area on one side of the diaphragm, the breathing muscle that
roughly divides the top and bottom halves of the body.
</P>
<P>
   Lymphoma of the spine often carries the risk of damaging the
spinal cord. Galarraga's cancer was diagnosed after he complained
of recurrent back pain, but it does not threaten the spinal cord,
Henderson said. ``This is nowhere near that point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga will undergo five months of chemotherapy to kill the
cancerous cells, followed by one month of radiation. Doctors said
that as of now they do not anticipate extending treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
