<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-PORT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS IN THE RUNNING TO LAND WINNING SITE FOR A NEW SPACE PORT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: VentureStar is cq) 
(Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A state-backed effort being formulated will pit Texas
against heavily favored Florida and 14 other states for a
potentially lucrative prize: a commercial space port for the coming
generation of unmanned reusable rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next two years, Lockheed Martin Corp. plans to select
a site in one of the states to serve as a launching and landing
site for VentureStar, a radically new spacecraft. Lockheed Martin
plans to develop VentureStar operations by 2005, marketing the new
rocket globally as a low-cost launcher for a burgeoning number of
new communications satellites. It also would be a low-cost
alternative to NASA's space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   State officials estimate a Lockheed Martin space port in Texas
could mean as many as 15,000 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we compete with those states?'' pondered Tom Moser, the
former space agency executive recruited to serve as executive
director of the Texas Aerospace Commission. ``It will be tough, but
the answer is yes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is spearheading the state's bid to lure Lockheed
Martin as well as at least two smaller companies to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry among states is straight out of Jules Verne's
19th-century, fiction classic, ``From the Earth to the Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   In that book, Verne writes of a politically charged rivalry
between Texans and Floridians over which state will serve as the
launching site for a mythical manned moon rocket.
</P>
<P>
   The fictional Floridians prevail, just as their real life
counterparts did a century later. Today, Florida's Cape Canaveral
hosts sprawling federally-financed launch complexes for NASA's
shuttle and the expendable rockets that hurtle easterly into
equatorial orbits with commercial, scientific and military
spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   Less frequently, California's Vandenberg Air Force Base
dispatches similar payloads launched by rockets on a southerly
course into polar orbits.
</P>
<P>
   Three sites in Texas under Lockheed Martin's consideration would
support launches on either equatorial or polar trajectories,
according to Moser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the financial stakes soaring, competition for the new space
ports is fierce.
</P>
<P>
   According to the International Telecommunications Union, global
communications has approached a $1 trillion a year industry, with
satellites playing a growing role in the expansion. The state
commission's own research estimates 1,700 satellite launches, many
of them to meet communications needs, over the coming decade. Last
year, U.S. companies conducted 42 percent of all rocket launches,
the most of any nation.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, and with little public fanfare, Moser has
marshalled a coalition of local economic development agencies from
across Texas to pursue VentureStar operations. With consultants
from the Aerospace Corp., a California-based Air Force think tank,
the commission assessed 14 potential sites in Texas, whittling the
total to three with the best qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   They include stretches of coastal plain south and west of
Freeport in Brazoria County near Houston and south and east of
Kingsville in Kenedy County in South Texas. The third site sprawls
across rural West Texas scrub land in Pecos County east of Fort
Stockton and just south of Interstate 10. Launch operations from
any of the three sites would pose no more than a one in 30 million
risk of casualty, Moser said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the state legislature is awaiting the introduction of
a bill this session that if enacted would create the incentives
Moser said Texas will need to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets down to dollars,'' he said. ``We can compete if we put
together the right public-private partnership. Texas has to be
willing to be a partner, but we want Texas to be a small partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Prospective sponsors of the legislation would not discuss
provisions this week. But they will likely provide for the creation
of a local space port authority, tax abatements and potential
funding mechanisms to provide roadways, utilities and other
facilities intended to serve as inducements.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency envisions VentureStar as a potential
replacement for the shuttle, cutting its cost of carrying cargos to
and from the U.S.-led international space station.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin's concept is a lightweight, wedge-shaped
spacecraft that, unlike the manned space shuttle, would lift off
vertically and soar to orbit without dropping off auxiliary
propulsion stages. After its mission, the VentureStar would glide
to an automated landing at its launch site along a 12,000 foot
runway.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the new rocket would be rugged enough to be
refurbished and launched again within days, a strategy it forecasts
could cut the cost of delivering cargo to orbit from the current
$10,000 a pound to $1,000 a pound. If successful, the strategy
could help to open new space markets, including tourism.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of site selection, right now that looks like sometime
in the year 2000,'' said Ron Lindeke, a Lockheed spokesman at the
company's Skunk Works division in Palmdale, Calif. ``We were
looking at early November. Now we are probably looking at late 2000
for the selection.''
</P>
<P>
   To hedge its competitive efforts, the Texas Aerospace Commission
is also pursuing space port opportunities with Washington-based
Kistler Aerospace Corp. and California-based Space Access.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
