<DOCNO> NYT19990219.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2330 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATH-PENALTY-BIAS-1S     02-19 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-PENALTY-BIAS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNUSUAL NEBRASKA CASE BEING WATCHED BY DEATH-PENALTY EXPERTS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS to expand 9th graf of 1st take. Tightens lede graf. No other
changes. ) (mk) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. _ If everything had gone according to schedule,
Randolph Reeves would be dead by now, executed in Nebraska's
electric chair for killing two women nearly 19 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But very little about Reeves' case has been predictable.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, in an overwhelmingly pro-death-penalty state,
some of those arguing most strenuously that Reeves' life be spared
are his two victims' relatives, who say they will be devastated if
Reeves is put to death.
</P>
<P>
   That is partly because Reeves, an Omaha Indian adopted as a
child by a white Quaker couple, was raised in that faith, which
shuns all violence, and because his two victims, one of them a
Quaker, were both strongly opposed to the death penalty. They were
killed in March 1980 in a Quaker meetinghouse in Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   National Quaker organizations have recently taken up Reeves'
cause, arguing emphatically that his death would only hurt his
victims more.
</P>
<P>
   But even more striking was the 11th-hour decision on Jan. 12 by
the Nebraska Supreme Court to grant Reeves a stay of execution
after his lawyer appealed under a new amendment to the Nebraska
constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment, which guarantees all Nebraska citizens equal
rights under the law, was approved in November by voters who
apparently did not expect it to be used to try to overturn a death
penalty sentence. (Most proponents of the measure had said they saw
it as a formality, a clause that most other states already had and
would make little practical difference in Nebraska.) But because of
the Reeves case, the new law could have repercussions well beyond
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Reeves filed an appeal asserting that he had been
the victim of a death penalty sentence that discriminates against
minorities. The lawyer said that although Indians and blacks make
up 4 percent of Nebraska's population, six of the 20 death-row
inmates _ 30 percent _ are members of these minority groups, as
were two of the three inmates executed in Nebraska since the state
reinstated the death penalty in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge filed under the Nebraska equal protection law is
one of several lawsuits in recent years that have sought to test
whether state constitutions might be interpreted differently than
the federal Constitution on issues ranging from gay rights to
searches and seizures. The Nebraska rights law was the issue that
the state Supreme Court said it would consider when it halted
Reeves' execution two days before he was to die.
</P>
<P>
   If Reeves is successful in his appeal, it would be the first
time that a death sentence was overturned based on an argument of
racial disparity, and death penalty experts are closely watching to
see how the Nebraska case turns out.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for death-row defendants have long sought to make the
case that the system disproportionately imposes death sentences on
members of minorities or on defendants whose victims were white.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 3,549 inmates on death row in the United States, 1,499,
or 42 percent, are black, according to the Death Penalty
Information Center, a research group. Blacks make up 13 percent of
the population. Hispanic inmates and those of other minorities make
up 391 of the people on death row. There are 1,659 whites awaiting
execution.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago, most experts thought the door was closed on
racial-disparity arguments when the U.S. Supreme Court found, in
the case of a Georgia black man, that it was not enough to show a
statistical pattern of racial disparity on death row without proof
that a jury or judge intentionally discriminated against a
particular defendant, something that is extremely difficult to
prove.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, states have begun to examine racial
discrimination arguments. In cases in New Jersey, North Carolina
and Colorado, state courts have suggested that they may be swayed
solely by a statistical pattern of discrimination, even though they
said they had not found a convincing pattern in the cases before
them, said Jennifer Friesen, a professor at Loyola Law School in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the death penalty law, passed in 1995, explicitly
allows for defendants to appeal by claiming that members of their
racial group are disproportionately sentenced to death. And last
year, Kentucky passed a law that allows defendants in capital cases
to make such claims even before they are put on trial, allowing
them to seek a guarantee that they would not get the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   In the Nebraska case, Reeves' lawyer, Paula Hutchinson, says she
believes that the discriminatory argument has a chance because the
language in Nebraska's equal protection clause, she says, suggests
that as long as there has been a discriminatory effect, no proof of
intentional discrimination is required.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say they would be stunned if the death sentence is
commuted on grounds of discrimination. Others say the outcome is
impossible to predict. Some point out that it is significant that
the argument is being considered at all by the Nebraska court,
which is viewed as fairly conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the last minute this new law opens up some possible relief
and we're just watching to see if that happens,'' said Richard
Dieter, executive director of the Death Penalty Information Center.
``Clearly, it's going to affect more than the Reeves case. Most
cases could be affected by this.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, 42, was convicted of using a kitchen knife to stab to
death Janet Mesner, 30, and Victoria Lamm, 28, in the early morning
of March 29, 1980. Ms. Mesner was living in the Quaker meetinghouse
and working as its caretaker, and her friend Ms. Lamm, who was 15
weeks' pregnant, had returned for a visit after moving to Oregon.
Ms. Lamm's 2 1/2-year-old daughter, Audrey, was also in the house,
but does not remember anything about that night.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mesner lived long enough to call police and identify Reeves
as the killer. Reeves, a construction worker on temporary jobs who
was known to be a drinker but not a violent man, later confessed to
the killings, but said he remembered little about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of Reeves say his actions were a result of heavy beer
drinking combined with the use of peyote, a cactus that causes
hallucinations. To counter that argument, prosecutors said that if
that Reeves had been so drugged he did not know right from wrong,
he would have been too impaired to commit the murders.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 3, Reeves was removed from a troubled family on
the Omaha Indian Reservation and adopted by Donald and Barbara
Reeves, who lived on a farm in Central City. The Reeveses are
distant cousins of the Mesners and attend the same meetinghouse in
Central City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watched him grow up,'' said Mildred Mesner, Janet Mesner's
mother. ``I taught him in Sunday school class. He was close with
one of our sons. I know he didn't have any hatred toward Janet.''
</P>
<P>
   Randolph Reeves' parents have generally stayed in the background
in the case, unwilling to ask for support even though they are
adamantly opposed to the death penalty and Donald Reeves has worked
for national Quaker organizations.
</P>
<P>
   For 18 years, Randolph Reeves' lawyers have appealed on various
grounds, sending the case before the Nebraska Supreme Court four
times and the U.S. Supreme Court twice.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers have complained that Nebraska law gave jurors a
choice only of convicting Reeves or acquitting him of first-degree
murder, without making allowance for a lesser crime, something the
jury foreman now says he would have supported. The lawyers have
argued that Reeves' intoxication had not been taken into account at
the trial or in sentencing, and they have cited what they say were
procedural errors in the sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   The courts have supported the way the original trial was
conducted and declined to order a new sentencing hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hutchinson's latest appeal asserts that in addition to
racial discrimination, her client's equal protection rights were
violated in two other ways. One occurred in 1991 after errors were
found in Reeves' original sentence, she says, when a Nebraska
Supreme Court resentenced him to death without sending his case
back to the trial court for another hearing. She also asserts that
electrocution, Nebraska's only means of execution, is a cruel and
unusual punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Janet Mesner's parents have lobbied against the
execution of Reeves, their efforts eventually getting the support
of national Quaker organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Nebraska, we're very much a minority,'' Mrs. Mesner said.
``Seventy-five to 80 percent of the people here believe in the
death penalty and so it's been very lonely for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lamm's husband, Gus, and her daughter, Audrey, now 21,
joined the protest only recently. The two, like Ms. Lamm, are not
Quakers but oppose the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Lamm, a mental health therapist in Portland, Ore., said he had
paid no attention to the case since the conviction. He said that
although he knew Reeves had been sentenced to death, he expected
him to end up serving a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Lamm said, he received a telephone call from a
Mesner relative, who told him about the impending execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `No, no, no,''' Lamm recalled. In a few short weeks,
the Lamms have become strident advocates for Reeves, shouting at
Gov. Mike Johanns after a meeting of the state Pardons Board and
deluging his office with flowers in a gesture of protest. Audrey
Lamm has decided to leave Oregon and move to Nebraska, where she
plans to work for several months for Reeves' lawyer, Ms.
Hutchinson. The Lamms even visited Reeves in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Lamm said he saw the incident as though ``three lives had been
lost that night,'' the lives of the two women and Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Audrey, said, ``I now feel I can approach Randy
not as the daughter of his victim but as someone with whom I can
find common ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Lamms seem to feel much less enmity toward Ms.
Lamm's killer than they do toward her father, brother and sister,
who support the death penalty for Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want that man out of sight,'' said Alan Zessin, Ms.
Lamm's father, who lives in Republican City. ``It's been 18 years
that my family has had to suffer from Randolph Reeves. I'd been
looking forward to Thursday, Jan. 14, 10 a.m., for a while. I
thought he was finally going to be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Johanns and Attorney General Don Stenberg, two of the three
members of the Pardons Board, are also disappointed with the stay
of execution.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Robinson, a spokeswoman for the attorney general, said
Stenberg ``felt there was no new evidence in this case that would
contradict any of the rulings by previous courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Peterson, a spokesman for Johanns, who was elected in
November, said the governor believed ``that to keep putting it off
and putting it off is not what the will of the public is and he's
frustrated by that.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said the governor, a Republican, had not supported the
equal protection clause on the ballot in November, fearing that it
might ``open the door to frivolous legal wrestling that would clog
the court system.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Hutchinson, the lawyer, is simply grateful for any extra
chance the case can get. She said she had not even been aware that
the equal protection clause was on the ballot until she walked into
the voting booth. Then, she said, she exclaimed loud enough to be
heard by her husband in another booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was what I was looking for,'' Ms. Hutchinson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
