<HEADER>
A2332 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-EISSLER-NYT &LR;      02-19 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-EISSLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 KURT EISSLER, DIRECTOR   OF SIGMUND FREUD ARCHIVES , DIES AT 90 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SARAH BOXER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kurt Robert Eissler, the New York psychoanalyst who
founded, directed and defended the Sigmund Freud Archives and then
handpicked a successor who ended up plunging the archive into a sea
of trouble, died on Wednesday at his home in Manhattan. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1980s Eissler was little known outside psychoanalytic
circles. As Janet Malcolm described him in 1983 in The New Yorker,
``he was tall, gaunt and unmistakably European,'' he was ``an
extraordinary clinician,'' and he was the author of many ``quirky
papers.'' His work included papers on the treatment of
schizophrenics and delinquents and a paper on the debate about
vaginal orgasm.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote ``The Psychiatrist and the Dying Patient,'' (1955)
``Leonardo da Vinci: Psychoanalytic Notes on the Enigma'' (1961)
and a two-volume work, ``Goethe: A Psychoanalytic Study'' (1963).
He also wrote a number of books on Freudian history, including
``Talent and Genius,'' about Viktor Tausk, Freud's troubled student
(1971). In that book, Ms. Malcolm wrote, he defended Freud against
``the insinuation that Freud was to blame'' for his patient's
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eissler's devotion to Freud,'' she added, was ``considered a
kind of lovable nuttiness.''
</P>
<P>
   After World War II Eissler and a small group of psychoanalysts,
Heinz Hartmann, Ernst Krus, Bertram Lewin and Herman Nunberg,
decided to preserve Freud's letters and papers in a single archive.
The Library of Congress, Eissler wrote, agreed ``to accept as a
donation all documents collected by the Archives, and to make them
accessible to scholars.''
</P>
<P>
   By the 1980s Eissler, with the help of Anna Freud, had collected
thousands of tapes, letters and papers for that archive. (An
exhibition of parts of the collection was held at the Library of
Congress last year and will be at the Jewish Museum this year.)
</P>
<P>
   But his role in psychoanalytic history took a turn (though he
did not know it then) when he met Jeffrey Moussaieff Masson, a
Sanskrit scholar and psychoanalyst, at an annual meeting of the
American Psychoanalytic Society.
</P>
<P>
   This is how Masson remembered him when they met in 1974:
Eissler, the Secretary of the Archives, was ``called the pope of
orthodox analysis,'' Masson wrote in his book ``Final Analysis.''
He had ``hundreds of hours of tape recordings of conversations with
many of Freud's patients,'' and he was a confidante of Anna Freud.
Masson continued, ``If anyone represented the link with Freud and
Freud's Vienna, it was the formidable Kurt Eissler.''
</P>
<P>
   Eissler, whose wife, Ruth, died in 1988, was a formal and
secretive man. But he befriended Masson because of their mutually
intense interest in Freud. Eissler let Masson listen to his tapes
of the so-called Wolf Man, Freud's patient, and borrow valuable
Freud documents.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in 1980 Eissler decided that Masson would be his
successor at the archives. He asked Anna Freud to release the
letters between Freud and Wilhelm Fliess that had not yet been
published so that Masson could translate and edit them.
</P>
<P>
   The fatefulness of that decision became clear to Eissler in
1981, when Masson, who was projects director of the archives,
delivered a shocking paper to the Western New England
Psychoanalytic Society, in New Haven. Masson said Freud had
abandoned his ``seduction theory'' _ the idea that adult neurosis
is caused by childhood sexual abuse _ for personal rather than
scientific reasons.
</P>
<P>
   By dropping the seduction theory, Masson concluded, ``Freud
began a trend away from the real world that, it seems to me, has
come to a dead halt in the present-day sterility of psychoanalysis
throughout the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The fallout followed quickly. Eissler led the 13-member board of
the Freud Archives into a vote to remove Masson from his position
as projects director of the archives. In explanation of his action,
Eissler said: ``Would you make director of the archives someone who
writes plain nonsense?''
</P>
<P>
   Then the legal tango began. Masson sued the Freud Archives for
$13 million. Eissler sued Masson to get back his audio tapes and
Freud's letters. After Ms. Malcolm wrote an article on the affair,
she too was sued by Masson. One matter at the heart of Malcolm
trial involved a quotation in which Masson describes Eissler
begging him not to tell Anna Freud about the scandal. Eissler
attended that trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was about him,'' Gwen Davis wrote in The Nation, ``the
poignance of old Geppetto, who had carved himself a son, only to
discover, to his profound chagrin, that Pinocchio was a naughty
boy.''
</P>
<P>
   George Gross, a psychoanalyst and friend of Eissler, saw
Eissler's emotions in a slightly different light. Eissler, he said
``was disappointed that he had not found a person who understood
Freud the way he did.'' In that, he was a little like Freud. Gross
said, ``Freud was constantly disappointed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
