<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAID-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRATION AGENTS DETAIN 74 SUSPECTED ILLEGAL ALIENS IN ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JANIE MAGRUDER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHANDLER, Ariz. _ Acting on a tip, federal officials raided a
motel north of downtown Chandler on Friday and apprehended 74
suspected illegal immigrants who had spent the night in four tiny
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The raid came nine days after the city of Chandler, near
Phoenix, settled a $35 million federal lawsuit filed by Hispanics
who alleged their civil rights were violated by police during a
five-day immigration roundup in July 1997 that netted 432 illegal
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The city settled for $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Juanita Encinas, head of the Chandler Coalition for Civil and
Human Rights and a frequent critic of the city's 1997 roundup, was
relieved Friday's raid involved only the INS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immigration can do their job as long as the Chandler police
aren't there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Chandler police were not at the site, but they had
been notified of the Immigration and Naturalization Service raid,
said Hank Woodrum, the INS' assistant district director for
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen agents from the INS in Phoenix surprised the 65 men,
five women and four children, who were smuggled into the Casa
Blanca Motel at 695 N. Arizona Ave. on Thursday afternoon or
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that they likely crossed the border at Nogales or
Douglas and that most were headed to Florida, Georgia and the
Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   Woodrum said he couldn't recall a bigger roundup at one location
in one day in Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials are questioning three individuals who they
believed smuggled the illegal immigrants from the southern Mexican
states of Chiapas, Veracruz and Oaxaca.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand they were just stashed here by smugglers who
were going to move them out very soon,'' Woodrum said. ``If we had
waited until later this afternoon or Monday, they may have been
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The 74 individuals were kept in three of the 10- by 14-foot
rooms until an INS van and two buses arrived about noon on Friday.
Some were handcuffed together, walking single file to an area where
INS investigators frisked them and confiscated an assortment of
mirrors, cigarettes and plastic combs.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms were littered with emply juice cartons, soda cans and
food wrappers. One woman, who was seated with 10 other people on a
bed, appeared exhausted and distraught.
</P>
<P>
   When it was time to leave the hotel, the immigrants, some in
handcuffs, walked single file. Most were somber as they left the
rooms, but a few were smiling and joking and one broke into song.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these guys have been caught many times,'' said Tom
Homan, Woodrum's deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Their bags, blankets, backpacks and other belongings were
searched for contraband and weapons.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-hour wait, the immigrants were taken to the INS'
district office in downtown Phoenix, where they can ask for a
hearing before an immigration judge or agree to be taken back to
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1997, the INS rounded up 15 suspected illegal
immigrants at the same motel, a white-brick structure with aqua
trim and tile roofs which is among Chandler's oldest. They were
staying in three rooms with three to seven men in a room.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Patel, whose wife, Anna, owns the 24-room motel, said
Friday that he wasn't around when the undocumented workers were
dropped off. Patel, who declined to say how much the men paid for
the rooms, said patrons must have picture ID to stay, but
citizenship isn't verified.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing written on someone's forehead whether they're
legal or illegal,'' he said. ``But we don't keep track of them.
People come and go.''
</P>
<P>
   Anna Patel said she and her husband call the police when they
suspect undocumented workers are staying there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like what they are doing, but not all of Mexico is
like that, and we can't ask them for their ID,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1997, the Border Patrol and Chandler police stopped
Hispanics at various locations throughout the city, mostly
downtown, and asked for identification.
</P>
<P>
   The joint operation also affected many U.S.-born Hispanics and
legal immigrants who said police unlawfully stopped and questioned
them about their citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix policy prohibits officers from stopping people just
to check their citizenship and from arresting people when the only
violation is an infraction of federal immigration law. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
