<HEADLINE>
ANDREAS FEININGER, WHO PORTRAYED NEW YORK IN PHOTOS, DIES AT 92  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., France, Germany, Canada)   By ANDY GRUNDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andreas Feininger, a pioneering photographer known
both for his pictures for Life magazine and for his more personal
images, died on Thursday at New York University Medical Center in
Manhattan. He was 92 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   During his 60-year career Feininger photographed a wide range of
subjects, from individual portraits to pictures of skyscrapers and
seashells. But whatever his subject, he described it with a clarity
and precision that were the characteristics of his style.
</P>
<P>
   The son of the painter Lyonel Feininger, he was born on Dec. 27,
1906 in Paris. He grew up in Germany and in the 1920s attended the
Bauhaus, where his father taught and where young Lyonel worked with
Marcel Breuer and Joseph Albers.
</P>
<P>
   The Weimar-based, innovative school of art and design was one of
the first to accept photography as an equal partner of the other
visual arts, and Andreas Feininger found it so intriguing a medium
that he pursued it on his own while studying cabinetmaking and
architecture. His pictures of the time focused on the products of
the industrial age, especially automobiles, which he portrayed as
epitomes of power and speed.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving school he worked as a cabinetmaker and as an
architect in Germany, but he continued to take photographs. In 1933
he moved to Sweden, and in 1936 he decided to devote himself to
photography. In 1939 he immigrated to the United States and found
work in New York as a freelance photographer with the Black Star
Picture Agency. His clients soon included Life, and he was invited
to join the magazine's staff in 1943. From then to 1962, when he
left the magazine, he completed 346 assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his most renowned photographs in Life were his telephoto
views of the New York skyline and mid-Manhattan sidewalks, taken in
the 1940s. The compressed perspective of these views, in which
buildings and pedestrians appear caught in rush-hour gridlock, was
achieved with experimental techniques and equipment that Feininger
devised.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of photographers have reproduced the same effects, but
none with better results. Many of his richly detailed photographs,
like ``Brooklyn Bridge in the Fog'' (1948), ``Sunday at Coney
Island Beach'' (1949) and ``Traffic on Fifth Avenue'' (1950)
appeared in Life spread across two pages.
</P>
<P>
   In the pictures he made for himself, Feininger showed the same
willingness to experiment and to reform reality. He used his
repertory of technical skills to isolate natural objects _
including shells, bones and feathers _ from their surroundings,
focusing the viewer's attention on their forms with specially built
cameras. He believed that all forms in the world, natural and
man-made, partake of the same design principles and that
photography was, in his words, ``the sole language to be understood
all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   He was the author of more than 30 books, publishing the first in
Stockholm in 1936. His books included ``The Face of New York''
(1954), ``Changing America'' (1955) ``The World Through My Eyes''
(1963) and ``Forms of Nature and Life'' (1966). He also wrote an
illustrated autobiography, ``Andreas Feininger: Photographer,''
published in 1986. &UR;  &LR; In addition, he was for several years a
columnist for Modern Photography magazine, and he also contributed
to many other photography journals.
</P>
<P>
   His work was widely exhibited. His ``Anatomy of Nature'' opened
at the Museum of Natural History in New York in 1957 and traveled
to the Smithsonian Institution in Washington. He had shows at the
Oakland Museum in California and, in New York, at the Neikrug
Galleries, the New-York Historical Society and the International
Center of Photography. He was also represented in shows at the
Museum of Modern Art, the Metropolitan Museum of Art and the
International Museum of Photography at George Eastman House in
Rochester. Most recently he helped to assemble 80 of his favorite
black-and-white photographs, taken between 1928 and 1988, for a
retrospective exhibition that has been touring Europe since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Wysse; a son, Tomas, of Quebec; a
brother, Lux, of Cambridge, Mass.; three grandchildren, and a
great-grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   Feininger's philosophy of photography was characteristically
brief and straightforward. He wrote in 1982, ``I believe that the
key to good photography is interest on the part of the
photographer, not in photography but in his subject.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
