<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CLEMENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: THE RULES OF BECOMING A YANKEE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN:   Mass., Canada, Fla.)   (See also BBA-YANKS-PITCHERS)  
(DW) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Joe Torre smartly and shrewdly infiltrated Roger
Clemens' mind during his first telephone call to the newest Yankee
pitcher on Wednesday night by comparing him to Bob Gibson. From the
first moment the manager spoke with the future Hall of Famer about
a first-ballot Hall of Famer, Torre wanted to give Clemens a clear
vision of who he thought and expected the Rocket to be.
</P>
<P>
   It was not an accidental comparison. The picture that Torre
always has painted of Gibson is of an intimidating pitcher who was
also the ultimate team player. Gibson did not need any special
treatment. Simply give him a baseball and let him scare hitters
with fastballs. No nonsense. That is what the Yankees want to see
and hear from Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes after they hung up, Torre called Clemens again
as he continued to work on turning a superstar who has occasionally
been pampered into another pitcher in pinstripes. Torre asked
Clemens to change his arrival date of Sunday night with Toronto to
Saturday for the Yankees, and Clemens quickly obliged. Advantage,
Torre.
</P>
<P>
   In a methodical manner, the Yankees hope to ease Clemens into
their gentlemanly clubhouse without treating him any differently
from the other 24 players. It is an intriguing chore because
Clemens evolved into a deity with the Boston Red Sox and routinely
came late for spring training and followed his own workout regimen.
He also was treated like royalty by the Toronto Blue Jays. The
Yankees are thrilled to have Clemens, but they want to be careful
not to create a throne for him. Those do not exist in Torre's
domain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that everyone gets preferential treatment,'' Torre
said. ``That's just the way we do things here. There are certain
privileges that a David Cone might get, but the rules are the same
for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   While Torre was cautious in discussing the future treatment of
Clemens before he has even met with the 36-year-old pitcher, George
Steinbrenner was more blunt. As much as Steinbrenner complimented
Clemens, he also made it clear that there is only one king in
Yankeeland, and he signs the paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's bigger than life almost, but he has been told that he's
coming to us and that he's going to fit in with this group,''
Steinbrenner said. ``He understands it. He's a Yankee. He'll obey
the Yankee rules. He won't be, for instance, doing some of the
things they may have allowed him to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner would not specifically explain what he was
referring to, but Clemens had a separate locker at Skydome for his
four children and was allowed to play baseball with them before
games. The Yankees permit players' sons to visit the clubhouse
after the team wins, but they are not allowed in before games or
after defeats. Torre is a simple manager to play for, merely asking
players to be on time and not to embarrass him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will not get special treatment, and he'll accept that,''
Steinbrenner said. ``This is one special young man in a lot of
different ways. He'll pull his share on everything, guest
appearances, helping for charity and helping kids, and he'll help
some of our pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Torre's strengths as a manager is his ability to gauge
the temperature of the clubhouse. Torre knows when to pounce and
when to stay silent, and he handled David Wells, a much bigger
distraction than Clemens will probably ever be. That is why Torre's
call to tell Clemens he is another Gibson and a second call to
request that he arrive earlier were astute. Slowly, yet decisively,
Torre is asserting his control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll talk to him about what we do, and I'm sure he'll have
some questions,'' Torre said. ``Hopefully, I'll answer them to his
satisfaction...`
</P>
<P>
   Entering his 16th season, Clemens is thirsty for a World Series
ring and already has said that he wants ``to slide in the side
door'' on a team that had 125 victories last season. The Yankees
want him to do that. It makes sense for Clemens to be a superstar
on the mound and a subordinate in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mr. Torre will probably let him know,'' Derek Jeter
said. ``He's got great control over the team. I don't anticipate
Clemens coming in here and thinking he's bigger than the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Zimmer, the Yankees' bench coach, who was a coach when
Clemens played for Boston in 1992, said that showing certain
players special treatment can be disruptive to others. But Zimmer
vowed that Clemens would follow the rules Torre dispensed. Because
of Torre and a player-policing clubhouse, Chili Davis said Clemens
had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Yankees,'' Davis said. ``You don't come to the New
York Yankees and think, `OK, now they've got to adjust to me.' It
doesn't work that way. You got to adjust to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting Saturday, Clemens will find that out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
