<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT, 20, IN TEXAS SLAYING MAY HAVE FLED TO ISRAEL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Filed in ``a'' and ``i'' categories) 
 
By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Texas man indicted in the stabbing murder of a
Houston shop clerk is believed to have fled to Israel, which
protects its citizens from extradition.
</P>
<P>
   Dror Hiam Goldberg, 20, is believed to be a citizen of Israel
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   His case could be similar to one in Maryland involving Samuel
Sheinbein, 18, an Israeli citizen's son who fled to Israel three
days after he and a friend allegedly dismembered another teen and
burned his torso.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, defense attorneys argued before the Israeli
Supreme Court that Sheinbein, though not born in Israel, is
guaranteed full protection from extradition by Israeli law. The
case is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg's divorced parents _ his father is a
obstetrician/gynecologist and his mother an attorney in Houston _
have declined to comment. Another son, who refused to give his name
and age, said claims that his brother is in Israel are ``rumors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the family of the (slain) woman is suffering more,
but it's tarnished our name as well,'' said the brother, who added
that the media have hounded his family since the indictment became
public.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg is accused of the Nov. 27 slaying of Manuela Silverio,
54, at Wigs by Andre, a Houston shop where she had worked for 23
years. The shop's owners, Roland Ingrando, 67, and wife Roberta,
55, were also stabbed but survived.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said nothing was stolen and there appears to be no
motive for the attack, believed to have been a ``thrill-kill,'' a
murder carried out for the sheer pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Chuck Rosenthal said Goldberg's past
includes behavioral patterns reflecting the profile of a
thrill-killer. He asked the FBI to establish a profile on Goldberg
with available evidence to use in trial.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Goldberg exhibited unusual behavior associated with the
type of murder committed, Rosenthal said, ``Yes, but I can't tell
you what.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Silverio's two daughters, Yvonne Palmer, described
Goldberg ``as a monster, someone who should have never been born.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bascially, (he was) a little rich kid that had nothing to do,
except he wanted to go out on a wild spree and kill someone,''
Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   She and her sister Yvette Menendez tearfully pleaded Friday for
Goldberg's parents, Dr. Isaac Goldberg and Michele Goldberg, to
supply information that will lead authorities to his whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to know how the justice system works, we want justice
to be done,'' said Palmer, 37.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer said her worst fear came true when she learned Thursday
that Goldberg may be in Israel. She said she suspected that his
parents could afford to buy their son's freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (authorities) assured us that he was under surveillance
and would not flee, because one of our biggest concerns was that he
would flee, and he's gone,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most devastating news was finding out my mother was
murdered and then this was the next devastating news.''
</P>
<P>
   The family has distributed 1,000 leaflets in the Houston suburb
of Bellaire, where Goldberg's parents reside, asking them: ``Where
is your son? Why is your son in Israel? Who paid for his plane
ticket?''
</P>
<P>
   The family also has posted a $10,000 reward for information
leading to Goldberg's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand, and it's not fair for someone who has
struggled so much in life to give her daughters everything, give
her grandchildren everything and go to work, and somebody can come
in, a psychotic, can came in and kill her.'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   She also accused investigators of letting Goldberg slip through
their fingers, even though he was a suspect since the night of the
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators obtained a search warrant for Goldberg's Bellaire
apartment that night and questioned him about the stabbings.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, he was living in a $625-a-month, all-bills-paid,
one-bedroom apartment a few blocks from the wig shop.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, a 1997 Bellaire High School graduate, was studying
hotel management at the University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Two male acquaintances of Golberg's at Bellaire High but who
haven't seen him since said they could not think of anything bad to
say about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put a thousand people up, he'd be the last person I'd
pick'' to commit a vicious crime, said Sam Spindel, who also knew
Goldberg from a Jewish youth group.
</P>
<P>
   Spindel said he played high school football with Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   Shlomi Uziyahu, a 1996 graduate, called Goldberg ``the last
person I'd think of as violent.''
</P>
<P>
   Uziyahu said Goldberg is good-looking, smart and has wealthy
parents, leading him to wonder how he could be involved in a
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg moved out of the apartment shortly after the killing,
and his father, who had been paying the rent, paid the final month
on his son's lease in December.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal said Goldberg, believed to have dual U.S.-Israeli
citizenship and grandparents in Israel, may have fled this country
in late January.
</P>
<P>
   He said Goldberg had just returned from Tel Aviv and was issued
a visa to return to Israel after the killing by the Israeli
consulate in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   However, Modi Ephraim, Israeli vice consul in Houston, said
Goldberg was not issued a visa.
</P>
<P>
   He did confirm that Goldberg's father held an Israeli passport,
but he said he does not know if the younger Goldberg is an Israeli
citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea if he is in Israel.'' Ephraim said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Israeli law, he said, an Israeli citizen is tried in
Israel for a crime committed in another country but will not be
extradited.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, an Israeli judge ruled that U.S.-born Sheinbein,
charged with the September 1997 chainsaw murder of another teen in
Maryland, could be extradited because he had ``no other
connection'' to Israel except for visiting there occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   The judge described Sheinbein as an ``outside observer'' who was
entitled to Israeli citizenship because his father was an Israeli
citizen, but that his degree of citizenship did not merit
protection under Israeli law.
</P>
<P>
   Sheinbein's parents flew him to Tel Aviv to avoid prosecution.
He had never lived in Israel prior to becoming a murder suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Sheinbein's attorneys, who include former Israeli Justice
Minister David Libai, argue that any Israeli citizen, regardless of
their degree of citizenship, should be guaranteed protection by all
Israeli law.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Silverio's daughters fear that Goldberg, shielded by
his parents' wealth, may never return to this country to stand
trial, and they may never receive justice for their mother`s
murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very close, we're all very close, she was my best
friend, she was my life,'' Palmer said. ``She was always there for
me always. We were like the three musketeers, everywhere you saw
us, we were all three together all the time and now she's not going
to be here any more.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
