<SLUG> BC-UMASS-ADMISSIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMASS AID, ADMISSIONS TO RELY LESS ON RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wake of successful legal and political assaults on
affirmative-action policies in this state and nationally, the
University of Massachusetts at Amherst is issuing a pre-emptive
strike: It will rely less on race and ethnicity in admitting
students and awarding financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   The university announced Friday that it will begin using
household income and other non-race factors as variables in
choosing students _ a decision that the university acknowledges
will result in a decrease in its minority student population.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an adjustment in light of the changing legal
environment,'' said Joseph Marshall, assistant vice chancellor for
enrollment services. ``It is clearly a sign of the times,
nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the move will allow the university greater flexibility
and will allow it to shield itself from criticism and, perhaps,
lawsuits claiming affirmative action by race or ethnicity is a form
of ``reverse racism.''
</P>
<P>
   But diversity will pay a price.
</P>
<P>
   The minority student population is expected to drop from 19
percent to between 13 and 16 percent next year, Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   The university began rethinking its policy after a federal court
judge ruled in November that it was unconstitutional for Boston
Latin School, one of the city's three elite public high schools, to
use race as a factor in admitting students.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston School Committee decided not to appeal the case to
the Supreme Court _ knowing the conservative court's ruling could
have meant a reversal of the 1978 Supreme Court decision Bakke v.
California.
</P>
<P>
   The decision not to appeal was encouraged by the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People and the US
Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   The Bakke decision _ which allows institutions of learning to
use race and ethnicity in admitting students _ still stands, but a
growing wave of sentiment against affirmative action has dealt
blows in several states.
</P>
<P>
   In California in 1997, a referendum question, Proposition 209,
struck down affirmative action. The same happened in Washington
with Initiative 200, which passed last year.
</P>
<P>
   After a federal court struck down the affirmative action policy
of the University of Texas in 1996, that institution chose another
way to get a diverse enrollment: It granted automatic admissions to
the top 10 percent of every high school graduating class in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   University officials calculated that because high schools there
are largely segregated by race, such a policy would ensure the
admission of the best black and white students. The 10 percent rule
has helped, but officials there report that it has not achieved the
level of minority enrollment that the old policy of affirmative
action did.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said it has always been a struggle to attract minority
students, but said he is confident the university can come up with
creative ways to attract them.
</P>
<P>
   About 19 percent of the 3,800 students in the freshman class at
UMass-Amherst this year are members of minority groups, which is
about the same percentage of minorities in the graduating classes
of Massachusetts high schools, university spokesman Kay Scanlan
said.
</P>
<P>
   UMass-Amherst plans to broaden its diversity definition away
from race and ethnicity to include age, gender, family income, and
whether the applicant would be the first generation in his or her
family to attend college.
</P>
<P>
   The average family income of a UMass student is $75,000, said
Scanlan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of work to do to reach out to lower-income
families,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
