<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, FEBRUARY 20
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(ss) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-GLOBAL-ECON-II-NYT (moved on Monday, Feb. 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Feb. 15,
about the global financial crisis, included a picture caption about
Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin and his deputy, Lawrence H.
Summers, with an incorrect credit. The photographer was Robert
Grossman for The New York Times.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-FRANCE-FILM-NYT (moved on Saturday, Feb. 13)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, Feb. 13,
about the Senate's acquittal of President Clinton misattributed a
verse recited by Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia:
</P>
<P>
   I think my country sinks beneath the yoke,
</P>
<P>
   It weeps, it bleeds,
</P>
<P>
   And each new day,
</P>
<P>
   a gash is added to her wounds.
</P>
<P>
   The verse is not anonymous; it is by Shakespeare, from
``Macbeth.'' And as he wrote in ``Hamlet'':
</P>
<P>
   Give me your pardon, sir: I've done you wrong.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-ELEPHANTS-VIRUS-NYT (moved on Thursday, Feb. 18)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent yesterday about a
virus that endangers Asian elephants in captivity misstated the
given name of the director of veterinary care for Ringling Brothers
and Barnum &AMP; Bailey circus. He is Dr. William Lindsay, not Bruce.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-BANKBOSTON-BRAZIL-NYT (moved on Thursday, Feb. 18)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent yesterday about
Spanish companies' investing in Brazil misstated the ownership of
Telefonica. It is private, not state-run.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-LARMORE-OPERA-NYT (moved on Thursday, Feb. 18)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent yesterday about the
mezzo-soprano Jennifer Larmore, who appeared Thursday and last
night in Mahler's ``Lied von der Erde'' with the New York
Philharmonic, included a performance schedule that misidentified
the other work on the program, which will be repeated tonight at 8
and on Tuesday at 7:30 at Avery Fisher Hall. It is Menotti's Violin
Concerto, not Bernstein's Serenade for Violin and Orchestra.
</P>
</TEXT>
