<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SPORTING MUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's confused and annoyed edition of The Sporting Muse:
</P>
<P>
   The only thing Dennis Rodman does better than rebound is annoy
people. He is just as skilled annoying people who like him, too, as
people who don't.
</P>
<P>
   That fact may wind up being the bottom line when and if Rodman
becomes a Laker. Whatever acceptance was coming his way from Laker
players, managers, fans and media types is fading faster than a
cheap tattoo obtained from a street vendor in Venice.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman may consider himself invaluable, but a majority of
basketball people do not agree with him. Lakers owner Jerry Buss
does, but the latest twists in the will-he-or-won't-he circus has
reached the point where everyone can smell the elephants.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible Rodman will unify the Lakers' locker room without
being in it. Team Psych needs a fleet of couches, but on the issue
of Rodman, they appear unified. Wouldn't that be a turn of events?
...
</P>
<P>
   Rodman says his choices come down to the Lakers and Miami Heat.
If I had to make a list of NBA coaches incapable of handling
Rodman, my first two choices would be Del Harris and Pat Riley.
These two coaches are wound tighter than fishing line. ...
</P>
<P>
   I re-read Rodman's book, ``Bad As I Wanna Be'' -- it only took a
few minutes -- trying to find his salacious comments on Shaquille
O'Neal. But other than wondering how someone who has everything can
focus on basketball, he really didn't rip Shaq. The toughest line
was ``I don't feel anything when I watch Shaq play.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazing. That's the same reaction I have when I watch Rodman
act. ...
</P>
<P>
   Here's the real reason why Rodman is unsigned: He can't get
teams to accept Jack Haley as part of a deal. ..
</P>
<P>
   I like Kevin Malone, the Dodgers' General Manager, but someone
has to tell him to shut up. A day after the Yankees obtained Roger
Clemens and redefined the word overkill, Malone was saying the
Dodgers and Yankees are destined to meet in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Dodger opponents have enough reason to dislike the Dodgers
without Malone painting a bigger blue target on the back of their
jerseys. And a team that won 83 games last season has no right
mentioning itself with one which claimed 125 last season. ...
</P>
<P>
   I don't care if Clemens is inducted into the Hall of Fame
tomorrow. There's simply no way he improves upon a team which had a
once-in-a-lifetime season. David Wells was 18-4 last season, so how
is Clemens supposed to improve upon that?
</P>
<P>
   The Clemens deal and Malone's comments could serve baseball very
well in 1999. Because if the Yankees ($87.6 million in salaries)
and Dodgers (first $100 million man) both trip over their cleats,
it will put a chink in baseball's theory of excess. ...
</P>
<P>
   Based on the rather skimpy inventory sold in the O.J. Simpson
auction, a lot of his other memorabilia must be well hid in the
homes of family members. Players have a lot more stuff left over
from their careers than a few jerseys and awards. ...
</P>
<P>
   Any combination of one 49er win and one Cal Poly SLO loss and
Wayne Morgan's 49ers will earn a berth in the Big West tournament.
You may commence champagne popping tomorrow evening if the 49ers
beat hated Cal State Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers would prefer to finish second or third rather than
fourth in the Big West's Western Division. A fourth place finish
means a first-round game against 18-5 Eastern Division leader Boise
State, the only conference team with a win against the Pac-10 this
season (over Washington in December).
</P>
<P>
   Everyone else in the league looks the same -- average on their
best nights, if they're playing at home, the moon is full and their
opponent had a bumpy four-hour bus ride on the way to the game.
</P>
<P>
   The conference's record against name opponents doesn't project
any field of 64 shockers. It is 2-23 versus the ACC, Big Ten, Big
12, Pac-10 and SEC, and even a sickly 7-14 against the West Coast
Conference. They're 3-9 versus ranked teams, and two of those wins
were in rivalry games (New Mexico State over New Mexico, Utah State
over Utah).
</P>
<P>
   Other Big West lowlights:
</P>
<P>
   Five of Cal Poly's 10 wins came against Division I-AA teams;
Irvine has lost 12 straight, and four of its five wins came against
Cal State Stanislaus, Northern Arizona, South Oregon and 2-21 North
Texas; Santa Barbara, 9-5 and atop the West, began the season 0-8
and lost at home to North Texas Thursday; Fullerton is 2-10 and
Idaho 3-8 on the road; and Pacific scored only 38 points in a loss
last week.
</P>
<P>
   In happier Big West developments, the baseball season is
underway. ...
</P>
<P>
   News item: IOC hints that Atlanta exceeded $200 limit on gifts
to Olympic delegates. Reaction: I had no idea grits were that
expensive. ...
</P>
<P>
   The guy who paid $233,000 for O.J. Simpson's Heisman Trophy said
he bought it to impress his girlfriend. How thoughtful, and just a
few days after Valentine's Day. ``Hey, sweetie. I bought you the
trophy of that guy who allegedly slashed his wife's neck.
Impressed?''
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a Hallmark moment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
