<SLUG> BC-RETIREES-TRAVEL-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL INDUSTRY FINDS RETIREES READY FOR ADVENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 3rd graf from end of 1sttake to add first name for MARK
Campbell;in 2ndtake, subs 4th graf from end to correct spelling of
Mapintour to MAUPINTOUR) 
(ATTN: Pa., N.M., Colo., Ill., Wash.)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It isn't that Chick and Adele Lebow do not enjoy each other's
company; the Royersford, Pa., couple have been married almost 55
years. But Mrs. Lebow is an avid golfer, with a passion for playing
the courses around their Philadelphia-area home, while Lebow's
passion for skiing keeps him away at least a month almost every
year. Even at 75, he has no plans to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I leave here, I'm heading for a week at Mammoth Mountain,
Calif., then to Taos, N.M.,'' Lebow said in a recent telephone
interview after coming off the slopes in Zermatt, Switzerland. The
week before he had skied at another Swiss resort, St. Moritz, and
shortly before that at Lake Tahoe, Nev., Salt Lake City and in
British Columbia. ``It's a lot of traveling,'' he acknowledged,
``but it's what helps keep me young _ or at least keeps me feeling
young.''
</P>
<P>
   Lebow, a semiretired furniture store owner, is emblematic of the
growing number of ``mature travelers,'' as the nonprofit Travel
Industry Association terms those over 55, who have not let age curb
their desire to travel. In fact, the 70-Plus Ski Club in
Schenectady, N.Y., to which he belongs, has 14,800 members.
</P>
<P>
   Retirees always have been big travelers. What is new is their
penchant for high-adventure travel more typical of those half their
age. These days, many older people, even octogenarians, can be
found riding elephants in India, horseback riding in Costa Rica and
bungee-jumping in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   The adventure-travel industry is rushing to accommodate them.
While many tour operators still offer typical retiree fare _
lengthy bus tours of Europe and the United States _ they now also
have offerings like river rafting, hiking and mountain climbing.
</P>
<P>
   Globus &AMP; Cosmos of Littleton, Colo., the world's biggest
escorted-travel operator, has added eight tours this year, offering
more excursions and optional tours as well as river rafting in the
Rockies and diving at Australia's Great Barrier Reef. It also has
tours of two weeks or less to accommodate the work schedules of the
growing group of travelers who are not yet retired or semiretired.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Nisbet, executive director for marketing at the tour
company, said this accommodation would become more important with
each year because many baby boomers were expected to continue
working full- or part-time well beyond their normal retirement
ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proliferation of adventure travel for seniors didn't exist
10 years ago,'' said Tom Otwell, a spokesman for the American
Association of Retired People.
</P>
<P>
   But now at least a dozen adventure travel companies either
market primarily to over-50 travelers or have discovered that they
do not need to single out mature travelers because they are signing
up for adventure trips without special prompting. According to Mark
Campbell, marketing director of Mountain Travel Sobek, which
specializes in safaris, rafting trips, treks and sea kayaking
journeys, ``Our clients 60 and over have been growing steadily.
They have the money, the time and the love of travel.''
</P>
<P>
   Clement G. Motten is one of the many older citizens who have
retained their lifelong love of travel. ``I don't know how much
longer I'm going to be able to continue traveling,'' said the
82-year-old professor emeritus of Latin American history at Temple
University. He recently returned from his umpteenth trip to
Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula, where he revisited Mayan ruins.
</P>
<P>
   Although his vision has deteriorated, Motten said: ``Even if it
degenerates more, I don't think I'd give up traveling altogether.
With so many places left to visit, I'm not ready yet to settle
down.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A study for the AARP found that travelers 50 and older spent
more than $30 billion on vacation travel in 1994. Since then, by
all accounts, their numbers, expenditures and travel options have
increased sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Although estimates vary widely as to the financial impact of
adventure travel, Campbell said the industry consensus is that it
is about $8 billion a year. ``But it is the fastest-growing segment
of the travel industry,'' he added, ``growing at 8 to 10 percent a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, many older Americans are too ill or too poor to
travel. But many mature Americans, including many of the 35 million
who are 65 or older, have paid off their mortgages and their
children's tuition bills. ``They have more money to spend on travel
than any large group of adults before or since,'' said Joe
Gallagher, president of the American Society of Travel Agents.
</P>
<P>
   David Oakley Sr., 61, an auto dealer in Bartlesville, Okla.,
whose two children are long out of college, acquired his love of
travel when he sailed to Chile and Taiwan in the Navy. In the last
30 years, he and his wife, Carolyn, have made about 25 trips to
Europe. ``Travel is my sin,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley is a mere stripling next to Otto Lang of Seattle, who
during a long career with 20th Century Fox produced movies
including ``Call Northside 777.'' Now 91, Lang plans his annual ski
trip to either Sun Valley, Idaho, or Vail, Colo., later this month.
If he does not spend as much time on the ski slopes this year as in
the past, he said, it will be because ``the knees have started to
become a maintenance problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at 88, Louise Wollan of Springfield, Ill., knows that
feeling; sore knees and assorted other aches and pains make getting
out of bed quite a challenge some mornings, she said. But she likes
challenges, especially when they are combined with travel. Four
years ago, for example, on a tour with her grandson, Dennis, and
two weeks short of her 84th birthday, she bungee-jumped from a
bridge over a gorge in Queenstown, New Zealand, plunging 150 feet
and, as she described it, ``bobbing like a yo-yo.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't she scared? ``Not really,'' she said, adding that she had
also flown in hot air balloons over France, traveled in Vietnam a
year ago with a son who served there as an Army engineer, and had
visited all 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived a fairly dignified life, as my five children would
probably agree,'' she said, ``but I bungee-jumped on impulse, and I
found it exhilarating.''
</P>
<P>
   Globus &AMP; Cosmos put together a ``travel think tank'' made up of
a geography professor, a mountain climber, a European tour guide,
travel agents and tour operators from six countries. The group drew
up some 300 possible tours, which will be trimmed to about 40, then
will be made available next year.
</P>
<P>
   Maupintour, another large tour operator, started in 1951 to
cater to what its founder, Steve Kang, described as ``a small,
elite group who could afford to take long escorted tours.'' Its
current 150 tours in 50 countries and 35 states include eight
first-time ``soft adventure'' tours designed primarily for
travelers 45 to 60 but available to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Five tours include horseback riding, others hot air balloon
trips, river and white-water rafting, hiking and canoeing. ``But
they aren't Spartan,'' Kang said. ``After you've been out all day,
you still come back to a comfortable hotel and get to have a nice
meal.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Gunnar, 70, a retired engineer and semiretired free-lance
photographer in Langley, Wash., said he and his wife, Antje, had
nothing against comfort, but not at the expense of a good
adventure. The Gunnars have been to the Antarctic and the North
Pole, and in September they hiked the Inca Trail through Peru,
crossing mountain passes up to 13,000 feet, and camping at 11,000-
to 12,000-foot elevations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can still remember when I was young the many old people in
rocking chairs waiting to die,'' Gunnar said. ``Now a lot of older
people have enough money and good enough health to travel. And when
they do die, they hope it's while traveling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
