<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE IN POLICE TORTURE CASE REFUSES TO MOVE TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The judge in the case of four police officers charged
with brutalizing a Haitian immigrant in Brooklyn rejected a request
Friday to move their trial outside the New York City region.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers had asked for the change because of intensive
news coverage of the beating of Abner Louima in 1997 and the events
arising from it.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Eugene H. Nickerson of U.S. District Court in
Brooklyn, said he would reconsider the ruling if the selection
process showed that an impartial jury could not be found. Jury
selection is to begin March 29.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers had argued that the news coverage _ and similarly
abundant coverage of the recent killing of Amadou Diallo, an
unarmed West African immigrant, by police officers in the Bronx _
had so inflamed public sentiment that a fair and impartial jury for
their clients could not be found in, or close to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors from the U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn argued
in legal briefs against a change of venue, saying that the news
coverage would not ``render it virtually impossible'' to empanel an
impartial jury.
</P>
<P>
   And in any event, they said, the ``best time to determine
whether a change of venue is required'' is during jury selection,
``when the court will have an opportunity to thoroughly examine the
potential jurors for prejudice from the pretrial publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickerson not only agreed with prosecutors Friday about a change
of venue, but also granted their request to allow the jurors to
remain anonymous, withholding their identities from the defense
lawyers and prosecutors as well as from the public.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution had argued that anonymity was necessary to keep
the jurors' judgment from being tainted by outside pressures. They
said it was not unusual to have anonymous juries in controversial
cases that have racial or emotional overtones.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the defense lawyers had opposed the anonymity, saying it
would encourage jurors to think there was something to fear about
the officers and would create prejudice against them.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lawyers, Marvyn M. Kornberg, who represents Officer
Justin A. Volpe, had said he did not object to an anonymous jury
``based upon media attention,'' although he had objected to other
arguments the prosecution had offered on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Nickerson did not specify the reasons for his rulings Friday. He
announced them from the bench and said he would elaborate on paper
later.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe is charged with torturing Louima in a bathroom at the 70th
Precinct station house by thrusting a stick into his rectum,
causing major internal injuries, after Louima was arrested in a
street brawl in Flatbush. A second officer, Charles Schwarz, is
accused of holding Louima down.
</P>
<P>
   They are also accused of joining two other officers, Thomas
Bruder and Thomas Wiese, in beating Louima in a police car before
they arrived at the station house. All four officers say they have
been falsely accused.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth officer, Sgt. Michael Bellomo, is to be tried with them
on charges that he tried to cover up the beating in the police car.
He denies the accusation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
