<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2354 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MET-BENITEZ-NYT &LR;      02-19 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MET-BENITEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENITEZ LUGS HIS BAGGAGE AND MANY TALENTS TO METS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ His agent, Mike Powers, vividly remembers
the first time he set eyes on the family home of Armando Benitez _
a 15-by-15-foot two-room shack in the Dominican Republic _ in which
Benitez lived with his mother, two brothers and a sister.
Electricity and plumbing were merely a rumor. There were no windows
or doors.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Benitez was about 18, and not long removed from
working in a sugar-cane factory for a dollar a day. Carlos
Bernhardt, the scout who discovered him, remembers a lanky child
weighing about 135 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, the 26-year-old Benitez has filled out more than
his frame. With tree trunks for arms and telephone poles for legs,
the hulking right-handed pitcher _ who stands 6 feet 4 inches and
weighs nearly 240 pounds _ is now a millionaire, thanks to a right
arm that can hurl a ball at speeds approaching 100 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   It is with that tattooed right arm that the Mets _ who acquired
Benitez from the Baltimore Orioles in the off-season three-team
deal that sent Todd Hundley to the Dodgers _ are hoping they can
help turn a competitive bullpen into a formidable one.
</P>
<P>
   And it is because of that right arm that Manager Bobby Valentine
admitted Friday, on the first day pitchers and catchers reported to
camp, that Benitez is the new pitcher he is most excited about this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had those kind of numbers,'' Valentine said,
referring not only to Benitez's lively fastball, but also to his 87
strikeouts in only 681/3 innings last season. The Mets have not had
a reliever who can throw this hard since they traded Randy Myers
for John Franco.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how far he has come from his dirt-poor beginnings,
Benitez _ who recently purchased a house for his mother in one of
the most expensive districts of Santo Domingo _ still appears to be
something of a man-child in the promised land of American
professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great kid,'' said Dodgers manager Davey Johnson, who
managed Benitez with the Orioles in 1996 and 1997. ``But you have
to understand, here's a guy who is still really young in baseball
terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career, it sometimes seemed as if Benitez
threatened to quit the game nearly as often as he would finish one
off. In June 1995, as a 22-year-old rookie, Benitez temporarily
packed his bags after he drilled Tino Martinez, then with Seattle,
one pitch after surrendering a grand slam to Edgar Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   This past May, the same Tino Martinez, now with the Yankees, was
in the unlucky position of following another big home run. This
time, it was a three-run shot by Bernie Williams. Benitez fired his
next pitch, a 97-mph fastball, into Martinez's back.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez's pitch sparked a Yankee Stadium brawl, but Valentine
defended his action Friday and said that the Orioles' Cal Ripken
had mentioned to him in the off season that he was impressed that
Benitez had the courage to do what he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ripken thought it was the most manly thing he's seen a guy
do,'' said Valentine, who added, in jest, that Benitez ``should
have worked on his jab a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if Ripken was impressed, many of Benitez's Oriole
teammates were not. And Benitez was so despondent after the
incident that he went into a funk that lasted until the All-Star
Game break.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a bad guy at all,'' said Alan Mills, who was with
Benitez in the Orioles bullpen from 1994-98. ``But I think a lot of
times people misunderstand him.'' That, said Mills, might be
because of the language barrier. It also could be because Benitez's
emotions often seem to get the better of him.
</P>
<P>
   And so, while those close to Benitez speak of how he has matured
over the years, the question now is whether he can deal with the
glare of playing in New York. It was only last season that Mets
fans practically booed reliever Mel Rojas out of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mel didn't have Armando's fastball,'' said Mets General
Manager Steve Phillips. All the same, how will the emotional
Benitez react if he struggles early and faces the kind of jeers
that Rojas did?
</P>
<P>
   ``If the people boo me, that will make me more emotional, and I
will work harder to show the people that I can do it,'' Benitez
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, if Benitez does his job well, there might be problems
of a different sort. Franco has been the Mets' closer since 1990.
But it's hard not to sense that the hard-throwing Benitez, who
recorded 22 saves in 26 opportunities last season, is waiting in
the wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' was Phillips' response when asked if Benitez will take
over the closer's role should he pitch well early. ``I'm assuming
that if he does real well early, he'll be getting the ball to
Johnny, who will be closing out the games.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if Franco, who saved 38 of 46 opportunities last season
but had an 0-8 record, should struggle early? It was a question
from which Valentine quickly stepped aside. ``We can't look into
the future,'' is all he would say.
</P>
<P>
   According to Benitez, he does not want Franco's job, anyway. ``I
know I'm not the closer,'' he said. ``Franco is the closer. I just
want to help.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
