<HEADER>
A2355 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SIDE1-LADN-(SLANG     02-19 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SIDE1-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER STALKS ON THE FRINGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hold that Tiger. The Nissan Open's leaders better
adopt that motto, because golf's biggest star is lurking in the
rough and primed to pounce.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods shot a not-so-special 68 on Friday at Riviera
Country Club and sits four shots behind second-round leader Bob
Estes. Even more daunting, he would have to surpass eight other
golfers to win the tournament championship.
</P>
<P>
   But don't discount Woods.
</P>
<P>
   You only have to go back to last weekend to realize Woods is the
one name missing from the leaderboard who should not be ignored.
Not that anyone would actually ignore Woods.
</P>
<P>
   After two rounds at the Buick Invitational in San Diego, Woods
had an identical two-round total of 137. But he was in even worse
shape, nine shots off the lead. Woods then went out and shot a 62
and 65 to claim the tournament title last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Are we about to witness a repeat performance?
</P>
<P>
   ``(Four) shots back is not where I want to be; obviously I want
to be closer,'' Woods said. ``(But) I'm right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods was nothing if not consistent Friday. He had 15 pars and
three birdies, and easily could have shaved three or four more
strokes off his score with a little luck on the greens.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone following Woods might have a hard time believing he
actually shot a 68. He slammed his putter into the fringe at 13,
forcing some emergency divot replacement. He tossed his iron at his
bag on the 15th fairway after his shot landed in an undesirable
spot on the green. After narrowly missing a 25-foot putt, Woods
took his putter and stuck it in his chest, pretending to commit
hara-kiri. And after slicing a fairway wood on 17, he yelled an
expletive.
</P>
<P>
   Tough day, Tiger?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play all that great, but I scored well,'' Woods said.
``I hit five greens through nine holes. I hit a lot of good putts,
but they didn't go in.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Woods' behavior wasn't that unusual. His emotional
outbursts on the course are well known, if rarely reported. It's
usually dismissed as part of his competitive spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most ironic occurrence of the tournament is that
Woods and David Duval _ unquestionably the tour's top two players _
are tied at 3-under after 36 holes.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend could easily intensify the budding rivalry between
the two. Unless you listen to Woods, who quickly dismissed
questions about dueling with Duval.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a media thing. You guys keep asking about it,'' Woods
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's also on the minds of other top players, who are
concentrating on figuring out a way to overtake the dynamic duo.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a golfer-celebrity, (Woods) has taken it to another
level,'' Davis Love III said. ``It's going to be hard to knock
Tiger and David off the roll they've been on the last couple of
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think the difference from being the fourth- or
fifth-best guy in the world to being No.1 is not a big difference,
but it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to understand that is by looking at the
galleries. Woods' supporters dwarfed everybody else's Friday, and
they were younger and more diverse than the other crowds.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the most familiar crowd Woods has seen recently,
since this is more or less the local stop on the tour for the
former Orange County resident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels nice. I see friends and family out here,'' Woods
said. ``It brings back good memories.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
