<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2428 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MEDIA20-COX     02-19 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEDIA20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Allegation of rape by Clinton hits print
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The story has been around for years, but picked up
renewed interest on the Internet the last few weeks: Bill Clinton
was said to have raped an Arkansas woman in 1978. NBC became the
first media outlet to interview the woman, on Jan. 20, but since
has sat on the story, leading some critics in this charged
political environment to suspect pressure from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Wall Street Journal became the first mainstream
press outlet to publish an article on Juanita Broaddrick in which
she details her version.
</P>
<P>
   While stories concerning the president's sex life often have
ignited a media frenzy, the effects of the Wall Street Journal
story had yet to be determined by Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Washington reporters did not address the Broaddrick story Friday
during Clinton's first news conference since his impeachment trial
ended last week. Charles Gibson did discuss it on ABC's ``Good
Morning America,'' and it was mentioned on the Fox News Channel.
</P>
<P>
   But CNN didn't mention it, and the three network evening
newscasts also avoided the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may have fallout over the next few days and weeks, but
it's a little too early to know whether it will have impact,'' says
CNN's Jeff Greenfield. ``It's not as though this is a shocking new
thing _ it has been around a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's personal attorney, David Kendall, denied Broaddrick's
account: ``Any allegation that the president assaulted Mrs.
Broaddrick more than 20 years ago is absolutely false. Beyond that,
we're not going to comment.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart also dismissed the story,
telling reporters, ``I spend very little time reading the Wall
Street Journal editorial page. They lost me after they accused the
president of being a drug smuggler and a murderer.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters have chased the Broaddrick story since the 1992
presidential campaign, but the Van Buren, Ark., resident would not
talk with the press. Her story arose again last year when she told
independent counsel Kenneth Starr that an affidavit she signed
denying wrongdoing by Clinton was false, and that he'd assaulted
her in a Little Rock hotel room. Broaddrick said Clinton held her
down on a bed, forced intercourse and bit her lips.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's story was written by editorial page writer and TV
critic Dorothy Rabinowitz, who went to Arkansas last week to
interview Broaddrick about her frustration over NBC's not airing
the interview.
</P>
<P>
   While NBC has been knocked by some critics, spokeswoman Alex
Constantinople said Friday the Broaddrick story is ``a work in
progress. It hasn't been killed. We're still trying to nail it
down.''
</P>
<P>
   As potentially explosive as the Broaddrick story is, it appeared
on the Journal's editorial page, not its front page. The placement
led some observers to wonder whether the Journal was pulling its
own punches. But Journal Editor Robert Bartley says there is ``a
long tradition of doing our own reporting on the editorial pages,''
and that the story's placement was never discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-19-99 2308EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
