A2441 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GYM-UGA-MICHIGAN20-CO     02-19 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYM-UGA-MICHIGAN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lucky No. 7: Georgia Gym Dogs defeat Michigan
 &HT;    By Plott Brice
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ The Georgia Gym Dogs, recently resuming the top
spot in collegiate gymnastics, proved too much from top to bottom
for No. 5 Michigan on Friday night to remain undefeated for the
year.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to their seventh win of the season, the Gym Dogs had
several high spots for the year:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Gym Dogs opened the meet with their highest score on the
year in vault with a 49.5.
</P>
<P>
   _ Senior Sam Muhleman, competing in vault for the first time in
her career, hit a 9.82.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sophomore Kristy Lichey scored a career high on the bars with
a 9.8. She then moved to a career high on the beam with a 9.95
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of night for Georgia. The final totals were
Georgia 197.200 to Michigan's 196.375.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan senior Nikki Peters put the Wolverines in position to
compete with a 9.9 in vault, a 9.87 in bars and a 9.85 on floor
exercises. Junior Sarah Cain the also helped keep Michigan close
with a 9.95 in the beam and a 9.950 on floor exercises.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gym Dogs had too much and showed it by trotting out
freshmen Talya Vexler, who scored a 9.75 on the beam, and Eileen
Diaz, who hit a 9.85 on the bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome out here,'' Vexler said. ``I tried not to worry
about the points or score but just to complete my routine.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia regained the top spot last Saturday by defeating rival
Alabama in Tuscaloosa. They didn't intend to lose it at home
against Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than the floor exercises, we were probably a little
better tonight than we were against Alabama,'' said Georgia coach
Suzanne Yoculan.
</P>
<P>
   Yoculan said the Gym Dogs worked in seven new parts to their
routines _ the final adjustments of the year _ and now Georgia will
focus on refinement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are where we want to be, right now,'' Yoculan said.
``Our goal tonight was One: win the meet; two: no let down (from
Alabama) and hit the 197 and three: put in our new skills. I think
we did that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the defending national champion Gym Dogs did show a weakness
and surprisingly, it was it a usual strength area _ floor
exercises. Karin Lichey, normally a show stealer, fell apart and
scored an 8.40. Unheard of for the senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened,'' said Lichey. ``I just hope I got
it all out of me in this one meet. I did just fine in the vault and
beam. I felt comfortable. I don't know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoculan said she was not totally surprised by the Lichey let
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see it in practice and actually, Karin said this week
she felt better a month ago. But she's methodical. She works hard.
What she needs is a break and our team will have a week off on
spring brak March 6,'' Yoculan said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has now defeated the Wolverines seven consecutive
matches.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
