u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-FAIRFAX20-COX     02-19 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-FAIRFAX20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roundabout trip ends with victory in hurdles for Torian
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRFAX, Va. _ Winning the 60-meter hurdles at the Adidas D.C.
Invitational was easy for Reggie Torian. The real headache was just
getting into town.
</P>
<P>
   In a story that sounds like a flashback from the Atlanta
Olympics, a shuttle bus driver lost his way from Dulles
International Airport, and it took Torian more than five hours to
reach his hotel here. What should have been a half-hour trip
included a side trip to Baltimore, where a frustrated Torian
abandoned the bus and hailed a cab _ costing him $75.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (bus) driver is asking me for directions,'' said Torian,
able to laugh about it Friday night. ``I'm from Chicago, and I
don't know my way around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Torian, a former wide receiver at Wisconsin, is fast figuring
out the hurdles _ winning his third indoor race in a row over last
year's No. 1-ranked hurdler, Mark Crear, at the George Mason
University Fieldhouse. Torian, the defending national indoor
champion, won in 7.45 seconds to Crear's runner-up time of 7.57.
</P>
<P>
   In the final tune-up before the USA Indoor Track and Field
Championships next weekend in Atlanta, Torian and women's hurdler
Melissa Morrison were among several top medal contenders turning in
strong performances.
</P>
<P>
   _ Georgia Tech grad David Krummenacker, the defending NCAA
indoor 800 meter champ, made a late decision to step up to the mile
here and finished second to Matt Holthaus in 4 minutes, 1.07
seconds. Krummenacker ran near the back of the pack most of the
race and made his move just before the bell lap.
</P>
<P>
   His decision to change events was based on a desire to compete
in the longer distance next weekend in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a debate over whether I could get a waiver into the
mile at the championships, so I just decided to run a qualifying
time here and get it over,'' Krummenacker said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Defending indoor and outdoor national champ Mark Everett won
easily over a strong field in the 800, though he's elected not to
run at next week's championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing this since 1987, and people shouldn't be
surprised,'' he said. ``I'm not going to lose to an American. I'm
not going to lose this year, period.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Atlanta resident Tisha Waller continued her dominance in the
women's high jump, winning her third straight event on the indoor
circuit with a clearance of 6-feet-4 1/4. The defending indoor
champion made three solid, though unsuccessful attempts at a
meet-record 6-6.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inger Miller remained undefeated in the women's 60 meters this
indoor season, while Jon Drummond took the men's in his season-best
6.50 seconds, setting the stage for a race against training partner
Maurice Greene that could possibly produce a world record next
weekend in the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
