<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2454 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-REFORM-2TAKES     02-19 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-REFORM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORM PROCESS COULD CHANGE ENTIRE IOC STRUCTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For more than a century, the International Olympic Committee has
existed as an exclusive club, answering only to itself, making its
own rules, choosing its own members, operating in an insular
climate that its critics and supporters alike admit lacked openness
and accountability.
</P>
<P>
   But now that a fifth of its members has been implicated in the
Salt Lake City scandal, and with drug scandals further eroding
confidence in the integrity of many international sporting events,
the Olympic committee is facing tremendous pressure, from within as
well as without, to reform itself. Having successfully turned the
Olympics into a lucrative business marketed on the idea of sports
as a kind of universal good, there is an urgency to limit the
damage and recover the luster and earning power the Olympics has
come to take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   There is, though, no shortage of skeptics who wonder whether the
IOC, because of its diverse makeup and tradition of unchecked
autonomy, is capable of significantly altering itself and its ways.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, for instance, in its latest attempt to set
serious drug policies, the committee failed badly, proving unable
to gain uniform support among international sports federations for
applying penalties to athletes who use performance-enhancing
substances. In that episode, during which government and sports
officials from round the world castigated the leadership of the
IOC, even Juan Antonio Samaranch, the committee's president, was
rebuffed in his attempt to head an agency that would oversee
worldwide anti-doping efforts.
</P>
<P>
   And so on March 17 and 18, the dates of the IOC's next full
meeting, the Olympic movement may face yet one more watershed
moment. The committee will attempt to ratify the expulsion of at
least five members for their roles in the Salt Lake City scandal,
and perhaps many more. The committee will also seek to reform the
process by which cities bid for the Winter and Summer Games. Such
steps, though, may be only the beginning of a process that could
eventually change the entire structure of an organization entrusted
with organizing what it likes to portray as the world's purist form
of sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is going to be reform throughout,'' said Michael Payne,
the IOC's marketing director. ``I'm convinced the IOC is going to
come out a lot stronger. It may be a very different organization
coming into the new millennium. It's going to be a painful year.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no questioning the stakes involved in the March meeting
in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public, sports people and the corporate sector are waiting
to see if the IOC is serious about cleaning its house,'' said Tomas
Sithole, IOCan Olympic committee member from Zimbabwe. ``If they
see the IOC is serious, they will continue to support us. If not,
there is going to be serious trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting last week in New York with Payne and Richard Pound,
an Olympic committee IOC vice president from Montreal who headed
the investigation of the Salt Lake City scandal, corporate sponsors
were firm in their demands for reform and accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for thorough reform at the highest levels,
expulsion of members, important changes in the bidding process and
controls, specifically financial disclosure consistent with any
organization that is responsible for billions of dollars in
revenue,'' said Debra Gottheimer, a spokeswoman for IBM, an Olympic
sponsor. ``We think they understand what the concerns are.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With reform appearing inevitable, there has been considerable
speculation in recent weeks about what the dimensions of that
change might be, and if the ouster or resignation of Samaranch was
a possibility. But every call for Samaranch's removal has been
balanced by a worry about whether the organization could withstand
such a degree of upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch's great strength, his critics even concede, has been
building consensus among the more than 100 delegates who make up
the committee. Samaranch may be the only one who can force through
real reform, IOC Olympic committee officials believe. If he
resigned now, vicious infighting could follow among those jockeying
to be his replacement, and the winner would then need time to build
his or her own base of support.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had to have a presidential election now, it would be
suicidal,'' Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch has insisted he will finish his term, which expires in
2001. But senior IOC officials believe that he may leave earlier.
Samaranch wants his legacy to include reform and not be dominated
by the smell of scandal. He has proposed, on an experimental basis,
not allowing IOC members to visit bid cities, and restricting the
voting to a handful of members on which cities play host to the
Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once all that is in place and there is relative calm,'' Pound
said, ``my guess is that he would want to sit back and say: `Is
this the best time for me to think about leaving? Should I stay for
another year or to the end of my term?' I think the jury is out on
what he might do and which is a better alternative for the IOC''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Samaranch's plan for limiting the number of
international committee delegates who can vote on which cities play
host to the Games has run into a roadblock. Mario Pescante, a
member from Italy, complained that this restriction amounted to an
admission that none of the IOC members could be trusted. A
compromise would have a small electoral college narrow the field to
two candidate cities the day before the vote, or the day of the
vote, and would allow the entire membership to select the winning
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever we do has to be fireproof,'' said Craig Reedie, an
Olympic committee IOC member from the United Kingdom. ``If this
method is fireproof, I can live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Any real reform cannot take place unless the IOC assembly
ratifies a decision by its executive board to expel five members
who were ousted in January for their part in the Salt Lake City
scandal. Several others have resigned, 3 remain under investigation
and 10 more were implicated in a report issued last week by a Salt
Lake City ethics panel. Some of the ousted members, including
Jean-Claude Ganga, the delegate from the Congo Republic who has
been accused of receiving more than $250,000 in payments from the
Salt Lake City bid committee, have said they will not go quietly.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Samaranch has done a good job, but now he wants to sacrifice
his friends,'' Ganga said. ``This is dangerous for him. It is war
now.''
</P>
<P>
   If the expulsions are not ratified by the full IOC assembly,
Pound and James Easton of the United States have said that they
would consider resigning as delegates. Already, one member, Crown
Prince Willem-Alexander, heir to the throne of the Netherlands, has
suspended his membership pending the outcome of the March meeting.
He has not been linked to the scandal in any way, but the Dutch
royal family has expressed concern that his reputation may be
sullied by being associated with the Olympic committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who don't need this for a feeling of self-worth are
the ones you need most,'' Pound said.
</P>
<P>
   John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance, a corporate sponsor that has
halted negotiations with NBC for $20 million in Olympic
advertising, has expressed concern about the aggressiveness of the
IOC's investigation into other cities bidding on the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not doing what any corporation with that kind of
revenue and reputation at stake would do,'' said David
D'Alessandro, the president of John Hancock, noting that the
investigation amounted to sending out letters asking for
incriminating information. ``They're too busy trying to cover their
tracks, too busy trying to make it all go away. They're trying to
give everybody a sleeping pill in hopes that they'll wake up and
forget about it.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of additional reform proposals have been made: restrict
delegates to term limits instead of an age limit of 80 years old;
elect delegates by national Olympic committees and international
sports federations rather than by Samaranch's appointment, and
forbid IOC members from also serving as presidents of their
national Olympic committees. Officials who investigated the Salt
Lake City corruption said cities seeking the Games should not be
allowed to give support to national Olympic committees during the
bid process, which was the guise used for a number of payments to
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know you are there 8 or 12 years, it's easier to follow
the principles of the Olympic charter,'' said Gerhard Heiberg, an
IOC Olympic committee delegate from Norway who favors term limits.
``If you sit there 30 years, you may be tempted to benefit a little
too much from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reedie, the IOC member from the United Kingdom, supported
wide-ranging alterations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole structure and governance will have to be
looked at,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One intriguing question raised by the scandal is whether the IOC
is necessary at all to put on a worldwide sporting event. Soccer's
world governing body, FIFA, puts on its World Cup every four years
and dwarfs the Olympics in terms of television audience for the
monthlong event. Figure skating, the most popular Winter Olympic
sport, holds an independent world championship every year. Track
and field, the most important summer Olympic sport, holds a
separate world championship every two years.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1986, Ted Turner has been organizing the Goodwill Games,
an international event held every four years that rivals the
Olympics in terms of competition, if not drama and name
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system seems very fragile at this point,'' said Harvey
Schiller, the president of Turner Sports and a past executive
director of the United States Olympic Committee. ``If the IOC
doesn't make the right corrections, those federations that can
sustain themselves may try to mimic what FIFA does with the World
Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   However, for women's sports, where there are few professional
leagues, and in many men's sports outside of soccer, the Olympics
remain the pinnacle of athletic achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you pass an Olympic medal around a classroom, it creates
a drama that's not there for a medal from the world
championships,'' said Lynn Jennings of the United States, who won a
bronze medal in the women's 10,000-meter run at the 1992 Summer
Olympics in Barcelona, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Shorter, the 1972 Olympic marathon champion, said that a
confluence of events from the Tour de France drug scandal to the
Salt Lake City corruption scandal has awakened an urgent need for
reform, leaving him more optimistic than he has felt in two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IOC used to have total discretion to do what it wanted,''
Shorter said. ``Now they don't have total discretion anymore.
They're going to have to adjust to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Inger Miller, who won a gold medal for the United States in the
women's 4x100-meter relay at the 1996 Summer Olympics in Atlanta,
said she believed that fans made a clear distinction between
Olympic scandal and Olympic athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the general public really even knows or cares''
about the Salt Lake City scandal, Miller said. ``They want to see
the athletes do what they do. I don't think it will affect
viewers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
