<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR URGES BLACK CLERGY TO TRUST INQUIRY ON TROOPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI  
(DW) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Gov. Christine Todd Whitman and top state
prosecutors met with leaders of an influential council of black
minister's Friday to assure them that the attorney general's office
will throughly investigate charges that the state police unfairly
single out black motorists on the state's highways.
</P>
<P>
   But after an hourlong, closed-door discussion with Attorney
General Peter G. Verniero, the Rev. Reginald T. Jackson, chairman
of the Black Ministers Council, said he would be ``astounded'' if
the state's review does not confirm that state troopers routinely
pull over motorists based solely on their race. Jackson also
renewed his call for the dismissal of the superintendent of the
state police, Col. Carl A. Williams, and said he believed it is
imperative that the U.S. Justice Department continue its own
investigation, which has been under way since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will stand in Macy's window at high noon and say that the
Justice Department needs to investigate the New Jersey State
Police,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The state police have long been accused of using racial
profiling in deciding whether certain motorists should be stopped.
But the issue became a source of increased controversy last April,
after troopers shot 11 times at four unarmed minority men who had
been pulled over on their way to a basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Whitman said Friday that she went to the meeting with the
black ministers to demonstrate that she will not tolerate
profiling. Some civil rights leaders have said they do not trust
Verniero's office to carry out a thorough inquiry, because the
attorney general is defending the state police in an appeal of a
1996 court ruling that found evidence of racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whitman said that the state investigation will be led by
Paul Zoubek, a first assistant attorney general who as a Justice
Department official led several police corruption inquiries. She
said she is confident the state's own assessment of the force will
be thorough and unflinching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day that government can't police itself will be a scary
day in this state,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department announced this week that its civil rights
division has been conducting a ``pattern and practice''
investigation of the racial complaints against troopers since 1996.
If the civil rights division finds evidence of discriminatory
practices, they can file a federal lawsuit and ask a judge to order
the force to reform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
