<HEADLINE>
NISSAN NOTES: KELLY GETS SOME REPAYMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jerry Kelly, the former high school hockey star
who says he loves Riviera even though he has never made the cut
there, got a little hug back from the Pacific Palisades course on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's 7-iron tee shot to the 156-yard par-3 sixth hole was
rewarded with a hole-in-one and, ultimately, his first Nissan Open
paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   He got to 3-under par for the day with the ace, parred out to
complete a second-round 69 and wound up 5-under 136 at the halfway
mark. It was enough to make his first Nissan cut by five strokes.
Only cut survivors are paid in PGA Tour events.
</P>
<P>
   __ Gone but not forgotten: This week's Nissan Open is without
two of its most-familiar faces. Pulitzer Prize-winning columnist
Jim Murray, who died at 78 in August, was remembered with a name
card and empty chair at a front-row media-room table.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Everett also was remembered. The man who had hand-penned the
media-room scoreboard as long as any tournament official could
remember died in December at 92.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would have been his 50th year,'' said PGA Tour director
of information Dave Lancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always used to come up and watch him,'' Bob Lowe said of the
Nissan's star calligrapher. Lowe replaced Everett on the scoreboard
this week.
</P>
<P>
   __ Home sweet home: Former Cal State Northridge golfer Bob Burns
is just six shots off the lead, but the best part of his Nissan
Open could be that he gets to stay with his parents in Granada
Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Burns, who has lived in Knoxville, Tenn., since 1994, has been
especially grateful that he could stay at home because he has
battled a cold since Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be home and have all the amenities,'' Burns said.
``My parents have the medicine cabinet stocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Another benefit is Burns has plenty of friends and family
offering support.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a bunch of people following me. They're rooting me
on,'' Burns said. ``It's not that distracting. It'd be terrible not
to have anybody following you.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Attendance update: After two days, the crowds at Riviera
Country Club are besting last year's numbers at Valencia Country
Club. Friday's attendance of 24,319 outdrew the 19,383 who showed
up for the second round at Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 37,971 spectators the first two days at Riviera.
There were 30,863 at Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   __ Turning it around: Brad Fabel made the biggest turnaround in
the second round, improving from a tie for 103rd to a tie for
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   After shooting a 2-over 73 on Thursday, Fabel bounced back with
a 4-under 64 on Friday. He is four strokes behind the leader at
137.
</P>
<P>
   He credits his round to going back to a simple approach after
trying to work on his mechanics the day before. He also pointed to
improvement on the back nine, where he went from a 40 on Thursday
to a 31 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday I hit the ball terrible,'' he said. ``I haven't been
playing, period. I've been out there, but I wasn't playing.''
</P>
<P>
   __ By the numbers: Nick Price was the last player in the
tournament to record a bogey, going 24 holes without one before
bogeying No. 7 on Friday. . . . Tiger Woods made the cut _ the 23rd
straight event in which he's done that. It's the longest streak on
the PGA Tour. Fred Funk ended his streak of making the cut at 18.
He shot a second-round 75 to finish at 145. . . . The 77 players to
advance to today's third round are the most to make the 72-hole cut
on the tour this season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Second-round leader: A Texan at the top of the leaderboard
might not be surprising, but it is when he's Bob Estes.
</P>
<P>
   Estes put together a solid 67 on Friday for a two-round total of
133 to break out to a one-stroke lead at the Nissan Open.
</P>
<P>
   While fellow Texan David Duval fell out of the lead, Estes
emerged as the tournament's leader at the halfway point with his
four-birdie, no-bogey round.
</P>
<P>
   Don't think for a second that Estes is comfortable at the top,
considering there's a pack of four golfers lurking at 134, three at
136 and Duval and Tiger Woods, among others, at 137.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could be leading after 54 holes and it wouldn't matter
because we all still remember what David did,'' said Estes in
reference to Duval's final-round 59 to win the Bob Hop Chrysler
Classic last month.
</P>
<P>
   __ Advantage Woods: While David Duval lost his grip on the lead
when he shot ``only'' par 71 on Friday, Tiger Woods recorded a 68
to create a tie between the world's No. 1 and No. 2 golfers at 137.
</P>
<P>
   While their names are linked on the leaderboard, the two won't
be linked on the links. Woods and Duval are not paired together for
today's round. Oh well, maybe on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hacker of the day: On Friday the sun came out, the scores
went down and the golf was good.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Ed Fiori.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-five golfers posted scores of par or better, although
Fiori wasn't one of them. He shot 81 _ the only golfer in the
tournament to go over 80 in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   In all fairness, we feel it necessary to mention that Fiori is
playing the 1999 season on special medical extension because of
back problems that limited him to three tournaments last year. It
is also necessary to mention that Fiori's nickname is ``The Grip''
because of his unusually strong grip on the club.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE OF THE DAY: ``It used to be the (high school) golf team
was the guys who weren't going to make the football team. Now,
every kid wants to play golf. If I came out now, I probably
wouldn't make it. __ Davis Love II.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
