<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-19 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2461 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GUN-PERMIT-SUIT-85     02-19 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GUN-PERMIT-SUIT-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT SEEKS DAMAGES FROM COUNTY FOR FAILING TO REVOKE GUN PERMIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Imagine, for a second, that the police know about a
licensed gun owner who has been cited for belligerent behavior.
Then one day, his pistol is used by a relative in a murder.
</P>
<P>
   The gun owner, in all likelihood, is going to be sued. But
should the local government be liable, too, because it knew about
his past but failed to revoke his permit?
</P>
<P>
   This is the crux of a lawsuit now moving through U.S. District
Court in Manhattan, involving a murder in the Westchester County
village of Dobbs Ferry in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The killer, an off-duty New York City police officer, used a gun
licensed to his father, who had been the subject of at least two
dozen complaints to the local police by people who said he had
harassed and threatened them. And now, the victim's family is suing
the village for failing to take preventive action.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit comes at a time when many people are looking for
ways to expand liability for the use of guns beyond the individuals
who fire them and toward those who make them, distribute them and
regulate their use.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, a Brooklyn jury found nine gun manufacturers
liable for shootings with illegally obtained handguns, saying the
companies' had negligent marketing and distribution practices.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dobbs Ferry case also presents a novel argument that
some lawyers say could set a precedent for determining where
government responsibility becomes government liability _ not just
with guns, but with all sorts of licensing procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a fairly bold theory, and a difficult, but
important case,'' said David Leebron, the dean of Columbia Law
School and a specialist in the field of tort litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Although courts have generally been loath to hold governments
responsible for the indirect consequences of their policies,
Leebron said, ``the lesson of the tobacco litigation is that even
claims that don't look legally sound can, for a variety of reasons,
prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   And regardless of the outcome of this case, he said, it seems
likely that more people will ``use the tort system as a way to
address the problems raised by guns.''
</P>
<P>
   The law is quite clear about how people qualify for a gun
permit. Before 1989 in Westchester, for instance, it was the duty
of the local police department to investigate an applicant's
background. Since 1989, the county has taken over the checks,
presenting its findings to a county judge, who makes the final
decision.
</P>
<P>
   The law is not as clear, though, about revoking a permit; the
most common circumstances prompting revocation, the law says,
include the improper use of a firearm or an arrest. In Westchester,
perhaps fewer than 100 gun permits are revoked a year, said Alan D.
Scheinkman, the Westchester County attorney.
</P>
<P>
   There is no methodical review of gun permits; the county is not
even sure how many valid gun permits exist. But in general, the
County attorney's office is supposed to collect information about
arrests or complaints pertinent to permit holders, and in the more
serious cases, ask a county judge to revoke the permit.
</P>
<P>
   In Dobbs Ferry, the gun owner involved in the lawsuit, Richard
B. DiGuglielmo, received his gun permit in 1972. In 1986, he was
arrested on third-degree assault and harassment charges after
scuffling with someone who had parked in front of his business, the
Venice Deli, without patronizing the store. The case was eventually
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   But over the years, more than two dozen other people filed
police complaints against DiGuglielmo, saying he had threatened,
harassed or assaulted them for parking in the wrong spot. Countless
others also tangled with DiGuglielmo over the parking spot,
neighbors said.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1996, Charles Campbell, 37, a sanitation worker and
youth counselor, was fatally shot by DiGuglielmo's son, Richard D.
DiGuglielmo, in a fight over a parking spot outside the store.
</P>
<P>
   One year later, the son was convicted of murder and sentenced to
20 years to life in prison; his father was acquitted of assault
charges in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, Westchester officials revoked the father's permit
for all six of his guns, saying he had displayed ``a pattern of
aggressive behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   But Campbell's brother, Bill, said that action came too late.
``They should have done more beforehand,'' said Campbell, an
insurance broker who is now the guardian of his brother's only son.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Campbell family's lawyers filed a federal civil
rights lawsuit against the DiGuglielmos and, among others, New York
City and its Police Department, saying the city had trained the
younger DiGuglielmo to shoot to kill. Then, after unearthing more
information about his father's record, the lawyers filed an amended
complaint in December 1998 against the village.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not suggesting that every time a city licenses a gun
permit, whenever a gun is misused, the city is liable,'' said
Randolph Scott-McLaughlin, a lawyer for the Campbell family and a
professor of law at Pace University School of Law. ``But when there
is a known danger, and the city is indifferent to that danger, then
the city should be liable.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Charles G. Fiore, a lawyer for the DiGuglielmos, said that he
did not want to comment on current litigation. But government
lawyers argued that the Campbells' case, while intellectually
intriguing, rested on shaky legal theory.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the local authorities appeared to have followed
the proper procedures, so it was uncertain whether they even had a
duty to take preventive action, said Kevin J. Plunkett, whose firm,
Plunkett &AMP; Jaffe, represents the village.
</P>
<P>
   Scheinkman, the lawyer for the county, which was a defendant in
the original lawsuit in 1997, also expressed concern that the
lawsuit, if successful, could spur much litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about potential liability way beyond any
reasonable bounds, and saddling an agency with a task that it
couldn't manage,'' said Scheinkman, who has filed a motion that
would remove the county as a defendant from the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, municipalities have recently been on the defensive,
fending off lawsuits seeking to hold government bodies responsible
for the actions of individuals, said Juan Otero of the National
League of Cities.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankel Rosenbaum case is one example. In that case, which
New York City settled out of court for $1.1 million, the city was
sued for failing to protect Hasidic residents from a rioting crowd
in Crown Heights, thereby contributing to Rosenbaum's death.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, municipalities have been wary of potential
lawsuits stemming from the year 2000 computer problem, Otero said.
</P>
<P>
   The courts have generally been reluctant to hold government
bodies liable for anything other than deliberate, active
wrongdoing, said Karen M. Blum, an expert on federal civil rights
law and a professor of law at Suffolk Law School in Boston. So the
odds are, the plaintiffs in the Dobbs Ferry case may do well to
force legislative, not legal, action on the issue of gun permits,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But given the unexpected outcomes of recent cases, Campbell's
lawyers like their chances. ``We are certainly charting new waters
here,'' Scott-McLaughlin said. ``But if the tobacco companies can
be held accountable, and the gun manufacturers can be brought
before the bar of justice, then I don't see why we can let cities
off when they put guns in the hands of a known violent person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
