<SLUG> BC-BOAT-AROUND-ALONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUND-THE-WORLD SAILORS FEELING VULNERABLE IN TREACHEROUS WATERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is as if the nine solo yachtsmen still competing
in the Around Alone race are sailing on broken glass these days.
Jolted by the accident that took the boat, and almost the life, of
Isabelle Autisser on Monday, those still competing in the
round-the-world competition are feeling a touch more vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an area full of ghosts, and I will be happy to get out
of it,'' Jean-Pierre Mouligne, a French sailor said in an interview
by e-mail Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Add to his concern a dose of trepidation over a storm that began
to blast the 40- to 60-foot sailboats Friday. The gale, predicted
for a week, was sending 45-knot winds across the 2,500-mile stretch
of South Pacific Ocean where the Around Alone sailboats were
scattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am in a full gale,'' Mouligne said, ``with triple-reefed
mainsail and a little bit of jib. I am going 14 knots, and it's
downright scary.''
</P>
<P>
   His reference about ghosts comes because two years ago, Gerry
Roufs, a Canadian solo sailor in a French nonstop competition,
disappeared during a storm in that same area of southern ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isabelle's accident, of course, is making me even more
careful,'' Mouligne said. ``I think that our boats are totally
safe, but in strong reaching conditions, they are closer to sailing
a multihull than a monohull.'' Mouligne was referring to the
typically wilder ride that a sailor on a multihull experiences.
</P>
<P>
   It took a night of searching before Giovanni Soldini, aboard
Fila, found Autissier holed up in her overturned yacht. Together
now, on one boat, they were about 500 miles astern of Marc
Thiercelin of France, the leader Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Thiercelin was close to Cape Horn at the tip of South America.
Once the boats round it, they head north out of the treacherous
Screaming Fifties into the relative calm up to Punta del Este,
Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   Autissier is forbidden by race rules to help Soldini, who is
still a bona fide competitor. ``You sleep better, you have someone
to talk to,'' Soldini told race officials Friday. ``But after
rescuing Isabelle, I figure I've pretty much won this race.
Anything else ultimately isn't very important.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
