<SLUG> BC-BOX-TEXAS-BOXER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS BOXER GETS HIS FIGHTING CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE SANCHEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Six months ago, Paulie Ayala fought for a
world bantamweight title in front of 18,000 fans in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, the Fort Worth boxer will be thousands of miles and
thousands of fans removed from the highlight of his young career
when he takes on David Gutierrez-Vazquez (13-4-2, eight knockouts)
in the main event of a seven-bout card at John Justin Arena.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Ayala (26-1, 12 KOs) finds himself on the long
road back to another title shot. But since losing a six-round
technical decision to World Boxing Council champion Joichiro
Tatsuyoshi in August in Yokohama, Ayala is convinced he can get to
the top no matter how many thousands of miles he must endure in and
out of the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm good to go, just waiting to get my title fight,'' he said.
``I shook \Rthe loss\S off easy. ... But now, I don't see anyone
beating me.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss against Tatsuyoshi was bad enough for Ayala (26-1, 12
KOs), but things got worse.
</P>
<P>
   Tatsuyoshi lost his title in his next defense to Thai challenger
Veeraphol Sahaprom. Sahaprom became the WBC champion, and Ayala
consequently dropped to being the WBC's fourth-ranked bantamweight,
behind Tatsuyoshi.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks of his defeat, Ayala, 28, returned to the gym to
train. He kept busy by easily disposing of Ivan Salazar with a
fourth-round knockout in his most recent bout, Nov. 14 in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala has been sparring with San Antonio's John Michael Johnson,
rated the No. 1 super bantamweight by the World Boxing Association
and the WBC's No. 6 bantamweight, to sharpen his skills in case he
gets a title shot sooner than expected.
</P>
<P>
   And for now, he waits patiently.
</P>
<P>
   Again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing my job,'' Ayala said. ``It depends on my promoters
to get me an opportunity to fight for a world title. It's not me.''
</P>
<P>
   The job belongs to Top Rank Inc., his promotional team, and his
management team at Boxing Management Inc. They say the wheels are
now in motion, but the time frame for his next title shot is vague
and could not be narrowed down to anything more specific than
``sometime within the year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at all of the different champions, but it has
to be the right place at the right time,'' said Todd Deboef of Top
Rank. ``Of course, the loss to Tatusoyshi was not ideal, but we
have to sweep that under the rug. We have to find the right person
and make it happen. It is my job to deliver and give him the
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala and his camp are counting on it, but they're not waiting
for a high-profile opponent to fall in their lap. BMI is pursuing a
match with WBA champion Johnny Tapia. Tapia is scheduled for a bout
in April, but no opponent has been named.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put our name in the hat. We want that fight badly,'' said
Rick Yuill of BMI. ``Paulie is at the point where he needs a
defining fight in front of a large audience, and Tapia would do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another option for Ayala is challenging the WBC's top-rated
bantamweight, Adan Vargas, in a bout for the opportunity to fight
the champion. Such a bout might be an unnecessary gamble for
Vargas, but could happen if the right purse is offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paulie's camp will not show any reluctance to fight anyone,''
Fort Worth matchmaker Wayne Harrison said. ``Challenging Vargas is
a very makable fight, but somebody will have to step up with some
major money for him to take that risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Mendez, Ayala's co-trainer, said they will do whatever it
takes for another title shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll fight anybody,'' Mendez said. ``We'll even fight twice a
night if we have to if that's what it takes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
