<HEADLINE>
WETTELAND WORKS OUT AT FULL STRENGTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Manager Johnny Oates described closer
John Wetteland ``very impressive'' after the Rangers' first
scheduled workout for pitchers and catchers yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland underwent arthroscopic surgery Oct. 27 to remove a
bone spur and one loose body from his right elbow, but the
32-year-old right-hander participated in every drill without
difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went through the full workout, but that doesn't surprise
me,'' Oates said. ``He's not the type of guy who babies anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will monitor their relief ace closely this spring
and may reduce his work to ensure his availability for Opening Day.
Oates gave Wetteland the option to reduce his work yesterday, but
the pitcher declined the offer despite an undershirt drenched from
top to bottom with sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just shows you how much he puts into it,'' Oates said.
RODRIGUEZ ABSENT
</P>
<P>
   Oates appeared annoyed that catcher Ivan Rodriguez was absent
from yesterday's first scheduled workout for pitchers and catchers.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez remains in Puerto Rico, and the Rangers do not know
when their seven-time All-Star will report.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be here,'' Oates said, ``and I would hope that he'll be
here soon.''
</P>
<P>
   So does ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez will be featured with ESPN anchor Dan Patrick for a TV
commercial supporting ``ESPN Magazine.'' ESPN plans to begin
filming next weekend.
SMOKELESS ENVIRONMENT
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will not provide smokeless tobacco products for
their players or opponents this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will not prevent their players from possessing or
using the products, but clubhouse attendants will not be permitted
to purchase the products, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be a party to them killing themselves,'' said Zack
Minasian, the Rangers' clubhouse and equipment manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Milwaukee Brewers and Chicago White Sox follow similar
guidelines.
EARLY BIRD
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter Lee Stevens participated in the workout even
though infielders and outfielders need not report until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never too early to start, and I need the work,'' said
Stevens, who reported to camp early the previous two seasons as
well. ``Plus, I couldn't sit at home while they're here. I would
feel guilty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
