<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GUNS-FAMILY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK COLUMN: ANOTHER GUN, ANOTHER DAY AT A CEMETERY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This has been some week for the Valentin family. It
began with Valentine's Day, which always has extra meaning for this
Bronx clan, whose very name is a reminder of the affection that
they share every day. It ends Saturday with the 22nd birthday of
their youngest son, Derek, a young man who would probably be
telling them about his plans for graduating from college and
starting a career.
</P>
<P>
   But he will not.
</P>
<P>
   Derek died on Aug. 8, 1994, killed with his friend Keith Simmons
during a fight over a girl. They had arrived on the corner of
Allerton and Barnes avenues full of adrenaline, but their hands
empty.
</P>
<P>
   One of their teen-age rivals held a $50 gun. Another shouted,
``Buck 'em! Buck 'em!'' The last words Derek heard became the
prologue for the dark mood that claimed his family.
</P>
<P>
   February is now a cruel month for Derek's parents, Al and
Nellie. The holidays they used to celebrate at home now include a
trip to Derek's grave.
</P>
<P>
   Making it more difficult this year, Ash Wednesday fell smack in
the middle of this week. That day, the Valentins went to church,
where a Roman Catholic priest smudged an ash cross on their
foreheads while intoning the words, ``Remember, man, you are dust
and to dust you will return.''
</P>
<P>
   They need no reminder of this, since so much of their old life
vanished when Derek died. Their active social life with friends and
family gave way to support group meetings with parents of other
murdered children.
</P>
<P>
   Caught up in a relentless, and successful, quest to see his
son's killer convicted, Al closed his real estate business for two
years so he could attend every single court date. He ran through
his savings and into serious debt to pay for lawyers and private
investigators for the case, counselors for his family and college
tuition for his son Michael and his daughter Vanessa (both of whom
had to postpone graduation by at least a year).
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody thinks about what happens to us and how difficult it is
to get up and survive,'' said Nellie, who is helping Al reopen his
real estate business. ``It took my husband three years to get back
on his feet. We suffered dearly. Starting all over affected us
financially, emotionally and socially.''
</P>
<P>
   The Valentins talked about their predicament not because they
were looking for money or sympathy. They had a chance to join the
relatives of murder victims in a lawsuit against gun manufacturers,
but they were so busy with the trial of their son's killer that
they missed the filing deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The gun lawsuit was decided last week in U.S. Court in Brooklyn,
where several manufacturers were held liable, although they were
ordered to pay damages only to the family of the lone surviving
victim. That is why Valentin is talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gun companies made money on the bullet and the gun,'' he
said. ``Somebody else lost a son. They go through hardship paying
for funerals. Families are destroyed. And somebody tells them
that's not worth anything? I boiled. When you love somebody so
much, it's not the money, it's the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife don't think anyone can put a dollar value on a
human life. But they agree with the lawsuit's contention that the
gun companies have profited by oversupplying guns to states with
weak laws. Those weapons, in turn, are used in crimes in cities
with tougher gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies know it, but they don't care,'' Nellie said.
``But it shouldn't be just about making money. This is about
accountability. Somebody has to be accountable when these guns get
into young hands. We're not at war. Why do we need so many guns?''
</P>
<P>
   The only accounting the Valentins will get this year is their
own, as they tally the toll taken by their lingering loss.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Al's business is slowly recovering, even though he had
to give up prime office space on Castle Hill Avenue after his eight
salesmen left when business dried up. Their daughter Vanessa
graduated from college, while their son Michael will get his degree
in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Al and Nellie will join some relatives Saturday and go over to
St. Raymond's Cemetery, where red and silver Valentine's Day
balloons still decorate Derek's headstone. They'll talk to him and
pray for him. Each word brings them closer to Derek and the end of
this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is painful to go there, but since I have no other choice, I
go,'' Nellie said. ``Instead of sending him birthday cards and
talking about his college graduation I have to go to the cemetery
with flowers, balloons and cards and cry my heart out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
