<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-STANLEY-PAY-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYCHECKS AT MORGAN STANLEY INCREASE FOR TOP EXECUTIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After weathering last year's financial storm better than many
rivals, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter's &UR;  &LR; top executives will take home
more money this year than last, but the Wall Street firm's profits
grew even faster than their paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Philip J. Purcell, Morgan Stanley's chairman and chief
executive, earned $31 million in salary, stock and stock options
last year, about 7.6 percent more than he took home in 1997. John
J. Mack, the president and chief operating officer, was paid just
shy of $17 million, an increase of 8.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That puts them among the best-compensated corporate executives.
But the increase was roughly half Morgan Stanley's profit growth of
15 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Graef Crystal, a leading compensation expert and shareholder
activist, said Purcell was ``grossly overpaid.'' But he said that
growth in the Morgan Stanley leaders' pay was modest relative to
the company's stock performance. The stock price has comfortably
outpaced the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index in each of the last
three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that you can deliver good performance like they
have, I don't think you will see shareholders begrudging them their
pay,'' Crystal said.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley, the largest Wall Street firm as measured by
capital, avoided the worst of the downturn in financial markets in
August and September that pounded earnings at several rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The pay increase for the Morgan Stanley bosses was lower than
that of Richard S. Fuld Jr., the chairman and chief executive of
Lehman Brothers, Wall Street's fourth-largest firm by capital. With
stock options factored in, Fuld earned $13.3 million last year, a
gain of 18 percent over 1997. Lehman's profits grew 14 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The figures are based on proxy statements filed by the
securities firms this week.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley is shifting compensation more in the direction of
stock, and especially stock options. Cash earnings were cut this
year. The proportion of compensation paid in equity instead of cash
rose to 47 percent, from 32 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Purcell, 55, and Mack, 54, have jointly run Morgan Stanley since
it merged with the retail brokerage firm Dean Witter almost two
years ago. They took home identical cash and stock bonuses last
year, including $775,000 in base salary, $8.11 million in cash
bonus and $4.44 million in restricted stock. But Purcell received
783,507 stock options valued at $17.7 million compared with 149,645
stock options valued at $3.56 million for Mack.
</P>
<P>
   Stock options confer the right to purchase stock at specified
prices at some time in the future and can expire worthless if the
company's stock price slumps.
</P>
<P>
   But Morgan Stanley's stock price has soared after hitting a
recent low in October. It closed at $93 Friday, up 68.75 cents, not
far off its all-time high of $97.875 last July.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
