r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SIDE2-LADN     02-19 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SIDE2-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANDAY TRIPS OVER FINE LINE, MISSES CUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There is not much difference between playing well
and playing poorly on the PGA Tour, which Jeff Sanday discovered
the hard way in Friday's second round of the Nissan Open at Riviera
Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   The South Pasadena resident and Cal State Northridge graduate
struggled to a 2-over-par 73 for a two-round total of 2-over 144
and missed the cut by two strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Sanday, who salvaged an even-par 71 in Thursday's round with
birdies on two of his last three holes, did not have the same good
fortune Friday and was 1-over on his last eight holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough out here,'' he said. ``You have to do everything
well . . . you have to be very efficient. It's a fine line between
playing good and playing bad. The difference between missing the
cut and making the cut is not a whole lot. One thought, one swing,
that's it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the difference between making the cut and winning, or
getting to the top, is a big gap. There's a big difference between
me and Nick Price. Nick Price could eat me for lunch . . . at this
moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm working on trying to get better. Maybe one day I'll be
up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanday drove the ball well off the tee Friday (he missed just
three fairways), but his iron play left him only a few good birdie
opportunities. It also left him in precarious positions, especially
on the par-3, 156-yard sixth hole made famous for a bunker in the
center of the green.
</P>
<P>
   Sanday tried to hit an easy 7-iron but came over the top and
left it on the back left portion of the putting surface. The only
problem was the pin was front right, and the bunker was directly in
Sanday's line. He chipped over the bunker, but his effort came to
rest about 20 feet below the hole. He barely missed his attempt to
save par.
</P>
<P>
   His caddy, Joe Citro, said he would have preferred Sanday putt
it instead of lob it over the bunker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he would have gotten it just as close for his third
shot,'' he said. ``I wish he would have putted it. It would have
been neat to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a split decision, 50-50,'' Sanday said. ``If I putted
around the bunker, I didn't know if it would have enough speed to
get down there. Plus, I thought it would go too far on the other
side of the green. I was actually trying to just pick it off with
my wedge and hit it just over the bunker. I just hit it too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanday said he had a great time playing before family and
friends _ ``even friends I didn't know I had,'' he joked _ but
plans to put in plenty of practice and perhaps take a few lessons
in trying to sharpen his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been playing all that great this year,'' he said.
``The rounds I have played, I've either been putting very well or
getting up and down a lot. My short game is in great shape right
now because I've had the practice of doing so. That's good, but I
need to hit it better.
</P>
<P>
   ``My swing is not where I'd like it to be. I don't trust it,
that's the big thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
