u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABOR-RIGHTS-1STLD-WR     02-19 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-RIGHTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFL-CIO FOCUSES ON COMPANIES THAT RESIST UNION ORGANIZING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 1st graf of optional add to change Wednesday to THURSDAY; 5th
graf of optadd to add context for Steelworkers' organizing budget;
6th graf of optadd to correct Delta Airlines to DELTA AIR LINES;7th
graf of optadd for clarification.)  (bl)  
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ In his three years as president of the
AFL-CIO, John Sweeney has repeatedly given a stark message to the
labor federation's 70 unions: organize or die.
</P>
<P>
   With union membership plunging to 14 percent of the work force
today from 35 percent in 1955, Sweeney has warned that unless
unions attract millions of new members, labor's influence in
bargaining and politics will continue to decline.
</P>
<P>
   Many unions have begun taking Sweeney's warnings to heart, and
as a result, the discussion at the AFL-CIO's executive council
meeting here often this week focused on how to woo more workers to
unions.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the talk was nearly comical: There was a debate about
whether union organizers who visit workers at their homes should be
barred from wearing tongue rings. To the dismay of some of its hip
organizers in California, the Service Employees International Union
has decided to prohibit them, concluding that such rings would
alienate potential members.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the discussion was serious. One important strategy
that emerged was to ask politicians, community leaders and
clergymen to bring their moral and political weight to bear on
companies that resist unionization drives. Sweeney made clear that
organized labor would also make a big push to unionize three groups
of workers viewed as especially ripe for labor's message: low-wage
workers, minority workers and female workers. One of labor's
selling points is that unionized workers earn 34 percent more on
average than nonunion workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone once said the best welfare program is a job, but lots
of people who have jobs are earning the minimum wage and they still
need welfare or food stamps,'' said Kirk Adams, the federation's
organizing director. ``We're saying the best welfare program is a
union job.''
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO is also mounting a nationwide campaign to publicize
labor's view that American companies are systematically trampling
on the right of workers to form unions. In speech after speech,
union leaders complained that companies illegally threaten to close
operations if workers vote to join a union and illegally fire
thousands of workers each year merely because they support
unionization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Workers are constantly faced with harassment, intimidation,
firings and threats of firings,'' said Arlene Holt, director of the
AFL-CIO's campaign to defend the right to organize. ``The
environment is not conducive to workers who want to freely form and
join unions. We want to change that, and we intend to change
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO not only plans to argue that the right to organize
is a fundamental right, but it also hopes to turn the campaign to
protect the right to join a union into a civil rights crusade.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Thursday, the AFL-CIO held a forum at which it sought to
test-drive many of these ideas, among them that the right to join a
union free of intimidation is a civil-rights issue.
</P>
<P>
   At the forum, which was attended by more than 200 workers,
several workers described the roadblocks and harassment they face
in trying to form a union. Their efforts were endorsed by a panel
of community leaders, including Bishop Thomas Wenski of the
archdiocese of Miami and two members of Congress from Miami, Carrie
Meek, a Democrat, and Lincoln Diaz-Balart, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get the community engaged in your struggle,''
John Due, widely viewed as Miami's foremost civil-rights leader,
told the forum. ``We might have to get arrested to protect the
right to organize.''
</P>
<P>
   One aim of the forum, labor leaders said, was to stress that
civic leaders should fight for unions because when workers unionize
it often helps communities by raising living standards and helping
foster a sense of community.
</P>
<P>
   After unions did little organizing for two decades, recruitment
efforts are picking up. But Sweeney said far more needs to be done.
The United Steelworkers of America has budgeted $40 million, far
more than ever before, to organize workers, while the American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees has approved
$35 million for that purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The service employees union is engaged in the largest organizing
drive in 60 years: About 80,000 home-health-care aides in Los
Angeles County are voting this month on whether to unionize. The
Association of Flight Attendants is seeking to recruit nearly
15,000 attendants at Delta Air Lines while the International
Association of Machinists is organizing 12,000 limousine drivers in
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau of Labor Statistics reported that the number of union
members rose by 100,000 last year, reversing several years of
losses, but that the percentage of workers in unions continued to
decline. Unions, however, reported that they recruited 475,000
members through organizing efforts. The difference is explained
largely by the many union members who lost their jobs when their
plants closed or downsized.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Chamber of Commerce president Thomas Donohue, who was in
Florida to become the first chamber president to speak at an
AFL-CIO executive council meeting, said unions were blaming
companies for their own problems in attracting members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say that no company is breaking the law,'' Donohue
said. ``There are probably 20 million companies in America, and my
experience is companies are tending to live within the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, who received heavy applause when he
spoke to the executive council Friday morning, was far more
supportive. Thursday, the federation announced that it would wait
at least until August before endorsing a presidential candidate for
2000. It urged individual unions to do likewise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe very deeply in the right to organize,'' Gore said at
a news conference. ``The decisions by some employers, thankfully a
minority, to use tricky loopholes to frustrate and ultimately deny
workers from joining a union is unfair, and it must stop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
