<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS HIT ROAD FOR CRUCIAL STRETCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ Step one as the Kings try to get back in the
playoff race was Thursday night's 3-2 victory over Edmonton, the
team that holds the final postseason spot in the NHL's Western
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the hard part _ a six-game trip _ and if Friday's
travel woes were an omen, the Kings are already in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' charter flight to Calgary took off on time Friday
afternoon, but after 20 minutes a warning light came on and the
plane returned to Los Angeles. The team switched planes and took
off again late in the afternoon, about three hours behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   It was on this unpromising note that the Kings' longest trip of
the season began. Starting tonight against the Flames, also
fighting for the last playoff spot, the Kings (21-31-4) begin a
stretch that will be key to their season.
</P>
<P>
   Three things could happen:
</P>
<P>
   __ They could completely fall out of the postseason picture,
leaving them with 20 games on the schedule to start thinking about
next year.
</P>
<P>
   __ They could continue to hang around, as they are now, not
really in the race but not really out of it, either.
</P>
<P>
   __ Or they could somehow use games at Calgary, St. Louis,
Detroit, Chicago, Dallas and at the Pond against the Mighty Ducks
to pull themselves into the thick of the race.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Kings coach Larry Robinson sounded as if he'd
settle for the realistic hopes provided by the second option, then
count on his team to make its major playoff push on the seven-game
home stand to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know our record against Dallas, Detroit,'' Robinson
said. ``If we can beat those teams, then it would be like bonus
points, and right now we need some bonus points.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury updates: Winger Vladimir Tsyplakov, who has played in
every game this season, suffered a sprained medial collateral
ligament in his left knee against Edmonton and is sidelined on a
week-to-week basis. Tsyplakov is not on the trip with the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Winger Glen Murray, sidelined with a knee injury since Jan. 2,
is on the trip, and his availability to play against the Flames is
considered a game-time decision.
</P>
<P>
   __ Big night for Boucher: During a recent 21-game stretch, Kings
defenseman Philippe Boucher was a healthy scratch 20 times and
during that time there were reports he wanted to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday night, Boucher had a hand in every Kings goal,
picking up a pair of assists and a goal, his first this season.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said the time on the bench might have been good for
Boucher.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times when you sit,'' Robinson said, ``maybe you
realize what you were doing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Motivational speaker: Kings general manager Dave Taylor
addressed the team Thursday morning and they beat the Oilers that
night for their most important victory to this point of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, the team prided itself on being a team that was
hard to play against,'' Taylor said. `I challenge them to say they
can't give any more. I think every one of them can give more
effort, a little smarter play and make us a better team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
